<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ INVESTIGATES NEWCOM'S CLOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Nasdaq Stock Exchange has halted trading in
shares of modem maker NewCom Inc. and initiated an investigation of
the company's abrupt Monday closure.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, the exchange said, ``Trading will remain
halted until the company has fully satisfied Nasdaq's request for
additional information.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq officials did not elaborate on what information they seek
from NewCom, and the Westlake Village company's chief financial
officer, Steven Veen, did not return several telephone calls
requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   NewCom issued a press release after the markets closed Monday
announcing it had ceased day-to-day operations and in fact had done
little business since January. The press release also said its main
creditor, Deutsche Financial Services, had seized the inventory and
was suing NewCom to reclaim some of about $8million owed it.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq had alerted NewCom in February that, because the
company's market capitalization was below $5 million, it no longer
met the stock exchange's minimum listing requirements. Nasdaq had
given NewCom until Thursday to come into compliance with the $5
million requirement, and NewCom shares are expected to be delisted
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To all appearances, NewCom is a company in disarray. Even the
firm's investor relations spokeswoman had said Tuesday that she was
unsure if she still had a job with the firm. ``I don't have a lot
of answers. Things kind of snowballed,'' said Dianne Will of
Willstar Consultants Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Will said she thought the company's current woes were in part
the result of internally funding expansion of operations that took
NewCom from sales of $2.1 million in 1995 to more than $93 million
last year. Some suppliers also demanded that NewCom begin paying
for components up-front, Will said, further straining the firm's
cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
