A2853 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-1S     05-27 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA LAUNCHES AIRSTRIKES IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Indian combat jets and helicopter gunships
attacked a large guerrilla force dug into the snow-capped mountains
of Kashmir on Wednesday and Thursday, sharply increasing tensions
in the nuclear-armed subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi is accusing the guerrillas of being Pakistan-sponsored
Islamic militants who are taking part in a carefully devised land
grab. But Pakistan denied knowledge of the militants.
</P>
<P>
   Two waves of air strikes on Wednesday, one just after dawn and
the other in the afternoon, were intended to dislodge a force of
500 to 600 well-equipped invaders who crossed a 50-year-old
cease-fire line between India and Pakistan this month and took
strategic positions along high ridges in the Himalayas, Indian
military spokesmen said. Those raids were followed by a third,
early on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The raids were the most serious confrontation between Pakistan
and India since the rivals tested nuclear bombs a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the conflict would test how the two countries could
manage such tensions, now that the stakes are so much higher.
</P>
<P>
   At a military briefing, Brig. Mohan Bhandari said that the
infiltrating force ``consists of a large number of well-trained
Afghan mercenaries and Pakistani regular army troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bhandari contended that Pakistan's involvement was obvious from
the extent of coordination and logistical support to sustain the
operation. ``Any escalation of this conflict will be entirely the
responsibility of Pakistan,'' the brigadier warned.
</P>
<P>
   That elicited a defiant response from a Pakistani military
spokesman, Brig. Rashid Quereshi, who said, ``The Pakistan armed
forces reserve the right to retaliate by whatever means are
considered appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan put its military on ``high alert.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest raid on Thursday morning was undertaken by six MIG
fighter jets and two helicopter gunships, according to the Indian
military. It targeted the same area as on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The territory of Jammu and Kashmir, which borders India and
Pakistan, has been the chief cause of two of the three wars that
the two nations have fought since gaining their independence in
1947.
</P>
<P>
   In the complicated give-and-take that accompanied the partition,
predominantly Muslim Kashmir ended up as part of predominantly
Hindu India.
</P>
<P>
   The countries began to fight, and a cease-fire divided Kashmir
in two. Since then, India has insisted that the territory is
Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan argues that the Kashmiris should be allowed to choose
their preference.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for Islamic militants to cross the cease-fire
line into India. But the force that was discovered this month was
exceptional not only for its size but also for its location.
</P>
<P>
   The intruders occupied a 30-mile stretch of inhospitable terrain
ordinarily abandoned to the cold and ice. They reportedly ambushed
an Indian patrol sent to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial surveillance later showed that the militants were
dispersed among 24 or more well-fortified positions around the
towns of Dras and Kargil. Rather than the usual hit-and-run
invaders, the units had snowmobiles, artillery and huge stocks of
supplies, the Indian military said.
</P>
<P>
   The operation had the earmarks of months of planning. The
Indians said they thought that it was most likely that preparations
were under way even as the two nations engaged in promising peace
talks in February. At those meetings, the two prime ministers
signed the Lahore Declaration, in which they pledged efforts to
resolve the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks, the Indian army and the militants have exchanged
artillery fire. The militants hold the formidable high ground, a
superiority that the Indians enjoyed in a 15-year-long conflict
with the Pakistani army in a region around the Siachen Glacier in
remote Kashmir. Neither side has used air power in that campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The assault with planes and helicopters represents an
intensification in the mountain combat. The Indians said they had
been careful not to invade Pakistani air space. But the Pakistanis
said that a number of bombs had landed on their side of the
cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that this is serious,'' an official of the
American Embassy here said. ``This is not being viewed by the
Indians as another summer infiltration of the usual order. On the
other hand, I think there is a desire on the Indians' part to treat
this as a limited phenomenon, to respond forcefully in a limited
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a State Department official mentioned that Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz
Sharif, had discussed the confrontation by telephone. ``We
encourage them to stay in touch,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, a militant separatist movement has grown among
Kashmiri Muslims in India, which has mounted an extensive military
response. Some estimates attribute up to 30,000 deaths to fighting
between rebels and security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic ``freedom fighters'' from several nations, especially
Afghanistan and Pakistan, have routinely entered the fray,
considering it a holy war. Pakistan concedes that it has offered
those soldiers moral and political support. India contends that the
assistance is financial and military, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz of Pakistan on Wednesday denied
knowledge of the Islamic combatants under attack. ``No one knows
where they come from and who they are,'' Aziz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
