<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS OFFERS REAL-LIFE LESSONS IN CONSTRUCTION TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER TAYLOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ One look at 18-year-old Sean Jackson's
paint-splattered hands and clothing and you may not think he spent
the last two hours studying.
</P>
<P>
   But to Art Sweany, his Oak Park High School building trades
instructor, the paint under the fingernails shows just how hard
Jackson and a crew of 17 students have worked on a newly
constructed two-story house in the Pine Lake subdivision in Kansas
City, North.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything. We framed all the walls, put on all the
ceilings,'' said Jackson, a senior at Oak Park who served as the
superintendent of the project.
</P>
<P>
   As in many school districts, building a house is an annual
project students take on to earn credit in the building trades
course. The vocational education program, open to juniors and
seniors from the North Kansas City School District's three high
schools, offers entry-level job training in building trades.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years Sweany has taught the course, he said, this is
the first year construction has run behind schedule. He attributed
the delay to heavy rain in the fall and a larger floor plan.
</P>
<P>
   The students are preparing for an open house this weekend, but
Sweany anticipates the house won't be finished for another two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main purpose for our guys who have worked on it is to show
Mom and Dad,'' Sweany said. ``They have a lot of pride in what they
have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,051-square-foot house has three bedrooms, vaulted ceilings
and fireplaces in the master bedroom and living room. It also has a
heat pump with backup gas furnace, a central air-conditioner,
custom kitchen cabinets, carpeting and a finished two-car garage
with insulated doors.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second house Jackson has completed in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got into it, I knew it was something I wanted to do,''
he said. He is considering an apprenticeship program after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson spent much of his time supervising others and making
sure younger students didn't hurt themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For David Sears, 17, of Oak Park High School, the program has
inspired plans of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. Once I got into this, I'm pretty sure this is what
I want to do,'' Sears said. ``When you are sitting at a desk, you
are doing the same thing day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that when they started the project, it was
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come here and there's nothing but dirt on the ground,''
Sears said. He said he'll notice the house for the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   The work completed by contractors included the foundation,
plumbing, wiring and brickwork.
</P>
<P>
   Interior design students participated by selecting brick and
roof colors, interior and exterior color schemes and wallpaper
borders. They also used faux painting techniques on walls and
helped select trim throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   The school district will sell the house to the highest bidder,
with a $135,000 minimum. The proceeds will support the program and
pay for materials. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
