<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION SOLIDIFIES KC PLANT AS BIGGEST FORD'S TOP PRODUCTION
FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Ford Motor Co.'s Claycomo plant now is the
company's biggest producer of vehicles worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   And the plant is expanding to accommodate increased production
expected from three new products, including the Lincoln Blackwood.
The Blackwood, which combines elements of a luxury sport-utility
vehicle and a pickup truck, made its Kansas City debut Wednesday on
the lawn of the Westin Crown Center hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Attending the official unveiling with Ford executives were
officers of the United Auto Workers union and Missouri Gov. Mel
Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackwood, which is expected go into production in late
2000, will be the third product to be launched at the Claycomo
plant over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, Ford expects to begin building the F-150
SuperCrew, a four-door pickup with a bigger backseat.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ford plans to start producing a compact
sport-utility vehicle at Claycomo in the first quarter of next year
to replace its Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant last year built 404,083 vehicles, more than
any other Ford plant worldwide. Previously, Ford's plant in Genk,
Belgium, was its biggest producer, said David Thursfield, Ford's
vice president of vehicle operations.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Minor, Ford's Claycomo plant manager, said the facility
was being expanded and retooled in preparation for the new
products.
</P>
<P>
   Minor said construction in recent months had added 320,000
square feet to the plant, giving it 4.5 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will soon have the capacity to build 514,000 units a
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minor added that the Claycomo plant's F-series truck line would
increase its line speed this September to 55 vehicles an hour from
52 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the projected production boost, Ford officials
maintained Wednesday that they didn't anticipate a lot more jobs at
the Claycomo plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a minimal impact on employment, due to
attrition,'' said Rich Voytowich, a Ford spokesman. ``We're not
looking at hundreds of jobs being added.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kline, president of United Auto Workers Local 249, had
earlier disputed management's statement, saying there could be a
net gain of up to 600 jobs at Claycomo. However on Wednesday, Kline
said: ``I guess the question of the day is what will be the impact
on employment. We're going to have a stable work force well into
the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Kline gave credit to the 5,200 employees at Claycomo for Ford's
decision to produce three new vehicles there. ``They're the true
stars of this plant,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
