<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULTIPLE-PERSONALITY-     05-27 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULTIPLE-PERSONALITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO HEAR ARGUMENTS ON UNUSUAL MULTIPLE PERSONALITIES CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tyrone attacked his therapist when she came to check
on him at his Everett, Wash., home. Sam tried to save the woman,
but couldn't make Tyrone stop.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tyrone and Sam are jailed for life _ along with the 22 other
personalities said to occupy the head of the therapist's client,
William B. Greene.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington state Supreme Court will hear arguments Thursday
on the unusual multiple personalities case, deciding whether Greene
should have been allowed to argue he was not guilty by reason of
insanity when he tied up and molested his therapist in 1994. In
doing so, the court will address a glaring clash between law and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   One arm of the state _ mental health professionals at Twin
Rivers Corrections Center _ had diagnosed Greene with multiple
personality disorder, now known as disassociative identity
disorder, and treated him for the illness since 1991. Therapists
determined there were 24 separate personalities who ``took
executive control'' of Greene's body at times, from a baby girl
named Tabatha to the father-protector Jack.
</P>
<P>
   But another arm _ a Snohomish County Superior Court judge _
ruled there wasn't enough evidence that the disorder existed to
allow it at Greene's 1995 trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, ``The state successfully prevented the jury from
hearing the very diagnosis that it had made years earlier,''
Greene's appeals lawyer, David Koch, said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The jury heard nothing of the mental disease, and convicted
Greene of indecent liberties and kidnapping. Greene, a
three-strikes, you're-out criminal with previous convictions
including a markedly similar indecent liberties case in 1988, was
sentenced to life in prison without possibility of release.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court last year reversed the Superior Court
decision and ordered a new trial for Greene. The appeals court
ruled that multiple personality disorder is indeed accepted in the
scientific community, relying particularly on its longtime
inclusion in the Diagnostic &AMP; Statistical Manual of Mental
Disorders, the bible of mental health diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will make a final ruling in the case after
deliberating Thursday's arguments, setting a statewide precedent
for future cases.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple personality defenses have been a rare phenomenon to
date nationwide, and there is no clear consensus in other state
courts on how to address them.
</P>
<P>
   But Seth Fine, the Snohomish County deputy prosecutor handling
the appeal, said the diagnosis is becoming increasingly common, and
is likely to make up a significant number of future cases if the
Supreme Court allows it as a legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the breadth of its ruling, the court's decision
also could open the door for other controversial mental disorders
to be considered at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The case is being watched by mental health professionals who
deal with disassociative identity disorder _ including Greene's
victim, who had opposed the decision to block evidence of the
disease at trial. She had hoped to see Greene confined to a
psychiatric facility, where he would receive treatment, rather than
be sent to the state prison in Walla Walla.
</P>
<P>
   The therapist, according to court papers, visited Greene at his
Everett home the day of the attack fearing he might be suicidal
after losing a job. He blocked her from leaving, molested her over
a period of several hours, then bound and gagged her and fled in
her car, court papers said. She freed herself and went to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Both the therapist and Everett police who later interviewed
Greene noted Greene appeared to be switching among different
personalities, court papers said. The therapist recognized
``Tyrone,'' identified by one defense witness as a child whose
mother taught him to commit indecent liberties as a way to gain
love, as the personality in control at the time of the assault.
</P>
<P>
   A history of childhood abuse is common in patients diagnosed
with disassociative identity disorder, and Greene's therapy records
indicated a lifetime history of abandonment, physical and sexual
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Greene suffers a mental illness that is not appropriately
taken care of and addressed in a prison,'' his victim said this
week.
</P>
<P>
   While the attack was frightening and traumatic, the therapist
said, she had no doubt that it stemmed from Greene's disease and
not from the sexual sadism that a prosecution expert claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that some day society will look at people who
are mentally ill like we look at people who are physically ill, and
deal with it in that context and not send them behind bars,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys face obstacles in bringing most insanity pleas
to trial, grappling with a public often skeptical of mental illness
claims and a narrow legal definition of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   In Greene's case, those difficulties were compounded by his
controversial diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The dissension over disassociative identity disorder within the
mental health field influenced Superior Court Judge Richard
Thorpe's 1995 decision that only the most obvious, rare cases of
the disorder are generally accepted in that community and that the
disease didn't meet the legal standard for trials. Science can
offer no way to tell legitimate patients from malingerers, Thorpe
wrote, and can offer no consensus even on matters as basic as
whether one personality knows what another is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Koch, Greene's appeals attorney, said the question isn't whether
every mental health professional believes the disease exists, but
whether it's a generally accepted diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   He _ and the appeals court _ holds that it does meet that
standard, relying partly on its inclusion in the most commonly used
diagnostic textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something is published in the (Diagnostic &AMP; Statistical
Manual), that means that according to the American Psychiatric
Association the research is sufficiently clear to say yes, this is
a (real) thing. I would offer that the controversy has more to do
with how widespread it actually is or isn't,'' said Dr. Robert
Olsen, past president of the Washington State Psychiatric
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen, who testified for the defense at Greene's 1995 hearing,
believes in the disorder's existence and has treated patients for
it since 1983. Still, he said, doubts remain among others in his
field and have become even more strident in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The legal controversy won't end even if the Supreme Court
accepts that there is a sufficient consensus the disease exists.
The state also has asked the court to address the mind-bending
legal questions its existence would raise _ namely, whether a
defendant's mind can really be divided into guilty and innocent
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   A verdict of not guilty by reason of insanity requires that
defendants either not know the difference between right and wrong
at the time of their actions or that they be unaware of the nature
and quality of their acts.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Fine asked the state court to set strict guidelines
for when a ``multiple'' would be considered guilty, rather than
leave the matter to a case-by-case basis as the appeals court did.
</P>
<P>
   How, prosecutors asked, could a childlike personality within a
40-year-old man's mind have less awareness of right and wrong than
that man? How can one personality really control another, they
asked, when both are part of the same human being?
</P>
<P>
   ``People with DID create imaginary personalities and divide
responsibilities for their actions among them. The law should not
join them in this game,'' Fine said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Fine argues that if any alternate personality was aware that the
criminal acts were occurring and that they were wrong, the
defendant as a whole should be considered culpable.
</P>
<P>
   But Elyn Saks, a University of Southern California law professor
who has written extensively on the legal questions raised by the
disorder, argued the opposite in a brief that nine legal experts
filed with the appeals court on Greene's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Saks suggests it would be wrong to hold a multiple criminally
responsible for one personality's actions unless every other
personality knew about and acquiesced to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``non-retributive'' confinement would be called for if the
personality in question remained dangerous, she said, but prison
would be unreasonable since there's no way to punish just the
guilty personality and spare ``the innocents within.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's valuable for therapists to hold a multiple
responsible for one personality's actions during treatment, Saks
said this week, criminal responsibility is another matter. She
compared it to the value of parents spanking a 5-year-old child for
wrongdoing versus jailing the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (Greene) has his day in court,'' Saks said.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing evidence of multiple-personalities disorder in court
would be only right, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he should prevail is obviously a different matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
