<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2866 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-27 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREMATURE FIRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't Charlie Hough's fault that the Dodgers picked up
Carlos Perez and unloaded Dave Mlicki. Nor can anyone accuse Hough
of goading Chan Ho Park's agent Steve Kim into contract talks that
got nowhere except into the pitcher's head.
</P>
<P>
   Hough couldn't help it if he was installed as pitching coach by
a regime that since has been pretty well purged. But somebody had
to pay for the sins of the team's .500 start. The ax conveniently
dropped Wednesday on the one-time Dodgers reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the knuckleball that was Hough's money pitch during his
25-year big-league career, the Dodgers' heave-ho didn't catch many
people off-balance. Anybody could see Hough was a made-to-order
scapegoat, as vulnerable to the blame-seeking missiles as Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' team ERA of 4.47 through their first 44 games was
just bloated enough to obscure the 3.68 team ERA and 11 complete
games that Dodgers pitchers threw last season on Hough's watch.
</P>
<P>
   First-year manager Davey Johnson foreshadowed the move in his
heavy-handed way, making repeated references over the past few days
to a corroding communication between the pitchers and the catchers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did we mention that Hough and Glenn Hoffman, the erstwhile
bullpen coach, were the only coaches Johnson inherited when he took
over for Hoffman who, in turn, had replaced Bill Russell?
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say Johnson had a voice in the selection of Hough's
successor, Claude Osteen, who brings to the task the one thing
Hough didn't: previous big-league coaching experience. Osteen has
13 years of it, most notably in Philadelphia. Osteen will be
working closely with former catcher and third-base coach Rick
Dempsey, who traded places with Hoffman in another personnel move
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So one bitter pill swallowed, a double dose of relief for this
headache of a season on the way. Or is it?
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers reached for the quick remedy last year _ firing the
front office, trading the franchise player and a few top prospects
_ and all they ended up with was a costly hangover.
</P>
<P>
   Plop, plop, fizz, fizz, oh what a relief it . . . isn't? If the
Dodgers in 1998 and the Lakers in 1999 showed Angelenos anything,
it's that there isn't always a quick fix for what ails a team.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the best thing a front office can do is sit back and
wait for the aches and (growing) pains to run their course. Team
slumps can be a sort of fever, spiking and then receding.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes if you rely on liquid cold medicines for relief, you
end up trading one symptom for another. The fever leaves and is
replaced by a drugged confusion. Sports teams also can trade one
malaise for another, if they're not careful.
</P>
<P>
   Take the trade of Mlicki to Detroit. The move was meant to give
the Dodgers some financial freedom. But all it has done is shrink
the margin for error among the remaining pitchers. The reliever
they got for Mlicki, Robinson Checo, appeared in two games before
being sent down to Albuquerque. The Dodgers couldn't in good
conscience keep Checo in L.A. after he allowed 10 hits and seven
runs in 32/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you wonder if Heather Locklear, in those
Nike ads, isn't really saying, ``Checo digs the long ball.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been so many multihomer games this season _ there
were eight in one day alone last week _ the only thing tighter than
the new strike zones are the collars of pitching coaches.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta pitching coach Leo Mazzone looks like he's fidgeting
more these days, there's a reason. Braves superstar pitchers Greg
Maddux's and Tom Glavine's early-season performances have been less
than Cy Young quality. But there's no talk there of replacing
Mazzone.
</P>
<P>
   The worry here is that the Dodgers panicked. A few months into
Kevin Malone's first year as general manager is no time to make
rush judgments and push good people aside.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' problems hinge on purpose, not personnel. The
team's record will get better as soon as does the players'
execution. Better to recognize that now, before another coach faces
the firing squad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
