<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS REGAIN ENERGY IN CINERGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ If this is what it takes to make the Dodgers'
offense take off, they might be out of coaches by the end of the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching coach Charlie Hough was fired earlier in the day
in what the players perceived as a shake-up move, the Dodgers
played one of their more sound games of the season and beat the
Cincinnati Reds 9-3 Wednesday at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Everything the Dodgers seemed to fail at in the past few weeks
was accomplished against the Reds. They scored early, received
solid starting pitching and came up with timely hits in a six-run
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (23-22) scored more than eight runs in a game for
only the second time since May 1 and kept from falling below .500
for the first time since April 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bats came alive,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``It was something we needed. It's what the doctor ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming sentiment in the Dodgers clubhouse was Hough
was fired to jolt the club, which had lost seven of its past nine.
Most of the players expressed remorse for what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all realize it's not Charlie's fault,'' said Dodgers second
baseman Eric Young, who returned from sore ankle after missing
three games. ``We go out and hit the ball and field the ball. I
think (the game) was crisp because it starts with the pitchers.
Chan Ho (Park) pitched well.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's outing was a welcome sight to the Dodgers. Park (4-3)
pitched seven strong innings. He allowed two solo homers and three
runs but fought out of two bases-loaded situations in the fourth
and fifth innings, allowing just one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan Ho battled,'' Johnson said. ``I'll tell you one thing: he
got in a couple of bases loaded jams and he battled. He showed me a
lot of heart. I've seen him a little sharper . . . but he made the
pitches he had to.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone should have felt the repercussions of Hough's firing,
it's Park. Left-hander Carlos Perez has pitched the poorest among
the Dodgers' starters, but Park could be classified as the biggest
disappointment through the first two months given the high
expectations placed upon him.
</P>
<P>
   Park's been inconsistent. He's yet to string together three
quality starts (three earned runs or less in six innings) this
season and has had trouble communicating with catcher Todd Hundley.
The two worked well together against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of confidence because we scored early,'' Park
said. ``I was really happy with that and with Hundley. We've been
talking about (getting on the same page) and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   But inevitably, Park's thoughts drifted to Hough, who was
replaced by Triple-A Albuquerque pitching coach Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up and got the message it was . . . a surprise,''
Park said. ``I miss him because he was trying to help. I miss him.
He gave me an idea and I just followed that. He told me to throw
more fastballs and be ready to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Park was aided by the Dodgers' ability to score two runs in the
first, sparked by the return of Young. He went 2 for 4 with two RBI
and two runs scored to lead a 10-hit attack.
</P>
<P>
   Young's single in the first gave the Dodgers a 1-0 lead. He
scored when he stole third and Reds third baseman Mark Lewis
couldn't handle the throw.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tied it on Sean Casey's solo homer in the first and
Lewis' sacrifice fly in the fourth before the Dodgers broke it open
against Brett Tomko (1-3) in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Young had an RBI double, Gary Sheffield doubled in a pair of
runs, Eric Karros stroked an RBI single and third baseman Adrian
Beltre hit a two-run homer to make it 8-2. Raul Mondesi added his
17th homer of the season in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys realize we haven't been playing well lately,'' Young
said. ``Maybe the shake-up of the coaching staff will make guys
realize we could be next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
