<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-THEFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA OFFICIAL NAMED IN ART THEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A former director of counseling at UCLA was
indicted on charges of stealing an original 19th century painting
and selling it for $200,000 through a middleman to a New York art
gallery, federal prosecutors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beverly Hills attorney for Jane Crawford, 50, said the
oil painting by American impressionist Arthur Wesley Dow was given
to his client by a fellow UCLA counselor and that she's now being
used as a scapegoat to cover up for the university's carelessness
in protecting donated art.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's being held out as a scapegoat for their slipshod manner
in which they record and maintain donated works of art,'' said
attorney Lawrence S. Strauss. ``In my opinion, they are trying to
blame this all on her to protect their reputation so people will be
not be afraid of making donations of art in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA spokesman Harlan Lebo said he is unaware of another art
theft of this magnitude at the university. Daily News records show
that a painting of George Washington valued at $200,000 was stolen
from UCLA in March 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university does everything it possibly can to protect the
artwork and other materials donated to the university by very
generous benefactors, and we'll continue to do so,'' Lebo said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted Crawford late Tuesday on two
counts of wire fraud, two counts of interstate transportation of
cashier's checks fraudulently obtained from the gallery and one
count of engaging in monetary transactions involving funds obtained
through fraud, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Ranee Katzenstein. If
convicted, the former director of counseling in the College of
Letters and Sciences faces a maximum of 40 years in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Crawford stole the ``Frost Flowers,
Ipswich 1889'' painting from UCLA in 1994 and sold the painting
through a middleman to the Ira Spanierman Gallery in New York for
$200,000. The painting depicts a field of flowers and a sky with
clouds in Ipswich, Mass. The proceeds were deposited into an
account controlled by Crawford and a cohort, Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money was used to pay her personal expenses,'' Katzenstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who has worked at the university since 1976 as a
professor and most recently as a director of counseling, has agreed
to surrender to federal authorities. She will be arraigned in
federal court in Los Angeles in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the investigation by the FBI began in 1996 when
Crawford and her cohort, whom Katzenstein did not name, had a
dispute and he went to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators learned that Crawford had the painting in her
office at UCLA, took it to her house and then sold it through the
middleman to the New York gallery, Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She represented to the gallery that the co-schemer was the
true and rightful owner of the painting, which of course is
untrue,'' Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   During the FBI's investigation, the Ira Spanierman Gallery sold
the painting to a collector for $300,000, Strauss said. After the
sale, the FBI seized the painting. Last November, the gallery filed
a lawsuit in New York against the UCLA Board of Regents to recover
the painting. A motion is now before a New York judge to transfer
the case to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15, UCLA fired Crawford, Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have documents saying the reason they fired her is
because of the Spanierman lawsuit,'' Strauss said. ``In my view,
the firing of her is an effort to save face. If the painting was
the property of UCLA, they were lax and remiss in safeguarding this
apparently valuable donation.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss said Crawford is a ``poor scapegoat'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She reasonably believed at the time (that the UCLA counselor)
had ownership of the painting that he was giving to her and she
never had any intent to receive stolen property or deprive UCLA of
any of its property,'' he said. ``I feel very bad for her. She has
lived a very law-abiding life and was a professor with tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
