<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT PIRATES, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Orel Hershiser had his second straight strong
outing on Wednesday night in the New York Mets' 5-2 victory over
the Pirates. But, after the game, the Mets received troubling news
about Jason Isringhausen, once considered one of their most
promising young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen felt pain in his surgically reconstructed right
elbow, and is having another magnetic resonance imaging test on it
Thursday. He said on Wednesday that he felt something he had never
felt before in his elbow after a 14-minute side session on
Wednesday afternoon. He and the rest of the Mets are hoping it is
nothing more than the breaking of scar tissue, but it obviously
puts his scheduled start against Arizona at Shea Stadium on
Saturday in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The initial diagnosis is a strain. ``It was just something I
never felt before,'' Isringhausen said late Wednesday night after
his latest setback. ``That's why I'm hoping it's just scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was an inch over, then I'd be worried,'' Isringhausen
added, pointing at his scarred elbow. ``But this is just another
nice day in my life. It's starting to become a joke. I'm just tired
of it. Every time I get close to being back, something's wrong.
Just the timing of it is more upsetting than anything.
</P>
<P>
   The news about Isringhausen put a damper on the Mets' sixth
victory in their last eight games, one that featured good hitting
and better pitching from the 40-year-old Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   But fortunately for the Mets, Hershiser (4-4) is feeling good
these days. He allowed five hits and two runs in six-plus innings,
and went 2 for 3 with a run-scoring double, en route to his second
straight victory. In three starts now with his new contact lenses,
Hershiser has allowed 8 runs in 18 2/3 innings, a respectable
earned run average of 3.86.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Hershiser _ who is now 6 victories shy of 200 for his
career _ admitted that he had questioned whether he was done after
he had allowed 22 runs in 29 1/3 innings, for an era of 6.75 over
his first three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have thoughts,'' said Hershiser, whose era is now
down to 5.63 ``Because even though I was healthy and strong as an
ox, I didn't have an idea where the ball was going. So it could
have been something as simple as my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser received a team effort on Wednesday. Benny Agbayani
belted a lead-off homer off former Mets left-hander Pete Schourek
(2-5) in the top of the fourth to tie the game at 1-1. Hershiser
later pulled his bat back on a fake bunt attempt and whacked a
run-scoring double into left.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hershiser was eventually thrown out at the plate
trying to score from second on Warren Morris' error at second,
before Morris tied the game in the bottom of the fifth with a
two-out home run, Edgardo Alfonzo and Robin Ventura each whacked
consecutive doubles in the sixth to give the Mets the lead for
good.
</P>
<P>
   After Hershiser _ who threw only 80 pitches _ walked
Pittsburgh's No. 8 hitter, Abraham Nunez on his first _ and last _
four pitches of the seventh, Dennis Cook recorded the next three
outs to preserve the lead.
</P>
<P>
   And then, after Armando Benitez struck out the side on 13
pitches in the eighth, John Olerud delivered a 2-run single in the
top of the ninth, before John Franco pitched a scoreless ninth for
his 14th save in 14 tries.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
