<HEADER>
A2878 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN     05-27 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSTEEN TAKES OVER AS PITCHING COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN d 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When Charlie Hough was promoted to pitching coach
of the Dodgers last summer, the staff experienced success.
</P>
<P>
   When Davey Johnson was choosing a pitching coach upon being
named manager of the Dodgers in the fall, he took that success into
account when deciding between Hough and Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hough was fired Tuesday, factored in the difficulty of
finding a new pitching coach in midseason, Osteen was the natural
fit. He was promoted from Triple-A Albuquerque to be the Dodgers'
pitching coach. He arrived here late Tuesday night and was on the
bench for Wednesday's 9-3 win against the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to be about pitching,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``Right now I'd have to say we haven't pitched
up to those expectations. I think Claude will help us establish an
approach, a tone, that will clearly establish the Dodgers pitching
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was concerned how the pitchers would react to
Osteen given their close relationship with Hough. But he said
Osteen, who has been a pitching coach for 13 years in the majors,
should be helped because he's worked with many of the Dodgers'
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Osteen watched several of the Dodgers' pitchers
throw on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough thing for the whole team,'' Osteen, 59, said.
``You get close to the team and coaches and you realize how much
they try to help you. I know, basically, what kind of stuff they've
got and what they throw.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to spending the last three seasons at Albuquerque,
Osteen was the pitching coach when staff ace Kevin Brown was played
for the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Osteen said he'll work with the pitchers on holding runners on
base and to quicken deliveries to home. He said it will take a few
weeks for him to familiarize himself with the pitchers on staff.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coaches switch spots: Hough and Osteen weren't the only
coaches involved in movement. Johnson also had coaches Glenn
Hoffman and Rick Dempsey swap roles. Hoffman will coach third base;
Dempsey moves to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he made the move so Dempsey could have more
hands-on dealings with the pitchers and catchers. Johnson said one
of the reasons the decision was made to fire Hough were weaknesses
in communication with the battery.
</P>
<P>
   ``That precipitated having Dempsey more involved with the
pitchers and catchers,'' Johnson said. ``This is not a demotion in
my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no overlooking the fact that in 44 games the
Dodgers had seven runners thrown out at the plate _ four from the
outfield and three from the infield on nonforce plays.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, the Dodgers' manager last season, doubled as Triple-A
Albuquerque's manager and third-base coach in the 1{ seasons he
spent with the Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, (Dempsey) was fine at third,''
Johnson said. ``He has the make-up. He fits over there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Extra bases: Dodgers right fielder Raul Mondesi hit his
National League-leading 17th homer in the ninth inning. . . .
Though Chan Ho Park recorded the win for the Dodgers, he gave up
two homers. He's tied with Ismael Valdes for most homers yielded on
the staff with 12. . . . Cincinnati's Mike Cameron struck out for
the 54th time in 41 games in the first inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
