<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY NIEUWENDYK HELPS STARS TAKE 2-1 LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Joe Nieuwendyk has been fighting the flu bug for two
weeks. And only last night could you tell just how much it has been
bothering him.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, who said he has been loading up on sleep and
vitamins, had his leg speed back and skated circles around the
Colorado Avalanche, scoring a goal and dishing out two assists to
lead the Stars to a 3-0 victory in Game 3 of the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same kind of performance that Nieuwendyk had been
producing at the beginning of the playoffs, and combined with the
electrifying goaltending of Ed Belfour, gave the Stars a 2-1 lead
in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel so much better now, like I can skate again,''
Nieuwendyk said before the game. ``I just felt so bad for such a
long time, like I was just holding on. Now, I can feel it coming
back, my legs and my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Nieuwendyk could be the key to the Stars' chances at a
Stanley Cup. After all, several players said Nieuwendyk's injury
last year was what sank the Stars. Now, the 1-2 punch of Mike
Modano and Nieuwendyk is proving to be the undoing of the
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're both going, I don't know how you check them,''
Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers said. ``Individually they mean a
ton to us. Together, they're incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's performance was so strong that it almost made
Belfour's spectacular night in goal seem average. But in stopping
34 shots and posting his sixth career playoff shutout, Belfour
continued to put up the best numbers of any NHL playoff goalie. His
1.61 goals-against average is better than the Avalanche's Patrick
Roy, the Toronto Maple Leafs' Curtis Joseph and the Buffalo Sabres'
Dominik Hasek. His .934 save average is better than Roy's and
Joseph's. Hasek's .942 save average tops all playoff goalies, but
Hasek is out with a groin injury and Belfour has been busy winning
two of the biggest games in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about the guy, he's been our best player in
the playoffs,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said of Belfour. ``This
was a big game, a road game. Your goaltender has to be your best
player in road playoff game, and he was that for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk wasn't far behind. He tallied his eighth goal of the
playoffs, second only to Detroit's Steve Yzerman _ and he recorded
his fifth game-winning goal, leading the NHL in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably more key than Mo,'' Avalanche winger Theo Fleury
said. ``When they need a big goal or a big play, they really look
to Joe to go out there and make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk was somewhat lucky on his first goal, but he earned
the luck with a fantastic shift. After keeping the puck in the
offensive zone for 25 seconds and getting a shot on goal,
Nieuwendyk wheeled behind the Avalanche net to win the battle for a
loose puck. Looking to create a scoring chance, Nieuwendyk tossed
the puck into the slot and watched as it deflected in off the skate
of Avalanche defenseman Aaron Miller at the 2:22 mark of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge, it gave us something to show for our effort,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   And Nieuwendyk and his linemates also worked for the other two
goals. On goal No. 2, winger Dave Reid gave up his body and took a
heavy check to make a pass to Nieuwendyk in the neutral zone after
a Fleury turnover. Nieuwendyk then hit Jamie Langenbrunner with a
pass from the left wing to the slot, and Langenbrunner lifted in an
insurance goal at the 10:44 mark of the third period. Reid added
another goal at the 16:05 mark, and the Stars were under the skin
of the Avalanche, who dropped to 2-5 in home playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were struggling at home and we wanted to take
advantage of that,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``We did and
we put the pressure on them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars were outshot 34-26 in the game, they again kept
their composure in a critical third period and received key
performances by all six defensemen, by Nieuwendyk, Reid and
Langenbrunner, by Belfour and by Carbonneau, who continued to be a
defensive demon and still fired a team-high five shots.
</P>
<P>
   And with all that, the Stars still vow to play better in Game 4
tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better because we were sucking wind all
night,'' Hitchcock said. ``With four days at this altitude, I
really feel we will be better in Game 4.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
