<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-KIM-     05-27 1923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-KIM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN PITCHER EARNING RAVE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ The kid they call B.K. has learned a new English
greeting this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up?'' Byung-Hyun Kim says to pitcher Dan Carlson in the
Tucson Sidewinders clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson rubs his sore right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Kim grabs Carlson's right hand and begins massaging the knuckle
on his ring finger. It's a pressure point that is supposed to
relieve soreness in the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You supposed to feel this much pressure?'' Carlson says,
cringing.
</P>
<P>
   Kim doesn't understand what Carlson is saying and continues
working the knuckle, deeply, quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an experiment now, but he was ready to drop me on that
one,'' Carlson says later. ``I tell you what, if it helps my
soreness in my elbow, I'm going to be rubbing that knuckle every
single day.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old Kim (his first name is pronounced Be Young He
Yun) didn't come here from Korea to provide acupressure for
sore-limbed players in the Diamondbacks organization. Signed in
February as a free agent, he's here to pitch, bringing 90-plus-mph
fastballs sidearm and submarine style, throwing four different
sliders, bringing breaking balls that dance to the plate, as El
Paso catcher Rod Barajas described.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the Diamondbacks envision him on the
mound at Bank One Ballpark someday. The question with Kim is not
if, but when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim has a very special arm,'' said Tommy Jones, Diamondbacks
director of minor league operations, who is monitoring the
right-hander's progression from Double-A El Paso to Triple-A
Tucson. ``The biggest challenges are off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after arriving in Tucson in late March, late because of
visa problems, Kim asked Manager Buck Showalter _ through
24-year-old interpreter Min Soo Kim _ whether it would be all right
if he pitched against Korean phenom Chan Ho Park in Arizona's
season-opening series in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. Slow down.
</P>
<P>
   It's the stuff of dreams and part of the confidence that Kim
took with him to America, where he is embarking on a whole new
world, one in which he is finding his way with an interpreter by
his side.
</P>
<P>
   He finds a sense of home through the Korean restaurants and all
the McDonald's locations along the way to what he hopes is a quick
rise to the big leagues. McDonald's is big in Seoul, Kim says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves McDonald's hamburgers,'' said Levern Wilson, who owns
Seoul Restaurant in El Paso, a five-minute jaunt from the park in
which Kim was dominating this month.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who speaks Korean and whose wife is from Korea, took in
the two Kims (no relation) while they were in El Paso. Nearly every
day, they came to the restaurant for kim chee soup, Byung-Hyun's
favorite dish. Wilson would use extra spice for the young Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Min Soo said when they go out to eat American food, he has to
describe everything on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes chicken, but he wants to know every ingredient that
went into making it,'' Min Soo said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he moved from El Paso, Kim corresponds with Wilson, who
wants Kim to branch out from Korean food and McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he tried steak but didn't like it,'' Wilson said. ``I
said, `Put some seasoning on it. There's more than one way to cook
a steak.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Menus and the English language have been far more puzzling than
the batters he has faced so far.
</P>
<P>
   In his short stint in El Paso, Kim was 2-0 with a 2.11 ERA in
relief appearances. He had four balks, a flaw that has been
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a mandate from the (Texas) league that his delivery was
illegal because it had a little pause in it,'' El Paso pitching
coach Dennis Lewallyn said. ``We corrected that. We taught him all
the bunt plays and team defense. We let him pitch and get used to
pro baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim has been a starter in Tucson. In his Triple-A debut May 14
in Omaha, Kim threw 5 innings, striking out seven, walking one and
giving up two runs on three hits for the win. He was less than
impressive in his second start but was dominating Monday in a 4-0
victory over Fresno, working seven scoreless innings, giving up
four hits and striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not difficult, but the batters are more patient here,''
Kim said through his interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   If batters are more patient at the Triple-A level, wait until he
sees major league hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still very much learning his trade,'' Diamondbacks
General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``Everything is so much
faster, things like defense and covering the bases and throws over
to first base. There are so many things.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional homesick feeling, Kim says he doesn't
feel lost on or off the mound.
</P>
<P>
   He is loose in the clubhouse, laughing with teammates, even
though he doesn't know what he's laughing`` at'' most of the time.
He is charmed by closer Rich Batchelor's guitar. He says he beats
starter Nelson Figueroa in fighting games on Play Station. Every
once in a while, he springs a Spanish phrase he learned from one of
the Latin players on a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's picking up more or less the swear words in Spanish,''
Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Batchelor tries to communicate with Kim through music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a nice guy, but it's got to be tough, coming into
a new culture and learning a new language,'' Batchelor said.
``Everyone includes him in everything, whether it's goofing around
in the clubhouse or going out to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   When pitcher Bobby Chouniard recently was brought up from
Tucson, Garagiola and Showalter asked how Kim was doing with his
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby said, `Actually, I think he's farther along in his
Spanish,' '' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks organization received permission from the Texas
and Pacific Coast leagues for Kim's interpreter to dress in uniform
and come to the mound for meetings with Kim. But that is not
permitted in the major leagues, Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter says the only Korean he knows is ``Byung-Hyun Kim.'' &QL; 
So far, the kid with the infectious smile is progressing so well
that the call to bring him to the Diamondbacks could come sooner
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   In his last appearance in El Paso, Byung-Hyun struck out eight
in four innings and ``looked like he was overmatching everybody,''
said Matt Hicks, Diablos play-by-play announcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the Diamondbacks were treating him special,'' Hicks
said. ``They didn't use him as a closer, only in a certain way in
relief. That limited how much an impact he could have had. He'd
come in the sixth or seventh inning, when not a lot was on the line
and there was no pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucson Manager Chris Speier hit against former submarine
pitchers Dan Quisenberry and Ted Abernathy, but none with Kim's
velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a tremendous sinker,'' Speier said. ``But then, his
breaking ball goes the opposite. You're used to seeing breaking
balls go down. He's got the breaking ball that goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun has a exercise routine that has his fellow pitchers
shaking their heads in amazement. He throws daily. He is constantly
on the bike or treadmill. He's lifting weights, running around the
park. El Paso Manager Don Wakamatsu said he had to slow down Kim's
pace after seeing him do exercises in the bullpen four innings
before he was scheduled to pitch the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Speier says he lets Kim go, knowing his regimen works for him.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks management realizes it has a gem.
</P>
<P>
   Min Soo was showing Kim how to grip the ball before the
Diamondbacks coaching staff stepped in and explained to Min Soo
that his job is to coach English.
</P>
<P>
   Min Soo understands. &QL; 
The two, it seems, are connected, if not at the hip. They live with
a Korean family in Tucson. Min Soo, a former pitcher and outfielder
who once had big league dreams like the man he speaks for, was
working for the Diamondbacks as a scout in Canada before Garagiola
hired him to be Kim's interpreter. Min Soo will join Kim in Phoenix
if the pitcher gets another promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a basketball, Kim keeps an English translator book in
his locker stall.
</P>
<P>
   Min Soo gives Byung-Hyun a new word or phrase to learn in
English each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing well,'' Min Soo said. ``I keep the words small,
simple. He's learning.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ken Huckaby, who roomed with Chan Ho Park in Albuquerque
in '95 when the hard-throwing pitcher came over from Korea to work
his way up the Dodgers organization, said both are soft-spoken and
exude confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to read (Kim),'' Huckaby said. ``He seems to
be having a good time out there more so than worrying about what is
going on. He's confident that nobody in baseball can hit his
slider. So he's always got that to fall back on when he's out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim doesn't admit it, but his teammates know he misses his
parents. He writes to them. They live in Kwangsan-ku Songjung-dong,
Ko rea, where Byung-Hyun said baseball is work and ``not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it fun here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. It is very fun,'' he said, his eyes lighting up.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said he'll return to Korea in November to serve a four-week
military training stint. Then he'll return to Arizona and take a
crash course in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I found out, there seems to be a correlation to
learning the language and developing as a player. There's that
ability to understand what is being told by the coaches,''
Garagiola said. &QL; 
Kim is getting a crash course on baseball with the Diamondbacks,
and his name could be called soon.
</P>
<P>
   But Showalter said ``it's tough to put a timetable on a
20-year-old'' still learning the culture and language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to bring him up for the sake of bringing him
up,'' Garagiola said. ``The baseball highways are littered with
young players who were rushed in.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the rate Kim is going, the Diamondbacks may have no
choice.
</P>
<P>
   He thrives on facing the best in America. He caught the
organization's attention last year when he was a member of the
Korean national team. During a trip to Tucson, pitching against an
American team, Kim struck out 15 in 6 innings. He led the team to
the finals of the World Championships in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   He said he looks forward to the day when he can pitch against
Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what they are doing, taking me step by step,''
Kim said through Min Soo. ``I'm very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Parr, president of the El Paso Diablos, predicts that by
August, when he gives away five yo-yos with snapshots of the club's
top prospects who started the year there _ including pitchers John
Patterson, Nick Bierbrodt and Brad Penny _ Kim's will be the most
popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be huge,'' Parr said. ``Everybody's going to want that
yo-yo.'' &QL; 
Hicks said it's easy to root for Kim because he's not only pleasant
and easy-going, but has the underdog look at 5 feet 11, 176 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can get guys out at the big league level,'' Hicks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who befriended Park during his transition period in pro
baseball in 1994 and gave him a place to live during his minor
league stint in San Antonio (where Wilson and his wife lived at the
time), said he often is asked which one is better.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson won't answer that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I will tell is that Kim will go a long ways,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim is ready, translation books in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the vision of pitching in Bank One Ballpark,
Byung-Hyun turns to Min Soo and says in Korean: ``It is no longer a
dream. It's a matter of time now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
