<HEADLINE>
STARS DISPLAY THE BENEFITS OF VERSATILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Forty-eight hours earlier it was out with the old, and
in with the new. The Stars had stomped on the gas pedal, enjoyed
immense success on this new fast track, and therefore, horsepower
hockey was here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about how the Stars used to do it. After Game 2 at
Reunion Arena, there would be no more rope-a-dope acts while
sitting on slim leads. And Ken Hitchcock all but vowed to burn his
defensive bible.
</P>
<P>
   And if you believed that ...
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Belfour has a couple of dented posts and one dimpled
crossbar he'd like to sell you.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as you win, it never matters how, right?
</P>
<P>
   Round 3 of the NHL's Western Conference finals here last night
came down to a third-period stretch with the Stars trying to hide
behind a one-goal lead. It was a defensive shell game that had only
one chance to succeed. That one chance was named Belfour, who gave
the performance of his between-the-pipes life.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour refused to lose the lead, or the game.
</P>
<P>
   And style of play, even though totally different from Monday
night in Dallas, again worked beautifully. Lured into offensive
mistakes, the Avalanche was stung twice in the last 11 minutes of
the third period, and the Stars hung up a 3-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Home-ice advantage swung back to Dallas, now up 2-1 in the
series, but more important, deep frustration piled up on Colorado's
front porch. In a 48-hour span, the Avalanche lost a shootout,
which is their strength, and then last night saw Belfour beat them
in goal _ and wasn't that advantage suppose to belong to Patrick
Roy in this series?
</P>
<P>
   But back in North Texas, there had to be massive nerve damage
watching the Stars try to milk a third-period lead for nearly half
of the final 20 minutes. And just think how Belfour must have felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't us sitting on the lead as much as it was trying to
work their defensemen as much as possible, hoping to wear them
down,'' said Hitchcock. ``The gamble was that the more we could
force the defensemen to start inching up on the rush, the better
chance we had for a mistake to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a mistake did happen, and probably not soon enough for
Belfour. Among his 34 saves, about 12 of them were on the
sensational side. Plus, he had the help of the crossbar and a post
in the second period, and another shot clanged off the post in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the mistake Dallas needed. The little man, Theoren
Fleury, lost the puck in the Dallas zone to Darryl Sydor, who fed
Dave Reid at neutral ice, and that set up a blunder by Colorado
defenseman Adam Foote.
</P>
<P>
   With Reid an easy target along the boards, Foote buried him with
a check, but not before Reid shoveled the puck to Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hitchcock said, a defenseman was pinching instead of
playing his man. Nieuwendyk was off to the races on an odd-man rush
with Jamie Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect feed across the slot set up Langenbrunner's
one-timer, which sailed above Roy's left shoulder and into the
strings.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was 2-0 with 11 minutes left, and the air was sucked out
of McNichols Sports Arena. As a matter of fact, the McNichols crowd
was docile all evening, taken out of the game by Belfour's robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing about the third period was we were wearing
down in the thin air,'' said Hitchcock. ``The altitude got to us.
We had some shifts out there with guys just hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee you we will play a better game on Thursday
night. That will give us four days up here, and we will be
acclimated. But it was a struggle tonight. Eddie had to save us.''
</P>
<P>
   A fluke second-period goal by Nieuwendyk changed the entire
course of the game. But there was nothing fluke about the way the
goal was set up.
</P>
<P>
   With Reid on the line with Nieuwendyk and Langenbrunner, they
dominated the Avalanche on every shift, and that line scored all
three goals. But in a forechecking frenzy early in the second
period, the puck stayed in the Colorado zone forever. Nieuwendyk
centered a shot from behind the goal that hit off the toe of
defenseman Aaron Miller's skate, and then scooted past Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Luck? Yes. But luck came as a result of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen in hockey,'' said Miller, ``but if we're
gonna give them the lead in every game, it going to be a long
series for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That one-goal lead caused the Stars to play the old way last
night. But they've also won in this series doing it the horsepower
way. And now Colorado has to guess what's coming next in Game 4.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
