<HEADLINE>
`CRAZY EDDIE' SHOWS NO SIGNS OF MELTDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ To some knee-jerk critics, he will always be Crazy
Eddie, the Inevitable Melting Goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the scouting report will always say that the way to get
to Ed Belfour is through his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the jury's still out on Eddie,'' Stars teammate
Mike Modano said last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the jury is in.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 3-0, in a manner of speaking. In these Stanley Cup
playoffs, we were reminded at McNichols Arena, the jury has found
Belfour not guilty of lapsing into Crazy Eddie. Belfour, not guilty
of allowing himself to be goaded into distraction. Belfour, not
guilty of being a speedbump on the road to Lord Stanley's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has pretty much silenced his critics,'' Modano
continued, after Belfour himself had stifled the Colorado
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been our best player.''
</P>
<P>
   It is time, indeed, to reassess the playoff prowess of Ed
Belfour. Time to peer again into those azure-blue eyes and try to
see what one can see.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the Stars' playoff fates were cast last year when
Belfour began raining fists on Shawn Burr late in an
already-decided first-round game at San Jose. It was a hint, they
said, of the total meltdown to come in the Western Conference
finals at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   What hogwash. The critics seem to ignore that the Stars' offense
had dimmed and that the power play had been firing nothing but
blanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been so much bull said,'' teammate Brian Skrudland
said. ``I know Eddie says he doesn't read the papers. But some of
the things that are written about him are really uncalled for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we play for the whole team. But for Eddie's sake,
I'd like to see us continue on and get this big prize, so he can
put this stuff, once and for all, behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment is spreading throughout the Stars' locker room.
And Belfour, ever quiet and inscrutable, keeps giving his teammates
reason to think so.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers alone don't do Belfour's night justice. Matched
against the well-credentialed Patrick Roy, Belfour turned back 34
shots and snuffed three power plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' defense, as per custom, did throw a spidery web in
front of him. But whether it was a game-opening siege by the
Avalanche, whether it was Theo Fleury trying to stick in a rebound
high, whether it was Sandis Ozolinsh with a backhander from the
slot, or whether it was Peter Forsberg flying in short-handed,
Belfour never blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was awesome,'' Colorado defenseman Aaron Miller said. ``We
could've easily had three or four goals, but he wouldn't let us.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury that Modano spoke about has been a kangaroo court. In
these playoffs, Belfour has displayed nerves of steel and a heart
of steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in that zone that people talk about,'' teammate Craig
Ludwig said. ``Our defense tonight? You can describe it in one word
_ Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he signed with the Stars as a free agent last year _ a
three-year deal worth $10 million _ Belfour carried the cross of
eight years of playoff frustrations in Chicago. His resume lacks
the silvery (or gold, in some cases) finish of a Roy, a Dominick
Hasek and a Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Of those four goaltenders, all having carried their teams to the
NHL conference finals, Belfour likely would rank fourth in most
straw polls. But there we go, convening juries again.
</P>
<P>
   Which of the four _ Roy, Hasek, Cujo or Belfour _ has been
better in this last month?
</P>
<P>
   Crazy Eddie. Clearly, we know which goalie has outplayed the
other in this Stars-Avs series.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour does not surrender much personal information in
interviews. Purportedly, he doesn't read the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that might be something that's driving Eddie right now,''
Ludwig suggested. ``He reads the papers. He knows what's been said.
And he's basically right now telling all you guys to stick it
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had those questions about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury can rest.
</P>
<P>
   With Belfour stealing the show, the Stars are poised to take a
giant leap in these Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   That's not crazy. That's the Stars' playoff MVP.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
