<HEADLINE>
ASU  COACH LIKES VIEW FROM DUGOUT  
 1ST SERIES BERTH IN 10-YEAR STINT 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ When the Women's College World Series begins
today, David and Blanche Wells will be camped in their familiar
seats (Section D, last row) at Don Porter Hall of Fame Stadium, but
not sitting with one of their usual party.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Linda, for the first time in the 18-year NCAA
softball history, will be in the dugout as Arizona State returns to
nationals for the first time since 1987 and first time of the
10-year Wells era. The Sun Devils open against Washington at 4 p.m.
(Arizona time).
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll know my mom: We look exactly alike,'' said Wells,
ecstatic that she can share this experience with three generations
of family. Her 88-year-old grandmother, Clara Shepard, and her aunt
Edna, 85, are here, as is her sister, Jodi Suerig, and 7-year-old
niece, Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crosses your mind that maybe you're not ever going to get a
(CWS) team that your grandmother can see,'' said Wells, who turns
50 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Or that her parents, in their early 70s, can cheer just as
they've been cheering for Linda since she first picked up a bat at
age 6.
</P>
<P>
   A three-sport athlete in high school, before it was cool for
girls to do even one, Wells expanded to five sports while a
collegian at Southeast Missouri. Then she coached three
(basketball, volleyball, softball) in 18 years at the University of
Minnesota before replacing Mary Littlewood at ASU.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA began administering softball in 1982, when Littlewood
had a fourth-place finisher. The Sun Devils were two-and-out at the
'87 CWS and only now are returning, in part due to the wave that
has swept the University of Arizona to five national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would take 10 years at all,'' Wells said.
``I thought ASU, how simple will that be to recruit. I've been
recruiting and playing in the top 25 at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I find out it isn't easy because of not being able to
attract the Arizona kids and there being so many schools in
southern California.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the last time ASU won a game over UA, the programs were
reasonably even. The Devils, in fact, were second in the Pac-10,
four games ahead of the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   But that postseason, when pitcher Susie Parra of Scottsdale was
a freshman, UA swept ASU in a regional and never looked back. The
Wildcats won the school's first women's championship in any sport
and now are within two of UCLA for the most softball crowns.
</P>
<P>
   ASU, even in this breakthrough season, is 0-4 against Arizona,
extending that losing streak to 36. It was last in the eight-team
Pac-10 but emerged as one of a record five CWS qualifiers from the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mistake I made was spending a lot of time recruiting kids
I wasn't going to get from the get-go,'' Wells said. ``Then by the
time you've crossed off three or four, you're getting pretty slim
and we're signing people in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had years when I'm just flat taking a body, and I know I'm
not taking anybody that I can compete with. I'm filling the
roster.''
</P>
<P>
   That began to change with the signing of Alyssa Johnson of Tempe
in 1993 and Lisa Dacquisto from southern California a year later.
But until ASU could land a blue-chip pitcher, the job remained
undone.
</P>
<P>
   Wells still recalls assistant coach and recruiting coordinator
Ann Pedersen returning from a 16-under national tournament in
Chattanooga, Tenn., after first seeing Kirsten Voak.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so excited to tell me about that young kid and she was
adamant, we're going to get her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it takes, early identification. There's only so
much you can do with them until they're juniors, but by then it's
important you get a relationship established and you do everything
you can do within the rules to make the difference. I think that
was the difference for Voak.''
</P>
<P>
   Voak, as a freshman, already has equaled the ASU single-season
record for victories (24) and set the mark for strikeouts (307).
</P>
<P>
   , Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ASU breaks ground June 15 on its new softball stadium, perhaps
the final piece in competing on even ground with UA, which is
212-14 at home since moving into $1 million Hillenbrand Stadium in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coached long enough, I've been on the pendulum, and this
pendulum has given me a big down ride,'' said Wells. ``Now I feel
very optimistic that it's swinging up.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
