<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PYRRHIC VICTORY FOR ALBANY
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 27:
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Republican county legislator named Thomas Morahan
defeated a Democratic county legislator named Kenneth Zebrowski for
an open seat in the New York State Senate. As a result, the
Republican majority's control of the Senate will rise from 35-25 to
36-25. For this, the Legislature killed a tax worth $360 million to
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a legislative body with a notoriously warped
decision-making process, the saga of the Rockland County Senate
seat represents a new low. In an attempt to score points for their
candidate in a close contest, the Republicans who control the State
Senate announced earlier this month that they were going to pass a
bill repealing the New York City commuter tax, which imposes a
modest levy on people who work in the city but live elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, including New York City's mayor, Rudolph
Giuliani, expected the Assembly Democrats to protect the city's
interest and allow the repeal bill to expire in limbo. But Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver stunned everyone by announcing that he
intended to help the Democratic cause in Rockland County by passing
the bill. Many of his New York City members supported the idea,
delighted at the chance to upset Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Now the game-playing is over. Control of the State Senate is
unchanged. Commuters, who are already the beneficiaries of a huge
state property-tax reduction program, will get a small boost in
their take-home pay. The courts will almost surely give the same
boon to Connecticut and New Jersey commuters. Unfortunately, when
the economy turns down, the city will have several hundred million
dollars less revenue each year for services, either for poor
neighborhoods represented by many Democrats who supported repealing
the tax, or for the Manhattan business districts where so many
commuters work. When New York City becomes an unpleasant place to
do business, the economic engine that drives the region begins to
falter.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani will probably be long gone from City Hall when that
happens. But when the legislators' constituents start complaining
about lost services, more dangerous streets and threats of
corporate departures for southern climes, perhaps they can console
themselves with the memory of how angry he looked when they socked
it to him on the commuter tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
