r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SHAKEUP-LADN     05-27 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SHAKEUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUFFLING THE DECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The disappointing Dodgers needed a fall guy, and
with the starting pitchers performing poorly, the choice was made.
</P>
<P>
   Saying they were displeased with how the pitchers and catchers
were prepared for games, the Dodgers fired pitching coach Charlie
Hough on Wednesday. Hough was replaced by Triple-A pitching coach
Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   In another move, manager Davey Johnson reversed the roles of
Glenn Hoffman and Rick Dempsey. Hoffman will coach third and
Dempsey becomes the bullpen coach.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear the motivation for the moves was to spark the
Dodgers, who were 22-22 going into Wednesday's game and 3{ games
out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't blame Charlie. I blamed everyone in the room,'' said
Johnson, whose eyes watered when he talked about the firing of his
friend. ``I wanted everyone in that room to know what a loss it was
to me. I wasn't just blaming the pitchers, but also my coaches and
me, individually.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were touted as having one of the best starting
rotations in baseball, but Chan Ho Park, Carlos Perez and Darren
Dreifort haven't lived up to expectations. Kevin Brown is pitching
spectacularly and Ismael Valdes has been solid, but they couldn't
save Hough's job.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers starters were a combined 19-16 with a 4.19 ERA,
which ranked second and fourth, respectively, in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a shame that a guy as good as Charlie is, as a
person and a coach, that it comes to this _ that he has to be on
the short end of the stick because we played so poorly,'' Brown
said. ``It's not a situation where Charlie Hough failed us. It's a
situation where we failed Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing. It really is, to play that bad to get a guy
like that fired. I have the utmost respect for Charlie.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and general manager Kevin Malone said the relationship
between the pitchers and catchers was substandard, which was a
major factor in the decision. Johnson pointed to poor pitch
selection and poor location as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitcher-and-catcher relationship has to be on the same
page,'' Johnson said. ``That's got to be tightened up. That's
paramount. That's on any club. Obviously, the (pitcher) has (the
ball) in his hand, but the relationship has to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Several pitchers and catcher Todd Hundley said Hough wasn't to
blame for the Dodgers' pitching problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie kept the players well-informed,'' Hundley said,
echoing the words of several pitchers. ``When coaches get fired, or
a manager gets fired, it's the players' fault. I think it's
something to shake up the club. We're going to make moves if the
job doesn't get done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have other problems beside pitching. Like batting
average (.266), hitting with runners in scoring position (.243),
defense (40 errors leading to 26 unearned runs) and the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had to go,'' Hough said. ``The only thing that upsets
me is I had to come here (to Cincinnati). I didn't get fired
because of (Tuesday) night's game. I'm going to play golf and watch
the season unfold. They'll be fine here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll go get (Greg) Maddux straightened out. (Tom)
Glavine, too. They're behind us in pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Hough was asked if he had been given a fair chance, to which he
responded ``No.'' Malone said it was enough time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as an organization, as a pitching staff, weren't moving in
a direction we wanted to go,'' Malone said. ``Should you wait just
for the sake of waiting? We felt we could make this move and get
the pitching back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about being 22-22. It's about the direction we're
going. It's like Davey pointed out, we're regressing. We're trying
to move forward and get better. Should we wait until we're 65-65?
When you identify something needs to be fixed, you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time a Johnson-managed team has changed pitching
coaches in midseason. Johnson said discussions of Hough's role
began ``a few weeks ago.'' He told Hough of the move after the
Dodgers' 3-2 loss to Cincinnati on Tuesday night at the team's
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers said Hough was offered a reassignment within the
organization, but Hough said he heard of no such offer. The
51-year-old Hough said he wouldn't accept a reassignment if one
were offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing the way we're playing with the talent we
have, it's the rule of thumb,'' Dodgers reliever Alan Mills said of
the move. ``I'm sure if we continue playing the way we are playing,
more changes will certainly be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
