u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PRIVACY-NYT &LR;      05-27 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PRIVACY AND RIDE-ALONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court followed understandable legal reasoning this
week when it barred the police from allowing reporters and camera
crews to follow officers into private homes that are being raided.
The unanimous decision, which cited ``the right of residential
privacy'' as a core principle of the Fourth Amendment, will mean
fewer television shots of drug busts. Even so, it is very important
that the police see the court's action for what it is, a narrow
reinforcement of traditional residential privacy rights, and not
use it to deter serious newsgathering and journalistic
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In any ruling of this sort, the danger is that secretive
officials will use it to chill reporting they dislike. That is
among the reasons The New York Times joined other news
organizations in arguing that such ride-alongs should not be
constitutionally forbidden in all cases.
</P>
<P>
   The issue in question arose in 1992, when a joint federal and
local law-enforcement task force, seeking publicity for its
operations, invited The Washington Post to send a reporter and
photographer to accompany agents on an early-morning search for a
fugitive in a Maryland couple's home. The photographer took
pictures of the couple wearing skimpy nightclothes, which The Post
never published.
</P>
<P>
   The court's disgust with the raid was clear. Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor called the raid ``an amazing invasion,'' foreshadowing the
court's ruling that inviting the media into a home without the
consent of the residents had turned a lawful search into an
unconstitutional invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the possibility of good public relations for the police
is simply not enough, standing alone, to justify the ride-along
intrusion into a private home,'' Chief Justice William Rehnquist
wrote for the unanimous court. By an 8-to-1 vote, however, the
court declined to impose personal liability on the officers
involved because it was not clear at the time that their actions
were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   A second case involving federal wildlife agents who took a CNN
camera crew on a search of a Montana ranch in 1993 was sent back to
a lower appellate court for review in light of the new ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The court's interest in privacy is healthy. But its decision
could have perverse consequences if police departments misread its
narrow holding as a broad license to fence off large areas of
police activity from journalistic observation and reporting. In
future cases the court should make clear that its ruling applies
only to residences, not to surrounding grounds or public areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
