<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY500_BOAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOYT'S POISE BOOSTS BOAT'S CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There are no bruises on his chin, no broken jaw
bones, no black eyes, no fat lip, no ear in need of stitching and
not a single chipped tooth.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to wear a body cast, doesn't need a cane to
stroll through Gasoline Alley and not once has he felt the need to
leaf through the checkbook to make sure the life-insurance policy
was paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, a thankful Billy Boat not only survived three hard
crashes in the days leading up to Indianapolis 500 qualifying last
Saturday at Indianapolis Motor Speedway, he also survived A.J.
Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   We know about Foyt, don't we?
</P>
<P>
   Remember two years ago, when he tried to box Arie Luyendyk's
ears during a victory lane ceremony at Texas Motor Speedway,
tearing into Luyendyk the way a hungry wolf might tear into a rump
roast?
</P>
<P>
   Or the time an incensed Foyt smashed a laptop computer to
smithereens during a frantic pit stop at Indy?
</P>
<P>
   Better some geek's computer toy than someone's fleshy neck,
right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' Boat said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boat helped make amends by later qualifying for an
outside front-row starting position in Sunday's Indy 500, he
remains somewhat surprised he wasn't forced to steer with one arm
in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, when (Indy Racing League Director of
Medical Services Dr. Henry Bock) was about to release me from the
infield hospital after the third crash (on a warm-up lap during his
first qualifying attempt), I told him I hoped I wouldn't be back in
10 minutes after I was done talking to A.J.,'' said Boat, who lives
in Glendale. ``But A.J. never once ranted and raved or raised his
voice at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time he ever came close to doing that is when I was
yelling at myself after the third crash. He said, `Don't worry
about it. We'll just put (the car) back together and go back out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gives you the confidence to go out and qualify for
the front row. He's always there for you. After what I'd been
through, he still made me feel confident that I could go out and
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   When Scott Sharp drove for Foyt during the 1996-97 seasons, he
also recalls an understanding Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, A.J.'s pretty cool about things like that,'' Sharp
said. ``He's been there before, and he's really pretty patient. He
knows when you try and get everything out of the car, it can get
away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt a softy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him (expletive) like that happens,'' Foyt said
Wednesday, standing a few feet away from where a smiling Boat was
busily signing autographs. ``I drove these race cars, and I made
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense jumping all over Billy and raising hell. The
worst thing you can do is bring his morale down. If you want
someone to push the button, you have to expect stuff to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuff happened all right.
</P>
<P>
   Three crashes translates into a lot of dollars, dollars that
could have been used to buy spare parts, not new parts to replace
broken parts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when it counted most, Boat delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, however, admits his confidence was shaken after
back-to-back accidents during the first two days of practice last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really tough week,'' Boat said. ``The roller coaster
of emotion was unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we tested here, we could run 222 (mph) to 224 (mph)
fairly easily, and I think that's what got me in trouble. We tried
something new, and I probably pushed the car a little too soon.
Then, after that first crash, we were behind and trying to play
catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we had the incident the following day and we got further
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the week went smoothly, and Boat began to
believe his string of bad luck was over.
</P>
<P>
   Then, whammo, a third crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to push the car as hard as I could to make sure I
had my tires hot when I took the green flag,'' Boat said. ``And I
pushed it too quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really dejected. It's not the lowest I've ever felt, but
I think it's the most I've ever been disappointed in myself. I
shouldn't have let (that accident) happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have to thank A.J. and the crew for picking me up.
After the week I had, I probably felt better being on the outside
front row than I did last year sitting on the pole. Last year, we
had a fairly flawless week leading up to qualifying. This year, we
struggled. So I feel like we made more of an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   With only today's Carburetion Day practice separating drivers
and the race, Boat already is feeling as chipper as he has the past
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my confidence is back to the level it needs to be,''
Boat said. ``The race is a totally different mind-set than
qualifying. It's 500 miles long, and you have to be very patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make sure you're there at the end of race, so
you're not quite on the edge like you are doing qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can sit back and just concentrate on the race, and let
me tell you, that's a big relief.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
