<HEADLINE>
COYOTES WILL INTERVIEW TORTORELLA FOR COACH'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said he intends to give
assistant coach John Tortorella a formal interview next week for
the team's vacant head coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   The interview likely will take place Tuesday after Smith returns
from Toronto, where he will spend the rest of this week on
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with John on the phone today, and I told him we'll
meet early next week,'' Smith said Wednesday, a day after
Tortorella publicly expressed an avid desire to replace the fired
Jim Schoenfeld behind the Phoenix bench next season.
</P>
<P>
   Tortorella, 41, an assistant with the Coyotes the past two
seasons, has emerged as the leading candidate for the job since
Schoenfeld's firing Monday. Others who have expressed interest in
the job thus far include former NHL coaches Mike Keenan and,
possibly, Ted Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan is also up for consideration for the vacant head coaching
job with the Los Angeles Kings, who also have interviewed
minor-league coach John Vanboxmeer and are expected to interview
Detroit Red Wings associate coach Dave Lewis, a former Kings
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Another Red Wings assistant, Barry Smith, is a possible
candidate for the Coyotes. Bobby Smith interviewed him for the job
two seasons ago before hiring Schoenfeld. Bobby Smith has not yet
contacted the Red Wings for permission to speak with Barry Smith
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't, but I could see a small chance that he might,'' a
Red Wings official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential candidate is former NHL great Bryan Trottier,
now an assistant with the Colorado Avalanche. Trottier, who played
18 seasons in the league 15 with the New York Islanders has been on
six Stanley Cup championship teams and won the Art Ross and Hart
Memorial Trophy in 1978-79 as the NHL's leading scorer and Most
Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   He previously worked as an assistant for the Pittsburgh Penguins
and spent the 1997-98 season as coach and director of hockey
operations for the Portland Pirates, the American Hockey League
affiliate of the Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Trottier also is among the candidates being considered by the
expansion Atlanta Thrashers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
