<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAAGOLF-ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY PLAYS NUMBERS GAME  
 ASU GOLFER WONDERS,`WHY NOT 58?' 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-CASEY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mad dog or Englishman? The answer is a bit of both, Arizona
State golfing sensation Paul Casey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the golf course, I'm probably a mad dog,'' said Casey, who
grew up in Weybridge, near London. ``Off the course, I'm probably
the Englishman.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Casey growl?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the worst loser ever,'' he conceded. ``They say the
English are good losers, but I've never said that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the prim and proper world of golf, Casey is fresh stuff. And
despite a lack of rigorous training, he plays golf on a level that
few of his peers ever realize.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case last month when the 21-year-old sophomore
posted the all-time low round in college golf. His 10-under 60 in
the final round of the Pac-10 Championship not only eclipsed Tiger
Woods' 61 at the same tournament in 1996, but it broke another
significant record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you shouldn't break records like that,'' said Casey,
referring to Byron Nelson's course-record 62 during the 1945
Seattle Open at the Broadmoor Club, the same layout Casey humbled
during the Pac-10s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a great player, and that 62 came a month after
he'd won 11 straight tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverence lasts only a few seconds before he jumps to the
possibility of other low scores in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I thought about the 59 (when he shot 60),'' he said of
golf's most coveted score. ``But why not 58? How come nobody has
ever shot a 58? I'm sure that Hazeltine is not going to give that
up. But then again, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   His reference to Hazeltine National Golf Course near Minneapolis
comes with the knowledge that he and his fifth-ranked ASU teammates
will attempt to win the NCAA Championship there next Wednesday
through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course reminds me of golf back home,'' Casey said of the
trees and rolling hills. ``I'm not a big fan of desert golf.''
</P>
<P>
   That Casey ended up among the cactus and sagebrush is part
coincidence and part choice. He heard about the ASU program in
1996, just after the team captured the NCAA title. His interest was
piqued by Ron Commans, a former player for Sun Devils Coach Randy
Lein. Commans was a teaching pro at Casey's home course in England,
Wisley Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul wrote me a letter looking for information, and I gave him
Ron's name,'' said Lein, who coached Commans at Southern
California, where Commans won the 1981 NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who was an 18-year-old bartender at Wisley, made a big
impression on Commans, now an instructor at the Karsten Course at
ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron wrote me back and said that Paul could start for any team
in the country,'' Lein said.
</P>
<P>
   A recruiting visit, and a wild football game between ASU and
Nebraska, convinced Casey that Tempe was the place for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my first football game, and it turned out to be a
complete riot, a 19-0 shutout (by ASU), where they ended up tearing
down the goal posts,'' he said. ``. . . I left convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   But it took Casey nearly a year before he convinced Lein that he
could be a force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul played OK the fall of '97, then he broke through that
spring, winning the USC tournament,'' Lein recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Casey added the '97 Pac-10 and NCAA West Regional titles, then
collapsed at the national championship. His game stayed in a rut
last fall, when he was dogged by a case of flu.
</P>
<P>
   But after Jeff Quinney, his chief rival among the Sun Devils,
exploded for a 62 at the Thunderbird/SAVANE Invitational in April,
Casey seemed to re-ignite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul has an ego, and Jeff has made Paul a better player, just
like Paul has made Jeff a better player,'' Lein said.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much to get Casey going. He is a free spirit,
something that shows in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why I'm majoring in sociology,'' Casey
admitted. ``I started out in business, then went to broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Casey earned a 3.8 grade-point average this past
semester, Lein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's the first time I ever tried,'' Casey conceded.
</P>
<P>
   His spirit is also displayed by ``misspent time in a hotel
room'' that led to his trick-shot abilities. And the kidding he
takes from his teammates for dating the assistant coach of the ASU
women's team, Ashley Adleta.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't winning, they'd give it to me even more,'' Casey
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he is, going 28 under in his past four tournaments and
lowering his scoring average to 69.23.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I was good, not great,'' Casey said. ``But I
played against some pretty good competition, like Justin Rose, the
guy that got all the attention after (the 1998) British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not great, but I'm playing the best I've ever
played.''
</P>
<P>
   So are his ASU teammates, who have captured three of their last
four tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the best team in the country,'' Casey said. ``Last
week in Tucson (at the NCAA West Regional), we won without our best
stuff. That's inspiring because, hopefully, our best is yet to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who finished eighth at the regional, has a little
something extra working for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are going to see me play for the first time in the
States,'' he said. ``It will be nice because my mum hasn't seen me
play in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the mad dog will give way to the Englishman with his
mother in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Nah, not Paul Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in the chase, I'm clueless,'' said Casey, whose
nickname is Spaceman. ``It's the mad dog thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
