<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS OF FIRST MAGNITUDE TURN OUT FOR RUSSELL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ How's this for a team?
</P>
<P>
   Centers: Wilt Chamberlain, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Bill Walton,
Dave Cowens, Willis Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Forwards: Bob Pettit, Julius Erving, Rick Barry, Jerry Lucas,
Dolph Schayes.
</P>
<P>
   Guards: Oscar Robertson, Tiny Archibald, Hal Greer, Dave Bing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the Hall of Fame,'' decided Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, him, too.
</P>
<P>
   When you're Bill Russell, the heaviest of the heavy hitters show
up for your time. And then you get videos from the likes of Michael
Jordan, Elgin Baylor, Jerry West, Bill Bradley, Lenny Wilkens,
Magic Johnson, Kevin McHale, and a major politician who lives in
Washington, D.C., and who described himself as ``a fellow
lefthander.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aretha Franklin said it best,'' explained Dick Ebersol, a TV
fellow of note. ``It's r-e-s-p-e-c-t.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. Guess who sang the national anthem?
</P>
<P>
   This is without even mentioning the other Celtic alumni. You
know, the Cousys, Heinsohns, Havliceks, Ramseys, Embrys,
Loscutoffs, Sanderses, Whites, Sharmans, Risens, and Joneses (both
Sam and K.C.). This is what Bill Russell deserved, and this is what
Bill Russell got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't know how to play if it weren't for him,'' declared
Abdul-Jabbar, whose adolescent tutorials came both at the old
Madison Square Garden and at Power Memorial High School. ``NBA
teams used to practice at our gym, and from 1960 through 1965 I
must have gone to every doubleheader. The Celtics played in many
opening games. I would have to say I saw them play 25 times and the
man I studied was Bill Russell. I learned so much. The next day my
coach would say, `How many of those guys scored 20 points?' and the
answer would be `none.' But everybody would have had something to
do with it, most of all Bill Russell. Watching him I learned the
dynamics of the game, and how to win. Being a Knick fan in those
days was agony.''
</P>
<P>
   Three thousand miles away, a tall, skinny redhead was studying
his Russellology in La Mesda, Calif. ``Most players play in spite
of their teammates,'' said Walton. ``Russell's sole purpose was to
make the rest of them the stars, and in so doing win the game. He
was my favorite player of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate that the charity that is currently near and dear
to Bill Russell's heart is the National Mentoring Partnership.
Russell operated on both sides of that relationship, and in each
case the party of the second part was here to pay his respects.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Bill Russell was not a finished product when
he entered the league in December 1956. He was talented beyond
measure, but he didn't know the NBA. That is where Arnie Risen came
in. Arnie was then in the penultimate year of what would turn out
to be a Hall of Fame career, and it didn't take long for him to
learn that his primary function on the team would be shifted from
being its starting center to the professor for this new kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel flattered when I hear Bill Russell say I was his
mentor,'' said Risen. ``I'm not sure that isn't just an old friend
boosting a teammate. If I did anything for him, it was tell him
what to expect from the other players in the league, and to help
him with our offense. But I never thought of it as mentoring. In
those days we all helped each other. It was the natural thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, Bill Russell was at the zenith of his career,
seven titles and four Most Valuable Player awards in hand. The new
backup center was a kid out of Providence by the name of John
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me,'' said Thompson. ``Very much so. I just felt so
safe with him. On and off the floor. When I was in his presence I
knew I had nothing to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is that no other great player gets talked
about in those terms. There was something very different and very
special about Bill Russell, as speaker after speaker made clear at
the well-attended (12,000-plus) and well-run (how can you go wrong
when you've got Bill Cosby at the throttle?) and long overdue
tribute to Bill Russell at the FleetCenter Wednesday night. It was
such a blissful evening a case can be made that if you've got to
wait 30 years in order to get it right, then maybe that's what you
should do.
</P>
<P>
   The point of it all was to do the right thing by the greatest
team sport athlete in American history, and the point within the
point was to see his No. 6 properly raised. It's been up there
since 12:55 p.m. EST March 12, 1972, when the Celtics ambushed
Russell by hoisting the number when he was in town on a broadcast
assignment for a Sunday afternoon ABC telecast of a Celtics-Knicks
game. A very grudging Russell would only allow the number to go up
if no fans were present, and so the big 6 was raised with only Red
Auerbach, Celtics players, local writers, Garden personnel, and ABC
techs watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red knows how I feel about this,'' Russell said. ``I'm not
that type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was then and this was now, and thus at 10:07 p.m. EDT
on May 26, 1999, the number was re-raised, this time before an
appreciative crowd that numbered a roster of NBA luminaries whose
combined 1999 market value would be in the billions, with a capital
B. And Bill Russell looked pleased.
</P>
<P>
   He talked team, as he always did and always will. ``Red's theory
was that there were 10 players, two referees, 13,000 people, and
one basketball,'' Russell explained, ``and we decided what to do
with the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   This was one time Bill Russell was not in control of anything.
The time had come for him to be properly honored, and that was
that. There were all those people in that building, and they were
the ones who made sure Bill Russell went to bed Wednesday night
aware that everything he has done for his team, the game, and his
country was completely appreciated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
