<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS_SPRINGTRAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SPRING HOME STILL UP FOR GRABS  
 VERO BEACH, FORT MCDOWELL IN CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tug-of-war between Arizona and Florida with the Los Angeles
Dodgers as the prize is about to enter its final phase.
</P>
<P>
   It's a contest between Indian River County in Florida and an
Arizona tribe that hopes to build the first spring training complex
on a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Face-to-face negotiations are under way between the Dodgers and
Vero Beach area officials over terms of a deal that would keep the
team training in its spring home of 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials in Vero Beach expect a final offer will be put
together in about 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, meanwhile, the Fort McDowell Yavapai-Apache Indian
Tribe continues to quietly work behind the scenes on its plans for
a spring training complex for the Dodgers on the reservation east
of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   But the once-grand vision of a mega-complex featuring housing,
recreation, practice fields and a 12,500-seat stadium likely will
be scaled back significantly if the tribe decides to make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of this time they're still working on the pros and cons,''
said Chris Baier, sports development director for the Arizona
Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Baier said talks with other teams such as Toronto, Texas and
Kansas City _ one of which could join the Cactus League with Los
Angeles and share the Arizona facility with the Dodgers _ are on
hold while efforts focus on LA.
</P>
<P>
   While the Tribal Council continues to weigh the merits of luring
the Dodgers and whether it would make long-term economic sense to
its community, an emerging public debate in Vero Beach over
financial issues could give Fort McDowell an opening and a chance
to pre-empt the Vero Beach talks.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has little to offer Fort McDowell now in the way of
financial aid because the car-rental tax that pays for improvements
to Cactus League facilities likely won't have any money available
until 2017. The available funds are locked into paying for the more
than $160 million in improvements to Cactus League facilities this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   A possible change in the car rental tax from a flat $2.50 in
Maricopa County and $3.50 in Pima County to a percentage of the
rental contract has been floated but would have to be approved by
the Legislature and county boards, and that couldn't happen until
next year.
</P>
<P>
   With such a change, though, Cactus League funds would increase
significantly and the Fort McDowell tribe could envision a payback
on some of its investment in a much earlier time frame than first
thought.
</P>
<P>
   In Vero Beach, the debate over a public buyout of Dodgertown
could add a nasty overtone to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   One Vero Beach businessman on Tuesday demanded the county
commission hold a referendum on the issue. The commission said it
would consider holding a non-binding referendum. Newspaper letters
to the editor question the merits of the plan and helping Rupert
Murdoch and his Fox Group, owner of team; others say the town would
be foolish to let the team go.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers, who likely won't have to pay a cent in either
place, stand to win either way but may not get everything they
want.
</P>
<P>
   The Vero Beach proposal centers on a $20 million deal with $7.5
million recently appropriated by the state Legislature with Gov.
Jeb Bush's support, and the rest to come from an increase in the
county tourism bed tax and extension of a local half-cent sales tax
increase that was approved years ago for a bond issue that is
almost paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The county and city would use some of the money to purchase
Dodgertown from the Dodgers and then lease it back to them, and the
rest of the money for improvements to the aged facilities and
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to work and the people are going to be
satisfied with it,'' said Milt Thomas, Vero Beach Chamber of
Commerce economic development director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there's a lot of misinformation. They're
raising the mantra of Rupert Murdoch and lining his pockets.
There's a lot of knee-jerking,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   One non-negotiable point in Vero Beach is that the Dodgers do
not want to own the facility any longer. They are the only major
league team that owns and operates its spring training facility.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want vast improvements to Dodgertown, including
construction of a cloverleaf four-field practice facility on what
is now a nine-hole golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Their appraisal of the facilities and land including the golf
course was $14 million. The Vero Beach appraisal was about $8
million and didn't include the golf course land. If Vero Beach had
to pay $14 million to buy Dodgertown from the team, it would have
only $6 million left for improvements, far short of what the
Dodgers envision.
</P>
<P>
   And while Fort McDowell, if it decides to move forward with a
proposal, may not have all the bells and whistles it once hoped to
offer, it would seem to be in a good position to best Vero Beach
even without housing and recreation amenities such as golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pessimistic, but I've been encouraged in my brief
discussions with the Dodgers recently,'' Baier said. ``They clearly
haven't made up their minds. And they are not using Arizona for
leverage. They want us to continue to work at this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort McDowell is working hard on this. We want to see what we
can do to help, but there are limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sculley, executive director of the Maricopa County
Sports Commission, said the commission is not assisting on the
project because the tribe is not a member.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal officials would say only that work continues on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is coming when our plans need to be on the table,''
Baier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
