r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-DRAF     05-27 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR SCOUTS TO EARN THEIR KEEP  
 ANNUAL AMATEUR DRAFT ON DECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They know which fast-food chain has the best french fries. They
know which rental cars get better mileage. They've hustled across
airports to make connecting flights so they can get to a game in
time, only to find that a high school coach has changed his
pitching schedule. They've even dodged tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   But it's all worth it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year that baseball scouts live for. They're
done scouring the country. Now it's a matter of going over reports,
making a few more telephone calls and perhaps getting one last look
at one or two prospects before Major League Baseball's annual
amateur draft, which will be held over a three-day period beginning
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 clubs will draft up to 50 players apiece, with about half
of those eventually putting their names on the dotted line.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will have the fourth overall pick, their
highest ever, and two compensatory picks (Nos. 31 and 71) for the
loss of center fielder Devon White to the Los Angeles Dodgers via
free agency.
</P>
<P>
   After the pick at No. 71 (second round), Arizona will not select
again until the sixth round because it signed three primary free
agents _ left-hander Randy Johnson, right-hander Todd Stottlemyre
and center fielder Steve Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks scouting director Don Mitchell conducted regional
scouting meetings in Atlanta on Friday, Dallas on Saturday and
Phoenix on Sunday. This week, Mitchell has been meeting with
assistant director Bob Miller, national coordinator Kendall Carter
and regional supervisors Howard McCullough (eastern), Mike Rizzo
(central) and Steve Springer (western).
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the team will hold an invitation-only workout for
two to three dozen players, similar to what it did before last
year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This draft appears to be very deep, pitching-wise,
particularly in college, and after the top couple of rounds, the
position players fall off a little bit,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   So because of that pitching depth, are the Diamondbacks more
likely to go for a position player higher, so they can get a
promising pitcher or two in the middle rounds?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a possibility,'' Mitchell said, not wanting to
reveal too much.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Diamondbacks have the fourth overall pick behind Tampa
Bay, Florida and Detroit, a lot of attention is being paid to that
spot.
</P>
<P>
   There is a consensus among Diamondbacks staffers and most people
around baseball that a small handful of players could go in the top
five or six.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the top four players likely will be high schoolers _
outfielder-pitcher Josh Hamilton of Athens Drive High in Raleigh,
N.C., pitcher Josh Beckett of Spring (Texas) High, and catcher Ryan
Christianson of Arlington High in Riverside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Other high first-round possibilities are catcher Eric Munson
from the University of Southern California, pitcher Kyle Snyder of
the University of North Carolina and outfielder B.J. Garbe of Moses
Lake (Wash.) High. Garbe's teammate, outfielder Jason Cooper, also
could fit into the top 10 mix.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said he has had direct contact with the families and/or
representatives of Hamilton, Beckett, Cooper, Garbe, Munson and
Christianson.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett, a right-hander, has been the subject of speculation as
the No. 1 overall pick for quite some time, but the left-handed
Hamilton, who likely will be an outfielder in the pros, may have
supplanted him. Munson is attractive because he is a left-handed
hitter with power. His defense needs work, as does that of
Christianson, ``but they know that. It's no real surprise,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianson is strong-bodied, with a plus-arm and plus-power.
He's aggressive and likes to get dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, Mitchell says, ``has a special approach to the game.
He comes from a great family. Our Texas-area scout, Ray Corbett,
has known Beckett since the ninth grade. The young man has a
tremendous breaking pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell calls Garbe ``a well-rounded player who can really
hit.'' Garbe also is a right-handed pitcher in addition to his
center field duties and has the versatility to where he could be
tried as a third baseman. Cooper, his teammate, hits for more power
and has similar long-ball potential to Arizona's top pick in 1997,
Jack Cust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those Washington kids are very bright. They've signed
college letters to Stanford, so that should tell you something,''
Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks also like University of Miami shortstop Bobby
Hill for his versatility and hustle but aren't likely to take him
at No. 4. It is doubtful he would be available at No. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Want a sleeper or two?
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on right-hander Matt Ginter of Mississippi State,
which is the alma mater of Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter, and
right-hander Ben Sheets of Northeast Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Signability also can figure into the thinking on draft day.
While the price tags for draftees has risen considerably over the
last few years, Mitchell said it is unlikely that most of this
year's crop will extend the negotiating process over a lengthy
period as their predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you draft and who you draft, there are no absolutes in
this thing. You do your homework as best you can,'' Diamondbacks
General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The projecting of where these players will be in three or four
years is difficult, because many of them use aluminum bats, and you
have to take into consideration what might be inferior competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with what we've done in our first three drafts,
particularly the first one in 1996. But none of them have reached
the major leagues, and you can't truly assess everything until that
time comes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
