<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     05-27 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER'S BOUNTY GOES BUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ At long last, the Anaheim Angels are seeing
the Tim Belcher they thought they had signed to a two-year, $10.2
million contract last December.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher put together his third consecutive solid outing
Wednesday night, but there was something missing as Belcher came up
short in his bid for a third consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, it was the Angels offense that took the night off in a
3-2 loss to the Baltimore Orioles before 22,058 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare showing _ or non-showing _ by the Angels hitters
in a game pitched by Belcher. The offense had averaged 5.9 runs per
game in Belcher's starts this season, including six games in which
they scored six or more runs.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Orioles starter Sidney Ponson (5-3) held the
Angels to four hits in eight innings, the Angels' two runs scoring
on solo home runs by Mo Vaughn (No. 10) and Garret Anderson (No.
11).
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Rhodes pitched a 1-2-3 ninth and earned his first save of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who gave up three runs and four hits in seven-plus
innings, had won his previous two starts before Wednesday, which
confirmed Angels manager Terry Collins' belief that Belcher's bad
starts early in the season were nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that would concern me would be his health,''
Collins said. ``Was his arm OK? Was there a drastic drop in
velocity from last year? There hasn't been. Command of his stuff
has to be there, and he's starting to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins also said he never sensed that Belcher got down on
himself during his slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think `down' as much as if he had a bad game, he
couldn't wait to get back out there,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   When Belcher has been hit this season, he's been hit hard. Going
into Wednesday's game, opposing batters were hitting .348 against
him. His 11 home runs allowed were tied for third-worst in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the home run ball that hurt him early on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Baines homered with one out in the second inning for a
1-0 Orioles lead. It was Baines' 356th career homer, moving him
past Gary Gaetti into 50th place on the all-time list. Later in the
second, Charles Johnson's two-out single on a 1-2 pitch scored Will
Clark for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick homered to lead off the third inning for a 3-0
Baltimore lead, but Belcher settled down after that.
</P>
<P>
   After Bordick's homer, Belcher retired the next 15 Orioles
batters, taking him through the seventh inning. It took a couple of
outstanding defensive plays to keep the streak going.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning third baseman Troy Glaus dived to his left
to snag a smash by Albert Belle, then threw him out at first. In
the seventh, right fielder Todd Greene caught a long drive by
Delino DeShields while crashing into the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's streak ended when he walked Johnson to begin the
eighth, and that was enough for Collins to summon relief help from
the bullpen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
