<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ROGER Goodell is one of NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue's
lieutenants and has been a behind-the-scenes backer of the
anything-goes movement to put pro football back in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Goodell was holding a scale model of the planned
rebuilt LA Coliseum and he dropped it on himself, opening a gash
that required 30 stitches to close and a calf-high walking cast.
</P>
<P>
   There is a message in there somewhere. Maybe that plague, famine
and pestilence will follow if the NFL ignores Houston's
flesh-and-bones proposal to chase a dream in La-La Land.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy to scare the league's ownership. We
could arrange to have a few horse heads turn up under their sheets
and be playing football in our own swanky new stadium by the fall
of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to keep reminding yourself that this is a weird
breed with which we are dealing. F. Scott Fitzgerald said the rich
are different from you and me, and the 31 owners of the NFL are
different from most of the rich _ stubborn, cliquish, bloodless. Al
Davis, Bud Adams, Bill Bidwill and the like. This is the strangest
collection of life forms outside of the bar scene in the original
Star Wars.
</P>
<P>
   So they ignore basic realities like a lack of public funding and
a shortfall of $225 million for 21st century parking garages in
Michael Ovitz's new whiz-bang renovation of the Coliseum and a
desperate attempt to get the NFL back into the nation's
second-largest TV market.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word out of the owners meetings in Atlanta that the
league has decided to back off and take another 30 days to review
this latest offering from Hollywood. There have been no official
announcements. But there are strong indications that commissioner
Tags and his cronies are talking about extending the Sept. 15
deadline for LA to get its act together.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is as much a revelation as learning that the
president plays fast and loose with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   However, after all these many months of waiting patiently, doing
all the right things and allowing himself to be used as the NFL's
foil in this rigged-from-the-start expansion game, Houston's Bob
McNair may have come to the end of the rope from which he has been
dangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to just fold our tent on Sept. 16,'' McNair
said. ``But do we continue to pursue the 32nd NFL franchise?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it becomes clear that their approach is delay, delay and
delay on the 32nd franchise, then I think it would be wise to turn
our attention then to an existing team that has problems in its
current city. That's not to say we're not talking to people right
now, because we are. I'd just say that if the NFL chooses to delay
past the Sept. 15 date, then we've got to look at turning 100
percent of our attention to getting an existing team rather than
about the 80 percent of the time we're spending now.''
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on how far the NFL wants to chase the LA fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand people saying, `Wow!' to the new LA plan,'' said
McNair's right hand, Steve Patterson. ``I mean, we could have put
glass with a frosted cocktail rim and salt around our stadium and
called it the Cuervo Dome. But we can pay for our deal. They don't
have the money, and they don't have approval from the Coliseum
Commission to do what they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're dealing with just two parties here _ us
and the NFL. Our deal in Houston is far more complicated. We've got
the concerns of the rodeo to take into account, the county's
deadlines and commitments, and the city has to decide what it wants
to do with a new downtown (basketball/hockey) arena. We just can't
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   And they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the NFL wants to be in Houston and eventually will be. But
whenever the NFL is ready and is through using Houston to leverage
every single dollar out of every other city that has not ponied up
for a new stadium and a sweetheart lease. If the league does extend
the Sept. 15 deadline _ formally or otherwise _ then this is the
signal for the bootlicking to stop and the hardball wheeling and
dealing to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is in play, having just had a stadium proposal voted
down. So are Buffalo, Minnesota and Oakland. And keep an eye on New
Orleans, where the closings of many corporate headquarters are
drying up a major revenue source.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having conversations with many people right now, and I
don't want to mention names because then it will all stop,'' McNair
said. ``But there are a lot of teams that might not be able to make
a go in their current markets. If the NFL doesn't want to deal us
into the expansion game, maybe it's time we went out and did
something on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Past time. Way past time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
