A2911 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-ARIZONA_VERDERIVE     05-27 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA_VERDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDE MAY BE SMALL, BUT IT PACKS A WALLOP  
 UPPER AREAS HARD TO FIND, JOY TO FISH 
</HEADLINE>
 RIVER-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost any experienced Arizona angler knows that the Verde River
above Horseshoe Lake contains smallmouth bass.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a more desirable fish than the smallmouth.
An old cartoon perfectly fits the smallmouth. In the cartoon, two
buzzards, known as birds that eat dead creatures, are sitting in a
tree. One says to the other, ``Patience, hell, I'm gonna kill
something.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the smallmouth. It constantly chases down prey. Its red
eyes, nasty disposition and great battling ability make it a
favorite of fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Verde. Significant numbers of anglers pursue the
smallmouth in the mid to lower reaches of the Verde. But they don't
know about its potential upstream.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Burton, an assistant director for the Arizona Game and Fish
Department in charge of services, once was a research biologist and
did a lengthy fisheries study on the upper Verde.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of Arizona's major rivers. Its flow is modest at the
upper end but grows in size from feeder streams as it progresses to
Horseshoe. It almost never gets very large _ not at all like the
Salt River _ but it's extremely important because of the riparian
areas it nourishes. It also keeps water in Horseshoe and Bartlett
lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, it contains seven native fish, tying it with
Aravaipa Creek for the most in the state. Included are two
endangered fish _ the razorback sucker and the Colorado pike minnow
_ and the threatened spinedace.
</P>
<P>
   Burton is a Type A personality, an extremely bright, friendly
man who seems to be in perpetual motion. He's so knowledgeable
about wildlife biology that he can answer almost any question, even
rhetorical ones.
</P>
<P>
   He and his boss, Steve Ferrell, who is the deputy director of
the agency, have fished the upper reaches of the Verde together too
many times to remember. They seldom encounter other anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Where are we talking about? Between Prescott and Ash Fork on
U.S. 89. You're right, that's a lot farther northwest than you were
expecting.
</P>
<P>
   This stretch of river was reached by going north of Prescott to
just beyond Paulden. There you'll see a sign on the right that
announces Verde Ranch Ranch Road. Take that road for about five
miles. There you'll encounter a road to your right. It's Forest
Road 638. You have to look up the road to see the marker.
</P>
<P>
   This road goes south. It's too rough for cars. A high-clearance
vehicle is needed, not necessarily a 4x4. Most maps show that the
road goes to the stream and out the other side. It doesn't.
Prescott National Forest was having too much trouble with
all-terrain vehicles and closed the road at the rim where it drops
down to the Verde.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a half-mile hike on a steep road with many rolling
rocks to the river where an awesome scene appears.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the area has been closed to livestock grazing for a
number of years. The river is lined now by large numbers of young
cottonwoods and willows. Its water is absolutely beautiful. The
trees have allowed the current to slow and create marshes and
waterweeds that slow the current even more. You probably won't see
a more impressive riparian area.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks, songbirds, beavers, muskrats, predators and fish now
thrive on this stretch of river. It's wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet water below riffles is filled with fish, some very small
because this area isn't fished enough. Spinners and other lures are
deadly in this areas. Some of us caught nothing but small fish.
Burton hit a honey hole and caught some larger smallmouth, a
largemouth, a channel catfish and a round-tail chub, which looks
like a trout and was called a Verde trout by early settlers. All
but the chub are exotics in Arizona but were stocked. The
largemouth was about 2 pounds. Ferrell caught his share, too.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a wonderful place for children old enough to do
the hike in and out. Fish are thick and the catching easy.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the farther anglers go downstream, the larger the
fish. And the rock formations along the river make even more a
beautiful spot.
</P>
<P>
   Like parts of the Black River, this river needs anglers. Food
doesn't match the number of fish. A lot of them need to be removed
to promote a larger average size.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rather long drive but a great fishing trip for light
tackle and fly-fishing gear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barry Burkhart can be reached at barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
