<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HN     05-27 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Pedro Astacio worried so much about who was on first base Wednesday
night, he forgot who was at home plate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glen Barker put the winning run in scoring position with his
speed in the ninth inning. Craig Biggio pushed it across with his
bat as the Astros stretched their winning streak to four with a 3-2
victory over the Colorado Rockies in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, one of the fastest Astros, played a game of
cat-and-mouse with Astacio. Inserted as a pinch runner following a
single by Paul Bako, Barker worked Astacio from first base while
the pitcher worked to Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   Barker eventually stole second.
</P>
<P>
   The distraction must have worked; after Biggio fouled off
several pitches, Astacio hung a 3-2 breaking ball that Biggio sent
up the middle for the game-winning single and the Astros' fourth
straight come-from-behind victory and 17th overall.
</P>
<P>
   At 29-16, the Astros are off to the best 45-game start in club
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking to try and deke me back and stuff to keep me
thinking about going back so my jump wasn't as good,'' Barker said
of Astacio. `` That's what their plan is, so you have to play the
game back.''
</P>
<P>
   Astacio (4-4) kept the Astros off balance most of the night
before they chipped away at a 2-0 deficit, scoring the tying and
winning runs in the last two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio allowed nine hits and struck out seven in 8 innings. The
loss broke his four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro did a good job of keeping us off balance,'' said Biggio,
who went 3-for-5 and is a .378 career hitter against Astacio. ``You
can't steal off him. His slide step is real fast, real quick.
Barker did a good job picking a good pitch to get himself in
scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Powell (3-1) pitched two scoreless innings in relief of Sean
Bergman, striking out three batters while suffering from a stomach
flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning with the chills, and my whole body
ached, which is something you don't want to have, especially
against the Rockies,'' Powell said. ``Once you get out there, the
adrenaline kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part was between innings sitting. They asked me how
I felt, and I was all right. Then we had a long (eighth) inning,
and I started feeling weak again.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight night, Carl Everett delivered late.
Everett, who drove in both Astros runs Tuesday, pulled them even at
2 in the eighth inning of Wednesday's game with a sacrifice fly
that scored Bill Spiers. Spiers had reached on an error by second
baseman Chris Sexton.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to be a high-scoring series, pitting two of
the National League's most explosive offenses, has turned into one
pitching duel after another. In three games, the teams have
combined for 15 runs, the Astros winning 5-2, 2-1 and 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman held the Rockies to five hits Wednesday before being
lifted in the seventh inning. His only lapse came in the fourth,
when the Rockies took advantage of a walk and two hits for their
two runs.
</P>
<P>
   All six starting pitchers used in the series have gone at least
six innings. Shane Reynolds and Mike Hampton each went nine innings
as the Astros won the first two games of a four-game set, which
concludes today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some good pitching. Pedro Astacio has been a good
pitcher for a long time,'' Bergman said. ``Just because they are
the Rockies doesn't mean they can't pitch. You have to give them as
much credit as you would us for pitching a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker said, ``Even to get three runs off Astacio
he was all over the corners, changing speeds, throwing breaking
balls. We really battled him hard. I know it looks like we weren't
hitting, but when a guy is pitching that way you don't hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado took the lead when Bergman walked Neifi Perez to lead
off the fourth and Larry Walker singled. Dante Bichette's sacrifice
fly and Todd Helton's RBI double gave the Rockies a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little frustrating knowing that I gave up a run
without giving up a hard-hit ball,'' Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sliced the lead to 2-1 in the fifth when Biggio hit a
one-out double to center, advanced to third on Spiers' grounder and
scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stranded eight runners Wednesday, bringing the total
to 32 for the series, but did enough in the final two innings to
win.
</P>
<P>
   With a little help from Barker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it may have helped a little bit to have Barker on
base, just a simple splitting of the concentration of a guy that
was already a little weary, I'm sure,'' Dierker said. ``That whole
situation at first base, maybe Biggio got a pitch to hit because of
it, or maybe he (Astacio) just made a mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
