<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL PUTS TRUST IN CURVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ask Troy Percival about the groove he's been
in recently and he'll give you the hand _ meaning ``stop right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival is a little superstitious when it comes to talking
about his string of nearly flawless performances for the Anaheim
Angels. ``Ask me about it when it's over,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday's game, Percival had thrown 91/3
consecutive hitless innings covering his previous nine appearances.
It's the longest stretch of hitless innings by a reliever in the
big leagues this season.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he hadn't allowed a baserunner in his previous eight
appearances covering 72/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Percival's success this season _ 12 saves in 13 opportunities _
is partly a result of him trusting his curveball again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two years I used my curveball quite a bit,'' he said.
``But the last two years I got away from it because I couldn't
throw it for strikes. Now, it looks like I'm throwing a lot of
off-speed stuff but I'm still throwing 85 percent fastballs.
Hitters have to respect my off-speed stuff because I'm throwing it
for strikes, and that makes my fastball that much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival also credits the overall success of the bullpen for his
success this season. The bullpen's ERA going into Wednesday was
2.87, best in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is predicated on the pitchers before me,'' Percival
said. ``Every time we get a lead, the bullpen is keeping it a save
situation for me. It limits the pitches I have to throw down there
(warming up in the bullpen).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's saved a lot of games, but I don't know if his stuff has
been as consistent as right now,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``His location, velocity, I don't know if it's ever been like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sparks skipped: Pitcher Steve Sparks will have his next start
bumped from Friday to Saturday so that Chuck Finley can remain on a
five-day schedule. When asked if Sparks was upset about the move,
Collins said: ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, though, said he doesn't have a problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised,'' said Sparks, who is 1-4 with a 6.04 ERA
in nine starts. ``I was here last year and I know how they shuffle
guys to keep Finley on his rotation. I'm used to that. It doesn't
bother me. I understand it. Even if I was pitching better, as well
as Chuck's throwing, they want to try to keep him on as normal a
rotation as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With next week's off-day (Thursday) falling on Sparks' turn in
the rotation, it's possible Sparks will miss his turn completely.
</P>
<P>
   __ It was no hitting clinic: The Angels pitchers took batting
practice for the first time this season in preparation for their
games in National League ballparks starting June 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very good,'' said Collins, who threw batting
practice to the pitchers. ``They need a few more days. We just need
them to learn to bunt, that's all. And know how to slide.''
</P>
<P>
   Sliding practice will come next week, but Collins doesn't
anticipate the pitchers needing to slide in a game very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get on base,'' he said. ``When they do get on, it
isn't pretty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
