r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     05-27 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOKSTRATTEN WEIGHS IN ON NFL AND L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm bamboozled by the world's events, unable to comprehend the
weird goings-on.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never understand how that sterling French gendarme,
Inspector Clouseau, wound up in charge of this country's espionage
security at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do I quite understand how Mr. Magoo, that notoriously myopic
cartoon buffoon, positioned himself to direct all those wayward
sorties for NATO, that peace-loving alliance that spreads so much
world-wide good-will with its lethal bombings of foreign embassies,
hospitals, prisons, trains, buses, refugee encampments and, I'm
sure once in awhile, even Slobodan Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   I'm totally in the dark about the stunning phenomenon of ``Star
Wars'', a science fiction piece of claptrap with cornball cinematic
gadgetry that is about as phony as, say, a Paul Tagliabue spiel
about the NFL returning to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite that (italicize that) phony, but just as
appallingly superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when it comes to current affairs that leave me hoarse
with laughter, that continuing NFL-L.A. football saga ranks right
up there at the top for sheer comedic impact.
</P>
<P>
   You might know that the latest development out of the latest NFL
meeting on the subject is that nothing is new, meaning Paul
Tagliabue still is playing it coyly with L.A. and encouraging
millionaires like Eli Broad, Ed Roski and Michael Ovitz to keep
coming up with glamorous new stadium and revenue plans.
</P>
<P>
   I just wish one, or all of these high-powered gentlemen would
stand up to the bullying Tagliabue and inform him, ``You can take
your NFL expansion franchise promise, and shove it! We only get on
our hands and knees in L.A. during earthquakes.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-time attorney for the late Carroll Rosenbloom when he
owned the Los Angeles Rams and an interested observer of these
NFL-L.A. proceedings, Ed Gregory Hookstratten isn't sure pro
football is destined to return here in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we seem to have going on now in L.A. is a lot of
amateurism on one side and heavy politicizing on the other,'' says
Hookstratten, a Beverly Hills based mover and shaker who once also
represented Elvis Presley and Johnny Carson and still does business
for such people as Tom Brokaw, Vin Scully, Dick Enberg, Bryant
Gumble, Jim Hill and many others. ``A lot of the participants
haven't spent as many as five minutes in an NFL office. They just
don't know the game, or the heavy politics that are involved in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hookstratten has maintained the many contacts he made around the
NFL during his years with Rosenbloom, and it's his distinct
impression that the NFL would rather not return to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, it's going to cost a ton of money to totally
renovate the Coliseum,'' he says. ``With the cost overruns that are
inevitable, the price is going to be exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to put up that kind of money? There is no way the
local government is going to do it. Not with school teachers
needing to be paid more money. Not with roads needing to be
upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I doubt, when all is said and done, that any one person is
going to put up his own money in such a risky investment. Look,
you'll only have 10 NFL games a year at the Coliseum. Where's all
the money going to come from? Concerts? Forget it. What group's
going to fill the Coliseum?
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem, as I see it, is who's going to pay for what.
The NFL wants the local government to chip in some money, but I'm
not sure that can happen. And guys like Eli Broad and Ed Roski
didn't become multi-millionaires blowing their money on bad
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hookstratten sees parking as another Coliseum problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they really think parking structures around the Coliseum
are going to be the answer?'' he says. ``Absolutely no way. You'll
all go in at the same time, and go out at the same time. That'll
take hours. And what happens when a car breaks down. It'll be an
absolute mess. To me, the parking structure idea is laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hookstratten also doesn't see L.A. corporate interests tripping
over themselves to purchase luxury suite boxes, nor locals plunging
down on PSLs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lifestyle here in Southern California is a lot different
than it is in Cleveland, Ohio, or Irving, Texas,'' says
Hookstratten. ``In those places, going to a sporting venue is a
vital part of social life. But here in Southern California, we have
access to the beaches, to the desert, to the mountains, to Las
Vegas, to do many different places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luxury suites won't be an easy sell here, and there is no way
the PSLs (private seat licensing) would be. No way you're going to
get many L.A. fans to spend extra money to buy their tickets so
they can be assured of buying the same ones for future years. That
might work in some towns, but never will in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Hookstratten believes the best area for a new stadium would be
at Chavez Ravine on the Dodger Stadium property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the perfect location with all the necessary roads in
place,'' he says. ``The next best place would be the Hollywood Park
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Hookstratten doesn't envision Paul Tagliabue changing his murky
stance towards L.A. in the upcoming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is going to continue its brinkmanship until some group
convinces the league it has the money and the wherewithal to do
it---and so far none has,'' he says. ``What's troubling is the
clock is clicking, and people in L.A. are finding other things to
do with their Sunday afternoons in the fall rather than look at NFL
games. I know a lot of people in L.A. now totally indifferent to
the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gregory Hookstratten was with the Rams when Rosenbloom had
his dispute with the L.A. politicians that led to Rosenbloom
deciding to move the franchise to Anaheim after the 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carroll wanted to put the team's daily training facilities at
Rancho Park which was near the team's headquarters on Pico
Boulevard,'' recalls Hookstratten. ``But an L.A. councilman killed
the deal, and that's when Carroll began talking with the Anaheim
people. Within a year or two, the deal was made. If the L.A.
politicians had given Carroll what he wanted back in 1976---and
Carroll didn't want much, in retrospect---I'm sure the Rams still
would be in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   And we wouldn't be treated to the obscene spectacle of
multi-millionaire moguls throwing themselves at the mercy of Paul
Tagliabue and his NFL bosses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
