<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT COULD EARN GALAXY STARTING SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Newly acquired New Zealand midfielder Simon
Elliott might have earned himself a start when the Los Angeles
Galaxy visits Columbus on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott became the first non-Latin foreigner to sign with Los
Angeles last week. Against New England Saturday, the former
Stanford standout made a strong contribution as a 35th-minute
substitute during the Galaxy's 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   He might not be the player L.A. needs to draw fans `/E5P-Y gate,
but as Elliott points out, there are other ways to draw fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I don't quite fit the mold of a typical sort of
L.A.-market foreign player,'' said Elliott. ``But if the team sort
of does well and gets wins, that will get the fans coming
regardless of where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid was impressed with Elliott's vision and
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played very well,'' said Schmid. ``He's not a
flashy player, but he's a player who does the little things to help
connect the team. I thought the thing he did really well was give
us some cover at midfield. And he did a good job of (giving)
Mauricio (Cienfuegos) the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he showed he can help us a little bit, we're thinking
about starting him (against Columbus). He's a foreign player. You
expect guys like that to play and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hermosillo returns:Schmid hasn't talked to Carlos Hermosillo
since his Mexican team was eliminated from the Mexican playoffs
over the weekend. Hermosillo, expected to arrive in 7-10 days,
could be back for the Galaxy's next home game June 6 against Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had agreed that after his season was over in Mexico, he
could take a week to 10 days off,'' said Schmid. ``I'd rather have
him take a break now than come into a situation and be tired. I
want to win a championship and that means we have to win games in
August, September and October. So if we miss him for one more game
that's OK, because we will need him later.''
</P>
<P>
   __ New old face: Another new face during training this week was
also a familiar one. Harut Karapetyan, who spent 1996 and '97 with
Los Angeles before recent stints with San Jose and Tampa Bay, is
hoping to earn a roster spot with the Galaxy again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's left-footed and offers us some options on that side of
the field,'' Schmid said. ``He's somebody who's comfortable in Los
Angeles because his family is here. Sometimes those players play
better when they're closer to home. He's had a couple good goals in
training and he's definitely someone we're giving a serious look
to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
