<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS LOOK LIKE REAL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is almost Memorial Day. The first checkpoint in the marathon.
The first alert for contenders.
</P>
<P>
   And if first place is still on the radar screen when summer is
sworn in for duty, it's time to take your baseball team seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of the lingering turnstile apathy at BOB, take a moment
and grasp the significance of what's happening here. The
Diamondbacks are fresh, entertaining, no longer nine ushers in a
giant amusement park. They have blown a bundle of games and
survived. They are a second-year franchise flirting with the
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The other night on ESPN, noted baseball analyst Joe Morgan was
asked an interesting question. Of all the teams in the National
League West, who did he feel was most capable of running away with
the division?
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco or Los Angeles,'' Manager Buck Showalter
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan picked the Diamondbacks. Without a hint of reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Joe has never been a GM or a manager,'' Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Winning carries its own aura, and while nothing is what it
seemed to be in 1998, the personality of this team is almost
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   We have learned that Jay Bell is not only combustible, but once
loved chemistry experiments in high school. That Joe Garagiola Jr.
is more than just a punch line, and if you needed any more proof
that Luis Gonzalez was a classic heist, well, the Hall of Fame
called earlier in the week. They want his bat.
</P>
<P>
   We have learned that Showalter isn't so rigid, after all, and if
you could've only heard the salty tales he told Wednesday. And not
only have we seen how Matt Williams responds to a bad year, we have
learned his wife wants him to ponder a career in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I can act,'' Williams said. ``I can do everything from
Jean-Claude Van Damme to Al Pacino. I can run the whole gamut. It
all just comes naturally. In my own mind, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Question is, can the Diamondbacks run the gamut?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the division is ripe for plucking. The Dodgers are
already in panic mode, reassigning coaches in effort to shake up
the room. The Giants are a scrappy bunch, but certain to encounter
the laws of gravity. And in the attrition of summer, during in the
guts of the season, the Diamondbacks' rotation has the potential to
carry the load. Even without Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   Much credit goes to Garagiola Jr. Whether by design or dumb
luck, there is an undeniable chemistry on this team, a lineup
producing a whole greater than the sum of its parts. For all the
solid acquisitions, the best move he didn't make was peddling Brian
Anderson, who was stellar in Wednesday's start against the Padres
and will fill a pivotal role in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   And you might want to take a seat for this: If it continues,
Garagiola Jr. will be in the running for executive of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great, balanced lineup,'' Gonzalez said. ``So much
was made out of our pitching staff in the off-season that I think
everybody forgot about the hitters. And I think we've surprised
some people with where we're at now. I think we're starting to open
some eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting to look like the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a really good mixture of guys,'' Gonzalez said.
``And we've all seemed to jell real well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are also creating a strong sense of place, a
reason to come to BOB. Entering Wednesday's game against the
Padres, they were 16-5 at home, the best mark in the majors. An
encouraging trend, and in June, they will play 19 of 26 games here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, they don't come to see a baseball game,''
Showalter said. ``They come to see the Yankees win. They don't come
to see the venue. They don't come to see the stadium. They come
there for one thing. To see the Yankees win. If you don't deliver
that, it ain't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, it's happening now. And as improbable as it
seemed eight months ago, it could happen all the way to September. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
