<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TALK WITH VAN BOXMEER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ John Van Boxmeer interviewed Tuesday for the
Los Angeles Kings' coaching position, and afterward, general
manager Dave Taylor labeled the Long Beach Ice Dogs' coach a
``serious candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good meeting with John,'' Taylor said Wednesday
afternoon. ``He's had a lot of experience as a coach. I think he
handles the bench well and I think he knows how to motivate his
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor interviewed former Buffalo Sabres coach Ted Nolan last
week. He said he would like to set up interviews next week with
``two or three'' more candidates for the job before inviting anyone
back for a second interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I've met with everybody, if one guy seems to be a
clear-cut No. 1 candidate, we'll move ahead and try to get a deal
done,'' Taylor said. ``Hopefully before the draft (on June 26), we
can get a coach in place. It's not absolutely necessary, but if I
can do that, I'd like to.''
</P>
<P>
   The job has been vacant since April 19, when the Kings decided
not to bring back Larry Robinson for a fifth season. Robinson was
hired Wednesday as an assistant coach by the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer, who could not be reached for comment, has forged a
relationship with Taylor the last two seasons, during which the Ice
Dogs have had a limited affiliation with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a comfort level with him,'' Taylor said, ``and
because of that we consider him a serious candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor would not name the other coaches he wants to interview,
but it is believed that Detroit assistant Dave Lewis is one of
them. Lewis, however, is expected to be the top candidate if Red
Wings coach Scotty Bowman decides to retire.
</P>
<P>
   In another matter, Taylor confirmed that the Kings have decided
not to offer a contract to 1997 draft choice Matt Zultek, a forward
who will thus become available in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Zultek was chosen with the 15th pick in 1997. Under NHL rules,
because Zultek was a first-round selection, the Kings will receive
the 15th selection in the second round this year as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt hasn't developed like we thought he would the last two
years,'' Taylor said. ``We feel we'll get a prospect as good as or
better than Matt Zultek with the 43rd pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zultek's agent, Larry Kelly, ``If they're not keen on him,
it's better for him to go back in the draft. I know Matt will play
in the NHL at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Zultek scored an overtime goal Sunday that gave his junior team,
the Ottawa 67's, the Memorial Cup championship, but there were
concerns about his lack of physical play given his 6-foot-3,
218-pound frame. Zultek was selected with a St. Louis draft choice
acquired in the 1996 deal that sent Wayne Gretzky to the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor continues to try to sign 1997 sixth-round selection
Richard Seeley, a defenseman. If Seeley is not signed by Tuesday,
he will go back into the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're negotiating with Richard and hope to have him signed by
June 1,'' Taylor said. ``I think we have a chance there.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the Kings have a shot at signing
Aki Berg. Taylor said there is nothing to report regarding
negotiations with the Finnish defenseman. Berg spent this season
playing in Finland after a contract dispute with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting with a clean slate and we'll see where they
take it,'' said Kelly, who is also Berg's agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have begun negotiations with another Finnish
defenseman, 24-year-old Jere Karalahti, a 1993 draft selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had only preliminary discussions with the Kings,''
said Karalahti's agent, Don Baizley. ``Nothing is resolved yet. I
don't have any timeline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
