<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED-HOT GRIFFEY'S MAGESTIC HOMER POWERS MARINER ROMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ A right-handed pitcher with a lifetime record 20
games below .500, the Minnesota Twins' LaTroy Hawkins doesn't seem
like a guy who dominates Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey had just one hit off Hawkins in 11 at-bats before
Wednesday, but he improved on that in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   After a single in the first, he tore into a third-inning
changeup from Hawkins, rocketing it 453 feet into the upper deck in
right field.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's major league-leading 19th homer crashed off a seat and
disappeared behind the white curtain that covers the uppermost
seats at the Metrodome. It was the longest of the Mariners' 95 home
runs this year and the second of four for the M's in Wednesday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   They took an 11-3 win behind eight innings from Jamie Moyer and
returned home with a .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys look at it as 1-for-11,'' Griffey said of his career
mark off Hawkins. ``When players are hot, it doesn't matter who's
pitching. When players are cold, it doesn't matter who's pitching.
It's just one of those things that happen in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But things like that don't happen for everyone. Everyone can't
hit eight homers in 12 games. Everyone can't take a pitch off the
shoetops and blast it to Mankato.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said Mariners rookie pitcher Jordan
Zimmerman, who recently joined the team from Class AA. ``That ball
had to be 520 feet up. You don't see that (in AA), I'll tell you
that. And it was a good pitch, too. It was down in the dirt, and he
pretty much golfed it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a drive that would please Griffey's Florida neighbors,
Mark O'Meara and Tiger Woods. Even Griffey, who does his best not
to talk about homers, gave in after this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it,'' he said. ``I knew I hit it, and that was
it. I knew when it left the bat it was high, and some places you
have to worry about speakers. This is one of those places. I lost
it, (but) I knew I just hit it high and after it got to a certain
point, I was just like, `OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   The homer was the 369th of Griffey's career, tying him with
Ralph Kiner for 45th on the all-time list. Griffey's a little off
Mark McGwire's record pace from last year (at this rate, he'll hit
67), but catcher Tom Lampkin is awestruck all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Mark last year _ unbelievable,'' said Lampkin, who
played with McGwire in St. Louis last year. ``He's just another one
of those guys you shake your head at. You don't know how they do
it, but you know they're going to do it. Every time they do
something like that, you ask yourself, how much more can a guy do?
You figure one of these days they're going to run out of magic or
run out of talent or run out of miracles. But they just keep on
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has been going and going ever since visiting his father
on an off-day May 4. On his way to a road trip in Cleveland,
Griffey stopped by Cinergy Field for batting practice with Ken Sr.,
the Cincinnati Reds' hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Senior noticed a slight flaw in Junior's swing. It took five
games for results to show, but once Griffey started hitting, he
hasn't stopped. In his career-best 15-game hitting streak, Griffey
is batting .441 (26-for-59) with eight homers and 21 runs batted
in. He has improved his average from .270 to .328 during the streak
and is hitting with renewed confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all hitting really is _ being confident that you're
going to go up there and pick out a good pitch and hit it,''
Griffey said. ``If you're not confident in your mechanics, you're
not going to perform like you can, and I think that was the biggest
thing. I couldn't figure out what I was doing wrong. I swung at a
couple of pitches (thrown by Senior), and he told me exactly what I
was doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's homer was majestic, but the one Griffey hit Tuesday
was more significant to hitting coach Jesse Barfield. That blast
was the opposite of this one, a 348-foot bullet down the left-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barometer for Junior, in my opinion, is how hard he hits
the ball to the opposite field,'' said Barfield. ``Even when a
guy's (struggling) at the plate, he can turn on a few balls and you
think, `Oh, man, he's hot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``No. From a mechanics standpoint, when you see a guy drive a
ball out of the ballpark opposite field, you know he's doing
everything right. You can't cheat and do that. That was impressive
today, don't get me wrong. But a batter can cheat and do that if he
has any kind of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, that wasn't a cheating swing. That was hands. He
got the hands through the zone and stayed closed and the ball
jumped off his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   As it left the park, the homer traveled over a sign for the
``FuncoLand Fun Zone'' at the Metrodome. Thousands of elementary
school kids were among the 17,022 fans on hand, a fact not lost on
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made a big difference,'' he said. ``It's fun to play in
front of 40 or 50,000 people, but to see all those kids out there
yelling, it felt like a playground.''
</P>
<P>
   For Griffey, it didn't just feel like a playground. It was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
