<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACK YOUR NUT CASES FOR THIS TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his quest to become America's nuttiest golfer,
Braemar Country Club member Nobby Orens came up a few goobers shy
of a full bag. It was not for lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Orens scattered ``peanut shells'' around the globe. He
played 152 rounds of golf during an odyssey that took him to 12
countries, seven states and 40 cities.
</P>
<P>
   He played on 41 different courses, 26 of them new.
</P>
<P>
   He logged 38,445 frequent-flier miles in the process, leaving
his wife to sometimes wonder just where the heck he was, anyway,
and when he would be coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Orens' destinations included Alaska, New Zealand, Hawaii and
Florida. He even managed to work in a family vacation and keep his
travel agency running.
</P>
<P>
   All this globe-trotting was only good for second place in the
Golf Nuts Society of America's annual quest to identify the golfer
most nuts about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wendi Keene, of Scottsdale, Ariz., is top nut for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Orens was operating under the assumption the award
went to the person who put together the most impressive resume
during the year. But as in a skins game, the ``carry-over'' factor
came into play. The winner had been amassing points for 12 years
and finished 1998 with 27,942 points, jumping to the top spot from
No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Orens, who has been affiliated with this loose group for five
years, started 1998 in 10th place with 9,095 points. He earned
nearly twice as many points as Keene did but finished 1,699 points
behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the lead was too much to overcome in one year,'' Orens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bukt he's racked up some impressive numbers. He started playing
golf five years ago and has taken his game to 173 courses
worldwide. He's played 865 rounds, for an average of 173 rounds
annually. In September of 1996 he played 33 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   There is another benefit, besides logging thousands of
frequent-flier miles.Orens has improved his index, which is used to
calculate a handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick recap of some of his more memorable stunts last
year:
</P>
<P>
   __ Visiting Alaska in July, he played 200 holes in one day. It
took 17 hours and 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   __ In September he flew to Auckland, New Zealand, where he was
met by a TV crew for a New Zealand golf show and driven to Gulf
Harbor Golf Club, where he played 18 holes. He then flew back to
Los Angeles and played 18 holes at his home club. Because the
international dateline was in play, Orens played in Auckland and
L.A. on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after flying 13,000 miles in 72 hours, he jumped
back on a plane and flew to Maui for a 100-hole tournament.
</P>
<P>
   __ In October, he played in a tournament sponsored by one of the
airlines. There was an ``Honest John'' contest, in which golfers
predict their final score. Orens predicted an 89 and ended up with
a 113.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the worst score I have shot in almost four years. For
that, I was awarded `The Optimist' trophy for missing my prediction
by the largest number, 24,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given stunts like this, Orens thought he was in pretty good
shape for bagging the trophy. But he decided to finish the year
with a flourish, just in case. In November he and his wife went to
a conference in Honolulu. But he had been invited to play in a
charity tournament on a new Greg Norman course in Naples, Fla.,
right after the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flew from Honolulu to Los Angeles on November 16, landing
at 9:04 p.m. I kissed my wife goodbye and got on a 10 p.m. flight
to Miami, landing at 5:47 a.m. on November 17, and took a car to
Naples, 110 miles from Miami,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   That tournament started at 10 a.m. and ended at 3 p.m. Orens was
back in L.A. by 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during 1998, he thought he could only do this kind
of crazy stuff for a year. But the title is so close, it would be a
shame to abandon the quest. So on July 20th, Orens plans to play 54
holes of golf.
</P>
<P>
   In one day. In three cities. In two countries separated by the
Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   He'll start the day at 5:30 a.m., teeing off at Stokely Park
Golf Course in London. At 10:30 a.m. he'll jump on the Concorde for
a quick flight to John F. Kennedy Airport. A tee time is reserved
at nearby Clearview Golf Course, where he'll play a quick 18. Then
he will fly to Los Angeles and arrive home in time for 18 holes at
his home course and then dinner with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   So how many time zones will that journey span?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got a clue,'' Orens said. ``Whatever is between
London and Los Angeles.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
