r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-CSUNANAL-ANALYSIS     05-27 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNANAL-ANALYSIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DULL HAS ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the right move.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge President Blenda Wilson, who created hard
feelings in the community when she forced out Robert Hiegert in
1995, gave the department a boost when she hired Richard Dull as
the university's athletic director on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN athletics has been plagued by bad decisions, scandals and
budget deficits. The problems aren't insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Dull, 53, has a healthy understanding of intercollegiate
athletics. He presents himself not as a potential cheerleader of
CSUN but as a professional who knows the nuances of dealing within
a department, university, conference and the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges he faces at Northridge are daunting. The athletic
department has an $800,000 deficit. Students and the community seem
to be apathetic about anything the university does, except for a
small bloc of neighborhood groups opposed to plans for construction
of an on-campus football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the athletic department's relationship within the CSUN
academic community soured in the wake of mistakes made by former
A.D. Paul Bubb _ or embarrassing things that happened on his watch
_ specifically the arrest of women's basketball coach Michael
Abraham on federal cocaine trafficking charges and the cover-up of
an incident in which a football player was shot at a party.
</P>
<P>
   Dull has to repair that bridge, which is one of his stated
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Lewis, vice chancellor for university relations at the
University of Nebraska at Kearney, said CSUN made the right
decision to hire Dull.
</P>
<P>
   ```He's a low-key guy,'' said Lewis, who worked with Dull when
Dull was the athletic director at Kearney from 1995-98. ``He does a
lot behind the scenes. He restructured our entire (athletic)
department. He made some hard decisions and did it with style and
class. Very professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Dull arrived on campus a month ago sincerely
contrite about his role in one of college sport's infamous scandals
_ the cocaine-induced death of Maryland basketball star Len Bias in
1986. Dull was forced to resign five months after Bias died and he
spent the next 10 years in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Bias' death uncovered investigations that revealed a Maryland
athletic department that tolerated basketball players with 1.5 GPAs
or lower. Many of the NCAA's get-tough standards for incoming
student-athletes were created because of the Maryland scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Dull discussed the circumstances of his resignation at Maryland
the day he interviewed. He said he made mistakes as a young
athletic director in admitting athletes who had no chance of
graduating. He's once again ready to prove himself as an effective
Division I athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dull returned from his college-athletics exile in 1995,
when he became the athletic director at Nebraska-Kearney, he's
familiarized himself with the new NCAA rules and philosophies. He
was successful at Kearney and also at Moravian College, a Division
III school with an enrollment of just 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   At both schools, Dull put special interest into their
substance-abuse programs. Two weeks ago, in a published interview,
CSUN interim athletic director Sam Jankovich said the athletic
department needs to establish a substance-abuse program.
</P>
<P>
   Dull's stated objectives as a successful athletic director were
pointed directly at CSUN on the day he interviewed. He said he
should report directly to the president. He said the key to
marketing and promoting an athletic department is basic hard work.
He said a Division I university can't afford to carry 20 or more
teams if those teams are mediocre across the board.
</P>
<P>
   He said sports facilities have to be top-notch for the health of
a college athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: It won't take long for Dull to identify
CSUN's strengths and weaknesses. It's time for CSUN to set the
proper course for establishing itself as a viable Division I
university again.
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
