u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     05-27 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL POWER DRIVING SHOW AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mary Pierce, who is engaged to Cleveland second
baseman Roberto Alomar, may be taking a few tips from baseball's
training rooms. It appears Pierce _ she of the 6-foot-tall,
pulverizing power-stroke tennis game _ is heavily into creatine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot see what all the fuss is about in France,'' Pierce
said after her first-round win at the French Open on Tuesday. ``You
can find it in any supermarket in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the mere comparison to America is nearly as bad as
asking for ketchup on your escargot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in spite of the serious culture clash, it is always a
good time to wish you were in Paris. There's Notre Dame. The
Louvre. The Pont Neuf. Sacre Coeur. There are the bagettes. The
butter. The wine. The haughty treatment from Parisiens who detest
les Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But spring is the best time, especially now, thanks to the young
ladies who are making a lot of noise at Roland Garros Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As Pete Sampras rolls and flops in the devilish red clay, and
the men's side of the draw lacks prestige and charisma and (wait
until we get to Wimbledon) tabloid fodder, the women are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   There is Pierce, who is prone to spandex and whose personal
history gets more interesting each step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   And how about the Swiss Miss? She was in a pickle ... for
awhile.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, No. 1-ranked Martina Hingis had already dispatched
with her second-round opponent and a public relations headache.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis beat Frenchwoman Amelie Mauresmo 6-3, 6-3 in a rematch of
the pair's Australian Open final. It was during that Open that
Hingis slammed Mauresmo, calling her ``half a man,'' an intentional
slap at Mauresmo, who is openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   Years after pioneers like Billie Jean King and Martina
Navratilova played on the women's tour after revealing they were
gay and losing endorsement deals, Hingis set the discussion back 20
years with her knock against Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, despite being pumped up in front of the home crowd to
knock off Hingis, Mauresmo faltered in her attempt at payback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to ... sink her. That's when I lost control,''
Mauresmo said.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean there is an end to the women's story lines.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 seed Steffi Graf and No. 3 seed Monica Seles have eight
French Open singles titles between them, but this time around, they
will both be sentimental favorites now that age (Graf is 30) and
setbacks have taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   After being stabbed, watching her father die of stomach cancer
and suffering through eating disorders and depression, Seles is
distressed over the three-month bombing of Yugoslavia and the
destruction of Novi Sad, her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   With a first-round win under her belt, perhaps like Serbian
Vlade Divac of the Sacramento Kings, who played his best basketball
ever during such a horrific time, Seles will find a way to reach
down for something extra these hard days.
</P>
<P>
   For comic relief, though, there are the Williams sisters, whose
bright, eccentric personalities continue to puzzle the tennis media
and many opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tennis Monthly Recap,'' which is written and published by
Venus and Serena Williams _ seeded Nos. 5 and 10 in the Open _
features an article in the latest issue called: ``Serena, Serena,
Serena!'' in which there is a bold prediction that one of the
sisters will win in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   And in case anyone is still looking for additional feminine
subplots, what about Jennifer Capriati?
</P>
<P>
   Capriati's first-round French Open victory comes just one week
after the 23-year-old won the Strasbourg Open, pocketing $27,500
and her first tournament title in six long years.
</P>
<P>
   The last week of tennis victories represents quite a comeback
milestone for Capriati who, in 1990 at age 14 at the French Open,
was the youngest semifinalist ever in a Grand Slam tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, women's tennis is defined by, if not still
recovering from, Capriati's well-publicized rise and fall. As the
bubbly youngster who burned out and then had her every adolescent
mistake held up for international scrutiny, Capriati became a
lightning rod for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   As Capriati's well-chronicled tailspin was played out, tennis
re-wrote its rules, setting new age restrictions for tour
participation. The Women's Tennis Association also struggled with
how to market the game _ something desperately needed in a time
when Virginia Slims dropped sponsorship of the women's tour.
</P>
<P>
   After all this, Capriati's new success and confidence could not
come at a better time. She said there used to be times she'd look
in the mirror, hated herself and wanted to die. But now she is
having fun again. She is stronger and more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it helps Capriati that these days, instead of being the
darling who is going to save tennis, she is just one of many women
who are making the ladies' side of the French Open draw the place
to see or be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
