</P>
<P>
   BATHROOM-SINK (Undated) _ Just when you thought there was no one
left to leave you, the bathroom sink is leaving, too. Those broad
porcelain shoulders you leaned on each morning, gripped in each
hand, that bore the weight of the world for you as you woke,
staring blindly into the void, unaware of where or who you were
until the basin filled, the water stilled and your face rocked
safely into sight. Gone. Or going, with a loud, emptying suck. By
William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PORCELAIN-TUB (New York) _ Imagine a prewar bathroom with a
deep, deep porcelain tub and gleaming (but not too gleaming) nickel
fittings: a wide sunflower shower head and those little porcelain
buttons marked with Hot and Cold in the middle of gutsy crossbar
handles. There are reproductions, of course, but the dream is the
real thing. It was my dream. By Donna Paul.
</P>
