<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2967 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-27 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS HARDLY WORTH STEALING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Now that we know the Chinese have tried to monkey-wrench our
elections and have ripped off our deepest nuclear-weapons secrets
for 20 years, shouldn't we at least TP their embassy?
<P>
   The Chinese are stealing weapons technology from our nuclear
labs, high-tech companies and Roadrunner cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we know the Chinese would never attack us with the
weapons they have developed from the stolen technology. If they
wipe us out, where would they get cigarettes? And weapons secrets?
</P>
<P>
   But the spy scandal has widespread implications. If you're like
me, you require simplistic personal advice and insight from total
strangers to direct your life, and a newspaper horoscope is too
complicated, so you rely heavily on fortune cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, I cracked open my fortune cookie, hoping for good
news about a promotion or a Pulitzer Prize. My ``fortune'' was
microfilm design specs for the W-88 nuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   We have nobody to blame but ourselves. Apparently you don't have
to be a James Bond to steal U.S. government secrets. Austin Powers
could pull it off, baby.
</P>
<P>
   The only crime you're more likely to get away with is removing
the tag from your mattress.
</P>
<P>
   What really hurts is that U.S. firms like Hughes Aerospace
handed sensitive secret technology to the Chinese in order to
protect investments. If a major firm does this, it's smart
business. If you or I do it, it's prison time.
</P>
<P>
   The golden rule: Corporate needs outrank national security. Take
Standard Oil. Please. History buff Jerry Matters says that during
WWII, the Japanese shut off U.S. access to all rubber plantations,
so we had a rubber crisis. The solution was synthetic rubber, the
patent for which was shared by Standard Oil of New Jersey and the
I.G. Farben group of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   So once a year, as American lads were busily killing German lads
and vice versa, Standard Oil's people got together with Farben's
people in neutral Lisbon to talk rubber and maybe play some golf.
Neither government was hip to the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Oil's penalty when the U.S. government found out, after
the war? Ha ha.
</P>
<P>
   China's not alone. As an international game, spying is more
widespread than soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley is probably the spy capital of the world right
now, with sensitive and valuable computer information under
constant siege.
</P>
<P>
   You can't get a table at a good restaurant in Silicon Valley
because of all the spies for foreign governments and cutthroat U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's common for guests at Silicon Valley hotels to demand
private phone lines, since hotel lines and cell phones can be
bugged.
</P>
<P>
   The huge San Francisco Bay Area law firm of Pillsbury, Madison
and Sutro opened a 400-attorney office in Palo Alto, Calif., within
the last year, specializing in protecting ``intellectual property''
_ the secrets everyone is busy stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's only a game.
</P>
<P>
   MORE CRIME: From the Healdsburg, Calif., Tribune's Police Log
(thanks, Ed Flesch): ``When a man ordered a plate of nachos and
disputed payment for the item, he dropped the chips and let them
fall where they may, which was on the floor of the business. The
clerk called police and learned that this was not a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is sharing rubber secrets with an enemy during wartime.
And did you catch the poetic/philosophic turn of phrase in the
first sentence of the nacho report?
</P>
<P>
   From the ``Sheriff's Calls`` in the Pt. Reyes, Calif., Light
(thanks, Les Blodgett): ``Deputies were notified that seven to nine
loose horses were headed east on Manana Way and then turned onto
Highway 1.``
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the local animal control has a vice squad.
</P>
<P>
   NAME DEPT.: Are we gradually returning to the days when your
surname was related to your occupation?
</P>
<P>
   Example: In old Germany and England, the ostler was the gent who
stabled your horse at the inn and mucked the stalls _ the scooper
of poop.
</P>
<P>
   A recent news story quoted an executive for the Metropolitan
Transportation Commission _ Russell Driver. Same day, another story
quoted a museum bird expert named Pamela Swan.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Franson notes that UC Davis has an entomologist named Bob
Bugg, who must be related to the insect Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Archer (a KRON news staffer and NOT an archer) came across
a news story involving an Army officer stationed in Pennsylvania.
Her name is Major Karen Basehore. I had a punch line, but coals to
Newcastle.
</P>
<P>
   Can I move the taste bar any lower?
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Peskin reports that the Syuk-Hee Spa on Broadway, scene of
many vice squad raids for prostitution, was finally shut down. But
the city has granted a massage parlor license to the shop's new
owner: Un Zipperer.
</P>
<P>
   That item makes it official: This particular column will not be
classified as ``intellectual property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 0331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
