<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3086 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-$ADV30     05-27 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LONG-ISOLATED ALBANIA LOOKING TO U.S. TO BRING IT OUT OF THE
WILDERNESS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With ALBANIA-BOX-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURREL, Albania _ Agim Kaziu, a 63-year-old businessman in this
remote, poor mountain village, looks as if he has seen a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's just an American sitting big as life across the table
at a dusty roadside cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Kaziu is moved to pause from his lunch of lamb and potatoes to
mark the moment with an elaborate wave of his fork. ``If someone
had told me 10 years ago that there would be Americans in my
village, I would have said, 'Yes and maybe the man in the moon will
pay us a visit, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Kaziu would have been putting it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, communist dictator Enver Hoxha made Albania
perhaps the world's most isolated country. Hoxha told his people
that Americans -- not to mention most foreigners -- were their
mortal enemies.
</P>
<P>
   It is a changed world -- especially since the Kosovo crisis.
While Americans still are rare in remote areas, young people in the
bustling capital, Tirana, like to wear clothes with American themes
-- the Chicago Bulls are particularly big -- and it is hard to go
without feeling a rumbling rap music bass.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the fall of communism many Albanians have come to
view the United States as the best hope their tiny Balkan nation
has to become a healthy, stable -- the word often used is
``normal'' -- country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look to America, which is the only country with a realistic
view of Albania,'' said Vladimir Prela, a journalist and writer
from Tirana. ``The United States is the only reliable ally we have.
This is our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanians have been impressed by the consistent no-compromise
message coming from Washington on the NATO bombing campaign against
Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia. This is in
sharp contrast to the vacillations of Italy, Germany, and Greece
and to some extent, France.
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, the war in Yugoslavia is regarded by many
here as just what the doctor ordered for Albania, some officials
say. A year ago, it would have been hard to imagine seeing Pandeli
Majko, Albania's boyish-looking primer minister, being interviewed
live on CNN or holding a joint news conference with NATO's
Secretary General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, Albania's most visible presence in the United
States was as the country in the hit film ``Wag the Dog'' that
seemed obscure enough to make it the perfect place to stage an
imaginary war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Albania is on the world's agenda,'' said Taulant Dedja,
the deputy minister of local government. ``This presents us with
really a great opportunity. Potentially, there is a greater
possibility of getting economic aid and moving closer to the West
-- particularly America, which has a great interest in Albania and
is our guarantor of stability in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While Macedonia's leaders have been half-hearted in their
support for NATO's using the country as a staging area for a
potential push into Yugoslavia's embattled Kosovo province,
Albanian President Rexhep Meidani has placed all his country's
assets at NATO's disposal.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the United States and NATO have been allowed to set
up a base to house the 24 Apache attack helicopters and 5,000
support troops that make up Task Force Hawk, which would be the
``tip of the spear'' of any ground force going into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this is the problem with Albania: The country is willing,
but its assets are weak.
</P>
<P>
   At first look, Albania seems dreadfully poor place with few
prospects for improvement. On further inspection, it is far worse
than it first appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Its ancient roads, bridges and sewer systems are in utter
disrepair. Driving on a smooth surface is a rare experience to be
found mainly in the capital. Many crumbling bridges are unsafe, and
the government has closed a few simply by blocking them with
concrete rubble. Billions of dollars in new infrastructure are
needed.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine a worse place to put 450,000 poor
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians worry the refugee crisis could push the country
to anarchy. In the decades since the communists lost power, the
country has endured occasional spells of chaos and always seems on
the verge of another.
</P>
<P>
   While it seems calm now, there are pressures from the refugee
influx roiling beneath the surface, said Genc Ruli, the president
of the Institute of Contemporary Studies. ``We're talking about a
sudden population increase of 15 percent for a country that is
barely functioning,'' Ruli said.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of refugees eventually will spark inflation, while
reducing stocks of basic commodities -- clean water is in short
supply -- an age-old cocktail for civic disorder. ``This relative
stability we see now is fragile and temporary,'' Ruli said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Albania's problem comes from being isolated so long and
then having no patron country to provide basic training when
democracy and a free market arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no stable cradle for the democratic
institutions to develop,'' said Ylli Pango(CQ both), a psychology
professor here who has written a book for Albanians about the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pango and others believe Western powers abandoned Albania at its
most fragile moment. ``It was crazy, really, for the West to allow
Albania to go without any help,'' said Pango, also a former deputy
minister of education. ``In terms of history, I think it was one of
the biggest mistakes. Now we think that it is clear that Albania
cannot succeed alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers here lately have been carrying articles pondering the
idea of Albania's becoming an American protectorate, to become a
ward of the great distant democratic uncle.
</P>
<P>
   While it is nearly unthinkable that the United States would go
so far as to assume such a role with Albania, there are clear signs
the countries are becoming closer.
</P>
<P>
   What one Western official described as a ``hidden protectorate''
is evolving with the United States and European Union members
providing advisors to guide Albanian government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration is moving quickly to replace the very
popular ambassador, Marisa Lino, who resigned last year. Earlier
this month President Clinton nominated Joseph Limprecht, a veteran
diplomat, to replace her.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton so near to the end of his term, this quick action
is seen here as a signal that Washington has come to regard Albania
with great importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans know that they now have a very keen interest in
Albania,'' Dedja said. ``Our futures are now joined.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
