<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3099 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV30-C     05-27 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE NEW COMMUNICATIONS CASBAH
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Suppose you drive around during the work week in a
sleek new Lexus but have to scale back to a clunky old compact on
weekends. Wouldn't it be nice if you could persuade the boss to let
you take the company Lexus home as well?
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays we often get a similar deal whenever we go online. A
huge slice of corporate America has invested in high-speed Internet
access for its office workers, suppliers and customers. But for
families with personal computers and modem connections, the glories
of World Wide Web all too often succumb to the frustrating World
Wide Wait.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the 100,000 or so U.S. households currently linked
to what's known in the trade as broadband services _ either cable
``modems'' or digital subscriber phone lines from the Baby Bells _
enjoy life in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   They can download in 20 seconds what might normally take 20
minutes with a standard link. They can watch a live BBC newscast or
even a movie without settling for the choppy images of a flick from
the early 1920s. They can listen to Internet-fed CD-quality music
on their stereos.
</P>
<P>
   In a few years' time, such fast networks could become widely
available at a price of about $30 a month, thereby blazing trails
to interactive electronic commerce, two-way long-distance learning,
powerful telemedical tools, and, most probably, enhanced
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   If and when such broadband services kick in, broadcast networks
and cable television outlets could be stuck with the type of
obsolete business model that undid the once thriving typewriter
trade in the 1980s, when word processing moved over to PCs and
printers.
</P>
<P>
   But such change could be slow in coming. Only about a third of
U.S. homes are hooked into cyberspace. And while 90 percent of
schools have Internet access, studies show that most teachers still
don't use computers, let alone the Internet, in their lesson
planning or teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as more Web sites become ``tuned'' to broadband, the
long-predicted convergence between PCs and TV could finally become
a reality. If that happens, the computing world will change
drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Already, along yet another digital frontier, two-way portable
devices are taking over from desktop and laptop machines. A
Canadian-built unit that hooks to my belt weighs only four ounces,
including a durable AA battery. With the aid of a PC-style keypad,
it supports a 1,000-entry address book, sends and receives E-mail
messages of up to 1,600 words and effortlessly handles
text-to-voice and text-to-fax transmissions. Like a pager, it beeps
or vibrates when E-mail or faxed messages arrive.
</P>
<P>
   With this $360 device in hand, anyone can call an toll-free
number, dedicated exclusively to a single user, and dictate a
detailed message to an operator. Or a user could startle someone by
tapping out a poem by, say, Edgar Allen Poe and having a deep
synthesized voice automatically read the poetry back to whomever
answers the phone.
</P>
<P>
   In today's communications casbah, the offerings are becoming
faster, smaller and easier to use than only a few years ago. The
new century promises even more profound change.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
