 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No. 254' - May 27, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2544 - May 27, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. A GAME BOY IN THE CROSS HAIRS One month after the Columbine
HIgh School shootings, another such nightmare occurred in Conyers,
Ga. Are we learning anything about what causes such violence and
how to end it? If videogames such as Doom and Quake have anything
to do with it, the possibility hasn't affected the makers much.
They are still working away to produce the bloodiest, most
weapon-laden participatory ``shooter'' games ever. By Paul Keegan.
From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (5,000 words) +
edited article available. 2. BEDLAM ON THE STREETS Increasingly,
the mentally ill have nowhere to go. That's their problem - and
ours. Especially in cases such as that of Andrew Goldstein, who
pushed a young woman to her death in front of a New York subway
train in January. A seriously mentally ill man, he repeatedly
attacked strangers, repeatedly volunteered himself for
hospitalization and repeatedly was discharged. As in many other
cases, he was left to the open streets and still the state of
America's shattered mental-health system all but assures such
calamities. By Michael Winerip. From The New York Times Magazine.
2,000 words. 3. NEW EVIDENCE ABOUT EARLY CHRISTIANITY AND THE
GOSPEL
</P>
<P>
   OF MATTHEW Biblical critics have offered many theories that
challenge the credibility of the gospels and the events described
in the New Testament. But now, out of the catacombs of history,
comes new information that will startle sceptics and make the heart
of believers rejoice. By Neil Altman. 2,500 words. 4. HAVE WE
FORGOTTEN THE PATH TO PEACE? Jimmy Carter, the 39th president of
the United States, who is now chairman of the non-profit Carter
Centre, writes that negotiation is an art we seem to have
forgotten, not only in the warlike approach to resolving ethnic
conflict in Kosovo, but also in our efforts to deal with other
flashpoints around the world. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words. 5.
ENGLAND DESERVES THANKS FOR CARING. For all the anti-welfare
rigours of Thatcherism and planned constraints of Prime Minister
Tony Blair's Third Way, Britain still can offer remarkably kind,
effective care to those who are suffering. It makes an enormous
difference. To those who become aware of it, it colours a whole
society with a glow of warmth and decency. Flora Lewis writes
movingly of her daughter's death and the hospice care in Britain.
800 words. 6. LOW-DOSE HORMONE TREATMENTS LINKED TO UTERINE CANCER
Hot flashes and night sweats are some of the most bothersome
symptoms that affect women early in menopause. For these symptoms,
many women take the hormone estrogen. Although the higher potency
estrogen treatments are known to increase the risk of uterine
cancer, it has been widely believed that the low-potency treatments
are safe. But a study in this week's Lancet suggests that
low-potency estrogen use can also substantially increase a woman's
chance of developing uterine cancer. By Michael McCarthy. The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo 19h00 BST
Wednesday, June 2)
</P>
<P>
   A. BIOTECHNOLOGY : GENES GET KNOTTED If tying a knot in your
handkerchief doesn't do much for your memory, what about tying a
knot in your genes? By Philip Ball. 500 words. B. SAY IT WITH
FLOWERS Never underestimate the role of smell in sexual attraction.
The orchid Ophrys sphegodes certainly doesn't. In order to better
spread its pollen, this cunning flower poses as a female bee of the
species Andrena nigroanea, by releasing pheromone-like chemicals
that lure males of this species in search of a mate. By Sara
Abdulla. 500 words. 8. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE: A. Brain
Imaging Can Help Predict Effects of Head Injury
</P>
<P>
   A technique that produces three-dimensional images of the brain
in action can predict behavioural and functional changes in
children with head injuries. 500 words. B. Action Figures Make
Unhealthy Role Models For Boys
</P>
<P>
   The bulky-muscled, thin-waisted action toys little boys crave
may be twisting their ideas of what a male body ought to look like,
researchers say. Just like Barbie, GI Joe has an unrealistic figure
that may promote unhealthy habits in boys as they mature. Please
