<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STUDENT-SUICIDE-NY     05-27 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STUDENT-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL, 14, IS FOUND HANGED IN A BRONX SCHOOL BATHROOM STALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 14-year-old girl was found hanged with a
clothesline in a bathroom stall at a Bronx high school on Wednesday
in what officials said appeared to be a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A student discovered the body of Anna Perez at 9:25 a.m. in a
third-floor girl's bathroom at Herbert H. Lehman High School,
according to police.
</P>
<P>
   The student alerted school officials, who tried to revive the
girl with cardiopulmonary resuscitation, but Anna was pronounced
dead on arrival at Jacobi Medical Center, a school board spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   A poem or rap about death was scrawled on one of the bathroom
stalls, and investigators were trying to determine whether Anna
wrote it, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Anna's death was not immediately declared a suicide, pending an
autopsy by the City Medical Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The incident shocked the school of about 4,000 students. Grief
counselors were on hand in the library and in the guidance office
to help students. Many students milled outside the three-story,
red-brick building, some crying, others holding prayer vigils in a
nearby park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' said Stephanie Belloni, 15, a freshman who
said she was a friend of Anna's. ``No one expected anything like
this, even though a lot of people wouldn't speak to her. They
sometimes called her names. They never really gave her a chance.
She was a smart, sweet, caring and intelligent girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students described Anna as a loner and an outcast. Some
said that she rarely came to school and that when she did, she left
early. Close friends said she was smarting over a recent breakup
with a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors on the quiet residential block where she lived with
her mother and an older brother refused to talk about her. No one
answered the door of the two-family, red-brick house where the
family lives.
</P>
<P>
   Details about events leading up to Anna's death were sketchy,
but the police said she attended her first-period class, which
started about 8:30. She was found during the school's second
period. Friends, acquaintances and school officials gave
conflicting accounts about her disposition Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   She was spotted in the cafeteria about 8 a.m., just before first
period, chatting with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was her regular perky self,'' said Jacqueline Figuero, 18,
a senior. ``She told me it was going to be her last day of school.
I asked if she was going on an early vacation and she said,
`Something like that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna had a lot of problems at home,'' Jacqueline added.
``School was the only place she would come to get away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Autry, 17, a junior, lashed out at students who
regarded Anna as an outcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope all the people who harassed her feel sorry now,'' she
said. ``People made fun of her. Sometimes she was beaten up by
other kids. She used to come speak to me about her problems. I told
her to take it day-by-day.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other friends, including 16-year-old Lucy Oppenheimer,
said there were signs that Anna was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``She talked about killing herself,'' she said. ``I didn't think
she would do it. She had problems at home. She had a boyfriend who
broke up with her. A lot of kids didn't like her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACADEMIC-JOBMARKET28-     05-27 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMIC-JOBMARKET28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    While rest of economy booms, jobs inside academia are scarce
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Many of this spring's college graduates are
leaving academia pondering multiple job offers, a bounty of today's
robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Luke Keller, who wants to teach astronomy to undergraduates,
knows he'll have a tougher time when he finishes his studies at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get a teaching position,'' said Keller,
who hopes to graduate in August. ``You can't assume that you're
going to be a professor.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Keller, many graduate students who want to return to
academia as tenure-track professors are finding few job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job market's very tight,'' said Rick Cherwitz, a professor
of speech communication and associate dean of graduate studies at
UT. ``That's why we created the Professional Development Program _
to increase the odds for graduate students to find non-academic
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The development program, which is designed to help graduate
students acquire skills not normally associated with the Ivory
Tower, was created by a partnership of UT's Office of Graduate
Studies, the provost's office and the Center for Teaching
Effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a pilot project with three summer courses in 1996
is now a year-round curriculum of 13 classes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 students studying 80 disciplines now take classes
such as Academic and Professional Consulting and Entrepreneurship.
Keller, who is studying for his Ph.D. in astronomy, said the
classes helped him learn how to sell his astronomy skills.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Keller couldn't find a teaching position. So, like many
doctoral students, he accepted a postdoctoral research job _ sort
of a ``holding pattern'' internship for graduate students, he
explained _ at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people that there is no logical reason why they
shouldn't have gotten (teaching) jobs long ago, except that there
are no jobs,'' Keller said. ``They're taking three and four
postdocs.''
</P>
<P>
   Universities around the nation awarded 42,705 doctorate degrees
in 1997 _ a record number for the 12th consecutive year, according
to a University of Chicago survey. That's 10 percent more than 1992
and 32 percent more than 1987. UT, which issued 787 doctorate
degrees in 1997, graduates more doctoral students than any other
university in the nation, the survey reported.
</P>
<P>
   With only about 30 to 40 tenure-track positions open in his
field nationally each year, Marty Meersman, who will receive his
master's degree in fine arts, said he feels fortunate to have found
a teaching position. He beat out about 150 other candidates and
will start teaching sculpture at Moorhead State College in
Moorhead, Minn., in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the type of person to not worry about the
future if I work really hard and am ambitious,'' Meersman said. ``I
want to teach because I love the reciprocal exchange of energy and
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other graduate students are putting teaching plans on hold
and pursuing non-traditional employment.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fiske, a scientist for Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory in California, said many graduate students are
benefiting in unintended ways from the lack of teaching positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant fraction of the Ph.D.'s in the sciences
genuinely find themselves less interested in academia than they are
in other fields,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiske, who received his doctorate degree in geology from
Stanford University in 1994, said he found the job market confusing
after graduation. So he wrote ``To Boldly Go ... ,'' a career guide
for new graduates. He also writes a Web-based column for young
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academia will learn that it will be stronger when its
intellectual children are pursuing a broad range of fields: in
government, in high schools, in business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
