<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A list of minor annoyances in the modern age
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGODOCHES, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Things that annoy me:
</P>
<P>
   _ Loud music piped outside at convenience stores as you pump
gas, especially when it's interspersed with canned commercials for
the establishment in question. I guess this is supposed to make one
more upbeat about buying gasoline, which is always a miserable
task. No matter what, I cannot get excited about buying gasoline,
though it's a necessity like food and water. But at least one gets
some satisfaction from consuming food and drink.
</P>
<P>
   _ I don't understand the point of playing commercials for the
store outside when you're already at the store. And the loud music
gets on my nerves. The world has gotten much too noisy, in my
opinion. It's as if we cannot stand the sound of silence anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nose rings. And eyebrow rings. If the good Lord had intended
people to pierce those parts of the body he would have made noses
and eyebrows look like earlobes. It just looks unhealthy to me. I
have nothing against earrings on either gender and am intrigued by
belly button rings on women, though it looks like that would hurt,
too. But my nightmare experience is buying gas at a store that
plays golden oldies at the decibel equivalent of a F-15 breaking
the sound barrier, and then having my money taken by a clerk whose
face has been punctured by any number of rings and studs in the
nose and eyebrow. And don't get me started on tongue studs.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I'm getting old.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who drive below the speed limit while sticking to the
left lane. I do not exceed the speed limit on the highway. I
learned my lesson the hard way after getting too many speeding
tickets. But I will drive as fast as the law allows. There is a
certain group of people who insist on moping along at 50 mph in the
left lane, forcing you to pass on the right, which is riskier and
actually illegal in some states. I do not understand the attraction
to the left lane if one does not intend to turn left sometime in
the next millennium or so.
</P>
<P>
   _ Magazine sweepstakes. I am a gambler, albeit a cheap one. I
buy Lotto tickets, play blackjack a few times a year at the boats,
and love to wager $2 on the ponies. This is not a moral issue with
me. I used to enter magazine sweepstakes faithfully, but they have
gotten too complicated. You have to put the gold sticker here, the
red star there, the blue dot on the back. Then, a few weeks later,
after you bought a magazine subscription to Auger Tips and
Techniques to improve the chances of winning, you get yet another
solicitation and are asked to go through the whole complicated
process again. Now I chunk them all in the trash. I realize this
means Ed McMahon will never come knocking on my door while I'm
taking a shower, but I'm willing to make the sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Children in television commercials. This is an alarming trend.
I'm not talking about genuine child actors, like the rugrats in the
Oscar Meyer wiener spots. They're professionals, trained from birth
by stage moms hoping to ride their child's fame to riches. I'm
talking about small-business owners who decide to put Bubba Joe in
a commercial _ even though Bubba Joe, who may be cute as a button,
can't speak the Queen's English well enough to be understood _
except maybe by his grandparents. Why would a gap-toothed kid who
can't follow a Tele-Prompter or pronounce three-syllable words
persuade me to buy a tire, furniture, car or other commodities just
because he's cute? I'm not persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Safety caps and seals. I bought a bottle of water the other
day. It had a plastic cap to shield the pull-up spout, which is
fine by me. I don't want someone sneaking a slug of water and
putting it back on the shelf. But it also had a seal beneath the
cap, which meant I had to pry the hard cap off, then unscrew the
pull-up spout to tear off the seal, then screw the cap back on. In
the process, being terminally clumsy, I spilled a nice load of
water on my crotch and had to drive around a while letting my pants
dry before I could go back out in public. One seal is enough. I'm
willing to take my chances.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, what annoys me the most is people who complain about
what annoys them...
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel. His
e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
