   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ Next time you think you're having a bad
day, recall these blunders. (Ernest Murray is managing editor of
The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED. EMBARGOED for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ A list of things that annoy me. I'm sure you'll
recognize some. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) MOVED. EMBARGOED for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Just when you
think the trade of accusations between John Cornyn and Dan Morales
can't get any weirder, it does. (Arnold Garcia is editorial page
editor of the Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ How points of order affect the
legislative process. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ As much as TAAS has helped improve
things for lots of low achievers, it's not the answer to our
nation's ills. In fact, if you ask some kids, teachers and parents,
TAAS is the illness. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SANFORD-COLUMN-COX _ When I return home from Washington every
week and see my boys playing, I'm reminded how their games of
make-believe reflect what's going on in our nation's capital
regarding Social Security. Folks in Washington, in general, seem to
be lackadaisical about shoring up Social Security for the 76
million baby boomers approaching retirement. Politicians are
feigning concern, but no one seems to be pressed to make anything
happen. If Washington keeps this up through the year, chances of
reform will be as great as my 6-year-old son striking down a storm
trooper with a light saber. (U.S. Rep. Mark Sanford, a Republican,
represents the coastal district of South Carolina.) MOVED.
</P>
