<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornyn, Morales &AMP; Murr's three-ring circus
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Just when you think the trade of accusations
between John Cornyn and Dan Morales can't get any weirder, it does.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the current attorney general said he had no evidence
that the former attorney general had benefitted personally from a
contract Houston lawyer Marc Murr says entitles him to a share of
the attorneys' fees in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Cornyn was leveling allegations of fraud against
Morales, saying the former attorney general fabricated the contract
so his friend Murr could pursue a claim of $260 million. That claim
has since been down sized to a mere $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a lot of head scratchers around here, but this one
trumps them all.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about this makes much sense.
</P>
<P>
   Question: If Cornyn has no evidence that Morales benefited
personally from the deal, then why did he air all that talk about
civil fraud?
</P>
<P>
   Question: If Murr really believes he is entitled to $260
million, why is he backing off to the tune of $259 million?
</P>
<P>
   I can give you a West Texas guarantee that if I thought I had
$260 million coming, it would take the 101st Airborne Division to
make me back off. And then I'd want to give them some lip.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious implication of the earlier innuendoes was that Murr
and Morales somehow were to split the $260 million. We might as
well say it, that's what people were thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Question: If two people, especially Ivy League lawyers, enter
into such a conspiracy implied by Cornyn, don't you think they
would be more careful than to perform a sloppy cut and paste job on
the contract?
</P>
<P>
   Think like a crook for a minute. If you and I were to enter into
a kickback agreement, why would you agree to take the full IRS ride
on the money we're cutting up? And how would I be assured that you
were going to live up to your end of the agreement once the check
is in your hands? If you tell me to buzz off, what I am going to
do? Call the cops?
</P>
<P>
   Question: Given the latest half turn, wasn't it the height or
irresponsibility for Cornyn to toss around words like ``fraud'' if
he had no evidence that Morales benefited personally?
</P>
<P>
   Morales has stoutly and consistently denied any wrongdoing and
maintained that the accusations are politically inspired. That
explanation by itself won't resolve the doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in the bull's-eye usually holler politics. Sometimes
they're even right.
</P>
<P>
   Ask anybody about this situation and you'll most likely get
shrugged shoulders as a response. Texans are entitled to better
than that.
</P>
<P>
   Texans are entitled to know the truth about the matter. Last
week, I suggested that the allegations and implications of those
allegations were serious enough to warrant a separate, independent
inquiry into the situation. I suggested then that a court of
inquiry be convened to look into the matter and look at it in the
open.
</P>
<P>
   Candidly, I don't expect a judge to leap into this morass
willingly, but Texans are entitled to know the truth. Something is
seriously wrong here, and citizens are entitled to explanations.
</P>
<P>
   A court of inquiry would be one way of getting to them.
</P>
<P>
   A friend and lawyer I respect suggested that a court of inquiry
would turn into a circus.
</P>
<P>
   That may be, but the difference between a circus and this show
we're watching now is that no one is selling popcorn and lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at (512) 445-3667 or
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
