<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Point of order can be bill's demise
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two years ago, Rep. Arlene Wohlgemuth knocked
down 52 bills in what came to be known as the Memorial Day
Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The chairman of the Calendars Committee neglected to
say out loud that the meeting at which the bills were set for
debate would be in the Speaker's Committee Room off the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlgemuth (R-Burleson) was retaliating to a similar legislative
move by Rep. Debra Danburg (D-Houston) in killing a bill on
parental notification on abortion. Danburg had noted that the
witnesses at a public hearing on the notification bill were
incorrectly identified.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative device Wohlgemuth and Danburg used is called a
``point of order.'' Such points are allegations that a bill, on its
way through the legislative maze to the floor, violated the House
rules designed to keep government open and aboveboard.
</P>
<P>
   Points of order are aimed at killing or delaying a bills. Some
points are duds, ruled invalid by the House speaker. But others are
deadly.
</P>
<P>
   They are seldom used in the smaller, clubbier 31-member Senate,
where senators can hold up a bill in committee for 48 hours if it
has not had a public hearing by ``tagging'' it or by talking it to
death with a filibuster. Because Senate tradition demands a
two-thirds vote in the first place to bring up a bill, points of
order are extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Sen. Mario Gallegos (D-Houston), a former House
member, raised a point of order two years ago that killed an
annexation bill sponsored by Sen. Jon Lindsey (R-Houston), Lindsey
derisively called it ``a rinky-dink House ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't call points of order in the Senate,'' Lindsey
declared with disdain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 150-member House, points of order are such effective
devices late in the session that some legislators have developed
reputations as accurate and often deadly snipers.
</P>
<P>
   The two most feared rules experts are Democrat Ron Wilson of
Houston and Republican Warren Chisum of Pampa.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, now in his 23rd year in the House, is feared like a hit
man when he approaches the House's back microphone, often wearing
his trademark dark glasses, during the closing days of a session.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says he actually does have a formula for finding points
of order. But like a master chef with a secret recipe, he hasn't
written it down _ anywhere. ``I keep it all in my head,'' he said
with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Chisum says it's no secret _ ``just work. You need to know the
rules and the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   But he credits Derek Seals, a lawyer on his staff for a decade,
with finding most defects in bills. Seals is ``the master of
disaster,'' lobbyist Rob Johnson said reverently.
</P>
<P>
   Some former legislative staffers hire out as bounty hunters,
charging a goodly sum to check out a bill for a lobbyist. If they
find a point of order that winds up delaying or killing a bill,
they get a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But they also look over bills some lobbyists are trying to pass
to help ``scrub'' them of glitches that could kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Some lobbyists avoid bounty hunters, because they don't want to
irk House Speaker Pete Laney. During Laney's tenure, the House
rules, and the bill-writing Legislative Council, have worked to
make points of order harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   The House rules, in fact, were changed in 1999 to allow the
speaker to strike down points of order that don't materially affect
a bill. And the House has set up a division to write required
analyses of bills to lessen the chance that a new committee clerk
will make an error that could jeopardize a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wilson and Chisum agree that bill-killing points of order
are tougher to find these days. And Chisum says that's mostly for
the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules are good,'' Chisum said. ``They keep from misleading
people about what's really in the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Pause. Slow smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Chisum added, ``you can also use those sometimes to
your advantage, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com or (512) 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
