<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFORD-COLUMN28-COX     05-27 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFORD-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Social Security dilemma is real
 &HT;    By Mark Sanford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My four little boys love to pretend. They can spend hours
pretending to be cowboys, corralling their brothers with ropes in
the back yard; or in their rooms with towels around their necks
like Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   When I return home from Washington every week and see them
playing, I'm reminded how their games of make-believe reflect
what's going on in our nation's capital regarding Social Security.
Folks in Washington, in general, seem to be lackadaisical about
shoring up Social Security for the 76 million baby boomers
approaching retirement. Politicians are feigning concern, but no
one seems to be pressed to make anything happen. If Washington
keeps this up through the year, chances of reform will be as great
as my 6-year-old son striking down a storm trooper with a light
saber.
</P>
<P>
   Folks back home in South Carolina consistently tell me they want
the system fixed. And they don't want to hear about higher taxes or
lower benefits. That leaves only one other option _ earning more on
our Social Security investment. The question will be how:
collectively or with personal accounts?
</P>
<P>
   As a proponent of the second option, I will propose a bill that
will help working Americans control their retirement security by
keeping Social Security surpluses away from lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Like most reform proposals, this plan would provide a system of
personal retirement accounts that would enable people to own and
control their retirement money. The bill would allow workers to
receive their share of the Social Security surplus each year, dir-
</P>
<P>
   ectly deposited in individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   How would this work? Let's look at last year. In 1998, Social
Security ran a $100 billion surplus. Washington spent $30 billion,
and the remaining $70 billion paid part of the existing federal
debt. The government didn't use one cent for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Under this approach, however, Social Security's $100 billion
surplus would have been rebated to Americans' PRAs. Every worker
would have had about one-quarter of what he paid in FICA taxes
returned by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, Congress voted to spend $13 billion of the
Social Security surplus to fund military actions in Kosovo. More
than 300 members of Congress, many of whom had previously talked
about ``not touching'' the Social Security Trust Fund, voted to
borrow the money.
</P>
<P>
   If last year's surplus had been deposited in personal retirement
accounts, there would have been no way for lawmakers to ``borrow''
that money.
</P>
<P>
   The money rebated to these PRAs would be considered down
payments on future Social Security benefits. This would then reduce
the program's future financial obligations. With $2.8 trillion in
surpluses expected over the next 15 years, it would be foolish to
waste this golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Make-believe is fun for children, but pretending, as a nation,
is scary. Social Security's problems are not going to magically
disappear. For the sake of my four little boys, I hope folks in
Washington consider real reform before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Mark Sanford, a Republican, represents the coastal
district of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
