<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRICLARK28-COX     05-27 1739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRICLARK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clark climbs charts with hatful of hits and no pretensions
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Terri Clark is one of those country music
artists whose look is so striking you could pick her out by
silhouette _ a cowboy hat the size of a truck tire, thick auburn
hair, tight T-shirt, cowboy-cut Wranglers and boots that could kick
up plenty of sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when most female acts in Nashville are donning
designer gowns, she's Cocky Chick Country, a carefully constructed
image of beauty and swagger that has made Clark the video darling
of Country Music Television and one of Nashville's critically
acclaimed hitmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of another female act in country who is doing
what she's doing. She's a knockout who is also aggressive and
comfortable enough to be one of the guys,'' says Steve Mitchell,
the program director at Atlanta country station Y-106.7. Like
others, Mitchell has watched Clark's ascension up the charts since
her breakthrough in 1995, and likes her ``refreshing style and
attitude in this day and age when everybody wants to play dress-up
and sing ballads.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Clark steps into Tootsie's Orchid Lounge on a recent
spring morning, no one in this historic temple of country music
recognizes her at all. She's not the posturing, tough tomboy one
would expect from come-hither album covers and sassy music videos.
The 30-year-old singer/songwriter, looks more like a student on the
way to class, sporting torn jeans, a simple denim shirt, little
makeup and a bottle of mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   And she's not wearing the famous hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't have it on today,'' she says, settling into her
favorite black vinyl booth in the beer joint where she got her
start as an 18-year-old newcomer from Alberta, Canada. ``You know,
it's been a blessing and a curse for me. Sometimes I feel like
Terri Clark is an alter ego. That's her and this is me. I think
I've definitely hit a turning point where I'm not inhibited about
people seeing another side.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark quickly proves that this growing liberation from her looks
is more than idle talk. She knows she's going to have her picture
made today, but hasn't demanded photo approval, a fairly standard
condition in today's marketing-obsessed Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gonna get riled up about something stupid like whether
or not a picture looks right,'' she says. ``Just pick something
flattering and don't make me look fat.'' She seems quite at home
here among the fading publicity photos that smother the greasy
walls, and says she still slips in the back door of the famous
watering hole from time to time to hear ``good ol' country music.''
</P>
<P>
   An image consultant would probably cringe at this earthy lack of
pretension. But it is Clark's refreshing candor in both her life
and her lyrics that has made fans _ and the Nashville music
community _ embrace her like a drinking buddy on a Saturday night.
Men seem to love the confidence she exudes. On Clark's Web site,
for example, two fans named Rodeo Man and Redneck Man are going to
head down to a show to ``drink beer and yee-haw.'' Women appreciate
the fact she's no magnolia, and often show up at her concerts
dressed from head to toe in Clark costume. Like Anne Murray,
Wynonna and Mary Chapin Carpenter, the divorcee also attracts a
large following of gay fans.
</P>
<P>
   Country queen Reba McEntire, who has toured with Clark and
claims to be one of her biggest admirers, says ``Something I've
learned from my 23 years in the business is that the fans love
honesty. With Terri, her natural personality offstage transfers
honestly and easily onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of today's pop-oriented Nashville acts, Clark's
sound is rooted in the twang of traditionalism. Although she speaks
with no regional accent, her singing voice rings like a dinner bell
_ girl is ``gurrrl,'' poor is ``purr'' _ phrasing drawn from hours
listening to albums by Ricky Skaggs and the Judds as a teen-ager.
As Y-106.7's Mitchell observes, ``she also has contemporary
sounding music behind her,'' which positions her somewhere between
the pop of Shania Twain and the rodeo sounds of George Strait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe she has had a lot of big songs because she cuts
through the clutter in country music,'' Mitchell says. ``She is
clearly having lots of fun, and that comes through the speakers at
you. You can't fake fun.''
</P>
<P>
   With the release of her third album, ``How I Feel,'' Clark finds
herself at a personal and professional crossroads. She's maturing
from the newcomer known for seductively cute novelty songs, such as
``Better Things to Do,'' to a more confident artist who isn't
afraid of testing a new look as well as new material. For example,
the first single off the latest album, ``Now That I Found You,''
was was originally an R&AMP;B tune. Clark's slow country treatment of
the song gave her her first No. 1 hit _ and she didn't wear a hat
in the popular video.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an artist, she seems to have more focus as to what she's
doing,'' says Chris Parr, programming director at CMT. ``The last
three videos we've gotten have been great material. Some of the
more ditty stuff she did earlier, like `Poor, Poor Pitiful Me' or
`When Boy Meets Girl,' there wasn't a lot of substance to them.
They were fun songs, which is fine, but she's starting to strike
deeper chords now.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be because, since finding fame and fortune in Nashville _
and going through a painful divorce from her husband of seven years
_ Clark has embarked on a personal journey to figure out just who
she is outside of the hit-making machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment industry is all about `look at me, look at
me', and I'm trying to find my niche in that,'' she says with quiet
reflection. ``It's an ego-based industry, and you have to have a
healthy ego to do this. But I've never had cockiness or phoniness.
What has really changed is that I've gotten in touch with my spirit
and what I am inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans have no doubt noticed Clark's soul searching on her latest
hit ``Everytime I Cry,'' which hit Billboard's Top 10 country
charts and was the No. 1 video on CMT for two weeks this month.
Overwhelmed by the whirlwind of fame, Clark says she felt an
increasing need to make some kind of an impact through her fame, so
she dipped into her own pocket to pay for a two-day video shoot
that turned the song into a platform against domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   CMT's Parr was so struck with the power of the tune and the
video that he chose Clark to be May's artist of the month. He says
when he first screened the clip, ``it really made you stop and
think. Visually, I think she's moved up a notch on the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   The metamorphosis may stem from the fact that, in the past year,
Clark has turned her attention to soul searching. She meditates
twice a day in the bedroom of her intown Nashville home, which she
calls ``ridiculously big. Sometimes I feel guilty.'' She's also
been writing songs with folkie Mary Chapin Carpenter, tunes she
says ``have a more uplifting, spiritual connotation to them.'' Her
bedside books are self-help guides by motivational guru Deepak
Chopra, whom Clark met on a retreat at his meditation center in La
Jolla, Calif. When she talks, her conversations are peppered with
New Age vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it has done for me is bring me to an awareness of my
spirit and that it does go on,'' she says. ``Everything that goes
on outside of me _ relationships, career, money, cars _ is all
nonlocal reality. When I'm seeking approval from everybody and
concerned that everybody likes me, that's an ego-based emotion and
not from the spirit. As long as you give, you get. If you stop
giving and only think of yourself, it's going to clot like a blood
clot. I realize what really matters, and it's inside me.''
</P>
<P>
   Can fans accept this newer, karmic version of Terri Clark?
Longtime fan Donna Raney thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the 33-year-old Delta Air Lines customer
service rep has run Clark's official Web page from her home in
Acworth, Ga. She says ``her true fans will follow her. A true fan
is in it for the music and not her image. Terri has worked very
hard for her career, and she's going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark says she believes that ``an artist pretty much has a five-
to-seven-year window to make their money, then it's over. So you
gotta make hay while the sun's shining.'' Having established a
track record, she says she believes now is the time to push the
envelope and explore new directions. For the next album, set for
release early next year, she's working with a new producer, new
session players and new co-writers. Mercury Nashville President
Luke Lewis has given her broad artistic license, telling Clark she
can do whatever she wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a side of myself that likes very organic, folk rock,
and I'm probably going to incorporate that more into what I do,''
she says. ``The next album is gonna be so different that it's
either going to be huge or bomb. There probably won't be a hat on
the cover, but every artist _ from Reba to Trisha _ has reinvented
themselves. But I'm going with my heart. If somebody is listening
to my music because I'm wearing a hat, they're listening for the
wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   A SNAPSHOT OF TERRI CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Age: 30
</P>
<P>
   Raised in: Alberta, Canada
</P>
<P>
   Family: Her father was an electrical engineer, mother a
housewife. Married for seven years, Clark divorced in 1995 just as
her second single was climbing the charts.
</P>
<P>
   Now lives: In Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Getting started: At age 18, Clark left home and moved to
Nashville, knowing no one in town. She worked in a western wear
store, was a waitress, and eventually got a job as the house singer
at Tootsie's Orchid Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The career: Signed to Mercury Nashville in 1994. A year later,
she scored a Top 10 hit with ``Better Things To Do.''
</P>
<P>
   The hits: ``Better Things To Do,'' ``Emotional Girl,'' ``When
Boy Meets Girl,'' ``Poor, Poor Pitiful Me,'' ``If I Were You,''
``You're Easy On the Eyes,'' ``Now That I Found You,'' ``Everytime
I Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   The hat: It's a custom-made Resistol. Clark owns dozens of them.
She gets them for free because she is a spokeswoman for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: Clark's official Web site is at
www.terriclark.avana.net. It's run by fan Donna Raney out of her
home in Acworth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
