<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX     05-27 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAAS: virtue or virus?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Check the appropriate:
</P>
<P>
   (A.) In a clinical setting, and with sufficient repetition,
education policies in Texas could have conditioned Pavlov's dogs to
do long division.
</P>
<P>
   (B.) Education policies in Texas would cause Pavlov's dogs to
stop salivating over sirloin.
</P>
<P>
   (C.) Given sufficient prodding, education policies in Texas
could lead a room full of monkeys working round the clock to type
out a single composition that would score a passing 3 on the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills.
</P>
<P>
   (D.) Education policies in Texas would find young William
Faulkner getting marked down on the same test for not getting to
his point in 27 lines.
</P>
<P>
   Answers: B and D are locks. A and C remain to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   That just about sums up the test-driven education policies in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember the ``back to basics'' movement? What we have in
Texas is not just a sequel, not just ``Planet of the Basics Part
II.'' We have ``Beneath the Planet of the Basics.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's working, which is really good and really a problem,
depending on who's getting taught. For those students who have
below-level English and math skills, it's improving their basic
skills. For many at or above grade level, I fear it is leveling
them off, numbing their palates. Sirloin? Um, what have you got in
the area of food pellets?
</P>
<P>
   In the Waco Independent School District, one of the state's
strictest TAAS-based retention-promotion policies has raised TAAS
passing rates that were in the 60s (passing all portions) for most
grade levels two years ago to more than 70 percent, 80 percent
among fourth- and fifth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   This is a definite point of pride, particularly in a district
used to getting roughed up over social ills it inherits and is
expected to abate.
</P>
<P>
   WISD deserves credit for doing what Texas has assigned: improve
low-achievers' skill levels. But what about those not so low?
Particularly in the elementary grades, particularly when there's a
thirst and a need for health, science, social studies and all else
that education really means.
</P>
<P>
   Even low achievers need these life-affirming, scintillating
experiences. But as applied, the TAAS drumbeat can drown them out.
This emphasis seems to assert the need for something school
districts long ago forsook: tracking, separating students according
to skill levels so that those who really need remediation get it,
and those who don't move on.
</P>
<P>
   Several states are positioned to emulate Texas' system. Let's
hope that what results isn't national standards focused on too-low
common denominators. Don't look now, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Recently textbook publisher Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co. was in the news
selling millions of dollars of books to Texas districts based not
just on quality but on the claim that the books offered an inside
track on passing TAAS. Harcourt Brace should know. One of its
subsidiaries writes TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   This angered lawmakers, who attached an amendment to the state
school funding bill, still pending, to prohibit those who write the
TAAS from selling textbooks to the state.
</P>
<P>
   At this point TAAS starts to loom as a viral agent. In the 1980s
the dumbing down of Texas texts based on the challenges of Longview
textbook monitors Mel and Norma Gabler influenced learning across
the country, since Texas is the second-largest purchaser of
textbooks. Publishers adjusted to meet Texas' specifications and
the Gablers' rants.
</P>
<P>
   As much as TAAS has helped improve things for lots of low
achievers, it's not the answer to our nation's ills. In fact, if
you ask some kids, teachers and parents, TAAS is the illness.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
