<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0525 -- For a first-time visitor, New York City
can be as intimidating as King Kong on a rampage down Fifth Avenue.
No wonder orchestrating a family getaway can be a daunting
prospect. There's so much to see and do in Manhattan, vacationers
find it hard to know where to start. (Crouch Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color photo of young
girl looking over the city from atop the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THINGS TO DO -- You'll have a much better Big Apple family
vacation if you remember this phrase: You can't do it all. Here are
some ideas to help you get started. (Crouch Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-color photo of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO -- Info box listing recommended reading and
where to go for information when traveling with children to New
York City. Art includes 3-column color photo of Central Park and a
1-column color photo of the Empire State Building.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS _ The State Department has rescinded a
warning for traveling to China, saying that the security situation
has improved, although the potential still exists for further
violent acts. (Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAJUNCOUNTRY _ Opelousas, La. _ Cajun country is the Deep
South with a French accent, a larded-up Loire Valley, where a
seven-course meal consists of a six-pack of beer and a link of
boudin, the Cajun sausage. Everywhere is evidence of a heritage not
lost in modernization but rather zealously guarded. That heritage
is being celebrated all year with Francofete, commemorating the
300th anniversay of French influence on Louisiana. (Konigsmark,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAJUN-SURVIVAL _ A list of everything you'll need to
survive in Cajun Country, from lip balm and bug spray to the
``Cajun Country Guide.''(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAJUN-TOUR _ We provide four agendas, fanning out from
Lafayette, that could be experienced over a four-day stay in Cajun
Country or separately. The greatest emphasis is on where to eat,
with music a close second. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Pensacola's Festival of Five Flags is June 2-12. We
visit beforehand and take readers on a tour of this historic town
with its museum, galleries, shops, restaurants and inns. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. MOVED.
</P>
