art and history. (Ruff, Palm Beach Daily News) WITH COLOR PHOTOS
and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CENTERPIECE
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-CHEFWEAR _ Television and other media have elevated chefs
to celebrity status in the 90s, so it's only natural that ``chef''
fashion has emerged. Chefwear, a line of clothing that used to be
marketed exclusively to working chefs, found last year that almost
20 percent of their business came from home cooks who wanted to
wear the baggy pants with crazy prints and boxy white shirts like
their chef idols. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May 30.
</P>
<P>
   CLOTHES-BABIES _ There's a baby boom rattling the fashion
industry. Infants and toddlers have become the muse of the moment,
inspiring designers to create pricey clothes and accessories that
give new meaning to the word ``pampered.'' (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SWIMSUIT _ Huge parody of Sports Illustrated swimsuit
issue. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Available as three open color pages.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-THRIFTSHOPS _ WACO, Texas _ Admit it. The first thing
you think about when you see a great dress in the window of a
department store is its price. There are wiser ways to spend your
hard-earned money but still look like a million bucks, experts say.
Ever considered stopping by that thrift store you pass by everyday
on the way to work? It may surprise you. (Mays, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Lee learns a lesson about resilience from the
tiny plants he planted in the rocky grounds of his McCaysville
home. What didn't survive the wintry nights or smouldering summers
was eaten alive by rabbits and deer. Still, seedlings from the rose
of Sharon, the prickly pear and many others are alive and thriving.
(May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   PLANTS-HEAT _ Some bulbs know how to take the heat. Particularly
noteworthy is the hydrangea. Once established, certain varieties
responds well to aggressive pruning. (Glasener, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by NYT clients).
</P>
<P>
   LOGCABIN _ AUSTIN _ how a couple stripped away a much-layered
1850s log house in the middle of Austin, the oldest such
continually occupied log structure in the city, and preserved the
original bldg as part of their home. (Allison, Austin
American-Statesman). 45.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-VIOLENCE _ Television is both more violent and less violent
than it used to be. Top-rated prime-time shows have very little
violence, yet Extreme TV grows around the fringes: pro wrestling,
Fox's violence-verite, Jerry Springer (they promised to tone down
the violence before, and didn't) and even local TV news and network
newsmgazines. What's causing Extreme TV? The audience
fragmentation, the hard-to-capture but lucrative market of young
men and teenaged boys, and overall social trends. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   TERRICLARK _ Of all the hat acts that came and went in country
music in the '90s, Terri Clark has survived to become one of
Nashville's hottest rising stars. When she burst on the scene in
1995, she was the only female wearing the costume du jour _ cowboy
hat, tight jeans, big belt buckle and boots. Now that her career is
in full gear, we talk with Clark about country music, Deepak
Chopra, divorce, fame, songwriting and the Shania-like changes
swirling around her in Nashville. Photos taken in Nashville.
(MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. MOVED
</P>
