<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0525 -- In ``Why the Cocks Fight,'' Michele Wucker
shares far-reaching conclusions about ethnic conflict in Hispaniola
that would apply to other countries as well. (Morris, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes 3-column B&AMP;W map illustration of
Hispaniola and a 1-column color photo of the book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW ``PHANTOM MENACE'' --There is basically just one
question about ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' Do
you read the book before or after you see the movie? (Guinn, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes 1-column color photo from
``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW BERLIN-- Edward Jablonski's bland but informative
biography of Irving Berlin conveys hardly any personal flavor of
the man, but it is valuable as an official show-by-show,
movie-by-movie, song-by-song account of Berlin's career. (Holden,
N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW WHOLE WOMAN -- When Germaine Greer's swaggering
call for sexual liberation, ``The Female Eunuch,'' appeared in
1970, it created a sensation. Now, some 30 years later, Ms. Greer
has written a sequel of sorts. It's a book that is as sour as
``Eunuch'' was exuberant. (Kakutan, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS -- After so many changes in the publishing industry
in the 20th century, what can we expect in the 21st? Will books as
we know them become as obsolete as Babylonian clay tablets?
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column
color photo of author Tom Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ If Tom Franklin's short stories seem gritty, maybe
it's because he worked in a grit factory in Alabama before becoming
a writer. Not the eating kind of grits, but grit used in
sandblasting. Franklin, whose title story in his book,
``Poachers,'' won the Edgar Award, is being touted as one of the
South's brilliant new writers. Also, a new novel by a Savannah
podiatrist, ``Delirium of the Brave,'' takes up where ``Midnight in
the Garden of Good and Evil'' left off. The book about family
skeletons and lost treasure is topping local best seller lists and
has attracted Hollywood interest; Anne Rice's son, Christopher, has
signed a deal for a two-book package. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   KIDBOOKS _ KIDBOOKS _ Roundup of new books for children,
including one about Gullah people of Georgia and South Carolina.
(Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by
NYTNS clients).BOOKS-NONFICTION _ A roundup of new nonfiction of
note: Joe McGinnis' ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro,'' Jon
Margolis' ``The Last Innocent Year,'' Michael Pearson's ``Dreaming
of Columbus,'' Cindy Aron's ``Working at Play: A History of
Vacations in the United States'' and new bios of Betty Friedan and
Germaine Greer. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 43.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ We arrived under cover of darkness and a light
patter of rain. Christopher Hitchens got out of the Toyota Camry,
surveyed the suburban expanse around him and said, ``Good
heavens.'' Earlier, at the hotel bar downtown, he had fortified
himself with a belt of Scotch. If he was wondering whether the
dosage had been sufficient, that would be remedied presently.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, 5/30.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GUTERSON _ Success hasn't spoiled David Guterson. Or if it
has, he keeps it well-hidden. Despite making millions from his 1994
best-selling debut novel, ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' the
42-year-old former high school teacher still dresses in jeans and
khaki shirts and still lives on Bainbridge Island off the coast of
Washington state in a house he rents for $325 a month. In between
gulps of bottled water at the Ritz-Carlton Buckhead, Guterson
talked about how his new novel, ``East of the Mountains,'' evolved,
how his life has changed, and how the power of language can change
others. A Q&AMP;A. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. EDs:
Embargoed until Sunday, 5/30.
</P>
