<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dear Grads: Please pay the $170,625 you owe us soon
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memo from: Society
</P>
<P>
   To: 1999 graduates
</P>
<P>
   RE: Your Happy Day
</P>
<P>
   Dear Graduate:
</P>
<P>
   Please accept this as society's sincerest congratulations on
your successful completion of 12 years of school. We know that it
isn't just 12 years of school you have completed, but also numerous
tests that you were required to pass in order to get your diploma.
</P>
<P>
   We're all very, very proud of you. As you well know, not all of
you made it. Some of those who began this journey with you in
kindergarten will receive your graduation notice in, say, the Beto
Unit of the Texas Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   We realize that it has not been easy to keep on the straight and
narrow course that brought you to this moment.
</P>
<P>
   But as a new graduate, it is necessary that we conduct just a
little bit of business at this time and we hope it does not detract
from the joy you and your family are feeling during your
commencement.
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary to inform you that it is time to pay Society
back for your 13 years of schooling. Surely, you did not think this
was free?
</P>
<P>
   By our calculations, your bill comes to $170,625.
</P>
<P>
   We realize that this may seem like a great deal of money,
especially when you see it all in one lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Please remember, though, that this accounts for a full 13 years
of schooling at our low, low price of only $75 per day _ which
really does not begin to cover all of our costs. The total is
figured on 175 days for each of the 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard the comment before, dear graduate, that for $75 a
day you could get yourself a cheap motel room and meals. This may
be true, but without a high school diploma, your life will seem
like an endless series cheap motel rooms, and, we might add, will
have the same faint odor.
</P>
<P>
   But, don't worried. It took you 13 years to amass this bill, we
would not expect you to pay it all at once. No way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we are willing to accept payment in three easy
installments, once per month. Of course, you'll understand that
this method does incur 21 percent interest, compounded hourly.
Furthermore, we must insist that you do not go beyond the 90-day
time period. We've been waiting for this money for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, given the fact that you are about to enter college, you
are a bit strapped for money just at this moment. Maybe you don't
have the $170,625 in your checking right now.
</P>
<P>
   If this is true, perhaps you'd like to consider our alternative
form of payment that does not include your paying ANY money, at
least not in the traditional sense.
</P>
<P>
   Permit us to explain. You can forego paying the $170,625 if you
agree to become a responsible and involved citizen. To follow this
course of payment you would agree, to wit (now that you're a
graduate, your life will be full of ``to wits.'' You had best get
used to it.):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To not only register to vote, but to actually vote and to
actually make some effort to be an informed voter;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To volunteer for something in the community. Take your pick.
It doesn't matter to us. It can be with your church, with a civic
club or just on your own. DO SOMETHING. And, by the way, we expect
at least a couple of hours a week to retire a $170,625 debt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To support some worthy cause with your dollars. Support
something. It can be United Way, it can be your high school
scholarship fund, it can be your church, but invest your own money
in doing something worthwhile. This can be pennies a week, just
make some commitment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perform at least one random act of kindness per month. We'd
like to ask for a higher frequency, but we'll settle for once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the most important to wit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Never, not once the rest of your life, ever utter a statement,
or even think it, which conveys the idea that Society owes you
anything whatsoever, not fairness, not a chance, not a meal, not
anything.
</P>
<P>
   We may someday give you something you need, but we don't owe
you. Not at all. It is you who owes us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
