<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3188 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVILIANS-SIDE-$ADV30     05-27 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILIANS-SIDE-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISTORY SHOWS CIVILIANS A CASUALTY OF WAR
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CIVILIANS-$ADV30.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civilian casualties are as old as war itself.
</P>
<P>
   Four centuries before Christ, during three decades of fighting
between Athens and Sparta, the massacre of children, leveling of
entire cities and the selling of captured women into bondage became
the stock-in-trade for combatants in the Peloponnesian War.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no length to which violence did not go,'' wrote
Thucydides, one of the world's earliest war correspondents. ``Every
form of iniquity took root in the Hellenic countries by reason of
the troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Two millennia later, English poet and novelist George Gascoigne
witnessed ``a pitiful massacre,'' of some 17,000 men, women and
children when Spanish troops sacked the German city of Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was neither man nor means to resist them,'' Gascoigne
wrote in 1576. ``When the blood is cold and the fury over, methinks
that a true Christian heart should stand content with victory, and
refrain to provoke God's wrath by shedding of innocent blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in history, however, can begin to rival the mass killing
brought on by the combination of lethal technology and the clash of
empires and values that the 20th Century has wrought.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 6 million civilians died during World War I, a
figure so appalling that it shocked a generation into believing it
had fought the war to end all wars.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams of peace were shattered just two decades later by World
War II, which claimed at least 20 million civilians from Moscow to
Shanghai, from London to Dresden, from Okinawa to Manila Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean War followed just five years later, leaving an
estimated 1.5 million civilians dead. A decade after that, the
United States began its involvement in Vietnam, a conflict that
killed an estimated 1 million civilians between 1965 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the United States launched air strikes on Iraq in
1991, the global reach of CNN made it clear that President Bush
would pay a heavy price in public support if civilian casualties
got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The use of laser-guided bombs aided U.S. pilots' accuracy in
urban areas, but there were still incidents of civilian deaths, as
when scores were killed in an attack on a supposed military bunker
that turned out to be in use by civilians.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison to that conflict, the air war against
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia is a full generation ahead in terms of
technology, the most intensive campaign of precision guided weapons
in history.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't ensured that all bombs hit their mark, but it's big
step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
