<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     05-27 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, May 27, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   O'HAIR-CHARGES (San Antonio) _ The federal government has for
the first time publicly accused David R. Waters, the office manager
of Madalyn Murray O'Hair, and three other men of the brutal murder
of the missing atheist and two of her children. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-HARASS (San Antonio) _ In a bruising defeat for this
city's police department, jurors have awarded a half-million
dollars to an officer who claimed his patrol unit was told to
harass surly looking teen-agers and soiled derelicts lingering
around San Antonio's downtown tourist areas. By MARO ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WAGE (San Francisco) _ This city's living-wage proposal
has suffered more setbacks. Three members of San Francisco's Living
Wage Task Force have resigned, citing delays and a lack of progress
in the plan to raise the standard of living for the working poor.
And another task force has told city supervisors it cannot support
the proposal. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   ZEDILLO-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
has postponed his goodwill trip to Texas, due to start June 16,
until July. The June trip to San Antonio, Austin and Dallas was to
have included separate meetings with Gov. George W. Bush, business
and political leaders and immigrants from Mexico. By CARMINA
DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-BROWN (San Francisco) _ Like singer Wayne Newton, Mayor
Jerry Brown was in Las Vegas and had a song to sing. His tune was
not aimed at the lounge lizards of Caesar's Palace, but to the
world's largest conference of shopping center developers and
retailers. It went something like this: Come to Oakland/The rents
aren't high/Crime is down/Downtown's on the rise. By the San
Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ A controversial bill that
would have set up a showdown between charter school supporters and
state teachers' unions has been killed as California lawmakers seek
a compromise to placate both sides. Assemblywoman Carole Migden, a
San Francisco Democrat, withdrew her measure to require charter
teachers to become members of the union in their district. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-2000 (Jerusalem) _ A middle-class pilgrim from Florida
swings his hoe through the hard Nazareth dirt, chipping away at
centuries of debris to help uncover the village of Jesus'
childhood. In a suburb of Jerusalem, a 53-year-old grandmother from
northern California stacks giveaway clothing for the poor as she
awaits the Second Coming. With the approach of the Third
Millennium, as many as 6 million tourists are expected in Israel
next year. Why do people impart so much religious significance to
such an arbitrary thing as the year 2000? By CECILE HOLMES. (For
Weekend release, May 29-30).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON (San Francisco) _ In the latest blow to San Francisco's
corporate image, Chevron Corp., the fourth-largest oil company in
the country, announced it is selling its Market Street headquarters
and moving up to 1,000 of its 1,400 employees to the East Bay. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC and RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-GAMES (San Francisco) _ With ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _
The Phantom Menace'' breaking box-office records, and Episode 2's
release still three years off, many Star Wars fans need an outlet
for their Force hysteria. Sure, there are action figures and story
books, but what does a fan do when all this is still not enough?
Star Wars creator George Lucas hopes to fill the void with video
games. By GLENN RUBENSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BLUE-HOUR (San Francisco) _ It's usually the kiss of death
to say of a new book, ``I challenge anyone to sit down with this
novel and get up without having finished it.'' But T. Jefferson
Parker's new mystery, ``The Blue Hour.'' comes real close to being
a one-sitting page-turner. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JELLIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Jellies, preserves and marmalades are
more than bread spreads. Here are a few of ideas to get the most
out of a jar of jam. By RUTH FANTASIA
</P>
<P>
   SALADS (Albany. N.Y.) _ To keep salads from becoming boring,
I've learned to add a few things to your basic lettuce, tomatoes
and cucumber. For instance, meats and fish turn a simple salad into
an entree. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The tendency to overreact to an
accident or some other tragedy is as American as talk radio. As
soon as a story breaks, the collective reflex is: Who's fault is
it? Is there someone we can sue? And, how many laws can we pass to
make sure this will never, ever happen again? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This city's Mission District is
being squeezed hard. Families are being crushed between low-lifes
and those who live the high life. This most vital of working class
neighborhoods, the heart of San Francisco's Latino culture, is
being overrun with prostitution, drugs and crime. At the same time,
it's being gentrified by hipsters and programmers, bringing with
them coffeehouses, trendy restaurants and sky-high rents. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-CLUB (San Francisco) _ David Brower is revered by many in
the environmental movement, but I am glad he didn't win the Sierra
Club presidency in last weekend's vote. Had he won, he told local
reporters, he would have considered resurrecting immigration as an
environmental issue. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
