<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3253 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-27 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA CAN'T LEAVE CHINA OUT IN THE COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans have a right to expect more of a candidate for the
presidency of their great nation than the kind of blatant, petty
and reckless political demagoguery that Texas Gov. George W. Bush
has spewed out in reaction to the release of the Cox report.
</P>
<P>
   Glossing over the fact that the select House committee on
Chinese espionage, headed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., found
that the Chinese pilfering of U.S. nuclear and missile secrets
spanned 20 years and four administrations, Bush rushed to blast
``the current administration's failed policies toward China.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Clinton administration's China policy differs in
no substantial way from that of former President George Herbert
Walker Bush, who arguably was the most ardent China lover to have
ever occupied the White House since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, the governor's father who went to the wall
for China to save its most-favored-nation trade status after the
Chinese government's massacre of the demonstrators for democracy in
Beijing's Tiananmen Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress passed numerous laws to restrict trade with
China because of human rights violations, Bush the elder vetoed
them all. Even after being defeated in his 1992 presidential
re-election bid, the former ambassador to China continued to be a
staunch advocate for ``engagement'' with China.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-day visit to China in 1994, the man who has been
described as the architect of U.S.-China relations since the 1970s
continued to champion Beijing's cause, speaking angrily of the
pressure brought to bear by Congress to prevent China's hosting the
2000 Summer Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my view that had those games gone to China, that kind of
openness, that kind of contact, that kind of influx of athletes and
interested people from all around the world would lead to more, not
less, to more individual freedoms in China,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Bush administration, trade relations with China
blossomed immensely, and major corporations stampeded to gain
access to the world's greatest concentration of potential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   It is reasonable to assume that during that buoyant period of
Sino-American relations, the opportunities for Chinese espionage
also blossomed. And it is just as reasonable to ask why the Bush
administration did not find out about it and put a stop to it.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be just as pointless at this juncture to point the
finger of blame at former President Bush as it is to assign an
excess of culpability to current President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Both were and are right in their view of the importance of
keeping China engaged. It is, to paraphrase an ancient saying,
better to have the giant panda inside the banquet hall micturating
out than outside the hall micturating in.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, George W. Bush wishes to repudiate the policies of
George H.W. Bush while taking a cheap shot at Bill Clinton, that is
his business. But he can't have one without the other.
</P>
<P>
   It is likewise counterproductive, and probably hazardous to
global security, to demonize China excessively for its espionage.
It did what comes naturally to nations in stealing the nuclear and
missile secrets. Greater vigilance simply should have been
exercised during past decades to prevent the Chinese from being
able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is what to do now that the secrets are out and
China may be able, within the next few years, to develop nuclear
intercontinental ballistic missiles capable of reaching the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the recommendations of the Cox report must be
followed, and more must be done to stop the bleeding of strategic
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, this country must take steps to protect itself
from a Chinese nuclear missile attack. In that regard, research
into and development of an anti-ballistic missile defense system
must be expedited.
</P>
<P>
   The Aegis sea mobile system advocated by the Heritage Foundation
appears to offer the best promise for early deployment, and the
price _ an estimated $3 billion during the next five years _
appears to be right. That would buy time for a more elaborate
ground-based system.
</P>
<P>
   All of this could be done while maintaining friendly relations
with China. In fact, the knowledge that the United States is
developing such a system might improve the climate of Sino-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, utmost care would have to be taken to make certain
that China didn't steal the secrets that would allow it to defeat
the system.
</P>
<P>
   Unless such a nuclear shield is established, this country could
one day find itself in a confrontation with China over Taiwan, with
only the fear of mutually assured destruction to deter them from a
war that could go nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
