<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3278 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WINSLOWBOY-TEX     05-27 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WINSLOWBOY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STIFF UPPER LIP QUIVERS, AFTER ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When writer-director David Mamet decided to direct a new version
of ``The Winslow Boy,'' he knew what he was doing. The material, a
warhorse of a play that has been performed at many a high school,
is about the troubles that befall a privileged London family when
its honor is assaulted. Winslow, 13, has been expelled from the
Naval Academy because he's accused of stealing. The family gives up
everything _ its money, its future _ to combat the attack on its
reputation that this charge becomes.
</P>
<P>
   This premise doesn't sound like something that would attract a
talent like Mamet. But Mamet embraces the squareness of playwright
Terence Rattigan's drama and improves upon it, in part by pulling
off a thoughtful trick. He doesn't play up the trial, which could
have been given the whooping adrenaline rush of ``A Few Good Men.''
Mamet knows we can handle the truth, especially the theatrical
parading of morality that passes for truth in a courtroom
melodrama. Instead, Mamet has chosen to go deep. He fixes his
sights on the rigidity of the upper class and the emotions under
all those waistcoats and corsets.
</P>
<P>
   The formalism of the staging corresponds to the bearing of
Arthur Winslow (Nigel Hawthorne), the smug patriarch who rules the
roost. When his son comes home and has to reveal what has happened,
the tension simmers in the room. But then an odd moment
materializes. Arthur looks his son square in the eye and asks,
``Were you so afraid to tell me the truth?'' Suddenly ``Winslow''
becomes as much about the love of a family as it is the pursuit of
what's right as compared to justice. This flinty-eyed old prat is
also revealed as a fierce papa bear who will do anything for his
children.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Winslow Boy'' moves forward, we can't help but feel
contemporary resonance. It seems remarkably similar to the
publicity and eventual impeachment trial surrounding the President
Clinton/Monica Lewinsky situation. This connection couldn't have
been planned. Yet Mamet's intent to strip away the stiff-backed
manner of the upper-class Brits gives this old chestnut new life.
</P>
<P>
   And a play that seemed like a joke takes on a whole new life.
Incredibly, its power intensifies when lawyer Sir Robert Morton
(Jeremy Northam) takes on the case. We're shocked that this frigid
barrister is capable of feeling; he's not just an imperious prig.
He's also not the forward thinker he seems to be, as Arthur's
daughter (Rebecca Pidgeon), who's part of her brother's fight as
well, finds out. A withered, beaten man by the time the trial comes
to its conclusion, Arthur has been forced to ask some questions.
When his wife asks, ``Why are you doing this? He'll never remember
it,'' we wonder, too. But by that point, Mamet's cool, elegant
direction has pulled us deeply into what might have seemed
frivolous on the surface: an examination of Old World heroism and
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Winslow Boy''
</P>
<P>
   Rated: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Mamet
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon, Jeremy Northam
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: G'
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
