A3282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     05-27 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K OBSESSION: MILLENNIUM BUG WILL CAUSE SEVERE ECONOMIC WOES,
AUTHOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How's that stockpiling going?
</P>
<P>
   For many, that question is a serious reference to gathering the
water, food, generators and other things needed to survive when the
mother of all computer glitches, known as Y2K, causes societal
chaos come Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For others, the Y2K scare is a joke. They scorn the doomsday
predicted for the first day of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planner John Mauldin of Arlington, Texas, suggests a
middle-of-the-road approach. He says the Y2K bug will cause severe
economic woes worldwide, but he stops short of suggesting that you
stockpile toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin predicts a serious economic downturn _ at least in the
short term. He predicts that the Y2K problem will cause the first
significant recession in the United States in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries even less prepared for the changeover than the
United States will face massive unemployment and depressions, he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin's predictions and suggestions are in his book, ``How to
Profit From The Y2K Recession ... By Converting the Year 2000
Crisis into an Opportunity for Your Investments and Business,''
(St. Martin's Press, 352 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   When I first glanced at the book title, I thought it read ``How
to Profit from The Y2K `Obsession.''' With all the outrageous
survivalist products and land deals out there, this book seemed a
natural. After learning that Mauldin publishes a Year 2000 Alert
monthly investment newsletter, lectures at Y2K investment
conferences and is a self-appointed ``expert'' on investment issues
regarding Y2K, I think my misread title may still be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer industry consultants say that the bulk of Y2K
problems are being addressed and that most of the glitches will be
fixed in time to avert a catastrophe. Mauldin even quotes a survey
by Ziff-Davis, a media and marketing company that publishes trade
magazines such as PC Week and Interactive Week. The survey
indicates that 150 small and medium-sized U.S. business are
optimistic about meeting their Y2K deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin, whose budding media empire depends on fueling Y2K
concerns, discounts the Ziff-Davis survey results. ``Of all the
reports, studies, surveys and stories about Y2K that I have read,
this survey amazes me the most. It boggles my mind ... If those of
you who are in business get nothing else from this book, I hope
that you will come away with an understanding that this is a
serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He then quotes numerous articles, congressional speakers,
professors and others to build his case for the seriousness of the
Millennium Bug. It is destined to be, Mauldin suggests, ``the cause
of the mother of all traffic jams on the information highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin then addresses multiple areas of Y2K concern _ from
utilities to banks to businesses _ and devotes a chapter to each,
focusing on the big troubles that he says await key sectors of the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among his economic predictions for the United States within the
first 18 months of 2000:
</P>
<P>
   _Double-digit unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   _Stock market declines of 50 percent below its 1999 highs.
</P>
<P>
   _Billions of dollars in deficits.
</P>
<P>
   He also says that electricity, phone service and other
infrastructure elements may be down for a time but should be up and
running efficiently by the third week of January. As for the
stockpiled food, he suggests donating it to food banks and homeless
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   But by the second quarter of the year 2000, the strains of Y2K
will begin affecting the economy in general, Mauldin predicts. More
businesses will go bankrupt than normal because of the ripple
effects of Y2K, unemployment will reach the highest levels in 25
years and the stock market will ``get ugly,'' he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin offers financial advice _ such as hedge funds _ to
counter the economic downturn. He also has advice for businesses
that may not have looked at this issue or its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And the good news is that Mauldin sees a bull market after the
Y2K recession. He offers ideas on how to capitalize best on that as
well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rewards That Drive High Performance: Success Stories from
Leading Organizations''
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas B. Wilson
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Yes, once again our favorite reward-based company, Southwest
Airlines, is recognized in this book on employee incentives. But so
are myriad newer companies, including Internet book distributor
amazom.com and coffee shop chain Starbuck's. Author Thomas Wilson
runs a consulting firm that helps companies design and implement
performance-based reward systems. He says that improved quality,
productivity and increased revenues will result from his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice Job: The Guide to Cool, Odd, Risky, and Gruesome Ways to
Make a Living''
</P>
<P>
   By Jake Brooks and Nicholas Croman
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press, $14.99
</P>
<P>
   If you've always wanted to be a body piercer, Zamboni driver or
pilgrim, this book will show you exactly what they do, how much
they typically get paid and what perks and risks are associated
with it. Other nontraditional occupations checked out by the
authors, who call themselves the Lookout Media Team, include rodeo
clown, mystery shopper, executioner and TV weathercaster. The
authors say the book isn't really to guide you to these
professions, but to help broaden your outlook.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Business Golf: The Art of Building Relationships Through
Golf''
</P>
<P>
   By Pat Summerall
</P>
<P>
   Birch Lane Press, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   If you ever need to convince your spouse that you really need to
play golf on Saturday, this may be the book for you. NFL
broadcaster Pat Summerall and two CPAs, Will Rhame and James
McNulty, discuss the fine art of schmoozing on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
