<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, May 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans three pages of coverage on the Kosovo
crisis in the indictment on war crimes charges of Milosevic and
other Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (The Hague) _ Solobdon Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, and four other officials _ the Serbian president,
Serbian interior minister, Yugoslav deputy prime minister and
Yugoslav Army chief of staff _ are indicted on charges of war
crimes. The chief prosecutor, Louise Arbour, says the indictment
raises serious questions about negotiating with the officials on a
peace accord. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SKETCHES (Belgrade) _ Sketches of the five indicted
officials.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the indictment.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Yugoslavia refuses to recognize the
indictment; Milosevic calls for a political solution ``without
delay;'' the arrival of Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy, may
be delayed until Friday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Military developments on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Dateline to kum) _ Albanian villages are shelled
again as more heavy fighting at border erupts. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering, among others, stories on the legal
implications of the indictment, reaction from Russia and reaction
from refugees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ Pakistan shoots down at least one
Indian warplane as India continues its attack in Kashmir and
tensions grow. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ They won't have Bibi to kick
around anymore: Benjamin Netanyahu, the former prime minister,
gives a farewell address at a meeting of his Likud party. He is
expected to withdraw from politics and give his analysis of the
election he lost to Labor's Ehud Barak. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Beijing) _ China's official press on Thursday
assailed the credibility of the congressional report accusing China
of massive military espionage, asserting that ``the specter of
Mcarthyism looms large in the Cox report.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno defends
herself on charges related to the espionage report at her weekly
briefing. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-FERTILITY (Rome) _ The Italian parliament has approved a
draft law on assisted fertility, which among other things, sets
prison terms for doctors who use donated sperm to perform
artificial insemination. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TABLOID (London) _ The Sun runs a big apology to Sophie
Rhys-Jones whose topless picture they published weeks before she is
to marry Prince Edward; the palace says it's not enough. By Warren
Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS (Istanbul) _ Just days before the leader of the
Kurdish rebels is to be tried for his life on charges of treason,
Turkish government leaders have suggested that the trial may be
postponed so the military judge on the three-judge panel can be
replaced by a civilian. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DEMS (Washington) _ The Democrats circulate another
petition today to force a vote, this one on a patients bill of
rights. In the mean time, the Democrats may try to stop the House
from adjourning. These two actions show the trend of this Congress:
Republicans are trying to fend off Democratic issues, pre-empt
Democratic issues, or stall Democratic issues. Deliberate or not,
this has the effect of moderating this Republican Congress. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Vice President Gore and House
Democrats try to push for more political advantage on gun control,
as a subcommittee of Judiciary holds hearings on the juvenile
justice bill. This will be first live discussion on issue from
House members. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Action on defense authorization
bills with the possibility of riders limiting high-tech exports to
China. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PICKERS-UNION (Oxnard) _ Pickers for the nation's largest
strawberry grower voted overwhelmingly to unionize, but state labor
officials said early today it was too close to call which union
would represent the workers. The vote is a key test of the United
Farm Workers' long-running effort to restore its once-formidable
clout in agriculture. About 100 people, including babies and
grandparents, were camped out on the floor of a state labor office
in Salinas on Wednesday night waiting for the results. Many had
been up since 5 a.m. picking strawberries. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SUIT (Denver) _ The first suit is filed in
Littleton, Colo., by the family of the black student killed at
Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Developments at the trial of police
officers accused in the sexual assault on Abner Louima, a Haitian
immigrant prisoner. By Joseph B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADING-HOURS (New York) _ After years of resisting a move to
extend trading hours _ and after several previous attempts failed
because of lack of interest among investors _ the nation's major
stock markets are now hurriedly readying plans to trade stocks for
several additional hours in the evening. On the horizon, many in
the industry see around-the-clock trading. A NASD announcement is
expected at 2 p.m. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BEER (Mexico City) _ In 10 years, Grupo Modelo has
transformed Corona from a once-obscure Mexican beer into a global
brand whose recognition approaches that of Coca-Cola or Marlboro
cigarettes. Modelo's success stems in large part from shrewd
tactics in marketing Corona to America's Generation X as well as to
millions of Mexicans living in the United States. And Modelo's
consistent refusal to take on debt has helped it avoid financial
turmoil during devaluations of the Mexican currency. By Rick Wills.
</P>
<P>
   INFINITY-OUTDOOR (Undated) _ Infinity Broadcasting, the radio
giant owned by CBS, agrees to acquire Outdoor Systems Inc., the
nation's biggest billboard company, for about $6.5 billion in
stock. The Advertising Column by Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-PINAULT (Rome) _ A Dutch court upholds the alliance
between Gucci Group and Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, dealing a blow
to LVMH's effort to gain control of Italy's biggest fashion
company. LVMH plans to appeal. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ Corporate profits rose 4.3 percent in
the first quarter, new figures show, the sharpest increase since
the first quarter of 1995. The data may quell fears that rising
stock prices are quickly outstripping growth in profits. The data
were part of the Commerce Department's revision of its gross
domestic product estimate. The revision, to 4.1 percent from 4.5
percent, was slightly sharper than expected. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 11:15 a.m., stocks were lower. The Dow
Jones industrial average was off 1.17 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 down 0.7
percent, but the Nasdaq composite was up slightly. European stocks
were lower, with London down 0.84 percent and Frankfurt down 2.29
percent. In Asia, the Nikkei and Hang Seng were little changed. The
U.S. long bond was at 5.82 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Raleigh, N.C.) _ An IBM executive gives a
deposition in the Microsoft antitrust case; he is expected to tell
of Microsoft threats to punish IBM for using non-Microsoft software
in its products. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BEATRICE (Undated) _ TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.
announces plans to sell the last of its holdings, dismantling what
was once the nation's biggest black-owned company. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Looking at Deutsche
Telekom's revised game plan after losing its Telecom Italia bid and
the fate of Global One. Deutsche Telekom's chief rival, Mannesmann,
meanwhile, buys out AT&AMP;T's and Unisource's stakes in Arcor for $523
million. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-BOOK (New York) _ Broadway Books, owned by Random House,
has canceled a book about Disney written by a respected
entertainment writer. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
