<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-HNS &LR;      05-27 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVRON TO TRIM ITS SAN FRANCISCO PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 and RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the latest blow to San Francisco's corporate
image, the Chevron Corp. says it will its Market Street
headquarters and move as many as 1,000 employees to other Bay-other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting move, which is expected to be completed by the
end of next year, will leave about 500 workers, including the
company's top executives, in the city, which Chevron will continue
to name as its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Well over 7,000 Chevron workers will be based throughout the
East Bay. No jobs are expected to be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made as part of cost-reduction efforts that
will save more than $500 million this year, said Dave O'Reilly,
vice chairman of the nation's fourth largest oil company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidating many of our San Francisco employees into our
offices in the East Bay makes good economic sense,'' O'Reilly said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, which has been based in San Francisco for more than 75
years, said it would put its two office towers on Market Street on
the market immediately. Following the sale, the company plans to
lease back office space for its corporate suite.
</P>
<P>
   The two high-rise buildings, totaling 750,000 square feet, could
sell for as much as $225 million, according to Jay Seiden, manager
of research services at Marcus &AMP; Millichap, a San Francisco-based
real estate broker.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron employees were notified of the company's plan Wednesday
afternoon, after the move was approved Tuesday by the company's
executive committee and Wednesday morning by the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Most employees now working in San Francisco will be transferred
to the corporation's San Ramon and Concord offices.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of several high-profile acquisitions of San
Francisco-based corporations by out-of-state and foreign companies,
the moves could be seen as another dent in San Francisco's
reputation as a premier city for corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Transamerica Corp., BankAmerica Corp., Pacific Telesis Group,
AirTouch Communications Inc., Montgomery Securities Inc. and
Robertson Stephens Inc. all have been swallowed up in such deals in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, the press secretary for Mayor Willie Brown,
noted the city's successful efforts to lure multimedia companies,
film industry business and a new University of California at San
Francisco campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's jobs in, jobs out,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, however, was less
phlegmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me to be a pretty ungrateful act,'' Ammiano said
of Chevron's plan. ``San Francisco has bent over backwards for
Chevron. It's not like there's a bad business climate here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano noted that Chevron had recently received several tax
rebates and credits and had historically been very successful in
lobbying the board on a range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has extensive operations in the East Bay already. Some
6,600 workers are spread over four major sites in Richmond,
Concord, San Ramon and Walnut Creek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
