<HEADLINE>
THE FORCE OF `STAR WARS' SPARKS VIDEO GAME SPINOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GLENN RUBENSTEIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom
Menace'' breaking box office records, and Episode 2's release still
three years off, many Star Wars fans need an outlet for their Force
hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are action figures, story books and the Taco Bell
meets KFC meets Pizza Hut ``Feel the Force'' sweepstakes, but what
does a fan do when all this is still not enough? Short of seeing
the movie again and again, many die-hard fans will be left cold by
what most Star Wars-related products have to offer (Jar Jar Binks
throw pillow anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars creator George Lucas hopes to fill that void with
video games. Among the hundreds of licensed Phantom Menace
products, the most interesting (and interactive) are the related
video games, two of which were released last week in conjunction
with the opening of the film. The games are part of Lucas' overall
licensing and marketing strategy for the film.
</P>
<P>
   LucasArts Entertainment, which develops games, is an especially
profitable part of the Lucas business empire. With software titles
based on Star Wars characters, Indiana Jones and original
properties like the Monkey Island series, the company consistently
has top-ranked computer game titles. In addition, through an
alliance with video game giant Nintendo, games that LucasArts has
developed _ like ``Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire'' _ have moved
more than a million units in the video game cartridge format.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company has looked to start publishing its
own games for console systems like the Nintendo 64 and PlayStation,
just as it has for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Forbes magazine placed Lucas on its annual list,
``The World's 200 Working Rich,'' estimating his fortune at $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal Lucas struck when he made the original Star Wars movie
for 20th Century Fox allowed him to keep both the sequel and
merchandising rights for the film. Since 1977, the Star Wars
trilogy has generated an estimated $4.5 billion in product sales.
</P>
<P>
   When the films were released as a special edition in 1997, the
licensing blitz for all things Star Wars heated up again, and
``Phantom Menace'' would appear to have more licensed products and
promotional tie-ins than any other movie in history. The formula
has worked in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a very good chance this will be the single
biggest movie ever,'' said Marty Brochstein, executive editor of
the Licensing Letter, a New York trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Brochstein estimated that sales from products related to
``Phantom Menace'' could exceed those of the industry's
merchandising champion, ``The Lion King.'' Brochstein estimated
that the Disney film had sold about $1.5 billion worth of toys,
mugs, T-shirts and videos since its 1994 release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody would be mightily disappointed if (`Phantom Menace')
didn't move over $1 billion in merchandise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally remains to be seen, but the two video games
currently available are sure to help the bottom line. The two games
are ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' (LucasArts for
PC; PlayStation version available shortly) and ``Star Wars: Episode
I Racer'' (LucasArts for PC and Nintendo 64).
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars fans can look forward to at least two more titles this
year. In June, LucasArts plans to release one for the PC that looks
at the making of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
Also planned is a PC game called ``Star Wars: Episode I _
Obi-Wan,'' which is similar to ``Star Wars: Dark Forces,'' an
earlier game that is a first-person adventure in the style of
``Doom'' or ``Quake.'' It's scheduled for release in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   LucasArts also has just released ``The Gungun Frontier,'' a
hybrid CD-ROM (it will run on both PCs and Macs). Players try to
help Jar Jar Binks establish a new colony on a nearby moon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
