A3314 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-THREE28-COX     05-27 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-THREE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Image, extremes of Vietnam today
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winner of three awards at the Sundance Film Festival _ the grand
jury prize, the audience award and best cinematography _ ``Three
Seasons'' also holds the distinction of being the first U.S. film
shot in Vietnam since the war. Twenty-six-year-old Tony Bui, a
Vietnamese-American born in Vietnam but raised in California, has a
natural eye for beautiful images and a naif's predilection for
emotional epiphanies. Thus, his feature debut is narratively facile
yet visually rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' interweaves several obliquely connected
stories into a tenderly appealing pastiche. In one, a simple
country girl, Kien An (Nguyen Ngoc Hiep), hired to pick lotus
flowers for a reclusive master poet (Tran Manh Cuong), dares to
penetrate the floating temple that's become his self-appointed
floating tomb. In another, Hai (Don Duong), a kindhearted cyclo
driver _ a cyclo is like a rickshaw-bicycle combo _ is smitten with
an ambitious call girl (Zoe Bui) who works Saigon's posher hotels.
Frequenting those same lobbies, though with considerably less
success, is Woody (Nguyen Huu Duoc), a street urchin who hawks
lighters and chewing gum from his tattered merchandise case.
Finally, there's James (Harvey Keitel), a Vietnam vet looking for
the daughter _ and the inner peace _ he left behind two decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company that helped produce ``Three Seasons'' is Open City
Films. So if there's a whiff of Italian neorealism in the film's
simple, unadorned style, it's probably intentional. Yet Bui has his
own voice. While he acknowledges the scars left by the war and the
disastrous Western residue that's turning Saigon into a place full
of Coca-Cola signs and artificially scented plastic lotuses, he
also shows us a Vietnam that's not just killing fields or steaming
jungles in which a Stallone can play out foolish retro-macho
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he presents a country in transition, caught between a
conflicted past and an uncertain future. The pace is slow
(sometimes irritatingly so) and the stories are predictable
(ditto). But there's an omnipresent lyricism that's seductive. And
when Bui tosses off a shot of Kien An and her fellow lotus-pluckers
floating serenely in the otherworldly embrace of giant waterlily
pads, you know you're in the good hands of a born filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Harvey Keitel, Nguyen Ngoc Hiep and Don Duong. Directed
by Tony Bui. Rated PG-13 for language and sexual innuendo. With
subtitles. 1 hour, 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: This Sundance fave is an appealing pastiche of
stories set in postwar Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
