<HEADER>
A3315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDANCE-BUI28-COX     05-27 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE-BUI28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Subliminally, director was drawn to native Vietnam
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was born in Vietnam, but from the age of 2 grew up in
Sunnyvale, Calif. When he was 19, writer-director Tony Bui returned
for the first time to his birthplace to visit his grandparents. He
hated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four hours I wanted to go back home,'' he says during a
recent Atlanta visit to promote ``Three Seasons,'' his feature
debut which won three awards at this year's Sundance Film Festival.
``I'm sure I insulted everyone around me. It was too hot, it was
too humid. Where I was staying, there was no running water, no
electricity. There was an outhouse in back. I'd never left the U.S.
before, and I'd grown up in the suburbs, so it was a real culture
shock.''
</P>
<P>
   He experienced another kind of shock when he returned to
California two weeks later. He realized he couldn't wait to return
to Vietnam. ``I felt very sad and embarrassed because I'd wanted to
leave, and I couldn't understand why I was being drawn back,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Consciously, he'd recoiled from the alien sounds, smells and
tastes of the country. But on a subliminal level, those very things
had begun to haunt him: The morning cries of women in the streets,
hawking porridge and bread; the tinkling of bells on passing
bicycles. ``All the different textures and sights and sounds would
be in my head every morning when I woke up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So Bui returned several times to Vietnam, staying with family
and becoming fluent in the language. That came in handy when he
decided to write ``Three Seasons'' and shoot in Ho Chi Minh City
(formerly Saigon). It became the first American film shot in
Vietnam since the war, and the first to be acted in Vietnamese by
native actors.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for Harvey Keitel, who plays an American vet
looking for the daughter he sired during the war. His is only one
of four interwoven story lines. The movie includes the tale of a
young woman who befriends a reclusive, dying poet; a cyclo driver
who falls for a brash prostitute; and a street urchin trying to
make ends meet by selling trinkets. The characters and much of the
dialogue derive from people whom Bui, 26, met in Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was going to focus on one story,'' he says. ``But I
liked them all so much, I decided I would create this fabric, and
each story would be a thread.''
</P>
<P>
   Keitel's participation helped Bui secure funding, though at
their first meeting, Keitel told the filmmaker that he was ``99.9
percent'' sure he couldn't take the role. Even so, he promised he'd
read the screenplay within seven days and make a decision. Bui
remembers, ``I left the meeting and thought, `Yeah, right. I bet he
gives that line to everyone.' I couldn't even get my mom to read it
in seven days. But he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
