<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOCCER, THEY AGE GRACEFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Walter Zenga's friends and former teammates are moving
on, retiring, being eased out from their playing careers. Or, they
are reinventing themselves as coaches, player-coaches, and elder
statesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Zenga and Lothar Matthaus helped Inter win the
Italian Serie A championship, the climax of a brief return to glory
for the Milan club.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zenga and Matthaus are involved in other projects. Zenga is
attempting to transform the Revolution, who have earned only seven
points in nine games going into their visit to the MetroStars
Saturday. Matthaus is on a bigger stage, playing Wednesday for
Bayern Munich against Manchester United in the European Champions
League final in Barcelona before 80,000 spectators and a 500
million-plus television audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matthaus shows what the mentality of soccer is,'' Zenga said.
``If you feel strong, if you have pride and courage, you can play
when you are 38. If you lose that passion, you can't do anything,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also luck and having someone believe in you. If I
lose a game and only have seven points I can be angry. But I am
only angry when we lose. On Monday, I am thinking only about New
York. And after New York I will be thinking only about Chicago,''
the Revolution's next opponent June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has attempted to restore the Revolution's confidence after
three successive losing seasons. His formula is to provide
consistency in game preparations, defensive organization, and
world-class goalkeeping. The methods appeared to be working at the
beginning of the season, but now the team is nearing a crossroads,
with only one point and without a regulation-time victory since
April 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``One point in a month can be a nightmare,'' Zenga said. ``By
the end of the season I am 100 percent sure we will have a good
team. But if we don't continue to work, if we don't continue to
believe, we will have a graph that goes up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has helped keep the Revolution in contention in most games
this season. Their only two-goal defeat occurred at Columbus two
weeks ago. So, the team has been able to retain some self-belief,
despite a 340-minute goal drought. Last season, the Revolution's
credibility was shattered after it began surrendering five and six
goals in games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution might be depending too much on Zenga's
goalkeeping, much as Bayern Munich needed Matthaus Wednesday. After
Matthaus was substituted, Bayern surrendered two last-minute goals
in a 2-1 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have not settled into a coherent attacking
formation, partially because of a lineup unsettled due to injuries.
Neither of their two most creative midfielders, Edwin Gorter and
Jair, have had an impact. Gorter did not travel to Los Angeles
because of a groin strain, but he has been practicing at near full
speed and said he expects to be on the bench against the
MetroStars. Jair has been playing on the right side of midfield,
minimizing his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   A change in formation might change the team's fortunes, but
Zenga plans to stay with a 4-4-2 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the coach who makes the formation, but the qualities
of the players,'' Zenga said. ``My mentality is a 4-4-2, we want to
have two forwards and a No. 10. Anyway, a 4-4-2 will become a 3-5-2
as soon as one of the outside backs moves into the midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the problem is not about numbers, but about mentality,
pride, and courage. The only difficult thing in soccer is when you
lose, because then it is easy to think you are bad. We have to
continue to follow our philosophy, not change just because we lost
a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
