<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR BUSINESSMEN TO PICK UP THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A month ago, Bob Kraft did the right thing. A week
ago, the Massachusetts legislature did the right thing. Twenty four
hours ago, the NFL did the right thing. Now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   Now the businessmen and businesswomen of Boston have to do the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Kraft did what he always promised he would, turning
his back on a pile of money so high it is difficult to fathom and
coming home to Massachusetts on a promise and little more. Kraft
walked away from a free stadium and guaranteed revenue in Hartford
that could have totaled more than a billion dollars because he
never wanted to go there in the first place and proved it in the
only way a businessman can. They showed him the money and he showed
them the door.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Kraft peeked through the door a few times and looked
at the pile but in the end one of the pet phrases of Kraft's mortal
enemy, Bill Parcells, speaks truthfully of this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go by what I see,'' Parcells often says and if you look in
Foxborough today and for many years to come, you will see the New
England Patriots there. You have Bob Kraft and no one else to thank
for that because he did not do what the Harvard Business School
taught him. He didn't take the money.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't take it in part because all those stories he used to
tell about the Boston Braves leaving town really were in his heart
and partly because local pols and business leaders promised they
would help him solve his stadium financing problems. A week ago,
against all odds if you know their history, the hacks in the
legislature came through on their end, doing what they said they
would by approving $70 million in funding to build roads, sewars,
and off-ramps even though they insisted on extracting a pound of
flesh by making Kraft the only owner in American sports history to
have to pay back infrastructure money, making him repay half that
sum over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wednesday, NFL owners voted 28 to 1 with two abstentions to
grant Kraft a ``loan'' of slightly more than $141 million to cover
half the cost of building what he projects to be a $277 million
stadium ($250 million for the stadium and $27 million in land
acquisitions). The Philadelphia Eagles and Denver Broncos received
similar financial assistance with their stadium projects but far
less total cash because both have more than double the public
funding Kraft received.
</P>
<P>
   That ``loan'' will be repaid from the 40 percent share visiting
teams receive of stadium income generated by the 9,000 club seats
the Patriots' new home will have; that is where Boston's business
leaders have a rare opportunity _ the opportunity to put their
money where their mouths have been.
</P>
<P>
   They promised to buy those seats, seats your average Patriot fan
could never afford, if Kraft came home from Connecticut. Now we'll
see if they do what Kraft, the legislature, and the NFL has done.
Now we'll see if they deliver or if their words prove to be more
empty than their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   If he builds it, will they come?
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, before he builds it, will they buy club seats
so critical to the financing plan?
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue spoke briefly about that
Wednesday, saying he will return to Boston next month to try to
coax business leaders into coming through on what both he and Kraft
view as a pledge to buy those 9,000 club seats.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, a second provision takes the ``loan'' money off
the top of the league's television revenue but one of the
abstaining voters, Raiders owner Al Davis, said he is not happy
about that provision and questions its legality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I didn't want to do anything to hurt Bob,'' Davis said
Wednesday. ``I'm glad he got what he needed to stay in Boston. But
this is a tax on all the teams that are not doing as well (as the
teams with new stadiums).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of owners didn't want to see Bob move out of Boston to
Hartford. They got him back to New England so they had to make him
promises. But never before in the history of the league have the
poor given to the rich for them to do well. When they destroyed us
at Hollywood Park, they didn't talk about TV revenue (as a form of
financial assistance).'' Hollywood Park is where the then Los
Angeles Raiders hoped to build a stadium in 1995 before the league
refused to grant Davis all the help he believed was necessary and,
he says, began to work against the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of TV revenue to cover a shortfall may not even be
legal,'' Davis said. ``We don't think it is. But a lot of them have
stadium problems and it's tough to get them to change their minds.
They can only think of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Davis's doubts and the lone no vote of Cincinnati
Bengals owner Mike Brown, Bob Kraft got what he needed Wednesday.
He got help from his partners, even though he still will end up on
the hook for between $150 million and $200 million in new loans to
cover his end of the project.
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't have yet is help from his friends. If the
Patriots' stadium deal is going to work, it's time for the FOBs
(Friends of Bob) to do what they asked Kraft and the legislature
and the NFL to do.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for them to spend some money. Their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
