<HEADLINE>
DON'T LET DANCE FEVER HIT TOO SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tricia Tanner has a date, a shimmery new blue dress, and an
appointment for a manicure and hairdo. ``This is going to be a lot
of fun,'' she says about the dance June 18 that will mark the end
of her years at Chenery Middle School in Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Middle school.
</P>
<P>
   Kids call the dance ``the semi,'' as in semiformal, even though
the Parent Teacher Organization which sponsors it calls it simply a
dinner dance. Last year, three limos delivered students to the
school, at least one boy wore a tux, and some girls had corsages.
This year, principal Deborah Alexander has sent out a letter to
discourage such grown-up and extravagant gestures for 14-year-olds,
especially having dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about the messages we're giving our kids when we let
them do things that are not age appropriate,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to tone the dance down are controversial. Robin
Gabrielle Moore, cochair of the PTO committee in charge, doesn't
see what the fuss is about. ``It's just a fun night,'' she says, a
conclusion she came to after attending the dance last year and
determining that behavior didn't get ``out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say it's not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents, the Tanners included, feel pressured by a culture
that encourages children to try on inappropriate grown-up behavior.
At the same time, they don't want to be so rigid that they create
barriers to communication. For them, a dance like this is the
perfect, albeit unintended, symbol of the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly,'' says Tricia's mother, Shawn, ``this whole thing has
been the largest issue we've ever had with her.'' Their solution
was to compromise: Tricia wanted to shop in December, they held her
off until February; she paid for the dress with baby-sitting money,
but her parents bought the bolero jacket they insisted she wear to
cover its skimpy top. They'll split the cost of hairdo and
manicure.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Voce, also an eighth-grade Chenery parent, wishes the
event to end the Chenery years was not a dance. ``We need something
more inclusive,'' she says. ``Something that appeals to a wider
range of kids, so every child can feel good about sharing the
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A meaningful recognition
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with marking the end of middle school;
the problem is how it's done,'' agrees psychologist and author
David Elkind, a professor at Tufts University. ``You need to look
at this in a context of what children this age are capable of
appreciating. Of what has meaning for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when they are feeling small and vulnerable because of
the looming transition to high school, what has most meaning is an
event that acknowledges their growth and links it to how well
prepared they are for what's next, says developmental psychologist
William Damon, director of the Center on Adolescence at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
   His preference is an achievement dinner, where everyone is
recongized either individually or in a group, as well as some
social event, preferably a field day off-site. He counsels against
anything that looks like a graduation _ ``They're not leaving their
community; they're not making choices about their path in life;
they're going on, most of them together, to another school,'' he
says _ and against anything that adds pressure or stress, such as a
dance.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why:
</P>
<P>
   --It's developmentally inappropriate. Eighth graders typically
like to do things in threes, fours, and fives, not in pairs, says
Robert Spear, executive director of the New England League of
Middle Schools. An activity that even tacitly encourages coupling
is not relevant or fun for them. ``They may push for it because
they're mimicking behaviors they see in older siblings, but it
doesn't mean they're comfortable or ready for it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a risk that parents inadvertently send a message
that translates to some children as pressure to do something they
aren't ready for and to other children as license to do something
they shouldn't: ``If Mom and Dad think I'm old enough to get all
dressed up, wear makeup, have a date, or go in a limo, just like
18-year-olds, what else can I do like 18-year-olds?'' In other
words, says middle school consultant Joan Lipsitz, ``You are
sending powerful signals about exclusive relationships, provocative
dress, sex, and alcohol.'' Lipsitz is the founder of the Center for
Early Adolescence at the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   --It's divisive. Eighth graders are so incredibly
self-conscious, it's as if they have an imaginary audience. ``They
assume people are watching,'' says Elkind. ``They feel
excruciatingly visible if they don't wear, sound, and act like
everyone else.'' By the time of a junior or senior prom, they will
be developmentally better equipped to tolerate differences in dress
and style. For now, however, a girl whose family can't afford a
dress like her friends' or a boy who thinks he can't dance as well
as his peers can be miserable. Not only does a dress-up dance
exacerbate differences and inadequacies, but the differences become
the basis for teasing and discrimination, says Elkind. His most
recent book is ``All Grown Up and No Place to Go: Teenagers in
Crisis'' (Addison Wesley).
</P>
<P>
   --It's how kids get jaded. ``Finishing eighth grade is not
enough of an achievement to warrant this kind of celebration,''
says Damon. ``It leads to a sense of entitlement and
self-importance. It also cheapens the real prom, three years
later.'' Indeed, an eighth-grade quasi prom may be what ups the
ante for The Prom. ``If you have a semiformal in the gym in eighth
grade, a senior prom in the gym isn't special enough,'' says Spear.
``You have to go to a hotel. You have to have the limo.''
</P>
<P>
   Spear's desire to abandon a dress-up, adultified event is not
only a developmental issue but also one of safety. ``There is more
alcohol use among eighth graders than parents realize,'' he says.
``A semiformal encourages kids to strut their stuff, to emulate
older behavior. That means drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Ephraim Curtis Middle School in Sudbury, Mass., principal
Kevin Thomas Plodzik has scaled back what was once a formal
eighth-grade dance to a dance-buffet. In a letter to parents, he
writes, ``This is not a mini-prom.'' He discourages dates, formal
wear, and limos. The students plan the menu and put together a
lighthearted awards and achievements ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner-dance is the last night of school. The next morning,
there's a ``Moving On'' ceremony, where Plodzik entrusts the class
to the principal of the regional high school, telling students, ``I
know you are prepared for the continuation of your education.''
Wrapping the two events around each other, says Plodzik, gives
eighth graders more of what they need: a balance of academic and
social interests, as well as closure for the past and a nod to the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in Belmont, Tricia Tanner's brother, Troy,
remembers his experience last year attending the eighth-grade dance
at Chenery Middle School. He had a date, but no tux or limo. He had
a good time, and he hopes his sister will, too, but, looking back,
he also remembers, ``There were some kids who felt left out, you
could tell. They were on the sidelines, just kinda sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Children need to reflect on accomplishments before they can
look forward. Reflect as a family on your child's growth and
accomplishments during middle school.
</P>
<P>
   --The end of middle school raises anxieties in students: Will I
have friends? Will I look as good as other kids? Will my study
habits be good enough? Am I going to have to drink to be cool? Will
I be safe? Am I weird to be thinking about sex?
</P>
<P>
   --Expect and show understanding for your child's tears, sadness,
or moodiness. Even though he knows he will be with the same kids in
high school, he also knows that friendships, interests, and
activities will change.
</P>
<P>
   --Many eighth graders worry about getting bullied, teased, or
even beaten up in high school. Researchers say there is some truth
to this, so don't pooh-pooh the fear. Just providing the chance to
talk can help. So can some coping skills: ``Maybe it's a good idea
to walk to classes in a group.''
</P>
<P>
   --Although youngsters will protest when you take a stand against
a skimpy dress or impose a curfew that's earlier than friends',
etc., they typically secretly appreciate it because it shows you
care and are able to tolerate their anger and frustration. However,
be sure to have reasons: Not ``Because I said so,'' but: ``This is
not safe for a 14-year-old to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ A study released last month by the University of
New Hampshire says that children whose child-care providers share
positive emotions, respond to their vocalizations, and offer
physical contact will have improved school readiness skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
