<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE COMICS SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite what some angry readers inferred from Monday's Ombudsman
column, I had nothing to do with those recent changes in the
Globe's comics. Nobody asked me if I thought Over the Hedge, Stone
Soup, and Kudzu should be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth _ and it's not worth much, obviously _ I
don't think any of the strips should have been eliminated. They
were among my favorites. But I had no part in those decisions. As a
member of the now infamous (in some quarters) Globe ``comics
jury,'' my task is to review new comics submitted for
consideration. That's all. Decisions about which comics will run
and which won't are made at a much, much higher _ one might even
say rarefied _ editorial level.
</P>
<P>
   I sympathize with readers who've been calling and writing to
excoriate me for my supposed part in all this. I'm one of those
childish people ombudsman Jack Thomas complained about in his
column, a reader who is devoted to the comics, who more often than
not turns to the comics first. Some may consider this a character
flaw, but I don't think it makes me any more intellectually
depraved than readers who turn first to sports, or Ann Landers, or
Names &AMP; Faces, or the horoscope, or even the op-ed page. Most of us
go on to read the rest of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Furious comics fans have mercilessly attacked Thomas in the wake
of Monday's column. I won't join in. I will even say in his defense
that he isn't as lacking in humor as his critics imagine. His is a
thankless job, by and large. In his column he describes how,
returning from vacation, he had to read more than 700 e-mails from
readers. Clearly he wasn't thrilled to receive hundreds more from
disgruntled comics readers. Since he confesses that he dislikes
comics, perhaps the paper should have a comics ombudsman, a person
who knows and likes comics and can represent readers' interests.
(Note to Editor: I'm not volunteering for the job.)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas wrote of the comics: ``More often than not, they are
merely recycled vaudeville gags that were not funny the first time
around.'' But there is a great deal more to the comics. On any
given day, individual strips may be lame. But overall, the Globe's
collection is of a high order. There's some very sophisticated
humor on the page. Robotman. Zippy. Sylvia. Dilbert. Rhymes With
Orange.
</P>
<P>
   The comics are not just a collection of cheap laughs. They
reflect the world we live in. Those who don't follow the comics
choose to ignore one of the great repositories of popular culture,
and may find themselves out of touch with social currents and
attitudes. Nothing strikes more sharply than humor. George Bernard
Shaw and Mark Twain knew it; Scott Adams, Nicole Hollander, and
Garry Trudeau, among others, know it. In recent years, few
editorial commentators have been as consistently effective as
Trudeau has been in ``Doonesbury.''
</P>
<P>
   Like every other newspaper, the Globe wants to attract younger
readers. One way to do it is with comic strips. A recurring reader
criticism of the Globe's comics has been that not enough of them
are aimed at children. Perhaps by adding The Boondocks, the paper
is trying to provide another strip that will appeal to kids. But
then why cancel Over the Hedge?
</P>
<P>
   Reading a daily newspaper is a habit. I was hooked at a very
early age, before I could read, by comics. At 11, I discovered Walt
Kelly's Pogo in the old Boston Herald. That comic strip changed my
life. I'm sure some people find that laughable. If they do, they're
unfamiliar with Kelly's work. He was a brilliant, humane social
satirist, as well as an inspired artist. Pogo led me to love
newspapers, and that led me here, I might say For Better or for
Worse. Which is another good strip. Let's hope they don't cancel
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
