<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RUSSELLTRIBUTE-AR     05-27 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RUSSELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL ENJOYS LAST LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
 TRIBUTE-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thirty years and three weeks to the day after Bill
Russell played his last game for the Celtics, a game that fittingly
ended in a world championship, the town, the team, the fans, and a
glittering list of celebrities and players paid homage to the man
and his career.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearly three-hour ceremony that featured lighthearted
moments and moving tributes, the 65-year-old Russell, an intensely
private man who called the whole affair ``totally and completely
embarrassing,'' had his uniform No. 6 re-retired in a very public
ceremony Wednesday night at the FleetCenter. The number originally
was retired March 12, 1972, in a private ceremony, which was
Russell's wish at the time.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was anything but private. Organizers of the event,
a benefit for the National Mentoring Partnership, expected a crowd
of about 10,000. The event was held on the 30th anniversary of
Russell's last season and last title, won May 5, 1969, in Los
Angeles against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates from his Celtics days were there, ranging from Bob
Cousy to John Havlicek to Bill Sharman to Sam Jones to Arnie Risen.
Celtics players who followed him and won titles, Larry Bird and
Dave Cowens, were there. Wilt Chamberlain decided at the last
moment to be a part of the night and took a red-eye flight from Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby and Bryant Gumbel were the masters of ceremonies.
Johnny Mathis and Aretha Franklin sang. President Clinton, would-be
president Bill Bradley, and Michael Jordan were among several who
offered taped tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's former coach and Celtics icon Red Auerbach helped him
raise the banner to the rafters to the music of ``Summon the
Heroes.'' Russell then spoke for about 20 minutes, telling stories
of his parents, thanking the fans, and saying, simply, ``The life I
led was the life I thought I should lead.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, Russell again said it was overwhelming to be
the subject of so much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think of myself as Charlie Russell's kid,'' he said.
``This kind of stuff is foreign to me. I really don't understand
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the ceremony was ``fantastic, almost like another
(championship) banner up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The stands were half-full, much like they were when Russell was
leading the Celtics to 11 titles in 13 years. Sixty-five tables
were scattered on the floor, each with a basketball centerpiece,
green and white napkins, and a chocolate dessert with a white
shamrock and green No. 6 on top. (Most went uneaten, except at the
Globe table.)
</P>
<P>
   Much like Russell's career, the evening got off to a late start
and lasted a little longer than expected. (Russell did not join the
Celtics as a rookie until December due to an Olympic commitment.)
The highlight for the fans was the joint appearance of Bird (also a
late addition), Bill Walton, Cowens, and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar to
offer their thoughts on Russell and winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Bill Walton doing up here?'' Bird cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Walton went on to explain how Russell was his hero and role
model, then took a shot at some conservative blacks, mentioning
Clarence Thomas and J.C. Watts. ``Somehow,'' said Walton, ``things
got turned around.'' But, he also said, ``no one in the history of
sports did a better job of making people's life better than Bill
Russell.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird noted that Russell set the bar so high ``that if you put on
a Celtic uniform and didn't win a championship, you have no game.''
Bird also took a shot at Jordan, who, in his video tribute, noted
Russell had won all his titles in an eight-team league. NBA
commissioner David Stern also took note of Jordan's remark, adding
that all the good players in the league in Russell's time were on
eight teams.
</P>
<P>
   When Russell made his first appearance on stage, the crowd gave
him a five-minute standing ovation, which brought him to tears. He
took a seat on the stage, looking almost as if he would rather be
anywhere else, comforted by a couple of Cosby wisecracks.
Eventually the crowd quieted to hear Auerbach present his franchise
center with a piece of the parquet floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby noted how Russell started as a champion, ended as a
champion, and won most of the time in between. He then admitted he
had trouble with all the adulation ``because I'm from
Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell also was praised on tape by Clinton, Bradley, Jordan,
Kevin McHale, Magic Johnson (who was thought to be coming), Jerry
West, Elgin Baylor, and Lenny Wilkens. Tom Brokaw, Jim Brown,
George Plimpton, and writer Frank Deford offered tributes.
Russell's daughter, Karen, broke into tears when she referred to
her father as ``the greatest daddy in the whole wide world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino presented Russell with a Paul Revere
bowl, which apparently was misinscribed. (Russell's middle name is
Felton. The bowl had the name spelled Fenton.) Celtics
coach/president Rick Pitino _ who got some boos _ presented Russell
with a small replica of the banner with Russell's number on it. He
said the highlight of this past season _ and admitted there weren't
many _ was the night when Russell addressed the team.
</P>
<P>
   Six teammates from Russell's first title team, 1956-57, were in
attendance. Cousy, on behalf of the squad, presented Russell with a
watch. ``You should have had this years ago because you were late
to every practice Arnold (Auerbach) ever called,'' Cousy said.
</P>
<P>
   Four teammates from the championship teams from the 1960s _
Havlicek, Tom ``Satch'' Sanders, K.C. Jones, and Sam Jones _
presented Russell with two wooden seats from old Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen opponents from Russell's years _ Jerry Lucas, Rick
Barry, Willis Reed, Bob Pettit, Oscar Robertson, and Dolph Schayes
_ offered their thoughts on playing against him. That, in turn, led
to the introduction of Chamberlain, who good-naturedly played the
role of villain.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby talked about the dinners Russell and Chamberlain would
have on Thanksgiving at Chamberlain's home in Philadelphia. The
Celtics and 76ers would play that night. ``He ate the dinner and
then he ate you,'' Cosby said to Chamberlain. Russell not only ate
at his house, but took a nap in his bedroom, too.
</P>
<P>
   The two then engaged in a toy game of pop-a-shot and Chamberlain
won, 1-0. ``I finally won a game in Boston,'' he cracked. Russell
earlier had said he was fortunate to have had Chamberlain as a
rival; it had made both players better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to improve,'' he said, ``and if I didn't improve, I'd be
embarrassed every night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
