A3330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSEX-ADDICTS-2TAK     05-27 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSEX-ADDICTS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGERS IN THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many of his chat pals nationwide, he stumbled onto the
universe of on-line sex with the most innocent of intentions.
Lonely and bored at work one day, the 37-year-old analyst began
clicking the mouse and discovered the Yahoo! cosmos of personal
ads.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he was talking dirty to dozens of women on the
Internet and becoming so aroused that he would masturbate in front
of the computer screen on line for four to five hours a night. Soon
he was having one-night stands with women he had met in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   By March of this year, James, who is now 40 and asked that his
last name not be used, had become so addicted to the X-rated
pleasures of the Net that he broke up with his girlfriend because
he preferred cybersex to real sex with a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell her why I was breaking it off _ I was too
embarrassed,'' says James, who describes himself over the phone as
tall (6 feet 2 inches), dark, and good-looking. ``But I would
rather go on the Net and talk to people in chat rooms than be with
her. It's more exciting. When I made love with her, the pace was
too slow.''
</P>
<P>
   James's behavior may be an extreme example of how the Internet
can become ``the crack of sexual compulsivity,'' as San Jose
psychologist Alvin Cooper puts it. But according to Cooper and
other specialists, an increasing number of Americans are drawn to
the lure of on-line sex _ chat rooms, personal ads, pornography _
because it is affordable, accessible, and usually, anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for many of these people, cybersex is becoming hazardous to
their health, psychological and otherwise. Consider the fate of
Ronald F. Thiemann, the former dean of Harvard Divinity School.
When Harvard officials discovered last fall that Thiemann had
compiled an extensive pornographic collection from the Internet on
a Harvard-owned computer, they demanded his resignation as dean.
</P>
<P>
   While on-line kinkiness does not usually exact such a drastic
toll on participants (most are not divinity school deans), new
research indicates that an excessive diet of on-line sex can cause
problems, even when it takes place in the privacy of one's home,
with one's personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recently published study of 9,000 on-line users found a direct
correlation between the amount of time people spent on line for sex
and the psychological problems they were grappling with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the more time people spent on line for sex, the more
problems they reported in their work lives or social activities,''
says Cooper, who spearheaded the study as director of the San Jose
Marital and Sexuality Center.
</P>
<P>
   While people who logged on for 11 hours or more each week seem
to lose themselves (as James has) in compulsive, and some would
say, destructive sexual activity, those who went on line for less
than one hour a week ``seemed to be using Internet sex in a way
that was more recreational than sexual, in the same way that people
read Playboy and watch `Baywatch,' '' Cooper says.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how deeply individuals become enmeshed in on-line
smut, Internet experts agree on one thing: cybersex, a behavior
continuum that ranges from occasional dirty talk in chat rooms to
spending hours viewing erotica from adult Web sites and
masturbating five to six times a night in front of the computer, is
big and getting bigger every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least 9 million people visited a sexually oriented adult Web
site every month of last year, according to one survey. In
addition, there are 250 sex-related bulletin boards on the Net
where users can post illicit messages, and hundreds of chat rooms,
many full by midday, where people with the nicknames Hornyman,
PurEvil, SexiLady09, and Busty68 chat around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   According to social scientists, the popularity of cybersex can
be boiled down to one simple reality: a surprisingly large number
of Americans have difficulty maintaining healthy sexual
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of people who comprise 90 percent of the
people on the Internet: those who are not in a relationship and
those who are dissatisfied with the relationship they're in,'' says
Dr. David Schnarch, director of the Marriage and Family Health
Center in Evergreen, Colo. and author of ``Passionate Marriage:
Keeping Love and Intimacy Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnarch points to a national study published in February in the
Journal of the American Medical Association that found that 43
percent of women and 31 percent of men report having sexual
difficulties. ``Cybersex is the trough to which these relationship
problems are now channeling themselves,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For people who are starved of real intimacy, sex chat,
euphemistically called romance chat, is a way to connect with
others. It provides a sense of belonging, an online ``Cheers''
where everybody knows your nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Net, people feel like they belong, like someone misses
them,'' says Maressa Hecht Orzack, a psychologist and founder of
the Computer Addiction Service at McLean Hospital in Belmont.
``These people are not in good relationships to begin with and they
don't feel like anyone cares about them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orzack says she counsels dozens of people every year that become
so addicted to sex chat that they flunk out of school, jeopardize
their job or marriage, and in some cases neglect their children.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3333 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSEX-ADDICT-2ND &LR;  &UR;      05-27 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSEX-ADDICT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... their children.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's a woman I'm working with right now who neglects her
child,'' Orzack says. ``She resents the fact that she has to get
offline and feed him dinner; she doesn't want to miss anything.
She's divorced and there are custody issues and she might lose her
child. Yet she tells me, `I'm not giving up the chat.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Pershica, 26, of Oklahoma, says she turned to the Internet
while recovering from a difficult divorce. She lives in an area
where there are few places to meet people, and chat rooms, she
says, allow her to screen people and explore her sexual desires in
a relatively safe context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cybersex lets me get to know a person and avoid the crazies I
might not recognize in person,'' says Pershica, who cleans houses
for a living. ``Sure, I've run across some perverts, but I've also
met gentle, caring people who, like me, were going through rough
times and needed someone to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch at the Cottonwood Cafe in Boston, Ben, a 24-year-old,
also says he prefers to meet people on line rather than go to
nightclubs. The risk of rejection is somehow less acute. And he
finds the sex talk titillating and at the same time benign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to a club, the women kind of look at you funny and
if they're not interested, they make it clear they want you to go
away,'' says Ben, a computer technician who works during the day
and takes night courses at University of Massachusetts at Boston.
``I find that tiring.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ben, who asked that his last name not be used, says
he corresponds regularly with a lot of female friends on the Net,
and they're more than willing to talk dirty with him. And on line,
he can fib about his height _ ``I'm short for a guy,'' says Ben,
who is 5 feet 6 _ and no one is the wiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lying is quite common on the Net. According to the San Jose
cybersex study, about 60 percent of the 9,000 participants
acknowledged that they lied about their age; 14 percent reported
lying about some other detail of their persona, and 5 percent
admitted they lied about their gender.
</P>
<P>
   And in what specialists say is possibly the most pernicious
aspect of cybersex, 70 percent of respondents said they keep their
on-line activities a secret from other people in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of working to improve the intimacy in their
relationship, many people are a lot more revealing about themselves
to perfect strangers'' on line, says Margaret Strauss-Black, a
marriage and family therapist. ``That takes the energy away from
their real relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss-Black and other therapists in the Boston area say they
treat a growing number of couples whose marriages are threatened
because one spouse can't stop himself or herself from logging on in
the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   I. Scott Cohen, past president of the Massachusetts Association
for Marriage and Family Therapy, says that with one couple he is
treating, the woman accidentally discovered that her husband was
involved in sexual chat on the Internet; he had saved a bunch of
X-rated e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt very betrayed, very violated,'' recalls Cohen, a
family therapist. ``The husband claimed that he was just playing
around, that it was all a joke. But to her, it felt like he was
having an affair.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case involving a professional couple, the woman
discovered that her husband was using cybersex to explore his
sexuality with other men. She confronted her husband and the man
with whom he was having cybersex (by e-mail) _ and then dragged her
husband into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It created big-time problems for them,'' says Strauss-Black,
who treated the couple. ``The wife was most upset about the fact
that her husband was not being upfront with her about what he was
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many people, specialists say, are ashamed of their sexual
fantasies and afraid to share them with their significant other.
Many men, for instance, don't want their wives or girlfriends to
know that they fantasize about cross-dressing or having sex with
another man. Similarly, some women fantasize about sex with another
woman and don't want their husbands to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to confide your secret fantasies to somebody
you're going to see day after day,'' Dr. Schnarch says. ``What the
Internet offers is the instant gratification of a fantasy without
the vulnerability and personal exposure of a real relationship. You
don't have to grow up to have sex on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   James, the cybersex addict, says he is just beginning to realize
that he has problems with the way he views women and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view of women is really low and I think that comes from
childhood, the way my father treated my mother, as a secondary
person,'' says James, who works for a high-tech company in
Metrowest and is in therapy. ``There are times when I'm driving
home from having sex with someone I've met on the Net and I say,
`Why the hell did I do that again? But I can't seem to stop; I have
no control over it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
