<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKED DOOR PANEL NEEDS CAULKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My new paneled wood front door gets lots of sun and is
painted black, under a storm. A panel cracked, and I can see
daylight through it. How can I fix it, and keep the door black?
</P>
<P>
   LESLIE HAUSMAN, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The wood in the door contracted when it dried out, and the
panel, set too tightly in the frame, cracked when it shrank. It
wasn't supposed to do that, but it was so tight in the frame that
it could not move with the shrinkage. Result, a crack. Panels in
such doors are free-floating in their frames, so they can expand
and contract without cracking. But yours was too tight.
</P>
<P>
   Short of replacing the panel (a horrendous job in itself), you
can do this: Caulk that crack with a flexible caulking material;
put a bead of this caulk on the crack and press it in with your
fingers. Avoid splinters by wearing gloves. Do the same on the
other side, and scrape and wash off any residue that remains.
Repaint. The caulking, being flexible, will expand and contract
with the movement on the panel, and it should look good for years.
</P>
<P>
   The black paint and the storm make the door hotter from the sun
than normal, and the hotter the wood gets, the more it can dry out
and shrink, so don't expect a perfect performance. But hope springs
eternal, and you will get some years out of the repair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My cedar deck was installed two years ago. I was told to
apply Thompson's Water Seal, but it wore off. I pressure-washed it
and applied Clear Wood Finish (CWF). I later pressure-washed this
in an attempt to clean it, and now the deck is an ugly gray. And,
the boards are creaking when I walk on them. How can I stop the
creaking and make the cedar look good for at least longer than in
the past?
</P>
<P>
   KAY CARLEY, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. We have been brainwashed into thinking that we should apply
sealer or other finish such as Clear Wood Finish to protect the
wood and keep it looking new. There is some truth to the fact that
such sealing will make the wood water resistant (the water beads
up, doesn't it?) to prevent spalling (little flat chips of wood
coming out of the boards), splintering, and cracking. This
waterproofing usually works, especially with pressure-treated wood,
but cedar doesn't always need such sealing, and no one tells us
that the sealer and CWF will wear off in a year or two and must be
applied that often. So much for a maintenance-free deck.
</P>
<P>
   The ugly gray is the result of weathering that all wood will
undergo, even sealed. The CWF is designed to make the wood new
looking, and will restore weathered wood to look new. Red cedar,
the wood of your deck, will weather, but sometimes cedar weathers
to a blotchy, multicolored mess.
</P>
<P>
   The best answer is a semitransparent stain. Colors are limited,
but such stains will last three to five years. Only one coat is
needed at a time. While semitransparent stains are designed to go
on wood siding (clapboards and shingles), they will work quite well
on a deck floor. Avoid paint and solid stains; they do not work on
floors.
</P>
<P>
   For the creaking, drive an extra deck screw through the boards
into each joist, using a power driver. If that does not work, the
superstructure is loose. It would be difficult to reinforce the
superstructure, so unless the frame is racking or swaying, live
with the creaks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an arched passageway 30 inches wide and 80 inches high
between my living room and dining room. I would like to close it
off while one of the rooms is being used temporarily as a bedroom.
I want to keep the arched passageway. What can I use?
</P>
<P>
   PHYLLIS ANDELLA, Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could hang a wide drapery rod above the opening and
install a heavy velvet curtain. Anything else, such as a door,
would require a framework on one side of the opening. A door made
to fit the curved top would be expensive. You could cut 3/4-inch
plywood to fit the opening but it might be difficult to hang,
because the sides of the opening are plaster, not wood.
</P>
<P>
   I think the velvet curtain is your best bet. It would look good
while providing privacy and a small measure of soundproofing as
well, particularly if the velvet is secured against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea: Secure a window quilt against the opening. This
requires a frame in which the quilt rides. The frame is lightweight
and can be secured to the wall with a minimum of fasteners. When
you are ready to take it down, just fill the holes with joint
compound, sand smooth, and repaint. Window quilts are sold in home
centers and specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My gutters are loose, at least I think they are because there
is a gap between the fascia and the gutter. The long nails seem
loose. When I drive them back into position they come out again
before long. How can I keep the gutter tight against the fascia?
</P>
<P>
   HAZEL HARRINGTON, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can buy long gutter screws; they are like the nails only
spiral-shanked like a screw, and are likely to hold better. You can
order them from the Improvements catalog: 800-642-2112.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
