<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINES-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAKE-UP CALL FOR FUND TITANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mutual fund industry has long lived by the slogan made
popular by Greyhound: Leave the driving to us.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying premise of mutual funds is that managing money is
a job for professionals. They know when to buy, what to buy, and
how much to buy. Entrust your money to them, the thinking goes, and
you can sit back, enjoy the ride, and reach your destination
safely.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, thanks to the rise of the Internet, many people have
decided they would rather drive themselves. This group prefers to
buy and sell their own stocks, relying on their own instincts and
their own information. For the moment at least, these investors
seem willing to take more risks for the chance to reap greater
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the day: How worried should the mutual fund
industry be about all this?
</P>
<P>
   The flow of new money into mutual funds has slowed sharply this
year. According to Financial Research Corp., a Boston firm, stock
and bond funds attracted $63 billion in new investment in the first
four months of 1999, down from $118 billion in the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the year was a strong one for the stock
market, so the dropoff cannot be attributed to some general
skittishness on the part of investors. In fact, trading volume was
extremely high during the period; on-line brokerage firms saw their
business grow 30 to 35 percent in the first quarter, according to a
report by CS First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious explanation for the decline is that some of the
money that typically would have gone into funds instead went into
direct purchases of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat skeptical of that idea at first, but I've come
around,'' says Burt Greenwald, a mutual fund consultant based in
Philadelphia. When you go to cocktail parties these days, he says,
everyone is buzzing about buying stocks, especially Internet
stocks. ``Someone says, `Joe made money in stocks. How come we
didn't?' So they go out and buy stocks too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greenwald is not convinced that the shift to stock-buying
represents a real threat to mutual funds. Once the Internet bubble
bursts, and people start to lose money, he predicts, investors will
once again appreciate the safety and security of mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Harvey, president of Dalbar, a local consulting firm,
makes the same point. ``These days people feel they can do no
wrong,'' says Harvey. ``Once they feel the pinch of losses, they
may feel differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund executives generally pooh-poohed the stock-buying
boom when they gathered last week in Washington for their annual
convention. They talked about the false sense of security investors
have developed and warned people against being seduced by the lure
of quick riches. Their message seemed to be: When you come to your
senses, you will realize we are the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   But what if that doesn't happen? What if some percentage of
investors find they like the do-it-yourself model better?
</P>
<P>
   The Internet in general is an empowering medium. It eliminates
the need for middlemen and puts the consumer in the driver's seat.
In the financial world, the Internet has leveled the playing field,
giving investors access to tools and information that once were the
exclusive domain of the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gazala, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge,
doesn't expect to see mass defections from mutual funds. For a
great many people, they are a perfect fit. But he predicts that a
certain segment of investors, having ventured off on their own, may
``be very hard to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   It is important to remember now that mutual funds weren't always
the investment vehicle of choice. Until 20 years ago, the vast
majority of people kept their money in the bank. They moved into
money-market funds in the late 1970s, bond funds in the 1980s, and
stock funds in the 1990s. Once they left the banks, they too didn't
go back.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund companies cannot afford to be complacent. Times
change, technology changes, consumer preferences change. People who
once thought the bus was the only way to travel can find new ways
to get from here to there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
