<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-CLUB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS PICK TO WRONG TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ David Brower is revered by many in the
environmental movement, but I am glad he didn't win the Sierra Club
presidency in last weekend's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Had he won, he told reporters, he would have considered
resurrecting immigration as an environmental issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, one of the nation's best known environmental
groups, was obliged by petition to hold a divisive vote of the
membership last year on whether to support increased restrictions
on immigration to the United States. The proposition didn't get
enough votes to change the neutral position of the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Brower and other dissidents favor another
confrontation on the issue. As I noted at the time of the first
Sierra Club vote, targeting immigration as a way to improve our
environment was off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there has been a slight lessening of anti-immigrant
fever in California since its height five years ago when then-Gov.
Pete Wilson, desperate for re-election, exploited poor immigrants
to win another term in office.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year California voters approved Proposition 187,
which sought to take away public services from undocumented
immigrants, including schooling for their children.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. and California economies have soared, immigrant
bashing has receded somewhat. But there are exceptions, such as the
focus on Chinese-American scientists who work in U.S. weapons labs
because of reports that Chinese spies have been stealing secrets of
American weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Brower's decision to drop his challenge of Chuck McGrady
for the Sierra Club presidency, it is worth reviewing why it's
wrongheaded to blame immigration for degrading the U.S.
environment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief culprits in environmental damage is our
unbelievable level of consumption of natural resources. By ``our,''
I mean Americans, not foreigners coming here to better their lives
(and, in many cases, contributing to the betterment of the United
States). I still find it remarkable that Americans _ only about 4
percent of the world's population _ consume about 40 percent of the
world's fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans do not realize just how wealthy _ and
materialistic _ we are. We take our exalted economic status for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know we still have an aching poverty problem in this
country, but it is nothing compared with the poverty in developing
countries. The wealth gap is a reason why people from other nations
want to come to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Without conscience, many of us lust after bigger and more
environmentally damaging vehicles like the status symbol of the
1990s, the sport utility vehicle. Few owners take these monstrous
light trucks into the backwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Even much higher gasoline prices have not deterred many of us
from seeking out the modern gas guzzler. Hey, what's a few extra
bucks for the privilege of driving a privatized tank?
</P>
<P>
   The never-ending rise in our standard of living is also driving
our desire for bigger homes that consume more water, electricity
and natural gas. A 2,000-square-foot home is now considered a
closet by many affluent Americans, who think nothing of buying
abodes with 3,000 or more square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Given the insatiable consumption patterns of the U.S.
population, I would suggest the Sierra Club focus on doing what it
can to reduce our materialism and not waste its time picking on
immigration as an environmental scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
