<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE THAT GROWS ON TREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does your breath catch when you come upon a tree gloriously
crowned with sunlit blossoms? Does your heart stop at the sight of
glowing green weeping willow buds? Does your head whirl at maple
tree flowers?
</P>
<P>
   Mine does. I've been having a love affair with trees ever since
my husband and I went to Newport, R.I., for a wedding last summer.
</P>
<P>
   We'd been invited to visit the bride's parents before the
ceremony, but our bed and breakfast was at one end of town and
their inn was at the other, several miles away. Around 11 on
Saturday morning, Jack and I set off on foot to visit Pat and Fran,
his college roommate.
</P>
<P>
   It was perfect wedding weather _ brilliant blue sky, a sea
sequined with glints of sunshine _ but it was very hot, especially
since I wasn't wearing a hat or sunglasses. With the sun directly
overhead, buildings didn't offer much shade, so Jack and I took to
pausing under trees.
</P>
<P>
   It was remarkably cool under their leaves. We'd sweat our way
through air hot as a sauna, then sigh with pleasure as we entered a
magical shaded realm where the air was cool and the brilliance of
the day no longer hurt our eyes. The air smelled sweeter. The
leaves of certain large trees I shamefully cannot identify formed a
whispering canopy above us. I felt intensely grateful. I began to
feel as if trees had been offering human beings shelter in their
shade all my life, but that for some reason I had never before
noticed their generosity of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   It's embarrassing, but I confess that I walked over to the
twisted, yet graceful, trunk of one lovely tree, put my arms around
it and laid my cheek against its smooth gray surface. For a brief
moment I had the distinct feeling that the tree was aware of my
presence, that within my arms something was responding to my rush
of gratitude with pleasure. If I had been alone and without a
destination, I swear I would have settled down among its roots and
read a book, just to keep it company.
</P>
<P>
   Jack takes these passions of mine in stride, but I never told
anyone lse until last night, when, in a discussion of spirituality
at our church, a woman named Sandra mentioned in passing that
during a lunchtime walk she had kissed every magnolia tree she
passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What possessed you?'' I said to her after class. ``I thought I
was the only one carrying on a love affair with trees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' she replied. ``Trees were one of the first
objects of worship in human history. Don't you know about the
druids?''
</P>
<P>
   I do now.
</P>
<P>
   Five thousand years ago, the druids practiced an earth-based
religion rooted in a profound attunement to nature. The druids
revered the yew, which can live for 3,000 years, as the sacred tree
of death and rebirth. Its longevity, combined with its being an
evergreen, gave the yew power as the tree of eternal life. The
druids also revered beech trees, symbolizing tradition, learning,
and wisdom, in part because they produce a plentiful harvest of
nourishing beech nuts. Each of these trees was traditionally
planted at each side of the gate to stone circles still standing at
ancient druidic sites in Britain. Nearby, in North Salem, N.H., we
have our own site called ``America's Stonehenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience comes when we allow ourselves to follow the voice
of the yew, to die and be reborn. Knowledge comes when we allow
ourselves to be fed by the beech _ the accumulated wisdom of the
past,'' writes Philip Carr-Gomm in his book, ``The Druid Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Camping one night upon an artificial hill built by the druids
for reasons we can only surmise, Carr-Gomm writes, ``I must sleep
here. Here on these sacred mounds we are at a place lifted up _
close to the sky, close to earth. The two meet and mingle, make
love, move together. And if we are quiet we can hear the earth
breathe and sigh, and we feel the pulse deep within.'' Ah, here's a
man after my own heart.
</P>
<P>
   When something changes inside, the external world also shifts.
That probably is why this spring for the first time I seem to be
stumbling upon so many instances of people in similar communion
with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what retired rabbi Everett Gendler says of the objects of
his passionate encounters: ``There have been a few of these, not in
their vastness, but in their intimacy, which have seemed to pulsate
with subtle, subdued life. I felt an awareness beyond my
comprehension, insisting, `Hey, that life force is right here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   You think it's far-fetched for me to believe that trees have
souls?
</P>
<P>
   Gendler's talking about rocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
