<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-MAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MAY NEARLY SPENT, SO MUCH TO DO REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's so much to do and so little time. Nature has its
timetable which cannot be ignored. If you love gardening and have
all sorts of wonderful ideas, spring can sometimes seem
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   But don't despair; just tackle a little at a time and eventually
enough gets done, for a garden is a never-finished
work-in-progress. No matter what lovely flowers my eyes may alight
upon, I find a chore awaiting beneath the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's even a nice surprise, like volunteer perennial
plants that can be moved to expand and grow. Prices being what they
are, perennials that renew themselves are a treasure indeed, as
long as they don't spread too vigorously. (Incidentally, if your
local garden club has a plant sale, you can often find varieties
with old-fashioned reseeding genes from members' gardens.)
</P>
<P>
   I was amused that Gertrude Jekyll, the Victorian doyenne of
perennials, always carried her garden shears to nip an errant shoot
or spent flower head (while her gardener did the digging and
planting). I, too, always carry my shears as well as a big
container for errant weeds that need pulling (by me).
</P>
<P>
   Tempting photographs in gardening magazines have fed the craving
for gorgeous, lavish flower displays. Horticultural fatigue can
easily set in when our eyes are bigger than our time, so here are
some time-saving tips. Don't expect to do them all, just what you
can, and enjoy gardening as a pastime, not a contest.
</P>
<P>
   --Mulch. It looks neater, keeps the weeds down and the soil
moist. About 2 inches deep is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   --Replace difficult perennials with types that are easier to
care for.
</P>
<P>
   For spring, consider peonies, iberis, coral bells, columbine.
</P>
<P>
   For summer, try perennial phlox, day lilies, coneflower,
rudbeckia, and coreopsis.
</P>
<P>
   For fall, use Sedum spectabilis and buy nursery-forced
chrysanthemums each year.
</P>
<P>
   --Consolidate flower beds so they are fuller and more effective.
Lots of skinny borders take more care and don't make such a
colorful spash. I have my main flower bed just outside the window
where I eat my breakfast so that I can see and enjoy it each day.
</P>
<P>
   --Combine plants by maintenance requirements, especially
watering.
</P>
<P>
   --To make beds look neat, edge the beds with a deep, crisp cut.
It does visual wonders.
</P>
<P>
   --Before you mulch, put down some granular or organic
fertilizer, and lime as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Before the month ends, test some of the new three-month slow
release pelletized fertilizer on part of the garden. (June will be
too late.) Don't use the six-month or eight-month fertilizers
because they will cause soft growth too late in the season, and
then trees, shrubs and perennial plants would not harden off before
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Pelletized fertilizer is fine anytime for pots of annuals
though.
</P>
<P>
   --Do away with poor grass, especially under trees. Replace it
with ground cover or just plain mulch, architecturally designed in
a perfect circle or an interesting shape. If you must have grass,
seed with shade-tolerant fescue the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   --Try a string trimmer although it's another added neatness
chore. Caution: Don't hit tree trunks or shrubs with the nylon
string because it gouges the bark. Messy looking ground covers
(myrtle, ivy, pachysandra, euonymus, ajuga, lamium) can be
string-trimmed to 2 inches, which encourages neater, new growth.
</P>
<P>
   --Protect transplants from sun and wind for a few days with
upside down flower pots, milk containers with tops and bottoms cut
out, newspaper hats secured with rocks, or staked paper bags.
</P>
<P>
   --Set up permanent hoses with sprinkler heads in just the right
place, then turn on the water when it's needed. You can even hide
the hoses under mulch or in shrub beds. It's worth the investment
in all-season time-saving. There are double and even triple hose
adapters, with shutoffs, that can be screwed onto a water spigot so
that more than one hose can be attached. Also available are
shape-adjustable sprinkler heads.
</P>
<P>
   --Hire a company to mow or fertilize the lawn, or both. Just
make sure to inquire about what is being put on the lawn, and that
it is mowed at least 2 inches high. If you don't fertilize too much
and you aren't a green-carpet perfection person, mowing every two
weeks during July and August is plenty. By mid-September, though,
the lawn usually needs weekly mowing again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
