<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-SHEETS-ART-BOS &LR;      05-27 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SHEETS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LUXURIOUS BEDDING, COUNT THE THREADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thread count. Thread count. Thread count.
</P>
<P>
   Once the concern of European royalty, the obsession with thread
count _ or the number of threads in a square inch of fabric, which
indicates how tightly they are woven _ filtered down a few years
ago to the very, very rich. Now, it has entered the realm of the
masses _ or at least of those middle-class Americans who have a
little extra spending money and want kingly comfort.
</P>
<P>
   High thread count equals comfort.
</P>
<P>
   And comfort is what people want when they are buying sheets.
After all, we spend one-third of our lives in
</P>
<P>
   bed, so why not spend it in beautiful, luxurious, soft bed
clothing? Bed linens are our second skin _ or third, if you count
pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   Americans spend more than $2 billion a year on sheets. Of that
total, 48 percent is on sheets with a 180 thread count and 38
percent with a 200 to 250 thread count, according to the trade
publication Home Furnishing News.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a continuing interest in accelerated thread counts,''
says Kim Lanciloti, Filene's home fashion director. ``The thread
count game has translated into the department store,'' rather than
remaining the exclusive province of specialty shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want anything under a 200 thread count these
days,'' Lanciloti says. ``Cotton is also important. A couple of
years ago, people were still buying blends'' of cotton and
polyester. ``But today they want 100 percent cotton. So cotton plus
a higher thread count gives consumers the desired softness.''
</P>
<P>
   And it can be a good deal, too. This is one instance, Lanciloti
says, where product improvement does not mean soaring prices.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Bruno, director of public relations at Bloomingdale's, sees
the same shift in the market. When it comes to comfort, Bruno says,
``Customers know what they want when buying sheets. High quality is
a must, and anything less than a 200 thread count is undesirable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charisma by Fieldcrest begins at 310, while (Calvin) Klein and
(Ralph) Lauren start at 200,'' says Bruno. ``But once customers
have slept on Charisma sheets, it's difficult to buy anything under
a 300 thread count.''
</P>
<P>
   A Charisma flat sheet in queen size with a 310 thread count
costs around $112.
</P>
<P>
   While the older customer buys a traditional brand such as
Charisma or Ralph Lauren's blues and beiges, younger folks lean
toward the trendier Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   A flat queen sheet in Lauren's Brooke line with a 200 thread
count costs around $40. A 280 thread count in Egyptian sateen in
Lauren's Kathleen &AMP; Emily line is around $60 at Filene's.
</P>
<P>
   For the really hip and young, there's Tommy Hilfiger. And for
teenage girls, Laura Ashley remains popular with her traditional
floral prints in lavender, sage, and gray. Both designers use 100
percent cotton, and their prices are in the $50 to $60 range.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Luxury detailing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are not only gravitating toward more luxury fabrics,
but they also want luxury detailing,'' says Filene's Lanciloti, who
points to Croscill as another popular line. ``They are looking for
hemstitching, embroidery, and lace. Some of our solid sheets have
grosgrain ribbon detailing that customers seem to like.''
</P>
<P>
   And the most popular colors? Deep purple and lilac, blues and
beiges. The hottest ``in'' color, retailers say, is yellow.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a bit more money to spend on luxuries, there are
several specialty linen shops with top-of-the-line offerings in
bedding.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular higher-end sheet lines is Palais Royal,
made by a French company that has been selling its line of 100
percent Egyptian cotton prints, embroidered cottons, and jacquards
in the United States for the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Linens on the Hill in Boston carries this line exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palais Royal is high-end but affordable,'' says owner Lynne
Wolverton. ``They make such beautiful designs that fit my taste.
And they have expanded their embroideries in the last few years.''
Queen sets range from $300 to $600, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Palais Royal is also a top seller at Bonsoir in Wellesley and
Lexington, Mass. Other popular lines, according to owner Jennifer
Berg, include Nancy Koltes, an Italian manufacturer of luxurious
bedding whose Eleanor's Ribbon, with a thread count of 320, runs
$220 for a queen flat sheet; and Sferra, another Italian maker,
whose Celeste line, with a 406 thread count, is very popular (a
queen set is $370). Other lines of note are Malabar Grove, Bonjour
of Switzerland, Lisa Galimberti, and Angel Simick. All their linens
are made from Egyptian cotton, reportedly the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street in Wellesley is Periwinkles, a decorating
store for children that started out with hand-painted furniture for
infants, young children, and teenagers and has moved into bedding
and custom bedding. Again, Palais Royal is a big seller here too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   European designs
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another small store, the Linen Closet in Boston, carries such
basic lines as Wamsutta, Springmaid, Esprit, and Hillcrest but also
has some unusual linens by less universally known European
designers.
</P>
<P>
   Souleiado of France, for example, makes a 100 percent percale
cotton with a 220 thread count called Maussane Fleurs. A queen flat
sheet costs $64.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plaid and floral print combination makes it appealing to
both males and females,'' says store owner and buyer Ilana Jerome.
``It's not too fussy. The thread count is 220, but the sheets are
very soft because the thread is spun very tightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another up-and-coming designer, says Jerome, is Anki Spets of
Sweden. The store carries only her duvet and shams, in a softly
colored and classic line called Blocks, but hopes to have sheets in
the pattern in the near future. They do carry sheets in her Tape
line, with sea-green and silvery gray stripes. A queen flat sheet
costs $69.99.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular lines for the under-30 crowd is Pen and
Ink by Esprit. The colors are sage and stark white, in a floral and
plaid combination, so ``guys and girls can share the same bed,
because it's both feminine and masculine and has a nice
flat-finished edging.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratesi linens, a 90-year-old Italian firm known for providing
linens to monarchs, wealthy businessmen, sheiks, and popes, has a
Boston shop. Pratesi, according to store manager Connie Chinaglia,
is the highest-quality linen line sold in the United States (their
only competitor being France's Porthault). The thread count of
Pratesi linens tops out at 880. The price for a set of flat and
fitted sheets with two pillow shams begins at $1,080.
</P>
<P>
   In a published interview, the head of Pratesi is quoted as
saying: ``Our sheets are sun-dried in Italy and, therefore,
perfumed in sunshine.'' Athos Pratesi goes on to describe his
flower prints as ``bringing the charm of a medieval garden to your
home. Nothing is more regenerating for a person than slipping
between fresh sheets so sweet and soft to the touch. Silk is the
best because it maintains the temperature of the body. It's like
having another skin. I become a poet when I think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such poetry and perfume were not always so costly. Sun-dried
sheets only cost the price of a clothesline, clothespins, and a
housewife's time during my childhood. But, alas, my children have
never known the delicious smell and soothing comfort of sheets that
had hung on a clothesline all day _ they crawled into bed with
sheets that had spent 40 minutes in the basement dryer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CATALOGS THAT OFFER SHEETS &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOP OF THE LINE: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chambers _ Thread counts from 230 ($285 for queen sheet set,
including two pillowcases) to 560 thread count ($165 for flat queen
sheet); 800-334-1254.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer Linen _ 220 to 480 ($750 for queen set, including two
pillow shams); 800-554-6367.
</P>
<P>
   Garnet Hill _ 200 (most of their sheets are this thread count)
to 275 (Fieldcrest Royal Velvet queen flat is $50); 800-622-6216.
</P>
<P>
   The Company Store _ 200 to 340 (queen fitted is $69);
800-285-3696.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OTHER CATALOGS: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coldwater Creek: Bed &AMP; Bath; 800-968-0984.
</P>
<P>
   Touch of Class; 800-457-7456.
</P>
<P>
   linensource; 800-431-2620.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Bean: L.L. Home, Bed and Bath; 800-221-4221.
</P>
<P>
   You can also check the Internet for good buys.
</P>
</TEXT>
