<SLUG> BC-SALADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADD FUN AND FLAVOR TO SALADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are only two times a year when I crave salads: in the
middle of winter, when I'm on the verge of catching a cold, and the
beginning of summer when all produce seems fresh and new.
</P>
<P>
   Those are times when I eat salads almost constantly. To keep
this grazing from becoming boring, I've learned to add a few things
to your basic lettuce, tomatoes and cucumber:
</P>
<P>
   _ Meats and fish turn a simple salad into an entree. Try topping
green salads with leftover steak, chicken or tuna.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheese. If you put steak on that salad, add a little blue
cheese. Have just a green salad? Top it with a bit of parmesan or
feta. A small amount of a highly flavored cheese can go a long way
toward making the bland better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nuts and seeds. Whether it's sesame seeds for an Asian touch
or sunflower seeds topping fruit and cottage cheese, seeds add
texture and flavor. Nuts do, too. Have you ever had a Waldorf
without walnuts?
</P>
<P>
   _ Dried fruit. Raisins, craisins and bits of dried apricot will
add a ``chewy'' component.
</P>
<P>
   _ Herbs. Finely chopped fresh herbs can add complexity to your
salad. Add mint to a light fruit salad, parsley to a green salad or
basil to a salad with tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt and pepper. Sometimes it's the simplest things that are
the most effective. A bit of salt and a few grinds of fresh pepper
can make even iceberg lettuce seem flavorful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
