<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JELLIES-HNS &LR;      05-27 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JELLIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO JAM THAN BREAKFAST TOAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jellies, preserves and marmalades are more than bread spreads.
Try a few of these ideas to get the most out of a jar of jam:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use any flavor as a topping, spooned over ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   _ Swirl into plain yogurt for a low-calorie snack.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place a dab in the middle of batter before baking muffins or
cupcakes for a surprise inside.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add orange marmalade and rehydrated bits of dried fruit to
wild rice for an interesting side dish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spread on grilled chicken just before serving to add a
slightly sweet glaze.
</P>
<P>
   _ For a quick appetizer, spoon dabs of jelly over cream cheese
and serve with crackers or toasts. (Burgundy wine jelly is
particularly good for this.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Spread a layer of apricot jam between layers of white cakes.
Frost with fluffy white icing and top cake with flaked coconut.
Other good combinations are strawberry jam with chocolate cake and
whipped cream for frosting, and lemon cake with raspberry jam and
buttercream frosting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stir jam to thin. (Use apricot if making yellow cake, or
raspberry if making chocolate cake.) Brush on cooled cake layers to
prevent crumbs from mixing into frosting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Combine a jar of peach jam with one envelope onion soup mix.
Use mixture to marinate chicken breasts before grilling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melt currant jelly over warm heat and use to glaze the tops of
strawberry or blueberry tarts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Combine 1 cup apricot preserves and 2 tablespoons dark rum or
cognac to glaze the tops of apple or pear tarts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Combine 1/2 cup seedless raspberry jam, 1/2 cup mayonnaise and
4 tablespoons Dijon mustard in a large bowl. Add 2 cups diced,
cooked chicken breast, 1/2 cup chopped walnuts, 1 cup chopped
celery, 2 cups chopped apples, salt and pepper. Toss to coat well
with mayonnaise-jam mixture. Garnish with fresh raspberries. (From
Smuckers)
</P>
<P>
   _ Combine 1 cup apricot preserves, 2 tablespoons vinegar, 1
teaspoon chili powder and 1 clove minced garlic. Serve as a dipping
sauce with cooked chicken wings or chicken tenders. (From Smuckers)
</P>
<P>
   _ To make sweet and sour sauce, melt 1/2 cup currant jelly, 1/4
cup cider vinegar, 3 tablespoons soy sauce and 1 tablespoon
cornstarch in a small saucepan over medium heat. Cook 3 minutes
until mixture is clear.
</P>
<P>
   JAMMY BISCUITS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 8 servings)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter plus more for the pan
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peach jam
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup minced crystallized ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 425 degrees. Grease an 8-inch square pan liberally
with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1/2 cup butter in a small saucepan. Pour 1/4 cup butter out
of pan and reserve. Add the jam and ginger to pan and stir, over
very low heat, until mixed. Pour into bottom of greased pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix the flour, baking powder and salt. Make a
well in the center of the dry ingredients and pour in the remaining
melted butter and milk. Use a wooden spoon to quickly mix until the
dough holds together in a rough ball.
</P>
<P>
   Turn out dough onto a floured surface and roll into a
12-by-8-inch rectangle. Combine the brown sugar and pecans and
sprinkle over the dough. Roll, starting with short side, into a
log. Cut into 8 biscuits. Place biscuits into pan snugly.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 15 minutes, until the tops of the biscuits are golden.
Allow to cool for 3 minutes then invert onto a serving plate. Serve
warm.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Butter Beans to Blackberries: Recipes From the Southern
Garden,'' by Ronnie Lundy, North Point Press, 1999.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
