<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIAN-BABY _ ATLANTA _ Azra Beso, the Bosnian baby who nearly
died because strife in her country prevented her from getting a
common heart operation, is on the mend. She got her operation this
week at Scottish Rite, and Thursday she's moving from ICU to a
private room. She's already acting more like a normal infant.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MARS _ WASHINGTON _ Erosion from ancient rivers long gone dry,
mountains that would dwarf Mt. Everest and possibly the largest
impact crater in the Solar System: NASA's Mars Global Surveyor has
produced a three-dimensional map of the surface of Mars. Members of
the Global Surveyor science team are to talk at a Thursday
afternoon press briefing about what they have found. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   READING _ WASHINGTON _ Are American children reading better? A
House subcommittee Thursday will examine witnesses about what the
results released earlier this year from the National Assessment of
Educational Progress really mean. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE _ WASHINGTON _ Sens. Bob Graham and Kay Bailey
Hutchison visit a company-run daycare center to unveil a bill that
would help employers provide on-site child care for their
employees. (Schultz, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ Everyone from Wayne LaPierre of the NRA to parents of the
Columbine shootings appear before the House Judiciary committee to
discuss gun control. (Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE _ Space Shuttle Discovery blasted off for the new
international space station Thursday, ending a six-month launch
drought for NASA. (Desmon, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMIC-JOBMARKET _ Many of this spring's college graduates are
leaving academia pondering multiple job offers, a bounty of today's
robust economy. But Marty Meersman, who wants to teach sculpture to
eager undergraduates, always knew that wouldn't be his case.
Students like Meersman, who plan to return to academia as
tenure-track professors, are finding job opportunities a tough
find. That's one reason why UT has created the Professional
Development Program, UT administrators said: to help those students
acquire skills for jobs not normally associated with the Ivory
Tower. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
