<HEADER>
A3388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BLUE-HOUR-HNS &LR;      05-27 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLUE-HOUR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLUE HOUR' IS MYSTERY WRITING AT ITS BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's usually the kiss of death to say of a new book, ``I
challenge anyone to sit down with this novel and get up without
having finished it.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what Elizabeth George, author of ``Deception
on His Mind,'' says about T. Jefferson Parker's new mystery, ``The
Blue Hour'' (Hyperion. $23.95. 359 pages).
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, there isn't a book that's been written by anyone,
anywhere, that you can't put down _ most of them for long periods
of time. If you finish a book in one sitting it usually says more
about the time you have on your hands than it does about the
quality of the writing.
</P>
<P>
   But give Parker his due. ``The Blue Hour'' comes real close to
being a one-sitting page-turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Hour'' centers on a retired detective, dying of
cancer, teamed with a brash, ambitious homicide deputy to find a
vicious killer of women. It starts with a portrait of 67-year-old
Tim Hess, brought out of the routine of watching TV and undergoing
chemotherapy to investigate a murder _ a portrait that has you
plugging for Hess from the first paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to live to be 75, he tells himself _ is that too much
to ask? He's surprised at what he remembers, what he forgets, and
at all times he has the reader's sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, author of ``Where Serpents Lie'' and ``Little Saigon,''
isn't as kind to Merci Rayborn, the daughter of an Orange County,
Calif., sheriff's detective who draws Hess as her partner in a
search for a deranged killer. Initially tough, Rayborn becomes more
likable as the book picks up speed from page to page.
</P>
<P>
   Parker has you hooked by the second chapter, as Hess drives out
to the crime scene. After his study of some oak trees and the dirt
underneath them, leading to the grotesque image of victims being
gutted like deer, it becomes harder and harder to put down the
book.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are the key. In addition to sharp images of Hess
and Rayborn, Parker draws the murdered women in fine detail _ a
letter written by the first victim as she sits alone in her Newport
Beach home is especially strong. Parker's portrayal of the killer
is just as impressive, though somewhat cliched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Hour'' has some flaws, including its assumption that
a news station would devote 24 hours a day filming a building in
which a sex offender lives. Parker also insists on vivid, gruesome
violence committed by an increasingly insane murderer, as if he
feels a need to trump contemporary suspense writers such as James
Ellroy.
</P>
<P>
   Parker handles the chemotherapy scenes with a minimum of
mawkishness: ``They said he'd lose his appetite during the sessions
and he did. They also said his hair would probably fall out and it
hadn't. Hess felt a secret pride in this. The sessions were three
days in a row, one session per month, for four months if you could
take it. If it killed off too many blood cells you had to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable May-November romance is handled as well as can be
expected, and Parker's depiction of Hess sitting on a bench at the
end, talking to a stranger about the three lives he saved in his
career, is honestly moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Hour'' is Parker's best work, impressive enough to
read in one sitting. Almost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RAND-REVIEW-SFCHRO     05-27 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RAND-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRREN CAPTURES THE PASSIONS OF AYN RAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three famous writers, two cable movies, one bull's-eye.
</P>
<P>
   The direct hit is scored by Helen Mirren as the steely novelist
and philosopher Ayn Rand in ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' (showing
Sunday on the Showtime pay cable channel).
</P>
<P>
   Mirren's is one of four astonishing performances in the year's
best made-for-TV movie. Peter Fonda plays Rand's self-sacrificing
husband, Frank O'Connor. Eric Stoltz is Nathaniel Brandon, Rand's
intellectual heir and lover. Julie Delpy is Barbara Brandon,
Nathaniel's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The other movie? It's ``Dash and Lilly'' (Monday on A&AMP;E), a sour
effort directed by actress Kathy Bates and starring Sam Shepard and
Judy Davis as Dashiell Hammett and Lillian Hellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dash and Lilly'' is Hammett and Hellman from A to M _
alcoholism to McCarthyism, as it forlornly chronicles the 30-year
love affair between the famous crime novelist and the celebrated
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm not mistaken, the movie itself is 30 years long.
</P>
<P>
   Best to stick with ``The Passion of Ayn Rand,'' in which Mirren
plays a complex woman who's capable of losing her temper, but never
an argument. Not even when she avers that it's logical to have sex,
openly and on a regular schedule, with her closest friend's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Rand, who died in 1982, was the author of ``The Fountainhead''
and ``Atlas Shrugged,'' and the founder of Objectivism, a
philosophy that binds egotism, logic and capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a book by Barbara Brandon, the movie lifts the curtain
that surrounds Rand, peeking at her inner circle and private life.
</P>
<P>
   The Brandons were college students who met Rand in 1951 and
built their own lives and marriage on an altar of admiration for
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' is an unabashedly adult movie with
plenty of sexual sizzle. Mirren provides much of the pleasure as an
imperious woman whose brilliance only partially conceals her
contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Her hair dyed dark and her voice drenched in the accent of
Rand's native Russia, Mirren finds in Rand an intimidator who can
be as tender as she is brusque _ sometimes. She's a romantic,
perhaps as only a Russian or a French woman could be; yet she
seemingly rules her tightly controlled roost with a constant
barrage of dispassionate reason.
</P>
<P>
   Rand is so strong that everyone else unavoidably becomes a
tragic figure. Stoltz is scorchingly corrupt as Nathaniel Brandon,
cast out after he cheats on Rand as well as his own wife.
</P>
<P>
   Delpy (``Before Sunrise''), successfully taming her French
accent, wins sympathy as a scorned woman who breaks down under the
tug-of-war between her intellectual and emotional lives. Fonda is
magnificent _ a quiet, long-suffering hero who knows he's too old
and too unemployable to take a stand against his famous wife.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Christopher Menaul (``Fatherland''), ``The Passion
of Ayn Rand'' benefits from a big-screen visual texture and a jazzy
score, by Jeff Beal, that fits the movie snugly.
</P>
<P>
   The movie wasn't necessarily made for small-screen release.
Showtime is approving deals that allow filmmakers to shop first for
a theatrical distributor. ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' apparently
didn't latch on with a distributor, and so it reverts to Showtime
for its premiere.
</P>
<P>
   When you see some of the brain-dead special-effects
extravaganzas that are getting plastered across theater screens,
you've got to shake your head slowly. Ah, well, it's television's
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dash and Lilly,'' sad to say, would fizzle on any screen.
</P>
<P>
   Give credit to Bates for trying to pin down substantive
characters in her directorial debut, but her film is an enervated
and sometimes overacted (by Davis) piece of business that never
rises above mundane. Jerry Ludwig's script, like so much about the
movie, is sort of OK but lacking in any exciting rocketry.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of it is that Hammett, creator of ``The Maltese
Falcon'' and ``The Thin Man,'' and the aspiring writer Hellman meet
in 1930 and then drink, smoke and torture each other for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's Bates' job to make us feel there's an overriding reason to
care about their famous love affair, as opposed to their literary
careers. She doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   And it's Davis' and Shepard's hope, presumably, to convey the
chemistry between the two writers. They don't. Shepard's drawling,
slow-moving style and Davis' red-eyed intensity don't seem a match
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Davis and Shepard, ``Dash and Lilly'' features David
Paymer as Hellman's first husband, Arthur Kober, and Bebe Neuwirth
as Dorothy Parker.
</P>
<P>
   None of the movie takes place in Hammett's creative home turf,
San Francisco, and Hammett's family in San Francisco is barely
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to promote the A&AMP;E movie with an event at John's Grill, a
repository of Hammett lore in downtown San Francisco, were called
off when it was learned that Hammett's daughter, Josephine,
disapproves of the film.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
