<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah aflutter with gentry-filled `Delirium'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Savannah gets ready to celebrate the long awaited paperback
publication of ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' on July
6, another book about old families and buried secrets is creating a
buzz in the coastal city. ``Delirium of the Brave'' (Frederic C.
Beil, $24.95), a debut novel by Savannah podiatrist William C.
Harris Jr., has become a local best seller and set the city's
gentry speculating about some of the thinly disguised families in
the book.
</P>
<P>
   While John Berendt's Gothic tome focused on a contemporary crime
and a bevy of colorful characters, Harris' novel covers the period
from the end of the Civil War to World War II. The story begins
when a Confederate officer and his slave companion bury a chest of
family valuables on Raccoon Island. Both are killed before they can
reveal the hiding place. Harris then follows the fortunes of old
Savannah families through the post-Civil War years and the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Savannah is predicting ``Delirium'' will be as big as
``Midnight,'' but some Hollywood producers have shown an interest.
The publisher has sold out of four printings and won't have any
more books until June 21.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRUE GRIT: If Tom Franklin's stories seem gritty, maybe it's
because he worked in a grit plant before he became a writer. Not
the edible kind of grits, but grit used in sandblasting.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in a style that echoes the raw energy of Cormac
McCarthy, the Alabama native is making waves in the publishing
world. The title story in his debut collection, ``Poachers''
(Morrow, $22), won the Edgar Award for best short story and was
selected for inclusion in ``New Stories From the South 1999,''
``Best American Mystery Stories 1999'' and ``Best Mystery Stories
of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the stories in ``Poachers'' reflect a dark side of
the South populated with working-class types living close to the
edge. It is a world Franklin knows intimately. Born in Dickinson,
Ala., he barely survived a bad marriage and divorce and worked his
way through college with jobs in a hospital morgue and a chemical
plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until I went to graduate school that I began to
realize how strange my childhood was,'' Franklin says. ``Not just
living in the woods, but being raised in a religious environment
that was very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unusual'' may not be the right word. Franklin's parents formed
their own rural church in a tin building where the congregation
spoke in tongues, burned books and practiced faith healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tried religion and I'd tried hunting,'' Franklin says.
``Neither seemed to come naturally, so I went to writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin will sign copies of his book at 7 tonight at Chapter 11
bookstore at Ansley Mall, 1544 Piedmont Ave. N.E. 404-872-7986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WRITERS CONFERENCE: Authors from around the state will gather
Saturday for the Georgia Writers 1999 Spring Festival. Among those
scheduled for book signings and workshops are U.S. Rep. John Lewis
(``Walking With the Wind''), novelist Phyllis Perry (``Stigmata'')
and poets Barbara Ras and Memye Curtis Tucker. 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
Smyrna Community Center, 2020 Village Green Circle. 770-943-5699.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
