<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION30-CO     05-27 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NONFICTION30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New nonfiction of note
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Miracle of Castel di Sangro
</P>
<P>
   by Joe McGinniss
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $25).
</P>
<P>
   When we think of McGinniss, we usually think of the determined
reporter who worked his way into the mind of a convicted killer in
``Fatal Vision'' (1983) and dissected the Kennedys in ``The Last
Brother: The Rise and Fall of Teddy Kennedy'' (1993). For his
latest book, though, this obsessed soccer fan moves to a small town
in Italy and devotes nearly a year to following the fortunes of the
village team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro'' is a passionate _ and funny
_ portrait of a town gone berserk over a ragtag collection of
soccer players. Despite coming from a poor region, the team has
managed to move up to Serie B, the second-highest professional
league in Italy. For a town of 5,000 to field such a team is truly
a miracle. The question is, can they keep the dream alive against
stiff competition from Genoa, Venice and Padua?
</P>
<P>
   After moving into a seedy hotel that shuts down completely on
Wednesdays and never has heat until October, McGinniss chronicles
every heart-stopping victory and every heartbreaking loss. He makes
friends with the colorful players (one is designated the official
cheese smeller before every meal) even though he speaks very little
Italian. He has less success with the team's owner, Signor Rezza, a
Godfather figure who travels with bodyguards and lives in a remote
mountaintop estate. Rezza is a man used to getting what he wants,
even if it means bulldozing a mountain to improve his view, or
refusing to pay a star player who would guarantee a championship.
</P>
<P>
   The author, as usual, injects more of himself into the story
than is necessary. But his celebrity-size ego is overshadowed by
the personalities of the players and the dream that is ultimately
shattered by corruption. Even readers who have never seen a soccer
match will find McGinniss' story compelling.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Innocent Year: America in 1964,
</P>
<P>
   the Beginning of the Sixties by Jon Margolis
</P>
<P>
   (William Morrow, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Someone once said if you can remember the '60s, then you
probably weren't there. Most of us who are old enough, though,
certainly remember 1964. As Margolis notes in his excellent
cultural and historical flashback, it was indeed a watershed year:
Lyndon B. Johnson pushed civil rights legislation through Congress
and launched the war on poverty as he escalated the conflict in
Vietnam. Three civil rights workers died in the South's ``Freedom
Summer.'' The Beatles and the Rolling Stones landed in America and
revolutionized rock 'n' roll; Tom Hayden and his friends gathered
on college campuses to formulate their counterculture attack on the
establishment; and women who were content to stay at home while
their husbands worked felt the first stirrings of liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with John F. Kennedy's assassination in November 1963
and ending with LBJ's election the following November, Margolis, a
former reporter for the Chicago Tribune, uses short, insightful
vignettes to masterfully re-create the mood and substance of a
pivotal year. For those of us who were there, it is a wonderful
memory-jogging book. For the younger generation, it is an
entertaining history lesson _ sort of like ``Forrest Gump'' without
the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Working at Play: A History of Vacations in the United States by
Cindy Sondik Aron
</P>
<P>
   (Oxford University Press, $35).
</P>
<P>
   At most job interviews, the issue of how much vacation time the
company allows is second only to salary in terms of importance. It
wasn't always like this, as Aron reveals in her detailed, scholarly
study of leisure time. In the early 19th century, she writes, only
wealthy Americans traveled to resorts for health reasons. Southern
planters headed for the cooler climes of the North Carolina
mountains and Newport, R.I., or the healing waters of Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., or Hot Springs, Va. It was only by the 20th century,
with the rise of the middle class, that companies began to
routinely offer time off to their employees. Americans gladly took
the vacations, but they never truly felt comfortable being away
from work, the University of Virginia professor says. The old
Puritan guilt hung over them like a suffocating mist. Since Aron's
book covers only until 1940, it is not clear (although quite
doubtful) that such anxieties still exist. Although it has a
somewhat academic tone, ``Working at Play'' offers some fascinating
insights into American attitudes toward leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine Greer: Untamed Shrew by Christine Wallace (Faber &AMP;
Faber, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   Unauthorized biographies are written all the time, but rarely
does the subject refer to the author as a ``brain-dead hack.''
Despite Greer's objections, Australian journalist Wallace still
managed to find sources to talk freely about the author of 1970's
``The Female Eunuch.'' Slogging through this solidly researched but
tedious tome, one wonders why Greer fought its publication _ other
than the fact that it would compete with her new book, ``The Whole
Woman'' (Knopf, $25).
</P>
<P>
   There are few revelations in Wallace's book that Greer has not
already disclosed. Wallace details Greer's childhood as the
daughter of an abusive mother and a weak father, her rape in
college and her later denials that her mother beat her. She traces
Greer's academic career (her doctoral thesis at Cambridge dealt
with ``The Taming of the Shrew'') and her foray into the feminist
movement with ``The Female Eunuch,'' a book that called for women
to embrace sex rather than sisterhood. The portrait that emerges is
that of a complicated, untamed woman who is still struggling to
reconcile her views on the war between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan: Her Life by Judith Hennessee
</P>
<P>
   (Random House, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   The best biographies deal with the mind of the subject and the
ideas that made that particular person unique. The worst are
laundry lists of dates, details and accomplishments cobbled
together without form or reason. Hennessee's biography of Friedan
falls somewhere in the middle. Hennessee, a free-lance journalist,
chronicles Friedan's career from her years as a labor union
activist through the writing of ``The Feminine Mystique'' in 1963
and the founding of the National Organization for Women in 1966. In
her groundbreaking book, Friedan dealt with her own frustrations as
an educated woman relegated to the role of housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessee finds that the woman behind the activist is a bundle
of contradictions. She was a feminist who didn't like most women, a
champion of equal rights who hired a black maid to serve
refreshments at a gathering of female organizers and an advocate of
the family whose marriage ended in divorce. Friedan's main
strength, Hennessee says, is her ability to focus on a goal and
ignore any barriers in her path. In an anecdote that is a metaphor
for Friedan's life, the author describes how Friedan would swim
across a channel at Sag Harbor, N.Y., through a narrow inlet that
was well-traveled by boats. ``She always swam straight across and
back,'' Hennessee writes, ``never dipping her head, never watching
for the boats, because Betty thought the boats should look out for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreaming of Columbus: A Boyhood in the Bronx by Michael Pearson
(Syracuse University
</P>
<P>
   Press, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs are all the rage now, primarily due to the success of
books such as Mary Karr's ``The Liars' Club'' and Frank McCourt's
``Angela's Ashes.'' But usually, unless someone has led a
compelling life, nostalgic memories are meaningful only to the
writer, his family and his friends. Michael Pearson, director of
the creative writing program at Old Dominion University, makes up
for the lack of drama in his Catholic-school childhood in the Bronx
with stylish prose and vivid descriptions of people and places.
Growing up with an abusive and mostly absent father, Pearson drew
his strength to survive from his mother. While his father read
about the latest murder on Mott Street, his mother read
Dostoyevsky. ``She believed that stories could change a person's
life, so she paid attention to people and their stories. In a house
and in a culture that seemed aware of only newsprint, she loved
books.''
</P>
<P>
   That love helped propel Pearson, like his hero Columbus, into a
new world. Years later, when Pearson returned to the old
neighborhood with his wife and children, he learns, as Thomas Wolfe
did, that you can't go home again. Or can you? Home, Pearson
decides, ``is a thing that moves and shifts. It is memory and
experience and desire. It is place and no place. It is crowded with
faces and filled with voices, and it is as mute as a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3404 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS30-COX     05-27 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nation writer Christopher Hitchens finds an audience with
Clinton haters
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We arrived under cover of darkness and a light patter of rain.
Christopher Hitchens got out of the Toyota Camry, surveyed the
suburban expanse around him and said, ``Good heavens.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at the hotel bar downtown, he had fortified himself
with a belt of Scotch. If he was wondering whether the dosage had
been sufficient, that would be remedied presently.
</P>
<P>
   The British are intrepid travelers, famous for roughing it in
far places and cabling home riveting dispatches while rifle shots
echo in the distance. But Hitchens had been posted to Dunwoody, a
destination he would later tell his publicist, Nils Hooper, was
``the sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been some curiosity about the place even before
Hitchens arrived. He was to read from his new book, ``No One Left
to Lie to: The Triangulations of William Jefferson Clinton''
(Verso, $19), at Borders Books &AMP; Music in the Perimeter Village
shopping center, and no one in New York or Washington _ where
Hitchens lives and works _ quite knew where or what Dunwoody was.
By some misunderstanding, Verso had thought Hitchens was being
booked for the better-known Borders on Peachtree Road, but, alas, a
book club was gathering there that night and so here was Hitchens _
ex-friend of Clinton loyalist Sidney Blumenthal, unapologetically
leftist writer for The Nation and Vanity Fair, scourge of a
president he calls a crook, a war criminal and a rapist _ in
precincts where the Republican Revolution of 1994 lives on as an
incandescent memory of national honor.
</P>
<P>
   But first some more Scotch.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Hitchens entered the store than a hostess thrust
into his paw a pint of Johnny Walker Black, wrapped in a ribbon and
accompanied by a card signed by fans. The thirsty Hitchens was
grateful. The hostess asked what he preferred with his Scotch, and
Hitchens said soda. It may be the suburbs, but ``you have to like a
place that invites an alcoholic and a chain smoker,'' Hitchens told
me. The rush-hour drive to Dunwoody was beginning to seem worth it.
</P>
<P>
   A quick smoke outside in the rain and Hitchens was ready to get
started, a vase of irises on the table before him and his tumbler
standing by. Fans sat on folding chairs like congregants, about two
dozen. (Later, checking in with his wife on the car phone, he
reported that they were ``fanatic but there weren't enough of
them''). None was more devout than a woman with frosted hair and
toenails painted tomato red. She had the habit of nodding in
smiling assent at every word, sometimes anticipating the word even
before it left Hitchens' lips, others times corroborating Hitchens'
confident judgments with her own. ``That's right, that's right,''
she'd say, and then look with wide blue eyes at a man alongside her
as if to ensure the point hadn't eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   You could understand the fascination _ some of it anyway. He may
not have been completely sober, but he was plainly brilliant. And,
of course, he hates Bill Clinton, and that was the glue that bound
this unlikely assemblage together _ an Oxford-educated literary
man, an acolyte earnestly recommending to Hitchens' audience
Plato's ``Republic,'' a middle-aged, self-confessed conservative
trying to make common cause and, frankly, a handful of nitwits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a cult out there,'' Hitchens said afterward, hungry
for ribs but having to settle for a Reuben sandwich, more Johnny
Walker Black and two glasses of Merlot at a sports bar. Even there
he did not go unrecognized. While the televisions blared from all
directions, two young patrons spotted him on their way to the men's
room and wanted to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   He would not seem, at first glance, a recognizable figure. If he
is 6 feet tall, it's only with his shoes on, and he has the
moderate paunch of many 50-year-old men. His fingers and feet seem
too small for the rest of his body, and his brown hair flops over
his ears and collar without apparent effort to do much with it. His
eyes are an ordinary blue-gray, although on this particular night
they were becoming bloodshot from travel and fatigue. It's a face
with no particular definition. Only when he speaks would you
notice. Words spill out effortlessly, the familiar word used in an
interesting way, the unfamiliar word used with an exacting
precision. He calls himself glib, as if to deflect attention. But
there is no deflecting it.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, appearing on C-SPAN's ``Booknotes'' with Brian
Lamb, Hitchens said his writing had always been fueled by contempt
for fools and wrongdoers. ``For a lot of people,'' he said, ``their
first love is what they'll always remember. For me it's always been
the first hate.''
</P>
<P>
   The same animus, he told his audience at Borders, went into the
writing of ``No One Left to Lie to.'' ``I wrote the book for two
reasons,'' he said. ``One was to revive the idea of the pamphlet as
a literary form, and the other was to whip up hatred and
contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter were securely in place when he arrived. If he also
rekindled in some of those bourgeois minds a desire to become
reacquainted with Addison and Steele, William Hazlitt, Thomas Paine
and George Orwell, then the evening was an unqualified success. But
one wondered if Hitchens' first aim really resonated with this
audience _ whether, for example, they might have relished the same
verbal dexterity had its target not been Bill Clinton but the
smaller figure of Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   For these listeners, there was no incongruity, no irony in
rumpling the bedsheets with a man of the Left. And a leftist, for
that matter, who assails Clinton for his ``personal crookery'' on
one hand and his ``cowardice and conservatism'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brilliant writer,'' one woman said, and no one would
deny that. Since moving to the United States in 1980, Hitchens has
been singularly admired by other journalists for his easy
erudition, lacerating wit and unflinching willingness to say it
outright. He's a virtuoso, able to move from mention of Montesquieu
in one paragraph to Bill Clinton's ``rust-free zipper'' in the
next. Of Clinton's relationship with Kathleen Willey, he writes in
his book:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Willey, some may recall, had been an admirer of President
Clinton, had been the wife of a Democratic fund-raiser, had been a
volunteer worker at the White House, had suddenly become a widow,
had gone in distress to the Oval Office for comfort and for a
discussion about the possibility of a paying job, and had been
rewarded with a crushing embrace, some cliched words of bar-room
courtship, and the guiding by the presidential mitt of her own hand
onto his distended penis.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not been his prose that has lost him so many friends.
Rather, it was his willingness to sell out a one-time friend,
Blumenthal, in print and then with an affidavit. It was Blumenthal,
Hitchens both wrote and testified, who told him that Monica
Lewinsky had been stalking the defenseless president in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchens thought this a craven ploy to disgrace Lewinsky and
exonerate the president. Moreover, he now had become ``hostage to a
piece of information,'' and his conscience did not permit him the
luxury of silence. ``I did not move to Washington in order to keep
quiet,'' he writes, ``and, as a matter of fact, nobody has yet
asked me to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is on the outs with almost everyone he once was friendly
with. ``The consequences in my own life,'' he writes, ``have made a
literal truth out of what I had once written only metaphorically:
Clintonism poisons everything it touches.''
</P>
<P>
   And here he was, in Dunwoody, looking a bit dissipated but at
least among friends. One had driven all the way from Kennesaw, and
she wore an American flag as a lapel pin. Tomato Toes was in
rapture the whole time. Later, asked if she were Republican, she
looked almost ashen with shock. And then she said: ``Of course. Any
thinking person has to be Republican _ not the present Republican
Party but the party as it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   She meant, she said, the Republican Party that rebuilt the
military, and now her face was glowing again.
</P>
<P>
   As she was saying this, Hitchens was busily signing books and
chatting with his new friends. He had betrayed everyone else, and
this was what he was left with.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
