<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SOMETHING GOES WRONG, WE ASK IF THERE'S SOMEONE WE CAN SUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The tendency to overreact to an accident or some
other tragedy is as American as talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as a story breaks, the collective reflex is: Who's fault
is it? Is there someone we can sue? And, how many laws can we pass
to make sure this will never, ever happen again?
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, our knee-jerk tradition produces useful reform.
</P>
<P>
   Often, it produces a lot of headlines and political posturing
and kicks up of a ton of dust that blinds us to reality and our own
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   So seems the case locally with the death of Julie Day, a
24-year-old administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Day got into a taxicab after a night of drinking with friends in
one of San Francisco's popular watering holes. She ended up dead in
a shallow grave in a neighborhood here called China Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Although police say an autopsy may yet show that Day's death was
accidental, the driver of the cab, Jehad Baqleh, has been charged
with rape, robbery and murder. The district attorney says he will
seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following Baqleh's arrest late last week, city cab
drivers reported that they were being yelled at and harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic and print media interviewed dozens of women who said
they now felt uneasy about ever taking a cab again. Business at the
company that employs Baqleh was down by two thirds.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Supervisor Leslie Katz made the hyper-reaction official
by proposing that the city look into installing 911 alarm buttons
and surveillance cameras in every licensed cab.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said she did not want her proposal to be interpreted as
``an overreaction to a very obscure, yet horrific incident,'' but
she reasoned: ``This tragic incident highlights the need for added
protection, but it is something that should have been a long time
coming. We want to ensure the safety of residents, city workers and
tourists. We want people to feel safe in taking taxis.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Julie Day's awful death, did scores of residents, city
workers and tourists equate hailing a taxi with crossing a six-lane
freeway on foot at rush-hour? Based on such a dramatic and
expensive proposal (and the logic behind it), one could only assume
that San Francisco has a chronic and dangerous cab crisis on its
hands.
</P>
<P>
   If it hasn't, then the reflexive public negativity and Katz's
proposal are precisely an overreaction to a very obscure incident.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gavin Newsom, who has operated as a go-between for
the board and the taxicab industry, has taken a thoughtful
approach. He's asked the police department for a statistical
snapshot of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   How many cabbies, he wants to know, have been convicted of
felonies and violent crimes? How many have been accused?
</P>
<P>
   The cops say a preliminary survey of the numbers indicates that
only about five to 10 allegations of assaults by drivers on
passengers are logged each year. Meanwhile, we know for certain
that six cabbies have been killed on the job in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Before the people of this supposedly sophisticated city condemn
5,000 cab drivers and their industry _ or before we go to the
trouble and expense of outfitting every taxi with security systems
worthy of Fort Knox _ wouldn't it be nice to know just how big of a
problem we really have?
</P>
<P>
   It may be the American way to want to do something in the wake
of any tragedy or to craft sweeping legislation from the aberrent;
that doesn't make it wise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
