<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEART AND SOUL OF FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Corey Thomas O'Neil, then 18, died quietly in a
hospital bed on Aug. 21, 1994. But his mother was so sad, the loss
she felt was so severe, he only stayed away a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son came back to me,'' Pat O'Neil says, ``and through a
series of miracles, he's never left.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for Corey's mother to speak about the days and
weeks her son was gone.
</P>
<P>
   That was the summer after he'd graduated from Trevor Browne High
School in west Phoenix. Corey spoke then of becoming an architect
or a draftsman. He was young and strong and as close to invincible
as a person gets, which is not close enough.
</P>
<P>
   After a family gathering that summer, a friend of Corey's came
to pick him up on a motorcycle. The two of them drove off into the
night, happy and untroubled. Not far away a car pulled out in front
of them and the motorcycle driver lost control. Neither young man
was wearing a helmet. Corey's friend survived. Within a few days,
doctors told Pat and her husband, Jay, that Corey was brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to have him disconnected from the life-support
systems that kept him breathing and, if he passed away, to donate
his organs.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened on Aug. 21. &QL; 
SEARCH FOR CHANGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The days after Corey's death are a blur to his family, like
sitting in front of a television set but not really watching,
having no idea what the actors just said or what the story is
about.
</P>
<P>
   As fall turned to winter, and signs of Christmas began appearing
in all the stores, the dark days of August became even more
difficult for Corey's parents and his sister, Amy.
</P>
<P>
   Pat, who was searching for a way to take her mind off the loss,
got a job in the salon of a local department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first miracle,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Lois Cousten walked in one day. Some of the other
women got excited when they saw Lois, asking how she was doing and
if she was healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   She was, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She'd had a heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   It was Corey's.
</P>
<P>
   They knew for sure after Lois described the thank you letter
she'd written anonymously to the donor family, the one in which she
described the healthy heart beating in her chest as ``Sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the chances are of a transplant recipient
like me running into someone from a donor family,'' Lois says,
``but in a city this large it has to be astronomical. That had to
be God's idea.'' &QL; 
LIFESTYLE ADJUSTMENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat sees it that way, too.
</P>
<P>
   She figures Corey asked the Big Fella if it would be OK to have
Lois run into Pat, and he went along with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a scary thing to meet the person who received your
son's heart,'' Pat says. ``I can see why that is kept anonymous.
But, in our case, it worked out beautifully. Lois and I hit it off
right away. She's a good, good person. It made me feel like Corey
was really with her, in all ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The transplant wasn't without some complications for Lois. She
had a few setbacks early on, and was told she had to cut back on
her physical activity. This wasn't easy for a woman who'd spent
part of her life as a paramedic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know what to do with myself,'' she says.
``And, if you'd have asked me back then, just about the last thing
I'd have come up with was studying for the ministry. But, somehow,
that's what happened. Of course it had something to do with the
heart, with being given this second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois stayed in touch with Pat's family, studied the Bible and
eventually became a minister. Not long after that, Pat's daughter
Amy asked Lois if she would officiate at her wedding.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Pat says, ``Corey was there. Through Lois, he was
there for his sister. Becoming friends with Lois has done that for
us. It's made it easier to accept what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows now, with absolute certainty, that where ever her son
may be, his heart is in the right place. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
