<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER DROPS BILL AFFECTING CHARTER SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A bill that set up a showdown between charter
school supporters and state teachers' unions has been killed as
California lawmakers seek a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Carole Migden, a Democrat from San Francisco, said
Wednesday she had agreed to withdraw her proposed legislation to
require charter school teachers to become members of the union in
their district.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she is offering a watered-down bill that would merely
allow charter school teachers to take their complaints to a state
labor board.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's original bill caused an outcry among charter school
proponents, including Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown, who said it was
not aimed at helping charter school teachers, but at increasing the
power of the California Teachers Association, the state's largest
union representing teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Charter school supporters also said Migden's bill would hinder
the schools' flexibility to have longer school days and years and
to hire and fire teachers based on performance.
</P>
<P>
   The unions argued that the bill was the only way to guarantee
that charter schools pay teachers a minimum salary and protect
employees' rights in disciplinary cases.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's decision to table her bill was a significant retreat by
the strongly pro-labor lawmaker and chairwoman of the
Appropriations Committee. But after sensing strong opposition in
the Democrat-controlled state Senate, she realized the bill would
never become law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crafting legislation is an art of compromise,'' Migden said
Wednesday. ``We believe the bill will garner more support in its
present form. I myself could have stomached a stronger bill, but I
am not a solitary voice.''
</P>
<P>
   But she insisted that her new bill would still provide a measure
of protection for teachers at charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new bill, AB631, charter school teachers with labor
grievances could go before the Public Employment Relations Board.
Without the bill, charter school teachers with complaints would
have to take their employer to court, Migden said.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's sudden shift surprised charter school advocates, who
were studying the details of the new legislation late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who heard about Migden's decision while attending a
conference in Las Vegas, was suspicious of the new bill.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor suggested that the Public Employment
Relations Board could force restrictions on charter schools that
strike at their very reason for existing: to be free of government
mandates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true objective (of the new bill) is to force charter
school teachers into the collective bargaining agreement of another
institution _ the school district,'' Brown said. ``The whole reason
for charter schools is to create separate, flexible and innovative
learning environments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly could consider the bill as soon as next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
