<SLUG> BC-FILM-NOTTINGHILL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT UNLOVABLE: SWEET ROMANTIC COMEDY PAIRS GOOD-NATURED ROBERTS,
GRANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is a meeting of the archetypes. Even though
it's supposed to be about a man (Hugh Grant) falling for a woman
above his station, a movie star (Julia Roberts) _ like a fable in
which a mortal tumbles helplessly into love with a goddess and then
learns how dangerous such an act can be _ Grant plays it like a
movie star. A very mannered movie star, perhaps, but anyone who's
seen him in ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' or any of the other
comedies, won't be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Notting Hill'' is like a fight for a big title; in this
case, the honor goes to the person with the biggest, boldest
persona, the contestants being an American and a Brit.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts steps into the ring ready for battle. She plays Anna
Scott, who's trying to play it on the down-low while making a movie
in London. She wanders into the failing travel store that William
(Grant) runs in the now-trendy Notting Hill section of London.
William is wed to his store; his marriage fell apart years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Opening ``Notting Hill'' as competition for ``The Phantom
Menace'' is a very smart piece of counter-programming. This
meticulously beveled and sanded romantic comedy has a glorious
conceit, because although it plays on a common fantasy _ what would
it be like to romance a movie star, and would such a person be
interested in a normal person _ the fact is that Grant has arrived
as a star already. There's nothing ordinary about him, really. In
fact, he seems to match up with Roberts because his wrists are as
skinny as hers. Together, they're a pair of slender, striking,
concave-of-cheek androgynes _ a match made in Vogue. They belong
together.
</P>
<P>
   The movie itself is about the inevitable genteel superiority of
the English that has become a staple, thanks to the films of
Merchant Ivory. (In fact, it's a film full of conceits; if a
bookstore devoted to travel would do well anywhere in London, it
would thrive in yuppie-ridden Notting Hill.)
</P>
<P>
   William's witty, askew group of friends _ who fall in love with
the ideal that Anna presents _ have the merciless, self-deprecating
breeziness that ``Four Weddings'' resuscitated, a cliche that many
of us thought had passed from view. The most vivid of William's
group is his ratty Welsh lunk of a roommate (Rhys Ifans) who, in a
key moment, gets to show exactly how cheeky he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is a more enjoyable trifle than ``Four
Weddings'' because it's better-looking. The difference between the
two films is almost like the evolution of Notting Hill itself from
chic slum to full-blown moneyed enclave. And it plays with
perception vs. reality. When William is summoned to see Anna, it
turns out that he's been invited to a junket _ a situation where a
slew of journalists are given brief interviews with stars promoting
a new movie: like when you see a local TV entertainment reporter
sitting in the same room with _ oh, let's say Julia Roberts _ and
sucking up to her.
</P>
<P>
   Anna turns out to have a streak of bratty temper; she's not
always the likable, backlit dream-come-true. ``Notting Hill'' also
has a lovely idea, a twist on the moment when a lover has dumped
you and you seem to see her face everywhere. In this case, it's
ridiculously true: William sees her soulful, sultry face gazing
back at him from the sides of buses and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is a confident confection, the kind of movie
that people from Notting Hills around the world will fall in love
with. And in case you're wondering who wins the title match for the
most lovably mannered, well ... when Julia Roberts turns on that
smile, and a tear reddens her big, brown eyes, let's just say that
America is still the champ _ though the fight goes right up to the
final bell.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Notting Hill''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Roger Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Julia Roberts, Hugh Grant
</P>
<P>
   Length: 123 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
