<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-PRIVATERYAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
THE CASE FOR _ AND AGAINST _ `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, there was much wringing of hands and gnashing of
teeth when Steven Spielberg's WWII epic ``Saving Private Ryan''
didn't walk home with a Best Picture Oscar earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the film's well-deserved statues in five categories,
including Best Director, the coveted Picture award was considered
by most critics to be a lock. I'm of two minds on the subject,
disappointed in some ways but ultimately happy with the way things
played out.
</P>
<P>
   My argument why it should have won:
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's portrayal of the D-Day invasion of Normandy is the
most horrifically wrenching depiction of war ever captured on film.
This isn't your father's war movie. These aren't a bunch of
anthem-singing GI Joe's picking off Nazis, then kicking back for a
communal drag on a Lucky Strike. These are terrified kids watching
their buddies ripped to pieces in a hail of bullets and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The film is packed with unforgettable moments that will sear
themselves into your memory. The scene with a Nazi soldier slowly
sliding a knife blade into the chest of the struggling Adam
Goldberg while whispering into his tear-streaked face is one of the
most haunting film images ever.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's top-notch cast including Tom Hanks (in a
delightfully nonshowy performance), Tom Sizemore, Giovanni Ribisi,
Jeremy Davies and Matt Damon, couldn't have been better.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's my argument why it shouldn't have won:
</P>
<P>
   Like Oliver Stone's Oscar-winning ``Platoon'' or even
Spielberg's own ``Schindler's List,'' these images, however
powerful, are not the kinds of things you want to relive. ``Ryan''
is a film you see once, are tremendously moved by, and then plan
never to experience again. This year's Best Picture, ``Shakespeare
in Love,'' is something that gets better with every viewing. Does
that make it a better movie? No. But it's certainly a more
watchable one. And that's worth something.
</P>
<P>
   For those who missed ``Ryan'' in theaters, by all means, rent
the video. It holds up well on the small screen, especially if you
have a good sound system. Watch it with your children when they're
old enough.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I'm still trying to shake the sight of Goldberg's
dead stare.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks Home Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic depiction of wartime violence, adult subject
matter and profanity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3415 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THIRTEENTHFLOOR-     05-27 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THIRTEENTHFLOOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIRTEENTH FLOOR' IS THE SAME OLD STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Question reality,'' urge the ads for ``The Thirteenth Floor,''
and you have to fight the temptation to respond, ``Again?'' People
in this movie talk about deja vu a lot, and deja vu is what its
virtual-reality story inspires after a season of similarly themed
films. A reviewer has to remember, though, that not everyone has
seen ``The Matrix'' _ much less the smaller-budgeted ``eXistenZ''
or ``Open Your Eyes'' _ and try to judge ``Floor'' on its own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, on its own terms, ``Floor'' is merely an OK
time-killer, hurt by rote direction and a story arc so familiar
that the movie's surprises aren't very surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Daniel Galouye's novel ``Simulacron 3'' (a much more
intriguing title), ``Floor'' feels held back by its literary
origins. It's less a science-fiction thriller than an old-fashioned
whodunit.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery begins in 1937, as sad-eyed old man Hannon Fuller
(Armin Mueller-Stahl) drops some bills on the dresser while his
younger lover lies sleeping, then tells a surly bartender (Vincent
D'Onofrio) to deliver a letter to a guy named Douglas Hall. Fuller
goes home, lies in bed with his wife, and the next thing you know,
he's going through a tunnel of squiggly blue lines and he wakes up
in the present. Turns out he's jacked in to a virtual-reality
device that he helped create, and that even in the present, he has
a message for Douglas Hall, who happens to be Fuller's assistant.
Too bad someone fatally stabs Fuller before he can deliver the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Hall (Craig Bierko, whose reality apparently doesn't include
razors that shave very closely) becomes a suspect in the slaying;
he even suspects himself, since he had a strange memory lapse
around the time Fuller was killed. So he decides to investigate,
hopping between the present and the alternate reality. Naturally,
all is not what it seems.
</P>
<P>
   You can see what drew the people involved in ``The Thirteenth
Floor'' to the material. It's no wonder that filmmakers are so
fascinated with alternate realities, because in a sense movies
``are'' alternate realities _ imagine making entertainment so
convincing that the audience lives it (anyone who's seen the
obsessive fans in ``Trekkies'' or the people who camped out for
``Phantom Menace'' tickets knows that this has already happened).
And the principal cast gets a chance to stretch its acting chops,
each playing dual roles in the parallel universes. Their
performances are so muted, though _ the always interesting
D'Onofrio is particularly wasted here _ that you have to wonder how
they reacted to the end result.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws in ``The Thirteenth Floor'' fall squarely on the
shoulders of director Josef Rusnak, who handles the film in the
most journeyman way. Movies like this need a sense of panache or
mood, and Rusnak can't even provide a strong period atmosphere for
the 1930s scenes. Curiously, the scenes in the present have more of
a retro feel, thanks to a weird bluish tint, Bierko's noirish
detachment, and the appearances of Dennis Haybert as a dogged,
hat-wearing detective and Gretchen Mol as a Chandleresque ``femme
fatale.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're at all interested in ``The Thirteenth Floor's''
themes, it should be the fourth movie on your to-see list. It
should come after the razzle-dazzle of ``The Matrix,'' with its
lofty attempts at myth-making; after David Cronenberg's
``eXistenZ,'' with its mixing of existential philosophy and
celebrity culture; and after the Spanish ``Open Your Eyes''
(opening this week in Fort Worth), with its deep sense of sadness
and its commentaries on vanity and shallowness. All these movies
are flawed, and in a way, they're less successful than ``Floor.''
But they're only less successful because they try to do much more,
and that makes them much more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Thirteenth Floor''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Josef Rusnak
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Craig Bierko, Gretchen Mol, Vincent D'Onofrio
</P>
<P>
   Length: 101 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and adult themes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
