<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_ADVICE ON HEART ATTACKS: EXPERIENCE DOES COUNT  
 _AMA OFFERS OLIVE BRANCH TO ITS NEXT JOURNAL EDITOR
 &HT;    _FURTHER NOTES: DIABETES, AND A CAUTION ON AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Advice on heart attacks: Experience does count
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At risk for a heart attack? Here's what a study says: Find out
which hospital in your area treats the most heart attack patients,
and get there at the first sign of chest pain.
</P>
<P>
   The study, reported to be the first of its kind, has found that
hospitals with the most experience gave elders a 17 percent better
chance of surviving heart attacks for a month than hospitals with
the least experience.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen percent translates to 2.3 fewer cardiac deaths for
every 100 heart attack patients _ a benefit that exceeds the rule
of thumb used to determine if a new drug or surgical procedure is
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice makes perfect,'' said Dr. David R. Thiemann of Johns
Hopkins University, who led the study of nearly 100,000 Medicare
heart attack victims. It is published in the current New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann added that the health care system ``isn't designed to
deal with'' heart attacks in the most effective way. ``Heart attack
patients, in most cases, are taken to the nearest hospital, and not
much regard is given to whether it's a low-volume or high-volume
hospital,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of high-volume hospitals has nothing to do with
whether they are teaching hospitals or can do open-heart surgery or
angioplasty. The finding ``raises questions about the benefit of
the proliferation of technology at smaller hospitals,'' Thiemann
and his colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said that one-third of the survival difference
at high-volume hospitals was related to more use of aspirin and
other drugs, such as clot-busters. But mostly it was attributed to
``an experienced health care team.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that ``in some sense we don't take heart attacks
seriously,'' Thiemann said. ``There's a sort of
take-your-anti-clotting-medicine-and-call-me-in-the-morning
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AMA offers olive branch to its next Journal editor
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To heal the wounded reputation of the Journal of the American
Medical Association, the AMA said Wednesday that it would set up a
committee to ``buffer'' the journal's next editor against
organizational politics.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is the latest development in a brouhaha
precipitated in January when the AMA fired its veteran journal
editor, Dr. George Lundberg. His offense ostensibly was publishing
a finding, on the eve of President Clinton's impeachment trial,
that most college students do not consider oral-genital contact to
be ``having sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg later complained that he had fended off AMA officials'
attempts to interfere with his editorial judgment for years.
</P>
<P>
   Lundberg's successor will report to a seven-member panel with
only one member on the AMA payroll, and that person may not be the
panel chairman. Any move to oust the editor will have to go through
the new panel and win approval from two-thirds of the AMA's
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMA management recognizes and fully accepts the necessity of
editorial independence for the editor-in-chief at all times,'' the
organization declared.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer, editor of the rival New England Journal
of Medicine, said the AMA's plan ``sounds good on paper,'' but
added: ``If I were a candidate for the editor's job, I'd want to
know who is going to be on that committee and I'd want to meet with
them to explore their point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Further notes: Diabetes, and a caution on AIDS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In other medical news, a new drug for Type II diabetes called
rosiglitazone (brand name Avandia) has won federal approval amid
hopes that it will not cause the rare but potentially fatal liver
problems seen with its cousin, called troglitazone. The drug is
expected to cost about $900 to $1,200 a year. . . . The AIDS virus
``cannot be eradicated with current treatments,'' a team from
Northwestern University has reported for the current New England
Journal of Medicine, on the basis of new evidence. Another group,
from New York's Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center, similarly found
AIDS virus replication in two of six patients treated for up to
three years. Dr. Anthony Fauci of the National Institutes of Health
said the studies underscore the need for better drug treatments
``as well as novel strategies to purge residual virus from the body
and boost the immune system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
