<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRTUAL-REALITY-LADN     05-27 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-REALITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS TAKE A DIM VIEW OF WHAT LIES AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPPS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We have seen the future _ and it stinks.
</P>
<P>
   In recent science-fiction movies like ``The Matrix'' and
``eXistenZ,'' tomorrow's earth is a desolate, disturbing and
thoroughly unpleasant place where virtual reality rules and free
will has been shunted off to some far and distant corner. Then
there's ``The Thirteenth Floor,'' arriving in theaters today, where
the future is OK (except for some tacky high-rise developments
along Southern California's coastline), but stupid humans still
muck everything up by creating virtual worlds with their computers.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying message: Get real. Because if it's not real, it's
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The irony here is that the hard-core fans watching these movies
generally don't share that world view. All those people who went
back to see ``The Matrix'' again and again generally feel
comfortable with technology and confident about the future. And
yet, they can't seem to get enough of the film's ground-breaking
special effects and its heady (but ultimately dour) mix of
symbolism and cyber-technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an interesting tension there,'' says Wired magazine
columnist Jon Katz. ``I don't think I've ever seen a technological
film that doesn't see the future as a dark, menacing place. I think
it's going to take a brave producer _ someone who isn't so cynical
about our world _ to wake up and finally make a movie that's both
hip and forward-looking and not so bleak.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Katz didn't like the movie. The author, whose
books include ``Virtuous Reality,'' a spirited defense of
cyberspace and youth culture, has seen ``The Matrix'' three times.
His loyalty _ and that of moviegoers like him _ is one reason the
film has made more than $150 million since its release in late
March. A sequel is already in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The themes explored in this crop of virtual reality movies are
hardly new to the science-fiction genre or, for that matter,
television and popular movies. Rod Serling's anthology series ``The
Twilight Zone'' often had episodes in which characters examined
their surroundings with a suspicious gaze, believing they were part
of some kind of cosmic practical joke. (Usually they were.)
</P>
<P>
   Science-fiction writers such as Harlan Ellison and Philip K.
Dick also explored the blurring of reality and illusion in their
stories. Last year, ``The Truman Show'' successfully captured that
queasy feeling that life, as we know it, is a fake, staged exercise
in futility. It was one of the year's most successful movies.
</P>
<P>
   Technology only enhances the level and quality of the fakery. In
``The Thirteenth Floor,'' there are multiple virtual worlds and its
denizens are never quite sure whether their society is the original
or a computer copy. That kind of guessing game fuels the audience's
interest, much as it did in ``The Matrix'' and the excellent
Spanish movie ``Open Your Eyes,'' which opened in the United States
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted to keep the audience just a little bit in the
dark so they'd be wondering what's going to happen next,'' says
Larry Wachowski, who wrote and directed ``The Matrix'' with his
brother Andy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the film's hodgepodge of biblical and mythological
references and its bleak view of the future, Wachowski declines to
go into too many specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the audience to use their brains while they're
watching the movie,'' he says. ``The idea of `The Matrix' is that
it's too easy to live the unexamined life and not be aware of
what's going on in the world. And that can lead to a sorry state of
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, in ``The Matrix,'' involves humans being kept awash in
amniotic fluid, blind and mute from birth to death, existing only
so their brain currents can power the machines that run the
universe. Meanwhile, the humans think everything is OK, living in a
virtual world that masks their dire plight.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common motif in these virtual reality movies: Unaware
people blissfully plugged into illusory worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Which, say some social critics, is kind of like the Internet
and, to a lesser degree of involvement, television and movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already live in a kind of virtual reality,'' says author
Neal Gabler, whose latest book is ``Life the Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Littleton. There was kind of a seamless transition
between the video games Doom and Quake and the actions of Eric
Harris and Dylan Kleibold. When you live inside giant fantasies,
you are essentially living in first-stage virtual reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz blanches at the correlation between video games and acts of
murder, but admits that he often feels a ``jarring sensation'' of
living in a parallel universe when he goes online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you do have to pinch yourself to know what is
real,'' Katz says. ``Going online is very empowering to some people
because they can assume personalities much different than their
own. And now you have people paying thousands of dollars on e-bay
for virtual personalities that they can use in games like Ultima
On-Line. The lines between fantasy and reality have definitely
blurred.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's actually good news for studios making
technology-driven movies since a little familiarity with the
subject matter can go a long way at the box office. Witness ``The
Matrix'' or ``Open Your Eyes,'' a big hit in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``The Thirteenth Floor'' are keeping their fingers
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scripts for virtual reality movies have been floating around
for five or six years now,'' says ``Thirteenth Floor'' director
Josef Rusnak. ``We're seeing them now because people have caught up
with the technology. They understand it better. And that makes it
easier for them to connect with the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Centropolis Entertainment, the film's producers, decided to take
that audience know-how to the next level and hosted a ``virtual
premiere'' of ``The Thirteenth Floor'' Monday night. It all
followed to form _ movie stars walked down the red carpet, the
paparazzi shot their pictures and fans sat in the bleachers and
cheered for their favorites. There were even celebrity guests _
Sarah Michelle Gellar and Jennifer Love Hewitt among others.
</P>
<P>
   And none of it actually happened outside of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point these premieres begin to feel redundant,'' says
producer Dean Devlin, who partnered with director Roland Emmerich
on ``Independence Day'' and ``Godzilla'' and spearheaded the
cyberspace gala.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all these movies about virtual reality in the air right
now, it's weird that nobody has ever staged a virtual premiere.
Being uncharted territory, it was a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the next step? Virtual moviegoing?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Devlin laughs. ``Not profitable enough.''
</P>
<P>
   What the future might hold, if technophiles have their way, are
movies that depict virtual reality in a manner that isn't so
destructive and despairing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These movies, particularly `The Matrix,' operate within a
convention that essentially says that happiness of a virtual
reality sort comes at the expense of free will,'' Gabler says.
``But that assumes we don't want those things, and I think we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy humming and with drugs like Prozac, we're
already on the road to purging a lot of the qualities _ anxiety,
loneliness, depression _ that make us human. Virtual reality will
probably take us to the next level. Yet you don't see any movies
that imagine the future that way. It's always the machines, not the
humans, who are in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Katz: ``We'll see one someday. Maybe it will take the `Star
Trek' people to go where no film has gone before.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it lives long and prospers (in theaters), maybe others
would follow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
