<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-WITNESS-BOS &LR;      05-27 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-WITNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTS PONDERING AS IDS ARE FOUGHT ON RACIAL BASIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Is the eyewitness identification of a black robbery
suspect by a white bank teller less reliable simply because he's
black and she's white?
</P>
<P>
   Dueling experts couldn't agree in Boston recently, and neither
could a federal jury, which late last week said it was hopelessly
deadlocked, unable to reach a verdict in the bank robbery trial of
a young black man whose chief accuser was an elderly white woman.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Nancy Gertner, breaking new legal ground, had
allowed expert testimony on the reliability of cross-racial
identification, a rare and controversial move in Massachusetts
courts, which have hesitated to allow such testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Just Wednesday, the state judge presiding over the murder trial
of Jeffrey Bly, the man accused of gunning down gang prosecutor
Paul McLaughlin in 1995, refused a request by Bly's lawyers to
present an expert witness to undercut the testimony of a white
woman who testified that she saw Bly, who is black, near the
commuter rail stop the night McLaughlin was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who identified Bly in court, said she noticed him
because it was unusual to see a black man in predominantly white
West Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   In refusing the request for expert testimony, Superior Court
Judge James D. McDaniel Jr. said there may be times when jurors
should hear such expert testimony, ``but this is not one of them.''
Some of the most incriminating evidence against Bly has come from
his former associates.
</P>
<P>
   But Gertner allowed two psychologists to testify in federal
court about the accuracy of eyewitness identification when it
involves people of different races.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the accused robber, Johanna Hines, contended that
the arrest of Hines was a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's expert cited experiments that indicate people have
difficulty identifying someone of another race. The prosecution's
expert, meanwhile, countered that the experiments could not be
applied to real-life situations, like a bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Saul Kassen of Williams College, who testified for the
defense, said studies show a witness is wrong 13 to 15 percent more
often when he or she is asked to identify a suspect of a different
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not overwhelming, but it is there,'' Kassen told jurors
in the Hines case. ``And it's true whether it's white on black,
black on white, white on Hispanic, Asian on white. It makes no
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a question of prejudice, not a `those people all
look alike' type of thing,' '' Kassen testified. ``It is an
innocent mistake. It is simply more difficult for people to
identify members of a race other than their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Kassen said there is no firm explanation for the difference in
reliability but added that ``the best reason seems to be the lack
of exposure to the other race.''
</P>
<P>
   But a witness for the prosecution _ Ebbe B. Ebbesen, a
psychology professor at the University of California in San Diego _
said the results of controlled laboratory experiments cannot be
automatically applied to real-life situations, such as a bank
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of a bank teller being robbed at gunpoint, Ebbesen
said, cannot automatically be equated with ``an experiment with a
group of college students, who are not the victims of crimes,
looking at photographs, students who are, perhaps, getting paid or
(receiving college) credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know how people react in a real-life robbery,
whether they focus more intently or less so,'' Ebbesen said. ``The
problem is taking research that's been done and applying it to the
real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts courts have resisted efforts to admit expert
testimony on eyewitness identification because it may confuse or
mislead the jury or prolong a trial unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   That may be changing. The US Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit in Boston has yet to consider the issue of cross-racial
identification. But in a 1995 opinion upholding a lower court's
refusal to allow an expert to testify about the reliability of
eyewitnesses in general, the court noted that courts in other parts
of the country were beginning to rethink the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door that was once largely shut is now somewhat ajar,''
the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Supreme Court recently set aside a rape
conviction of a black man accused of raping a white woman, saying
the jury should have been instructed that it can be difficult for
people of one race to identify people of another.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent case in federal court here, a white teller, Jeanne
Dunn, identified Hines, 39, as the man who robbed her at gunpoint
of $10,982 at the Broadway National Bank in Chelsea on Jan. 27,
1997. The teller picked Hines out of a lineup seven months after
the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   A Hispanic customer who was in the bank at the time of the
robbery could not identify Hines.
</P>
<P>
   Although the robber was photographed by a bank surveillance
camera, the image was blurry. According to court papers, Hines
allegedly told a government informant that he applied Vaseline to
his face during bank robberies to distort his image.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Elizabeth Loftus of the University of Washington and
Boston lawyer James M. Doyle, who have both written extensively on
eyewitness identification, suggested the reason for
misidentifications may lie in the way we process the faces of
people of different races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on different features,'' Loftus said. ``Showing a
white person photos of Asians, for instance, they might focus on
the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said recent studies of cases in which DNA evidence cleared
defendants who had been wrongfully convicted found that in a large
number of cases, eyewitness testimony was a key factor in obtaining
the faulty conviction.
</P>
</TEXT>
