<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL PILGRIMS TURN TO JERUSALEM AS THEY PREPARE FOR 2000 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, May 29-30) 
 
By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Blaine Schrag, a 61-year-old church bus driver from
Florida, swings his hoe at an archaeological dig near Nazareth,
voluntarily helping chip away centuries of debris and rubble to
uncover the village of Jesus' childhood.
</P>
<P>
   In the working-class, mainly Muslim neighborhood of Bethany near
Jerusalem and the Mount of Olives, Sister Sharon, a 53-year-old
grandmother from northern California, stacks giveaway clothing for
the poor as she awaits the Second Coming.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the Rev. Ed Young of Second Baptist Church urges the
faithful of his affluent megachurch to worship and evangelize, even
though no one ``knows the day or hour'' Jesus will come back.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, the year 2000 is a magnet of fear and hope. Many
find themselves drawn to Israel to welcome the new millennium and
celebrate the anniversary of Jesus' birth.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 6 million tourists may come to the Holy Land next
year _ almost double the usual number. About 1.5 million of them
are identified as religious pilgrims. Texas Gov. George W. Bush
visited this year. Even the frail and ailing Pope John Paul II may
go for the first time next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most destinations, the millennium means the biggest New
Year's party in history. For us, it means playing host for a year
or more to a celebration of worldwide importance,'' says Arie
Sommer, Israel's tourism commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pilgrims, such as Schrag and Young, are mainstream
believers who see the trip as the opportunity of a Christian's
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But a visible minority, such as the Colorado group recently
expelled from the country, have a scarier vision. As many as 100
millennial Christians, who believe the end is drawing nigh, have
trickled in already. Believers predict more will come next year.
</P>
<P>
   Compounded by heavy tourism and a possible papal visit, the
presence of the millennialists promises even greater media
attention and monumental security risks for this nation of 6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, who uses no last name, came here on a one-way ticket
seven years ago, becoming a mainstay in the 30-member millennial
community known as the House of Prayer. She met the group's
gregarious leader and founder, Brother David, a week after
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's life and work focus on a pastoral village near the
Mount of Olives. Hot, dry and dusty, it is where many believe Jesus
began his journey on a donkey to Jerusalem for the first Palm
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where Jesus spent a lot of time,'' Sharon says.
``There were several miracles in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Her tiny apartment overlooks some of Christianity's most famous
landmarks. During Jesus' ministry in Jerusalem, he made his home in
Bethany. His friends Mary, Martha and their brother, Lazarus, lived
there. Tradition says Bethany is where Jesus went after his
resurrection to ascend to heaven, and many interpret Old Testament
prophecies to mean the Messiah will return to the Mount of Olives.
</P>
<P>
   David arrived in 1980. He believes it was God's will; he has no
passport. Members of their small group live in 14 houses and
apartments leased by the House of Prayer. Some apartments house
group members; others are leased to visiting pilgrims for $5 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   The timeless voice of the lion of Judah, an Old Testament
metaphor for God, roars in their ears, alerting them the end is
near, they say.
</P>
<P>
   As Sharon describes her ministry, a rooster crows outside her
apartment. A Muslim chants midday prayers to Allah. A baby cries.
Traffic roars by on a nearby thoroughfare. Yet she remains focused,
telling her story in a strong, quiet voice. She has grown used to
the city noise and the media attention. A Wednesday night House of
Prayer service drew three TV crews one night this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, whose easygoing nature and flowing reddish-brown hair
mask the strength of her convictions, became a Christian 30 years
ago. Biblical prophecies linked to Israel always fascinated her,
she says, but she didn't pursue her interest until the last of her
seven children left home. One of them, Brother Raymond, has moved
to Israel and joined the House of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever God has given me to do, I do,'' she says. ``I do all
of our communication, all our letter-writing. I write, by hand,
approximately 2,500 letters a year. I have about 80 families in the
area that I deliver clothes to. They're donated by pilgrims and a
couple of churches in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli authorities keep a wary eye on end-time groups such as
the House of Prayer, but tourist dollars remain important in the
nation's economy. About 10 percent of Israel's gross national
product comes from tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the land where time began,'' trumpets Israeli tourism
in a $5 million U.S. national advertising blitz. Galilee.
Bethlehem. Nazareth. Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   A direct-mail campaign, bolstered with ads in local U.S. papers
and radio stations, targets the nation's 60 million Roman Catholics
and 100 million evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's state airline, El Al, is offering a free stopover in
Rome, another pilgrimage city, en route to Jerusalem. This spring,
tourism officials courted travel agents in a campaign that included
an enormous dinner and trade show in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You love Shakespeare, go to England. You love Christianity, go
to Israel,'' advises Haim Gutin-Golan, director of Israel's
Southern U.S. tourism office.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel is drawing the fearful as well. Fundamentalists and
end-timers are among the most worried, anticipating widespread
disruption and panic in the wake of the Y2K computer bug that some
predict could shut down airlines, banks and other services at
midnight Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Other believers are preparing for Jesus' imminent return. Some
Americans are selling all their belongings, as Sharon did in 1992,
and buying one-way tickets to Israel to await the Second Coming.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has laws protecting freedom of religious expression, but
authorities will not tolerate violent extremists, perhaps fearing
incidents like the one in 1969 when an Australian fundamentalist
Christian set fire to the El Aksa Mosque, seeking to replace it
with the predicted Third Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials avoid discussing security. But new police
sub-units have been set up in the Old City of Jerusalem. Concern
for pilgrims' safety is high, as is attention to major Christian
shrines, such as the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, traditional site
of Jesus' tomb.
</P>
<P>
   At all costs, Israelis want to avoid the sort of standoff that
ensued in 1993 in Waco, Texas, between David Koresh's Branch
Davidian sect and agents of the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   While people such as Brother David of the House of Prayer
technically may remain in Israel only as visitors, a few insist on
staying. The more belligerent risk being arrested and deported.
That is what happened this spring to 14 members of Concerned
Christians, a Colorado-based group. Authorities suspected the group
of planning dangerous activities to bring on the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should anyone be foolish enough to openly declare their
intentions and to gather in large numbers, I don't think the police
would hesitate to act decisively,'' says Rueven Hazan, a professor
of political science at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials emphasize the lack of crime in Jerusalem,
and the nation's readiness to welcome visitors. They hope a tourism
boom will bring in 50,000 jobs. Projected income from tourism next
year could reach $5 billion. Millions have been spent repairing
roads, building hotels and increasing parking.
</P>
<P>
   Tzion Evrony of Houston, consul general for Israel's
southwestern region, says pilgrims may expect ``an unforgettable
cultural and spiritual'' visit.
</P>
<P>
   Others warn of long lines, water shortages and other problems.
One experienced Catholic tour guide in Jerusalem suggests that
pilgrims not come next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HISTORICALLY, the land that is Israel and its capital,
Jerusalem, played a key role in the world's three great
monotheistic religions: Judaism, Christianity and Islam. God
brought Abraham here to become the father of many nations. Jesus,
born to Jewish parents in Bethlehem, ministered here. His
crucifixion and his followers' account of his resurrection spawned
a worldwide church. Muhammad, Islam's prophet, is believed to have
traveled to Jerusalem on a winged horse with the angel Gabriel.
From Jerusalem, he ascended to meet God.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Israel and Jerusalem are indelibly linked to millennial
hopes. Both have difficult, controversial histories laced with
high-minded ideals and mystical religious power, and burdened by
power struggles and blood baths.
</P>
<P>
   Fast, savvy and in many ways Americanized, Israel struggles to
bridge the religious and ethnic differences of its polyglot
culture. Created in 1948 in the aftermath of the Nazi Holocaust
that claimed 6 million lives, Israel brought together Jews from 102
countries speaking 74 languages. Compounding the stress and strain
of this cultural mix in the last 10 years has been the advent of
900,000 Jews from the former Soviet Union and 70,000 from Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   That growth and the establishment of controversial Jewish
settlements on what some claim were formerly Palestinian lands
breed success and failure. Away from business and political centers
in Palestinian-controlled areas, people are poorer, roads rougher
and modern conveniences harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   But a new millennium brings hope even in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of church and interfaith leaders see this as a time for
rejoicing, bridge-building and peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 is a useful peg to assist us in focusing on why
we have the church at all,'' says the Rev. Maxwell Craig, head of
the Church of Scotland's Jerusalem office. ``The question I would
ask is: Why is God giving us a new millennium? The answer is to
build Christ's kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it also calls for making peace. That calls for peace in
the Balkans, for peace in Northern Ireland. It calls for peace in
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the millennium is a complicated matter in Israel,
where politics often compete with prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, Palestinian Christians working with Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat hope to restore the village of Jesus' birth
with adequate hotel accommodations, water, parking and other
services in time for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns include offering enough access to the Church of the
Nativity, the traditional site of Jesus' birth. Entrance is
possible only through a low doorway, according to legend, designed
so that nonbelievers could not ride into the church on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   In Nazareth, restoration in time for 2000 is still being heavily
promoted by Israel, despite local tensions between Muslims and
Christians. At issue is whether the town of Nazareth should build a
public plaza for millennial celebrations on a half-acre near the
famous Church of the Annunciation or devote that land to a huge
mosque.
</P>
<P>
   And the country is coming off a wrenching election that brought
a new prime minister to office.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural tensions plagued this region as long ago as the first
century. But for early Christians, these worries paled in the wake
of spiritual concerns. The Apostle Paul believed Jesus would come
back soon, and he warned Corinthians, Ephesians and other Christian
communities to settle their petty squabbles, forsake sinful
pleasures and live as though the risen Christ lived among them.
</P>
<P>
   With the approach of 2000, many Christians around the world feel
the same urgency today.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, Texas, the Rev. John Hagee of Cornerstone Church
challenges Christians to heed biblical prophecy, back Israel and
forsake the church's historical anti-Semitism. Raising Christians'
awareness that they are ``rapidly approaching the end of the
dispensation of grace is critical,'' says Hagee, who has led
regular pilgrimages to the Holy Land for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Such leaders as the pope, the Dalai Lama and the Rev. Billy
Graham long for such reconciliation as well. The pope has asked the
Jews for forgiveness. The Dalai Lama, esteemed among Tibetan
Buddhists, argues in his newest book that fewer poor people would
suffer if the world's better-off lived more responsibly. Graham,
famous for his global ministry, asserts that evangelism must change
with the times. He is inviting 10,000 evangelists from around the
world to a one-time conference in July 2000 in Amsterdam,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has declared 2000 a ``jubilee year,'' urging his
worldwide flock to prepare prayerfully. With the Archbishop of
Canterbury, titular head of the world's Anglicans, the pope is
asking the United States and the world's other richest nations to
forgive the staggering $200 billion debt of the globe's poorest
countries. A cross section of European nations, including Germany,
is endorsing similar moves, as have religious leaders from Sikhs in
India to Christians in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has even reinstituted ``indulgences,'' an ancient form
of church-granted amnesty that releases penitents from certain
forms of punishment in this life or the next. Medieval Catholicism
sold indulgences, a habit that led Martin Luther to protest,
spawning the Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   The pope announced last year that, for the duration of the
millennium celebration, penitents who perform a charitable deed or
give up cigarettes or alcohol for a day can earn an ``indulgence,''
eliminating the time they must spend in purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   In a distinctly modern development, embattled Middle Eastern
Christians of 19 denominations, minorities in a troubled region,
assisted the builders of Jesus2000.com, a Web site offering a
``virtual pilgrimage to the Holy Land.'' Once signed on, Christians
can send their prayers and blessings to Christian holy sites,
including Bethlehem and the Sea of Galilee, for a fee of $15 plus
$3 postage and handling.
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes links to a ``mall'' that offers Holy Land
videos, books on decoding biblical prophecies and, for $39.95, a
gold-plated cross with crystals ``filled with Jordan River water
and Holy Land earth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOVEN through the history, scriptures and traditions of
Christianity is the virtue of waiting. Waiting in prayer for God's
guidance. Waiting in the wilderness to make it to the promised
land.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle Ages, as today, millennialism sprang from the seed
of fear _ or hope _ of a great final battle between the Antichrist
and the Messiah. Prophets since Daniel in the Old Testament had
predicted a final accounting, an ultimate confrontation. The
Revelation of St. John, the final book in the New Testament,
explores that conflagration in glorious and often frightening
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Like their predecessors, the people drawn to today's Jerusalem
believe God calls them there. The journey is less taxing and
dangerous than 10 centuries ago. Earlier pilgrims had neither the
luxury of interfaith understanding nor the extravagant welcome
promised by Israeli tourism. But the goals of such pilgrimages are
similar.
</P>
<P>
   If there is such a thing as a ``millennial mentality,'' it mixes
optimism and pessimism. On the one hand is a real hope, a desire
for a new start, the promise of a better age. On the other is a
desperate fear that the end may come and one may not be ready.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, alternative spirituality gurus are
advertising millennial events in a spring issue of New Age
magazine. They are inviting their followers to Kaua'i, Hawaii, Dec.
21, 1999, through Jan. 2, 2000, to ``join kindred spirits as we
create a sacred celebration to bring in the new millennium in the
true spirit of aloha!''
</P>
<P>
   Televangelist Robert Schuller of Garden Grove, Calif., is
preparing for a grand millennial event. His ``Hour of Power'' show
will broadcast from Jerusalem on Christmas Eve, where he is asking
the faithful to join him on a tour.
</P>
<P>
   And Ed Young, pastor of Houston's Second Baptist Church, plans
to ring in the millennium with his wife, Jo Beth, and several
hundred members of his church on an eight-day trip to Israel. Young
has reserved Caiaphas' house, the home of the high priest who
helped convict Jesus, in Jerusalem for a special service Dec. 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a spiritual standpoint, I think the whole world revolves
around Jerusalem,'' Young says. ``It is an international city, full
of people of every nationality, every creed, every religion. It's
sort of a melting pot. As a Christian, it's home for me. Everyone
wants to go home at Christmas. I'd like to be `home' in Jerusalem
for this date.''
</P>
<P>
   More fundamentalist Christians view the coming days as a time of
battle. Most believe genuine Christians will be ``raptured,''
literally vanishing from their posts in offices, fields and
factories, being taken to heaven by Jesus Christ. Those left on
Earth will suffer through ``the tribulation,'' seven years of wars,
social and political chaos, a devastating earthquake and the
miserable rule of the Antichrist. After the battle of Armageddon,
when Jesus and the angels defeat Satan's minions, Christ will
return to reign for 1,000 years, presiding over a glorious age of
peace.
</P>
<P>
   So ingrained in Christian consciousness is this chain of events
that fictional books depicting such an apocalypse have become
best-sellers. Sales of the ``Left Behind'' series, by Tim LaHaye
and Jerry B. Jenkins, have been robust. Even secular readers are
snapping them up, along with many end-times novels being published.
Others have been written by big Christian names such as television
broadcaster Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe apocalyptic traditions need to be taken very
seriously, but not literally,'' says Bernard McGinn, a University
of Chicago historian and one of the editors for the three-volume
Encyclopedia of Apocalypticism. ``These symbols are important in
our culture and are ways of understanding our past.''
</P>
<P>
   Human beings mark time in anniversaries, birthdays, New Year's
Eve parties and Fourth of July barbecues. And, notes McGinn, ``We
observe the end of centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is especially important at the end of the millennium,''
he says. ``One in three generations see the end of a century. But
only one in 33 see the end of a millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   At such moments, humanity looks backward and forward. Some
entertain the possibility of miracles; others see clouds of doom.
In truth, commemorating Jesus' birth at 2000 celebrates an
inaccurate date. Experts believe he was born between 4 B.C. and 1
B.C., depending upon how one dates the rule of Herod the Great.
</P>
<P>
   So Jesus wasn't born in the year 1, but before. And the new
millennium doesn't begin until 2001 because there is no zero in the
Christian calendar.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't deter the millennialists converging on Jerusalem,
or people who plan to celebrate in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though many people know rationally that the year 2000 is
arbitrary in terms of when the actual millennium should be
celebrated, it becomes a convenient hook on which to hang all the
anxiety, all the fear, all the hope and all the speculation,'' says
Diane Winston, of New York University's Center for Media, Culture
and History.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, Christians have looked to Israel for spiritual
sustenance. This is the Holy Land to Jesus' worldwide flock of 2
billion. They want to walk where Jesus walked.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the number of Christians living in the Holy Land _
many of them Palestinian or Arab _ continues to decline. An
estimated 52 percent of the population of the Old City of Jerusalem
was Christian in 1922; today, Christians make up only 2.5 percent.
Thousands of Palestinian Christians emigrated following the
withdrawal of British troops from the region in 1948 and the
founding of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the reference in the Psalms to the `peace of
Jerusalem,' the Holy City has probably seen more rapine and
pillage, more regularly, than any comparable patch of ground on the
planet,'' says Scottish travel writer William Dalrymple.
</P>
<P>
   Politics are secondary concerns to most pilgrims. Pain, hope and
a desire for renewal bring them to the Holy Land. Here,
Christianity is in evidence from the stark watchtowers of Mar Saba
monastery in the wilderness of Judea to the quiet confines of the
Garden Tomb, outside the Old City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions, Blaine Schrag came to Israel for spiritual
renewal. He retired as an accountant and general contractor after
being diagnosed with bone cancer in 1991. Since then, the lanky,
blue-eyed Floridian has put his energy where his faith lies _ in
doing for others.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Schrag raised $50,000 for a housing ministry by
riding his bicycle from Pensacola, Fla., to San Diego, Calif. This
spring, he paid $2,000 to volunteer with a Gulf Breeze, Fla.,
church group that went to Israel to work in Nazareth Village.
Located on a grassy knoll in the shadow of Nazareth Hospital, the
village is a multiyear restoration of 20 acres. Experts say the
land may be the same ground farmed by Jesus and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Underwritten by the Miracle of Nazareth Foundation, the project
is an interdenominational effort to resurrect the town where Jesus
grew up. Archaeologists are working with volunteers, clearing
trash, digging for artifacts and planting vineyards and olive
groves. They hope to open a model village by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors would take ``a parable walk,'' based on one of Jesus'
famous stories, and interact with village workers in First Century
attire and character.
</P>
<P>
   Nazareth Village director Mike Hostetler compares the concept to
Colonial Williamsburg. The project, to develop in stages, is the
dream of Dr. Nakhle Bishara, an Arab Christian and ninth-generation
Nazarene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where people once saw dusty stones and open meadows, we hope
they'll now see the mustard plants, vineyards and olive trees of
Jesus' childhood that he used to illustrate spiritual truth,'' says
Bishara, medical director of Nazareth Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For Schrag, digging in Nazareth is like his cross-country bike
trip: a way to fight pain, fatigue and depression. In the winter,
he drives truckloads of clothing and blankets to needy Indians in
South Dakota. He has served on church boards, worked with the men's
club, built houses with Habitat for Humanity. All his life, the
church has been a path to ways to live as Jesus lived. That matters
more than ever now.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Israel in May, he helped put up two terrace walls
in Nazareth Village and planted a vineyard. Looking out over the
craggy hillside, he has a distant look in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this is spiritually uplifting,'' he says. ``After a
couple of days, I forgot my pain. Just knowing that Jesus walked
through that land is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're here, you feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
