<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-HARASS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY RULES IN FAVOR OF COP WHO PROTESTED POLICE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal jury has awarded $500,000 to an officer
who said his patrol unit was told to harass surly-looking
teen-agers and soiled derelicts lingering around the downtown
tourist area.
</P>
<P>
   After some eight hours of deliberations on Wednesday, seven
jurors found that Police Department officials retaliated against
Officer Onofre Serna for protesting the heavy-handed tactics that
the Downtown Foot and Bicycle Patrol was encouraged to use in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Serna was transferred to overnight squad-car duty in 1996 after
an internal inquiry into the downtown unit described the officer as
``disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the nine-day trial, Serna sat subdued as U.S.
District Judge Edward C. Prado read aloud the verdict, which was
less than half the compensation and damages the police officer had
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Once the court adjourned, Serna said spotlighting police abuses
was as important as the $500,000 award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's still going on right now, to this day,'' he
said. ``I believe it has a long way to go before it changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers on both sides, however, testified that the department's
problems in the downtown tourist district diminished with the
transfer of Serna and several other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Al Philippus said the city may appeal the verdict.
Philippus insisted, as he did on the witness stand, that the
department never targeted anyone based on income, race or any other
category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We target problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors found that Philippus, who was named as a separate
defendant, didn't maliciously single out Serna when he approved a
recommendation to transfer five officers and supervisors from the
downtown beat.
</P>
<P>
   Serna filed the lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court saying that
the Police Department retaliated against him because he objected to
the orders. He also contended that the transfer violated his civil
rights and laws protecting whistleblowers.
</P>
<P>
   Two other officers who were transferred then have filed similar
lawsuits against the city. One is slated for trial next month.
</P>
<P>
   Because the jury's verdict focused on Serna's retaliation, it
did little to answer clearly the question that dominated testimony:
Were officers told to snatch bandannas and other gang-related
regalia, to demand identification from patrons in certain bars, and
to drive homeless people from the heart of San Antonio, with or
without provocation?
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trial, eight officers asserted that the patrol
supervisor encouraged illegal searches and seizures and other
heavy-handed methods aimed at keeping the downtown
tourist-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other officers said the complaints originated from
disgruntled officers who resented their strong-willed supervisor
and twisted his words against him.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mery, the lawyer representing Serna, said the police
policies or targeting certain people put civil liberties were at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``When has the freedom to walk the streets of San Antonio become
an issue you can call a petty squabble?'' he asked the jurors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
