<HEADER>
A3516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-CARE28-COX     05-27 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD GIVE EMPLOYERS A TAX CREDIT FOR CHILD CARE
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Standing in a playground at a federal office
building Thursday, a pair of senators unveiled legislation making
it easier for businesses to offer on-site child care for their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many businesses are trapped,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
``They understand that companies who help employees with child care
enjoy a significant competitive advantage, but they can't afford to
provide that care.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was joined by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, to
announce a bill that would give businesses a federal tax credit for
providing on-site child care for employees.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, estimated to cost the federal government $800 million
over five years, would give employers a 50 percent credit:
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $100,000, for start-up costs of an on-site facility,
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $25,000 annually, for operating costs of the facility,
and
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $50,000 each year for employers who help pay for child
care outside the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   As the work force has changed over the past several decades, the
need for child care has increased, Graham said. In 1947, nearly
one-fourth of all mothers with children between 6 and 17 were part
of the labor force. Currently, two-thirds of all women with
children under 18 are in the work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill puts families first,'' Hutchison said. ``For
two-parent families working to make ends meet, and for the many
parents who are unable to find affordable day care, it offers
incentives to employers to set up on-site child care.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham and Hutchison expect the legislation to be included as
part of a tax reduction bill that will be considered later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
