  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MAY
27, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-WINE. It's easy to buy liquor over the Internet. Just
point, click, and order -- no middleman necessary. But the very
ease of alcohol sales over the Internet is at the center of a
political storm brewing in Congress. Wholesalers are up in arms
because they're getting cut out of the business, while alcohol
producers are reaping the benefits of a new marketing tool. (800
words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-UDALL-KOSOVO. Rep. Mark Udall, a Boulder Democrat,
called on President Clinton today to halt NATO bombing for 72 hours
to test whether Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is willing to
accept a political settlement and withdraw troops from Kosovo.
Udall, who has staunchly defended the airstrikes in the past, and
19 other Democrats urged Clinton to work harder for a diplomatic
end to the fighting, which polls show is losing public support.
Udall's shift away from the administration's position brings him
closer to the stance of Colorado's Republican lawmakers, who have
long supported a stop to the bombing. (600 words.) By Charles
Davant
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-WELFARE-GAO. A General Accounting Office study released
today shows that welfare recipients in Indiana and other states
have returned to the work force in far greater numbers than
previously thought. (450 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-VETERANS. Hundreds of New Jersey veterans gathered in
a park next to the Capitol today to rally against budget cuts in
the Veterans Affairs administration. (400 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-GORE. A look at the political machine behind Vice
President Al Gore's bid to steamroll former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley in the Democratic primary. By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-ROSES. Phil Fogarty this week helped make sure the
unveiling of new roses honoring the nation's veterans went
smoothly. The Mentor resident organized the unveiling, all the way
down to helping arrange the roses in a garden at the Arlington
National Cemetery. (300 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-GUNS. When the House returns from the Memorial Day
recess, gun legislation will top the agenda. In the wake of a year
of several deadly school shootings, Wisconsin lawmakers discuss
what they think Congress should do to keep guns out of the hands of
children. (450 words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -30-
