A3537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-27 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Record on Attendance
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere Friday or Saturday, a Broadway ticket taker will rip
someone's ticket and set a record.
</P>
<P>
   With that ticket, Broadway attendance will top last year's
record 11.5 million. The record for yearly box office is already
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the week the total attendance figure for the
year was 11,406,930, according to the League of American Theaters
and Producers, with weekly attendance averaging about 250,000. That
means that by Sunday, the final day of Broadway's fiscal year, the
old record should be shattered.
</P>
<P>
   As for money, last Sunday the yearly box office figure stood at
$575,468,742, already $17 million more than last year's record.
With a weekly average of about $12 million, the league estimates
that the total yearly take will be $588 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, president of the league, said the attendance
figures were especially encouraging because of the large number of
straight plays in smaller houses on Broadway this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another barometer of the strength of a type of live
theater that maybe wasn't that strong four or five years ago,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rosy industrywide news, not everybody is smiling.
Five shows played to less than half-capacity last week. ``Ring
Round the Moon,'' produced by the nonprofit Lincoln Center Theater,
is a limited run; but the four others _ ``Side Man,'' ``The
Lonesome West,'' ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' and ``The
Civil War'' _ are open-ended commercial runs, and their numbers
were distressing.
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive of the bunch is ``The Civil War,'' which cost
$7 million to produce, and which lost about $130,000 last week.
</P>
<P>
   An agent connected to the show said its producers were looking
for a ``name'' country-and-western singer like LeAnn Rimes or Amy
Grant as a possible replacement for a departing cast member, Irene
Molloy. Norman Zagier, spokesman for the show, said he could not
comment on any potential casting. ``The producers are working
assiduously to market the show,'' Zagier said, ``to the widest
possible audience.''
</P>
<P>
   `Riverdance' Redux
</P>
<P>
   Theatrical trend spotters, consider this: The first musical
project of Broadway's next century will likely be ``Riverdance.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya Doherty, the producer of the enormously successful Irish
dance spectacle, said this week that the production had signed a
deal to play the Gershwin Theater, Broadway's largest, with
performances beginning in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-member company will be made up of dancers in the
production's three touring companies, which have been raking in a
hefty profit. Ms. Doherty said the production would probably be
open-ended, though it would probably be initially offered for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement's significance can be read in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, ``Riverdance'' offers another example of
producers aiming for a tourist audience with a show that needs
little English or highbrow theatrical savvy to enjoy. Shows from
``Cats'' to ``Footloose'' have employed this tourist-friendly
formula, and Ms. Doherty said that out-of-towners were expected to
be a large part of the ``Riverdance'' crowd. Its international
appeal has been proved, Ms. Doherty said, by successful runs across
Europe and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   The booking could potentially take the Gershwin out of the mix
for an extended period just as many producers are complaining about
the lack of large musical houses. Until this month, the
Nederlanders had offered the theater for a fall revival of ``The
Music Man,'' to be produced by Dodger Theatricals, but that show
has been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Riverdance'' may work in a theater that has
bedeviled many productions before it. The theater's large size,
1,935 seats, has always challenged commercial producers. ``On the
Town'' lost $6 million last fall; before that ``1776'' fared better
but it did not make a profit. ``Peter Pan,'' its current tenant, is
doing fair business now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Riverdance'' may well break that streak. Since first
arriving in North America in 1996, ``Riverdance'' has toured
worldwide and maintained remarkable box office figures. According
to a report published in Variety, the show's two North American
companies had combined gross sales of nearly $2 million for the
week ending May 16, leading all other road companies.
</P>
<P>
   Luck of the Irish
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Brian F. O'Byrne has had a charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   An Irish native who took up acting in college, O'Byrne came to
the United States in 1988 after inadvertently winning a green card
in an immigration lottery; his uncle had entered his name without
telling him. After arriving, he said, he got his first professional
acting job because the director's brother was married to O'Byrne's
aunt. Several years later another twist of fate earned him a part
in the play ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' by Martin McDonagh,
after an actor dropped out because of illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' he said. ``I've made no decisions about
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his role in ``Beauty Queen'' earned him a Tony
nomination for featured actor. And this year O'Byrne, 32, has just
earned another nomination, this time for leading actor in a play,
for his performance as a brawling rustic in McDonagh's ``Lonesome
West.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hilarious,'' O'Byrne said, laughing, ``to be
included at the end of that list.'' The other nominees include
Kevin Spacey and Brian Dennehy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has a clue who I am,'' O'Byrne said. ``They always kind
of mumble out my name.''
</P>
<P>
   What does he think of his chances? O'Byrne broke into a big
smile, and said, mock seriously: ``I'm lobbying very hard. I've
secured two votes. Both took weeks of drinking to secure, but they
finally came around.''
</P>
<P>
   In true seriousness, O'Byrne said he was honored, if a little in
awe of his luck. So, what will he do next?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the master plan,'' he said. ``And I have no
idea.' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
