<HEADER>
A3545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-WARS-$ADV30-C     05-27 1684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-WARS-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO 'BILLS' COOL CONGRESS'S IRE TOWARD NEA, NEH
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories for
release Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the personal ways that matter on Capitol Hill,
the ``two Bills'' have already been approved by Congress, before
any votes have been cast on legislation to fund their populist
views of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ivey, chairman of the National Endowment of the Arts, has
chatted about country music with Rep. Dick Armey of Texas and Sen.
Jesse Helms of North Carolina _ conservative Republicans who tried
to abolish his agency in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ferris, the chairman of the National Endowment of the
Humanities, has turned a Mississippi drawl into a political asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the leadership on both sides of the aisle are
Southerners,'' said Ferris. ``There is a deep bond that Southerners
have. It's kind of a tribal world in that they like to see their
own do well _ whether it's a professional football player, a
musician or a political figure.''
</P>
<P>
   But along with soft-spoken charm, the ``two Bills'' have brought
substantiative change to endangered agencies. Under orders from a
hostile Congress, they broadened their agencies' notion of culture
to touch more Americans, and tightened controls to prevent federal
grants for controversial works like Robert Mapplethorpe's
homoerotic photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Ferris and Bill Ivey have renewed each agency's
commitment to serving the American people in a way that recognizes
and respects the wealth of culture that exists in every
community,'' said Sen. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the
Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions, which has
oversight over the NEA and NEH.
</P>
<P>
   One result: After suffering budget cuts for several years while
fighting for their very survival, the agencies may actually receive
an increase in funding this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had unanimous commitment to increases from all of the
congressional leaders with whom we have been speaking,'' said
Ferris.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has requested $150 million for each
agency for the fiscal year 2000 _ a sizeable increase over the $98
million NEA budget and the $110 million NEH budget for FY 1999. The
budgets of both endowments were slashed by over one-third four
years ago and have remained at around $100 million apiece since
then.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing education and community projects, the two Bills have
changed the perception that the endowments are elitist and the fact
that grants were skewed toward cultural centers like New York and
California.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional reaction has been heartening, said a staffer on
Jeffords' committee. He recalled how committee member Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., almost came over the dias in outrage after
former NEA chairwoman Jane Alexander implied that Arkansas didn't
get a proportional share of grants because the state lacked worthy
artists.
</P>
<P>
   The new chairmen have the endowments ``moving in the right
direction,'' said Hutchinson. ``I'm pleased with their progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   A sense of place is important in folklore, and both Bills are
folklorists. Their place in Washington is the Old Post Office
Pavilion, a handsome building with a clock tower on Pennsylvania
Avenue. Built in 1899 as a headquarters for the U.S. Post Office,
it was nearly demolished during the Great Depression but renovated
in the early 1980s into a center for private shops and restaurants
and for federal offices. It serves as headquarters for the NEA and
NEH.
</P>
<P>
   Although he spent 27 years as director of the Country Music
Foundation in Nashville, Ivey is not a native Southerner. He grew
up in a copper mining community in upper Michigan. On his
conference table, he keeps a wooden form used to make a cast iron
pipe fitting for a mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me back to my days in high school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On his desk is a small sculpture of a young Bing Crosby at a
recording session. Created as part of an exhibit for the Country
Music Hall of Fame, it was left over when Bing was replaced by a
figure of Ernest Tubb. On his wall are photos of Minnie Pearl and
the Ryman Auditorium from a 1946 Life magazine piece on the Grand
Ol' Opry.
</P>
<P>
   A considerable number of country music fans have votes in
Congress, said Ivey, who was confirmed as NEA chairman a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   His background ``provides me with a basis for conversation with
many members,'' he said. ``It also grounds me in a grassroots
American arts form that is based in middle America and is connected
with America's folk art heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his definition of the arts, he explained that defining
is not what his job is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of things agency tries to do, perhaps its primary goal, is
to help communities and organizations and citizens realize their
dreams through the arts,'' said Ivey. ``We spend a lot of time
supporting what other people think is art, not trying to impose
what we think is art.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ivey, Ferris has a spacious office with high ceilings. The
NEH is located on the fifth floor, two above the NEA. Ferris has
been chairman for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   An antique electric fan stirs the air. Behind his desk is a
painting of dirty dishes in a sink _ the work of a former student
at Ole Miss. There is artwork by his daughter when she was 4 years
old and a painting by his sister of the farm where they grew up.
There are photos of Eudora Welty, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Alice Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bring your family with you'' with such mementos, he
explained. ``Paintings and plants kind of give you a feeling that
you're building your little nest here.''
</P>
<P>
   The former director of the Center for the Study of Southern
Culture at the University of Mississippi, Ferris believes his job
now is not about some ``distant kind of ivory tower kind of
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I define the humanities as the many voices that we hear.
Voices over the dinner table at night, of parents and grandparents.
Voices from the past: Plato. Shakespeare. The great history of
literature, philosophy, music. Our American voices: Abraham
Lincoln, Robert Kennedy, Martin Luther King, William Faulkner,
Herman Melville, Robert Frost,'' said Ferris.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all voices in our ear _ some of which we discover in
classrooms and the media, some of which we listen to daily. Those
are all a part of the sound that helps us have a richer and fuller
and more secure life.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Under orders from Congress, Ivey has changed the NEA. Grants to
individual visual artists were abolished, as were seasonal grants.
Geographic distribution is now considered in making grants. There
are special grants for states and communities that have been
slighted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The changes ``basically put us in the position of knowing in
advance what funds will be spent on,'' Ivey said. ``There is less
uncertainty about what outcomes will be like.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey moved quickly to tamp out the only controversy during his
tenure _ a $7,500 grant earmarked for the Texas publisher of a
bilingual children's book. The author turned out to be
Subcomandante Marcos, the leader of the Zapatista guerrilla
movement in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have subjected the agency to criticism had the grant
been made,'' he said, recalling that he received ``phone calls and
letters from members after the decision was made saying they felt
it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``two Bills'' have received bravos from the nation's
cultural community for helping save the agencies. But there are
also a smattering of boos for some of the changes, especially in
the NEA.
</P>
<P>
   Archibald Gillies, director of the Andy Warhol Foundation for
the Visual Arts, is among many critics of the policy abolishing NEA
grants for individual artists. Before the cutbacks began, these
grants totaled about $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fault the Clinton administration for not standing up for
artists during that battle as much as they could have,'' said
Gillies. ``As a political tactic, I comprehend it. But I don't
accept it. I would have preferred the fight to have been made.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Roberto Bedoya, executive director of the National
Association of Artists' Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The agency ``no longer supports individual artists. That's had a
very dramatic effect,'' said Bedoya. ``There's been a shift toward
audience development and arts education.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, Congress demanded that the agencies become more
conservative in order to stay alive. So they did. But they are no
longer committed to supporting new artists and new ideas and forms
in art. I don't like that. Other people are content to live with
this compromised agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivey did only what Congress demanded, countered Jan Denton,
director of the American Arts Alliance, an advocacy group for 2,500
non-profit arts associations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My observation is that Congress definitely needed to be calmed
down for, particularly, the NEA to survive,'' said Denton.
Lawmakers ``needed to feel more comfortable with funding
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this was necessary before he could rebuild the agency
back to what it was in the glory days,'' said Denton. ``Our vision,
in time, is that (the agency) will be able to fund individual
artists. We have to have a long view.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar view was expressed by Ruby Lerner, director of the
Creative Capital Foundation, an organization recently formed to
make private grants to individual artists. Some cast the foundation
as reactive to the NEA ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not courting controversy. We're here to support
individual artists,'' said Lerner, who formerly headed Image
Film/Video Center and Alternative Roots in Atlanta. ``But we
realize some of work will end up challenging convention.''
</P>
<P>
   She said both endowment chairmen are ``very smart strategically.
If given the time, they will take the agencies in as interesting a
direction as possible in these funding circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
