<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian Silents That Say a Lot
</P>
<P>
   In Aleksandr Dovzhenko's ``Arsenal'' (1929) a one-armed farmer,
furious over his imminent starvation, beats his decrepit horse with
a stick. Slowly the weary animal turns to him. ``You're hitting the
wrong one, Ivan,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true horse of the Soviet avant-garde, which in the
'20s used about anything to get its point across. In ``Arsenal,''
one of three films from the Soviet silent era to be released in new
editions this month by Kino International, a portrait on the wall
comes to life, if only to roll its eyes as a Bolshevik cadre
prepares to go to its glorious demise at the hands of Ukrainian
forces in an Alamo-style defense of a factory (the arsenal) in
Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   If flocking to the barricades suggests one-note filmmaking, rest
assured that the Russians found ways to make it fresh and startling
even today.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most fertile examples is ``Strike,'' Sergei
Eisenstein's first feature film and one of his freest and most
inventive. A new Kino edition is made from film elements found in
Russia. ``It was in beautiful shape,'' said David Shepard, the film
conservationist who often oversees Kino projects. ``Sometimes we
work with scraps, but on this one we were incredibly lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstein, who was 26 in 1924 when the film was released, had
experience in the theater, which he both relied on and broke away
from on screen. Full of dazzling technique, brilliant visual
surprises and surreal juxtapositions, ``Strike'' is something of an
explosion. The story, about a group of workers who have finally had
enough and close down a foundry, becomes a choreographed pageant of
exaggerated characters and wildly roiling action.
</P>
<P>
   Stoking the excitement is the Alloy Orchestra, a present-day
group from Boston that lends live accompaniment to silent films.
For ``Strike'' the tempo is kept tightly coiled and pounding,
which, if it doesn't get on the nerves after a while, consistently
adds fun to the deepening pandemonium. The Alloy generates a big,
busy sound. ``Actually they're a trio, but it sounds like each one
of them has nine arms,'' Shepard said.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the music, grubby upstarts plot, and the masses brawl
and scream and roll around in mud puddles. Bosses, usually leering,
grossly obese men with cratered faces, have no compassion. Finally,
mounted troops ride up into the apartment houses to club down
strikers and murder babies. At the end a field is strewn with
hundreds of corpses who all look as if they can't wait to jump up
and rush off again.
</P>
<P>
   The third film of the series, Dziga Vertov's ``Kino-Eye,'' is of
a decidedly different disposition. Vertov was a documentarian who
regarded the acted film as a perversion of truth. At the start of
``Kino-Eye,'' also released in 1924, is a brief description: ``The
first nonfiction film thing without a script, without actors,
outside the studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Vertov didn't shoot his films himself but sent camaramen into
the field to film what they would while he remained in Moscow to
edit the results. In one fascinating stretch, ``Kino-Eye'' begins
with a hamburger and traces it backward to its origins as a walking
piece of beef. The caption reads: ``Here we have what 20 minutes
ago was a bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Information: (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Central Station
</P>
<P>
   A former schoolteacher, the cynical Dora (Fernanda Montenegro,
left, with Vinicius de Oliveira) works at the Rio de Janeiro train
station writing letters for the illiterate and then not bothering
to mail them. Then a woman with her 10-year-old son, Josue, in tow,
dictates a beseeching letter to her absent husband and gets killed
by a bus. Despite her loathing for children, Dora takes Josue home,
where she develops a plan to sell him to an adoption racket and get
a new television set. When the scheme lands her in trouble, she
gathers up the boy and goes on a wild goose chase after his father.
On the road the two slowly develop an affinity that takes on a
Felliniesque sense of spiritual discovery. Avoiding sentimentality,
Walter Salles uses his experience as a documentary maker, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, to give ``this lovely, stirring
film a strong sense of Brazil's impoverished rural landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Columbia Tri-Star. 115 minutes. Portuguese with English
subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   Waking Ned Devine
</P>
<P>
   One of the 52 souls who constitute the population of the Irish
village of Tulaigh Mohr holds a winning lottery ticket. When no one
lets on who that might be, Jackie O'Shea (Ian Bannen) and his wife,
Annie (Fionnula Flannagan), carry out a detective project that gets
nowhere until they invite 18 of the biggest lottery players in town
to a dinner. When one, Ned Devine, doesn't appear, it turns out he
is dead, which inspires Jackie to try for the pot by making a
living Ned plausible to a visiting lottery official. In that
pursuit, Jackie and his friend Michael (David Kelly), both about
70, ride naked on bicycles, but this is one lottery film that is
about generosity and not divisive greed. Written and directed by
Kirk Jones, a blithe comedy ``has the knack of finding rubbery,
expressive faces and letting each villager's quirks emerge on cue''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   -1998. Fox
</P>
<P>
   Insomnia
</P>
<P>
   In the far reaches of northern Norway, the fog and endless
daylight start to get on the nerves of the investigator Jonas
Engstrom (Stellan Skarsgard), who has been sent to look into the
killing of a beautiful young woman (Maria Mathiesen). Normally a
hard case capable of taking care of himself, Engstrom finds
developments working against him in ways he can't control. Spooked
by the setting early on, he shoots into the fog and accidentally
kills a colleague. Then he connects much too closely with suspects
in the case he has come to investigate, eventually becoming a
suspect himself. In Erik Skjoldbjaerg's taut debut feature, ``
Skarsgard's performance as a man pushed to the breaking point gives
the film its share of Hitchcockian undercurrents'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Home Vision. $29.95. 97 minutes. Norwegian with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TASTE OF CHERRY.  &LR; In Abbas Kiarostami's film, a mysterious
middle-aged man (Homayoun Ershadi) drives around the dusty Iranian
countryside looking for someone to complete the job of burying him
after he has committed suicide. The man will place himself in a
shallow grave. All the assistant has to do is throw 20 spadefuls of
earth on the body. At first he finds no takers. A young soldier
flees in terror, and a seminarian can't condone suicide. Only an
elderly taxidermist agrees in a film, Stephen Holden wrote in The
New York Times, with ``a vision of human scale that is
simultaneously epic and precisely minuscule.'' 1997. . $29.95. 95
minutes. Farsi with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOYZECK. &LR;  Based on the play by Georg Buchner, Janos Szasz's
film tells the exceedingly grim story of a humiliated Hungarian
railroad worker (Lajos Kovacs) who must endure an unfaithful wife
and brutal bosses before he erupts in violent rebellion. ``An
unremittingly savage evocation of life sadistically crushed under a
totalitarian boot heel,'' Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times. 1994. . 93 minutes. Hungarian with English subtitles. No
rating. Information: (800) 551-8304
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BENT.  &LR; Sean Mathias' film, based on Martin Sherman's play about
the Nazi persecution of homosexuals, sends gay lovers (Clive Owen
and Brian Webber) off to Dachau. Onstage the idea worked as stark
drama, but on film, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times, it
becomes ``mawkish, overwrought kitsch with a pornographic gloss.''
1997. Orion. $59.99. 105 minutes. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
