<SLUG> BC-LIVING-WAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO WAGE PLAN HITS SNAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A plan to boost pay for working people suffered
setbacks Wednesday as a coalition of nonprofit organizations said
they could not afford the higher wage, and three members of the
city's Living Wage Task Force resigned citing a lack of progress.
</P>
<P>
   The living wage plan, proposed by Board of Supervisors President
Tom Ammiano earlier this month, would require employers who hold
service contracts with the city to pay their workers at least $11
per hour and provide health benefits, or a cash equivalent to the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The mandate also would apply to businesses that lease property
from the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Services Task Force of San Francisco, representing
nonprofit organizations, said it was concerned that the proposal
would have ``a tremendous negative impact on the nonprofit
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignations of Dan Martin, Robert O'Malley and Walter
Johnson were sparked when a city supervisor called for extending
the committee's work beyond its original July 12 termination date
to Dec. 31, and a separate plan for an independent economic
analysis of the proposed law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further delay would mean thousands of people who are working
hard every day in this city _ caring for our parents and
grandparents, guarding our buildings, cleaning our offices _
continue to live in desperate poverty,'' the three resigning
members say in a letter to the task force. ``The situation demands
prompt attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the possible cost of wages for employees, the
Human Services Task Force said it didn't want the legislation to be
rushed through.
</P>
<P>
   At least 28 cities in the United States, including Oakland and
San Jose in California, already have living wage laws; San
Francisco's, if adopted as proposed, would pay the highest wage and
be the first to include businesses that lease city property.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. minimum wage is $5.15 per hour; California's minimum
wage is $5.75 per hour. A person working full time earning the
living wage envisioned by Ammiano would make $22,800 a year,
$10,840 more than a minimum-wage earner.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's proposal would exempt businesses with five or fewer
employees and those with city contracts worth less than $25,000 per
year. Also exempt would be employees under 21 who are working
after-school or summer jobs; employees in short-term training
projects; and disabled workers in special federal jobs programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
