<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE 13TH FLOOR': TRAVELING IN CYBERSPACE CAN GET A GUY
CYBERKILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some doors are best left unopened, and one of them leads to
movies with the kind of denouement that resembles one of those
boxes of salt with a picture of a woman holding a box of salt with
a picture of a woman holding a box of salt with a picture of ...
The possibilities extend ad infinitum and, in the case of ``The
13th Floor,'' ad nauseam.
</P>
<P>
   Repackaged as cyberthriller, the old time-travel adventure
returns in this stylish but overplotted and ultimately illogical
combination of science fiction, mystery and romance.
</P>
<P>
   The science fiction seems up to date with its computer images
and parallel worlds, including 1937 Los Angeles. The solution to
the mystery turns out to be a yawner that doesn't bear much
scrutiny. And the romance, with ever-so-faint echoes of Hitchcock's
``Vertigo,'' needs a better chemistry set.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The 13th Floor,'' directed by Josef Rusnak from a
screenplay he wrote with Ravel Centeno-Rodriguez, can be
appreciated for its re-creation of a Los Angeles of empty lots on
Wilshire Boulevard, a skyline of oil wells and visions of
white-tied swells riding in Packard town cars or dancing the night
away to ``Caravan'' in Art Deco supper clubs while the less
fortunate sweat out the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, based on the novel ``Simulacron 3'' by Daniel Galouye,
positions its main characters in parallel worlds where they lead
different lives. In the world of the 1990s the principals are
employees of the visionary magnate Hannon Fuller (Armin
Mueller-Stahl), whose projects include an experimental
computer-chip simulation of old Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After a journey to this virtually real world, where he leaves an
important letter with Ashton (Vincent D'Onofrio), an untrustworthy
bartender in the elegant supper club Hannon frequents for its young
female companionship, he returns, makes a hurried telephone call
from a seedy bar and is promptly and brutally knifed to death.
</P>
<P>
   Next morning Hannon's favorite executive and heir apparent,
Douglas Hall (Craig Bierko), wakes to find a blood-drenched shirt
in his apartment and to find himself the prime suspect in events on
a night he cannot remember.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters Larry McBain (Dennis Haysbert), a police
detective, promptly singles out Douglas as the probable killer, and
an alluring young woman (Gretchen Mol) turns up and announces
herself to be Jane Fuller, Hannon's previously unknown daughter.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of clumsy dialogue, Douglas and Jane are soon, as
Yogi Berra might observe, experiencing a lot of d'eja vu all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   These being the complications, there is but one thing for
Douglas to do: travel to 1937 Los Angeles with the help of his
colleague Whitney ( D'Onofrio again) and, in the persona of a bank
teller named John Ferguson, try to sort things out.
</P>
<P>
   With strong performances by D'Onofrio and Mueller-Stahl and with
the help of the costumes of Joseph Porro and the production design
of Kirk Petruccelli ``The 13th Floor'' begins promisingly with the
murder that straddles two worlds. But it strikes no sparks with its
romance, and as the mystery unravels, so does the film. By its end
a return to genuine reality is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``The 13th Floor'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It contains a bloody murder, shootings
and other violence, as well as coarse language and suggestions of
sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   THE 13TH FLOOR
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Josef Rusnak; written by Rusnak and Ravel
Centeno-Rodriguez, based on the book ``Simulacron 3'' by Daniel
Galouye; director of photography, Wedigo von Schultzendorff; edited
by Henry Richardson; music by Harald Kloser; production designer,
Kirk M. Petruccelli; costumes by Joseph Porro; produced by Roland
Emmerich, Ute Emmerich and Marco Weber; released by Columbia
Pictures. Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Craig Bierko (Douglas Hall), Armin Mueller-Stahl (Hannon
Fuller), Gretchen Mol (Jane Fuller), Vincent D'Onofrio
(Whitney/Ashton), Dennis Haysbert (Detective Larry McBain) and
Steven Schub (Zev Bernstein). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INNOCENCE-FILM-REVIEW     05-27 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOCENCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LOSS OF SEXUAL INNOCENCE': THE STORY OF ADAM AND EVE, SORT
OF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' Mike Figgis' visually
exquisite, intensely personal meditation on the story of Adam and
Eve, the world's first couple are a black man (Femi Ogumbanjo) and
a white woman (Hanne Klintoe), who emerge like angelic beings from
the waters of a golden lake. Discovering each other, they explore
their anatomical differences like playful children delightedly
splashing around in the water.
</P>
<P>
   These are the happiest moments in a movie that locates the
essence of evil in sexual jealousy, betrayal and possessiveness.
The scenes of the first couple meeting, frolicking and eventually
running into the hills, where they gorge on pulpy red fruit from
the tree of knowledge and are galvanized by a lust that hardens
their eyes, convey powerful charges of sadness and eroticism.
</P>
<P>
   Those two feelings suffuse this audacious full-length
avant-garde film from the British director of ``Leaving Las
Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' is no simple Bible story. It is
a dreamy semi-autobiographical reverie that fuses the
lost-childhood pathos of the Terence Davies films ``Distant Voices,
Still Lives'' and ``The Long Day Closes'' with the erotic symbolism
of Derek Jarman, and inserts a portentous layer of myth.
</P>
<P>
   Interwoven with its version of the Adam and Eve story are scenes
from the life of a filmmaker named Nic (Julian Sands), who, like
Figgis, spent his early years in Kenya and moved to northern
England as a boy. Different actors play Nic at ages 5, 12 and 16.
</P>
<P>
   As the director has demonstrated in his more conventional films,
he is a master of mood with a keen musical ear. And in ``The Loss
of Sexual Innocence,'' he outdoes himself in creating atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film is a nearly wordless tone poem that sustains an
intense emotional gravity and sexual tension through its mixture of
music, beautiful outdoor cinematography and somber, silent acting.
</P>
<P>
   Solo piano performances by Joanna MacGregor of pieces by Mozart,
Schumann, Beethoven and Chopin deepen the feeling of ethereal
melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the strongest scenes remembers a mid-'60s teen-age party
at which Nic's girlfriend disappears and is discovered in a bedroom
drunk and making out with another boy, who intends to seduce her.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect period pop nugget, Sandie Shaw's hit ``Girl Don't
Come,'' accompanies this moment. Later, the grown-up Nic, unhappily
married with a son, has a silent, angst-ridden sexual encounter
with his wife in the kitchen of their farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Still later, a wordless scene set at a railroad station observes
the furtive erotic signals exchanged between attractive strangers
waiting side by side on a platform for their respective lovers to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in a moment reminiscent of Michelangelo Antonioni, a
sound recordist working on a documentary film in Tunisia strolls
into a field with his equipment and accidentally picks up the
groans of his girlfriend and another man making love in a nearby
tent. The incident triggers a tragedy that resonates deeply with
the Adam and Eve story.
</P>
<P>
   But for every haunting scene, another one fizzles. A subplot
involving identical twins separated at birth who encounter each
other in an airport is extraneous. A scene of the obese 12-year-old
Nic being humiliated by a gym teacher also belongs in another
movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Adam and Eve story is cluttered with intrusive Christian
symbolism. And the expulsion from Eden with its mixture of fascists
and paparazzi is discordantly shrill. Ultimately, the strands of
this elliptical allegory aren't pulled tight enough.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent screening of ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' the
one word bandied about the film afterward was ``pretentious.''
Perhaps. It takes a certain presumption to make a movie comparing
your personal erotic history to Adam and Eve. On the other hand,
isn't that what all great myths invite us to do?
</P>
<P>
   Those with no patience for avant-garde films will want to avoid
``The Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' which opens Friday in New York
City. Everyone else will find moments of surpassing beauty in this
courageous, deeply flawed film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has full frontal nudity
(male and female), sexual situations and one scene of violence.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOSS OF SEXUAL INNOCENCE
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Mike Figgis; director of photography,
Benoit Delhomme; edited by Matthew Wood; produced by Figgis and
Annie Stewart; released by Sony Pictures Classics. Running time:
101 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Julian Sands (Adult Nic), Femi Ogunbanjo (Adam) and Hanne
Klintoe (Eve).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      05-27 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANN RAND CLIFFS NOTES: PHILOSOPHY AS FOREPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlas shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   You will, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even the estimable Helen Mirren cannot make a compelling
protagonist of loopy old Ayn Rand. And while the opportunity to see
Ms. Mirren hurl herself into simulations of noisy, athletic
coupling with Eric Stoltz may sound like voyeuristic fun, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   These determined May-September lovers sweat through ``The
Passion of Ayn Rand,'' which Showtime is unveiling on Sunday night.
This film is ``adult'' (in the nudge-nudge, wink-wink sense), but
it's a pretty muddled drama.
</P>
<P>
   It traps Ms. Mirren and Stoltz, as Rand's acolyte, Nathaniel
Branden, in cardboard characterizations. Julie Delpy suffers
angelically as Nathaniel's wife, Barbara. But among the actors,
only Peter Fonda, as Rand's pathetic husband, Frank O'Connor, is
really worth watching. And he never takes his clothes off.
</P>
<P>
   Rand (1905-1982) may not be discussed much nowadays, but people
of a certain age remember her as the author of two puzzling
anvil-size best-selling novels, ``The Fountainhead'' (1943) and
``Atlas Shrugged'' (1957).
</P>
<P>
   Storytelling was not her real goal, though. She was, as she was
the first to point out, a philosopher. She believed in ... well,
something that had to do with capitalism and self-reliance and that
sounded a lot like selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   Many thoughtful people continue to say that their lives were
elevated by Rand's beliefs. But you'll have to do your own
homework. This portrait of a philosopher has scant time for any
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Rand's outstanding creation was herself. She was
originally Alice Rosenbaum, born in St. Petersburg, Russia. She
fled to the United States, landing in Hollywood. She met O'Connor
there, while they were working as extras for Cecil B. De Mille. But
she had ideas. She also had a Remington Rand typewriter, from which
she appropriated her new surname. She wrote, people read.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens in 1951, she and Frank, who has already been
crushed by her ever-expanding identity, are welcoming a couple of
eager young college students, Nathan Blumenthal and Barbara
Whiteman, into their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you zee, Frank,'' Ms. Mirren exclaims in an odd
pan-European accent, ``zees two bee-utiful people who haf come to
our house!''
</P>
<P>
   In no time the young people put their lives in Rand's hands.
They are her disciples. She gives Nathan a new name and instructs
the couple to marry and enjoy sex. They do their best to comply,
but Barbara has trouble with the enjoyment part.
</P>
<P>
   You learn a lot about Barbara's feelings because the film is
based on the real Barbara Branden's 1986 memoir. And she was a
consultant to the film, which was written by Howard Korder and Mary
Gallagher and directed by Christopher Menaul.
</P>
<P>
   When Ayn explains that as a remedy for her writer's block she
must have sex with Nathaniel twice a week (once in the afternoon,
once in the evening), Barbara is not too thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theez (italics)chh(end italics)ad to (italics)chh(end
italics)appen,'' Ayn says. (You may want to (italics)chh(end
italics)old your (italics)chh(end italics)ed.) ``Lesser people
could never accept it. But veee are not lesser people.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer's block? What writer's block? Now the words come pouring
out. ``Atlas Shrugged'' is finished in a blink.
</P>
<P>
   Ayn and Nathaniel prove quite a team, for a while, anyway.
Besides their workouts (more often than twice a week, thank you),
he's soon running the Nathaniel Branden Institute, which makes lots
of money from Ayn's reflected glory.
</P>
<P>
   But the film makes clear that Nathaniel's a bum, not worthy of
the trust put in him by either woman, both of whom he betrays.
</P>
<P>
   His life is so complicated that when another lover, Caroline
(Sybil Temchen), asks in yet another bedroom scene, ``What if she
finds out?,'' Nathaniel asks, ``Who?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mirren, so adept at mixing tough and vulnerable in ``Prime
Suspect'' on television and in other memorable roles, would seem an
ideal choice to play Rand, whose photographs captured the kind of
steely bearing this actress has perfected. But her Rand seems just
plain nutty.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda can't save the day. But he can make it more interesting.
His portrait of a strapping man who's withering inside is quietly
moving. Toward the end, when Nathaniel tells poor, drunk Frank that
he's sorry for the way things worked out, Fonda replies softly: ``I
am, too, Nathan. I'm really very sorry.'' Pause. ``For you.'' That
perfect instant between ``sorry'' and ``for'' is just the kind of
breath that this suffocating film desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE PASSION OF AYN RAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Branden. Christopher Menaul, director; Peter Crane and Linda
Curran Wexelblatt, producers; Ron Orieux, director of photography.
Music by Jeff Beal. Irwin Meyer and Marilyn Lewis, executive
producers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Helen Mirren (Ayn Rand), Eric Stoltz (Nathaniel Branden),
Julie Delpy (Barbara Branden), Peter Fonda (Frank O'Connor), Sybil
Temchen (Caroline), Tom McCamus (Richard), Don McKellar (Alfred),
David Ferry (Interviewer), Donald Carrier (David), Hamish McEwan
(Henry), Elyssa Livergant (Naomi), Chris Marren (Aaron) and
Jennifer Gould (Janet).
</P>
</TEXT>
