<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     05-27 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S AT THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend.
Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``BESIEGED,'' &LR;  starring Thandie Newton and David Thewlis.
Directed by Bernardo Bertolucci (R, 92 minutes). Like all
Bertolucci's films, the love story of an expatriate African woman
(Ms. Newton) fleeing an oppressive military regime and the
reclusive British pianist ( Thewlis) for whom she works as a
housekeeper in Rome is a visual jewel. Based on a short story by
James Lasdun, ``Besieged'' is a film of few words and powerful
images. (Especially of a military coup in an impoverished African
country.) The love is sealed through an extraordinary act of
self-sacrifice and a deepening appreciation of each other's tastes
in music. If this elliptical movie leaves too much unsaid, it has
strong understated performances by its two stars (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``COOKIE'S FORTUNE,''  &LR; starring Charles S. Dutton, Glenn Close,
Patricia Nel, Julianne Moore and Liv Tyler. Directed by Robert
Altman (PG-13, 118 minutes). What a treat. The sweet assurance and
guerrilla wit of Altman's vintage ensemble films make a copacetic
return with a Southern small-town black comedy. Seamlessly made and
completely enveloping, it tells of the machinations set off when a
wealthy old woman (Ms. Neal) outrages her diabolically genteel
niece (Ms. Close) by committing suicide. As the old woman's dearest
friend and the niece's unwitting nemesis, Dutton is rock solid and
appealing. The entire cast works on a single wavelength as Altman
makes the most of a well-woven screenplay by Anne Rapp (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS,''  &LR; starring Elodie Bouchez and
Natacha Regnier. Directed by Erick Zonca (R, 113 minutes; in French
with English subtitles). In this very special French film about two
freewheeling young women, their turbulent friendship is frayed by
sexual passion and economic realities. The weaker and more
head-turning of the women (Ms. Regnier) falls for the advances of a
rich nightclub owner, while her fiery friend, played with
unforgettable immediacy by Ms. Bouchez, rages against what she
views as imminent disaster. In the process, Zonca shows astonishing
acuity in observing how the women's diverging values affect every
aspect of their lives. A rare and wrenching drama (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``EDGE OF 17,''  &LR; starring Chris Stafford and Tina Holmes.
Directed by David Moreton (not rated, 100 minutes). It's 1984 in
Sandusky, Ohio, and Eric (Chris Stafford), a skinny, fresh-faced
high school student who worships the Eurythmics and Culture Club,
has his first homosexual experiences. This is not boy-meets-boy
(Romeo meets Romeo and they fall madly in love) but boy is used and
confused and tries to go straight by sleeping with his former
girlfriend. The teen-age coming-out story is realistic but
warmhearted, the best among the recent gay coming-out films
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``ELECTION,''  &LR; starring Matthew Broderick and Reese
Witherspoon. Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the
acerbically funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic
satire of the American electoral process in a high school setting.
Its leading candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms.
Witherspoon, has a mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from
Connie Chung and Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless
good-guy teacher who thinks this wicked little front-runner needs
to be stopped. And the hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's
reluctant opponent in a style best described as early Keanu. With a
lovely ear for hypocritical conversation, the screenplay
specializes in keeping all the characters a few beats off what they
actually mean (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``ENTRAPMENT,''  &LR; starring Sean Connery and Catherine
Zeta-Jones. Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy
caper summons the days when being a thief was the profession of
choice among debonair movie heroes. And heroines: as the
great-looking insurance investigator who is supposedly
investigating Connery's glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones
makes a smashing gymnast and heist expert in her own right. No need
to believe the outlandish details of the story; there's enough
verve and charisma to the stars to make the escapade easy on the
eyes. The action sequence, in which the stars hang off the side of
the world's largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper. And
here's a nice bonus: nobody gets killed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE LOVE LETTER,'' &LR;  starring Kate Capshaw, Blythe Danner,
Ellen DeGeneres, Tom Everett Scott and Tom Selleck. Directed by
Peter No-sun Chan (R, 88 minutes). Cathleen Schine's whimsical
romantic novel about a summer affair between a divorced bookstore
owner (Ms. Capshaw) and a college student half her age ( Scott)
bleaches out pungent ruminations on May-September love in favor of
a bland cuteness. The teeny-weeny story revolves around an
unaddressed, unsigned love letter that floats into people's lives
and recharges their romantic fantasies. The dialogue is flat, the
level of the acting grade-B sitcom (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE MATRIX,''  &LR; starring Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne and
Carrie-Anne Moss. Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120
minutes). The time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will
be all but incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the
film borrows unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with
a big debt to ``The X-Files'' in the paranoia department. But the
storytelling is intricately bizarre and the special effects are
indeed special, notably when it comes to midair martial arts with a
gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows that you can look like a
Prada model while behaving like an action hero. One of the main
stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive cinematographer. He and the
Wachowskis provide a couch-potato epiphany: while the characters
seem to be performing marvelous feats, they're often lying
stock-still in the grip of virtual reality (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM,''  &LR; starring Rupert Everett,
Calista Flockhart, Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer and Stanley
Tucci. Directed by Michael Hoffman (PG-13, 115 minutes). This is
potluck Shakespeare, with a wildly uneven range of performances and
no clear style holding them together. Rather than wonder why the
actors are wrestling with bicycles in 19th-century Tuscany (a
setting used much less enchantingly than it might have been), it's
best to focus on the most comfortably Shakespearean performances
and not wonder what Ms. Flockhart is doing here. Kline makes a
perfect Bottom, Everett slinks seductively through Oberon's role
and Ms. Pfeiffer makes an appropriately gorgeous fairy queen. The
younger cast members are largely used as window dressing for the
Leo-Does-Romeo set (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE MUMMY,''  &LR; starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes). More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent
spoof (very loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror
classic), overloaded with cheesy special effects, suggests an
unwieldy hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and
Costello Meet the Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.'' The
intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that
carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the Foreign Legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed
English librarian) and John Hannah (as her twitty older brother).
It's all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve swarming
scarabs who burrow under the skin and do awful ``Alien''-like
things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE''  &LR; (the Oscar winner for best film, best
original screenplay, best art direction, best costumes and best
comedy score). Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow (the
best-actress winner) and Judi Dench (best supporting actress).
Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily
literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise that only
gets better as the film unfolds. The screenplay, originating as
Marc Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard into
razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his ``Rosencrantz and
Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine whatever it likes about
the link between Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad
yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile, this
tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an Elizabethan theater
fraught with the same backbiting and conniving we enjoy today and
has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo and Juliet,''
glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous
duo, and she gives the first great, fully realized starring
performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,''  &LR; starring Liam
Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd. Directed by
George Lucas (PG-13, 132 miutes). Stripped of hype and breathless
expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy surprise:
it's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and
offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions
that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of
``Jurassic Park.'' While the human stars here are indeed reduced to
playing action figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and
hordes of crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in
Lucas is given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier
and scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,''  &LR; starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Dame
Maggie) who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously
relish chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted
from a chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of
English expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War
II. Dame Maggie, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of
the pack, nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are
shattered when the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves
carted off to another city where they are held under house arrest.
Cher is her usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving
wealthy American heiress and art collector who befriends the group
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THIS IS MY FATHER,''  &LR; starring Aidan Quinn, Moya Farrelly and
James Caan. Directed by Paul Quinn (R, 120 minutes). Made with
obvious sincerity, this story of a glum Chicago schoolteacher (
Caan) in search of his more interesting Irish forebears ( Quinn)
involves a third Quinn brother as well. And Declan Quinn's
cinematography adds warmth to an atmospheric, sentimental tale
featuring stellar Irish actors (Stephen Rea, Brendan Gleeson, Colm
Meaney) in cameo roles. Aidan Quinn's sturdy performance, as a
lonely farmer in love with a fiery young lass from a prosperous
family, does a lot to help the film override its hackneyed elements
and keep it moving (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``THE WINSLOW BOY,''  &LR; starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon
and Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played with
unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it works
as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family of a
cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the consequences of
that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography is beautifully
lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch acting style sets
the film's tone and gives her suffragist character a sharp edge
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
