<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-JOHN-HURT-RECALLS-ALIEN-ART-ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 STOMACH-TURNING: JOHN HURT LOOKS BACK ON `ALIEN' AT 20 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JUNE 7, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of John Hurt in
the classic film, ``Alien.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Squish! Splat!
 &HT;    It hurts just to think about the infamous chest-bursting scene
in Ridley Scott's 1979 sci-fi favorite, ``Alien.'' So gross and
horrifying was John Hurt's convulsive demise, so genuine were the
terrified reactions of co-stars Sigourney Weaver, Tom Skerritt, Ian
Holm and Yaphet Kotto, that it remains the film's signature scene,
one of the most indelible in movie history.
 &HT;    ``I remember shooting that scene, vividly,'' Hurt says by
telephone from his home in Ireland. ``I was doubled over on the
table, then they cut away _ and when they cut away I went through a
hole in the table and (fake) legs were built on, so the prop guys
could fiddle around with the little creature.
 &HT;    ``It was not very high-tech.''
 &HT;    Hurt chuckles.
 &HT;    ``A lot has been said about the other actors not knowing what
would happen,'' he says. ``Of course they knew, but they didn't
know there would be caps to splatter the blood around.
 &HT;    ``Ridley had four or five cameras on everybody to capture the
moment in closeups and two-shots,'' the actor adds. ``So a lot of
it was done in one shot. I, of course, couldn't see very much.''
 &HT;    Hurt admits he had no idea that ``Alien'' _ basically a
haunted-house flick set in outer space _ would emerge as a classic,
popular enough to merit Fox Video's current release of a gussied-up
20th-anniversary edition on video and DVD, featuring a new
documentary and deleted footage.
 &HT;    ``You don't think like that,'' he says. ``You hope that
something will be successful. You don't realize while making
something that it will become a classic in its own vein.
 &HT;    ``Ridley had a very, very real approach to `Alien,''' he adds.
``It was not just a formula film, but an original piece with an
original concept and an original design.''
 &HT;    Scott's concept and H.R. Giger's legendary designs made
``Alien'' even tougher to make than the usual science-fiction film.
 &HT;    ``I don't think sci-fi is ever an easy shoot for an actor,''
Hurt says. ``And Ridley at the time was not that easy to work with.
He's gotten a lot better with actors over the years, but at that
time, if you asked him a question, he'd hide behind the camera.
 &HT;    ``And I say this all very lovingly, because Ridley is a
remarkable director.''
 &HT;    Hurt has not seen ``Alien'' in its entirety since 1979, nor has
he caught the last two sequels. He did, however, check out James
Cameron's 1986 blockbuster, ``Aliens.''
 &HT;    ``It was a good film, but it was of a different genre,'' Hurt
says. ``It was an action-adventure, which is completely different
from `Alien.'''
 &HT;    The Oscar-nominated actor surprised many by spoofing his
``Alien'' death scene in Mel Brooks' 1987 comedy, ``Spaceballs,''
easily eliciting the biggest laugh in that movie.
 &HT;    ``Mel didn't have to twist my arm,'' says Hurt, who had already
worked for Brooks in 1981's ``History of the World, Part I.'' ``It
sounded like a good joke, and I was into it.
 &HT;    ``Mel said, `We'll put you up at a nice hotel. It'll be a bit of
fun,''' he recalls. ``When I got on the set I realized that, if he
hadn't gotten me, the whole scene wouldn't have played for
anything. They'd spent a lot of money on that set, and they needed
the original guy.''
 &HT;    Though best known as a serious actor for his work in 1978's
``Midnight Express'' and 1980's ``The Elephant Man,'' Hurt has
turned up in several sci-fi films, from the forgettable
``Monolith'' to Roger Corman's deliciously bad ``Frankenstein
Unbound'' and the much better ``Contact'' in 1997.
 &HT;    Still, he says, most sci-fi doesn't excite him.
 &HT;    ``As a spectator, I am not fond of the genre,'' he says.
```Alien' had something really original about it, as I say, which I
liked a lot. `Contact' was conceptually interesting.
 &HT;    ``Every now and then something does come up, and I'll quite
enjoy it.''
 &HT;    In other words, if a script for a certain sequel dropped onto
his desk ...
 &HT;    ``Alien 5?'' Hurt says. ``It would have to be a very, very
expensive rebirth.'' 
 -0- 
 SIDEBAR: DENISE CROSBY HOSTS TREKUMENTARY  
 &HT;    Can't get into ``The Phantom Menace,'' but need an otherworldly
fix? Want to meet the kind of creatures that even Qui-Gon Jinn
would blink twice at?
 &HT;    Then line up for ``Trekkies,'' a documentary about ``Star Trek''
fans. Co-produced and hosted by former ``Next Gen'' cast member
Denise Crosby, it's in theaters now.
 &HT;    ``A lot of people who aren't `Trek' fans are enjoying the
movie,'' Crosby says. ``They're so curious, amused and interested
in the phenomenon.
 &HT;    ``They're discovering that some of the cliched images of `Trek'
fans aren't necessarily true, that not every `Trek' fan is a
basement-dwelling geek with no life,'' she adds. ``In that sense,
the film is re-educating people.''
 &HT;    Crosby and director/editor Roger Nygard whittled 35 hours of
footage into 90-plus minutes of conversations with ``Trek'' talent
from Leonard Nimoy to Kate Mulgrew, from makeup artist Michael
Westmore to historian Richard Arnold _ and visits with Trekkies, as
the film calls them.
 &HT;    Among the fans interviewed are an Orlando dentist with a
``Trek''-themed office, a Boston-based would-be veterinarian whose
cats wear Dr. McCoy uniforms, Starfleet-uniform-wearing Whitewater
juror Barbara Adams and a California man contemplating surgery to
give him Vulcan ears.
 &HT;    Some diehard fans claim that ``Trekkies'' mocks them. Crosby,
who lives in Los Angeles with her husband and year-old son,
disagrees.
 &HT;    ``I don't know how anyone could say that,'' she says. ``I'm not
editorializing _ the fans are speaking for themselves. I think it's
pretty evenhanded.
 &HT;    ``There's plenty of room to mock fans,'' she admits. ``They're
an eccentric, obsessive bunch, as anybody would be if they have
such fanaticism about something. That's an easy jab, to make fun of
people _ which is exactly what I did not want to do.
 &HT;    ``If people say I'm mocking `Trek' fans, they've got a
problem,'' she concludes. ``Nobody could please them.''
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Ian McDiarmid, Emperor Palpatine in ``Return of the Jedi,''
reappears for ``The Phantom Menace.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Trekkies,'' consult the film's
official Website at www.trekdoc.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
