<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAKLAND-BROWN-HNS &LR;      05-27 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAKLAND-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERRY BROWN PITCHES OAKLAND TO DEVELOPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Like singer Wayne Newton, Oakland Mayor Jerry
Brown was in Las Vegas and had a song to sing.
</P>
<P>
   His tune was not aimed at the lounge lizards of Caesars Palace,
but to the world's largest conference of shopping center developers
and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   It went something like this: Come to Oakland/The rents aren't
high/Crime is down/Downtown's on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're pitching Oakland as the place for retail
development, especially downtown,'' Brown said Wednesday. ``We want
to bring back the retail splendor that once was the hallmark of
Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Council of Shopping Centers conference in Las
Vegas may not be everyone's idea of a picnic, but it's exactly the
kind of event Brown must attend to realize his vision of a
revitalized downtown.
</P>
<P>
   To lure 10,000 new residents to downtown, as Brown has promised,
there will need to be shops, restaurants, movie theaters. And that
means persuading sometimes reluctant investors and developers to
put money into the dilapidated but improving city center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tell people why, in this age when urban living is
enjoying a renaissance, Oakland is a dramatic opportunity for the
creation of housing and for the creation of retail,'' said Oakland
Councilmember John Russo, who joined the mayor for the day-long
trip to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Russo, who has been to the conference the past four years, says
interest in Oakland has steadily risen. This year, the main
attraction was the new mayor, a former governor of California and
three-time candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just stopped and looked at him. They wanted to talk to
him,'' Russo said. ``It creates contacts we need.''
</P>
<P>
   But the city's strongest sales pitch may be the increasingly
inflated rents in San Francisco and other parts of the San
Francisco Bay area, which have made Oakland more attractive to
businesses and residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market dynamics are just right,'' said William Claggett,
executive director of the city's Community and Economic Development
Agency. ``Oakland is sitting in the catbird seat for the region
because we have an advantage in terms of rents and also an
advantage in that we are relatively underserved by retail
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Over several decades, city officials have watched retail
projects go to the suburbs or to other are cities, such as
Emeryville, that have been more aggressive in seeking out
developers to build major shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Oakland has been perceived by some as not
particularly development-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast hosted by city officials on Wednesday, City
Manager Robert Bobb told 150 people at the conference that
developers who hit bureaucratic roadblocks should contact his
office.
</P>
<P>
   The new administration would be a ``more entrepreneurial
government,'' he vowed.
</P>
<P>
   To show its business-friendly side, a half dozen city officials
staffed a booth on the convention floor. The effort was noted by
writers of the trade publication, Shopping Centers Today.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland ``hopes to sell developers and retailers on its downtown
area, which has rebounded strongly after `hitting rock bottom'
following the 1989 earthquake,'' says the on-line version of the
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in a speech at the Wednesday morning breakfast, promised
that the city would continue to reduce crime and streamline its
permit process.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said it was too early to announce any new agreements.
He met with officials from The Gap, Sears and Target, and said he
made progress with mega-developer Forest City Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very bullish on urban centers and they like
Oakland,'' Brown said of Forest City. ``They're going to be
visiting us in the next 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   John Protopappas, an Oakland developer, praised Brown for
understanding that developers won't come to Oakland out of a sense
of duty or generosity, but only if they can earn a better rate of
return than elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry respects capital,'' said Protopappas, president and
chief executive officer of Madison Park REIT, which is renovating
the Tribune Tower in Oakland. ``He's in a position where he can say
(to developers), `We're not going to be easy on you, we want you to
develop aesthetically pleasing projects. But we want you to earn a
return.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
