<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3617 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY28-COX     05-27 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History lives as Pensacola celebrates its past and future
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ De Luna has landed.
</P>
<P>
   The cry will go out June 5 during the 50th anniversary Fiesta of
Five Flags as locals re-create the arrival of Don Tristan de Luna
in 1559 on these shores.
</P>
<P>
   The explorer had been commissioned by the Spanish king to
establish a colony. But within two years, after suffering a
devastating hurricane followed by a yellow fever epidemic, de Luna
and his men abandoned the Panhandle settlement.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that St. Augustine _ founded in 1565 by Pedro
Melendez de Aviles _ has the distinction of being the oldest
permanently occupied European settlement in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Pensacola is no also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   Civic pride compels Marshall Emerson to point out that Pensacola
retains the claim of ``the first attempt'' at a permanent
settlement in North America, predating both Jamestown and St.
Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Nature wasn't cooperative,'' says Emerson, a museum
education specialist with the Historic Pensacola Preservation
Board, a state agency that oversees the Historic Pensacola Village
and T.T. Wentworth Jr. Florida State Museum. ``In 1698, they tried
again (to colonize), and it took.''
</P>
<P>
   Since de Luna planted the Spanish standard in 1559, five flags _
Spanish, French, British, American and Confederate _ have flown
over the city that takes its name from the Choctaw word for ``Bread
People,'' Panzacola.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the first Fiesta of Five Flags was staged to celebrate
the city's colorful heritage. This year's event, June 2-12,
includes re-enactments, a treasure hunt, sand sculpture, parades
(boats and floats), concerts, the crowning of a royal court,
fireworks and an exhibit of costumes and memorabilia from five
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The event goes into high gear June 3, when the Fiesta Forces
``capture'' public officials, local business people and media
personalities and hold them hostage until the city ``surrenders to
a week of fun and frivolity'' during festivities in Seville Square.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to visit here during a festival to appreciate
the city's dual commitment to past and future.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the once-neglected downtown has been revived
with trendy boutiques, art galleries and restaurants on Palafox
Street _ the main north-south corridor _ and surrounding streets.
The restored 1925 Saenger Theatre on Palafox hosts name
entertainers and touring Broadway musicals. Just north of the
Saenger is the Civil War Soldiers Museum, which highlights
Pensacola's role in the conflict. And the Bayfront Auditorium on
the pier at the end of Palafox will have a new neighbor within a
year: the Palafox Pier development, with restaurants, shops and a
marina.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a small-town feeling permeates this city of 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot like the old Florida I grew up with,'' says
Bruce Fender over waffles at the Pensacola Victorian Bed and
Breakfast. The Miami native, who lives in Forest, Va., was
celebrating his 25th wedding anniversary with his wife, Zoraida.
</P>
<P>
   A thriving arts community is anchored by the Pensacola Museum of
Art and the Pensacola Cultural Center, home of the Pensacola Little
Theatre. Next door to the museum is the Quayside Art Gallery,
featuring hundreds of works by regional artists on three floors.
Smaller galleries, such as the Adams Street Gallery in a historic
house overlooking Seville Square, are dotted throughout town. The
Seville Dinner Theatre stages Broadway musicals such as
``Nunsense,'' the current show, in the old post office on East
Garden Street. Plus, there's a ballet, opera company and symphony
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something to do,'' says Terance Johns, a native
who returned home to create the Orpheus Vocal Consort. ``The
community has been very receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best deal in town is a 25-cent trolley ride that
includes a narration by a driver-conductor as it loops through the
city. I hopped aboard one of the old-fashioned green trolleys
driven by Jerry Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago,'' Cooper says, ``downtown Pensacola was, uh,
not too pretty. They've really turned this downtown into a nice
area. Pensacola is going through a transition. There are people who
don't want it to change; but it's going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   I end my rolling tour where I began, across from the T.T.
Wentworth Jr. Florida State Museum, which houses such Ripley-like
oddities as a petrified cat and a shrunken head. But there are also
exhibits showcasing ongoing excavations of colonial fortifications
and a hands-on children's area called Colonial Kidstown, featuring
a kid-size representation of Fort Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and historic village _ a nine-square-block area
flanked by Plaza Ferdinand and Seville Square _ lie in the heart of
the Seville Historic District. During the Summer Open House on June
5, admission is free. Throughout the summer, the village buzzes
with costumed interpreters and craft demonstrations such as candle
dipping, gardening and bread baking at the outdoor beehive oven.
</P>
<P>
   Twice-daily guided walking tours of the village include stops at
three houses: the 1805 Lavalle House (a Creole cottage), 1871 Dorr
House (a two-story Greek Revival home overlooking Seville Square)
and 1890 Lear-Rocheblave House (a folk Victorian home decorated to
reflect its days as a boardinghouse in the 1920s). Currently being
renovated and not open for visitors, Christ Episcopal Church,
established in 1832, is the state's oldest church building. Tours
begin at the Tivoli House, 205 E. Zaragosa St., at 11 a.m. and 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also tour two village museums in historic warehouse
buildings. The brick Museum of Commerce holds a reconstructed 1890s
streetscape with a collection of horse-drawn buggies and a trolley
car. The Museum of Industry depicts major early industries,
including fishing, brickmaking, railroad and lumber.
</P>
<P>
   I found it helpful to visit the Pensacola Historical Museum on
East Zaragosa Street before touring the village. Exhibits in this
small museum trace the history of the area from the Indians of
10,000 B.C. to the present. Artifacts from archaeological digs
conducted by the University of West Florida and Historic Pensacola
reveal how people lived between 1752 and 1821. You can see the
excavation sites on a self-guided tour of the Colonial
Archaeological Trail in the historic district. Pick up a brochure
at Tivoli House.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the white-sugar sands and emerald waters of Pensacola
Beach are what lure you to the area, spend a day in town to explore
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Like de Luna, you'll find that it's quite a discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Celebration
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 3: ``Fiesta Surrender of the City'' at 7 p.m. in Seville
Park. Concert by the show band Mr. Big follows. Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 5: A Spanish Mass at 11 a.m. at the historic St.
Michael's Catholic Church downtown.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 5: The landing of de Luna will be re-created at Pensacola
Beach. The celebration begins with the Fiesta Boat Parade, which
departs from the mouth of Bayou Chico at 2:30 p.m. At 4 p.m., de
Luna lands at the Quietwater Beach Boardwalk. At 4:30 p.m., de Luna
proceeds to the Boardwalk amphitheater, where Chief Mayoki, his
queen and tribesmen greet the invaders. Dance and music
performances.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 5: The Wentworth opens the 50th anniversary exhibit
featuring a half century of Fiesta costumes and memorabilia. $6
(includes admission to historic village).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 6: The Fiesta Sand Sculpture Contest is held near the
Pensacola Beach Pavilion. Registration begins at 9 a.m.; judging
begins at 2 p.m. Free to enter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 7: The Fiesta Days Celebration, a black-tie event at the
historic Saenger Theatre, features a Las Vegas-style revue.
Tickets, $37.50, include food, drink and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 10: The Grand Fiesta Parade winds through downtown
beginning at 7 p.m., with a procession of clowns, costumed
celebrants, animals, marching units and gaily decorated floats.
Finale: fireworks over Pensacola Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 12: The Krewe of Lafayette parade, a lighted procession
through downtown, begins at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 12: The Pensacola Twirlers Square Dance Club holds its
annual Fiesta dance at 7:30 p.m. at the Sanders Beach Recreation
Center. $6 per person. 850-934-0574.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 south to Montgomery, then follow I-65
to Exit 93 and take U.S. 31 south to U.S. 29 to I-10. Go east on
I-10 to I-110, then south into Pensacola. It's about a five-hour
drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Staying over: I stayed at the Pensacola Victorian Bed and
Breakfast, 203 W. Gregory St., within walking distance of downtown
attractions and restaurants. Innkeeper Barbee Major's hearty
breakfasts include egg-based casseroles, waffles and a wonderful
broccoli and chicken quiche. Rates $80-$150. 1-800-370-8354 or www
</P>
<P>
   .pensacolavictorian.com. (There are several other inns and
hotels in or near the historic district; the Pensacola Convention
and Visitors Bureau at 1-800-874-1234 can help with
accommodations.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining:
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Manatees: Go for coconut shrimp served with an orange
marmalade dipping sauce, preceded by a crisp green salad with
homemade raspberry vinaigrete dressing and topped off with a slice
of Key lime cheesecake. If the weather's nice, eat on the deck
overlooking the marina and dine to the sounds of squawking sea
gulls and piped-in reggae. 619 S. Palafox St. 850-434-0001.
</P>
<P>
   Dharma Blue: Try the Salmon BLT sandwich, served with a green
salad and pasta salad, on the lunch menu. The creamy Key lime pie
is rich and tangy. 300 S. Alcaniz St. (porch and sidewalk seating
overlooking Seville Square is available). 850-433-1275.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Bennett's Restaurant and Wine Bar: The name is a hybrid of
Frank Sinatra and Tony Bennett. I sampled two house specialties:
the Diana Salad (romaine and spinach with sun-dried tomatoes,
pecans, blue cheese crumbles and Dijon-Gorgonzola dressing) and
horseradish-encrusted grouper over mashed red bliss potatoes. 25 S.
Palafox Place, 850-435-0930.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  City of Five Flags Trolley Co.: The 45-minute loop runs 7
a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays-Fridays; a 15-minute version is offered 4-6
p.m. weekdays and 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Saturdays. No service Sundays.
850-595-3228 or www.ecat.pensacola
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Historic Pensacola Village: Open 10 a.m.-4 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays. $6 adults, $5 senior citizens and military
personnel and $2.50 ages 4-16. 850-444-8905 and
www.dos.state.fl.us/dhr
</P>
<P>
   /pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola Historical Museum: Open 9 a.m.-4:30 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays. $1. 115 E. Zaragosa St. 850-433-1559.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Evenings in Old Seville Square: Free concerts under the leafy
live oaks Thursdays through Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Pensacola Convention and Visitors Bureau,
1-800-874-1234 and www.visitpensacola.com; and Fiesta of Five
Flags, 850-433-6512 and www.fiestafiveflags
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
