<HEADER>
A3619 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAJUN-SURVIVAL     05-27 0208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAJUN-SURVIVAL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cajun country survival kit
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are my recommended, must-bring items, based on several
trips made without them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lip balm. Your burning mouth will thank me after a pile of
spicy boiled crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Moist towelettes. Yes, there are bathrooms in Cajun
restaurants, and in some places, hand-washing sinks in the dining
room, but sometimes you just want to freshen up midway through a
table-load of boiled seafood. And they're great when you're eating
boudin in the car.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More clothes than you think you'll need. You will sweat. You
will splatter crawfish juice on yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Suntan lotion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bug spray.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A cell phone or lots of quarters. I can't emphasize this
enough: Call places before you head out to be sure they are open.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Antacid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cajun Country Guide'' (Pelican, $17.95), by Macon Fry and
Julie Posner. This is one of the best guide books I've ever used
and by far the best one on this region.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
