<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3621 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAJUNTOUR2NDTA     05-27 1899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAJUNTOUR2NDTAKEJ-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Voorhies likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   Abbeville
</P>
<P>
   The swamp tour returns you to Lafayette in time for lunch. Drive
south 30 miles on U.S. 167 to Abbeville, home of the coldest,
cleanest, biggest raw oysters in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   There are several places to get oysters in charming Abbeville,
including Black's, Shucks! and Dupuy's. We went to Dupuy's _ open
since 1887 _ ordered two dozen and soared into oyster ecstasy.
Order as many as you can eat: They are a steal at $4.25 a dozen _
at least $2 less than in New Orleans. Dupuy's also has good gumbo
and crispy, freshly made onion rings.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with cold oysters and greasy rings, wander around the
picturesque town square and have a look at the Steen Syrup Mill
(119 N. Main St.) with its giant ''cans'' of syrup outside. There's
a lovely old cemetery across the street.
</P>
<P>
   On your way back to Lafayette, you could stop at either
Vermilionville (318-233-4077) or the Acadian Village
(1-800-962-9133). These model Cajun villages are right next to each
other off U.S. 90 near the airport and offer a glimpse of life in
19th-century Acadiana. Also nearby is Lafayette's Acadian Cultural
Center (318-232-0789), similar to the one in Eunice, except this
one focuses on the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Prudhomme's Cajun Cafe, Carencro
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, I recommend Prudhomme's Cajun Cafe (318-896-3646),
due north of Lafayette on I-49. It's a little overpriced and not
everything is divine, but the deep, dark roux of the gumbo and the
homemade jalapeno cheese rolls are worth the seven-mile drive out
of Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back into Lafayette, take a turn around the dance
floor at Prejean's (318-896-3247), on the I-49 service road and
clearly visible on the east side of the highway. This cavernous
Cajun dance hall and restaurant is a little touristy, but the music
is authentic and the dancers enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   El Sido's, Lafayette
</P>
<P>
   You're not ready for bed yet, are you? Wind up the night at El
Sido's, a zydeco dance club (1523 Martin Luther King Drive, 318-
235-0647) a very short drive from Bois des Chenes. Zydeco is the
black Creole version of Cajun music, and the main way to tell the
difference is that zydeco bands include someone with what looks
like a washboard against his chest that he scratches with spoons or
bottlecaps. The rhythm of zydeco is different too, but I'll leave
that to you to study. (Be sure and call ahead to see if a band is
playing.)
</P>
<P>
   El Sido's is a nondescript place _ a large room with a long bar,
lots of tables, and space in front of a raised stage for dancing _
but the people-watching is fun. The night we went, Roy Carrier and
his band were playing and there were many older couples, some quite
dressed up, dancing close during the slow songs and sitting through
the fast ones.
</P>
<P>
   DAY THREE
</P>
<P>
   Henderson
</P>
<P>
   During crawfish season, which runs from late January until
mid-summer, I eat crawfish at least once a week. But the ones
shipped to New Orleans look like fire ants compared to those the
Cajuns save for themselves. The meat in the tails can be as big as
your thumb. And the heads, for those of you who suck them, and you
know who you are, are full of juicy, spiced-up fat.
</P>
<P>
   It seems every time we visit a ''boiling point,'' as boiled
seafood joints here are called, we proclaim the crawfish the best
yet. But three places stand out: Hawk's in Rayne, west of
Lafayette; Crawfish Town USA in Henderson; and the Guiding Star,
between New Iberia and Opelousas. Two of these could be hit in Day
Three.
</P>
<P>
   Start at Crawfish Town USA (318-667-6148), at exit 115 off I-10
a few minutes east of Lafayette. It may look like a tour-bus
magnet, and it is, but this place has crawfish big enough to last a
round or two in a ring with a small lobster. My husband doesn't
think they are spicy enough, but they make up for that by being
incredibly sweet and succulent.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martinville
</P>
<P>
   Next, drive west on I-10 a bit further and exit at Breaux Bridge
and head south. You will wind up on La. 31, a pretty, winding road
that will take you by the Bayou Teche, a narrow waterway named for
the Indian word for snake. You will pass through Breaux Bridge,
which is home of the Crawfish Festival every May, and St.
Martinville and New Iberia.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martinville, a beautiful town once called ''Little Paris,''
has a Cajun attraction almost as famous as Fred's. In the ''Cajun
Country Guide'' (Pelican, $17.95), this attraction is labeled
''Guys Under the Oak,'' and that's just what it is. The Romero
brothers are two retirees who have spent the last decade sitting
beside the Bayou Teche by the famous Evangeline Oak tree, singing
traditional Cajun songs in French and English and telling tales of
local history. I was expecting to find these ''guys'' sort of
silly; instead, I was completely charmed by them. Don't forget to
tip them, and don't try to see them on Sundays _ they'll be in
church.
</P>
<P>
   I took a look around the Old Castillo Hotel (220 Evangeline
Blvd., 1-800-621-3017) _ a steal at $80 a night for a large,
charming room with French doors onto a second-floor gallery
overlooking the Evangeline Oak and the Romero brothers. The hotel
has a restaurant as well.
</P>
<P>
   New Iberia
</P>
<P>
   But don't settle in until you drive on a little further on La.
31 to New Iberia. Be sure to find East Main Street, which is one
way, and travel its length. It has at least a dozen lavish old
homes and a cute downtown. Take a tour of Shadows on the Teche on
East Main Street (offered 9 a.m.-4:30 p.m. daily, $6;
318-369-6446). It is an 1834 plantation home which has 40
trunks-worth of family artifacts here and there.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan of mystery writer James Lee Burke, you know
that his protagonist, detective Dave Robicheaux, lives and works in
New Iberia. Burke himself splits his time between here and Montana.
Drop by Books Along the Teche, (110 East Main St.; 313-367-7621)
and you can pick up a free, self-guided tour of Robicheaux's New
Iberia.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for some more crawfish? Of course you are _ it's not like
they have them in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Drive out of New Iberia, find U.S. 90, and head north about four
miles. Look on your right for the Guiding Star Restaurant
(318-365-9113), a squat, windowless cinderblock building with a
shooting star painted on the outside. Inside are rough-hewn wooden
chairs and newspaper-covered tables, industrial hand-washing sinks
in the corner, and a jukebox stocked with Cajun and zydeco hits.
This is the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   But please, a moment of silence for the crawfish. They are
obscenely large and covered in Tabasco mash _ the crushed peppers
left over after the Tabasco plant on nearby Avery Island makes a
vat of hot sauce. The crawfish, and the boiled crabs, will fill you
up and dirty your shirt and make you a happy soul.
</P>
<P>
   DAY FOUR
</P>
<P>
   Joe's ''Dreyfus Store''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant, Livonia
</P>
<P>
   I have saved the best day for last. Begin with lunch in Livonia,
on U.S. 90 between Opelousas and Baton Rouge, about an hour from
Lafayette. The only reason to come here is Joe's ''Dreyfus Store''
Restaurant (504-637-2625), but I would drive all day to come here
again.
</P>
<P>
   And the drive itself is interesting: U.S. 90 is a classic old
highway with rundown truck stops and retro neon signs, but with the
added attraction of swamps and bayous running alongside the road.
</P>
<P>
   A large, comfortable room that looks like the general store it
once was, Joe's serves food as good as anything I have had in New
Orleans. We began with a link of perfect boudin served with, of all
things, sweet, sticky pepper jelly. Then, I had Oysters Grand
Central _ cooked in a lemon-butter sauce and served in a French
bread boat that made me want to run around the block a few times
and order it again.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien Point Plantation,
</P>
<P>
   Sunset
</P>
<P>
   Next, drive west on U.S. 90 toward Opelousas and then south on
I-49 to the Grand Couteau/Sunset exit. Go west and follow the signs
to Chretien Point Plantation (tours daily, $6.50; 1-800-880-7050),
hidden at the end of a narrow blacktop that winds between sugar
cane fields. Built in 1831, it is an elegant, two-story brick
residence with Tuscan columns and a wide upstairs gallery with
wicker furniture. There are lots of good stories here: The
staircase in the back was copied for ''Tara'' in ''Gone With the
Wind,'' and the house was damaged by a Union cannon during the
Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien Point is a bed and breakfast: Rooms are $110-$225 a
night, which includes a tour, breakfast and use of the pool and
tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Couteau
</P>
<P>
   Drive back toward the interstate and go under it on La. 93 into
Grand Couteau, a picturesque little wide spot in the road with
historic homes and the Sacred Heart Academy and Convent
(318-662-5275), the oldest school west of the Mississippi. This
stunning place was the sight of the only Vatican-sanctioned miracle
to occur in the United States. The shrine where the miracle took
place _ I'll just tell you there were some visions and a curing _
is free and open to the public, but call ahead. Tours of the school
and convent are available for $5. Again, call ahead.
</P>
<P>
   My real reason for steering you to Grand Couteau is, of course,
food. A new restaurant called Catahoula's (1-888-547-2275) has
commanded attention with nouveau Cajun cooking and a sleek, modern
interior. Named for the Louisiana state dog _ images of whom are
among the wonderful photographs on the walls _ Catahoula's is,
excuse me, howlingly good. The grilled gulf shrimp with three
roasted pepper sauces and a sauteed black bean cake was a grand
start. I followed that with a quail with an apple, sausage and
pistachio stuffing, and somehow saved room for a seven-layer
chocolate cake, one layer of which was pure caramel.
</P>
<P>
   Opelousas
</P>
<P>
   Time to groove off those calories at Slim's Y-Ki-Ki, about 20
minutes away in Opelousas (Route 167 North; 318-942-9980). This is
the state's most popular zydeco dance hall, and I had one of my
favorite evenings here. Call ahead and make sure a band is playing
_ one usually is on Fridays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone dances with everyone here. My husband watched as I went
off with three different strangers, none of whom flirted or even
asked my name. They just wanted a dance partner.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chretien Point is very nice, if you don't want to drive
back to Sunset, stay instead in Opelousas at the Estorge House Bed
&AMP; Breakfast (318-942-8151), just a few minutes away from Slim's.
This is one of the best B&AMP;Bs I've stayed in anywhere in the South.
Not only is it a beautiful house furnished with very fine antiques,
it is also home to a very friendly hostess, Sherl Picchioni, who
cooks up a sensational breakfast, leaves a rose on your pillow at
night, and is a wealth of knowledge about the home and its past
inhabitants. Don't miss the tour, included in the price of the
room.
</P>
<P>
   POSTSCRIPT
</P>
<P>
   One last piece of advice: When visiting Cajun country, don't try
to do too much each day. Set aside time to sit by a bayou and watch
the water loll by, or linger over a plate of crawfish long after
the last tail has been cracked. And leave any big-city, modern
inhibitions at home: Talk to people, dance with them, share a beer
or a meal with them. This is a place where talking to strangers is
not only OK, it's expected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
