<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKE     05-27 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SELLING OF A LEGEND OF DECOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most of us missed the party of the century: Carlos de
Beistegui's masked ball in Venice in 1951, the first truly
flamboyant fete after the Second World War. Guests donned elaborate
18th-century Venetian costumes and masks and congregated via
gondola at Beistegui's Palazzo Labia on the Grand Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Beistegui, a famous esthete, designed individual uniforms for
all the staff, as well as his own outrageous costume as a
``procurer of the Republic of Venice,'' which he wore standing on
stilts.
</P>
<P>
   The evening was recorded in ``Fetes Memorables (Legendary
Parties) 1922-1972,'' a 1986 book by Prince Jean-Louis de
Faucigny-Lucinge. ``It was a total fantasy,'' said Roger Prigent,
now a Manhattan antiques dealer, who attended the ball to
photograph it for Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Guinness, who accompanied his American friend Daisy
Fellowes to Venice in 1951, recalled that ``Beistegui became a hero
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Beistegui is back in the news.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, from Wednesday through Sunday, Sotheby's France and
the Paris auction house Poulain Le Fur will sell the contents of
the Chateau de Groussay, Beistegui's house in the village of
Montfort l'Amaury, 30 miles southwest of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The seller is his nephew, who inherited the property when
Beistegui died in 1970 and who is selling the house as well. Art
collectors, dealers and interior designers are making a beeline to
the auction because they know it will be the last time they will
see its decor in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house is a dream,'' Prigent said. ``It's a pity it's being
sold. The French government should have bought it and made it part
of the Musee des Arts Decoratifs.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Sotheby's has organized the sale and prepared the
four-volume catalog, Poulain Le Fur will conduct the auction
because French auction houses still have a monopoly on running
sales in France.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will be held on the grounds of the chateau, whose
buildings, park and 18th-century-style follies were classified as
historic monuments by the French government in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's predicts that the auction _ 2,000 lots of furniture,
paintings, drawings, sculpture, porcelain and works of art _ will
realize $16 million. Others say the total will be higher.
``Groussay is the kind of sale where the whole is greater than the
sum of the parts,'' said Tony Victoria, the New York antiques
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about furnishings, not furniture,'' said Mindy Papp,
another New York dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Aslet, the editor of Country Life, wrote in the catalog:
``The Chateau de Groussay occupies an almost legendary place in the
history of decoration. Not because of its fame, but legendary
because of its status as the only surviving masterwork of a man who
was consumed by a passion for creating the settings amid which his
life took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Prigent was unequivocal: ``Beistegui was the greatest decorator
of the century. It is he who was the inspiration for Renzo
Mongiardino and Alberto Pinto.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Cheneviere, a London dealer who specializes in
18th-century Russian antiques, said that Beistigui ``was more of a
decorator than a collector,'' adding, ``He was an extravagant man
who lived in a spectacular way.''
</P>
<P>
   Beistegui (1894-1970), always known as Charlie to his friends,
was born into a Spanish family that had settled in Mexico at the
end of the 18th century. The family made its fortune there in
silver, but left Mexico after the execution of the Emperor
Maximilian in 1867.
</P>
<P>
   Though the family had Spanish passports, when Beistegui was
born, his parents were living in Paris. He was eventually sent to
Eton, where he wrote a volume of poetry he illustrated with his own
drawings. He was about to attend Cambridge when World War I broke
out. He then joined his parents in their mansion on the esplanade
of Les Invalides.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Mexican who thought he was an Englishman who was
living in France,'' Prigent said.
</P>
<P>
   Beistegui's interest in design dates to the 1920s, when he asked
Le Corbusier to create a penthouse for him. But Beistegui did not
love the ultra-modern space that resulted and became disenchanted
with modernism.
</P>
<P>
   He decorated the modern duplex with Baroque antiques and highly
decorative objects. One ``surtout,'' ornamentation for a grand
dinner table, is an 18th-century-style Nymphenburg porcelain
pyramid to which he added four antique blackamoor archers, much to
the consternation of Corbusier.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of his roof garden shows a carved oval picture
frame that was set outside to frame the glorious view of the
Champs. In 1939 he bought Groussay, a country house that had been
built in 1815 for the Duchesse de Charost. He spent the rest of his
life transforming it into a pleasure palace with help from his
friend Emilio Terry, a Cuban-born architect based in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Because he carried a Spanish passport, the Germans did not
bother Beistegui during World War II. He spent the war decorating
and entertaining a small band of friends including Daisy Fellowes,
Cecil Beaton and Christian Berard.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite room was the two-story library. The sale includes
an Italian bronze gueridon in the Empire Style dating from around
1820 whose specimen marble top has a micromosaic head of Medusa
(sale estimate: $80,000 to $128,000) and an English oval convex
mirror from the early 19th century surmounted by a gilded set of
arms (estimate: $12,800 to $19,200).
</P>
<P>
   A handsome rare Louis XVI ``table a la tronchin,'' named after a
Swiss doctor who thought it was healthier to read standing up, is
made in plum pudding mahogany and is signed by Feuerstein
(estimate: $32,000 to $40,000).
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Salon has a pair of bronze-mounted white Meissen
porcelain pots-pourris circa 1750 (estimate: $128,000 to $192,000)
and an ebony and gilt bronze writing desk from around 1770 with
spiral-turned legs, which Sotheby's attributes to Rene Dubois, a
royal cabinetmaker who is considered a pioneer of the Louis XVI
style (estimate: $240,000 to $320,000).
</P>
<P>
   The Billiards Room has two impressive, massive mahogany desks,
including a cylinder desk with gilt bronze mount of circa 1785 made
by a Russian follower of the cabinetmaker David Roentgen (estimate:
$160,000 to $192,000). The Yellow Salon has a big, colorful
Savonnerie carpet, circa 1790, designed with Pompeian motifs
(estimate: $160,000 to $240,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very like an English country house, with staggeringly
wonderful objects,'' recalled Kenneth Winslow of Butterfield's, an
Englishman who spent three days there at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   In the catalog, Aslet wrote: ``How was it possible for him to
have created a work of such sumptuousness at a time when almost
everyone else in the country was suffering the privations of war?
It is tempting to imagine that Beistegui conceived Groussay as an
essay in the arts of living, created at a time when the
civilization in which he believed seemed about to succumb to
barbarians.'' It is an essay worth reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
