<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      05-27 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As American As, Well, Sex
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Forget that George Lucas film!
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely as it seems, the movie that has the town buzzing is an
oddball, funny, charming and sometimes gross comedy, ``American
Pie.'' The film, about teen-agers in the Middle West who are
struggling to inaugurate themselves into the ways of sex, marks the
feature-film debut of its screenwriter, Adam Herz, and its two
director-brothers, Paul and Chris Weitz. Only Paul gets the
director's credit on the film, because the Director's Guild is
extremely reluctant to give two people such billing).
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opens on July 9, has been welcomed in early
screenings by mostly younger audiences. Studio executives around
town expect it to emerge as the sleeper hit of the summer, even
with a mostly unknown cast. But Universal, the studio that made it,
seems to be befuddled about it; the studio sold off rights to the
$11 million film in many foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, if not bizarrely, the movie has had rating
problems. The Motion Picture Association of America, which has
given extremely violent films an R rating, said at first that the
jokey sex talk and situations deserved a far more prohibitive NC-17
rating, which bars anyone under 17 from seeing the movie and
severely limits its distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back to them four times,'' Chris Weitz said. After
several editing trims, the ratings board reluctantly gave the movie
an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Weitz brothers themselves have a somewhat elite pedigree _
they are third-generation Hollywood _ although the film itself is
about as elite as ``There's Something About Mary,'' with which it
may be compared. The brothers' grandfather was the famous agent
Paul Kohner, who represented John Huston, Billy Wilder and Ingmar
Bergman. Their parents are the actress Susan Kohner and the fashion
designer John Weitz. Paul Weitz, who is 33, graduated with a film
degree from Wesleyan University, and three of his plays _ ``Mango
Tea,'' ``Captive'' and ``All for One'' _ were produced Off Broadway
by the Ensemble Studio Theater just as he left college.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Chris, 29, earned a bachelor's and master's degree
in English literature from Cambridge University in England, and
worked as a freelance journalist there. He then decided to join the
United States diplomatic corps. Although the State Department
accepted him, there was a one-year wait. So he began writing
comedies with his older brother, and the two have never looked
back.
</P>
<P>
   Their early scripts, which opened doors in Hollywood and led to
several years as script doctors, included a comedy about a porn
director trying to make a legitimate movie, as well as a take-off
on buddy cop movies whose lead role was, of all things, a
nonviolent Hindu detective. They also collaborated on recent
screenplays, including the animated film ``Antz'' and the
children's movie ``Madeline.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``American Pie,'' the brothers were given the script by
the producers Warren Zide and Craig Perry, who are also talent
managers representing, among others, the screenwriter, Herz.
Despite the inexperience of the Weitz brothers, Zide said their
vision of the film was appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted adults to see this movie, too, and say how much it
reminded them of their high school years,'' Zide said. ``And our
goal was to appeal to girls as well as guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Paul Weitz said: ``The issue of female sexuality is
just not explored in the canon of high school sex comedies. But
girls are as curious as boys. Why not deal with that?''
</P>
<P>
   The two said their childhood had given them a sense of
wonderment about film directors because they met so many of them.
On one occasion, they went to the circus in New York with Ingmar
Bergman. In Los Angeles, they said, they often go to a revival
house to see Billy Wilder and John Ford films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tend to think about the oldies more than a lot of
people our age,'' Chris, left, said. Paul added, ``A lot of younger
people here aren't aware that there were great writers and
directors doing this years ago, and there was actually a world
before `Armageddon,'''
</P>
<P>
   The movie itself deals with a group of seniors at a high school
in Michigan who are desperate, in one way or another, to discover
sex. The boys are as hopelessly inexperienced and anxious as the
girls and endure numerous sexual mishaps and humiliations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our personal experience was not quite the same, except for the
extreme humiliation and total inability we had in dealing with the
opposite sex,'' said Paul, who attended the Collegiate School in
New York. His brother attended schools in London.
</P>
<P>
   But reluctantly the brothers did acknowledge similarities
between themselves and the boys in the film. In a scene near the
movie's opening _ one of the more benign scenes _ a boy is found by
his father watching a scrambled porn channel on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll cop to that,'' Chris said. ``Anything more extreme I
absolutely deny. You'll have to go to my brother for that.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother laughed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lemmon as Darrow &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spans 50 years, Jack Lemmon, a two-time Academy
Award winner, has played a dizzying number of film roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``First I was typecast as the comedic lead, the boy next door,''
Lemmon said. ``That was a long period for me. Then `The Days of
Wine and Roses' and `Save the Tiger' got rid of that. From that
time on, I got a lot of dramatic parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a lot of roles, but the thing that's eluded me so
far is playing a cop,'' he said. ``I don't know why I've never
played a serious role as a cop. In `Irma La Douce,' I sort of
played a cop, but that wasn't serious. I'd love to play a cop, a
detective.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon, 74, will have to wait just a little longer. He is to
appear as the Clarence Darrow figure in the drama ``Inherit the
Wind,'' on Showtime on Saturday at 9 p.m. The play, written by
Jerome Lawrence and Robert E. Lee, was a Broadway success in the
1950's during the McCarthy era when it had unmistakable relevance.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it was a fictionalized version of the Scopes
``monkey trial'' 74 years ago, in which a Tennessee schoolteacher
was prosecuted for teaching Charles Darwin's theory of evolution to
students. The trial pitted the Presidential nominee, Bible scholar
and orator William Jennings Bryan against the nation's most
celebrated defense lawyer, Clarence Darrow. In the current
production, George C. Scott plays the Bryan character, and Beau
Bridges enacts the role of a reporter who in real life was H.L.
Mencken.
</P>
<P>
   The drama itself deals with religious fundamentalism, the
unbridled power of the media and, to some degree, mass hysteria.
Lemmon said, ``It's really about freedom of speech, the freedom to
think and express yourself in whatever way you want, the fact that
you can't throw someone in jail just because they're teaching
something you don't particularly like.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon said he had wanted to work for years with Scott, his
longtime friend. Last year the two appeared in the ensemble
television production of ``Twelve Angry Men'' on Showtime. This led
them to try to revive ``Inherit the Wind,'' which was also an
acclaimed 1960 Stanley Kramer film with, among others, Spencer
Tracy, Fredric March and Gene Kelly. It was remade in 1988 for
television with Kirk Douglas and Jason Robards.
</P>
<P>
   Why the continuing interest in the drama?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolutely beautiful play,'' Lemmon said. ``The words
are gorgeous. And those parts _ they're terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon acknowledged that he had been fortunate over his enduring
career to have so many terrific parts. His most memorable ones, he
said, included Ensign Pulver (an Oscar-winning performance) in
``Mister Roberts''; the alcoholic in ``Days of Wine and Roses'';
the troubled businessman in ``Save the Tiger,'' another
Oscar-winning role, and a salesman in ``Glengarry Glen Ross.'' He
also cited his roles in the Billy Wilder films ``The Apartment''
and ``Some Like It Hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon said that he was being offered roles as a grandfather now
but that he wanted to reach beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to be a kindly old grandfather,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the most important advice he ever got came decades ago
in New York from a Broadway character actor, Myron McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just done `Mister Roberts,' and I was pretty full of
myself, and I walked into Sardi's, and I saw Myron there,'' he
said. ``After a while he said, `Let's take a walk up the street.'
So I'm walking with Myron, my old buddy, and I'm talking nonstop
about me and ` Roberts,' and I just don't shut up. And finally he
stopped and said: `I'll bet we just passed about six young actors
since we left Sardi's, and all of them could have played Pulver
better than you. But you got the part.' And he just kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' Lemmon said. ``And he was right. There'll
always be someone who's as good as you or even better who didn't
get the part. But you did. And you're the lucky one. And don't
forget it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
