<HEADLINE>
A DAVID PORTRAIT IN WILLIAMSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Sterling and Francine Clark Art Institute in
Williamstown, Mass., is unveiling its latest purchase Friday:
Jacques-Louis David's ``Portrait of the Count Henri-Amedee de
Turenne,'' from 1816. Not only is this the Clark's first painting
by David, the French neo-classicist, but it has not been publicly
seen for more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Count de Turenne was an important officer in the French Army
who served as First Chamberlain to Napoleon. He was made a count of
the Empire in 1813 and led the retreat at Waterloo a year later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1816 David painted the count's portrait and in a letter said
he was ``amusing myself making easel portraits of M. le Comte de
Turenne ... who is passionate for the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   David's records show that this is the first of two portraits he
made of the Count. The second, a three-quarter-length painting, is
in the Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that the Clark had been aggressively buying important
Old Masters recently, Etienne Breton, a Parisian dealer who is a
partner in the firm of Marc Blondeau, heard that the painting had
become available and contacted Michael Conforti, director of the
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was last seen in 1878 in an exhibition in Paris,'' said
Conforti. ``No photograph of it was ever published.'' The portrait
had, until now, remained in the sitter's family in a country house
in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relates very well to our collection,'' said Conforti. ``We
have a Goya portrait and Jericho's `Trumpeter of the Hussars.' And
being able to get an unpublished portrait by David that is of equal
quality was both a surprise and a unique opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim at 9
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheim visitors are early risers. Every morning museum
officials have noticed lines forming outside its Frank Lloyd Wright
building on Fifth Avenue, as crowds wait for the doors to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a substantial number of visitors from Europe who wake
up early,'' said Judy Cox, one of the Guggenheim's deputy
directors. So the museum will wake up early, too, opening at 9,
instead of 10. The change is to take effect on June 4, opening day
for ``Surrealism: Two Private Eyes, the Nesuhi Ertegun and Daniel
Filipacchi Collections.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum will still close at 6 p.m. on Sunday to Wednesday and
at 8 on Friday and Saturday. But the Guggenheim's SoHo branch will
not open earlier, Ms. Cox said, because downtown visitors tend to
show up later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are not the only change at the Guggenheim. Its stationery
and logo have been redesigned, too. ``We're trying for a consistent
graphic identify,'' said Ms. Cox. Now all the Guggenheims around
the world will have the same logo, but each with the word
Guggenheim in a different color: In New York it's a bright red, a
favorite shade of Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim in the Peggy Guggenheim Collection in Venice is
green; Deutsche Guggenheim Berlin's is blue, and at the Guggenheim
Bilbao in Spain it's a metallic silver. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change at Artist's Space &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Gould has resigned as director of Artist's Space, the
nonprofit institution in SoHo, after five and a half years.
Beginning on Sept. 7 she will become director of the Institute of
Contemporary Art at the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I'd done everything I could,'' she said. ``We're
on sound financial footing, having raised $1.2 million of an
endowment campaign.'' The institution has also just received a
$71,500 matching grant from the National Endowment for the Arts for
its own endowment.
</P>
<P>
   And it has just published a book, ``5,000 Artists Return to
Artists Space: 25 years.'' Meanwhile, Virginia Cowles, chairwoman
of the Artist's Space board, said, the museum was in the process of
forming a committee to look for a new director.
</P>
<P>
   Topkapi Treasures
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of treasures from the Topkapi Palace in Istanbul
will travel to three American museums next year.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring art and objects from the royal home of the Ottoman
sultans, ``Palace of Gold and Light: Treasures From the Topkapi,
Istanbul,'' will first open at the Corcoran Gallery of Art in
Washington on March 1, then go to the San Diego Museum of Art and
the Museum of Art, Fort Lauderdale, in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by the Palace Arts Foundation, based in Washington,
the show is to include more than 200 objects. ``This show sums up
everything the Ottoman Empire was in its heyday,'' said Walter
Denny, a professor at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst
who has been an adviser to the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's highlights are a famous emerald and diamond
Topkapi dagger and an imperial throne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
