r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEMORIAL-DAY-COMPASSI     05-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-DAY-COMPASSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEMORIAL DAY TRIBUTE TO MY DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    TIVERTON, England _ At a time when the daily diet of news and
information is about war, hatred, crazed murders of schoolmates and
all the vile things we human beings are capable of doing, it is
good to be reminded that we can also be kind, helpful and
considerate. And how important that is to a whole society.
 &HT;    I suppose goodness isn't news because we like to think it can be
taken for granted. Still, when you see it, when you feel it, when
it is part of a country's image of the self it wants to be, it
evokes a feeling of gratitude. In this sense, England did well for
my Sheila.
 &HT;    For all the anti-welfare rigors of Thatcherism and planned
constraints of Prime Minister Tony Blair's ``third way,'' Britain
still can offer remarkably kind, effective care to those who are
suffering. It makes an enormous difference. To those who become
aware of it, it colors a whole society with a glow of warmth and
decency.
 &HT;    My daughter Sheila Gruson died last week, after living in
England for more than 15 years. She had breast cancer, and after a
year or so of the usual treatment which had no useful effect, she
began to need special care. When she broke her leg, because the
cancer got into some bones, the social services loaned crutches and
brought equipment into her home to help with getting in and out of
the bath and using the toilet.
 &HT;    Volunteers were organized to pick up her daughter (my
granddaughter) and take her to the school bus stop in the morning
and bring her home in the evening while Sheila was unable to drive.
Nurses visited Sheila at home and supervised the pain relief which
doctors ordered.
 &HT;    At the end, which suddenly went very fast, she was taken to the
Marie Curie Cancer Care Hospice in Tiverton, Devon, and was looked
after with gentle, dedicated attention focussed on making sure that
she suffered as little as possible. There are 11 such centers in
Britain and they are totally admirable, without the intimidating,
sterile atmosphere of a hospital and with rules that can take
account of the ill person's family and friends in a way that
hospitals cannot.
 &HT;    They do not charge at all, existing on a combination of public
funds and donations, and they spend less than hospitals do. When I
stopped by before leaving England to thank the nurses for their
understanding, soothing care, the Home Care Sister who had been
assigned to Sheila told me, ``We are very good at what we do.'' Her
name is Anne Hunneyball, a large, comforting woman who joked, ``We
have broad shoulders.'' She is completely right.
 &HT;    The Center is due to close in October for lack of funds, a
dreadful shame because it performs such a well-organized, necessary
service. My daughter, who had convalesced there after the operation
on her leg, knew about that and told me she was glad the place was
still open when she needed it.
 &HT;    We buried her near the town of Watchet, in Somerset, where she
and her daughter had lived before moving to Tiverton. The place was
called the Woodland Burial Ground, recommended by a funeral home
called Green Undertakings, and it is acutely sensitive to
environmental needs.
 &HT;    It is on a green hillside with a magnificent view of the rolling
valley and wildflowers in the fields. Trees are planted at the
gravesites and there are no headstones, only flat markers in the
ground. There is nothing morbid. There is rather a consoling sense
that death is part of nature too, and can be accepted as the needed
completion of nature's cycles, though it doesn't feel natural for a
parent to survive her child.
 &HT;    I won't go on much about Sheila here. She was a generous,
intensely intelligent, artistically talented, passionate person who
drew people to her and enhanced the lives she touched. But I was
moved by the outpouring of emotion from her friends and neighbors
and the feeling that there really was some community for her in
England, although they all had come from very different
backgrounds. It seemed that they really do care about each other
and the simplicities of love.
 &HT;    The health service, the social services, which make sure that
the society provides concern for all are crucial to that
willingness to leave none out. There is a point beyond which
individual enterprise, initiative and self-responsibility just
can't meet the human need.
 &HT;    Britain gains by the assurance that it is determined to go
beyond that point when it is required; other countries might well
take it as an example of decency and compassion, which are never
out of date.
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
