<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A summery weather pattern will spread over a large part of the
nation during the next few days as the jet stream continues to
retreat north into southern Canada. Areas of substantial rainfall
will be confined to clusters of thundershowers which will roam near
the Gulf of Mexico and across parts of the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   After a cool dawn, a strong warming trend will begin over the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic states. Sunshine will be plentiful in
most areas, however, a few widely separated showers will develop in
New England during the late part of the day Friday and Friday
night. Little or no rain is expected during the next few days which
will exacerbate the unusually dry conditions which are beginning to
develop across these regions.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of clouds and scattered thundershowers will surround a
wavering front that separates humid air near the Gulf of Mexico
from drier air to the north. A few strong afternoon thunderstorms
will erupt in Florida where converging sea breezes force sultry air
to rise rapidly. Meanwhile, the interior Southeast and much of the
Middle West will be dry and warm under the influence of high
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will form during the warmth of the
afternoon over parts of the southern Rockies, especially where
breezes ascend the sloping terrain in eastern parts of Colorado and
New Mexico. Farther north, a moisture-starved cold front will
produce some clouds and isolated showers near the mountains of
western Montana and eastern Idaho. In the wake of the cold front,
the Northwest will be windy with ample sunshine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Lightning and Cars
</P>
<P>
   An automobile is not immune to being struck by lightning. On
Wednesday, lightning struck a car in Bexar County near San Antonio,
Texas. One person was killed, though the exact cause of death was
not known. Yet a car is one of the safest places to be in a
thunderstorm if taking refuge inside a building is not feasible.
When lightning strikes a car, electricity is conducted along the
car's metal skin. It then typically harmlessly jumps to the ground
or flows through the tires to the ground. The notion that tires
ground a car and thus prevent a car from being struck by lightning
is false.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
