<SLUG> BC-IMPRESSIONISTS-WINTER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRESSIONISM'S ICY BEAUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Think of the Impressionists, and chances are you
think green (or possibly pink, or lavender, or bluebird-blue in the
case of Monet). They were painters of lawns, hedges and fertile
fields, of a deciduous nature caught at full leaf.
</P>
<P>
   But like artists anywhere with rents to pay and mouths to feed,
they were year-round workers. And inevitably winter landscapes,
quickly brushed in the frosty open air or caught through the glass
of a studio window, figured in their repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionists in Winter: Effets de Neige,'' which opens
Friday at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, brings together some 60 such
paintings. And if ever a show were tailor-made for summer viewing,
this one is. It's of perfect, modest, untaxing size. It has been
installed with plenty of elbow room to spare. And its deep-freeze
images of snow-covered fields and ice-caked trees are the visual
equivalent of air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Impressionism needs a promotional hook. It has long
since been a shrink-wrapped cultural fixture and box-office gold.
And like any critic-proof phenomenon, it provokes its share of
resentment. Even this show's dutifully descriptive catalog ventures
a note of pique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most Impressionist paintings,'' one writer says of a
certain Monet, ``it asks nothing of the viewer, which is very
likely the reason it is so appealing to modern audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Impressionism may not demand much, but there's no question that
it offers a broad audience substantial rewards. Through a
material-rich, instantly recognizable painting style, it turns
everyday life into something exotic. Suburbs became mini-Edens.
Urban smog has a pulverized radiance. Workaday pleasures _ a
country walk, a spin on the dance floor _ assume a vibrant glamour.
</P>
<P>
   This is an art that projects a direct, uncomplicated sort of
beauty. It is Romanticism with the prickly bones removed, Realism
with fabric softener added. And, perhaps most important, this
beauty is dynamically theatrical: it delivers its full impact only
when experienced live.
</P>
<P>
   Hold a postcard of any Impressionist painting up to the original
and be prepared to wonder how on earth photography could get color
so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   All of which brings us back to this very beautiful show, which
was organized by the Phillips Collection in Washington and
coordinated in Brooklyn by Elizabeth Easton, the museum's curator
of European painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Seven brand-name artists are included: Monet, Pissarro and
Alfred Sisley are each represented by several works; Gauguin and
Gustave Caillebotte by a few, and Cezanne and Renoir by one apiece.
The work has been arranged more or less chronologically, beginning
with a very early snowy landscape _ or ``effets de neige,'' as the
motif was called _ by Monet, done in 1865 when he was living in
Honfleur.
</P>
<P>
   Monet was the outdoors type; a friend once found him dressed in
three overcoats and standing at his easel in a field on a
bone-crunching midwinter day. For the 1865 painting, he planted
himself in the middle of a country road and recorded what he saw:
low-lying farm buildings, snowbanks and trees, a cart up ahead, and
a huge expanse of sky.
</P>
<P>
   But light is the real subject here. He must have been working in
late afternoon. The snow is slate-blue, soot-gray, ivory-yellow,
anything but white. The sky is a rich, custardy mix of these colors
and tones but concentrates to an opalescent glow where the sun lies
below the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   This point of banked warmth can be seen _ sensed is more like it
_ all the way across the museum's gallery. It grows intense, even
brightens and dims like a mood ring as one moves in close, though
it is almost invisible in printed reproductions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chromatic epiphanies of a similar kind abound in the show. A
nothing-special Pissarro street scene has a patch of electric Jacob
van Ruisdael-blue sky. A picture of an alley in the village of
Louveciennes by Sisley is a little chamber music ensemble of
russet, ocher and turquoise. The green-gray sky in Gauguin's ``Snow
at the Pont d'Iena, Snowy Weather'' has a scary, leaden feel like a
dark lid descending.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every painting, a stripped-down palette amplifies
individual colors and throws compositional structure into relief.
Such structure is most apparent where architecture is involved.
Caillebotte's vista of Parisian rooftops with chimney pots against
snow is an example.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Monet's wonderful ``Red Cape,'' a
frames-within-frames portrait of his wife, Camille, taking a stroll
and glancing in through a window as she passes.
</P>
<P>
   But winter makes nature itself look diagrammatic, and the
paintings reflect this. Many of Sisley's landscapes (one suddenly
sees) are geometric puzzles carefully pieced together around a
dominant foreground triangle, like his ``Snow Effect at
Argenteuil,'' with its giant, wedge-shaped shadow. And Cezanne's
single contribution, a woodland scene at Fontainebleau, is a
proto-Cubist mosaic of angles and faceted blocks.
</P>
<P>
   It is Monet, given pride of place by himself in the final
gallery, who most effortlessly blends structure and color and in
the process gives winter the metaphoric resonance that it has
always enjoyed in poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the images are pure magic. The whipped-up white tree
branches in ``Frost'' look like a species of calligraphy, with
hair-fine strokes standing out in low relief. In the celebrated
paintings of stacks of wheat, each stack sits in its snowy field
like a Technicolor muffin on a breakfast table.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the mysterious pictures of ice drifting on the
flood-swollen Seine. These date from the winter of 1879-80, a
terrible time in Monet's life. His wife had died of cancer in
September. (In the unforgettable deathbed portrait he did, which is
not in the show, her face is shrouded by a snow-white veil.)
</P>
<P>
   His work had been clobbered by critics. And even the weather was
calamitous. After record snowfalls, a January thaw sent an
avalanche of ice careening down the river, leaving destruction in
its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Monet captured the aftermath of the disaster _ of all the
disasters of that fall and winter, one is tempted to say _ in two
very different paintings, each an exercise in minimalist
compositional and expressive color. In one, titled ``Breakup of the
Ice,'' white floes lie in becalmed water. Distant trees rise above
the flood like thin plumes of smoke. The sky and its reflection are
a benumbed, depressed blue-gray.
</P>
<P>
   From that same period comes ``Sunset on the Seine in Winter.''
The trees, dashed off in fading light, seem charged with static.
Floating ice looks as weightless as mist. The colors of the sky _
hot oranges, golds, pinks _ spread through everything like a high
flush, and at the center is a thick circle of scarlet paint, the
setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   The picture drew strong reactions when it first appeared; one
critic called the depiction of the sun ``a slice of tomato stuck
onto the sky.'' Viewers today are likely to approach it in other
ways. For some it will be read as a gauge of an artist's emotional
temperature. For others, it will crystallize the classic, defining
Impressionist vision of nature caught on the fly. For still others,
it will be an image of the world both extravagantly strange and
reassuringly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   In short, more than almost any other kind of painting,
Impressionism tends to yield what is asked of it. Maybe this
explains why it has been for a century and more the attraction it
is: an art for many audiences and for all seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
