<HEADLINE>
TONY STEWART TRIES FOR TWO WINS IN ONE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Tony Stewart is going for the daily double: a
win Sunday afternoon in the Indy 500, another Sunday night here in
the Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Stewart's attempt intriguing is that he has a
legitimate chance to win both, although the odds are certainly not
in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   But his Indy car is competitive, and so is the Pontiac he drives
in NASCAR competition for Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   It is questionable, given the concentration level required now
in both types of racing, whether any driver can divide his time
between stock cars and Indy cars and make a total effort in both.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, though, shrugs that off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've driven just about every type of race car there is,'' he
said. ``Once you leave pit road, you remember what car you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has spent most of this month in a race car, about 25
days in fact.
</P>
<P>
   He came to stock cars from the Indy Racing League, which
features the Indy 500 as its top event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a young race driver from Indiana, it isn't hard for most
people to understand when I say that this is the single most
important race to me,'' Stewart said about the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could guarantee a win in any race in the world, I'd pick
the Indy 500,'' said Stewart, 28, who grew up in Columbus, about 45
miles from Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   To keep Stewart from wearing down trying to run both races,
Gibbs hired a personal trainer to work with him two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was crazy at first, but it's really worked to
improve my stamina,'' Stewart said about the trainer. ``I feel
stronger and more alert throughout a race, and I'm definitely not
as drained afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes strength training has improved his ability
to control his stock car and has helped his reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston Cup is a whole new ballgame when it comes to physical
requirements for the driver,'' Stewart said.``I went from running
1,500-pound open-cockpit Indy cars a dozen times a season to racing
3,400-pound stock cars every weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has also been on a high carbohydrate diet to build
endurance and offset the affects of traveling back and forth
between Indianapolis and Concord.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be racing to win, so there's even more reason for me to
prepare myself as much as possible, both mentally and physically,''
Stewart commented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to keep a level head, and I've got to make sure my
body holds up.''
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of the two race cars.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
