<HEADLINE>
TRANS AM UPHOLDS BAD-BOY IMAGE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, MAY 29) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Pontiac Firebird Trans Am is today's archetypal
American muscle car: loud, fast, and in your face.
</P>
<P>
   Barely acceptable in polite society, Trans Am is a survivor from
a lost automotive era, along with sibling Chevy Camaro SS and rival
Ford Mustang GT.
</P>
<P>
   Some might call Trans Am a throwback. Some might ask, ``Hey, who
said dinosaurs are extinct?''
</P>
<P>
   Even General Motors has been muttering about doing away with the
F-body cars, as Firebird and Camaro are known internally. Too
heavy, too archaic, too aggressive, just too much.
</P>
<P>
   But others still get a thrill. Few things on the planet will get
a group of teenage boys to spin around faster than the thunderous
roar from those twin exhausts. Midlife hot rodders, nostalgic for
the muscle cars of the '60s, hear the call of the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Power and sex appeal, Trans Am's got 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car was the full-boat Trans Am convertible in sinister
black with the huge, flaring nostrils of the WS6 Ram Air package,
bright 17-inch aluminum wheels with performance tires, free-flow
dual exhaust and six-speed stick shift.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's that 5.7-liter V-8 cranking out a convincing 320
horsepower and 345 pounds of pure grunt, accompanied by the
aforementioned thunderous roar. Acceleration is of the
pinned-to-your-seat variety.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, just what the doctor ordered to perk up a Sunday
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Ram Air system, by the way, boosts engine power from 305
horses and 335 pound-feet. There's also a 200-horsepower V-6
available for the thrifty sort.
</P>
<P>
   As prehistoric as it may be, Trans Am certainly has come a long
way since it wore a big screaming chicken on its hood. Recently, it
was the recipient of a cosmetic face lift and some minor
performance tweaks.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I can forgive most of its adolescent styling cues, such as
the honeycomb rear lights, figuring that it's all part of the
territory. But those big nostrils, with associated bulges that lead
up over the entire hood like big, square sinuses, are just way over
the top. Embarrassing, even.
</P>
<P>
   At least they are for this modest driver, who would like to
enjoy his midlife crisis in quiet humility.
</P>
<P>
   But once you get used to peering over those sinuses, put down
the automatic top, relax and enjoy the ride, Trans Am does exactly
what it's supposed to do. Which is: be fun. A hoot, even.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I was impressed with the power, and the enjoyable
six-speed tranny that came along with it. Six speeds? Well, one
through four are the usual driving gears, and fifth gear is the
normal .75 ratio overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's sixth gear. The ratio here is .50, meaning that
for each turn of the engine, the rear wheels spin twice. This gear
is so tall that when cruising at 75 on the freeway, the engine is
ticking over at about 1,500 rpm, just a rumble over idle speed.
</P>
<P>
   This translates to relaxed high-speed touring, and gas mileage
in the 28 mpg range. In case you're wondering why every automobile
doesn't have a similar setup, the answer is: torque. It takes the
low-end muscle of a mighty V-8 to make this system work.
</P>
<P>
   At speed with the top up, the Trans Am's cabin is quiet with
just a whisper of wind noise, a dramatic improvement over past
practice and the better to hear the fantastic optional stereo
system. With the top down, the large sweptback windshield keeps the
wind roar and buffeting to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The topless body feels generally tight and rattle-free, though
it occasionally sets up some shimmies on corrugated surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with Firebird and Camaro is the tight interior,
especially in relation to overall size. Front-seat legroom is just
acceptable, while the rear seats are a cruel joke. When they say
bucket seats in the rear, they mean it literally.
</P>
<P>
   One continuing complaint: For the past several years, the Camaro
and the Firebird each has a ridiculous hump on the passenger-side
floor. Everybody who gets in the car for the first time lifts up
the floor mat to see if I'm smuggling a meatloaf. I'm told the hump
is there to accommodate the catalytic converter below the floor.
There had to be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, handling is tight and aggressive. An improved handling
and traction-control system keeps the unwary driver out of trouble,
and does so without being overly obtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a disconcerting feel of twitchiness to the rear
suspension, as if it would like to perform some impromptu spins,
especially under braking. That's also a typical fault in this line
of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Trans Am is equipped impressively, I thought the
bottom line was way up there. There are plenty of great cars
available in the $35,000 range. And I don't think Firebird's
natural constituency is in this arena.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, once I got used to the mighty nostrils and settled
in behind the wheel, I found the Trans Am to be an enjoyable and
satisfying ride, though it takes a high level of self-control to
keep from mashing the gas pedal every chance you get. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pontiac Firebird Trans AM &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: &QL; 
Four-passenger, two-door convertible, rear-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: &QL; 
$30,245. &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$35,030. &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
5.7-liter V-8, 320 horsepower at 5,200 rpm, 345pound-feet of torque
at 4,400 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: &QL; 
Six-speed stick shift. &QL; 
Curb weight: &QL; 
3,536 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: &QL; 
101.1 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
19 city, 28 highway. &QL; 
Highs: &QL; 
Massive power. Top-down appeal. Solid structure. &QL; 
Lows: &QL; 
Big price. Big nostrils. Big hump in floor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at bob.golfen(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
