<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-SCHRADER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEN SCHRADER LOOKING TO BREAK OUT OF SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.) (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ There have been bright spots. Winning the pole
at Talladega, Ala., and finishing sixth in the April 25th race
there was one of them. But for Ken Schrader, the bright spots have
been few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor Speedway here,
Schrader stands 12th in points with three top-10 finishes. A year
ago after 11 races, Schrader was ninth in points with one top-five
and four top-10s.
</P>
<P>
   The only race this season Schrader has really been competitive
in was the Diehard 500 at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   That, though, is nothing new. For various reasons, Schrader has
been in a slide for several seasons. He has not won a race since
1991 and has not finished as high as second since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Schrader left Rick Hendrick, where he drove the
ill-fated Bud car, to go with a new team formed by Andy Petree, who
had been Dale Earnhardt's crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   If determination and drive could win races, Schrader would have
a bunch of victories because Petree has the determination and
Schrader will drive anything.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some have felt that has been one of Schrader's
downfalls. Schrader's job is driving race cars and his hobby is
driving race cars, and some think that's too much of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The move from Hendrick to Petree has not turned things around
for Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   In his third year in Petree's Chevy, Schrader has not finished
higher than third.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that's because Petree's team is still coming together.
Petree added a second car this season, driven by Kenny Wallace, and
hired Sammy Johns to be Schrader's crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   In his third season as a Winston Cup crew chief, Johns struggled
with a low-financed car owned by Buzz McCall his first two years,
but got to know Petree through a consulting agreement between
Petree and McCall.
</P>
<P>
   When McCall's team folded, Petree offered Johns a chance to take
over Schrader's car.
</P>
<P>
   The least experienced of the major players on the team, Johns
knows if Schrader doesn't do well, he could end up being the fall
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with the situation I'm in,'' Johns said. ``If
I can't get the job done, they'll let me know, and if I can't get
the job done, I'll probably be the first one to let them know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a fortunate situation with Andy Petree. He's been there
and done it. He knows what's going on and he's a honest person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not winning every week, it's tough,'' Johns said.
``Everybody who works in this sport is doing it because they want
to win races. You just have to keep coming back and do all you can
to keep morale up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team doesn't perform, there's a reason,'' said Schrader,
who's been driving full time on the Winston circuit since 1985. The
Fenton, Mo., native turns 44 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the driver and the crew chief together can't get the
job done, or the driver plain old can't drive, or the crew chief
can't make the car handle or get you in and out of the pits,''
Schrader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, the crew chief could be the scapegoat, just like the
driver could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate in having Andy as a team owner,'' Schrader
went on. ``Andy has worked with some of the best drivers. He's won
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy can't go to Andy and say Schrader can't drive the car
because Andy knows better. I can't go to Andy and tell him the car
is terrible, Sammy can't make it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate we don't have to worry about that because we
can't BS our car owner.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they can't, which gives them all the more reason to get
their car running up front.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
