<SLUG> BC-NOTTING-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANTIC STROLL UP NOTTING HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Just because Julia Roberts plays a fabulous movie star
imprisoned by her face and fame doesn't mean she's playing herself
in ``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it doesn't mean she isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Julia adds a sense of honesty to her accustomed
luminescence, which makes ``Notting Hill'' one of the most
satisfying romantic comedies in years: witty, sweet and genuine.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts plays Anna Scott, a famous movie star in London to
promote a new film. She wanders into a small bookstore run by
William Thacker (Hugh Grant), a man with considerable wit but no
prospects for career or love life.
</P>
<P>
   Anna is rather taken with the ordinariness of his life,
William's self-effacing good nature and the supportive spirit of
his down-and-out friends, who like to compete to see who has the
most miserable life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setup and the movie's previews, ``Notting Hill''
isn't one of those automatic Hollywood romances where two
mismatched beauties fall madly in passion to the accompaniment of a
musical montage.
</P>
<P>
   Director Roger Michell (``Persuasion'') and writer Richard
Curtis have a bemused sense of the difficulties of finding real
love and how easily it can slip from your grasp. They keep the film
grounded in the impossibility of a romance between a creation of
celebrity and a normal guy: Anna can't uncomplicate her life, while
William can't believe his good fortune or that he deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   Michell uses their slowly evolving yearnings to pose a number of
intriguing questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Can an ordinary man find perfect happiness with the goddess of
his dreams?
</P>
<P>
   _If it's not quite so perfect, will he care?
</P>
<P>
   _What do you say when you find a naked movie star in your
bathtub?
</P>
<P>
   _What exactly is a stunt bottom?
</P>
<P>
   Writer Curtis, who also scripted Grant's ``Four Weddings and a
Funeral,'' understates the humor in that British way. His comic
style blends smoothly with the film's halting but touching sense of
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is expressively tender in a role that obviously means
much to her, as she conveys the burden that the dream places upon
the person who must live the reality behind the fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   As she did in ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' Roberts creates not
just passion with her co-star but a sense of real affection.
</P>
<P>
   Michell and Curtis have deglamorized Julia considerably to
demonstrate that, off screen, the most beautiful actresses are not
what they're lighted up to be.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is a natural as the funny but discomfitted Englishman who
finds humor in hesitancy and self-doubt while convincing us that
much of love is based on simple human kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is an English production banking on an American
star to achieve popularity. Difficult to imagine Hollywood making a
romantic comedy this sweet, this touching and this unforced.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the movie slips up on one Hollywood cliche: Bookstore
owner has now replaced architect as the occupation of choice for
hopeless romantics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' should be equally agreeable to men and women.
While women enjoy the tenderness and humor of the love story, men
can imagine themselves in William's predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is misrated at PG-13. Although it contains no
nudity or sex, the film has ample enough profanity to have merited
an R rating. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
