<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AND CALIFORNIA COULD LOSE SOME PUBLIC TRANSIT FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York and California stand to lose millions of
dollars in federal transportation funds next year in the wake of a
Senate panel vote Thursday to cap the amount of money each state
can receive for subways and buses.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected move by the Senate Appropriations Committee drew
immediate criticism from California and New York lawmakers who
vowed they will try to reverse the funding formula.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer of
California and Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer of New
York said they will fight the mass transit provision when the $12.1
billion transportation appropriations bill reaches the Senate floor
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y., said he will work to ensure that the
provision isn't adopted in the House version of the bill. The House
has yet to take any action on its draft $12.7 billion
transportation bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures give each state funding for such transportation
projects as roads, bridges and mass transit for the fiscal year
that begins Oct. 1. The total for mass transit is $5.4 billion. The
measures also provide funding for the Federal Aviation
Administration and the United States Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new formula that the Senate Appropriations Committee
adopted Thursday for mass transit funding, California would lose
about $117 million and New York, about $160 million in fiscal 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, devised by Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., limits the
amount of money any one state may receive to 12.5 percent of the
total amount available for mass transit. Under the current formula,
New York would receive 15.5 percent of the total, or $837 million,
and California would receive 14.7 percent, or $794 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the new formula were to go into effect, both states would
each receive about $676.5 million next year in mass transit funds.
The other 48 states would receive about $5 million each in such
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his new formula, Shelby told his fellow committee
members that New York and California receive a ``disproportionate
share'' of federal transit dollars, according to a source who
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If his formula prevails, California and New York, which,
combined, now receive 30.2 percent of the total amount of federal
mass transit dollars, would be limited to a combined total of 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein noted that California and New York have almost half
the nation's public transportation riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transit is and should be a needs-based program,'' Feinstein
said, adding that the funding now ``goes to states that have the
most invested in transit and who have the most need.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney called the formula change ``unfair'' because it undoes
the existing formula that was agreed to last year ``after several
months of careful negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said he plans to ask House Transportation Committee
Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., to work to ensure that the transit
formula is not changed as the House considers its legislation.
Shuster was the chief architect of the existing formula.
</P>
<P>
   The House version of the transportation funding bill does not
change the transit formula. Any differences between the House and
Senate bills must be worked out in a conference committee of
lawmakers from both chambers before the overall measure can be
signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said the San Francisco Bay Area could lose $27 million
and Los Angeles, nearly $48 million if the Senate version of the
bill prevails.
</P>
<P>
   A Sweeney aide said the Albany, N.Y., area would be cut by about
$2.2 million in mass transit funds. The cut would be primarily in
money for bus service, the aide said. In the current budget the
Albany area received $5.7 million for mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
the email address: jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
