<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLINDLEMONJEFFERSON-T     05-27 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLINDLEMONJEFFERSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASING THE ELUSIVE GHOSTS OF DEEP ELLUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The streets of Deep Ellum are the province of rock
bands unloading their gear on the sidewalk, tony-looking couples
going into tony restaurants, college students dancing the night
away in funky clubs, suburban kids with an attitude, wearing black
T-shirts and cruising, looking to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Govenar's Deep Ellum, however, is rooted in the past and
its ghosts, which he still plainly sees: Blues pianist Alex Moore
and western swing acts playing long-gone juke joints; gospel
musician Blind Willie Johnson moaning ``Nobody's Fault but Mine''
on one corner; and legendary bluesman Blind Lemon Jefferson
standing down there on Elm Street, just east of the Gypsy Tea Room,
where cars rumble overhead on the Central Expressway overpass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the phantom presence is; it makes you wonder
what was, what life happened here that no longer exists,'' Govenar
says, as cars shoot down the off-ramp toward downtown, and a couple
of homeless guys sip from brown paper bags nearby. ``Blind Lemon
stood right about here, and when he played, people gathered around
him. He had a tremendous presence. This is the nexus of past and
present, humor and fear, life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also one of the major sources for Govenar's inspiration.
His career has included filmmaking, directing the Dallas Folk
Festival, presenting conferences on American music in Paris, and
producing numerous CDs by folk and blues artists. Through it all,
the Boston-born Govenar, 46, has returned again and again to Deep
Ellum and the music and shadowy story of Jefferson to spark his
creative imagination. This week, that imagination delivers ``Blind
Lemon: Prince of Country Blues,'' a mixture of history and fiction,
music and dance that debuts at the Majestic Theatre's Experimental
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived by Govenar six years ago and written over the past two
years with Dallas actor/director Akin Babatunde, ``Blind Lemon''
presents the legend and music of Jefferson as seen partially
through the eyes of Eli, a young, white blues researcher. We see
Jefferson in his prime, wandering the streets of Deep Ellum, and
then going to Chicago to cut the records _ among them ``See That My
Grave Is Kept Clean'' and ``Matchbox,'' the latter of which was
retooled by Carl Perkins and became a rockabilly staple.
</P>
<P>
   But we also see him as a myth, an archetype of the bluesman who
gave voice to his community and then disappeared off the face of
the earth. There is, for example, only one known photograph of
Jefferson, and the date and cause of his death have never been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   His mythical status suits Govenar and Babatunde just fine.
Govenar has been writing about the blues for years; his 1995 book
``Meeting the Blues'' was a thorough examination of the people and
forces that shaped Texas' blues sound, from Jefferson to Stevie Ray
Vaughan. This past spring saw the publication of ``Deep Ellum and
Central Track'' (University of North Texas Press), in which Govenar
and Dallas Morning News writer Jay F. Brakefield portray the
neighborhood in its wild and woolly prime.
</P>
<P>
   Babatunde, the founder and artistic director of the Vivid
Theater Ensemble, hails from Brooklyn and moved to Dallas nine
years ago. The only Blind Lemon he knew about was the
not-exactly-funky Deep Ellum bar of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   The two met through a mutual friend, and Babatunde was perplexed
about why Govenar, a white guy from the East Coast, would care so
much about a long-gone black bluesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were working on it, I kept talking to Alan about the
nonlinear aspect of the play,'' says Babatunde, who directs and
stages the play, and who enlisted gospel/R&AMP;B singer David Peaston
to play Jefferson. ``The images are flashbacks, which is what
happened to me in doing this: What was this time like?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I didn't know about him made this more
creatively engaging. For anybody who leaves the theater, we want
them to take what we think we know about the blues and go
investigate it. We want to spark the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Govenar emphasizes that Eli and his research of Jefferson are
not the focus of the play, which finds Jefferson/Peaston
encountering such people as Leadbelly and Johnson, and going to
Chicago to record.
</P>
<P>
   Because the blues is defined by the interaction of performer and
audience, Govenar says, much of the story is told through a ``Greek
blues chorus'' of various people, who at times challenge the man's
motives for investigating Jefferson's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the whole thing is a running repartee of the
ensemble _ what is true, and what isn't?'' he says. ``Why is Eli,
or anybody, doing this? Blind Lemon is the metaphor for not only
wanting to know about him but also about yourself _ the desire to
find out about more and not finding it right away. What is the
truth you find in the blues?''
</P>
<P>
   And the truth that Govenar finds, after all these years, is that
the music still speaks to him at a basic, emotional level. No, he
says, he's not Eli, not anymore. But it was that sort of quest to
understand a different culture _ and why he wanted to understand
that culture _ that fired his desire to write ``Meeting the Blues''
and do other projects related to Texas folk and blues performers.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Ellum, and by extension Jefferson himself, are the phantoms
that he has chased to find himself. And ``Blind Lemon'' is putting
that onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about the blues that makes it transcultural and
multicultural?'' he asks. ``That's the bigger question. We're just
putting that out there in this play, which I hope will be both a
touring stage show and a repertory piece for this area. Eli knows
he's dealing with the myth _ that he'll only find Blind Lemon in
his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Blind Lemon: Prince of Country Blues'' runs through June 12.
Show time is 8 p.m. Thursday through Saturday at the Experimental
Theater in the basement of the Majestic Theatre, 1925 Elm St. in
downtown Dallas; there are also 3 p.m. Saturday matinees. Tickets
are $20, available by calling (214) 515-0543.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
