</P>
<P>
   FILM-WINSLOW BOY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ When writer-director David Mamet decided to direct a
new version of ``The Winslow Boy,'' he knew what he was doing. The
material, a warhorse of a play that has been performed at many a
high school, is about the troubles that befall a privileged London
family when its honor is assaulted. Winslow, 13, has been expelled
from the Naval Academy because he's accused of stealing. The family
gives up everything _ its money, its future _ to combat the attack
on its reputation that this charge becomes. This premise doesn't
sound like something that would attract a talent like Mamet. But
Mamet embraces the squareness of playwright Terence Rattigan's
drama and improves upon it. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THIRTEENTH FLOOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ On its own terms, ``The Thirteenth Floor'' is merely
an OK time-killer, hurt by rote direction and a story arc so
familiar that the movie's surprises aren't very surprising. By
ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NOTTING HILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Notting Hill'' is a meeting of the archetypes. Even
though it's supposed to be about a man (Hugh Grant) falling for a
woman above his station, a movie star (Julia Roberts) _ like a
fable in which a mortal tumbles helplessly into love with a goddess
and then learns how dangerous such an act can be _ Grant plays it
like a movie star. A very mannered movie star, perhaps, but anyone
who's seen him in ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' or any of the
other comedies, won't be surprised. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has
moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-PRIVATE RYAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As expected, there was much wringing of hands and
gnashing of teeth when Steven Spielberg's WWII epic ``Saving
Private Ryan'' didn't walk home with a Best Picture Oscar earlier
this year. Despite the film's well-deserved statues in five
categories, including Best Director, the coveted Picture award was
considered by most critics to be a lock. I'm of two minds on the
subject, disappointed in some ways but ultimately happy with the
way things played out. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLIND LEMON JEFFERSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The streets of Deep Ellum are the province of rock
bands unloading their gear on the sidewalk, tony-looking couples
going into tony restaurants, college students dancing the night
away in funky clubs, suburban kids with an attitude, wearing black
T-shirts and cruising, looking to be seen. Alan Govenar's Deep
Ellum, however, is rooted in the past and its ghosts, which he
still plainly sees: Blues pianist Alex Moore and western swing acts
playing long-gone juke joints; gospel musician Blind Willie Johnson
moaning ``Nobody's Fault but Mine'' on one corner; and legendary
bluesman Blind Lemon Jefferson standing down there on Elm Street,
just east of the Gypsy Tea Room, where cars rumble overhead on the
Central Expressway overpass. By DAVE FERMAN. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ How's that stockpiling going? For many, that question
is a serious reference to gathering the water, food, generators and
other things needed to survive when the mother of all computer
glitches, known as Y2K, causes societal chaos come Jan. 1. For
others, the Y2K scare is a joke. They scorn the doomsday predicted
for the first day of 2000. Financial planner John Mauldin of
Arlington, Texas, suggests a middle-of-the-road approach. He says
the Y2K bug will cause severe economic woes worldwide, but he stops
short of suggesting that you stockpile toilet paper. By TERESA
MCUSIC. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Americans have a right to expect more of a candidate
for the presidency of their great nation than the kind of blatant,
petty and reckless political demagoguery that Texas Gov. George W.
Bush has spewed out in reaction to the release of the Cox report.
Glossing over the fact that the select House committee on Chinese
espionage, headed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., found that the
Chinese pilfering of U.S. nuclear and missile secrets spanned 20
years and four administrations, Bush rushed to blast ``the current
administration's failed policies toward China.'' By CECIL JOHNSON.
Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
