<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GACHET-FORGERY-2TAKES     05-27 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GACHET-FORGERY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPARING THE FAKE AND THE GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Western attitudes toward forgery have changed over
the centuries. In the 16th century, Vasari admired Michelangelo for
his ability to fake antiquities. The most famous forger in this
century, Han Van Meegeren, went to jail for painting fake Vermeers.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Vermeer partly because the public had recently begun to
admire him after centuries of neglect, and fakery thrives when
people are beginning to prize an art, a situation akin to new love.
</P>
<P>
   History being full of odd coincidences, it happens that Van
Meegeren was born roughly when van Gogh, his compatriot, moved to a
village called Auvers-sur-Oise, near Paris, where he was to be
under the care of a homeopathic physician, art collector and
amateur painter named Paul-Ferdinand Gachet.
</P>
<P>
   Gachet (1828-1909) is one of those curious figures of French
bohemia, an intimate of Courbet, the novelist Champfleury and
Baudelaire and later a friend to painters like Monet and Cezanne,
who at the time were unrecognized. He had a voracious and
indiscriminate appetite as a collector.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh described him as a strange man, a sad widower
disheartened by his medical work but excited by art. If Gachet's
name is familiar today it is probably above all because one of van
Gogh's portraits of him made front-page news in 1990 when it was
sold to a Japanese businessman for $82 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gachet tended to van Gogh after van Gogh shot himself, and
quickly removed the paintings that were left in van Gogh's room
after he died.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned Van Meegeren because the Gachet legacy, which is the
subject of a new exhibition at the Met, ``Cezanne to van Gogh: The
Collection of Dr. Gachet,'' has for decades stirred discussion of
deception and fakery.
</P>
<P>
   When the show opened in Paris a few months ago it prompted
another spate of newspaper articles. Did Gachet or his son, who was
also named Paul and was also a painter of sorts, forge pictures?
Did they, like Van Meegeren, capitalize on the public's sudden
enthusiasm for previously neglected masters, in this case Cezanne
and van Gogh?
</P>
<P>
   The questions arose because of the behavior of the son, a
recluse who spent his life (he died in 1962, at 89) tending his
father's legacy with pathological and paranoid zeal. He preserved
everything in the family house as if it were a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Only rarely did he let visitors see the collection, preventing
photographs of it. Its contents didn't become known until the
1950s, when, having discreetly sold off parts of the collection,
Paul bequeathed what remained of it to France. People inevitably
asked what, if anything, he had been hiding all those years.
</P>
<P>
   The present exhibition is considerably absorbed by these
questions. The heart of it consists of paintings (by Monet, Sisley,
Cezanne etc.) donated to France, which until now had never left the
country, supplemented by other works once in the Gachets'
possession. There are a few important paintings and some small,
pleasant surprises, like a Cezanne still life of green apples.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts have been expressed about several of the other
pictures on view, among them a spectacularly awful scene of cows by
van Gogh and a clunky still life by Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
   The curators, Anne Distel and Susan Alyson Stein, argue sensibly
for authenticity: they say Paul's secretive nature provoked
unnecessary suspicions, that good painters have bad days and that
some of the pictures are simply bad, not fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   All of which may be true, although an exhibition that in large
measure invites you to contemplate the difference between fake van
Goghs and poor van Goghs is, as you might expect, not visually
thrilling. The show has an instructive value as an exercise in
comparative viewing, along the lines of the Met's previous
``Rembrandt/Not Rembrandt'' exhibition, and this is not negligible.
But mostly it's a hodgepodge of second-rate work with a handful of
great pictures among the curios.
</P>
<P>
   We see, for example, the paintings that the Gachets signed under
their pseudonyms, Paul van Ryssel (Gachet) and Louis van Ryssel
(Gachet's son), which are, more or less, in the styles of various
artists whose works they owned: Pissarro, Armand Guillaumin,
Cezanne and van Gogh. The Gachets also copied various works they
acquired, which they clearly marked as copies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gachet's hilarious version of Cezanne's ``Modern Olympia''
belies the idea that Gachet might ever have imagined himself to be
a capable forger. You see the difference between an original artist
and an earnest dabbler paying him homage. The fact that the Gachets
made and kept copies argues against any concerted program of
deception.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a book about van Gogh that Dr. Gachet intended to
write, additional copies of the collection were made by a woman
named Blanche Derrouse, a family friend. These are in the
exhibition, too, with artifacts like van Gogh's palette and vases
and silverware that were the basis of several van Goghs and
Cezannes in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Like all relics, they have an extraordinary talismanic appeal
that often exceeds the attraction of the pictures on view. In
particular there's something about the authenticity of these
objects _ their direct contact with the artists _ that inevitably
returns a visitor to the question of the authenticity of the
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar romance of forgery will no doubt attract many
people to the show, particularly attached as it is to alluring
names like Cezanne and van Gogh. Fakes have endless popular appeal,
which supersedes any debates about a show's overall quality. And
maybe this isn't such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Forgery is a measure of our shifting values. Fakers in previous
days forged religious relics. Now we have counterfeiting of
brand-name products, like Rolex watches and Chanel bags. Does this
tell us something about ourselves?
</P>
<P>
   Whether the authenticity of the Gachets' collection will be
resolved to everyone's satisfaction will depend on whether someone
someday steps forward with irrefutable evidence. Many fakers have
become known because the faker confessed, sometimes even having to
overcome experts who refuse to believe the confession.
</P>
<P>
   Van Meegeren's fakes, which now look comically implausible, were
identified only because he was arrested in 1947 for selling art to
the Nazis. A Vermeer in the collection of Hermann Goring was
discovered to have been owned by Van Meegeren. To exonerate
himself, he had to prove that he had faked the picture by painting
a Vermeer in court.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question that everyone asks remains: What
difference does it make? If a picture is admired before it is
revealed to be a fake, isn't it still admirable afterward?
Esthetically speaking, Michelangelo's fake antiquity would be as
good as any genuine antiquity. Isn't the esthetic value of a work
finally independent of who made it?
</P>
<P>
   No. No matter how much we think art can be judged purely in
visual terms, it's a commodity. Authenticity is a measure of market
value, a peculiarly Western idea that we impose even on works from
other cultures.
</P>
<P>
   What we call primitive art, for example, may apply to an object
made not by an individual but by a group of people mimicking a form
with no thought about originality. Over the years the object may be
reworked and repaired until it is no longer recognizably what it
was, then discarded.
</P>
<P>
   But in our marketplace its value is nonetheless based on
standards of invention, individuality, authenticity and so on. This
is our way of measuring quality.
</P>
<P>
   And quality is about faith. We value a van Gogh to the extent
that we may trust it is by him. For good reason, fakery is
sometimes likened to sex: admiring a fake, it's said, is akin to
making love in the dark to someone who turns out to be the wrong
person. That is, art appreciation, on a basic level, is
transactional and not simply esthetic. It demands trust.
</P>
<P>
   Fakes loosen our foothold in reality because they mix with true
objects to infect the historical record. Sometimes, in the case of
forged documents, they can actually change history itself: the
``Donation of Constantine'' and the ``Protocols of the Elders of
Zion'' are two such fakes.
</P>
<P>
   A forged Egyptian statuette from Rhodesia that at one time was
taken as proof of Egypt's presence there changed the way history
was imagined. Likewise, as we've seen in recent books and
exhibitions, Stalin tried to alter history by eradicating Trotsky
from photographs of the Russian Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The philosopher Nelson Goodman, who died recently, wrote
influentially on this subject. He once compared the relationship
between a genuine painting and a forgery with that between an
edible mushroom and a poisonous one. To think that the difference
is merely esthetic or superficial is to be dangerously ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can either look harder for the difference,'' he wrote, ``or
avoid paintings and mushrooms entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Gachet show tells us anything, it is that even mediocre
paintings have a purpose, which is to give us a firmer grasp of
genuine greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
