<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-27 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA ADLER ON ...': VOTARY OF STANISLAVSKY AND CHAMPION OF
CHEKHOV 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an actress and, most importantly, as a teacher of acting,
Stella Adler was one of the most influential artists in the
American theater. Through her classes, she trained several
generations of actors, including Marlon Brando and Robert De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s and '80s, she gave a series of lectures to
theater professionals, and from them Barry Paris has compiled the
book, ``Stella Adler on Ibsen, Strindberg and Chekhov.'' As the
title indicates, this is primarily Adler's instructive advice on
how actors should approach roles in works by three seminal modern
playwrights. The book also serves as an introduction to Adler and
her extravagant personality. One regrets never having seen her
perform, but reading her on these writers, especially Chekhov, is
the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   She derived her realistic techniques directly from Konstantin
Stanislavsky and not from Lee Strasberg. From Adler's vantage point
as a founding member of the Group Theater, Strasberg misled actors
through his egotism and his insistence that they mine their own
experiences for use in their art. For her, the emphasis should be
on the character, not the performer, and the text of the play is
only the beginning. It is the actor's mission, as a creative
artist, to draw a full portrait, before the character comes on
stage and in terms of the physical and emotional attributes one
chooses to stress in performance.
</P>
<P>
   Forged in the heady atmosphere of her celebrated theatrical
family (whose patriarch was Jacob Adler, an actor at the pinnacle
of the Yiddish theater), she had a fierce dedication to her craft.
Harold Clurman, who was married to her for seven years, was
enraptured with her, extolling her in his book ``The Fervent
Years'' as ``a living symbol of so much I treasured in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as she approached 80 _ she died in 1992 at the age of 91 _
she was a striking woman. I remember talking to her for a profile
of Clurman I was writing. She received me in her elegant Fifth
Avenue apartment. Candlelit, it was the most theatrical of
settings, and she exuded glamour along with a kind of radiant
intelligence about theater and her place in it. In contrast to
Clurman, she was not a writer. But she gave of herself passionately
in her classes.
</P>
<P>
   As transcribed and then edited by Paris, these lectures have a
certain spontaneity _ at moments we feel as if we are in the studio
with Adler _ but they are also diffuse and repetitive. The fact
that they are undated leaves the reader somewhat adrift about
specific references. Because the book is drawn from tapes and not
from written notes, they are far removed, for example, from
Vladimir Nabokov's artfully composed classroom lectures on
literature.
</P>
<P>
   The section on Ibsen, focusing on two plays, ``A Doll's House''
and ``An Enemy of the People,'' offers insights, particularly when
she is dealing with the character of Nora, but it lacks the rigor
and acuity of Clurman's own brief critical book on that playwright.
With Strindberg, the slightest of the three entries, she strikes a
provocative comparison between ``The Father'' and ``A Doll's
House.'' The former, she says, represents ``the revolt of the male
against the tyrannical female,'' and the latter, the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   With Chekhov, she makes her most original observations. The
scene-by-scene analysis is an illuminating guide to the plays and
to the power of the playwright to reveal reality through indirect
action. For actors and directors and for theatergoers seeking a
greater appreciation of the plays, this section should be an
invaluable resource.
</P>
<P>
   That value derives from her intense love of Chekhov and her
intimate understanding of the motivations and the milieu (in
contrast to her treatment of Ibsen and Strindberg). For her, ``The
Seagull'' is very much a play about theater people. As she
discusses the relationship between Konstantin and Arkadina _ the
son's intellectual snobbishness, the mother's obsessiveness about
her profession _ she could be talking about herself and the people
she knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Konstantin and his play are a social embarrassment to
Arkadina,'' she says. ``She is irritated by the play, by his age,
by his bringing in a young pretty girl who in two years will want
to take her place.'' She continues, ``Actresses must remain the
same, and this is very annoying to the boy.'' Therefore, they are
``in eternal, psychological strife.'' Illustrating Arkadina's sense
of pride, she retells an anecdote about her own mother. When asked
by a reporter how she could have a son of 38 when she was only 48,
Sarah Adler replied, ``He lives his life and I live mine.'' Her
daughter comments, ``Very witty and very applicable.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing ``The Cherry Orchard,'' she says that the great theme
of Chekhov is ``the destruction of beauty in the world.'' With
``The Three Sisters,'' which she regards as his masterpiece, she
links Chekhov with Tennessee Williams: ``Chekhov is able in one
sentence to convey the most shattering experience _ the suffering
of having lost yourself without it being your fault.'' For her,
Blanche in the last act of ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' becomes a
Chekhovian figure: ``Chekhov says, finally you must accept your
loneliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in detail about the characters, in effect she tells us
how she would play them: Arkadina and Ranevskaya, and each of the
three sisters as well as Natasha, the ``utterly vulgar'' provincial
who assumes control of the Prozorov household. She even seems to
undertake the male roles, with a special understanding of the
various doctors who populate the world of Chekhov.
</P>
<P>
   Chekhov had, in his words, ``iron in the blood,'' the power of
survival ``in order to get past what is defeating you.'' Clearly,
Stella Adler also had that in abundance. This book offers a
sampling of the brilliance of her teaching. What is still needed,
of course, is a full recounting of Adler's extraordinary life in
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `STELLA ADLER ON IBSEN, STRINDBERG AND CHEKHOV'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Barry Paris
</P>
<P>
   323 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
