<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS SADDLED WITH SEVERAL WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ A question comes to mind after three
glorious days in the greater Tampa Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world did baseball ever decide to expand here?
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, the exorbitant $130 million expansion fee that the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays and the Arizona Diamondbacks were forced to
hand over to their eager fellow owners.
</P>
<P>
   Money is ever the driving force behind decisions made by Major
League Baseball. It's why the baseball owners are seriously
considering putting advertising on uniforms. The more money they
make, the more money they can put into player salaries, always
forgetting that it's not a lack of revenue that has created the
serious problems, but the way the rather-bountiful revenue is
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Devil Rays are in danger of becoming just another
small-market team unable to keep up with the big boys, especially
since they're stuck in the same division as the behemoth New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays are making an honest effort, having plunged into
the free-agent market to sign Fred McGriff, Wilson Alvarez, Jose
Canseco and Roberto Hernandez. General manager Chuck LaMar also has
done an admirable job putting together a strong organization with
some pretty decent young players.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a good sign that the Devil Rays are ninth in the
league in attendance, drawing 19,485 per game through 23 home
dates. That's only 1,000 or so ahead of the Kansas City Royals, not
exactly the franchise you want to be compared with these days.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays' marketing department is trying, but Christmas in
May and a Labor Day special where all pregnant women get in free
smacks more of desperation than innovation.
</P>
<P>
   One problem _ and there are many _ is that St.
Petersburg/Pinellas County (pop. 851,659) is becoming almost the
sole supporter of the team as interest in Tampa and other places
dwindles.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Vince Naimoli already has been forced to squelch a rumor
the team was thinking of moving _ where could they possibly go? _
but he did meet with St. Petersburg Mayor David Fischer and Tampa
Mayor Dick Greco about ways to drum up more support.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the efforts are directed at Tampa and Hillsborough
County, a 22-mile drive to the northeast. Many of the 830,000
residents there are unwilling to make that drive because it's too
far and _ surprise, surprise _ tickets are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Another troubled spot is an area that includes the Sun Coast
resort cities to the south: Sarasota, Bradenton, Port Charlotte and
Fort Myers, another area with more than 800,000 residents. These
should be Devil Rays strongholds, but the team can't even get their
cable games televised there.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays are on SportsChannel Florida, but cable systems
in those areas carry the Sunshine Network, which shows the
cross-state Florida Marlins. SportsChannel Florida, trying to get
Sarasota to switch, regularly runs ads in the local newspaper
advertising Devil Rays games with the plea, ``See what you're
missing?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Tropicana Field, which is not a field but a domed
stadium. Naimoli spent $60 million upgrading the place, adding a
cigar bar, a left-field upper deck known as ``The Beach'' and an
Ebbets Field-style rotunda at the center-field entrance.
</P>
<P>
   But it still is a domed stadium, and the roof is not retractable
unless the right-sized hurricane comes along. Domed stadiums, as
every other team in baseball knows, went out of style a long time
ago, but the Devil Rays are facing a 26-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is the country's fourth most-populous state, but many
residents are senior citizens on a fixed income, and two major
metropolitan areas _ Orlando and Jacksonville _ are too far away to
be of significant help to either the Devil Rays or the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoli said the Devil Rays are committed to building a
championship team for the Tampa Bay area, but this franchise is 2
years old and already in trouble.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
