</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALDER-WHITNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITNEY GIVES UP A GIFT, AND COMPETITORS BLANCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Minn., Texas)  (rk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the hammer came down on the sale of Alexander
Calder's ``Constellation'' at Sotheby's on May 18, there was joy in
the auction room. The painted wood and wire sculpture fetched $1.9
million from an anonymous private collector, more than double the
pre-sale estimate of $600,000 to $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one problem. The work had been promised to the
Whitney Museum of American Art in 1981 by its owners, Theodate and
Scott Severns. Considered to be the most sophisticated work in
Calder's constellation series, it was commissioned in 1943 by Mrs.
Severns and her brother, architect Philip Johnson, for their
Manhattan home. It is one of four Calder works in the catalog for
``The American Century: Art and Culture, 1900-1950,'' the Whitney's
current blockbuster exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   But in a move that has stunned people in the art world, the
museum has permitted ``Constellation'' to slip from its grasp. Mrs.
Severns, who is 91 and is ill, could no longer afford the gift and
asked for relief. Instead of structuring a deal that both helped
Mrs. Severns and kept the work, the Whitney decided that it could
be sold, potentially undermining the concept of promised gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets an extraordinary precedent for the diminished
importance of promised gifts,'' said a retired museum director who
insisted on anonymity. ``It means you can play with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell L. Anderson, the Whitney's director, defended the
museum's action as a necessary ``renegotiation of a promised
gift.'' He could think of no exact parallels, he said, but added
that museums have on occasion restructured pledges privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to lose the work, but over the course of 20
years things can change,'' Anderson said. ``We have a rich Calder
collection. It's a loss to us, but it's not a crisis to the
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale began several months ago when Johnson approached his
lawyer, Joel S. Ehrenkrantz, who is also the president of the
Whitney's board. Johnson told Ehrenkrantz that Mrs. Severns needed
round-the-clock care, and that she and her husband, a semi-retired
dentist who is 76, had limited financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dilemma because the Whitney had documentation of a
promised gift that it received from a donor in good faith,''
Ehrenkrantz said. ``But there's a moral issue here: how to deal
with an ill, financially needy person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrenkrantz said he discussed the situation with Anderson and
Arthur Fleischer, a lawyer who is chairman of the Whitney board's
legal and ethics committee. They decided the solution was to
establish a trust with the proceeds from the sale of
``Constellation'' and to give the Severnses the interest income for
the rest of their lives. ``The Whitney will receive the balance of
the principal when they both die,'' Ehrenkrantz said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Anderson said the board's executive committee approved
the deal without dissent. ``We will gain handsomely, financially,''
Anderson added.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum has lost ``Constellation,'' which has twice been
on view at the Whitney, in 1991 and in 1976, when as part of a
traveling show called ``Calder's Universe'' it also went to museums
in Atlanta, Minneapolis and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ```Constellation' is unique in Calder's career,'' said Richard
Marshall, an independent curator who worked on ``Calder's
Universe'' when he was employed by the Whitney. ``It's a
spectacular work, the largest and most complex wall piece, derived
from Miro's work at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at other museums, who insisted on anonymity, said
that the Whitney should have structured a different deal. The
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Contemporary Art in
Chicago have each sued to enforce promised-gift agreements, though
financial need was not a consideration in either dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Whitney ``could have bought an annuity for her
and kept the work,'' said one of the administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrenkrantz rejected the idea of an annuity. ``You don't know
how much that would come to; she might live another 10 years,'' he
said.``The museum would really be buying the object. Although the
museum really covets the work, the museum doesn't want to be in the
insurance company business.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen E. Weil, a senior scholar at the Smithsonian
Institution's Center for Museum Studies, said he was surprised at
the museum's course of action, but did not censure the Whitney.
``If the person honestly can't afford to give the gift, and the
museum found a middle way, it sounds kind of creative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in another decision that may rankle museum purists, the
Whitney's executive committee did not commit the museum to using
the money it eventually receives from the sale for acquisitions,
Ehrenkrantz said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when a museum sells an artwork, standard practice
dictates that it use the proceeds solely to purchase additional
art. While technically the Whitney is not deaccessioning
``Constellation'' _ it never formally accepted it into its
permanent collection _ the rule might still be expected to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money goes to the board to be used for board-designated
reasons,'' Ehrenkrantz said. ``The executive committee will decide
what to do with it. We said it will be up to the board at that
time, though there is strong feeling that it will be used for
acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that his solution was not desired by Mrs. Severns or the
Whitney, Ehrenkrantz called it a compromise. ``We tried to be very
compassionate,'' he said. ``The institution will never benefit as
much as it would have, but at least we'll have the opportunity to
take a substantial sum of money in the future and buy a Calder or
another work of art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
