<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDICT-REACTION-BOS &LR;      05-27 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDICT-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYALISTS STAND BEHIND MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Sitting on a plush couch in the lounge of a hotel
here late Wednesday night, Zeljko ``Arkan'' Raznatovic used a
remote control to turn down the sound of the European soccer
championship game on a giant screen and turn up the volume on a
second, smaller television tuned to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had
been indicted for war crimes, Raznatovic turned his attention back
to the soccer match, shook his head and later said, ``He is no war
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of Raznatovic, the Serb paramilitary leader, was
not surprising, given that he also stands indicted by the same war
crimes tribunal at The Hague which Thursday announced the
indictment of Milosevic and four of his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   But if Milosevic's loyalists are united in their belief that the
charges are a trumped-up political ploy, many other Yugoslavs
received the news with less defiance and more concern. Many
Yugoslavs see the indictment as ending any chance for a negotiated
settlement. They say it shows that NATO is determined to escalate
the war, and that Milosevic now has no incentive to negotiate an
end.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government was contemptuous of the indictment,
dismissing the tribunal as a NATO front. A government minister,
Goran Matic, said the tribunal is used to ``destroy the sovereignty
of countries the United States does not like.'' Matic said it was
illegal to charge Milosevic and the others with war crimes in
Kosovo because ``it is not a war. It's an operation against
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who despise Milosevic _ and believe his policies have
unnecessarily made Yugoslavia a pariah in the international
community _ were bitterly critical of the indictment, and
especially its timing, coming just hours before Russian envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin was scheduled to arrive here for more talks
with Milosevic Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, who was recently fired as a government minister
because he suggested Milosevic needed to compromise, criticized the
indictment as ``politically provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope President Milosevic will ignore that and strengthen
efforts to approach the peace on the principles of the charter of
the UN ... in the interest of our nation, our state, and stability
of this region,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zarko Korac, a psychologist and critic of Milosevic, said the
indictment ``shows that NATO is determined to escalate the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is meant to wreck the peace process,'' he said. ``NATO is
not interested in finding a solution. This is warmongering.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanimir Miljkovic, a leader of the students movement that wants
to get rid of Milosevic, said the tribunal needs to prove its
independence by indicting those in NATO who have killed civilians
and routinely hit civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indicting Milosevic is one step, but Serbian people will see
it as an injustice if that is all that happens,'' he said. ``This
is the real test of the court's credibility. It's hard to indict
someone who is paying your bills, but people here will be waiting
to see how credible the court is.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the tribunal's budget is paid for mostly by the United
States, Britain and France, many people here dismiss it as biased.
Few people here see the tribunal as independent, believing its
prosecutors take their cues from NATO. Government-controlled media
reinforce that perception.
</P>
<P>
   Vojin Dimitrijevic, director of the Belgrade Center for Human
Rights, who supports the tribunal's mandate, said the tribunal,
which was created in 1993 to prosecute war crimes in the former
Yugoslavia, is seen as anti-Serb here because most of its early
prosecutions were of Serbs. But Dimitrijevic, a law professor,
believes the tribunal can be used to redress Serb grievances, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it necessary for NATO to destroy the bridges in Novi Sad?
Is depriving civilians of electricity and water legitimate? These
are questions that the tribunal must answer, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs interviewed Thursday had not heard about the
indictment, which received scant attention in the
government-controlled broadcast media. Many are preoccupied with
the daily grind of getting by in a country where the economy has
collapsed and the air raid sirens sound and bombs fall every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic is a war criminal, then so is Clinton and
everybody else in NATO,'' said Dragan Jovanovic, 26, who, like most
Yugoslavs right now, is unemployed. ``This doesn't mean anything to
me. Losing my electricity means something. Finding Pampers for my
daughter means something. Not getting bombed means something. War
crimes tribunal means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   If some of Milosevic's enemies hope the indictment will inspire
a military coup or popular uprising against him, few here seem to
believe that possible.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Svilanovic, a spokesman for the Civil Alliance, a small
opposition party, said he saw no successor to Milosevic on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm wrong,'' said Svilanovic, 35, as he prepared to
report for military duty, ``but I don't think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
