A3792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-O'HAIR-CASE-HNS &LR;      05-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-CASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'HAIR FIGURE PLEADS GUILTY TO GUN CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The prime suspect in the disappearance of
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair pleaded guilty Thursday to two
federal firearms offenses.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, 52, who had faced a June 7 trial on the gun
charges, admitted guilt during a pretrial hearing before U.S.
District Judge Sam Sparks. The weapons charges are unrelated to the
missing atheist leader and her two adult children, who vanished in
September 1995 from San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no defense. They've got 30 pictures of him using the
gun at a firing range,'' said Waters' attorney Patrick Ganne.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was charged with one count of possessing ammunition and
one count of transporting firearms, both federal offenses because
of his prior felony convictions, including one for murder.
Sentencing was tentatively set for July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Each count carries a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine, but because of the vagaries of federal sentencing
guidelines, officials said Thursday it was unclear how much time
Waters may serve.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who arrived in court shackled at the ankles and waist,
has not been charged with any crime in connection with the O'Hair
case.
</P>
<P>
   However, an affidavit unsealed late Wednesday accuses him of
being the mastermind of the kidnapping and murder of O'Hair, her
son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair gained prominence in the 1960s for her successful court
battles to eliminate organized prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' lawyer denounced the Internal Revenue Service special
agent who filed the sworn statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first read it, I thought I had been handed a script for
Oliver Stone's next move,'' Ganne said of the affidavit. ``It's all
double-talk, speculation and conjecture. It's an affidavit that
quotes news stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters had worked for the O'Hair in 1993 and 1994, and later
pleaded guilty to stealing $54,400 in funds from her atheist
organization. According to confidential sources quoted in the
affidavit, he nursed a wish for revenge, as well as an ambition to
separate O'Hair from her money.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit was used to obtain a search warrant that led to
the raid on March 24 of Waters' apartment in Austin. In the search,
federal agents turned up 119 rounds of handgun ammunition and other
gun paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   The second firearms charge stems from Waters shipping guns and
ammunition from Austin to a family member in Peoria, Ill. The
charge states he sent a 9mm pistol and a .357 Magnum revolver.
</P>
<P>
   Although no arrests have been made in the O'Hair case, the
affidavit also names Waters and two other men as suspects. The
others are Gary Karr, who is imprisoned in Detroit, and Gerald Lee
Osborne of Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Fry, who was killed shortly after the O'Hairs vanished in
September 1995, also was named as an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit of IRS agent Edmund I. Martin says Waters, Karr
and Fry ``executed the scheme to abduct, kidnap and murder'' O'Hair
and her children ``for the purpose of stealing at least $600,000
from the United Secularists of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin also accuses Waters of killing Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Waters and Karr are ex-convicts who had served time together in
an Illinois prison.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit describes how the former manager of an Austin
storage facility recalled seeing three white males inside the unit
in late 1995 with at least two blue plastic barrels. Investigators
believe Osborne rented the storage unit for Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have theorized the remains of O'Hair and her
children were disposed of in barrels, although investigators have
been unable to find either the barrels or bodies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
