A3804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      05-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLAND GARROS PROVES HAZARDOUS FOR SAMPRAS _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Most people wouldn't consider the leafy 16th
arrondissement a dangerous neighborhood. Anything but.
Nevertheless, Georgia Sampras ought to ground her little boy, Pete,
whenever he wants to hang out in this part of town called Stade
Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   There are too many hooligans in short pants cruising the clay
pits, awed neither by Pete's wealth nor reputation as the best
tennis player in the world, and quite willing to bash him while
picking his pocket. Must be some other world this kid's from, they
mutter while conducting the annual May mugging of Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Pete doesn't understand their languages or their game. Never
has. Probably never will. But he dutifully shows up at the French
Open like a demented blackjack player holding 13 and demanding,
``Hit me! Hit me!'' And they do _ every year for 10 years, and no
payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the second-round task of dispatching him in the
direction of an airport _ any airport _ fell to a burly Russian
ranked No. 100, Andrei Medvedev, who did so, 7-5, 1-6, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Having somehow survived 4 1/4 hours of punishment at the hands
of the only player in the history of Costa Rica, Juan Albert Marin,
in the opening round, Pete thought he'd stretch his luck and go for
two. Medvedev threw him out effortlessly as Sampras stacked 61
unsolicited errors and 10 double faults.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should hire James Carville to scream, ``It's clay,
stupid!'' the way Carville shouted, ``It's the economy, stupid!''
at Clinton. Carville got through to his man. But poor Sampras
increasingly acts as though a clay court is the deepest mystery
since Humphrey Bogart tried to cross the Sahara in a World War II
flick.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Sampras is undertrained, physically and tactically, to
last long among the dirtkickers. He needs professorial help in Clay
101 from somebody like Spaniard Jose Higueras, who tutored the last
American guys to win French titles: Michael Chang in 1989, Jim
Courier in 1991-92. Those two kicked a considerable amount of the
Europeans' and Latin Americans' favorite soil in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was covered with plenty of it and acted self-delusional
afterward. ``I felt fine,'' he said. ``Physically, I was pretty
fresh, quite good. You know, it's still something I need to figure
out, how to play well here. Sometimes I think I overcomplicate
it.'' After going zero for 10 French Opens?
</P>
<P>
   Felt fresh? Napoleon said the same thing about his troops on the
way home from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Slogging about the court, Sampras frequently seemed to be
working on the choreography of an opus by the local composer
Berlioz, ``The March to the Scaffold.'' By this time, a useful
gimmick might be to hold his press conferences at Pere Lachaise,
Paris's most celebrated cemetery. One of the inmates, Chopin,
couldn't play on clay, either, preferring ivory.
</P>
<P>
   Pete says he, too, ``gets into a hole. I just try to serve my
way out; that's my instinct. But you can't do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   There's definitely an identity crisis here. Sometimes Sampras's
head droops so low that he seems to be impersonating an ostrich.
Other times, he tries to convince himself he's a Spaniard, but he
hasn't got the topspin or patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel numb,'' he said. ``The next few days will be very long
before I get over this.'' He yearns for the green grass of
Wimbledon, where he may be able to reclaim No. 1 with a sixth
title. ``Sure, I'm frustrated, PO'd. I let it slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   If the court is gritty, so is Sampras. To his credit, he said,
``Sure I'll be back. I'll never give up on the French. It's my
biggest challenge, the only major I haven't won.''
</P>
<P>
   Masochists everywhere will delight in his words.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras might have a future as a press agent. Look at the
no-names he's made headlines for by losing to them here: No. 76,
France's Thierry Champion; No. 24, Austrian Gilbert Schaller; No.
65, Swede Magnus Norman; No. 98, Paraguayan Ramon Delgado; now
Medvedev, the lowest ever to beat him in a major. Still, Sampras
did get to the semis in 1996, losing to the champ, Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, his current successor at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But No. 1 doesn't really exist these days. Kafelnikov has
crumbled like that other Russian treasure, the Berlin Wall, losing
seven of his last 12 starts. Carlos Moya held it for nine days
before swooning, and the possibility of getting up there has made
such players as Greg Rusedski, Richard Krajicek, Petr Korda, and
Patrick Rafter fade at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   It may be painful watching a player as great as Sampras trying
to cope with crimson earth, sort of like witnessing Don Knotts cast
as Romeo, but he's still the man week in and week out. At least his
mom must be relieved that her boy is out of this hazardous
neighborhood with a French kiss-off for another 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras says he may even show up in Boston for the Davis Cup
joust against Australia July 16-18. ``What those guys (Courier and
Todd Martin) did in beating Britain was inspiring,'' he said. ``I'm
very sensitive about jumping on the bandwagon now. They should play
the singles, but I might be a help in the doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   After slapping a last forehand mildly into the net and shaking
hands with Medvedev, Sampras sat in his chair a long time, head in
hands. He resembled a statue by a another local artist: Rodin's
``The Thinker,'' perhaps trying to figure out something Rodin was
good at _ clay. If Rodin had been here Thursday, he might have used
Pete as a model and called it ``The Clinker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
