<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY HEADS TOWARD U.S.-LED SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ The shuttle Discovery late Thursday sped
toward a rendezvous with the first components of the new U.S.-led
international space station, following a dawn liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The four-man, three-woman crew of U.S., Canadian and Russian
astronauts was on course to reach the 235-mile high, unstaffed
orbital outpost early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle carries nearly two tons of supplies and equipment,
including laptop computers, a range of spare parts, drinking water,
air purification equipment and clothing for the new station's first
resident crew.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. commander Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Sergei Krikalev and
Yuri Gidzenko are to arrive aboard a Russian Soyuz capsule early
next year to coordinate a crucial, five-month construction period.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery soared from NASA's Kennedy Space Center at 6:49 a.m
EDT Thursday . The shuttle climbed steeply on a northerly
trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a great flight,'' pledged Discovery
commander Kent Rominger, as the final seconds of the countdown
ticked away.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is scheduled for 10 days, but even as Discovery
departed, shuttle managers were prepared to extend it by 24 hours
to give the astronauts more time for the cargo transfers, a
demanding spacewalk and internal repairs to the station's power
generation and satellite communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   The transfers will require the astronauts to carry 120 soft
cargo bags packed with hundreds of small items from the big
Spacehab module in Discovery's cargo bay, through the shuttle
docking module and into the station's compartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single bag, every single item has an exact place it's
supposed to go, and the crew has been trained to put each of them
down in one and only one place,'' said NASA's Wayne Hale, the
mission's lead flight director. ``It reminds me a lot of packing
for a long camping trip. We are trying to get everything in and to
make the maximum use of the space.``
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew's activities at the orbital outpost will begin
late Saturday as Discovery astronauts Tammy Jernigan and Dan Barry
begin a near seven-hour spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   During the excursion, the two spacewalkers will work with
colleague Ellen Ochoa. Stationed inside the shuttle's cockpit,
Ochoa will operate the shuttle's 50-foot long robot arm, using it
to hoist Jernigan around the exterior of the station, cherry
picker-style.
</P>
<P>
   Jernigan and Barry, who will scale the exterior of the outpost,
have trained to install a small U.S. cargo crane and the first
segments of a similar Russian device. Future station crews are
depending on the two cranes to lug large power storage batteries
and other bulky equipment across the orbital laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The two spacewalkers also plan to fasten three bags filled with
a variety of hand tools to the exterior of the station so they will
be available to future astronaut construction teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new house,'' said Barry. ``It doesn't have much
furniture or exterior trim yet. ``We are bringing up the parts to
help finish out our house. All the pieces we bring up are support
for future flights, things future construction crews will use to
help them get their jobs done more easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-year effort to build the new station began late last
year with the launch of the Russian-fabricated Zarya and U.S.-made
Unity modules. They were successfully joined by a shuttle crew last
December into a single 68,000 pound spacecraft, spanning 78 feet in
length and measuring 84 feet between the tips of the two wing-like
solar arrays.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Rick Husband, Canadian astronaut Julie Payette and Russian
cosmonaut Valery Tokarev will join their colleagues for several key
tasks within the new station.
</P>
<P>
   These include installation of sound dampening insulation in the
Zarya module to quiet a noisy air circulation system. Payette and
Tokarev will replace 18 faulty amp meters that regulate the
constant charging and discharging of the half-dozen storage
batteries in Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   Husband will lead efforts in the Unity module to repair a
satellite communications system that faltered in early March. The
system permitted ground controllers in Houston to communicate with
the station independently of the Russian control facility in
suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's flight is the first for a shuttle in nearly six
months. The unusually long hiatus was caused by Russian financial
and political difficulties that have stalled the arrival of the
station's crew module by 19 months, until late this November. A
succession of unresolved technical problems with an American X-ray
observatory called Chandra has pushed its launch to no sooner than
late July, nearly a year behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
