<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS28-COX     05-27 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SATELLITE PROVIDES DETAILS OF MARTIAN GEOGRAPHY
 &HT;    Eds: photos from the satellite can be found on the Web at
http://mars.jpl.nasa.gov/mgs/
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Details of a crater on Mars probably dug by a huge
asteroid and evidence of ancient seas gone dry are among the
earliest findings of a topographic mapping satellite orbiting the
planet, scientists said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mars experts already knew that the huge Hellas impact basin in
the planet's southern hemisphere was the largest impact crater in
the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   But in millions of measurements beamed back to Earth since early
last month by instruments on the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft
they have found surprising evidence that the floor of the huge
crater is covered by a smooth material that is different from
surrounding terrain.
</P>
<P>
   They also have found that an ice pack at the south pole of Mars
contains as much frozen water as a similar pack they already knew
about at the North Pole, making the amount of known water on Mars
equal to about 1.5 times that found on Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   And for reasons that are not at all clear, the southern half of
Mars appears to be about three miles ``higher'' than the northern
half.
</P>
<P>
   The new data, flooding into NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center
in Greenbelt, Md., at the rate of 900,000 measurements a day,
suggest a planet that is losing its interior heat rapidly, largely
through volcanism, scientists working with the spacecraft said.
</P>
<P>
   The information is provided courtesy of an instrument known as
the Mars Orbiter Laser Altimeter, which sends bursts of light down
to the surface of Mars and determines the height of the surface at
each point on the basis of how long it takes the light to reflect
back.
</P>
<P>
   The mapping program was delayed by nearly a year while space
engineers worked to correct a malfunction in the craft's solar
power panels shortly after it reached Mars orbit in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Hellas crater is nearly six miles deep and more than 1,300
miles across, said Goddard scientist David Smith, meaning that a
person standing in the middle of it would be surrounded by walls as
high as the Earth's Mt. Everest. Yet those walls would be so far
away that the observer would not know he was in a crater. The ridge
would be beyond the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The new mapping tool shows that when the object that caused the
crater hit Mars _ probably 4 billion years ago _ enough rock and
rubble to cover the continental United States to depth of two miles
was splashed onto the surrounding terrain, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   This material is pocked with thousands of additional craters,
evidence that it has been there for eons.
</P>
<P>
   The floor of the crater appears much smoother, suggesting that
it is much younger than the surrounding terrain. One speculation is
that the object, probably an asteroid up to 500 miles in diameter,
hit with such force that it broke through to the planet's molten
interior, which has been oozing out ever since, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the data suggest Mars once had much more water than
today _ and that it could have ``ponded'' in oceans _ there does
not seem to be any evidence of river systems, with creeks and
tributaries, Smith said. That would mean Mars probably never had
``rain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While water flowed south to north in general, the data clearly
reveal the localized areas where water may have once formed ponds,
`` said geophysicist Maria Zuber of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, another project scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Zuber added that the mapping data show that the southern
hemisphere of Mars is unusually ``rubbly'' and that much of the
lost water could have run underground _ back where it came from,
since the planet's early volcanos probably sent it steaming into
the atmosphere to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
