<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-ART-3TAKES-N     05-27 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SINGING! ALL DANCING! ALL GOTHAM! 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 Ann Douglas, the author of ``Terrible Honesty: Mongrel Manhattan in
the 1920s'' (Noonday), is writing a history of American culture in
the Cold War period.  
 By ANN DOUGLAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During rehearsals for ``I Married an Angel,'' a 1938 musical
comedy about a Hungarian banker, the show's lyricist, Lorenz Hart,
a quick-witted master of the last-minute fix, decided to add a new
number called ``At the Roxy Music Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joshua Logan, the director, asked anxiously how a number
filled with allusions to contemporary New York personalities could
possibly be made to fit into a comedy set in old Budapest, Hart
answered airily: ``Well, just bring up the subject of New York. You
can't sing about Budapest all night. We've got to give people a
little fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Hart's collaborator, the composer Richard Rodgers, moved
out of the city to Fairfield, Conn., in the early '40s, Hart
remained behind, giving parties for the homosexual elite in his
duplex at the Ardsley on Central Park West. On a visit to Khartoum
he was indignant to learn that his hotel didn't carry Variety.
</P>
<P>
   To Hart's mind, no musical comedy, whatever its putative locale,
could be inhospitable to a mention of New York. Dependent on a
lavish flow of cash and illusion, too loud and fast-moving for
introspection or tragic denouements, the city is not only the
birthplace of the musical comedy form but also its primary
exemplar.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan's skyline, a competitive cluster of peaks and flops,
metamorphoses architecture into a musical number, an affected riot
of energy as irregular and surprising as the popular jazz rhythms
Hart evoked into diabolically inventive lyrics. Daringly divorced
from its continent, a gigantic, jagged sculpture served up to the
world on an exceedingly fragile platter, New York is the
``Syncopated City'' (the first title of George and Ira Gershwin's
``Fascinating Rhythm''), a vaudeville act of desperation and glee.
``Now I'm sane,'' a Hart lyric runs, ``but I'd rather be gaga!''
</P>
<P>
   Movie musicals came in with the advent of the talkies in the
late 1920s. From the start they depended on Broadway and Tin Pan
Alley talent, including Rodgers and Hart, all of whose hit shows
were turned into movies. Hollywood's most important artists in the
musical form _ notably Fred Astaire, Gene Kelly and Bob Fosse _
began on Broadway and kept up with its fashions after they left;
Fosse alternated between plays and movies throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   The big Hollywood studios maintained large, all-purpose New York
City sets where New York stories like ``Broadway Melody'' (1929),
``42nd Street'' (1933), ``Easter Parade'' (1948) and ``My Sister
Eileen'' (1955) were largely shot. A montage of the neon signs of
Times Square, a glimpse of a palpably cardboard Empire State
Building, a Cole Porter tune on the soundtrack, is enough to tell
us where we are.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most photographed cities in the world, New York, like
the musical, is a state of mind, an instance of the supremely
American confusion of the real and the fake. A New York set is a
real New York location.
</P>
<P>
   The movie musical had its own brand of realism, however, sharing
its heyday and occasionally its personnel with gangster and noir
films. Although these went in for stylish camera angles and moody
cynicism, while the musical preferred advertisement-friendly
frontal shots and happy endings, both genres specialized in
synthetic extremes and the unexpected possibilities of public
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   If noir's investigations took place in the seedy urban back lots
of American capitalism and crime, the musical staked out its
underside in the sometimes deliciously low-life stories of the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Hays Code, imposed in 1934, hit gangster films and musicals
hardest. James Cagney went from ``Public Enemy'' to ``G-Man,'' and
Shirley Temple became more popular than May West. The musical
banned openly gay characters and girls shimmying to songs like
``Shake My Powder Puff.''
</P>
<P>
   Slight, suave Fred Astaire _ who thought of himself as a
character actor, not a Romeo _ benefited from the new standards.
His style of singing and dancing was smart but refined, almost
censor-proof, and he elevated Ginger Rogers from her ``42d Street''
Anytime Annie persona to romantic-partner status. Yet the fairy
tale aura of the Rogers-Astaire films contained a tough-minded show
biz core.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Swing Time'' (1936) Rogers and Astaire play hard-pressed
New York performers who get their big chance when he wins the
contract of the Silver Sandal club's band leader at the gambling
table. ``I own you,'' Astaire announces to the unlucky Georges
Mataxa. Even in the smart Art Deco world Astaire and Rogers
inhabit, everyone is a professional; popular art is also hotly
contested property.
</P>
<P>
   In the magical ``Never Gonna Dance'' number, Rogers and Astaire
give away their talents for nothing, singing and dancing just
because they feel like it, because they have to, but we always know
where they got the skills to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In ``You'll Never Get Rich,'' a wonderfully romantic musical
with Astaire and Rita Hayworth, the couple, again playing
professionals, never dance outside an entertainment context.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein II's ``Oklahoma!'' (1943;
filmed in 1955) represented a dramatic shift in the musical form.
Rodgers had brought the project to Hart first, but when Hart read
this period romance about cowboys and farmers in Oklahoma
territory, replete with rustic dialect cast in ominously phonetic
spellings like ``purty,'' ``skeered'' and ``fer,'' Hart told a
friend, ``Baby, I don't see it,'' and turned it down. ``Oklahoma!''
became the hit of the war years, establishing the integrated,
serious musical play as the new Broadway-Hollywood ideal.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Oklahoma!,'' none of the characters are professional
entertainers. They sing and dance precisely because they are
amateurs, to quote Irving Berlin's own ``Oklahoma!''-inspired
musical, ``just doin' what comes natur'lly'': to wit, militantly
heterosexual mating and patriotic state-building.
</P>
<P>
   In a premature moment of Disneyfication, when the Hotel Astor
was host to a costume party to celebrate the success of
``Oklahoma!,'' it christened itself the Hayloft and instructed
guests to ``check your shootin' irons at the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   The mongrel world-city was masquerading again, this time as the
American heartland. But the losses involved were real, too.
</P>
<P>
   No numbers like ``At the Roxy Music Hall'' appeared in
``Oklahoma!'' Here the songs were integral to the plot. They
weren't detached from the show and sent through multiple
interpretations as Rodgers and Hart's had been, but packaged in a
recorded ``show album.''
</P>
<P>
   Folk ballet, superbly choreographed in ``Oklahoma!'' by Agnes de
Mille and drenched in what Martha Graham portentously called the
``aura of race memory,'' eclipsed the percussive wizardry of tap,
black vaudeville's gift to Broadway. Hammerstein remarked that not
one of the characters in ``Oklahoma!'' ``has a brain in his head,''
but no sharp-witted urban racketeer is on hand to satirize or
exploit rural credulity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
