<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3826 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADVISORY-APACHE-PILOT     05-27 0047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISORY-APACHE-PILOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Papers planning to use the May 25 transmission of
BC-NATO-PILOTS-BOS, by Lynda Gorov (i), are advised to substitute
the version sent today, which deletes the full name of the pilot
interview.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-ART-2NDTAKE-     05-27 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: rural credulity.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodgers and Hammerstein's major musicals weren't set in New
York, nor did they make extensive allusions to it. Something like
the anti-New York musical had been born, and it was long vastly
influential, though never uncontested, on Broadway and in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kelly, who succeeded Fred Astaire as Hollywood's foremost
musical comedy star in the 1940s, had the muscular physique,
athletic skills, ballet training and Irish-American charm to work
in the wide-open, space-eating ``Oklahoma!'' mode of prescribed
World War II and postwar optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Mention of Kelly today conjures up the image of an overeager,
overenergetic professional amateur with an Ipana-white grin and a
penchant for on-the-beat movement, desperately trying to persuade
us how much fun he's having. (One British reviewer found his smile
as reassuring as a ``nuclear accident.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kelly wasn't really a booster type, but rather an early
example of that peculiarly late-'40s and '50s phenomenon, a rebel
disguised as a cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1912 into a working-class family, fiercely intelligent
and ambitious, Kelly never lost his acutely class-conscious
resentment of the rich and powerful. Ballet was a late acquisition.
His roots were in the tap and vaudeville routines he had learned in
the cheap clip joints and burlesque houses of his native
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Though he directed ``Flower Drum Song,'' a minor Rodgers and
Hammerstein hit, on Broadway in 1958, he made his name in 1940 in
the starring role of Rodgers and Hart's ``Pal Joey,'' John O'Hara's
slang-filled, mordant portrait of a fast-talking hoofer-hustler
with New York ambitions stuck in the seedy Chicago nightclub scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, who regarded ``Pal Joey'' as his masterpiece, adored
Kelly. After rehearsals the two men drank and talked all night in
the rough bars of the Eighth Avenue theater district. Kelly went to
MGM in 1942, but his best movies were collaborations with New York
talent, often recruited by Kelly himself; he played sanitized
versions of Joey Evans for the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Astaire's styles were radically different. Wittily
stylish, implacably if nonchalantly superior, Astaire endures the
routine uncertainties his plots inflict on him with the well-worn
patience of a host handling an ill-timed guest. Behind the
mechanics of his lines, behind his balding, even comic appearance,
the real Fred Astaire, endowed with a genius invisible in repose,
waits, on hold until the moment when he can sing and dance,
effortlessly compelling the world's adoration.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a has-been in ``The Band Wagon'' (1953), Astaire steps
off a train in Grand Central Terminal to find a throng of reporters
brushing him aside to get to Ava Gardner. He walks off singing
Howard Dietz's lyrics, ``I'll face the unknown, I'll build a world
of my own. ... By myself.'' Temporary neglect is merely a
provocation to greater self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   If Astaire's preternaturally stable persona defined and
normalized every movie in which he appeared, Kelly's volatility
upset genre conventions without being able to control them.
Bringing to his roles the gift of male beauty, a charisma,
vulnerability and warm, full-chested density outside Astaire's
range, Kelly cast himself as Marlon Brando to Astaire's Cary Grant,
bypassing top hat and tails for form-fitting T-shirts and jeans
designed to show off the body line. Astaire's masculine status is
an elegant hypothesis, but Kelly's virility is insistent and in
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cover Girl'' (1944), on the brink of losing his club and
his girl, Kelly dances a fierce debate with his Alter Ego (also
performed by Kelly) on a dark Brooklyn street piled with packing
crates. Tap exploding into skids and big balletic leaps to a jazzy
bass-dominated score, colloquial in movement, taut in execution,
sexy, angry and scared, this is psycho-dance, the musical spliced
with Method and tinged with noir, laying bare its roots in despair.
</P>
<P>
   A canny four-decade survivor of Broadway's Golden Age in the
wide-open 1920s, Astaire, whose centennial we are celebrating this
year, knew how to be timeless, innately emblematic of the best
America can offer. But Kelly was a veteran of the Depression whose
career peaked when Sen. Joseph McCarthy's did; Kelly had scant
talent for the varied rhythms self-invention requires.
</P>
<P>
   As a passionate opponent of the blacklist, Kelly narrowly
escaped investigation by the House Committee on Un-American
Activities; in several of his finest numbers, cops interrupt
dancers: musical comedy cops but censors all the same.
</P>
<P>
   While Astaire's movies require only that he reveal himself,
Kelly's films demand a confession, an apology, even a conversion.
His ``Oklahoma!'' style is in part a repudiation of his ``Pal
Joey'' past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma!'' takes Manhattan in Kelly's sunniest movie, ``On
the Town'' (1949), with a divine script by Betty Comden and Adolph
Green. Playing a country boy, one of a trio of sailors released
from shipboard discipline for 24 mad, magical hours, Kelly brings
us the tourist's New York, a utopia in the here and now, whizzing
and glittering with open-air scenes, shot on location.
</P>
<P>
   But in Kelly and Stanley Donen's last great musical, ``It's
Always Fair Weather'' (1955), also written by Comden and Green, the
ravishingly exuberant camaraderie of the ensemble work of ``On the
Town'' gives way to a bitter comedy of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Three wartime buddies hold a reunion in New York, now a noir set
of midnight streets, grimy boxing gyms and man-eating television
studios, only to discover they have nothing in common. Despite an
implausibly happy ending, Kelly, in his most openly ``Pal Joey''
role, never sings or dances with his romantic partner, Cyd
Charisse. Drunkenly carousing on a dark street with garbage can
lids affixed to their left feet, Kelly, Dan Dailey and Michael Kidd
turn dancing into an obstacle course.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood musical was going out of style, and Kelly would be
as firmly (and unluckily) associated with its fall as Astaire was
with its peak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 Bob Fosse, perhaps the musical's greatest talent, was
only 28. A practitioner in a nearly posthumous form, Fosse took
advantage of the collapse of the Cold War verities that shaped
Kelly's career to prove that the coda can sometimes trump the
composition it concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Like his idol Astaire, Fosse was unprepossessing in appearance,
a fair, slight, balding man with few acting skills beyond a
pleasant manner. As a dancer, he, too, relied on wit, irony and
superbly inventive timing to transform a quality of physical
absence into eloquently astute commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But where Astaire built poignancy and excitement into his
low-key emotional repertory by the choreographic tactic of freeze
and melt, stop-motion alternating with glides, subtle bends and
musical curves, Fosse banished the melodic and sheerly expressive
in favor of the old percussive soft-shoe ``Tea for Two'' rhythm,
finding the antidote to motion not in relaxation, but in another
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Only in his late homage to Astaire, ``I Wanna Be a Dancin' Man''
(which can be seen Friday on Broadway in the revue ``Fosse''), did
he even try to approximate Astaire's aristocratic panache and
fundamentally ballroom style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pal Joey'' and Kelly's success in the role were a lifelong
impetus to Fosse's ambition. Although his background was firmly
middle-class, before coming to New York in 1946 he apprenticed as a
dancer in the strip joints of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICALS-ART-3RDTAKE-     05-27 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICALS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of Chicago.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1951 he starred in a summer stock revival of ``Pal Joey,''
playing the role again in two off-Broadway productions of the '60s.
He never made it to Broadway in the part (and bitterly lamented the
fact), but he injected the ``Pal Joey'' story into every movie and
play he directed.
</P>
<P>
   Fanatically hard working, chronically insecure, abrasive, even
cruel, yet compulsively eager to please, Fosse aspired to Astaire's
unassailability, but he identified with Kelly's hunger. For Fosse,
too, the noir and the musical were kin, though he learned to
integrate them into a new hybrid form as Kelly never could.
</P>
<P>
   Dancer-choreographers like Astaire, Kelly and Donen had proved
themselves the best translators of Broadway musicals into cinematic
terms. Choreographers come to film knowing how to divide space by
form, to manipulate matter to visual effect.
</P>
<P>
   Fosse was the first, however, to have started in television,
choreographing and performing for ``Your Hit Parade'' in New York
in 1950. By the time he arrived in Hollywood in 1952, he had
already conceived the body as an intricate, two-dimensional display
of silhouettes, profiles, angles and attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In a Fosse number the body seems to cut and edit itself into
sharp, unexpected shifts and splices of perspective, mind
experimenting on matter as only a camera can. Mimicking a close-up
shot, one dancer turns manic miniaturist and compartmentalizer. A
single segment of her body _ a pelvis convulsing in bumps and
grinds, a stiff turned-out knee, a raised shoulder blade or eyebrow
_ goes free-lance, abruptly detaching itself from its physical
context, before the number shifts back to the ensemble long shot,
allowing the overall pattern, the kaleidoscopic, high-tech repartee
of multiple bodies, to click into focus.
</P>
<P>
   In his movie ``Cabaret'' (1972), Fosse brought the integrated
musical to new heights, even as he unplugged its heterosexual
imperative, discarded its folk pretensions, decimated its
euphemisms and satirized its equation of singing and dancing with
national salvation. ``Cabaret'' reminds us that the Nazis sang and
danced, too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fosse's greatest contribution was to return the musical to
its mongrel, episodic, Hartsian roots. His dances suggest the
nervous system in acute states of spasmodic withdrawal (a condition
to which Fosse, an addictive womanizer and a drinker and drugger of
mammoth proportions, was no stranger), the war of the part against
the whole. Yet his later productions often refuse any coherence
other than their status as show biz.
</P>
<P>
   Ransacking entertainment's trunk, Fosse used the various styles
of Chaplin, Astaire, Kelly, Busby Berkeley, Al Jolson, Bert
Williams, Bill (Bojangles) Robinson and the Nicholas brothers as
multiple ideas in nonstop collaboration and collision, creating a
fugal exercise allergic to blurred edges.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the ``Steam Heat'' number (included in
``Fosse'') in ``Pajama Game'' (1954; filmed in 1957), the dazzling
Carol Haney and her two male partners, garbed in unisex
Chaplinesque black suits and derbies, don't bow themselves off the
stage, eliding gracefully from number back to narrative, from
theater to life.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they scamper into the wings, come back to cavort in the
applause, return yet again to scramble for a dropped hat, then
finally chase one another offstage, intent on further deviltry, as
fresh as they began. Artifice is nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have to put it on,'' Fosse remarked, ``to make it
through the day.'' The stage may showcase entertainment, but only a
body bag can end it.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiographical movie masterpiece, ``All That Jazz''
(1979), Fosse's stand-in, Joe Gideon (Roy Scheider), a middle-aged
Broadway director dying of heart disease in a hospital, escapes his
nurses and enters the room of an old woman groaning in final agony.
</P>
<P>
   The film, shot without filters or glamorizing tricks,
mercilessly shows the woman's yellow teeth and decaying skin. In a
shocking, wonderful moment, Gideon tells her he loves her and
kisses her passionately full on the mouth. Her pain forgotten, she
kisses him back, then looks at him in amazed happiness and dies.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, when the Angel of Death asked Gideon if he believed in
love, he gave the cynical show biz response ``I believe in saying I
love you.'' It's a good answer. The dying woman is his mother, that
is to say his audience, and he does indeed love her. The ``Pal
Joey'' heel is a hero in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before his death after a heart attack in 1987, Fosse
considered doing a movie about the gossip columnist Walter
Winchell. Looking at Times Square's new Marriott and Holiday Inn,
noting its increasingly upscale tourists and pedestrians, he asked
a friend: ``Where am I going to shoot it? This isn't Broadway
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, while Disney redesigns Times Square into
``Oklahoma!''-bright colors and Madison-Avenue Americana, Broadway
is host to a major Fosse revival. No wonder ``Chicago'' and
``Fosse'' are hits. Like the city he loved, a Fosse production
sometimes blocked out the sky, but he had his own oxygen supply. As
the narrowing fin de siecle funnels us fast into the 21st century,
could we possibly need Bob Fosse more?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
