<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, May 28. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (The Hague, Netherlands) _ The International
Criminal Tribunal here charged President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia with crimes against humanity in Kosovo, including the
murder, forced deportation and persecution of ethnic Albanians.
Announcing the indictment of Milosevic and four other senior
Yugoslav officials, Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor, said
arrest warrants for the five accused had been served on all member
states of the United Nations and Switzerland. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ Publicly, the Clinton
administration has applauded the indictment of Slobodan Milosevic,
a move that would appear to change Milosevic's status from
potential deal maker to an off-bounds pariah. In private,
administration officials say that the indictment virtually derails
the efforts to find a diplomatic solution through Russia and
President Martti Ahtissari of Finland. A news analysis. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TRADING-HOURS (New York) _ After years of resisting a move to
extend trading hours _ and after several previous attempts failed
because of lack of interest among investors _ the nation's major
stock markets are now hurriedly readying plans to trade stocks for
several additional hours in the evening. On the horizon, many in
the industry see around-the-clock trading. A NASD announcement is
expected at 2 p.m. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SCHOOLS-BUSH (Brownsville, Texas) _ On national
examinations, Texan school children have begun to show up their
peers in other states. The trend has become so consistent that
Texas' public school system, long among the nation's most troubled,
is viewed today as an emerging model of equity, progress and
accountability. Texas children are the primary beneficiaries. But
with a presidential election next year, there will very likely be
another beneficiary, Gov. George W. Bush, at the moment the
Republicans' best hope for taking control of the White House. By
Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MBEKI (Vredendal, South Africa) _ Though he has none of
the spontaneous charm and sense of the right gesture that has made
President Nelson Mandela so beloved, the reserved, bookish Thabo
Mbeki, 56, has thrown himself into campaigning to replace the
retiring Mandela. He is everywhere these days, offering a message
of hope that many South Africans, appalled at the rising crime and
unemployment rates, are eager to hear: Change will come faster now
because the policies are in place. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ Two Indian fighter jets were
lost in combat on the Pakistani side of a cease-fire line in
troubled Kashmir, further worsening a nerve-wracking confrontation
between the subcontinent's two nuclear-armed rivals. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ The prosecution rests in the Louima
case.
</P>
