A3830 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-BREWERS-CO     05-27 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BREWERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves frost Brewers 8-7
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The last hurrah for the Braves in their former
County Stadium home was a wild one, to the enjoyment of much of the
Milwaukee Brewers' first decent crowd of the four-game series,
22,252.
</P>
<P>
   Day game. Seventy-degree weather. Bases full of runners. Little
bit of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good game,'' said Chipper Jones, who did his part to lead the
Braves to an 8-7 victory with a three-run homer and a tag at third
base in the critical play down the stretch. ``Competitive. Lot of
offense. We swung the bats well and played just good enough on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory probably came down to one moment in the eighth
inning. The Braves got a double play when Jeromy Burnitz struck out
on a 3-2 fastball from reliever Russ Springer and Javy Lopez threw
out Ron Belliard trying to steal third.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers had been battling back all day against Braves' leads
of 4-1 and 8-4. They were still battling until the final out, when
Rudy Seanez coaxed a double play ball from Lou Collier to give the
Braves a 3-1series victory.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season the Braves have won three road games in a row.
Atlanta won three against the Florida Marlins during its first
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was just strange,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``It's
not a game you'd like to film and show your minor-leaguers. We
probably played worse than they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the daylight and some fat pitches from
starters Scott Karl and Kevin Millwood, the teams combined for 24
hits _ including 10 off Karl and eight off Millwood _ and left the
game to late-inning hitters and relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood gave up six runs, his highest total of the season. But
he improved to 5-2 with the victory, tying John Smoltz for the most
victories on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like it wasn't really there,'' Millwood said. ``I
didn't have any confidence. I thought my curveball was bad, my
slider was bad, my changeup was bad, and I couldn't locate my
fastball. It was like every hitter was a huge battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood watched a 4-1 lead disappear in the fourth. He hit
Geoff Jenkins in the foot, walked Bobby Hughes on five pitches and,
after giving up an RBI single to Mark Loretta, fielded Scott Karl's
sacrifice bunt and threw past Chipper Jones to allow a run to
score.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves used a pair of Brewers errors in the next inning
to score four more runs, including the two that won it on Brian
Hunter's double.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody deserves this win,'' Millwood said, ``it's the
eight guys behind me.'' Rogers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
