<HEADER>
A3831 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SAUNDERS-COX     05-27 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SAUNDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Throwing force may be to blame in Saunders' injury
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The incredible force a pitcher exerts while throwing a baseball
probably is to blame for Tony Saunders' broken arm, an Emory
University sports-medicine expert says.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible cause is a bone abnormality, such as a benign
or malignant tumor, that weakens the bone, said Dr. Robert
Frederick, an orthopedic surgeon who heads Emory's Sports Medicine
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, 25, who had not been diagnosed with any such problem,
broke his left humerus in mid-pitch Wednesday. The humerus is the
large bone that connects the shoulder to the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when people break their arms, they fracture the smaller
forearm bones, the radius or the ulna. That Saunders' humerus was
fractured indicates how tremendously it was stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an acute overload that the bone just can't stand,''
Frederick said.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen the problem before, generally with younger pitchers
who aren't as strong and well-conditioned as professionals. All
pitchers risk injury, however, simply by the nature of what they
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're starting with the arm way back over the head, then
whip the arm forward,'' Frederick said. ``It creates a tremendous
torque, or rotational stress in the bone. At some point it may
surpass what the bone is able to tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even under such circumstances, the humerus rarely breaks. More
frequently, it comes out of its socket, resulting in a dislocated
shoulder. Alternately, the rotator cuff _ the four muscles that
hold the humerus in its shoulder socket _ tears.
</P>
<P>
   If Saunders' injury proves unrelated to any other medical
problem, he has a good chance of returning to his previous form,
Frederick said. The bone, which breaks in a spiral manner in such
cases, will take three to four months to heal, Saunders' doctors
said. No surgery was required, a team official said, and Saunders
left the hospital Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His recovery might be complicated if the surrounding muscles and
tendons are damaged. Such injuries might create scar tissue, which
in turn might limit the range of movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, when you're dealing with an athlete at that
elite level, any small change can sometimes make the difference in
getting back to their top performance level, versus being just not
quite there,'' said Frederick, who was director of athlete care for
gymnastics during the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Other major-league pitchers who broke or fractured their humerus
bones while pitching include the Cleveland Indians' John Smiley,
the Cincinnati Reds' Tom Browning and, most memorably, Dave
Dravecky of the San Francisco Giants. Dravecky's humerus snapped
shortly after his triumphant return to baseball after cancer
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
