<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3832 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STEWART-COX     05-27 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STEWART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Since he was a teenager driving sprint and
midget cars on the dirt tracks of Indiana, Tony Stewart dreamed of
winning the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Stewart, from Columbus, Ind., will make his fourth
start in the Indy 500. He'll start in the outside position of the
eighth row, but if he's fortunate enough to take the lead late in
the 200-lap race, Stewart says he could do the unimaginable: Pull
onto pit road and shut off his Oldsmobile Aurora engine.
</P>
<P>
   That's the dilemma Stewart, 28, faces when he attempts to become
the first driver ever to complete all 1,100 miles in the
Indianapolis 500 and then the Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR race at Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 1997 Indy Racing League champion but a rookie on
the Winston Cup circuit this year, says he doesn't want anything to
hinder his early-season performance in the No. 20 Pontiac stock car
of Joe Gibbs Racing. Not even the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were leading Indy with five laps to go and it was time
to get on the airplane (back to Concord), I would have to leave,''
said Stewart, who has hired John Paul Jr. to drive if that happens.
``We would stop the car and make sure I got to Charlotte on time. I
am not going to be late to Charlotte. We would have to quit early.
Charlotte is my No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis 500 begins at 11 a.m. on Sunday; the Coca-Cola
600 starts at 6:15 p.m. If the Indy 500 is delayed by accidents or
inclement weather, Stewart says he'll pull out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart already faces one obstacle in the Coca-Cola 600. He
probably will miss the drivers' meeting in Concord at 4:15 p.m., so
he'll have to start at the rear of the field on Sunday, no matter
how well he qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it and decided we're not going to open
ourselves up to a Pandora's box,'' NASCAR spokesman Tim Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
