<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NOTTING-HILL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOTTING HILL' A PERFECT ROMANTIC VEHICLE FOR ITS STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It doesn't happen very often these days, but every once in a
while, the Hollywood Dream Machine gets it right. The Julia
Roberts-Hugh Grant romantic-comedy fairy tale, ``Notting Hill,'' is
one of those times. It's pure fluff, but as irresistible as cotton
candy.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, it's a near-flawless example of the old-fashioned
movie-star romance: a vehicle in which the script is witty,
original and effortlessly romantic, the stars are at their
crackling best, and their chemistry is magical.
</P>
<P>
   Its main character is William Thacker (Grant), a mild-mannered,
recently divorced, self-deprecating man who owns a small travel
bookstore in the Notting Hill section of London. In recent years,
he has been spectacularly unlucky in love.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Anna Scott (Roberts), the most famous movie star in the
world, walks into his store looking for a guide to Turkey.
Flustered, he manages to spill orange juice all over her, and when
they go to his nearby flat to get cleaned up, sparks fly.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie follows the storybook romance over the
course of a year, which becomes complicated by her immense fame, a
pre-existing boyfriend (Alec Baldwin, in a cameo) and, more
gradually, by Thacker's lack of confidence that true love can
endure under such an intense spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the film _ in which the two fall inexorably in
love and she finds refuge in his cozy circle of family and friends
in Notting Hill _ comes off with a kind of mesmerizing perfection,
sweeping us up in the manner of such classics in the genre as
``Roman Holiday'' or ``Love Affair.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half is slightly less satisfying, but it also works,
and it adds a rather unexpected edge to the film as it becomes, in
part, a fairly devastating portrait of the freakishness of big-time
fame, revealing the sheer horror of what it is like to have a face
that's so instantly recognizable that it draws a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The script by Richard Curtis (``Four Weddings and a Funeral'')
is funny, rich with enjoyably eccentric supporting characters, and
custom-made for the star's personalities. In his first Hollywood
effort, British director Roger Michell (``Persuasion'') has wisely
opted for the lightest possible directorial touch _ staying well
out of the way of his stars and script.
</P>
<P>
   As she's aged, Roberts has developed a hard angularity to her
face, but she's still immensely captivating and more exquisitely
vulnerable than ever _ especially in the scenes in which she fully
realizes how her fame is a handicap to personal happiness. (Her
character here is reportedly closer to her true self than any she's
ever played.)
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the movie more properly belongs to Grant. In role after
role in the '90s, he has skillfully constructed a
befuddled-but-charming-educated-Englishman persona very much in the
vein of his role model and hero, David Niven. In this movie, that
construction seems to have reached its zenith, and it should
finally make him what he's long threatened to become: an A-level
Hollywood movie star.
</P>
<P>
   Notting Hill. Directed by Roger Michell. Written by Richard
Curtis. Cast: Julia Roberts, Hugh Grant, Hugh Bonneville, Emma
Chambers, Rhys Ifans. Universal. 120 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1848EDT &QL; 
