<SLUG> BC-ADAM-YAHOO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adam.com strikes deal with Yahoo!By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam.com on Thursday announced a deal that will put the
company's name, content and links to its home page on a new,
Internet healthcare site being created by Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility and brand name are seen as keys to Internet success,
and the agreement is meant to give Atlanta-based Adam a bit of
both, said Chief Executive Officer Robert Cramer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Adam, which has shifted from a software strategy to a bet on the
Net, has its own site. But Cramer said the company sees Yahoo as
one of the premier portals _ gateways that most Net surfers use to
start a search. Yahoo Health could be the way they go looking for
healthcare tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts us in position to be seen by 50 million Yahoo users
so that when a Yahoo user wants more information, a connection to a
community or imagery, the odds are they will find us,'' Cramer
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to get its name and content in front of more
Internet eyeballs, Adam has in recent months signed agreements with
CNN, Excite and Cox Interactive. However, the Yahoo deal is the
broadest, Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is probably the most significant development
we've had with the company yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo and Adam declined to release financial details of the
deal. However, Cramer said that Adam was not paying for the right
to be carried on Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Briggs, a senior producer at Yahoo, called Adam a ``key
component'' of the company's service.
</P>
<P>
   However, Adam does not have an exclusive arrangement with Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Yahoo's new site, the company announced agreements
with HealthCentral.com, and Dr.Koop.com, the Web site operated by
Dr. C. Everett Koop.
</P>
<P>
   Healthcare, which represents 14 percent of the nation's $6
trillion-a-year economy, remains a hot area on the Net as investors
and companies vie for a piece of the growing action.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD Inc., a high-flying Atlanta-based Net company, last week
announced a multi-billion dollar merger with Healtheon Corp. The
combined company will have Net services in healthcare for both
consumers and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
