<SLUG> BC-ENCOMPASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo! buys Encompass for $130 million in stock
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo! announced Thursday that it had paid about $130
million in stock for Encompass, an Atlanta company that makes a Web
browser that comes with PCs made by 7 of the 10 largest PC-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which closed Wednesday, gives Yahoo! a company that
controls the first few minutes of a new PC-user's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC-makers were in the business of just renting their
desktops, selling space so companies like America Online could
place an icon, let people link to their site and become a
customer,'' said Jeff Mallett, president and chief executive
officer of Yahoo!. ``Lately, the PC-makers have been getting back
control of the browser.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett said Encompass' 27-person staff will stay in Atlanta.
John Willcutts, Encompass founder, former chairman and chief
executive, said he expects to expand the Atlanta office. He said he
will continue to run what had been the Encompass operation in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Encompass software handles the registration of the hardware,
software and Internet Service Provider for people who have bought a
new PC.
</P>
<P>
   The company's browser acts as a kind of welcome wagon for people
new to the Web, pointing them toward the sites and companies that
have paid for that recommendation. A browser is the windshield
through which much of the Internet is viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Encompass has distribution agreements with Acer, CTX, Dell,
Diamond Multimedia, Hewlett-Packard, Micron, Toshiba and Sony and
with ISPs such as Earthlink, AT&AMP;T and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who recently bought an Acer computer, for example, would
use an Encompass browser that would already have links set up to
popular Web sites, such as Yahoo! or Amazon.com or Excite. Yahoo!
had been a link on the Encompass browser for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The company made money by selling banner ads on the browser and
links to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let the PC-makers point their customers toward the
companies they do business with,'' Willcutts said. ``We make it
easy for a PC-maker to maintain an economic tie to its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Encompass is based on Circle 75 Parkway, near
Cumberland Mall, but has offices in San Francisco. The 33-employee
company was founded in January, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting the company, Willcutts was vice president of
engineering for Softnet, an Atlanta company that made fax
communication software. Encompass was financed by Benchmark Capital
and Technology Crossover Ventures, both in Silicon Valley, as well
as the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
