<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN YOUR FACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; There is a lunatic attempt by out-of-work Cold Warriors in
Washington and retrograde Chinese nationalists in Beijing to use
the latest Chinese spying scandal and bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade to put China and the United States on a
collision course. It is times like these when you need a president
who is ready to get right in the face of both his critics and the
Chinese leadership and say the following: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President to the China-bashers in Congress: ``Where exactly do
you guys think you're going with this? Yes, the Chinese spied on
us. Is it serious? You bet it is. Do we need to drastically improve
security at our nuclear labs and stop our companies from selling
everything that isn't nailed down? You bet we do. But you all seem
to be pushing for something more. Let's cut to the bottom line
here: Do you want to declare war on China? Is that what you want?
Fine, let's do that. Let's take them all on _ all 1.3 billion of
them. Hey, they're only one-fifth of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's not what you want? Well then, cut the war dance and
get real. Yes, China is a rising power, and over time we may have
no choice but to have a Cold War with China. But it is not a
confrontation we should be cultivating. China is not the Soviet
Union. It's not committed to the universal spread of communism.
These are not people who build television sets that blow up when
you turn them on. These are serious people. They've had nuclear
weapons for 35 years. China is not the Soviet Union, which was
surrounded by weak countries that needed our military backing and
welcomed us. China is largely surrounded by strong countries, which
have decent relations with it, and they would not be eager to join
us if we picked a fight with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what if you win your Cold War with China and produce a
collapse of the regime there? What do you think happens the morning
after? That China is going to become a replica of the United
States? That the Dalai Lama will be embraced by Chinese democrats?
If this regime collapses, the morning after will be utter chaos.
You want chaos in China and Russia at the same time? You think that
is going to make America safer? What is it you're trying to trigger
here?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible to be an American patriot, be outraged at the
lax security of our nuclear weapons labs, be outraged about China's
pervasive spying and still want to foster better relations with
Beijing to bring about a stable transition there and a more
rule-based regime. You seem to have forgotten that we engaged in
sweeping arms-control deals with the Soviet Union at a time when it
was patrolling our coasts with nuclear submarines and trying to
steal every secret we had. If you can't juggle multiple objectives
at the same time, that's your problem. But I am not going to take
this country down the lunatic path of destroying relations with
China so that you can have a cheap political thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   President's message to China's leaders: ``OK, boys, you've had
your fun now. You've sucked up everything from our nuclear labs. I
just want you to know a couple of things. First, we're going to
step up our electronic spying on you. In fact, we're going to be
bouncing so many microwaves off your Defense Ministry your generals
are going to feel like rotisserie chickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, I have heard enough about the bombing of your embassy
in Belgrade. We both know it was an accident, and if you keep it
up, I'm going to close the visa window at our embassy in China.
After all, your people wouldn't want to visit a war-mongering
country like ours. Could be dangerous. You want to play footsie
with the Russians? Be my guest. Let's see how many of your young
people want to go to Moscow University for an M.B.A. By the way,
there's no Disney World in Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Chinese friends, you're not the only ones with power and
weight in this relationship. I'm struggling to keep this thing on
track. But if you're not ready to do the same, if it just isn't
important enough for you to stand up to your lunatics, then we
 &UR; will &LR;  end up in a Cold War. And if you think China can develop
without us, well, then the opium trade must have come back to your
shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I checked  &UR; you &LR;  had a $60 billion trade surplus with
 &UR; us &LR; . Oh, I'm sure the Russians would be happy to buy your exports
and give you rubles. Rubles, yes, they make wonderful wallpaper.
You get my drift? So let's cut the bluster and resume a sensible
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
