<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SWINDLE-SPI &LR;      05-27 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SWINDLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SWINDLE' IS A WICKEDLY HUMOROUS PSYCHOLOGICAL THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Hollywood, the filmmaking process has become so labyrinthine
and expensive over the past few decades that even the best
filmmakers seem to progressively make fewer films. The late Stanley
Kubrick, for instance, was able to make only five films in the past
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the best French directors somehow manage to keep cranking
out film after film: all have produced a vast body of work in the
'80s and '90s. Claude Chabrol's ``The Swindle'' (which jumps out of
the Seattle International Film Festival lineup for a regular run on
Friday) is his 50th film in 40 years of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   And, while not his best, it represents no big letdown in
quality. It's another wickedly humorous psychological thriller that
provides a showy part for his favorite star, Isabelle Huppert. It's
very much in the tradition of his body of work, but also different
enough to be worth seeing.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a pair of small-time bunco artists, Betty
(Huppert) and the much-older Victor (Michel Serrault), who work a
circuit of resort hotels and conventions. Betty lures men to her
room, drugs them and steals part of their cash _ but only part, so
their crime might go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   The scam has been successful, but has become routine for Betty,
and when she takes a holiday in St. Moritz, she branches out with a
more ambitious scheme to roll Maurice (Francois Cluzet), an
accountant for the mob who is about to transport a suitcase full of
cash to the island of Guadeloupe.
</P>
<P>
   When Betty calls Victor and confesses her plan, he hurriedly
joins her in St. Moritz and the rest of the movie is a strange
cat-and-mouse game in which Betty is swindling both Victor and
Maurice, and in which the audience is never completely sure who
knows what or what exactly is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Chabrol once co-wrote a book about Alfred Hitchcock, who greatly
influenced his style, and hostile critics often dismiss him as a
mere imitator of the master. Since the mood of ``The Swindle'' is
one of his more Hitchcockian in years, it could be in for a rough
critical time.
</P>
<P>
   But it's mostly great fun. The tone is light (it's being
advertised as a comedy, which is not exactly the case), the plot
puzzle is agreeably challenging, and the locations are glamorous,
beautifully composed and well integrated into the story line.
</P>
<P>
   Like the best of Chabrol's films, this one also has a
fascinating, ambiguous, slightly perverse human relationship at its
core: a platonic love affair between a weather-beaten, 70ish master
criminal and a beautiful, 40ish protege who calls him ``Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another SIFF veteran beginning a regular theatrical run this
weekend is the Canadian-Irish feature, ``This is My Father'' _ only
this one is leaping out of the '98 festival, where it had its world
premiere last June in the prestigious closing night slot.
</P>
<P>
   A collaboration of the Quinn brothers _ star Aidan,
cinematographer Declan and writer-director Paul _ it's a
labor-of-love, family project that tells the story of a Chicago
schoolteacher (James Caan) who stumbles upon a 50-year-old photo of
his mother and a man who likely was the father he never knew.
</P>
<P>
   Unsatisfied with his own life and obsessed with the mystery of
his family background, he impulsively takes his own troubled son to
their ancestral village in Ireland, and pieces together the story
of his mother's star-crossed love affair _ which we see in
flashback.
</P>
<P>
   The movie somehow fails to be something truly memorable, but
it's touching, full of the moody magic of Ireland, and well-acted
by a cast that includes not only Caan, Aidan Quinn and John Cusack,
but a virtual who who's of the New Irish Cinema: Stephen Rea, Colm
Meany, Donal Donnelly and Brendan Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   The Swindle. Directed and written by Claude Chabrol. Cast:
Isabelle Huppert, Michel Serrault, Francois Cluzet, Jean-Francois
Balmer. New Yorker Films. 105 minutes. In French with English
subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   This is My Father. Directed and written by Paul Quinn. Cast:
Aidan Quinn, James Caan, John Cusack, Stephen Rea, Moya Farrelly,
Brendan Gleeson. Sony Classics. 120 minutes. Rated R for mature
themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
