<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds investigating potential dragging case in South Carolina
 &HT;    By Lyn Riddle
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTREE, S.C._ They call the area ``on the crick,'' a cluster
of country homes beside a creek, where, by reputation, someone
looking for drugs can find them.
</P>
<P>
   Local deputies know Bloomingvale all too well. Now, state and
federal agents are getting to know it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Williamsburg County Sheriff Kelvin Washington has asked for a
full-blown investigation into a black man's claims he was dragged
beside a truck by two white men, even though the sheriff doubts the
incident was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Texas,'' said Washington, referring to the recent
Jasper, Texas, case in which three white men were charged with
murder in the dragging death of a black man. ``It is unknown and
uncertain whether this is racially motivated. We are not ruling out
the possibility it was drug-related.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said the two white men were driving through
predominately black Bloomingvale at about 1 a.m. in a red pickup
truck that allegedly was stolen. The two came upon Sharon Green,
23, standing in a driveway. The men stopped to ask directions,
Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow Green ended up halfway into the vehicle and they took
off,'' said Washington. ``It is undetermined whether they were
holding him or he was holding them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some law enforcement officers here said they believe it was a
drug deal gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   But Green told a Charleston television station the passenger in
the truck grabbed his arm as the driver sped off. The passenger did
not let go until he bit him, Green said. He said he was dragged
about a quarter-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Green's right leg and ankle, right arm and lips were injured,
the incident report says. Washington said Green was treated and
released from an area hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Eric W. Jones, 38, of Gastonia, N.C., and Arthur Marshall, 35,
of Georgetown, S.C., have been charged with assault and battery
with intent to kill. Marshall, who has family in the area
</P>
<P>
   and criminal convictions including assault and grand larceny
dating back to 1981, was also charged with possession of a stolen
vehicle. The men were in custody in the Williamsburg County
Detention Center Thursday afternoon. No bond had been set.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has called on the FBI and the South Carolina State
Law Enforcement Division to see if Green's civil rights were
violated or if other charges are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Munn, SLED spokesman, said state agents will take
statements from witnesses and gather physical evidence before
filing a report with the local solicitor. South Carolina does not
</P>
<P>
   have a hate crime law.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will look into possible civil rights violations, and
will turn over its report to the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton came to this area of tobacco and soybean farms
in 1996 to help celebrate the rebuilding of Mount Zion AME Church,
a black church burned by two men with ties to a local Ku Klux Klan
group.
</P>
<P>
   Riddle writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
