<HEADER>
A3859 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FLOOR-SPI &LR;      05-27 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FLOOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`13TH FLOOR' HAS SOME NICE PRODUCTION TOUCHES AND CHALLENGING
SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood's latest movie about a computer-generated universe,
``The 13th Floor,'' is, in its own way, no less imaginative than
``eXistenZ,'' or ``The Matrix,'' but it definitely suffers from
being the third cat out of the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw the first two entries in this 1999 mini-cycle
will sit through this latest one with a certain sense of deja vu.
The two teenagers who sat in front of me at a preview screening
(discussing every scene as it happened in a loud voice) certainly
did.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, you're new to the concept of a
computer-generated alternate world, you may just find much to enjoy
here. The film has a wonderfully noir-ish production design and a
challenging script that takes its premise straight to max.
</P>
<P>
   It's about an L.A. software company that, over six years time,
has painstakingly built a model of the city in 1937 (complete with
``thinking'' characters) that can be downloaded into the human
brain, so the recipient can enter that world as if transported by a
time machine.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, the aged creator of the program (Armin
Mueller-Stahl) is in this world, but has discovered a serious
problem with it _ a problem that, for no reason that makes any
sense, he commits to paper and leaves with a bartender in the old
Ambassador Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns to the real world of 1999 L.A., he's promptly
murdered, and it becomes the task of his handsome young successor
(Craig Bierko) to journey to the simulated L.A., interview the
various ``characters'' the old man met there, and find the message.
</P>
<P>
   Like the two earlier films, this one requires you to swallow a
preposterous concept that really doesn't stand up to any analysis.
If you think about it too hard, the absurdity of it creeps in, and
makes it hard to stay in that necessary state of suspended
disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   As co-produced by Roland Emmerich (``Godzilla'') and directed
and co-written by his protege, Josef Rusnak _ members of
Hollywood's growing German emigre community _ the film also has a
certain heavy-handedness and ponderousness to the action and chase
scenes, which seem drawn-out, overdone and emotionally uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, charismatic newcomer Bierko does surprisingly
well with his first starring role, the several big twists of the
script are clever and fun, and the production design of the '90s
sequences nicely evokes the stylish bleakness of ``Blade Runner''
(to the point of using some of the same L.A. locations).
</P>
<P>
   The visual recreation of Depression-era L.A. may be
anachronistic (it actually looks more like 1910 L.A.) but the
dream-like, desaturated images are haunting, and indicate that _ as
James Cameron discovered with ``Titanic'' _ the more fertile domain
for computer-animation in the new century may be less the
unappealing future as the lost past.
</P>
<P>
   The 13th Floor. Directed by Josef Rusnak. Screenplay by Joseph
Rusnak &AMP; Ravel Centeno-Rodriguez. Cast: Craig Bierko, Gretchen Mol,
Vincent D'Ononfrio. Columbia. 100 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0305 </DOCNO>
