<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODJOBS-COX     05-27 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODJOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian job program delivers a paycheck, spiritual aid
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM _ Cheryl O'Hair has found Microsoft Windows, the
minimum wage and God. Suddenly, she says, life doesn't look so
bleak.
</P>
<P>
   She's been tricked by false hope before. In those days, she
relied on whiskey and AA meetings.
</P>
<P>
   When she was taking home $500 a week selling alarm systems for
ADT Security, O'Hair figured she finally had moved past two failed
marriages, bouts with alcoholism and a hodge-podge of rotating
jobs. But she just couldn't stop buying as much Crown Royal as she
could drink. Alone, she had spent her days crying and sleeping on
her couch contemplating ``impending doom.'' She quit her
door-to-door sales job after three months. The bank repossessed her
Toyota Celica. She lost her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at rock bottom,'' said the 39-year-old, who ended up
living in government housing and losing custody of her 14-year-old
son.
</P>
<P>
   She feels she's on the rise _ this time for real. Following the
suggestion of a friend, O'Hair discovered self-sufficiency and
salvation through the Christian Women's Job Corps.
</P>
<P>
   During an Atlanta campaign stop Monday, Vice President Al Gore
said the program is a tonic for what ails American society. While
proposing new financial partnerships between the federal government
and religion-based agencies, Gore called the Birmingham-based
program a model of spiritual aid.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs program, an offshoot of the Southern Baptist
Convention, trains women to fend for themselves. It started two
years ago and has expanded nationwide to 100 cities. There's a
similar group in Peachtree City, Ga., and multiple programs in
Florida, South Carolina, Tennessee, North Carolina, Kentucky and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they are religious or not, most Americans are hungry
for a deeper connection between politics and moral values,'' said
Gore, treading on ground traditionally held by Republicans.
``Americans profoundly _ rightly _ believe that politics and
morality are deeply interrelated. They want to reconnect the
American spirit to the body politic.''
</P>
<P>
   Spirituality fills a gap in today's culture, O'Hair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what's happening in schools now,'' she said. ``They've
taken prayer out of school and look what's going on. I believe
everybody needs God.''
</P>
<P>
   A bonus: The Christian job program also delivers a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Certified volunteers teach five-week classes. An expert on labor
relations from BellSouth conducts mock interviews. A horse farmer
gives lessons on money management. Community professionals donate
clothes for interviews and for the first days on the job.
Volunteers canvass businesses for second-hand computers.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair makes $6 an hour _$9 on Sundays _ as a church janitor.
When she cried on her couch, she thought mostly about survival. Now
she has the gumption to think about going to school and becoming a
paramedic. On Tuesday, she begins paying her own rent _
$300-a-month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work with them as long as it takes,'' said Anna
Holmes, who runs one of Birmingham's four programs. She registers
about 50 women a year and half find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a notebook, pen, pencil and a binder outlining basic
job skills, the Christian job program gives its graduates a Bible.
Daily devotionals are as integral as learning how to keep a budget.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Gore invited the group to be a founding member of his
Welfare to Work Coalition, a task force that, among other things,
helps women find ways to climb out of poverty. The four Birmingham
programs operate on $84,500 a year from donations and grants. The
nonprofit organization pays each of its coordinators about $12,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, while Gore backs ``carefully tailored partnerships''
with faith-based groups, the Christian Women's Job Corps refuses
federal entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a historical and Biblical perspective, we feel neither
the church or state should interfere with each other,'' said Trudy
Johnson, national director for the Christian Women's Job Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and civil libertarians look skeptically on Gore's
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's reading the same polls everyone else is,'' said GOP
pollster Whit Ayres. ``The economy is good and many in the public
say that what's wrong can't be fixed by the government but by
something in the spiritual realm. ... It's a tough sell for the
party that has made a religion today of taking religion out of
public life.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's an easy sell to O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more spiritual than religious,'' O'Hair said. ``It's not
like organized religion. You come in and you share your experience.
No one's telling you what God to follow. There's not as much dogma
as in a church.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair shares traits with many of the program's students. She
was a single mom with little education, age 30 to 45 with no job
training and little life experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a dead-end cycle,'' Holmes said. ``But the jobs are
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Thurman, 42, never had been to a job interview until Holmes
helped her get a job at The Greater Birmingham Humane Society.
Before that, Thurman said, she had been spending nearly every penny
she made _ $100 to $300 a week _ on drugs, usually crack cocaine.
She lost her house and bounced between relatives. Eventually, ``no
one wanted to see me.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Holmes, Thurman enrolled in job preparation
classes. She had never seen a resume. Technology was beyond her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I had seen a computer was at the food stamp
office,'' said Thurman, who now catalogues animals on her desktop
PC.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman becomes a full-time employee in a few days. She splits
her rent with the government, paying $286 a month from her own
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a hopeless situation,'' Thurman said. ``But
being with positive people just boosted my confidence. Now I have a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
