r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS28-COX     05-27 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore says GOP trying to shoot down gun control measures
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As House Republicans held their first hearing on
proposed gun control legislation, Vice President Gore appeared on
Capitol Hill Thursday to accuse the GOP leadership of seeking to
kill the measures with needless delays.
</P>
<P>
   Are they ``genuinely troubled over the details of the
legislative language?'' asked Gore, flanked by more than a dozen
House Democrats. ``Of course not. It is because some within the
Republican caucus are so responsive to the NRA. They are hoping
against hope that if they can slow-walk this whole measure, then
the American people will lose the sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   The House adjourned for the Memorial Day recess without taking
up the gun legislation, though House Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.) has pledged a vote by mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore's second appearance on Capitol Hill in just a week
to lobby lawmakers on tougher gun control legislation in the wake
of shootings in Littleton, Colo., and Conyers. Last week, Gore cast
the deciding vote on a Senate provision that would require gun
buyers to undergo criminal background checks at gun shows just as
they do at gun shops, closing the so-called gun show loophole.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions include requiring trigger locks and safety
storage boxes to be sold with all handguns and banning the
importation of large ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   Those testifying at Thursday's Judiciary subcommittee hearing
included the top lobbyists of the gun lobby, including National
Rifle Association executive vice president Wayne LaPierre, and the
parents of teen shooting victims.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Scott, the father of a teenage daughter killed at
Columbine High School and a son who was wounded, told lawmakers not
to scapegoat the NRA and work to re-integrate God and prayer into
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think guns kill people without people behind those
guns,'' said Scott, urging lawmakers to avoid ``political posturing
and restrictive legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia mother of a teenage son gunned down ten years broke
down in tears as she described how her son, Scott Phillips-Taylor,
was shot six times with an AK-47 assault rifle stolen by a troubled
teen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns killed my son,'' said Byrl Phillips-Taylor, crying
softly. ``The easy availability of guns got my baby killed.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre, whose 3-million member organization waged a fierce
lobbying effort against aspects of the Senate bill, urged Congress
to enforce existing laws, rather than pass new ones.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre said the NRA would accept ``instant'' background checks
at gun shows, but would reject the current language of the Senate
bill, which allows law enforcement three days to conduct the checks
and defines gun shows as any gathering where more than 50 firearms
are sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a red tape nightmare,'' LaPierre said. ``It's a
massive ... federal government bill that gets into everyone's life
if you just mention the word 'firearm.'''
</P>
<P>
   Before hearing from LaPierre, two Clinton administrated
officials testified about the president's proposals for reducing
gun violence, including limiting handgun purchases to one a month
and re-instating the three day waiting period for handgun sales.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, criticized the officials for failing to
enforce existing gun laws. They demanded to know why criminals
denied a gun by the instant background check were not prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder acknowledged that federal
prosecutions were low, but said most gun violations were prosecuted
at the state and local level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than talking about the gun show loophole, let's talk
about the current loophole that allows criminals to avoid
prosecution,'' said Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), an NRA board member.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Barr suggested that if a copy of the Ten Commandments
had been hanging in the hallways of Columbine and Heritage High in
Conyers, as it does in his own congressional office, ``we would not
have had the tragedies that bring us here today.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the media, Gore called on the House to adopt
even tougher gun restrictions than those included in the Senate
bill. But after he had departed House minority leader Richard
Gephardt (D-Mo.) said he would be happy ``if we could simply pass
what the Senate passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats blame huge losses in the 1994 elections on
unpopular votes they cast in 1993 and 1994 on handgun waiting
periods and an assault weapons ban. Democratic leaders are
reluctant to push to hard on gun control for fear of creating
similar problems for Democrats, particularly in rural Southern
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue on which there is not absolute consensus,''
Gephardt acknowledged. ``I think a vast majority of Democrats will
vote for reasonable, moderate gun safety legislation, and I think
you'll find that when we get the bill on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
