<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VACATION-HNS &LR;      05-27 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VACATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS TAKE TIME OUT TO RELAX ON FLORIDA PLANTATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YULEE, Fla. _ While Republicans roar about Chinese spying and
Democrats crow about Hillary Rodham Clinton's future political
plans, the only commotion the Clintons are likely to hear this week
might be coming from amorous white rhinoceroses.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the first lady are taking a pause from
what has been a rather tumultuous year to relax at the White Oak
Plantation, a 7,500-acre conservatory and timber operation near the
Georgia border owned by the Howard Gilman Foundation. Howard
Gilman, who died two years ago, owned one of the largest privately
held paper and building products companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The plantation includes an array of exotic wildlife, including a
white rhinoceros mother and her 4-week-old baby, who reside just
outside of the two-story, cedar-sided house, where the Clintons are
staying through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The five-day vacation is designed to be relatively low-key, with
no prominent guests arriving until the weekend when the Progressive
Policy Institute, a group of moderate Democrats, will gather here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it,'' Clinton said, when asked about the respite from
the ordeals of the nation's capital. So far this year the president
survived an impeachment effort and plunged the nation into a
bombing campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple seem intent on keeping outside distractions to
a minimum. The traveling White House press has been kept at a
distance, housed a half-hour's drive away and across a bridge on
Amelia Island along the Atlantic Ocean. Unlike their favorite
vacation spot of Martha's Vineyard, the opportunities for outside
socializing are limited in the four-stoplight town of Yulee, where
the only Dunkin Donuts just closed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the outside world can't help but intrude as the
conflict in Yugoslavia continues and Congress considers a new
report that details how China stole classified military information
over decades.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the buzz continues to grow over Hillary Clinton's likely
plans to run for the Senate from New York. The first lady is
reportedly using some of the down time to put the finishing touches
on her plans to launch an exploratory committee to replace retiring
Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. She is expected to face
the feisty Republican mayor of New York City, Rudolph Guiliani, in
what political observers predict could be one of the most
pugnacious matches of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This week New York Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope confirmed
that Hillary Clinton was likely to announce the exploratory
committee by late June or July.
</P>
<P>
   Hope said that Hillary Clinton called her from Florida to
inquire about spending part of the summer visiting families in
upstate New York, a Republican-tilting region in a largely
Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seems very exuberant and very excited,'' said Hope. ``Her
commitment seems to be increasing toward this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the speculation about her political plans were reports
that the Clintons are checking real estate in Westchester County,
the leafy suburbs north of New York City, where the president is
more apt to find a good golf course.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been no comment here from the first lady. A press
spokesman said her big activity of the day was bike riding with the
president. On Sunday, she is expected to participate in the seminar
put on by centrist Democrats, which may be an effort to soften
likely attacks from New York Republicans that she is an unabashed
liberal who helped mastermind the administration's politically
disastrous national health-care plan in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The president also will participate in the Democratic group's
conference. But until then he has played plenty of golf on the
plantation's nine-hole course.
</P>
<P>
   While he may not have had lots of company, Clinton did have his
dog Buddy, who bounded off Air Force One with the president when he
landed at Jacksonville Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The president also brought plenty of reading material, including
Carl Hiassen's ``Lucky You,'' Robert Parker's ``Sudden Mischief''
and Tony Campolo's ``A Reasonable Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the president had totally left behind voters' concerns.
Aides noted that Clinton also brought along weightier reading
matter, including a binder of Medicare information. The
administration is expected to unveil its proposals for shoring up
the federal health-care program for the elderly soon.
</P>
<P>
   The president also could not escape the situation in Yugoslavia,
and took time out to issue a statement supporting the decision by
the International War Crimes Tribunal to indict Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   He also telephoned European leaders to confer about the air
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The president did not comment on the Cox report to Congress that
revealed widespread theft of U.S. nuclear technology by China.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans were quick to note that the embarrassing report
came out as Clinton headed to vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National committee chairman Jim Nicholson, through a
spokesman, quipped that Clinton is ``joining the ostriches with his
head in the sand the day after the Cox committee exposed the worst
case of espionage in the U.S. history under his watch.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, there are no ostriches at the White Oak
plantation, although there are wolves, tigers, lizards and a
cockatoo. The Clintons took a tour of that animal kingdom,
including a compound where white rhinos were in the midst of the
mating season.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart defended the president's decision
to take some time off in the midst of the varying crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important from time to time to take the chances to get
away,'' Lockhart said. ``I don't think there is any worry on their
part about appearances here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
