<HEADER>
A3868 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW, A FEW MESSAGES FROM JERRY GARCIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wendy Weir &LR; , sister of Grateful Dead guitarist  &UR; Bob Weir &LR;  and a
veteran of careers in ``finance and environmental education,''
claims to have conversed with  &UR; Jerry Garcia &LR;  after his death.
Weir's new book is ``In the Spirit: Conversations With the Spirit
of Jerry Garcia'' (Harmony; $24).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the book was an agreement Jerry and I had before
this life, before being incarnated here on Earth,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After this life, however, there were problems. Weir wasn't in
touch with Garcia until August 1996, a year after his death, when,
she says, she was able to ``break through.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's spirit ``looks like a brilliant, white-gold beam
radiating out from a center of pure light,'' writes Weir. He urges
the Grateful Dead survivors to continue playing together, and tells
the author he wants her to be an example from whom others may
learn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRANSIT ISSUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower Your Cholesterol Day festivities, including a planned
giveaway of 25,000 bagels shmeared with the margarine substitute
Benecol at San Francisco's Justin Herman Plaza on Wednesday
morning, were canceled after the food truck broke down near
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   _ The drivers are fine:  &UR; Ann Byington &LR;  applauds the 19-Polk bus
driver she saw present each (delighted) child on his bus with a bag
of potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   _ And the passengers are fine, too: We were aboard a 45-Union
whose passengers looked the other way when the driver tried to sign
up witnesses after a fender-bender. When the driver of the car
involved appeared in the bus doorway to blame the accident on the
bus driver, at least half the passengers _ outraged by what they
perceived as an unfair charge _ changed their minds and filled out
witness forms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some imp has been going around painting out an ``n'' in
``Hemingway Dined at Jack's'' signs atop cabs. But no, Papa didn't
die there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Secure Wrap, an outfit in Miami, New York and Panama, charges
about $9 to wrap a traveler's suitcase in plastic, which isn't
impenetrable but is considered a deterrent to airport thieves, says
Maxim magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Metropolitan Transportation Commission voted to spend
about $1.7 million _ funds that will need final approval from
Caltrans and the feds _ for renovating the 16th Street BART station
in San Francisco and $350,000 for Pioneer Park atop Telegraph Hill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Motorcyclists in Tennessee have organized a letter-writing
campaign to complain about the recent naming of a stretch of state
highway after a state senator who killed a motorcyclist in a
hit-and-run crash in 1996.  &UR; Carl O. Koella Jr. &LR; , who died in
January 1998 after heart surgery, had pleaded no contest to the
hit-and-run charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the highway named after Koella ends on the road
where the accident took place. ``Soon to come,'' prophesies
Citybike magazine, ``the Jack Kevorkian Hospice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspired by mention of  &UR; George Washington &LR; 's dogs, a local
historian reports that  &UR; Calvin Coolidge &LR;  had a raccoon named
Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What I don't want,''  &UR; Cosimo Cavallaro &LR; , an artist who has
plastered every surface of a Manhattan hotel room with melted Swiss
cheese, told People magazine, ``is to become known as the Cheese
Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In London, the Sun ran a full-page apology Thursday on Page 8
for publishing topless photos of  &UR; Sophie Rhys-Jones &LR;  on Page 1 the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading about the movie ``Alien'' playing on the TV in a
government immigration office,  &UR; Lloyd Chiswick &LR;  was reminded of the
last time he called the IRS, when the music on hold was ``The
Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Listings:  &UR; Richard Delwiche &LR;  noticed a University of San
Francisco classified ad in Sunday's paper looking for help in the
``Duel  &LR; Degree Program,'' which he says must have a pretty high
dropout rate. And  &UR; Sandy Malloy &LR;  noticed an ad in a local weekly
placed by that weekly, looking for a worker who would be paid
salary ``commiserate with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  has delivered a sermon, ``When I Lay My Burdens
Down,'' at Glide Memorial Church in San Francisco. Stone told a
packed church not to hang onto things that are destructive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not all, you know, Cameron Diaz. There's got to be some
of us who don't represent the beautiful people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Actress Rachel Griffiths in Interview magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
