<P>
   INFINITY-OUTDOOR (Undated) _ Infinity, the radio and billboard
giant controlled by CBS Corp., significantly expanded its presence
in out-of-home advertising Thursday by acquiring the No. 1 company
in that field, Outdoor Systems Inc. of Phoenix, for about $6.5
billion in stock. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Top display)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BEER (Mexico City) _ At Key Food in Queens, N.Y., a
six-pack of Corona Extra costs $6.99 plus tax. For the same beer,
supermarkets here charge less than $2.50. For Mexicans who regard
Corona as a humble, even low-rent beer, it is something of a
mystery why drinkers in the United States are eager to pay so much
for it. Corona's triumph is a testimony to the power of clever
marketing. By Rick Wills.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ How much more do Internet
stocks have to fall before many investors lose interest? Not much,
according to the latest mutual-fund data. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom center)
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-PINAULT (Rome) _ Gucci Group triumphed Thursday in the
latest round of a struggle to thwart a hostile bid by its bigger
rival, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, when a Dutch court upheld
Gucci's sale of shares to the French department store group
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute SA. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom right)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-BOOK (Undated) _ Less than a year after Bertelsmann AG
purchased Random House and blended it with existing holdings into
the nation's largest publishing house, top executives moved
Thursday to consolidate some of its long-established imprints,
which produce popular paperbacks and hardcovers. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's other regular features:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices resumed their losing ways
Thursday as rising long-term interest rates prompted many investors
to cash in profits on the approach of a long holiday weekend. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
