<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, May 28, and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   SHAG-AOL (Los Angeles) _ It's quite a bit smaller than the
distribution of ``Star Wars'' tickets, but AOL has teamed up with
New Line Cinema to sell advance tickets to ``Austin Powers: The Spy
Who Shagged Me'' for showings on the night before the official
opening. In an industry first, tickets will only be available
online until a few days before the June 10 screenings. By Dave
McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   XIRCOM-YAHOO (Los Angeles) _ Xircom Corp. has not gotten word
from Yahoo! about the identity of the person who Xircom claims has
posted illegal messages about the company on the Web site's
investors forum. But John Doe has hired an attorney who filed a
motion to quash Xircom's subpoena to Yahoo! to divulge John Doe's
identity. By Deborah Adamson. (Will move in the ``f'' financial
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-HOWARD (Los Angeles) _ Workers and other creditors of a
defunct firm partly owned by Congressman Howard P. McKeon, R-Santa
Clarita, got more disappointing news Thursday when an auction of
the company's assets failed to result in a successful bid. By Jason
Takenouchi. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
