<SLUG> BC-INDIA-KASHMIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN CLAIMS TWO INDIAN JETS DOWNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pakistan Thursday claimed it shot down two Indian
combat jets over the disputed territory of Kashmir, further
inflaming a border conflict between the rival nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The shootdown _ and two days of Indian air attacks on hundreds
of separatist invaders _ represented the most serious escalation in
tensions between the countries in a decade, pushing them
dangerously toward their fourth war since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   It has prompted a series of diplomatic appeals for calm from
Washington, the European Union, and the United Nations. US
Assistant Secretary of State Rick Inderfurth urged India's and
Pakistan's ambassadors in Washington to show restraint and stop the
fighting from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about rising escalation of violence in
Kashmir,'' said US National Security Council spokesman Mike Hammer.
``We have appealed to the governments in both India and Pakistan''
to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, India launched a major air assault against Muslim
guerrillas crossing from Pakistan into Indian-controlled territory
in Kashmir. India announced it would continue to use fighter jets
and attack helicopters to dislodge some 400 Muslim separatists that
it claims have infiltrated India in recent weeks with the backing
of the Pakistani army.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has dealt a blow to a February agreement between
India and Pakistan to use peaceful means to resolve the
half-century-old dispute over control of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   US officials and other analysts said that the course of the
conflict is highly unpredictable. But they expressed confidence
that India and Pakistan would have the sense to climb down from its
current confrontation, noting that the countries' leaders have been
in telephone contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this will escalate to war by any means,'' said
Ashley Tellis, a military analyst on South Asia at the Rand
Corporation in California. Tellis believes that Pakistan's
orchestrated the rebel incursion into India-controlled Kashmir in
an attempt to restart flagging peace talks over the fate of
disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan's chief objective was to embarrass New Delhi, let
them know that normalcy will not return to the border without a
settlement and to remind them there are lots of Afghan militants
willing to carry on the fight,'' Tellis said. ``Now that India has
called their bluff, Pakistan has no reason to go on. It has
achieved its objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has vowed to keep on shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pakistan Armed Forces are ready to defend the territorial
integrity of our motherland at every cost,'' said Major General
Anis Bajwa, Pakistan's vice chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials said Thursday that a pair of jets, a Mig 21
and a Mig 27, were hit with ground fire as they ``intruded into our
air space.'' The jets were recovered more than four miles behind
the border, according to Pakistani authorities.
</P>
<P>
   India admitted that one of its fighters was downed by Pakistan.
But it insisted that the second jet was brought down by mechanical
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need to panic,'' said Brajesh Mishra, a security
adviser to Prime Minsiter Atal Behari Vajpayee. ``We do not think
that is will escalate into a war.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over Kashmir dates to the birth of two nations. The
mountainous region has been contested since Pakistan and India each
became independent in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, which has long sought greater UN involvement in
mediating the dispute, urged the world body to send an envoy to the
region and reinforce a tiny UN military observer force that has
been monitoring the dispute since 1948, making it the
longest-running UN operation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the UN Security Council passed a resolution calling for
a referendum on whether the territory should become part of India
or Pakistan. It has been divided by an uneasy and shifting cease
fire line ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have been particularly high since a separatist Muslim
movement took up arms against the predominantly Hindu nation of
India nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say that artillery exchanges and commando raids across
the cease fire line are routine at this time of year, when the snow
begins to melt in the Kashmir highlands. And dozens of combatants _
including Afghan veterans of the war against the former Soviet
Union _ die each year during the exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
