<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3880 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-CONSENT-HNS &LR;      05-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CONSENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDES CLASH OVER TEEN ABORTION LEGISLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A conservative congressman and like-minded
professors clashed with liberal lawmakers and a doctors' group
Thursday over legislation that would bar people from transporting
pregnant girls across state lines to circumvent local laws
requiring parents to be notified before abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., chairman of a House Judiciary
subcommittee, said the proposal would ensure the rights of parents
in states with parental-notification laws to be apprised of their
daughters' medical care. But Rep. Maxine Waters of California, a
senior Democrat on Canady's Constitution Subcommittee, assailed the
proposed Child Custody Protection Act as ``a thinly veiled attempt
to chip away at a constitutionally protected right'' of girls and
women to terminate their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Texas law, at least for now, does not require parents to be
notified when their young daughters seek abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The pending federal legislation is designed to end the practice
of adults escorting girls into Texas and other states with relaxed
abortion laws. Under the measure, adults who transport girls across
states lines for abortions could be sentenced up to one year in
jail and fined.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas law is expected to change soon. Gov. George W. Bush is
predicted to sign legislation on his desk that would require
doctors to notify parents by telephone or mail two days before
performing an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant girls fearing violence from their parents could bypass
the notification requirement with a judge's consent.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a hearing of his subcommittee Thursday, Canady said
the federal proposal would end the practice of people interfering
with parents' involvement in a critical medical decision affecting
their children. The Florida Republican said parents usually are the
most knowledgeable about their daughters' medical history,
information a doctor must have before performing an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across this county, a child can't even be given an aspirin at
school without her parent's permission,'' Canady said. ``It is not
surprising, then, that many states have decided that a serious
surgical procedure like abortion should also involve the child's
parents, or in some cases, a judge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-backed legislation has virtually no Democratic
support in the House or Senate and little chance of becoming law
with President Clinton, an abortion rights advocate. But the
measure has given supporters and opponents of abortion rights a
focal point around which to continue debate.
</P>
<P>
   Though not participants at the subcommittee hearing, Planned
Parenthood Federation of America and the National Right to Life
Committee issued dueling statements on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planned Parenthood encourages young women to involve their
parents when they face an unintended pregnancy and are considering
abortion,'' the abortion rights group said. ``But not every family
is a model family. (The legislation) would place young women who
are unable to talk with their parents at risk _ and treat the
people they turn to for help as criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered the National Right to Life Committee: ``By passing the
Child Custody Protection Act, Congress would take a clear stand
against the bizarre notion that the U.S. Constitution confers a
`right' upon strangers to take one's minor daughter across state
lines for a secret abortion, even when a state law specifically
requires the involvement of a parent or judge in the daughter's
abortion decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before the subcommittee, University of Texas law
professor Lino Graglia praised the proposed law as a legal and
appropriate way for Congress to regulate abortion.
</P>
<P>
   University of Virginia law professor John Harrison agreed that
Congress has the constitutional authority to make it illegal to
transport pregnant girls across state lines for abortions. He said
Congress' exclusive authority to regulate interstate commerce
extends to the interstate transportation of people _ a comment that
drew fire from Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., a subcommittee member.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Harrison's testimony, Nadler said he knew of no
federal law that bars people from escorting others to another state
for the purpose of engaging in a lawful activity. ``Could Congress
make it illegal for citizens of New York to go to New Jersey to
gamble?'' Nadler asked.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Klein of the American Academy of Pediatrics said
the legislation would do pregnant girls a disservice by making it
more difficult for them to seek medical care. The girls,
apprehensive due to their pregnancies, must be able to consult
doctors free of the fear that their parents will be notified, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A teen struggling with concerns over his or her sexual health
may be reluctant to share these concerns with a parent for fear of
embarrassment, disapproval or possible violence,'' Klein told the
subcommittee. ``The guarantee of confidentiality and the
adolescent's awareness of this guarantee are both essential in
helping adolescents to seek health care.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
