<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-27 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID NEWS OF INDICTMENT, HEAVIEST BOMBING YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ NATO conducted its heaviest bombing raids yet on
Yugoslavia Thursday as the international War Crimes Tribunal
accused the nation's president, Slobodan Milosevic, and four top
aides of being personally responsible for war crimes committed in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary indictment of a sitting head of state, Chief
Prosecutor Louise Arbour of the United Nations War Crimes Tribunal
in The Hague accused Milosevic and his aides of ordering,
executing, instigating, or aiding and abetting the murder of 340
Kosovar Albanians and the deportation of 740,000 others from Kosovo
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The five have ``personal criminal responsibility'' for the
alleged ``crimes against humanity,'' Arbour said, and not simply
``command responsibility.'' The distinction means that the men are
accused of being intimately involved in the murders and
deportations, and not just culpable as leaders whose forces
committed the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment ``says to the hundreds of thousands of victims of
atrocities in Kosovo that their voices have been heard,'' President
Clinton said from his Florida vacation post.
</P>
<P>
   The government in Belgrade dismissed the allegations, calling
Arbour a ``puppet in the hands of the masters of war.'' The
indictment _ coming as Russian Balkans envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin
readied to travel to the Yugoslav capital for peace talks _ ``is
just another way of stopping diplomatic attempts to solve the
crisis through peaceful political negotiations,'' the state-run
Tanjug news agency said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   NATO stepped up the pressure as well, announcing Thursday it had
flown the highest number of attack sorties _ 741 _ in the 66-day
war. Thursday evening in Belgrade, the power went out after a loud
explosion, believed to be a hit on an oil refinery, was heard.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia upped its defense as well, firing at least 33
surface-to-air missiles against the attacking planes, NATO
spokesmen said, more than three times the daily average. One of
them jolted an F-16 fighter with a near-miss.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is benefiting from an improvement in both the weather and
its geographic launching capability. With the conclusion of
agreements for the use of air space in Romania and Bulgaria, along
with the stationing of 24 F-18 fighter planes in Hungary, Milosevic
is virtually surrounded by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're boxing him in,'' said a Marine pilot at Hungary's
southern air base in Taszar.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Milosevic has a lot of military capability,'' NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea said Thursday, and Yugoslav air defenses and
runways are being continually repaired after NATO has damaged them.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Milosevic, the indictment names Serbian President
Milan Milutinovic, who is commander of Serb forces in Kosovo and
who was present at the failed peace talks in France earlier this
year. The other accused are Nikola Sainovic, a Yugoslav deputy
prime minister and close aide to Milosevic; Vlajko Stojiljkovic,
Serbia's Interior Minister, and Dragoljub Ojdanic, head of the
Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   But if indicting the leaders is dramatic, catching them is
trickier. Just a few more than half of the 84 publicly accused war
criminals from the Bosnian war have been apprehended or have turned
themselves into The Hague, human rights workers note. The biggest
names _ Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic _ are among those at
large, and are believed to be hiding among loyalists in Serbia and
Republika Srpska, the Serb part of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very unlikely'' Milosevic will be apprehended or
volunteer himself to the tribunal, said Colin Soloway, an analyst
with the Sarajevo-based International Crisis Group.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments were hailed by human rights leaders, who have
long accused Milosevic and his cronies of committing atrocities in
not only Kosovo, but in Bosnia and Croatia during the 1992-95 wars
there. Arbour said she was still investigating allegations of war
crimes committed in all three locales.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the 41-page indictment said, Serb police hunted
down villagers hiding in a Kosovo forest two days after the bombing
began. The police ordered the women and children to go to Albania,
and demanded identity documents from the males.
</P>
<P>
   The men and boys were herded into a house, and ``Serb police
opened fire on the group. After several minutes of gunfire, the
police piled hay on the men and boys and set fire to it in order to
burn the bodies,'' the indictment said, killing 105 Kosovar
Albanian males.
</P>
<P>
   The account is similar to stories told by legions of refugees
who fled or were forced to Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro in the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said the West could
negotiate even with an indicted war criminal, if it meant an
acceptable agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to rule out future contact if it helps us
achieve our objectives,'' Rubin told reporters. ``But there is no
deal on an immunity to be cut, and we will not support efforts by
anyone to suggest it.''
</P>
<P>
   Austria's secretary general for foreign affairs, Albert Rohan,
Austria's top career diplomat, said the indictment of Milosevic was
long overdue and that there would not be any immediate effect on
attempts to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment ``firms him up in the opinion that he cannot give
in,'' Rohan said, but Milosevic will not drastically change his
perspective because he already was strongly resolved not to
compromise Serbia's dominion over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Many diplomats exprienced in Balkan affairs ``were quite amazed
the tribunal did not proceed sooner,'' he said, adding that he and
other leaders had been in direct contact with the tribunal on the
matter and were ``always told that there was an important
difference between information and truth. Countries in possession
of evidence withheld it for various reasons, presumably
political,'' until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Arbour's work is independent of any military strategy or
diplomatic negotiations, U.N. officials said. ``The prosecutor must
therefore go where the evidence leads her,'' U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said in a statement. ``Justice must be allowed to take
its course.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbour said the indictment was not timed to assist or interfere
with NATO's objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will say the indictment comes too late; others will say
it came too soon. I say it was perfectly appropriate because it was
governed by the demands of our mandate,'' she told reporters in The
Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have anything to lose now,'' Soloway said. ``He
could go down in flames, creating as much chaos as possible'' in
Kosovo and politically tenuous Montenegro in the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the real end game for Slobo, I think,'' Soloway said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Charles Radin contributed to this article from
Vienna.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
