<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3886 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-INHERIT-SPI &LR;      05-27 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-INHERIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INHERIT THE WIND' WORTH A LOOK, IF ONLY TO SEE LEMMON, SCOTT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kermit said it best. It's not easy being green.
</P>
<P>
   Differentness is, well, different. Sticking out like a sore
thumb, or like an amphibian among dry-land creatures, will get you
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   For some, this individuality remains the ultimate quest, life's
irresistible aphrodisiac. For others, individuality is not so much
sought after as it is a natural byproduct of personal growth.
Either way, it comes at a price, sometimes affordable, sometimes
not.
</P>
<P>
   With all the subtlety of an inflated ego, Showtime presents a
seminar on the suggested retail price of individualism this
weekend, pairing two worthy study aids: ``The Passion of Ayn Rand''
and a remake of ``Inherit the Wind.'' Both films are period pieces
based in fact, with ``Ayn Rand'' coming out slightly ahead on the
satisfaction meter.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Inherit the Wind,'' the fictionalized story of the John
Scopes ``monkey trial,'' is also worth a look, if only to see Jack
Lemmon and George C. Scott sparring in the courtroom as the thinly
veiled individualists, Clarence Darrow and William Jennings Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   The film has some problems, notably a reliance on unimaginative
scenes lifted whole from the movie-of-the-week handbook. But Lemmon
and Scott trudge slowly up Mount Banal to present an entertaining
debate on the sanctity of individual thought vs. the venerability
of the unthinking collective. It's a pleasant, leisurely walk,
punctuated by Beau Bridges' gently acidic take on the sharp-tongued
journalist, H.L. Mencken.
</P>
<P>
   His name in the film isn't Mencken. It's E.K. Hornbeck.
Likewise, Lemmon's and Scott's characters are named Drummond and
Brady, not Darrow and Bryan and the town is Hillsboro. The names
are changed in keeping with the original 1955 drama by Jerome
Lawrence and Robert E. Lee, which takes huge liberties with the
1925 events.
</P>
<P>
   The Scopes character, named Bert Cates in the film, is on trial
as much for his individualism as for teaching Darwin's theory that
we're not so much monkeys' uncles as monkeys' nephews. Drummond
says at one point: ``I didn't come here to make Hillsboro
different, I came to fight for his right to be different!''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Everett Scott plays Cates as the simple, honest, small-town
schoolteacher caught up in something he never envisioned. An
individual simply because he colors outside the lines, he is
charged with thinking outside the box. (Brady, the fundamentalist
with a voice like a cement mixer and a personality to match,
bellows that Cates teaches EVIL-ution.)
</P>
<P>
   The price of his individuality is loss of employment and
possible loss of freedom. Drummond and Brady, meanwhile, pay higher
than retail for displaying their own brand of individualism.
Lemmon's Drummond is liberal and open-minded; George C. Scott's
Brady is conservative and intransigent. Such polarization is
horribly hackneyed, but over the course of two hours, Lemmon and
Scott, both outstanding in shirt-sleeves and suspenders, manage to
keep the cliche subsidiary to an engaging debate about free thought
and conformity.
</P>
<P>
   For Ayn Rand, conformity was death. Even worse, it was just so
unfashionable.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Passion of Ayn Rand,'' the marvelous Helen Mirren
stylishly conveys the cult of self that Rand forged into a
mini-industry after her two novels, ``The Fountainhead'' and
``Atlas Shrugged,'' found a willing and receptive audience in the
'40s, '50s and even today.
</P>
<P>
   Her most willing audience was Nathaniel Branden, a brilliant
UCLA psychology student who became her protege, and then her lover
for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was not your usual affair. Rand and Branden, who both changed
their Jewish-sounding names to fit their self-images, carried on
with the full knowledge and grudging consent of their respective
spouses. The film is based on the book by Barbara Branden, who to
this day remains devoted to Rand for giving her ``the gift of life,
because I learned to think from her in a way I don't think I would
have fully have discovered on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   The French actress Julie Delpy plays Barbara Branden in the
film, sometimes struggling with an American accent but nobly
displaying the conflicting emotions of a scorned wife who remains a
disciple in Rand's inner circle. Peter Fonda is Rand's cuckolded
husband, Frank O'Connor, who also manages to extract a measure of
nobility from his unhappy situation.
</P>
<P>
   But the film belongs to Mirren, as the brilliant and
controversial writer-philosopher, and to Eric Stoltz, as Nathaniel
Branden, the icy-cool intellectual who gets Rand's motor running
with his smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Of their relationship, the enormously condescending Rand says,
``Lesser people could never accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but with arresting imagery, great music and a quality
cast, ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' makes it fun to watch how
uncomfortable nonconformity can be.
</P>
<P>
   Inherit the Wind. Cable-TV movie about the trial of a rural
Tennesseean for teaching the theory of evolution. Starring Jack
Lemmon, George C. Scott, Tom Everett Scott, Kathryn Morris and
Piper Laurie. Saturday night on Showtime. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The Passion of Ayn Rand. Cable-TV movie about the
novelist-philosopher and the 15-year love affair she had with her
protege. Starring Helen Mirren, Eric Stoltz, Julie Delpy and Peter
Fonda. Sunday on Showtime. Parental guideline rating: TV-MA. Grade:
A-
</P>
</TEXT>
