<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-BABY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby from Bosnia on the mend now
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _The sound of blood and oxygen swirling and swishing
underneath a tiny patched-up chest signals a new lease on life for
Azra Beso, the 2 1/2-month-old Bosnian baby who fell from the sky
into Atlanta's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Azra is expected to be discharged this weekend or early next
week from Egleston Children's Hospital, where she was moved
Thursday from the cardiac intensive care unit into a room.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kirk Kanter and a team of eight on Monday switched the
baby's main heart arteries, which were transposed at birth. The
condition causes an inadequate mixture of blood and oxygen, leading
to labored breathing and, if untreated, eventually death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect she should have a normal heart and a normal
life expectancy,'' said Kanter, a pediatric cardiac-thoracic
surgeon. ``She's doing much better and she's started to take in
food on her own.''
</P>
<P>
   Azra should be on the mend after a few weeks of recovery in the
home of a host family, Dr. Joe and Sharon Wilson, where she will
stay with her mother, Almira Beso, and translator Julijanna
Mikulic.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the color of her daughter's lips from bluish to pink
was one of the first changes that Azra's mother noticed, Kanter
said. ``She's pink now, for the first time in her life, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mom also knows that her daughter feels better. ``She's been
smiling a lot,'' Almira Beso said through Mikulic. ``She's a really
happy baby, and she likes to be held.''
</P>
<P>
   Azra's arrival in Atlanta last month was unexpected. She was
aboard a Delta Air Lines flight from Vienna, Austria, to Detroit
for scheduled heart surgery there when her breathing went from
troubled to touch-and-go halfway across the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls made from the plane quickly arranged emergency
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Azra is one of dozens of infants born with congenital heart
defects in Bosnia who are being helped by Samaritan's Purse Bosnia
Heart Project. The babies can't be treated in Bosnia, because its
civil war disrupted medical services and drove doctors out of the
country. In the United States, about one in every 1,000 babies is
born with the same congenital heart defect as Azra, the cause of
which is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Samaritan's Purse, a nonprofit international Christian relief
group, is headed by Franklin Graham of Boone, N.C., and provides
medical and spiritual assistance. The Heart Project finds U.S.
hospitals willing to treat Bosnian babies on a charitable basis and
arranges a round-trip flight and a host family for the baby, mother
and a translator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure when we will go home, back to Bosnia,''
Mikulic said. ``We could be here a few more weeks or another month.
We both want to get back to our families.''
</P>
<P>
   Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
