<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC INDICTMENT LIMITS PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that there's an arrest warrant out for Slobodan Milosevic,
hopes for a negotiated end to the Kosovo conflict are fading fast,
say Balkan watchers. And military escalation _ including the use of
NATO ground troops _ is growing more likely every day.
</P>
<P>
   By indicting the Yugoslav president for war crimes committed in
Kosovo, the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia has deepened his isolation. He will, for instance, be
unable to travel to a peace conference without risk of arrest.
</P>
<P>
   All 185 member states of the United Nations plus Switzerland
(which maintains a permanent observer mission to the United
Nations, but is not a full member) are obligated to detain
Milosevic if he sets foot on their soil. This includes nations like
Russia, Belarus, and China that have sympathized with the Serbs in
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Also, all UN states must freeze any assets of Milosevic and the
four lieutenants indicted with him, said war crimes prosecutor
Louise Arbour, who announced the indictments Thursday at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``This complicates the political situation,'' said John Reppert,
a specialist on international security at Harvard's Kennedy School
of Government. ``Think how it would be if you invited him back to
Rambouillet and he was given an arrest warrant, not a hotel key.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paris suburb of Rambouillet was where negotiators tried to
work out a peace plan for Kosovo before the conflict began.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Milosevic may never be brought to trial. He might
hunker down as Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko
Mladic have done. Both were indicted for war crimes; neither has
been arrested despite the presence of NATO troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has watched NATO operate,'' said Reppert. ``He may know
that an indictment isn't quite as serious as it may seem.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a public relations win for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has been struggling for a legal rationale
for the intervention in the Balkans,'' said Michael Scharf,
professor of international law at New England School of Law and a
former State Department official. ``Now they've got it. This gives
them the legal high ground.''
</P>
<P>
   With more and more NATO troops being readied for deployment to
the Balkans, that sort of justification will be important in
convincing the public that potential casualties are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how the indictment likely will affect the Yugoslav
conflict and attempts to bring it to a peaceful conclusion,
according to Balkan analysts.
</P>
<P>
   --Peacemaking: Though Russian, Finnish, American, and other
diplomats are shuttling from capital to capital talking peace, the
United States and its allies will be loathe to sign a treaty with
an indicted war criminal, many specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you negotiate with a war criminal?'' asked Uri Ra'Anan,
professor of international relations at Boston University. It's a
question that many analysts have been asking. Ra'Anan takes it a
step further: If Milosevic does not surrender himself to the UN or
is not toppled by his own people, NATO will have to fight him to
the bitter end. ``If you don't negotiate with him,'' Ra'Anan said,
``it appears that the NATO stance is unconditional surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is not shared by other observers, including Reppert,
who still sees diplomacy as a live option. But he noted that the
indictment may have set back these efforts, pointing out that the
Russian media have expressed suspicion that the timing of the
indictment was an attempt to undermine the efforts of Balkan envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO resolve: Germany, Italy, and Greece have been
increasingly uncomfortable with the NATO air campaign, which is now
in its third month. Public support in the United States and Europe
also has been weakening in recent weeks, according to opinion
polls. There are many reasons for this, say analysts, including the
bombing mistakes by NATO planes and televised reports of suffering
by the Serbian people. With the Serb leader labeled a war criminal,
allied support for the campaign against him might firm up, say
several analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that this will stiffen the resolve of some
wobbly people in NATO and have an impact on public opinion in
non-NATO countries,'' said Terry Scott, former Air Force lieutenant
general who directs the national security program at the Kennedy
School.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility made Ra'Anan a bit skeptical about the timing:
``It's an interesting coincidence between the appearance of this
indictment and the need to shore up public opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   --Opposition in Belgrade: Though the Serbian people are
overwhelmingly bitter about the NATO bombing, the singling out of
Milosevic as an alleged war criminal may give pro-democracy forces
some hope. Jasminka Udovicki, a local academic who stays in touch
with anti-Milosevic activists in Belgrade, said the indictment at
least encourages them ``that Milosevic is not going to be there
when this is over.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said both Udovicki and Scott, military and
political leaders in Belgrade may begin to distance themselves from
him _ may even oppose him _ to save themselves from guilt by
association in a post-war Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a staff apparatchik without much blood on your
hands and you suddenly realize that before this is over you might
have something to answer for, you might split off from Milosevic,''
said Scott. ``It becomes more difficult to be seen sitting at the
table with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
