<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-MBEKI-ART-2TA     05-27 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MBEKI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBEKI, MANDELA'S LIKELY SUCCESSOR, IS NO CLONE OF SOUTH AFRICAN
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VREDENDAL, South Africa _ When Thabo Mbeki rose to speak in the
half-empty community hall here recently, the applause was polite.
Barely visible behind the tall lectern, the diminutive Mbeki began
with what sounded like an attack on the press.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters never come to places like Vredendal, he said. They
never look at the new housing project here or the farming project
that is about to give 50 people new jobs. The press, he said,
believes that bad news will sell. But, he said, there is plenty of
good news to be told about the new South Africa, and some of it is
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vredendal speaks of the capacity we have to work together,''
Mbeki said. ``To generate good stories, not just the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In this small, remote farming community awash with poverty, the
pep talk was clearly welcome. By the time he had finished speaking,
Mbeki, South Africa's deputy president and the man who will almost
certainly inherit President Nelson Mandela's job after the election
on June 2, had earned a standing ovation _ a bit restrained
perhaps, but a standing ovation nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has none of the spontaneous charm and sense of the
right gesture that makes Mandela so beloved, the reserved, bookish
Mbeki, 56, has thrown himself into campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   He is everywhere these days, kissing babies, escorting old women
to the podium to speak with him, and offering a message of hope
that many South Africans, appalled at the rising crime and
unemployment rates, are eager to hear: Change will come faster now
because the policies are in place.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, Mbeki has been the behind-the-scenes
administrator as Mandela has greeted dignitaries and traveled the
globe to woo foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   It is Mandela, 80, who basked in the photo opportunities wearing
his open-necked ``Madiba shirts,'' while Mbeki _ rarely out of a
suit and tie _ handled the nitty-gritty, giving few interviews and
offering little of himself to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts say they are not yet sure who the real
Mbeki is. No one doubts his intellectual abilities. He writes his
own speeches, some of them memorable. He is said to be a chief
architect of the country's conservative economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   But some say an aura of fear lurks around him. They point out
that his early political rivals have been all but extinguished,
some leaving for the business world, others pushed to the fringes
of the governing party, the African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, an economist with a degree from Sussex University in
Britain, is working hard at a new image. He has even been seen in a
sports shirt under a blue blazer. But, frankly, stiff may be more
his style.
</P>
<P>
   During a broadcast on AIDS last year, he gave a speech while
seated, surrounded by orphaned children, some of them climbing up
his legs and pulling at his clothes. During the entire 15 minutes
the camera was fixed on him, he didn't pat or touch a child.
</P>
<P>
   When he is surrounded by adult well-wishers trying to touch him,
he often looks like a deer caught in the klieg lights. Mandela goes
right for the tallest beauty queen in a crowd and chats her up;
Mbeki smiles but seems tongue-tied with almost everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is now wading into the crowds, grabbing hands, and is
even occasionally dragged into dancing with the ladies.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the African National Congress will
win the election _ perhaps by the two-thirds majority it is hoping
for. The party still commands loyalty for its role in the
liberation struggle, and it has delivered on its campaign promises,
at least in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Electric and telephone poles can be seen crisscrossing even the
tin shack settlements that sprawl across the landscape. A new
constitution has been enacted and more than 500 laws have been
passed, revamping a legal system that once ordained that blacks
could not vote and needed only a rudimentary education.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems remain enormous, and South Africans are
beginning to grumble. Every day newspapers deliver a catalog of
rapes, killings and armed robberies. And the country has lost more
than 500,000 jobs since 1994 _ leaving many who have just gotten
phones, lights and clean water unable to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent community meeting in the black township of Soweto,
many of those who came to speak to Mbeki simply described their
poverty. Holding her paycheck in her hand, Rebecca Madiba said she
was earning about $220 a month as a nurse's aide and could not pay
her electricity or her taxes.
</P>
<P>
   She now owed more than $1,000 and was afraid she would lose her
new house. She simply asked for help. Mbeki, sitting on a dais
surrounded by officials, listened intently.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that he is gaining in popularity, though he does not
yet approach the status reserved for Mandela and he is
significantly less popular than Mandela among whites. Some
political analysts were sure that Mbeki would rely on Mandela to do
most of the campaigning. They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign kicked off in earnest, Mandela was abroad,
visiting China, Pakistan, Russia and Hungary. Early posters
featured the two men together, but the vast majority now feature
only Mbeki and the slogan that the African National Congress used
in 1994: ``A Better Life for All.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mbeki remains a fiercely private man. In a rare television
interview recently, he repeatedly turned away personal questions,
saying at one point that he was willing to tell people what size
shoes he wore and how much coffee he drank, but he didn't think
they really cared _ so he wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   When the dogged interviewer insisted that people wanted to know
him, he replied that on the hustings ``people want to shake
hands.'' He added: ``They want to embrace. They want all sorts of
things and you see the passion in their eyes, and none of them have
said, `Who is this Mbeki whose hand I want to shake?'''
</P>
<P>
   Pestered further, he briefly relented. He was reading a book on
economics by two Americans and had just stayed up late the night
before to watch the movie ``Educating Rita'' on television. He
should have been sleeping, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, having poured out one-eighth of an inch of his soul, he
turned on the interviewer. What had revealing that ``done for the
South African public?'' he asked. ``Well I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The interviewer gave up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His unknowability particularly worries non-blacks. Mandela could
sometimes be harsh about how little whites were contributing to
remaking this society, but most whites believed that they could get
a fair hearing from the president _ who talked often of the need
for forgiveness. Mbeki, though, is seen as a man who keeps whites
out of his inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thabo's priority is not national reconciliation,'' said Themba
Sono, the head of the nonprofit South African Institute for Race
Relations and a frequent critic. ``It is national reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Mbeki's most notable speeches, often referred to as the
``two nations'' speech, delivered last year, harshly questions
whether South Africa is moving toward national unity. It is two
nations, he said, one white and rich, one black and poor. Unlike
the case in Germany, where the West paid to help the East when the
Berlin Wall came down, whites are not doing the same in South
Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said about 30 percent of corporations were trying to
dodge their taxes while the new government was being faulted for
failing to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, which prompted nervous responses from the country's
editorial writers, most of whom are white, ended with a reference
to the American poet Langston Hughes and what happens to a dream
deferred: it explodes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mandela and Mbeki come from Transkei, an area of almost
treeless rolling hills that Mandela talks of with great fondness.
Mandela was from Xhosa nobility, though he was the first in his
family to receive a formal education.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, on the other hand, was the product of a small black
middle class. His family converted to Christianity early on and had
been successful farmers, teachers, preachers and clerks for
generations before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   But Mbeki did not grow up in wealth or ease. His father was
Govan Mbeki, an early African National Congress intellectual and an
avid Communist who spent much of his life imprisoned on Robben
Island with Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Though educated, the family was often desperately poor as Govan
Mbeki, dedicated to the cause, was in and out of jail. The main
income was from a small shop that Thabo Mbeki's mother, Epainette,
ran. It also served as the post office and one of Thabo's chores as
a youth was to read and write letters for villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Govan was a distant father even before he was sent to jail and
says himself that he does not really know his son. Thabo joined the
movement at 14 and was a student activist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 the African National Congress decided to send him abroad
to study, but not before he had fathered a child with his young
sweetheart. The boy disappeared in 1980, apparently on his way into
exile, and is presumed to have died at the hands of South Africa's
brutal security police.
</P>
<P>
   But even the country's Truth and Reconciliation Commission was
unable to find out what had happened to him. Mbeki later married
Zanele Dlamini, who is now the director of the Women's Development
Bank, which provides small loans to women, mostly in rural areas.
They have no children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his university degree, Mbeki went to Russia for
military training. But he was always considered better with a book
than an AK-47. During one frigid night march in the Russian
wilderness, he lost his map, forcing his disgruntled platoon to
wander for miles. But he is considered a shrewd politician,
particularly able to find compromise.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, he rarely asks for a vote. Instead, he
highlights the government's accomplishments. As in Vredendal, many
of his stops focus on new schools, new roads, new water pipes. He
talks often about the need to root out corruption, strengthen the
police and the justice system and get ``delivery'' moving faster.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be successfully forging an image of himself as a
tough leader, perhaps more willing to enforce discipline than
Mandela. After listening to Mbeki in Soweto, Hazel Mashinini, 22,
who counsels AIDS sufferers, said she was optimistic about the
course Mbeki would set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ANC has gotten a bad name because some in the Cabinet are
there for their own pockets, but I think Mbeki will fix that,'' Ms.
Mashinini said. ``Mandela is an old man and maybe too soft. He
wants us all to live a happy life. But Thabo Mbeki is still young.
He understands the problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
