<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, May 28,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-DURHAM (Seattle) _ A serious illness has caused Washington
state Supreme Court Justice Barbara Durham to withdraw her
nomination to the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, White House
and Justice Department sources said Thursday. Durham was recovering
from eye surgery Thursday and could not be reached for comment. It
was not certain whether her illness _ the nature of which has not
been publicly disclosed but is unrelated to the recent surgery _
would cause her to step down from the Supreme Court as well.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ28 (Seattle) _ In a rehearsal studio near Seattle's Fremont
Bridge, 14-year-old Tyler Musgrave and Shorecrest freshman Tom
Miller are no longer just kids. Tyler is a drummer, a human
metronome whose left foot can be as relentless as a dripping
faucet. The boys and their surroundings are part of a music and art
program developed in Seattle by jazz pianist Bill Rossi. Rossi's
organization, Youth Advancement Through Music and Art, or YATMA,
recently was awarded a $25,000 grant from the William H. Gates
Foundation. The money will help to underwrite lessons for kids who
can't afford them at a time when many schools can't either.
</P>
<P>
   By Gordy Holt. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-ISRAEL (Seattle) _ Boeing has sweetened its offer to
Israel in hopes of winning a $2.5 billion fighter plane order,
which would keep alive future production of the company's
profitable F-15. John Boyle, vice president of international
business development for Boeing, personally presented the Israeli
defense minister with a proposal in which Boeing will guarantee an
additional $500 million in work for Israel companies. Boeing
already provides about $1.7 billion to Israeli companies in these
so-called offsets.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HILL (Undated) _ It doesn't happen very often these days,
but every once in a while, the Hollywood Dream Machine gets it
right. The Julia Roberts-Hugh Grant romantic-comedy fairy tale,
``Notting Hill,'' is one of those times. It's pure fluff, but as
irresistible as cotton candy.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FLOOR (Undated) _ Hollywood's latest movie about a
computer-generated universe, ``The 13th Floor,'' is, in its own
way, no less imaginative than ``eXistenZ,'' or ``The Matrix,'' but
it definitely suffers from being the third cat out of the bag.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SWINDLE (Undated) _ While not Claude Chabrol's best film,
``The Swindle'' represents no big letdown in quality. It's another
wickedly humorous psychological thriller that provides a showy part
for his favorite star, Isabelle Huppert. It's very much in the
tradition of his body of work, but also different enough to be
worth seeing. With tag-on review of ``This Is My Father.''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-INHERIT (Undated) _ With all the subtlety of an inflated ego,
Showtime presents a seminar on the suggested retail price of
individualism this weekend, pairing two worthy study aids: ``The
Passion of Ayn Rand'' and a remake of ``Inherit the Wind.'' Both
films are period pieces based in fact, with ``Ayn Rand'' coming out
slightly ahead on the satisfaction meter.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH (Undated) _ Mike Peters, a manager with
UPS's Northwest region, can't Brandon, a first-grader and one of 10
children in a fatherless family, off his mind. Peters tutored the
little boy for about four weeks during a recent internship as part
of his senior management training program to build management
skills and leadership. During four weeks with Brandon, he learned
more about management than he has in years of wrangling with adult
employees.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Mark McGwire and Latrell Sprewell star
in ads that make you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
