<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PILGRIM DROPS MEDICARE COVERAGE IN WESTERN MASS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Harvard Pilgrim Health Care Thursday announced it will
be exiting the Medicare market in western Massachusetts, leaving
over 3,500 seniors with the task of selecting another insurer by
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The health maintenance organization cited financial losses due
to inadequate reimbursement by the federal government to care for
seniors enrolled in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim, which covers about 60,000 Medicare patients in
Massachusetts, southern New Hampshire and Rhode Island, did not
rule out the possibility that it would pull out of the Medicare
business in other areas where it operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're currently evaluating our product and our network,'' said
Patti Embry-Tautenhan, spokeswoman for the Brookline-based HMO.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is the latest in a series by HMOs across the
country to scale back their Medicare businesses. This year, 100
HMOs cut back their Medicare business, with some pulling out of the
program entirely, according to the U.S. General Accounting Office,
a federal watchdog agency. On Jan. 1, Aetna U.S. Healthcare dropped
its Medicare program in six states, including Massachusetts. The
move left 17,000 Bay State seniors scrambling to find another
insurer.
</P>
<P>
   More than 239,000 seniors in Massachusetts belong to Medicare
HMOs, according to the state Division of Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs, including Harvard Pilgrim, blame low reimbursements for
their decisions to pull out and are lobbying for more generous
payments from the federal government. But a GAO study published in
April said low payments are just one of many reasons for the waning
interest among HMOs in the Medicare business. Inability to compete
with more established rivals and difficulty in knitting together a
network of hospitals and doctors also account for many withdrawals,
the GAO found.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim said one factor in its decision to withdraw from
Franklin, Hampden and Hampshire counties in the Pioneer Valley is
the low rate of reimbursement in those counties.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, through the Health Care Financing
Administration, pays HMOs in Franklin County, for instance, $426.56
a month on average for each senior. For Suffolk County, which
includes Boston, the rate is $663.04. In an effort to encourage
HMOs to move into less urban areas, HCFA has tried to boost
payments more in those locations. The rate for Franklin County will
increase 9.7 percent in 2000, while Suffolk County will see just a
2 percent hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very sorry to see them go,'' said Peter Toland,
associate regional administrator for Medicare at HCFA. ``They're
one of the best plans in the country and one of the original
Medicare HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   While Harvard Pilgrim has been offering Medicare insurance since
1985, it has only been in western Massachusetts since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors in the Pioneer Valley enrolled with Harvard Pilgrim will
be notified of the cancellation of their HMO policy by letter in
the coming days. Seniors will either have to return to traditional
non-HMO Medicare or join another HMO. Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Massachusetts and Fallon Community Health Plan offer Medicare HMOs
in all three counties, while Tufts Health Plan and Kaiser
Permanente operate in Hampden County.
</P>
<P>
   For seniors who return to traditional Medicare and wish to buy
so-called ``medigap'' insurance that will cover expenses not paid
for by Medicare, the Division of Insurance is considering allowing
an open enrollment period for residents of Pioneer Valley to
purchase such plans at the end of this year, according to Chris
Goetcheus, a division spokesman. Normally, seniors can only sign up
for medigap policies in the spring for coverage that begins June 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
