<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION WORRIES THROW DOW INTO DIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled 235.23 points Thursday
as a selloff _ prompted by fears of rising inflation _ caused the
market's worst percentage decline in more than 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The index lost 2.2 percent of its value, falling to 10,466.93,
its fifth down day out of the past six.
</P>
<P>
   The decline was blamed on institutional investors and day
traders preparing for the Memorial Day holiday by selling stocks
they do not want to hold over the long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, analysts and portfolio managers said investors
should brace themselves. Thursday's drop may signal more declines
ahead as investors react to the increasing likelihood of an
interest rate hike by the Federal Reserve Board to ease
inflationary pressures building in the economy. Reflecting these
fears, the bond market also declined Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little pessimistic about the stock market right now,''
said Easton Ragsdale, director of quantitative research for State
Street Research &AMP; Management Co. ``We'll be up for the year but the
market has been expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which has experienced a spectacular rise this year, has
lost 420 points since last Thursday. Since its May 13 high of
11,107.1, the Dow has fallen 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's rise on Wednesday ``was the aberration,'' said Ned
Riley, chief investment officer for BankBoston Corp. ``Today was
just an acknowlegment that the higher interest rate environment is
starting to strike some fear in the hearts of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which has not risen as much as
the Dow, declined just 1.79 percent Thursday. While the
technology-heavy Nasdaq index dipped only 0.33 percent, analysts
predicted rough waters ahead for the high-flying sector.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Minervini, chief investment strategist for Quantech
Research Group in New York, said he is ``negative on the Nasdaq 100
kinds of stocks. We think we're in a short-term correction.'' The
Dow, he predicted, ``could undercut 10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the yield on 30-year US Treasury bonds rose
5 basis points to 5.85 percent, close to its highest level in a
year. But yields on two-year notes were hardest hit, rising to
their highest level in more than nine months, 5.42 percent. Bond
prices move in the opposite direction of yields.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates hammered financial company stocks. J.P.
Morgan led the pack, declining 3 3/4, to 135 1/8; Bank of America
Corp. fell 3 1/2, to 62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had a mixed day. Internet stocks, which have been
pushed to heights professional investors have long said were
unsustainable, continued to be battered. Lycos lost 4, closing at
98 a share, and Amazon.com fell 6 3/8, closing at 111 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   But computer companies that have posted good earnings reports
were only nicked in the selloff. Dell Computer lost 1/6, closing at
34 1/2; Hewlett Packard dipped 7/8, closing at 92 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
