<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-     05-27 2497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino, Phil
Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' R (profanity, sexuality, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro,
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal and Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   This farce about a mobster (Robert De Niro) who takes his issues
to a psychiatrist (Billy Crystal) never becomes the laugh-riot it
could be. It's an offer you could refuse, but the stars (plus Lisa
Kudrow as Crystal's fiancee) make it worthwhile. (SM) 1 hour, 46
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Castle'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Caton.
</P>
<P>
   A sunny little sleeper from Australia. A cheerfully dimwitted
working-class bloke named Darryl (Michael Caton) takes on the
system when the neighboring airport decides to expand and tries to
force him and his family out of their home. It's a genial and
just-goofy-enough David-and-Goliath (Darryl-and-Goliath?) comedy
that aims to do little more than put a smile on your face. Which it
does. Handily. (ERG) 1 hour, 25 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dreamlife of Angels'' R (strong sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Elodie Boucher
</P>
<P>
   and Natacha Regnier.
</P>
<P>
   A beautiful character study of two young women trying to make
sense of life in a working-class town. The film is shot with a
documentarian style that registers every nuance. Subtitles. (SM) 1
hour, 52 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' R (profanity, sexuality and drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Broderick
</P>
<P>
   and Reese Witherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   In this cruelly funny satire, high school teacher Matthew
Broderick schemes to thwart perky student Reese Witherspoon in her
bid for the student government presidency. The second feature from
``Citizen Ruth'' director Alexander Payne may sound like a bouncy
comedy. But it's really a
</P>
<P>
   bittersweet ode to the everyday lies people tell themselves to
justify their actions. (SM) 1 hour, 44 minutes A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment'' PG-13 (violence and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Connery
</P>
<P>
   and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A thriller with no thrills. A he/she sexual pas de deux with
little
</P>
<P>
   chemistry. Sean Connery plays Max, a dapper thief swiping
priceless works of art and computer chips. A shapely insurance
agent (Catherine Zeta-Jones) slinks into the picture and
``Entrapment'' becomes a cat-and-mouse game with lots of twists and
turns. Sadly, it's almost always a bore. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 50
minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM) 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' PG-13 (profanity, sexuality, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Ben Affleck.
</P>
<P>
   Opposites attract as strait-laced Ben Affleck heads to his
wedding with free-spirit Sandra Bullock. Like ``My Best Friend's
Wedding,'' it's a savvy blend of romantic-comedy formula and wise
'90s updates. (SM) 1 hour, 41 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' R (language, sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy
</P>
<P>
   and Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence bicker for more than 60 years
in this sometimes hilarious and racially poignant prison comedy.
How they landed in a Mississippi correctional facility with life
sentences isn't nearly as important as the knack these talented
performers have for taking turns at
</P>
<P>
   generating laughs out of a throwaway script. (Bob Longino). 1
hour, 49 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock
</P>
<P>
   and Two Smoking Barrels'' R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran and Jason Flemyng.
</P>
<P>
   Smokin'. This whip-smart lark is an English caper comedy
glistening with confidence and a wicked sense of humor. Four
likable, conniving East End lads have a week to settle the debt
they owe a hood named Hatchet
</P>
<P>
   Harry. Rookie writer/director Guy Ritchie piles on the
characters, plot twists and violence, but one thing is clear:
Everyone involved had a fine time making this movie. (ERG) 1 hour,
45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kate Capshaw,
</P>
<P>
   Tom Everett Scott
</P>
<P>
   and Tom Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   Not lovable, but generally likable. An anonymous love letter
circulates among the residents of a small New England town setting
off rendezvous, revelations and romantic misunderstandings. The
film has two problems: It flirts with a serious case of the cutes
and Kate Capshaw, sexually appealing and adorably flustered, never
quite takes over her own star vehicle. Still, it has enough charm
to keep you interested. (ERG) 1 hour, 29 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' R (sci-fi violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves,
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Fishburne
</P>
<P>
   and Carrie-Anne Moss.
</P>
<P>
   A knockout sci-fi flick. Writer-directors Andy and Larry
Wachowski bring their sharp storytelling and visual showmanship to
an adventure
</P>
<P>
   starring Keanu Reeves that should please both comic book
fanatics and mainstream moviegoers. Balancing intelligence with
stunning special effects and action, it's a movie that earns its
explosions, high kicks and cascades of spent
</P>
<P>
   bullets. (SM) 2 hours, 15 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' PG-13 (pervasive adventure violence
</P>
<P>
   and partial nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Fraser
</P>
<P>
   and Rachel Weisz.
</P>
<P>
   Mummy, make it stop! Please! Just because a movie has desert
scenery, a hunky action hero (Brendan Fraser), hissable bad guys
and supernatural hoodoo doesn't make it an Indiana Jones flick.
You'll miss Steven Spielberg's masterful touch watching ``The
Mummy,'' a petrified mixture of retro adventure, clumsy slapstick
and minimal chills. (SM) 2 hours, 4 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Been Kissed'' PG-13 (profanity, drug use,
</P>
<P>
   sexual references)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Barrymore
</P>
<P>
   and David Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore is Josie Geller, a mid-20s newspaper copy editor
and former high school dweeb (``Josie Grossie,'' they called her)
who goes back to teenville as an undercover reporter, promptly
relives high school hell and pretty much bumbles her way to
popularity. Everything about her career is implausible. The movie's
jokes are lame, its situations loopy. But Barrymore does make a go
of it. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 47 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hugh Grant
</P>
<P>
   and Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Boy gets movie star, boy loses movie star, etc. Hugh Grant plays
a decent London bookseller and Julia Roberts a version of herself
(worldwide movie star) in this romantic comedy. The latest from the
writer of ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' is old-fashioned hokum,
short on surprise but very long on charm. (SM) At metro theaters. 2
hours, 4 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' PG (profanity, sensuality, alcohol use,
</P>
<P>
   some thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jake Gyllenhaal,
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cooper and Laura Dern.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply satisfying tale of West Virginia teenager Homer (Jake
Gyllenhaal) and three friends who, in the 1950s, began to build and
shoot off model rockets. Their goal: to win a science fair, which
could help them escape a future of working in the coal mine of
their small town. Based on Homer Hickam's autobiography ``Rocket
Boys,'' it makes the process of learning seem as exciting as a
special FX-driven action flick. (SM) 1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack, Billy Bob
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, Cate Blanchett
</P>
<P>
   and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   A juiced-up ensemble comedy-drama that loses its bearings
halfway through its flight. John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton play
rival air traffic controllers who keep 747s from colliding every
few seconds in the super-crowded sky above New York. The talented
supporting cast includes Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth'') and
Angelina Jolie. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 2 hours, 3 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' R (extreme violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon
</P>
<P>
   and Edward Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Part gung-ho heroism, part in-your-face horror show, Steven
Spielberg's superb film shows us World War II as we've never seen
it before. Tom Hanks leads a courageous squad on a mission to find
a private (Matt Damon) whose three brothers have already been
killed in combat. Hanks'
</P>
<P>
   performance is a miracle of decency and subtle emotion, but
kudos all 'round here. (ERG) At area discount theaters. 2 hours, 50
minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I
</P>
<P>
   _ The Phantom Menace'' PG (sci-fi action/violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liam Neeson,
</P>
<P>
   Ewan McGregor and Natalie Portman.
</P>
<P>
   Is George Lucas' new movie visually amazing? Yes. Exciting?
Sometimes. Emotionally involving? Almost never. As a technological
Mount Everest (and the Mount McKinley of marketing), ``Menace'' is
a
</P>
<P>
   remarkable achievement. Too bad writer-director Lucas left out
the gee-whiz enthusiasm of the original movies. He also left out
memorable characters. He left out the fun. (SM) 2 hours, 11
minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini'' PG
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joan Plowright,
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Smith and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Known in 1930s Florence as ``the scorpioni,'' thanks to their
collective sting, a band of British and American expatriate women
become surrogate mothers of a young boy named Luca. Based on his
own autobiography, director Franco Zeffirelli's film is an uneven
but enjoyable tale of a boy growing up in Black-Shirt Italy,
entrusted to a handful of Auntie Mames. (SM) 1 hour, 58 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You'' PG-13 (sex-related dialogue,
</P>
<P>
   alcohol/drug-related scenes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Stiles
</P>
<P>
   and Heath Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a terrible teen version of ``The Taming of
the Shrew'' unexpectedly starts to percolate with wit and charm,
thanks largely to its Kate-and-Petruchio stand-ins, Kat (Julia
Stiles) and Patrick (Heath Ledger). The script can't go too far
wrong with Shakespeare's plot. (It's worked for 400 years.)
References to the original verge on precious. But the film also has
a few nutty touches of its own. (SM) 1 hour, 34 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thirteenth Floor'' R (profanity, sex and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Craig Bierko,
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Mol
</P>
<P>
   and Armin Mueller-Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   A ``what is reality?'' sci-fi thriller that doesn't measure up
to earlier and better films like ``The Matrix'' and ``Dark City.''
It's about a modern-day computer wiz team that creates, then walks
around in, a digitized
</P>
<P>
   version of 1937 Los Angeles. What follows is murder, intrigue
and too much flat acting. Your ultimate warning: The movie's from
some of the creative team that earlier flubbed ``Godzilla.'' (Bob
Longino) 2 hours. C
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' R (sex)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Aidan Quinn
</P>
<P>
   and Moya Farrelly.
</P>
<P>
   A burned-out teacher travels to Ireland to unravel the mystery
of his father. What unfolds is a tragedy, tinged with romance and
regret. In '30s rural Ireland, a headstrong young beauty (Moya
Farrelly) falls in love with a shy tenant farmer (Aidan Quinn)
nearly twice her age. But everything conspires against the lovers _
from curses and small-town snobbery to the kind of timing that
makes Romeo and Juliet look lucky. (ERG) 2 hours. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual innuendo)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Harvey Keitel,
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Ngoc Hiep and Don Duong.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of three awards at Sundance and further distinguished as
the first U.S. film shot in Vietnam since the war, this tenderly
appealing
</P>
<P>
   pastiche interweaves several obliquely connected stories while
catching a country in transition between a conflicted past and an
uncertain future. Reminiscent of Italian neo-realism, the movie may
be narratively facile, but it's visually and emotionally rich. With
subtitles. (ERG) 1 hour, 50 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Trekkies'' PG (sexual and drug references)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by Roger Nygard,
</P>
<P>
   with Denise Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Nygard's documentary looks at the TV franchise's ardent
</P>
<P>
   followers with a tone that fuses affection and deadpan satire.
Most of the time, Nygard and game narrator/interviewer Denise
Crosby let the fans speak for themselves, often with
unintentionally hilarious results. If you ever wondered what your
dog or cat would look like in a Star Fleet uniform, this is your
movie. (SM) 1 hour, 28 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``T. rex: Back to the Cretaceous'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liz Stauber
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Horton.
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX film has awesome special effects but, as a fictional
story, is too short. Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber) is a budding teenage
paleontologist who wants to go on a dig with her dino-hunting dad
(Peter Horton). When her dad brings what could be a dinosaur egg
into his lab, Ally accidentally cracks it and is thrust back in
time 65 million years, when the big beasts roamed the Earth. (ERG)
40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Trippin''' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Deon Richmond
</P>
<P>
   and Donald Adeosun Faison.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps trippin' up on its own mixed message. Deon Richmond
plays Greg, a high-school senior whose plans for college keep
getting waylaid by his fantasies of living the phat life,
surrounded by gorgeous women whose sole goal in life is to show him
their breasts. The movie has flashes of charm and heart, but
they're undermined by the filmmakers' pandering to the basic
instincts of its target teen audience. (SM) 1 hour, 32 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``William Shakespeare's
</P>
<P>
   A Midsummer
</P>
<P>
   Night's Dream'' PG-13 (sensuality and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, magic doesn't happen. A sexy cast, a classic play,
the
</P>
<P>
   sensuous Tuscany countryside. How could ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' misfire? Blame it on director Michael Hoffman, whose
</P>
<P>
   picturesque but pedestrian approach dims the sparkle of William
Shakespeare's script. (SM) 1 hour, 55 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Winslow Boy'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nigel Hawthorne
</P>
<P>
   and Jeremy Northam.
</P>
<P>
   David Mamet proves an unexpectedly good match for Terence
Rattigan's 1946 play loosely based on a true story of an Edwardian
patriarch's risky and costly fight to clear his 13-year-old son's
name when the boy is expelled from a prestigious school for
stealing pocket change. Mamet brings care, thoughtfulness and even
a theatrical spark to the material. Nigel Hawthorne and Jeremy
Northam lead an excellent cast. (ERG) 1 hour, 44 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some IMAX films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Phil Kloer) 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
