<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3910 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADING-HOURS-ART-2TA     05-27 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADING-HOURS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ APPROVES PLANS TO EXTEND TRADING HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a world so fast-paced that few bankers keep
bankers' hours anymore, there remains something quaint about the
insulated world of stock traders.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange, which closes each day at 4 p.m.,
operates just 32.5 hours a week, barely an hour a day more than
when it began trading stocks continuously a century ago. Even the
more technology-oriented Nasdaq Stock Market, a 28-year-old market
that exists only in computer links between trading houses, has
hewed to a schedule laid out when a broker's most important tool
was a pencil, not a computer.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of resisting longer trading hours _ and after
several attempts to extend them failed because of lack of interest
_ the nation's major stock markets are now hurrying plans to trade
stocks for several additional hours in the evening. On the horizon,
many in the industry see around-the-clock trading.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the board that governs the Nasdaq market approved a
plan to add an evening session for trading of the 100 largest
Nasdaq stocks. Beginning perhaps as soon as September, evening
trading would last from 5:30 to 9 p.m. In response to Nasdaq's
emerging plan, the New York Stock Exchange has said it too might
add an evening session lasting until 10 p.m. this year; its board
will meet June 3 to discuss the possibility. Any extensions are
subject to approval of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   By extending their hours beyond the current sessions, which last
from 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m., the exchanges will cause untold changes
in the lives of thousands of traders, clerks and others who work in
and around Wall Street in lower Manhattan. But the change will also
touch, in ways yet to be seen, millions of people across the
country, from investors on the West Coast whose opportunities to
trade stocks now end shortly after midday, to small brokerage firms
that could be severely strained by a much longer business day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about it,'' said Robert Neff, president of
Carnes Capital, a brokerage firm in Naples, Fla., with 18
employees. ``If something occurs after hours, will I have to come
charging in from home and man the machines? Running a small shop
like ours, I don't have extra people to staff those hours. And
where do I get them?''
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of adding an evening trading session already have
proved so cumbersome that Nasdaq pushed back its timetable to a
probable start in September from midsummer. And there remain dozens
of unresolved issues that must be answered before such a monumental
change takes place. Among them is whether to extend trading hours
five days a week or only Monday through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike consumers who wander the aisles of an all-night grocery
store to avoid crowds, many investors who attempt to trade
securities when traffic is light will be giving up in profits what
they gain in convenience. Generally, more participants means better
prices for both buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies whose stocks are being traded after hours will face
demands for information from investors long after headquarters has
closed for the day. Trades made in the late session would be
considered to be next-day transactions, meaning that mutual funds,
which by law must report the value on their assets once per day,
might rely on 4 p.m. prices to do so. Newspapers and wire services
that provide stock prices to investors around the world would also
have to decide which closing prices to publish.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that so many questions remain unanswered, even as the
exchanges move toward a late session, demonstrates how the
exchanges have lost control of their destiny. In fact, their hands
have been forced by a handful of upstart computerized trading
systems that are using cheap technology to provide a forum for
late-night trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask why the New York Stock Exchange still closes
at 4 o'clock, I say it's because the last bar car to Greenwich
leaves at 4:40,'' said Douglas M. Atkin, president and chief
executive of Instinet, an electronic trading system owned by
Reuters PLC that already offers late trading to mutual funds,
insurance companies and other institutions to trade among
themselves around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Instinet itself is also exploring ways to allow small investors
to trade on its network. Eclipse Trading, a computerized service
started by two former lawyers for the Securities and Exchange
Commission, plans to start its own system allowing individual
investors to trade with each other beginning this summer; it has
already signed deals with Discover Brokerage, part of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, and Dreyfus Brokerage to provide after-hours
trading to their customers. Wit Capital, an Internet-based
brokerage and investment banking firm, has said it plans to offer
extended-hours trading this summer. And Island ECN, which has
applied to Federal regulators to become a full-fledged stock
exchange, aims to provide an around-the-clock computerized market.
</P>
<P>
   Many market participants think individual investors, who in the
past two years have turned stock investing into a sort of national
obsession, will be keen on the idea. ``Why shouldn't people be able
to trade when it's convenient for them?'' asked Harvey Houtkin,
chief executive of All-Tech Investment Group, a day-trading firm
based in Montvale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market has become a tremendous part of millions of
peoples' lives,'' Houtkin said. ``It's what people talk about at
cocktail parties. I'm pretty sure by the end of this year you'll
see pretty good volume in an evening session.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, the battle over whether to extend trading
hours lines up the traditional Wall Street firms against the
electronic brokers. It also pits the big-ideas people against those
who make the markets run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who ultimately are voting on this are not the ones
sitting in the trenches,'' said Edward Collins, head of trading at
Daiwa Securities America. ``The clerks at the New York Stock
Exchange already get to work two hours before trading starts and
stay two hours after it's over, making sure the paperwork gets done
properly. I know how Wall Street works, and these firms are not
going to hire a whole lot of new staff for extra hours. So you're
going to get the fatigue and boredom factors, and all of the
problems that goes with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan L. Davidson, president of Zeus Securities, a small
brokerage firm in Jericho, N.Y., said extended hours could prove to
be a burden to thousands of small brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the brokerage firms in the country have fewer than 10
employees,'' said Davidson, who heads a trade group of independent
brokers and who serves as a board member of the National
Association of Securities Dealers. ``For us, it will mean a lot of
pressure on profits if we have to add staff to stay open late.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Similar concerns weigh on Sam Chuopayev, manager of Wall Street
Shoe Repair, located in Chase Manhattan Plaza, a block from Wall
Street in lower Manhattan. ``I already am open from 6 to 6,''
Chuopayev said. ``How many more hours can I work? I don't think
more people will be coming to get their shoes done at nighttime.''
Even the subway entrance near his shop closes at 7:30 p.m., he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Larger brokerage firms, however, say extending their operations
into the evening would take little effort. ``I could probably take
one senior trader out of 120, plus a couple of assistants, and they
could handle the after-hours business,'' said Kenneth D. Pasternak,
chief executive of the Knight/Trimark Group, one of the largest
Nasdaq market makers. ``To use the factory for another shift costs
us very little.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the pressure on brokerage firms, it is clear that
investors are scouring for investment opportunities well after the
exchanges are closed for the day. At E-Trade, the online brokerage
firm, 20 percent of each day's orders are executed in the first
hour of trading, said Lisa Nash, vice president for customer
management. Many, if not most, of those orders are placed while the
markets are closed, she said, producing a big queue of orders
awaiting the opening of trading each morning.
</P>
<P>
   But in exchange for having their orders executed in the evening
when they are placed, rather than the next morning, investors may
give away the ability to participate in a far more liquid market.
That's because price swings can be exaggerated in light trading.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq and Big Board officials have begun to warn that stock
prices could move more erratically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors should not expect the same liquidity that is present
during the normal trading day,'' said Richard Ketchum, president of
the Nasdaq's parent regulatory group. And in a speech to a meeting
of financial executives in Vancouver Thursday, Richard Grasso,
chairman of the New York Stock Exchange, said that investors could
expect greater volatility during evening trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   While the new, smaller systems that aim to provide late-night
trading can do so on their own, the New York Stock Exchange and
Nasdaq will need the approval of the Securities and Exchange
Commission to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, chairman of the SEC, said Thursday that the
commission ``strongly supports investor choice in trading hours,''
but he cautioned that investors should be warned about after-hours
liquidity and volatility. He also voiced concern that the exchanges
and large securities firms are ready to deal with year 2000 issues
before turning their attention to longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Nasdaq and the Big Board have portrayed themselves
as not-especially eager to embrace late trading hours. Grasso has
told exchange members that a move to extend trading would be a
necessary competitive response, but one that the exchange would not
take on its own. And he advised members that an evening session was
unlikely to be profitable for members.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq officials, in pushing their anticipated start date back
to September from midsummer, have said that their extension of
trading hours primarily is a response to competitive threats.
</P>
<P>
   Part of their effort is designed to ward off foreign markets,
many of which have been building systems that will allow them to
trade any country's stocks around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Few companies whose stocks will be traded late into the evening
appear to relish the idea. In part, that is because companies
prefer to make news announcements on earnings trends or
acquisitions and to schedule conference calls with financial
analysts and major investors during non-trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potential upheaval can be gleaned from what happened
to previous attempts to extend hours. In 1991, the New York Stock
Exchange attempted to move its opening time up by a half hour, to 9
a.m., but the proposal failed when it was vigorously opposed by
West Coast brokerage firms. In 1989, the exchange said it would
offer limited night trading, but those plans fell through. Efforts
to promote trading in European stocks in an early-bird session on
both the New York and Nasdaq markets has all but failed. And in
1981, regional stock exchanges actually shortened their hours,
citing lack of participation, moving their closings from 90 minutes
after the major exchanges to 4:30 p.m., where they remain.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of Nasdaq market makers, conducted this year by
Traders magazine, 70 percent of the firms said Nasdaq should not
extend its hours. Only 27 percent supported longer hours, with 3
percent registering no response. The results most likely reflect
the misgivings of small brokerage firms; many of the largest firms
did not answer the survey.
</P>
<P>
   So just who is in favor of longer trading hours? Clearly, the
movement is driven by individual investors, newly empowered by
computer technology and increasingly interested in buying stocks
whose prices only seem to go up. Frank Zarb, chairman of Nasdaq,
insists that individual investors, particularly those who trade
online, are banging down the door to be able to trade after hours.
``The fact is that online traders are not going to go away, and
there are going to be more of them a year from now than there are
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least a few individuals are not so sure. Krishan Datt, of
New Hyde Park, N.Y., who was visiting the Charles Schwab office at
the World Trade Center Thursday, said stock trading should be done
during the day. ``I'm afraid after hours trading would be giving
the wrong message to people,'' Datt said. ``That is time that
should be spent with your family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
