<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMP2000-COX     05-27 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMP2000-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign 2000 column: Gore opposes anti-gun suit bills in Texas
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore was not naming names when he
criticized efforts in some states to prevent cities from suing gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was in Dallas, speaking at a forum on school safety. Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, who happens to lead all other GOP presidential
prospects and Gore in the polls, is expected to sign a bill banning
those lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's time to take steps to prevent the kind of
lawsuits that many cities are filing to protect their citizens,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters interpreted the comments as an attempt by the vice
president to distinguish himself from Bush on an issue that has
new-found public support following school shootings in Colorado and
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could have made the same point two days earlier in Georgia,
where he met with families of students who were wounded at Heritage
High School in Rockdale County and where Gov. Roy Barnes in
February signed into law a bill that bars Georgia cities from
filing such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gore's silence had something to do with the fact that
Barnes endorsed him for president this week.
</P>
<P>
   A Nudge from Newt
</P>
<P>
   Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who once considered running
for president in 2000, is injecting himself into the 2000
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Gingrich will send to senior Republican leaders, he
is suggesting that the Lincoln-Douglas debates of 1858 are a better
model for sorting out candidates than the made-for-television
soundbites of today, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is proposing a series of encounters in which each
contender is allowed to present a 15-minute speech on a prearranged
topic, and then answers questions for five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach would establish an adult rhythm of responsible
people describing important ideas in a serious way,'' Gingrich
wrote to Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson, all 50 state GOP chairs
and all Republican members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas held a series of three-hour
debates in Illinois in their campaign for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the modern age would not afford that kind of
opportunity to nine or 10 different candidates,'' Gingrich wrote.
``On the other hand, there is nothing which requires us to reduce
the presidency to an average soundbite of nine seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's bucks
</P>
<P>
   The money and the endorsements keep rolling in for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   His exploratory committee announced this week that Bush has been
endorsed by 114 House Republicans, a majority of the 222-member
Republican caucus. Just two of eight Georgians in the House, Reps.
Mac Collins and Charlie Norwood, are backing Bush. The others are
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, Bush's campaign has raised more than $500,000 since
March. Most of that total comes from a fund-raising event last
weekend that was headlined by former President George Bush and his
wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' Iowa blitz
</P>
<P>
   Magazine publisher Steve Forbes has named Ohio Secretary of
State Ken Blackwell chairman of his presidential campaign, making
Blackwell one of the highest-ranking campaign officials in either
party.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell called Forbes ``an advocate for the politics of
inclusion.'' Forbes campaigned for Blackwell last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Blackwell may be of particular help to Forbes in Ohio, the
candidate will be spending most of his time in Iowa, New Hampshire
and California, campaign manager Bill Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes may spend as many as 35 days in Iowa this summer,
including the two weeks leading up to the August 14 presidential
straw poll there, although Dal Col said his final schedule has not
been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant event in Iowa, but you don't want to
overemphasize it,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa Republican party bills the straw poll as ``a test of
organizational strength'' for the presidential candidates. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, supporters of Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas packed
the event and held former Sen. Bob Dole, the leading Republican
candidate, to a draw. The straw poll may have been the high point
for Gramm's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Not Your Father's GOP
</P>
<P>
   The Republican tent may be getting bigger than anyone ever
expected. Thinking about running for Congress next year as
Republicans are Jeff Baxter and Bob Backlund.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter, whose nickname is Skunk, used to play guitar in two rock
bands, Steely Dan and the Doobie Brothers. The former is named for
a sex toy, the latter for a marijuana cigarette. Baxter may run
against Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman of California.
</P>
<P>
   Backlund is a Connecticut Republican who is preparing for a run
against Democratic Rep. John Larson. But Backlund already has an
affiliation, WWF.
</P>
<P>
   That stands for the World Wrestling Federation. Like Minnesota
Gov. Jesse Ventura, Backlund is an ex-pro wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
