<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-27 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GIRL WITH A SKULLCAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Sometimes when I am nearing the end of a trip to a
nation that has a special meaning in my life, happy or dismal, I
make a list of the words, images and memories that will keep fresh
the people, and happenings, that shaped my attitudes and emotions
about that country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   India _ the oranges and reds of the clothes of peasant women of
Rajasthan, part of their inherited sense of art as daily life, and
then the memory of them rising predawn to line up to use a new
heritage they had never dreamed would be theirs _ the right to
vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Poland under Communism _ a nasty sense of absence, the sudden
disappearance of a Polish colleague in the New York Times Warsaw
bureau, snatched from his apartment by the secret police. I never
saw him again until told by a famous Polish editor who was also a
secret police colonel that he had not been beaten much, ``even
though he is a Jew.'' That, but also the Polish determination to
rebuild first Warsaw's lovely 17th-century Old Town, brick by
brick, to show that the Germans had not destroyed Polish history
with all their house-by-house bombing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had not made an Israeli list for myself until now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What surprised me was that words like peace talks or names of
politicians did not leap to mind in the first cut of memories. But
words like music, arts festival, university, road, sand, trees _ in
Jerusalem and in the desert _ and the hilarious scene of the little
girl leaping up at the King David Hotel to snatch her brother's
skullcap for her own pretty head, they all popped up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then came awareness of a sensation I diagnosed as optimism _ not
mine, but of the people who planted the trees, built the buildings
of everlasting stone and always-renewing talent at Bar-Ilan
University in Tel Aviv and Ben-Gurion University in the sands of
the Negev. All of them, and the little girl, had in common the
optimism necessary to live and plant trees or children here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so do all the Israelis, perhaps half of them or more, who
believe that this time they may get a peace that might become
permanent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I do not share that particular attack of optimism, but in
leave-taking gentleness, I hereby concede that they might be partly
right. I think that the Prime Minister-elect, Ehud Barak, will try
mightily to achieve peace with Palestinians, as did Benjamin
Netanyahu, whose inability to keep loyalty of friends and followers
drowned him in antipathy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barak is now going through the excruciatingly delicate
complexities of trying to make a national unity government grow
from the losses of his Labor Party. He won, his party slipped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He negotiates with defeated Likud, now being steered by Ariel
Sharon, one of the more admired people in Israel, and the
burgeoning Shas religious party, which questions whether the laws
of democracy can or should be superior to the law of the Torah. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Likud is asking Barak questions before saying yes or no _ will
he really return to Syria the Golan Heights from which Syrians
shelled Jewish villages in the Galilee for decades, what borders
will he demand with the Palestinians for security's sake, what will
happen to the Jewish ``settlements'' on the West Bank, most of them
now established Jewish communities ranging from rugged to
Scarsdale. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I think that a temporary peace can be patched together with an
independent Palestine if it is willing to make concessions of
military and immigration sovereignty, and if the Clinton
administration, loaded and panting with longtime Labor supporters,
does not push Barak too hard and too fast, and out of public
trust. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But permanent, no; Palestine will be one more Arab dictatorship,
led by a Yasser Arafat who openly wants to make the supposed final
settlement simply part of the 1974 Arab plan to slice Israel down
to an unprotectable country with its thin back to the ocean.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The whole clutch of Arab tyrannies can hardly be trusted to let
the Jewish, and only, democracy in the Mideast live in a permanent
peace that will be a constant reminder to Arabs of the political
freedom reaching so much of the world. Permanent peace depends on
its reaching the Muslim Mideast too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, a taste of optimism is not surrender or passivity _ as
the little girl showed racing about the hotel lobby, hand firmly
clutched on the skullcap on her head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
