<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-GENJI-ART-700&AMP;A     05-27 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GENJI-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NUN BREATHES NEW LIFE INTO A VENERABLE, AND LUSTY, JAPANESE
HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KYOTO, Japan _ As Japanese heroes go, he is an unusual one. He
never wore a tie, never got a job, and after seducing his
stepmother when he was a teen-ager he had a string of affairs with
women who included his own adopted daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But Prince Genji is a central figure in Japanese culture, and he
never had a wit of trouble with the law _ perhaps in part because
he never existed. He was the title character in ``Tale of Genji,''
the nearly 1,000-year-old love story that is sometimes described as
the world's first novel and is usually considered Japan's greatest
literary achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Prince Genji is an unusual cultural icon, his latest
chronicler is if anything even more startling. Jakucho Setouchi, a
77-year-old Buddhist nun with shaven head and twinkling eyes, has
translated ``Tale of Genji'' into modern Japanese and turned it
into a huge best seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man and a woman are in love, the situation hasn't
changed in the last thousand years,'' Ms. Setouchi said cheerfully,
explaining the tale's popularity as she sat on the tatami floor of
the temple she heads here in Kyoto, the ancient Japanese capital.
``There's jealousy. There's agony. Even a modern career woman can
feel those same pains of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, yes, `Tale of Genji' is relevant to today's people. And
after all, it teaches the basics of love. And that's very useful,
isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Setouchi is helping Japan address one of the fundamental
tensions in any society: how to move into the future without
entirely losing a grip on the past. The challenge is particularly
great in Japan because Japanese has changed far more than most
languages.
</P>
<P>
   While English-speakers can still enjoy the 14th-century
``Canterbury Tales,'' most Japanese cannot understand works written
100 years ago. Young people often have difficulty reading anything
written more than 50 years ago, making their past largely
inaccessible to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tale of Genji'' has been translated into modern Japanese
before, by some of the nation's greatest writers, but the other
translations have tended to be in formal Japanese that today's
young people find largely indigestible or even unintelligible. So
Ms. Setouchi, who was already a famous author and renowned for her
racy novels, decided to tackle ``Genji.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a mammoth task, in part because the novel is so long _ Ms.
Setouchi's translation is 10 volumes _ and in part because the
original language is so abstruse. In the original, many sentences
have no subjects, go on forever and use many layers of archaic and
deeply nuanced politeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put lots of subjects in my sentences, so people can figure
out who is doing what, and I also broke up some long sentences,''
Ms. Setouchi said of her translation. ``My goal was to make a very
readable book, one that could be enjoyed by both elementary-school
children and by people in their 90s.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Altogether, almost 2.1 million volumes have been
sold, including 340,000 of Volume 1 and lesser numbers of the later
volumes. A ``Genji'' play has come out, and Ms. Setouchi is a
television star on the national lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   She also gives regular talks at her temple about life and
prayer, and huge throngs now turn up at them. The next step was
video collections of her lectures, and Ms. Setouchi is also
churning out various other novels and translations. Her temple _
for all its idyllic gardens and lovely antiques _ seems to have
compromised its serenity with all the fans coming to see Japan's
most famous nun.
</P>
<P>
   Janine Beichman, an American who is a professor of Japanese
literature at Daito Bunka University in Tokyo, says sales of the
latest ``Tale of Genji'' translation reflect both the greatness of
the original story and the reputation of Ms. Setouchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything she writes would be a best seller,'' she said. ``She
manages to make anything interesting, and people are also very
interested in what she does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Tale of Genji'' was written at the beginning of the 11th
century by a brilliant young widow, Shikibu Murasaki, who was
governess to the empress and had attracted the (apparently
unwanted) attentions of the empress's father. ``Tale of Genji'' was
read aloud to the emperor, and its mix of plot and heartache and
psychology _ a bit like Jane Austen _ have made it a hit ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   The renowned British translator Arthur Waley, whose ``Tale of
Genji'' is one of several translations into English, described the
original in 1925 as ``the greatest novel in the East'' and ``one of
the dozen greatest masterpieces of the world.'' In Japan, it seems
to be particularly popular among women, particularly those in
middle age or older.
</P>
<P>
   ```Tale of Genji' is filled with psychological themes,'' said
Hideyo Ueda, the director of the Japan Classic Literature Research
Institute in Tokyo. ``It subtly describes the political stage in a
different way, from the women's side.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Setouchi sees in the novel a strong feminist voice,
protesting the conditions of women at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Murasaki was a very highly educated woman, widely read,
and she knew that if she were a man she could have accomplished
much more,'' Ms. Setouchi said. ``So she wanted to express
dissatisfaction about the status of women in her day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Setouchi argues, in contrast to many other critics, that the
key figures in ``Tale of Genji'' are the women whom the prince uses
and discards. She sees the prince himself as merely a literary
device to carry the plot along and develop the more interesting
characters of the women in court.
</P>
<P>
   While Genji's liaisons are normally described as seductions, Ms.
Setouchi scoffs at that. ``It was all rape, not seduction,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   These days Japan is still ``a man's society,'' Ms. Setouchi
says, but she argues that Japanese women have made so much progress
since World War II that they are now quite free. ``Maybe too
free,'' she grunted. These days, Japanese sexual mores are becoming
more relaxed, she said, and despite some wavering she ultimately
thinks that is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are very free now to have girlfriends, and women to have
boyfriends, and it's getting back to the way it was in Genji's
time,'' Ms. Setouchi said. She paused, and a wicked smile spread
across her face, making her look more like a rebellious high-school
student than a 77-year-old chief nun with a shaven head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good to be free,'' she said, giggling, ``and to
have sex with anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
