<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3938 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-ART-2     05-27 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC AND FOUR OTHER YUGOSLAV LEADERS ARE CHARGED WITH WAR
CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ The International Criminal Tribunal
issued an arrest warrant here Thursday for Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president, charging him and other senior officials with
crimes against humanity in Kosovo, including the murder, forced
deportation and persecution of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing the indictment of Milosevic and four of his top
associates, Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor, said arrest
warrants for the five had been served on all member states of the
United Nations and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is now a much smaller place for these men,'' Ms.
Arbour said. ``We require these states, including Yugoslavia, to
arrest the accused if they are within their jurisdiction and
deliver them to The Hague for trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The others accused in the 42-page indictment are Milan
Milutinovic, the Serbian president, long a close aide to Milosevic;
Dragoljub Ojdanic, the chief of staff of the Yugoslav armed forces
and former commander of an army corps active in eastern Bosnia;
Nikola Sainovic, the deputy prime minister of Yugoslavia, and
Vlajko Stojilkovic, the minister of internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the charges branded the Yugoslav government as a
criminal regime _ an extraordinary development. But the arrest of
Milosevic, whose tenacity in holding onto power is by now
notorious, appeared highly unlikely in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the indictment clearly changed the terms of the hectic
international quest for a peace settlement to end the two-month-old
NATO bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The charges of crimes including the forced deportation of
740,000 ethnic Albanians from Kosovo this year and the murder of
more than 340 identified Albanians instantly turned Milosevic into
little short of an international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   They made it almost impossible for him to travel abroad,
rendered his signature on any international document deeply
suspect, and made negotiation with him awkward _ but not illegal _
for any state respecting the United Nations charter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these diplomatic difficulties, President Clinton
formally backed the indictment. ``I welcome the decision of the
international war crimes tribunal to indict Slobodan Milosevic and
four other senior Serbian leaders of crimes against humanity and
war crimes,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, tribunal officials said the United
States had expressed serious concerns about timing when informed a
few days ago that the indictment was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objections to our timing were quite strong, and it took a
while for everyone to understand,'' one tribunal official said.
``We had to patiently explain to Washington and some other capitals
that there was no alternative to our procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, is deeply
involved in Russian-led diplomatic efforts to end the war. The
failure of these efforts would inevitably lead to greater pressure
for a ground invasion of Kosovo by NATO forces, a step that Clinton
opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's envoy to the Balkans, is to travel
to Belgrade on Friday for a meeting with Milosevic, and he plainly
doubted the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian foreign ministry issued a statement saying the
indictment was ``politically motivated,'' and Russian officials
said talking to the Yugoslav president remained essential.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arbour, however, suggested Chernomyrdin might be talking to
the wrong man. ``Although the accused are entitled to the benefit
of the presumption of innocence until they are convicted, the
evidence upon which this indictment was confirmed raises serious
questions about their suitability to be the guarantors of any deal,
let alone a peace agreement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But the 52-year-old Canadian judge, who was appointed to the
tribunal in 1996, added that she did not expect politicians to tell
her how to do her work, and she said, ``I have no intention of
telling them how to do their work.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration made clear that contacts with
Milosevic would continue for the moment. Still, it is evident that
the Western view of the Serbian leader has changed radically. Long
seen as an unsavory strongman who could also be a de facto ally, as
he was in the negotiation of a Bosnian peace, Milosevic now appears
to be viewed as the central obstacle to Balkan peace.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said this change in the Western attitudes opened
the way for what amounted to a remarkably fast indictment by
allowing Ms. Arbour access to intelligence and other information
long denied to her by Western governments.
</P>
<P>
   It also meant that the court was able to overcome political
resistance in Western capitals to what amounted to an indictment of
devastating diplomatic timing, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arbour signed the indictment on Saturday, and it was
confirmed as valid by a tribunal judge on Monday. Western
governments were informed of the court's action between these
dates, but wider disclosure was delayed to allow a United Nations
mission to Yugoslavia to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree that this is a bad time,'' Ms. Arbour said
Thursday. ``Some will say that this indictment came too late.
Others will say that it came too soon. I say it came perfectly
appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the indictment, the British foreign secretary,
Robin Cook, said Thursday, ``There can be no deal, no amnesty for
war crimes.'' He added that there would be no negotiation on NATO's
objectives, even if ``we have to deal with those who can implement
those objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's central aims include the removal of all Serbian forces
from Kosovo, the return of all Albanians refugees, and approval
from Milosevic for the deployment of an international peacekeeping
force that would have NATO at its core.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal's action clearly complicates the attainment of
these objectives. At a minimum, Milosevic's incentive to bring a
quick end to the war no longer seems clear, for peace would bring
him no protection from arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian-dominated Yugoslav government reacted with
predictable fury to the indictment, describing it as ``another
attempt to mislead the world community in order to conceal who is
really responsible for the genocide against the Yugoslav people.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Yugoslavia began to unravel in the late 1980s,
``genocide'' has been one of the most often used words in the
Serbian political vocabulary. It has been applied to the
difficulties of some Serbs in Kosovo in the 1980s, to the effects
of the Western trade embargo on Serbia in the early 1990s, to
Croatian attacks on Serbs between 1991 and 1995, and, most
recently, to NATO's bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's aim in using this language has clearly been to
reinforce the Serbs' predominant image of themselves as victims,
and blind them to the repeated acts of Serbian violence against
civilians during the wars of Yugoslavia's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But the indictment drew a tough portrait of the Yugoslav
leader's acts, seeking to demonstrate Milosevic's personal criminal
responsibility for ordering, planning, instigating, executing or
aiding and abetting crimes committed in Kosovo this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arbour said that the role of Milosevic in Bosnia, where more
than 750,000 Muslims were driven from their homes by the Serbs in
1992, was still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accuses Milosevic of the persecution of Albanians
on racial, religious and political grounds and traces, in some
detail, what it describes as the mass execution of hundreds of
Albanians in several towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
   Before reviewing these killings, the indictment describes the
range of Milosevic's powers, in an evident attempt to establish his
responsibility for what has happened in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that, beginning on or about January 1, 1999,
and continuing until today, the forces of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and Serbia, ``acting at the direction, with the
encouragement, or with the support of Slobodan Milosevic'', have
committed acts resulting ``in the forced deportation of
approximately 740,000 Kosovo Albanian civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes on to describe Serbian acts of shelling, intimidation,
random shooting, systematic humiliation and destruction in towns
including Kosovska Mitrovica, Djakovica, Orahovac, Pec, Pristina
and Prizren that, it says, resulted in the departure or death of
large numbers of Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In some communities, the indictment describes how large numbers
of named Albanians were executed by Serbian police. For example, it
relates how 105 named Kosovo Albanian men and boys from the
villages of Velika Krusa and Mala Krusa were assembled in a house
and killed on March 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the men and boys were assembled inside the house, the
Serb police opened fire on the group,'' it says. ``After several
minutes of gunfire, the police piled hay on the men and boys and
set fire to it in order to burn the bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said such charges were based on testimony
gathered from ethnic Albanians who have now fled to Macedonia or
Albania, and on intelligence reports from western governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received, and we are continuing to receive valuable
information from governments, as well as from groups and
individuals,'' Ms. Arbour said. ``We are still awaiting further
evidence that I believe many states will be able to contribute to
our larger investigation. I repeat my pressing call to them to come
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected accusations that his forces have driven
large numbers of Albanians from their homes, saying that their
flight was prompted by the NATO bombing. He has not responded to
specific accusations of Serbian-perpetrated massacres in Kosovo,
focusing instead on the eviction of over 150,000 Serbs from Croatia
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the warrants for the arrest of the five accused, the
Tribunal also ordered United Nations member states to freeze the
assets of the men in order to limit their ability to escape and
allow possible restitution to victims in the event of conviction,
but the order is not legally binding.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arbour said she did not find it ``impossible to imagine''
that Milosevic would eventually give himself up to the court,
where, she said, he would be guaranteed a ``fair and transparent''
trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serbian leader has long made his contempt for the
international court clear, and such a surrender appeared possible
only in circumstances of complete desperation. Milosevic still
appears to have some options, including looking to Russia for
eventual protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you if Mr. Milosevic is willing to come here and
be tried,'' Ms. Arbour said. ``I say he has to. That is the rule of
law. The Yugoslav minister of justice should stand up for the rule
of law and provide for his arrest and transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Such words might appear naive or even absurd, especially in the
light of the fact that NATO forces have proved unwilling to arrest
the Bosnian Serb political and military leaders _ Radovan Karadzic
and Gen. Ratko Mladic _ who were indicted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian judge, like other tribunal officials, was
resolute and quietly confident. The tribunal, created in 1993 in
what looked like an attempt to salvage Western political
consciences after the failure to stop the Serbian rampage against
Muslims in Bosnia in 1992, long seemed peripheral and weak.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's indictment, the first time the court has moved
against a head of state, appeared to signal its definitive
emergence as an important, and perhaps highly disruptive, element
in the Balkan equation.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the charges marked a culmination of its efforts in
that Milosevic has been central to four consecutive Balkan wars _
in Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and now Kosovo _ over the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arbour said that she had chosen not to reveal much of the
evidence in the indictment, and would only do so when the accused
were under arrest in The Hague. ``That,'' she said with a smile,
``is the prudent course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
