<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-PRISONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 42,000 TEXAS INMATES INFECTED WITH HEPATITIS C, STUDY
INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE SNYDER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Preliminary results of a study of hepatitis C in Texas
prisons show that 28.6 percent of the prison population _ more than
42,000 inmates _ are infected with the potentially lethal liver
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Smith, chairman of the state's Correctional Managed
Health Care Advisory Committee, which oversees prison health care,
said the final figure ``may creep up a bit'' after further analysis
of data obtained from a sampling of about 2,600 incoming prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The figure is lower than many observers expected. A 1994 study
of California prison inmates found that 41 percent were infected
with hepatitis C, and a more recent study in Maryland prisons found
an infection rate of about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the results provide the first documentation of the scope
of an epidemic that is forcing prison policy-makers to confront
difficult medical management questions and potentially enormous
costs.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of experts who met with prison health officials in
Austin in December advised them that a ``minimal'' program for
treatment of Texas prisoners for hepatitis C would cost $65
million, said Allen Hightower, executive director of Correctional
Managed Health Care, the prison system's health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   In its current session, he said, the Texas Legislature has
appropriated $12 million for vaccinating inmates against hepatitis
B, a disease that can cause illness in patients with hepatitis C to
be more severe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, about $40 million in new funding is
available for a variety of inmate health care services. How to
apportion those funds among programs for hepatitis C and other
purposes, Hightower said, will be ``a medical decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The most effective treatment for hepatitis C, a combination of
the drugs interferon and ribavirin, costs about $10,000 for a
course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the prison system has provided treatment only with
interferon, which is less effective than combination therapy but
also significantly less costly. To date, about 95 prisoners have
been treated, said Dr. Michael Kelley, director of preventive
medicine for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is president of the Texas Tech University Health
Sciences Center and a former Texas health commissioner, said a new
policy for management of hepatitis C in the prison system will be
presented June 17 to the health-care advisory committee that he
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the new policy will be ``more aggressive in every
area, including education as well as evaluation and treatment.''
Among other changes, he said, the policy calls for moving toward
the use of combination treatments for prisoners rather than
interferon alone.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that the relatively poor results even of
combination therapy must be considered in deciding which prisoners
to treat. The combination therapy has yielded long-term benefits
only in about 40 percent of patients in clinical studies.
</P>
<P>
   And because of side effects that can be severe, Smith said,
``the dropout rate is rather high within the first two months of
treatment. In some cases, we've already experienced patients that
find the treatment worse than the disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Common side effects include fatigue and flulike symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The study, begun last November, involved drawing blood samples
from incoming inmates at selected prison units, including units
populated exclusively by drug offenders. Injection drug use is the
most common means of transmitting the hepatitis C virus.
</P>
<P>
   Among the so-called ``drug abuse units,'' where all inmates
participate in intensive drug treatment programs, the prevalence
rate was about 34 percent, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gullahorn, a founder of the Central Texas Hep C Connection,
an Austin-based patient advocacy group, said he found it
``encouraging'' that the rate of infection in prisons appears to be
somewhat lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's pretty sobering when you think about what it means''
in terms of the prison system's responsibility, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gullahorn said he is confident that the prison system and its
health care providers will develop an effective program to deal
with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Young, who chairs the health-care committee of the prison
system's governing board, said the study results will provide a
solid basis for policy decisions. She acknowledged, however, that
these decisions will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funding is always a problem,'' Young said, ``particularly in
light of the fact that we are juggling a lot of things. As
important as this (hepatitis C) is, we have to focus on a lot of
other issues. All of this is incredibly expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Emil Miskovsky, a liver specialist at the University of
Texas Medical Branch in Galveston and a principal investigator in
the study, said the results provide a valuable planning tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It documents the frequency and allows people to make concrete
plans for this prevalence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now can go full steam ahead with educational programs for
the inmates, talk to care providers about the substantial frequency
(of hepatitis C) and what kind of effect it has on the health of
the inmates that they care for.''
</P>
<P>
   Several prison inmates with hepatitis C interviewed recently
said the infection appears to be rampant in the units where they
are confined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everyone I associate with in here has it,'' said James
Whittington, an inmate at the Ramsey 1 unit in Rosharon in Brazoria
County. ``I don't know hardly anyone that doesn't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whittington, who has served eight years of a 22-year sentence
for aggravated robbery, said he learned of his disease in 1992. He
assumes his infection came from his use of injection drugs for more
than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
