<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS TUMBLE A FIFTH TIME IN SIX DAYS AS THE DOW DROPS 235.23 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices resumed their losing ways Thursday as
rising long-term interest rates prompted many investors to cash in
profits on the approach of a long holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth decline in the last six sessions and except for
the Nasdaq market, where losses were relatively modest, the drop
more than wiped out the lone recent advance on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, the hardest-hit gauge, tumbled
235.23 points, or 2.2 percent, to 10,466.93, its biggest skid of
the year in terms of points and the third time this week that its
loss surpassed 100 points. Over the latest six sessions, the
blue-chip index has lost 420 points, or 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks seem to be the tail tied to the interest-rate kite,''
said Timothy E. O'Grady, senior portfolio manager at the First
Capital Group in Philadelphia. Yields jumped by nearly 0.1 percent
on two-year notes.
</P>
<P>
   Two government reports, as well as desultory bidding at the
Treasury's note auction on Wednesday, may have contributed to the
further unease over rates and caused investors to focus again on
the Federal Reserve's stated inclination to increase rates if the
economy shows no signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   One report disclosed revised figures on first-quarter economic
output showing that personal consumption grew at a 6.8 percent
annual pace, even faster than first estimated. The other,
suggesting a continued taut labor market, recorded no rise last
week in first-time claims for jobless benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rising long-term bond yields create valuation issues,'' said
Richard B. Hoey, director of equity research at the Dreyfus Corp.,
referring to the appeal of stocks relative to fixed-income
securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's decline was not much greater than that of the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which fell 23.35 points, or 1.8 percent,
to 1,281.41. The latter, however, had 85 rising components, paced
by Intel, while only Johnson &AMP; Johnson among the Dow's 30 stocks
managed an advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which is laden with high-technology
stocks, fell 8.03 points, or three-tenths of a percent, to
2,419.15.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were at a loss to explain why most of the technology
sector resisted the decline other than it has already been badly
battered, especially Internet issues. The index is down 8.8 percent
from its record on April 26 and was down 10.2 percent on Tuesday,
enough to technically qualify as a correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have raised a lot of cash,'' said Matthew W. Johnson,
head of Nasdaq trading at Lehman Brothers. But he said whether they
were putting this money aside to buy new issues ``or taking money
off the table, is not clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Volume was moderate again Thursday, with 830 million shares
changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange and 834 million on
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the market was concerned with economic
growth, cyclical stocks were the main casualties among the Dow
components.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon lost 3[, to 78 13/16; Minnesota Mining and manufacturing
fell 2 13/16, to 86; United Technologies was down 2 9/16, to 62
3/16; Allied Signal fell 2 9/16, to 56}, and Caterpillar slumped 2
7/16, to 55].
</P>
<P>
   The other top losers were financial stocks _ J.P. Morgan lost
3}, to 135[, and American Express fell 2 11/16, to 116~.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's cyclical index slumped 2.5 percent, its biggest
loss of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is again concerned about the Fed tightening,'' said
John Kattar, director of U.S. equities at Boston Company Asset
Management.
</P>
<P>
   Some drug stocks bucked the downtrend, with Pfizer gaining 2~,
to 103~, after naming a new president and chief operating officer,
and Lilly, recommended by Credit Lyonnais, gaining 2, to 69.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which soared on Wednesday, fell 2[, to 116, after a 2-for-1
split took effect, while Merrill Lynch added 4 5/16, to 83,
continuing its run-up on rumors it will be acquired by Chase
Manhattan. Chase fell 2|, to 72}.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco, whose merger talks with Chevron seem to have stalled,
fell 2], to 62~.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, computer and Internet stocks were mostly lower
while chip-makers were mixed. Star Media Network, which went public
on Wednesday at 15, surged 19 7/16, to 45{, while DLJ Direct jumped
8, to 38, in its second day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay lost 5 5/16, to 169, Amazon.com declined 6], to 114 9/16,
and Yahoo fell 7{, to 133].
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones on the New York
Stock Exchange by nearly two to one, with 39 making new 52-week
lows and 25 new highs.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilshire 5000, the most inclusive gauge of domestic stocks,
declined by 1.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
