<SLUG> BC-TRADING-HOURS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPERS, TV NETWORKS PONDER RESPONSE TO EXPANDED TRADING HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TRADING-HOURS)  
(gm) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday's decision by the the board that governs the
Nasdaq stock market to add an evening trading session puts new
pressure on newspapers, wire services and television networks
already competing to get the latest market information to their
readers and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nasdaq's plan to continue using the traditional 4 p.m.
closing time for the day's prices could make the potential
production headaches for newspapers less severe than they had
feared. They had faced the prospect of having to update stock
listings after 10 p.m. to reflect the late trading.
</P>
<P>
   But The Associated Press, which provides stock listings to 900
newspapers, will update them with the evening results as fast as
possible, said Randy Picht, business editor at the AP.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, part of NBC and the parent General Electric Co., and
CNNfn, the business-news cable network owned by Time Warner, said
they would continue to cover the markets whenever they are trading.
</P>
<P>
   But the later hours give CNBC a potentially costly problem.
Between 8 and 10 p.m. on weeknights, the network has two programs _
``Hardball with Chris Matthews'' and ``Rivera Live'' _ that earn
higher Nielsen ratings and more advertising revenue than its
daytime business coverage does.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC could run a scrawl with the ticker figures along the bottom
of the screen during those programs, or move the programs to new
time slots, and executives there said that no decision had been
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a real sea change in financial news on
television,'' said David Borman, executive vice president of CNNfn,
which carries business news from 6 a.m. until midnight. He said the
network would probably have to add reporters to cover business
stories that break in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, too, may face that need. For example, companies
inclined to release certain information only after the market
closes may now release it at 10 p.m., rather than 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nielsen, a spokeswoman for The New York Times Co., said:
``As we learn more about the securities exchanges' plans, The Times
will decide on the best way of supplementing the traditional
tables, consistent with still providing prompt delivery of the
newspaper to subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In whatever we do,'' she added, ``we will also look for ways
to make use of The New York Times on the Web to update our
financial market coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Richard J. Tofel, a spokesman for The Wall Street Journal,
a unit of Dow Jones &AMP; Co., and Jim Henderson, deputy managing
editor for the Money section of the Gannett Co.'s USA Today, said
that editors were waiting to see what final plans the exchanges
developed before making coverage decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Borman of CNNfn said he thought that the era of 24-hour trading
was fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``After-hour mechanisms like Strike are filling the gaps, which
are already getting smaller,'' he said. ``Down the road, the
markets will fill in all the gaps. I wouldn't be surprised by
spring to see a morning session popping up. It's fascinating to see
the competition going on, and the questions it raises, and we have
a great front-row seat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
