<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK RENEWS PLEDGE TO PULL TROOPS OUT OF LEBANON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak on Thursday
pronounced as policy his campaign promise to ``bring our boys
back'' from Israeli-occupied south Lebanon within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had pledged such action repeatedly during his election
campaign against outgoing Israeli leader Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister-elect spoke while visiting a house along
Israel's border with Lebanon that had been damaged by a rocket
fired by Lebanese guerrillas as Israelis went to the polls May 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to stand firm in our right to provide a
secure life and prosperity to citizens in Kiryat Shemona and the
whole north,'' said Barak, referring to the Israeli border town
often hit by rockets fired by Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bring our boys back from Lebanon under an agreement and
make it a more secure place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, in Jerusalem, several Palestinian legislators were
beaten by Israeli police during a peaceful sit-in at the site of a
controversial Jewish housing project in east Jerusalem. Two
legislators were treated for minor injuries at nearby Maqassed
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Ariel Sharon was named temporary leader of the
Likud Party, replacing Netanyahu who stepped down hours after his
crushing election defeat against Barak. Netanyahu said he would
resign his Knesset seat as well but hinted he was not leaving
politics permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's renewed pledge to pull troops out of Lebanon kindled
speculation that preparations to leave the zone, set up in 1985 to
protect Israel's northern towns from guerrilla attack, might be
seriously in the making.
</P>
<P>
   For days, the local press has been reporting that the army was
considering withdrawing its proxy militia, which it calls the South
Lebanese Army, from the Christian enclave of Jezzine, a move that
could be carried out in weeks or even days.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, the Israeli army's chief of staff, said
the decision was made by SLA commander Antoine Lahad, not Israel,
and should not be taken as a sign that Israel intended to withdraw
farther from the zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly suggest not to draw conclusions from Antoine
Lahad's decision to withdraw from Jezzine,'' Mofaz said on Israel
Army Radio. ``We will deliberate our future steps according to
decisions made at the political level and the (army's) assessment
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With casualties mounting _ nine soldiers have died in Lebanon
this year _ Israel's government has come under increasing public
pressure to get out of Lebanon, even if it means unilaterally
withdrawing troops.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Israel's military commanders have come out against
withdrawing without a peace agreement with Syria, or at least some
kind of guarantees from Lebanon's government to curb Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the end,'' said Eyal Zisser, a
researcher at the Moshe Dayan Center for Middle Eastern and African
Studies, Tel Aviv University. ``It's quite clear that the concept
of the security zone has collapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was based on the readiness of the Lebanese to
cooperate with Israel and on their ability to resist Hezbollah and
secure the northern border,'' Zisser said. ``The fact that the
South Lebanon Army cannot maintain its presence (in Jezzine) and
Israel has decided it can't send its forces there, well, it means
that the concept of the security zone is not valid anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If the regular Lebanese Army moves into Jezzine after the SLA
leaves and prevents Hezbollah activity, Israeli commentators say it
could make it easier for Israel to leave more Lebanese territory in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Matan Vilnai, a former deputy chief of staff and Labor party
legislator close to Barak, called Jezzine ``a litmus test for what
is to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yossi Beilin, a member of Barak's Labor party who led an
earlier drive to quit Lebanon, said this week that a unilateral
withdrawal would not work without security guarantees from Syria,
the main power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Those guarantees are not likely forthcoming without an agreement
that involves substantial Israeli withdrawal from the Golan
Heights, captured from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he plans to restart stalled negotiations with
Syrian President Hafez Assad. The stumbling point is over the point
at which those talks should begin.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, under Netanyahu, wanted to begin without reference to
any progress made in negotiations between Syria and Israel's
previous Labor-led government. Syria insisted on entering the talks
at the point at which negotiators left off when talks stopped in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
