<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBOUND IN CORPORATE PROFITS REPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients
and to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than a year of weak growth, corporate profits
rebounded in the first quarter, the Commerce Department reported
Thursday. The giant settlement of litigation against tobacco
companies distorted the figures, temporarily fattening the
first-quarter number. But the rebound also suggested that the
squeeze on profits evident last year may have lifted a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The profit report, the first for the January-through-March
period, appeared in the Commerce Department's latest estimate of
first-quarter economic growth. The gross domestic product grew at
an annual rate of 4.1 percent, the report said, down somewhat from
the 4.5 percent rate reported last month and well below the 6
percent annual rate in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending and investment rose strongly, or as Robert
Barbera, chief economist of the Hoenig Group, put it, ``The front
end of the economy remains strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were drags. Exports were lower than the Commerce
Department originally estimated for the quarter. That was also the
case for federal spending and for inventory accumulation, which is
the stockpiling of newly manufactured merchandise in anticipation
of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is not weakening, but there is a kind of bending
off in the growth rate,'' said Chris Varvares, a partner at
Macroeconomic Advisers Inc. The GDP grew by 3.9 percent for the
year that ended with the first quarter, down from 4.3 percent for
the year that ended with the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate profits number produced by the Commerce Department
is hard to interpret. Yet many economists consider it perhaps the
most realistic measure of how much money American companies are
actually making.
</P>
<P>
   Each quarter, the department's Bureau of Economic Analysis
calculates profits before taxes, and adjusted so that the value of
inventories and capital reflect their actual replacement costs.
Profits figured in this way rose by 3.9 percent in the first
quarter, to an annual rate of $853.5 billion. That was the biggest
quarterly jump in more than a year, and it followed a string of
quarters in which profits either declined or grew by less than 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco settlement, in which the companies reimbursed states
that had sued them for health costs, turned out to be the biggest
single factor in the first-quarter jump. The companies had paid out
$13.5 billion at an annual rate in the fourth quarter, but only
$900 million in the first quarter. The swing cut into
fourth-quarter profits and produced a jump in the first-quarter
number.
</P>
<P>
   For the nation's nonfinancial companies _ that is, companies
other than banks, brokerage firms, investment houses and the like _
the swing represented more than 60 percent of the profit growth.
But other factors, perhaps more enduring, were also in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Wages rose, but so did productivity, or the amount that a worker
produces each hour on the job. And that extra output for the same
labor cost helped to improve profits, economists said. Nonlabor
costs, including raw materials, also eased off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting the tobacco stuff aside,'' Varvares said, ``profits
still seem to be in some sort of a rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the GDP report, the Commerce Department also produces
an inflation indicator that is broader than the Consumer Price
Index. Commerce's ``implicit price deflator'' rose 1.4 percent in
the first quarter, the same estimate published last month.
</P>
<P>
   In another report on Thursday, the Labor Department said that
the number of Americans filing new claims for state unemployment
benefits was 300,000 last week, unchanged from the week before. The
number has held to 300,000 or less for 12 of the last 21 weeks, a
sign that the demand for workers remains robust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
