<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-WRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT LIVES ON THE EDGE WITH HIS PITCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Almost every club in baseball wishes it had a
pitcher like Jaret Wright. Only 23, he throws a 97-mile-an-hour
fastball that hitters have learned to fear. Therein lies the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two seasons, Wright has become a regular in the
Indians rotation, helping Cleveland compile the best record in
baseball this season. But he also has developed a reputation as a
headhunter, a pitcher not afraid to push the limits of throwing
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams consider this a badge of courage. Others consider it
an invitation to battle.
</P>
<P>
   Wright has hit four batters in his career. One is Darren Lewis
of the Red Sox, whom he will face Friday night in a rematch of a
tension-filled game at Fenway Park April 23.
</P>
<P>
   That game produced hard feelings and suspensions for both teams.
Wright triggered a benches-clearing confrontation when he hit Lewis
with a pitch after buzzing Damon Buford following a Troy O'Leary
home run. The righthander was suspended for five games and fined
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't alter his habits. Last Saturday, Wright hit
Detroit's Tony Clark in the batting helmet with a pitch that set
the stage for a benches-clearing brawl a half-inning later.
Thursday he was fined an undisclosed amount, and American League
president Gene Budig took a further, extraordinary step: He
announced his intention to talk to Wright and Indians manager Mike
Hargrove next week about the pitcher's ``deportment on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright seems unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to get outs for my team and keep the game
close,'' he said. ``Baseball is baseball. You play hard and you
play the game to win. At this level, it's a war out there. You do
what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   How Wright goes about the job is symptomatic of what
commissioner Bud Selig considers an alarming trend.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said he understands the history of such skirmishes between
pitchers who throw at hitters and hitters who charge the mound in
retaliation. But he advocates stiffer penalties for both, perhaps
as soon as this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the violence . . . throwing at players'
heads especially,'' he said. ``We're going to take some very
stringent action . . . there's much too much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Indians don't want any judicial tampering with Wright's
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaret is always going to have to pitch in,'' said general
manager John Hart. ``It's a part of throwing the ball 96-97 miles
an hour. In no way is he a headhunter. But a reputatiion like this
is hard to get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   ``His pitches are frequently up in the zone. When he's up and
away, nobody says a thing. When he goes up and in, there can be
problems. When Pedro Martinez was at Montreal, he was accused of
throwing at guys. But he settled down, and now his career has taken
off. I think Jaret will eventually get beyond it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have brought in veteran pitching coach Phil Regan to
help Wright with his mechanics. The youngster must figure out how
to avoid hitting batters who dive across the plate and how to deal
with statues in the box like Mo Vaughn who wear thick elbow pads
and shrug off inside pitches like gnats.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is to have command of all your pitches. It is all
that keeps Wright from moving up to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``To label Jaret Wright a headhunter is like going out and
saying the same thing about Roger Clemens or Pedro Martinez,'' said
Indians manager Mike Hargrove. ``Pedro did the same thing in
Montreal. I can go back to Bob Gibson or Nolan Ryan. These guys
were hard throwers and tough guys who established themselves
inside. That's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inner half is part of the plate. It always has been. It's
got to be. I don't care if you pitch 40 miles an hour or 400 miles
an hour, you've got to pitch in to be effective. Ninety-five
percent of the outs are made on pitches away. So people are working
outside to get people out, and don't think the hitters don't know
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright reiterated several times this week that he has never
diliberately thrown at a batter. He is what some managers call
effectively wild. Last year he appeared in 32 games and posted a
12-10 record. But he gave up 207 hits and had a 4.72 earned run
average with just 140 strikeouts in 192 2/3 innings. With his
stuff, he should be doing better. This year he is 4-2 with a 6.08
ERA. As he says, he's still learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew where it was going all the time, then I wouldn't
have a 6.08 ERA,'' said Wright. ``Last year was my first full year,
and I pitched in a lot of games. This year I've been working on
other things with Phil Regan to iron out my mechanics so that I
know where the ball is going. A lot of hitters are diving over the
plate. As pitchers, we can't let that affect us. We've still got to
throw inside as much as we can. I think you have to throw inside to
be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's priority with Wright is to make him a better
pitcher. He has the talent to do it, Regan believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed his delivery a little bit and he's getting more
body into his motion,'' said Regan. ``He's changing speeds. He's
getting over to the lefthand side of the rubber. He's getting the
ball more outside to righthanders and more inside to lefthanders.
His changeup has been coming along real well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can throw a ball 97 miles an hour. But now he's pitching.
The other day in Detroit with (Bobby) Higginson up on a 3-2 pitch,
he took a little bit off his sinker _ down to 90 miles an hour _
and got the batter out front and got a ground ball. He's doing very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox may not agree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
