<SLUG> BC-JUDICIAL-LAPSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE CHASTIZED FOR DELAY IN HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For months Edwin Jones languished in a jail cell while
the judge he had repeatedly written to requesting a bail hearing
devoted much of his time to a protracted case involving
high-profile mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in a rare breach of judicial etiquette, Chief US
District Judge William G. Young called the lapse by Judge Mark L.
Wolf, who apparently ignored Jones's appeals, ``inexplicable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be no excuse other than the press of other
important court business for not timely addressing this motion,''
Young wrote in a memorandum released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is crystal clear that Jones never received the prompt
hearing to which he was entitled,'' added Young, who nonetheless
refused to release Jones, an alleged drug dealer, from jail pending
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, he languished in custody for nearly a year before a
district judge even considered his detention status.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jones waited in jail, Wolf presided over lengthy mob
hearings that apparently crowded out other court business, such as
Jones's personal appeal for a bail hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the spring and summer of 1997 and continuing
sporadically into this year, Wolf has devoted much of his attention
to the legal claims of jailed organized crime figures Francis P.
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, boss of the New England Mafia, Winter
Hill Gang leader Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi, and two
associates.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is asking that extortion and racketeering charges brought
against him be dismissed, asserting that as a longtime FBI
informant he had been given permission by his handlers to commit
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Salemme, Flemmi, and their associates were indicted in January
1995. Wolf has yet to rule on the legality of the charges and no
trial date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his involvement with the mob case, Wolf has sent some
of his other cases back to the court clerk's office to be randomly
assigned to other judges.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite Wolf's inaction in Jones's case, Young refused to
release him pending trial, saying Jones was dangerous and might
flee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Young called Wolf's delay in holding a detention
hearing ``a serious matter.'' Young did not mention Wolf by name in
his memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was complicated, Young said, by the fact that
Jones's previous lawyer withdrew from the case without the court's
permission, leaving Jones in the lurch. Four letters Jones sent to
the court requesting a hearing apparently never reached Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Young said that occurred because the court's internal
computer-generated tracking system focuses unduly on motions, to
the exclusion of other types of correspondence, such as letters.
</P>
<P>
   Young promised to perform a ``searching review'' of court
procedures to ensure such mixups do not reoccur. He proposed
training docket clerks to recognize the importance of all motions
and letters pertaining to the detention of defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was arrested on May 29, 1998 and ordered detained on June
17, 1998 by US Magistrate Judge Marianne Bowler. Jones's
then-lawyer, Jeremy Carter, filed a motion for a bail review
hearing on Sept. 10, 1998, 18 days before he withdrew as Jones's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Carter did not obtain court permission to withdraw,
but Carter insisted he had.
</P>
<P>
   During the months that followed, Jones wrote several letters to
the court requesting a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until a new lawyer, Jonathan Shapiro, was
appointed to represent Jones in January that the case was
transferred to Young for a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said Thursday it was ``outrageous'' that Young refused
to release Jones. ``To say it is terrible that this happened but
then do nothing about it makes a mockery of the law,'' Shapiro
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
