<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RENO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO SAYS SHE WAS NOT FULLY BRIEFED ON PLAN TO WIRETAP SCIENTIST
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-NUKE)  
(sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusual defense of her handling of a nuclear
espionage case, Attorney General Janet Reno said on Thursday that
she was never fully informed of a dispute between the Justice
Department and the FBI over a proposal to wiretap a scientist
suspected of spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who rarely comments on internal disputes, said that FBI
Director Louis J. Freeh or her own intelligence staff should have
advised her of their disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there is something serious, where Louis Freeh disagrees
with the findings, it should be discussed at my level,'' Reno said
at her weekly news conference, referring to the disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   She discussed the case after a congressional report determined
that the government had failed to plug security leaks at the
nuclear weapons laboratories over many years and that China had
systematically pilfered key design details of the United States'
most advanced nuclear weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   While she has testified in closed hearings in Congress, Reno's
comments on Thursday represented her most extensive defense in
public of her handling of the most serious case of suspected
Chinese espionage. Her remarks appeared to be an attempt to deflect
tremendous Republican pressure exerted against her in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   When Reno was asked on Thursday whether she knew about the
details of the FBI's request to wiretap the suspected scientist,
Wen Ho Lee, she said, ``I was not briefed on the details of the
application.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Should you have been briefed?'' a reporter asked.
</P>
<P>
   She replied, ``I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks came after lawmakers in both political parties have
held Reno responsible for failing to aggressively respond to the
espionage threat, accusing her of bungling the investigation of
Lee, a Los Alamos nuclear scientist who has been fired but has not
been charged with any crime. Lee has denied that he spied for any
foreign power.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans have demanded Reno's resignation, but she said
on Thursday that she had not considered stepping aside. She said
she had called Charles F.C. Ruff, the White House counsel, who told
her that President Clinton had confidence in her stewardship.
Later, Ruff confirmed that he had told Reno that her job was
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats expressed support on Thursday for Reno, saying
she had been unfairly singled out as a scapegoat. Sen. Joseph
Biden, D-Del., who is experienced in criminal justice and
intelligence issues, said, ``The bottom line is that from my
standpoint, I don't know what else any other attorney general would
likely have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The theft of secrets from the country's nuclear weapons labs is
suspected to have occurred in the early 1980s. Energy Department
officials did not suspect Lee until 1995 and the FBI investigation
did not begin until mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
   But officials have said evidence against him was dated and
fragmentary, based primarily on his access to data believed to have
fallen into Chinese hands and on collateral evidence, like his past
travels to meetings with scientists in China.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1997 the Justice Department's Office of Intelligence
Policy Review concluded that the evidence was so thin that it
refused an FBI request to apply to a special foreign intelligence
court for a warrant to put a wiretap on Lee's telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that John F. Lewis, a senior FBI official,
subsequently questioned the decision. Based on his concerns, Reno
said she ordered a second review by the Justice Department, which
also concluded that the FBI had failed to produce enough evidence
to justify asking the espionage court for a wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, in August 1997, Reno asked the Justice
Department's Executive Office for National Security to review the
decision. A lawyer in that office, Daniel Seikaly, agreed with the
earlier decision, she said. He communicated his opinion to the FBI,
but did not advise Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said FBI officials dropped the issue. For her part, Reno
said, ``I assumed that since I did not hear from the FBI, that the
matter had been resolved to their satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, FBI officials said that investigators decided to pursue
other avenues. An FBI agent posing as a Chinese intelligence
officer approached Lee, but the scientist rebuffed the invitation
to spy for Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Not until this year did FBI agents obtain Lee's consent to
search his office computer _ finding, they said, that he had
downloaded from a classified to a unclassified computer system
thousands of lines of secret computer codes used in the design of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
