<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-KIDNAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAGAN TO PLEAD GUILTY TO KIDNAPPING DAUGHTERS IN 1979 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a negotiated end to a case rooted in a bitter,
20-year-old custody fight, Stephen H. Fagan will plead guilty
Friday to kidnapping his daughters from his former wife's North
Adams home in 1979 and raising them under assumed names in Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The plea deal for Fagan, nearly six months in the making and
similar to one rejected by a judge in February, doesn't require him
to serve any jail time, according to sources. But Fagan _ who
remade himself from a bar bouncer with a law degree to a
high-society patron who was a national security consultant _ will
be placed on probation and pay a fine.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing will mark the first time in 20 years that Barbara E.
Kurth will see her two daughters in person. After he swept them
away from her as children, Fagan told the girls that their mother
had died in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley and
Richard M. Egbert, Fagan's lawyer, sealed the agreement. Neither
Egbert nor Coakley's office would comment on the case or specifics
of the agreement, such as the length of his term on probation or
the size of the fine. Fagan faced up to 10 years in prison for the
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   The current plea deal is similar to one both sides agreed to in
February, but it was never presented in court because the presiding
judge, Joseph A. Grasso Jr., raised objections in private that it
did not include any jail time for Fagan.
</P>
<P>
   However, Grasso was assigned to sit in Essex County under a
routine rotation earlier this month. As a result, the Fagan case
was taken by Judge Peter M. Lauriat.
</P>
<P>
   He has reportedly indicated he will approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark T. Smith, Kurth's lawyer, said Thursday that Kurth _ now a
molecular biologist at the University of Virginia _ did not oppose
the deal, even though Fagan won't go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that he makes an admission of the crime, Dr.
Kurth supports the agreement,'' Smith said. ``As for the other
parts of the agreement, that is a matter between Mr. Fagan and the
District Attorney's office.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Kurth and her lawyers have dodged when asked
whether she wanted Fagan behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that Kurth plans to attend the session and was
writing a statement that either she or Rooney would read in court.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughters, Rachel Martin, 23, and Lisa Martin, 21, who have
steadfastly remained by their father's side, are also expected to
accompany him to the 2 p.m. session.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Thursday that Kurth has not seen her daughters in
person since October 1979, when Fagan took them for a weekend visit
and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Fagan and Kurth had been divorced for a year but
were locked in a bitter custody battle. Fagan argued that Kurth,
then a homemaker, was an alcoholic and an unfit mother.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after their disappearance, the probate judge on the
case ruled in Kurth's favor and ordered Fagan to hand over the
children. By then, Fagan, who had changed his identity to William
Martin, and his daughters had arrived in Key West, Fla., where an
old female friend took them in.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, he moved to Palm Beach. While he never worked,
Fagan lived well: he married two wealthy women and passed himself
off as a top-echelon government consultant and CIA agent.
</P>
<P>
   From all accounts, Fagan was a good and nurturing father: both
daughters were top athletes and attended college. They have also
spurned overtures from Kurth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
