<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM-500&AMP;     05-27 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN PHONE GIANT SEEKS TO REPAIR DAMAGE IN WAKE OF LOST ITALIAN
BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Stung by the collapse of its $81 billion
attempted acquisition of Telecom Italia, Deutsche Telekom AG is now
scrambling to rescue a global partnership with France Telecom and
the Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Though peppered with occasionally angry questions about the loss
of Telecom Italia to Olivetti at Deutsche Telekom's annual
shareholders meeting Thursday, executives pledged to press ahead
with foreign takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deutsche Telekom's goals for the future will still be reached,
even if the merger with Telecom Italia doesn't take place,'' the
company's chairman, Ron Sommer, said. ``We are in a position of
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he defended the failed Italian acquisition, Sommer
announced the need to reposition a money-losing international
venture, Global One.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are immense. Owned jointly with France Telecom and
Sprint, Global One provides worldwide networking services for
multinational companies. But the venture lost hundreds of millions
of dollars last year and sales have been stagnant. And complicating
matters, Sommer has all but destroyed his relationship with the
chairman of France Telecom, Michel Bon, who was infuriated by the
bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Sommer's chagrin, Deutsche Telekom's biggest rival at
home consolidated its position a bit more on Thursday. Mannesmann
A.G., which is already buying out Olivetti's stake in Italy's
second-largest cellular phone carrier, announced that it is buying
out its minority partners in Arcor, the German concern that
competes with Deutsche Telekom in wired service.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives are now trying to reconstruct their strategy
amid the wreckage of the bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Global One sales are nearly insignificant compared with those of
Deutsche Telekom. But executives said it remains crucial for
retaining big corporate customers like Siemens or DaimlerChrysler.
If they cannot offer such customers worldwide networking, they fear
losing them as domestic customers, too.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the French and German telecommunications giants
are barely speaking with each other, neither is willing to ask for
a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, from Deutsche Telekom's perspective, would be
to either increase its stake or perhaps to buy Sprint itself.
Either would require approval from France Telecom, which appears
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom executives seem to be angling for a new
approach that would reduce the central role in the alliance of
Global One and give each partner more flexibility to market
multinational services on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to provide comprehensive service around the
world, they said, Global One would be better off by focusing on
particular regions with heavy traffic. Jeffrey A. Hedberg, Deutsche
Telekom's new managing director for international strategy, said
that to provide all services everywhere would be very expensive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens with Global One, Sommer insisted that
his futile bid for Telecom Italia had not lessened his interest in
international acquisitions. Indeed, he said that Deutsche Telekom
would have been interested in a merger with France Telecom, but
recognized that the French government would never have agreed to
relinquish its controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
   Though executives of France Telecom insist that the two
companies never held discussions, German executives said they had
explored ways to ``accelerate'' the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer would love to buy more wireless companies, particularly
now that Mannesmann controls huge franchises in both Germany and
Italy and Vodafone PLC of Britain is buying Airtouch Communications
of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He also placed heavy emphasis on Deutsche Telekom's Internet
business, T-Online, the largest access provider in Europe, and
which competes with AOL Europe, a joint venture of America Online
and Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   And he expressed interest in companies that install and maintain
complex information networks, which has led to speculation here
that Deutsche Telekom might buy an American company like Electronic
Data Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sommer was peppered with criticism from some shareholders
at Thursday's meeting in Cologne, no one called for his
resignation. On Wednesday, the company's board issued a statement
of support and on Thursday his contract was renewed for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer seemed somewhat amazed at what he called the emotional
reactions by France Telecom and by many critics in Italy. ``I
believe it was personal reaction, not a business reaction,'' he
told reporters on Wednesday night, referring to Bon's anger. In the
United States, he said wistfully, ``it is much more pragmatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
