<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 The Temps Strike Back  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
How do you tell the difference between an employee and a temp?
<P>
   That's not a riddle with a bad punch line: It's a modern-day
conundrum facing American businesses who want to use temporary
workers but fear getting in legal trouble over them.
</P>
<P>
   As companies use more nonpermanent workers than ever before,
they are facing a growing number of lawsuits claiming these temps
and contractors are really employees who deserve millions of
dollars worth of retroactive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile case so far has involved Microsoft Corp.
Two weeks ago, a San Francisco federal appeals court told the
software giant that it may have to give retroactive benefits not
just to a few hundred former independent contractors but to
thousands of temporary employees from staffing agencies.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft is far from alone in its temp troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area companies such as Pacific Bell and PG&AMP;E are also
grappling with lawsuits by former temps and contractors who claim
they should have received the same perks as regular employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the next wave of employment litigation,''
said Larry Shapiro, editor of the California Employer Advisor
newsletter in Tiburon. ``The Microsoft case sounds a siren of
alarm. Employers should be very careful because, later on, if their
contractors or temps are reclassified as employees, they may be
eligible for very expensive retroactive benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Temp Work on the Rise
</P>
<P>
   The evolving court rulings about temporary workers have a broad
impact because so many companies today rely on nonpermanent or
``contingent'' workers.
</P>
<P>
   The portion of the U.S. workforce employed by temporary agencies
rose from 0.5 percent in 1982 to 2.2 percent in 1997, according to
the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Together with independent contractors and employees of
contracting firms, temps now account for one of every 10 workers _
more than 13 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Many are traditional kinds of temp workers such as secretaries.
But others are highly-paid professionals such as computer
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Silicon Valley, the use of temps &LR;   &LR; and contractors is
rampant,'' said Mark Thierman, attorney for a group of former
temporary employees who are suing Pacific Bell for back benefits.
``It's a combination of the entrepreneurial spirit of people who
prefer to be contractors, and the psychological issue of companies
feeling that if you don't officially hire someone, it's easier to
fire them.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal risks of using contractors first hit the headlines in
the early 1990s, when the IRS ruled that Microsoft owed back
payroll taxes for hundreds of independent contractors who should
have been classified as employees.
</P>
<P>
   Later, many of those contractors filed suit against Microsoft
demanding the same benefits as regular employees _ including
participation in Microsoft's employee stock purchase program.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld a lower court
ruling in favor of the contractors.
</P>
<P>
   And on May 12, a three-judge panel of the Ninth Circuit Court of
Appeals in San Francisco said that the company may also have to
extend its stock purchase program to long-term temporary staff who
were working through temp agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is appealing that ruling. But in the meantime, the
message to employers is clear: Longtime temporary workers may be
legally considered your employees even if they're on the payroll of
a staffing agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier rulings have all pointed in the direction that if
a business uses temporary help over a (long) period of time, they
could be considered employees for benefit purposes,'' said Ed Lenz,
general counsel for the National Association of Temporary and
Staffing Services. ``The Microsoft decision moves the ball a little
further down the field toward that point,'' Lenz added. ``But
there's quite a way to go before we know how this will all work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruled that Microsoft exercised enough daily
control over its temps to be considered their employer, even if
they were being paid by an outside agency.
</P>
<P>
   Other legal cases are also addressing the question of
temps-versus-employees _ but with conflicting results.
</P>
<P>
   In one local case, more than a dozen clerical workers sued PG&AMP;E
in 1995 claiming they were legally employees even though they were
on the payroll of temp agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The temps worked side by side with permanent PG&AMP;E employees;
they used PG&AMP;E letterhead and business cards; they took part in
PG&AMP;E training and had their expenses reimbursed by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They missed out on the company's pretty generous pension plan,
a savings plan with matching contributions, and a wide range of
health and disability benefits,'' said Janet Brown, an attorney
with Sigman Lewis &AMP; Feinberg who is representing the workers.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge dismissed the temps' case on May 12, saying they
were not PG&AMP;E employees because they were paid by temp agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision seems at odds with the Ninth Circuit's ruling
in the Microsoft case _ and so the temps are planning to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a group of temporary employees filed a class-action
suit against Pacific Bell on May 18 _ citing the Microsoft ruling
that was handed down just six days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Bell plaintiffs include more than 360 longtime phone
company workers who were laid off during a downsizing in the early
1990s. They were then immediately re-hired to do the exact same
jobs _ but as temp agency employees without benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Thierman, who is representing the Pacific Bell workers, said the
suit covers a total of 1,700 temporary employees who lost out on
$30 million in pensions and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell declined to comment on the suit.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it remains unclear what the courts' final word
will be on who is the legal employer of longtime temp workers.
</P>
<P>
   While companies wait for an answer, legal experts advise them to
take a close look at their staffing practices: The more control a
firm exercises over its long-term temps and contractors, the
greater the risk that they will be considered employees.
</P>
<P>
   Employment law experts also advise them to review the
eligibility rules for their benefit plans. ``See if there's
anything that can be done to tighten up the definition of
`employee,''' said Shapiro of the California Employer Advisor.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms have hired outside human resource consultants to help
them steer clear of Microsoft-like legal messes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients are Fortune 1000 companies that are committed to
using contingent workers but want to manage them better so they
don't do what Microsoft did,'' said Terrie Weinand, senior vice
president of PrO Unlimited, which helps companies manage their
temporary workforces.
</P>
<P>
   At PG&AMP;E, HR executives have stepped up efforts to educate
managers on how to deal with temps and contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our guidelines is that if you want a (temp) agency
worker to stay on a job longer than six months, it requires the
approval of a vice president or above,'' said PG&AMP;E spokesman Len
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No.1 rule is to remember that agency workers are employed
by the staffing company,'' Anderson added. ``If anything comes up
around performance or working conditions or wages, those
discussions need to be between the worker and the staffing
agency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
