</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 When the Boss Plays Favorites  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question:  &LR; I work at a large unionized company. My boss is a very
ambitious micro-manager who has a favorite employee and a
scapegoat. She constantly writes up the scapegoat and has
threatened to fire him, while she turns a blind eye to problems
caused by her favorite. The rest of us feel this is unfair. The
union says it can't do anything. What can we do?
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  This is one of those all-too-common workplace problems
where there's unfortunately no easy fix.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the obvious. Has anyone in your department
talked to the boss about this? Sometimes there are good reasons _
such as fear of retaliation _ to avoid such a conversation, but
often people are just too cautious or fearful of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that can happen in union shops is that people don't
deal with problems in a person-to-person way, and instead look for
someone else to do it,'' said Rick Maurer, a Virginia management
consultant and author of ``Beyond the Wall of Resistance:
Unconventional Strategies that Build Support for Change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Choose an individual who has credibility with the manager,''
Maurer added. ``Then have them go forward and say they've noticed
this (scapegoating) and don't think it's productive or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Another piece of obvious advice is to talk to your human
resources department. Not all firms have an HR staff. And not all
HR people will have the authority to intervene in a situation like
this. But there's a chance that HR would be willing to confront
your boss or alert her superiors if she is clearly out of line.
</P>
<P>
   There also may be more that the union can do. If your colleague
is being written up without justification, the union should be able
to file grievances over those notices.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, it's possible there's no way to solve this
problem. Your boss' approach to the world has been formed over
decades and is unlikely to change overnight.
</P>
<P>
   You can offer the scapegoat friendly words or a shoulder to lean
on. These small gestures can make a big difference to someone who
feels under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the scapegoat may simply need to move on.
And if the work environment is really demoralizing, you may want to
move too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God it's a good time to find a new job,'' said Matt
Weinstein, a Berkeley management consultant with the firm Playfair
and author of ``Work Like Your Dog: 50 Ways to Work Less, Play
More, and Earn More.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to take a radical measure like getting
out of there. And later you'll say, `Thank God for that untenable
situation, since it made me move on to a better one.'''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've worked at a computer consulting firm for several years.
My boss recently asked me to sign a statement saying that if I
leave the firm, I will not work for any current client for two
years after I leave. Is this legal? Should I sign it?
</P>
<P>
   A: California's laws were written to give employees a lot of
freedom to seek work in an open job market. So California courts
typically throw out contracts that say employees can't leave their
job to work for a competing firm, or can't leave and work for their
current firm's clients.
</P>
<P>
   But the courts do allow companies to prohibit employees from
taking trade secrets (such as confidential customer lists) with
them when they leave.
</P>
<P>
   And the courts often allow companies to draft
``nonsolicitation'' agreements barring employees from actively
soliciting the firm's clients for a limited amount of time after
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   If your boss' statement says you can't  &LR; solicit &LR;  clients, that's
probably legal, although two years may be an overly long period.
``I think the courts would view six months to one year as more
reasonable,'' said Gary Moore, an intellectual property lawyer with
McCutchen Doyle Brown &AMP; Enersen in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   But if the statement simply says that you can't  &LR; work &LR;  for the
firm's current clients after you leave, that's legally shaky.
</P>
<P>
   One option is to avoid rocking the boat and sign the agreement,
knowing your boss probably won't be able to hold you to it. But
that's risky. Who wants to face a lawsuit _ even if the chances are
good that you'll win?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's generally a bad idea to sign something you think is
unenforceable,'' said Moore. ``Instead, I'd suggest talking to the
boss. You can say that you're sympathetic to the idea of a
nonsolicitation agreement, but it's inappropriate for the company
to say whom you can work for after you leave.''
</P>
<P>
   One note about nonsolicitation agreements: You're banned from
actively marketing your services to the firm's clients, but you're
allowed to notify them in writing that you're leaving the firm. And
if clients choose on their own to follow you to your new company,
that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
