<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Guidelines on Difference Between Employees, Temps  &HT;       
 Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It would be nice if there were a simple definition of who's a
regular employee and who's a temp _ if, for instance, the courts
ruled that temps and contractors must be considered permanent
employees after six months on a job.
<P>
   But as of now, there's no clear and simple way to differentiate
employee versus temp.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly used guidelines so far come from the IRS,
which has what is called a ``20-factor test'' for determining who
are employees and who are independent contractors for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Some civil courts also have used the IRS definition to help
determine whether longtime temps should be eligible for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS' guidelines can be found in its Publication 15A
(Employer's Supplemental Tax Guide), available at
 &LR; www.irs.ustreas.gov &LR; . In a nutshell, the IRS considers:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Behavioral control.  &LR; Employees generally are subject to the
company's instructions about when, where and how to work. They may
be trained to perform services in a particular manner. Independent
contractors, on the other hand, typically set their own schedules
and use their own methods.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Financial control. &LR;  Contractors tend to control the financial
aspects of their job; employees don't. For instance, contractors
are more likely to have unreimbursed business expenses and to
invest in their own work equipment. Contractors usually (but not
always) are paid by the job, while employees are paid by the hour,
week or month. And unlike employees, contractors can make a profit
or loss from their work.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Type of relationship. &LR;  Is there a written contract describing
the relationship between the worker and the company? Does the
company provide benefits such as vacation pay and insurance? Is the
relationship open-ended or for a fixed amount of time? Are the
services rendered by the worker a key part of the business' regular
activity, as opposed to a special project?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
