<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDOM HOUSE CANCELS BOOK ON EISNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broadway Books, a publishing division of Random House Inc., has
canceled its contract with Kim Masters, a contributing editor of
both Time and Vanity Fair magazines, to publish her book about
Michael Eisner, the chairman of the Walt Disney Co., and his
ascension to Hollywood power.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Fields, Ms. Masters' attorney _ who currently represents
Jeffrey Katzenberg in a dispute with Eisner _ contended Thursday
that Broadway Books canceled the book, ``Keys to the Kingdom,''
because Random House does not want to offend Eisner or the Walt
Disney Co. The cancellation was first reported on the MSNBC Web
site ``The Scoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields said, ``I found it strange that Broadway Books, having
publicly and privately raved about the book, mysteriously decided
that they did not want to publish it and we are gathering evidence
on why.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Applebaum, a spokesman for Random House, said the Walt
Disney Co. had no role in ``tampering with Broadway Books'
editorial integrity'' and questioned Ms. Masters' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going forward with the Kim Masters book because we
found the author's reporting to be sadly inadequate,'' Applebaum
said. ``When we acquired the book, Broadway was led to expect that,
upon completion, it would be a groundbreaking and wide-ranging
investigative book on the Disney company. It was anything but.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields said there were several possible reasons for the
cancellation, including the fact that Random House published
Eisner's autobiography, ``Work in Progress,'' last year. (Ms.
Masters contracted to write the book with Broadway Books when it
was a division of Bertelsmann AG not affiliated with Random House.
Random House was purchased by Bertelsmann last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Random House has requested that Ms. Masters repay the first half
of her reported $700,000 advance. Editors at William Morrow &AMP; Co.,
which is owned by Hearst Corp., have offered to buy the rights to
the book when the dispute surrounding Ms. Masters' contract is
settled. Ms. Masters Thursday referred all questions to Fields.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Ferris, the executive editor of William Morrow, described
the reporting as ``solid,'' and anticipated that the book could be
a big seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book certainly holds up her reputation as a journalist,
and her ability to get a story in a way that no other reporter on
this beat seems to be able to do,'' Ferris said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
