<HEADER>
A3974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-NUKE-525&AMP;ADD-N     05-27 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-NUKE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING A SUSPECT SITE, U.S. FINDS ONLY AN EMPTY TUNNEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. investigators in North Korea have discovered
that an underground site that Washington suspects could be used to
revive that nation's nuclear weapons program is a huge, empty
tunnel, the Clinton administration said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary report by an inspection team should ease recent
tensions between the United States and North Korea that had
threatened the collapse of a five-year-old agreement meant to
freeze North Korea's nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   The American inspections began last week under an agreement that
required modest commitments by the United States to continue food
aid to North Korea and to begin a pilot project to help it grow
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials cautioned that while the tunnel is now
empty, it could still be used someday to hide the equipment needed
to build nuclear weapons. And they also noted that material inside
the tunnel could have been moved out in recent weeks in
anticipation of the American inspection, although the movement of
any major piece of equipment would probably have been detected by
American spy satellites.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said initial reports from the
inspection team suggested that, apart from digging a huge hole in
the ground, the North Koreans had made no obvious preparations for
construction of a nuclear reactor in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday outlining the work of the investigators,
James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said the American
team began the inspection last Thursday and ended its work on
Monday, earlier then expected. He said the team credited North
Korea's ``cooperation for its unhampered access and the rapid
completion of the work plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The team found an unfinished site, the underground portion of
which was an extensive, empty tunnel complex,'' he said. ``A
careful technical analysis of the team's work will now take place
before further judgments can be made and reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement reached with North Korea in March, the United
States will be allowed repeated and regular visits to the remote
mountainous site at Kumchangri, about 25 miles northwest of
Yongbyon, a nuclear research center that has been under inspection
by the International Atomic Energy Agency for five years. The next
American inspection is scheduled for May of next year.
</P>
<P>
   A separate White House delegation led by former Defense
Secretary William Perry continued its visit to North Korea on
Thursday, with no clear indication that he would be permitted to
meet the nation's shadowy leader, Kim Jong Il, to offer an American
proposal to lift economic sanctions in exchange for North Korea's
agreement to scrap its long-range missile program.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Perry, the first presidential envoy ever sent to
North Korea, presented government officials there with a letter
from President Clinton for Kim outlining the American proposal.
Reports from the official North Korea news agency said Perry toured
Pyongyang today and visited a collective farm, where he watched
farmers transplant rice seedlings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   North Korea has repeatedly denied that the underground site at
Kumchangri is intended for nuclear research or production, although
the government has acknowledged that it was designed for ``a
sensitive military purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Some type of construction at the site was easily detected by
American satellites. Thousands of North Korean military workers
were seen excavating a huge area under a mountain. The shape of the
excavation led experts to conclude that the North's intention was
to recreate the installations at Yongbyon, which are under
intensive inspection by the Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The underground site had alarmed the administration and had
threatened to undermine the 1994 agreement that was supposed to end
North Korea's efforts to build a nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the so-called Agreed Framework, the North Koreans were
promised billions of dollars in energy assistance, including two
new nuclear reactors, in return for a promise by North Korea to
shut down its nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's threat to break the agreement unless an
American team was allowed to inspect the underground site led to
warnings from the North Koreans last year that the situation was
moving ``to the brink of war.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopes that the accord allowing inspections of
the site will quiet a rising movement in Congress to cut off
fuel-oil shipments to the North, a key provision of the 1994 pact.
The Pentagon feared that a fuel cutoff would lead North Korea to
resume production of plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans had initially demanded a payment of $300
million from the United States for the right to a one-time
inspection of the tunnel. But they dropped the demand after the
United States offered new promises of food aid, which the State
Department insists is for relief purposes unrelated to the nuclear
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
