<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG CONTENT AS WHITE'S `CADDIE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The list included Jose Vizcaino, Mark Grudzielanek,
Devon White, Adrian Beltre, Todd Hollandsworth and Todd Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   On the plane flight from Los Angeles to Cincinnati, Dodgers
leadoff hitter Eric Young thought it may be time for him to take a
shot at it.
</P>
<P>
   It's the No. 2 spot in the Dodgers lineup, and Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson spent the spring and the first two months of the
season trying to find a capable, consistent hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who wasn't warm to Johnson's idea of hitting second in
the spring, saw the offense struggling and reconsidered. Devon
White leads off in the new order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize Devo has led off before and he's been on a
championship team as a leadoff hitter,'' Young said. ``I don't have
an ego. If Devo can lead us to a championship, I'll be his
caddie.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two games Young has batted second, the Dodgers haven't
mis-clubbed. They've won both and Young is 3 for 8 with three runs
scored and four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Young can do what the Dodgers' other No. 2 hitters haven't done.
He can hit behind a runner, take pitches, hit the ball to the
opposite field and bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the bat control to do it,'' Young said. ``I
feel pretty confident batting second. If we get hot, don't even
think about moving me back to the leadoff spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth batted first in the Dodgers' 4-3 win against
Cincinnati on Thursday, until an injury forced him out of the game.
But the ideal situation has center fielder Devon White leading off
with Young, who has good bat control, second.
</P>
<P>
   The White-Young sequence worked well in Wednesday's game. White
doubled to lead off the game, Young singled to right to score White
and went to second on the throw home. Young stole third and scored
when Reds third baseman Mark Lewis was late covering third and the
throw went down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson called the feel of it ``100 percent championship
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got chills. What took me so long?'' Johnson said. ``There's
two ways of looking at it. You take a guy (White) that can hit a
double, it's the best way to lead off. If you're bunting and the
leadoff guy is an RBI guy, it offsets his on-base percentage. Those
two guys in the one and two spots is the best scenario we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth hurt: Hollandsworth left the game in the bottom of
the fifth inning with a rib cage strain. He suffered the injury
swinging at a pitch but continued his at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   However, after scoring from first on a double by Young,
Hollandsworth reached for his lower back on the right side. ``It
hurt to breathe,'' Hollandsworth said. ``Something popped.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hollandsworth is expected to miss three to five
days, but added the team would know more this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon returns: Dodgers reliever Pedro Borbon spent the 1995 and
1996 seasons pitching for the Atlanta Braves in Fulton County
Stadium, and each day he would see Turner Field and anticipate
pitching there.
</P>
<P>
   But Borbon hurt his arm late in the '96 season and spent the
next two years rehabilitating it after surgery. Though it's
unlikely he'll pitch today for the Dodgers given he's thrown the
past two days, Borbon figures to get to the mound at some point
during the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I think about is I never did step on the mound in a
real game there,'' Borbon said. ``I saw it being constructed but
never got a chance to be on the mound. I saw it being built from
scratch and it looked like a nice place.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: Dodgers team psychiatrist Herndon Harding arrived
in the Dodgers clubhouse before the game and spoke with several
players. . . . Also before the game, Johnson talked briefly with
his former employer, Reds owner Marge Schott, in the Dodgers
dugout. . . . Cincinnati reliever Scott Williamson struck out all
six Dodgers he faced. Williamson has struck out the last seven
batters he's faced and nine of the past 10. The other batter
reached base on a walk. ``I might be able to find a spot for him,''
Johnson said. . . . Reds pinch-hitter Hal Morris was ejected after
striking out in the eighth and arguing with home-plate umpire C.B.
Bucknor.
</P>
</TEXT>
