<HEADER>
A3977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-DISCRIMINATION-C     05-27 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DISCRIMINATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs protest memo by Coke chief
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _A federal judge in Atlanta should order Coca-Cola to
notify all of its U.S. employees that the company cannot retaliate
against them for participating in a recently filed racial
discrimination suit, plaintiffs' attorneys said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys filed a motion seeking this order in the wake of a
Wednesday e-mail memo from Chairman and Chief Executive M. Douglas
Ivester. He told employees the company valued diversity and had
``no room'' and ``no tolerance'' for discrimination against any
worker.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story must decide whether Ivester's
message _ which focused on diversity without specifically
mentioning the lawsuit _ is an ``end run'' around a court order
regulating communications in the case, which is what the plaintiffs
allege.
</P>
<P>
   Story has told Coca-Cola to put a disclaimer on its e-mails when
sharing its views about the case with employees. The disclaimer
should say: ``The foregoing represents Coca-Cola's opinion of this
lawsuit. It is unlawful for Coca-Cola to retaliate against
employees who choose to participate in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola did not add this disclaimer to its memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't put a disclaimer on Wednesday's e-mail communication
because it was not about the lawsuit,'' said company spokesman
Robert Baskin. Instead, he said, it was about diversity at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaintiffs want Story to order Coca-Cola to send out a
corrective notice to all 10,000 U.S. employees. The notice would
express the principles outlined in the disclaimer and tell
employees that they are free to contact the plaintiffs' attorneys
to hear their side of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ivester's practice of sending messages to Coca-Cola
employees ... without any indication that an opposing viewpoint
exists or that employees are free to explore and to hold that
viewpoint, is coercive, improper and violative of the court's
order,'' the plaintiffs' attorney said in their motion.
</P>
<P>
   The four black plaintiffs, who allege discrimination in pay,
promotion, performance evaluations and terminations, seek
class-action status for their case. If successful, that could add
as many as 1,500 other black salaried employees as plaintiffs. It
is those prospective plaintiffs whom the attorneys said they are
trying to protect from coercion.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' attorneys also are asking the judge to ``caution
Ivester'' on his plans to hold small meetings about diversity with
employees ``in light of the extreme danger of coercion and
intimidation presented by such personal meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   They want Ivester to abide by a second ruling that the company
can only hold direct discussions about the lawsuit with black
salaried employees if they are managers with information the
company needs to prepare its defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Baskin, the Coca-Cola spokesman, insisted Ivester ``does not
intend to discuss the lawsuit at these meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
