<HEADLINE>
WITH AN SUV, THE KEY IS RESPONSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (l and f coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of testing autos, what a difference a day makes, to
coin a phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Climb down from the sprawling cab of the rumbling Ford F-250
Supercab pickup truck and wiggle straight into the tight cockpit of
the 2000 Audi TT, a whistling little sports coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a change in perspective. You go from looking down
onto and into virtually every passenger vehicle encountered to
looking up at all of them. The first time the Audi pulls up beside
a Ford truck, what you see is the truck's tires, right there at
window level.
</P>
<P>
   It is a contrapuntal clash in the world of motorized steel. You
go from driving with an awareness of what the big truck you had
been driving might to do smaller vehicles to driving fully aware of
what some other large vehicle might do to yours _ and to you.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings up thoughts of the distaste _ or, in some cases,
shrill hatred _ with which many folks these days look at sport
utility vehicles. (A digression here to fine-tune our nomenclature:
Despite whatever manufacturers tell us, if an auto does not have
low-range four-wheel-drive _ as opposed to simple all-wheel drive _
and if it does not have hefty ground clearance, and if it does not
also have a certain bulk, it is not an SUV. In other words, Subaru
Forester owners, breathe easy for this debate.)
</P>
<P>
   The Ford F-250 Supercab that was just parked fits into this
debate because it is from this F-Series' platform that Ford will
build the biggest of all SUVs: The 2000 Ford Excursion. And because
it will be 226.7 inches long, weigh nearly four tons (2,000 pounds
more than the Chevrolet Suburban) and, in V-10 form, get around 10
miles per gallon, it is being dubbed the Ford Valdez by those who
are appalled by its creation and threat to the earth.
</P>
<P>
   So the Excursion will soon be walking straight into the
minefield of debate over the moral propriety of owning an SUV. And
for many folks, myself included, it truly is a moral debate because
it raises questions about safety (at least for those in smaller
vehicles) and environmental issues because of exhaust emissions and
fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any motorized vehicle or craft we drive, moral
issues can be answered with a simple word: responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long after I'd pulled away from the light at which
I'd sat in the Audi beside that big Ford truck that I encountered a
vehicle that frightened me far more: It was a mid-'80s Oldsmobile,
coming up on me fast, right up to my bumper, it seemed, before it
careened out to pass me, swaying on spongy suspension, hurtling on
what I was sure were bad tires, spewing black smoke from an engine
on its last legs.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure a big pickup truck doing the same thing would have been
just as unnerving, though its engine would have been running
cleaner and its suspension would have been more agile, but in both
cases, it would have been the driver, not the vehicle, putting me
at risk. And that is where responsibility comes in.
</P>
<P>
   If you drive a big SUV, you have to drive it with an awareness
of just how big you are out there; how your headlights look in
someone's rear-view mirror; how your tires look to someone seated
in a low-slung car; how imposing your gleaming bumper can look.
Don't race up on people at high speed. Don't let the inevitable
feeling of invincibility that comes with driving an SUV turn you
into a bully.
</P>
<P>
   SUVs have their place on our roads, but it is fair to ask which
roads and what we use these big rigs for.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in the city and own a big SUV, you're out of bounds
unless you keep it parked in private space and use it only for
family-filled trips into the country. It is not a city car because
it is at its most inefficient, space-hogging, and polluting worst
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In an insightful letter to the editor in this paper last week, a
gentleman discussed how much more efficient it is to haul an SUV
filled with as many as nine people on an outing, as opposed to two
or three smaller cars splitting the same load.
</P>
<P>
   An SUV filled with skiers or young soccer players is a good
thing. An SUV being driven by one person out to fetch milk or
papers or commute to work is a bad thing. That is simple.
</P>
<P>
   Do they pollute more than small cars? Certainly, because their
engines are bigger. But the government is continually tightening
emissions limits and there is no reason even the largest SUVs can't
be reined in as time passes. Already, many of them are far below
government emissions standards and as the line continues to blur
between car and truck and SUV, those numbers will naturally go down
even further. I just had a quick spin in the new Toyota Tundra
pickup truck, a V-8 powered four-door that is the first foreign
challenge to America's big trucks, and while it has the power of
the big rigs, it runs as clean and quiet as most cars.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, we should be environmentally conscious about what and
how we drive, and compared to where we were 10 and 20 years ago we
are far along that road.
</P>
<P>
   But it is humorous, sometimes, to read letters to the editor
from those who feel morally superior because they hate SUVs so
much; those who write in to say they are saving the earth because
they drive little Hondas or Subarus to and from their homes in the
suburbs around Boston. I always wonder how many of them go home
each night to a sprawling, restored Victorian or other house that
is arguably far larger than what their family requires, but is
instead what they want, and whose multiple rooms they gladly heat
all winter from a dwindling global fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
   We live in an age when things are big. A big economy, big
houses, big cars and trucks. What is truly fascinating is that we
have had this expansion of jobs and homes and transportation and
still, somehow, managed to do it all even as we steadily have
cleaned our environment.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't had to ban big trucks any more than we have had to
ban big homes or big industry. Instead, we have set standards of
performance for all these things _ from insulation in our homes to
fuel standards for our vehicles to pollution from our factories _
and, though it may seem too gradual a process for some (or not
Draconian enough for others) it is working.
</P>
<P>
   But that is just the framework that's been laid out for us.
Within that framework, we can all live in as big a house as we can
afford and drive as big a truck as we want, but any one of us who
fails to approach these opportunities with responsibility is simply
a jerk. Heat that 12-room Victorian that is home to a family of
four to 72 degrees through the winter and you make the list.
</P>
<P>
   Drive a near-empty, gas-guzzling SUV around town for small
errands or to and from work and you make the list. Use it to
tailgate or intimidate smaller vehicles, you go to the top of the
list.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that responsibility, common sense, and courtesy are
often lacking on our highways, but when they are present there is
plenty of room out there on the road for all our automotive tastes
and the wonderful and ever-evolving array of the vehicles we get to
drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
