<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT     05-27 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS UP THE ANTE ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mo., Ga., N.Y.)  (Eds: See also COLO-SCHOOL-SUIT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic advocates of gun control urged the House
Thursday to adopt even more stringent restrictions on firearms than
the Senate did, upping the ante for Republicans as the political
gamesmanship over the issue intensified.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Capitol Hill that represented a belated
victory lap for his tie-breaking vote on a gun-control amendment in
the Senate, Vice President Al Gore said the Senate's package of
regulations had not gone far enough. Gore was not specific about
what additional proposals he favored.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that ``for all the praise that's been heaped on the
Senate action,'' the Senate stopped short. ``What should be done
here in the House is a tougher bill, with tougher restrictions
related to guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a hearing of the House Judiciary Committee's
subcommittee on crime, House Democrats and representatives of the
Clinton administration called on the House to pass elements of
President Clinton's proposed gun-control package, like an
individual limit of one handgun purchase a month, that the Senate
did not even consider.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused Democrats of meaningless grandstanding,
saying there was no proof that the Democratic proposals would do
any good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a dereliction of our duty as lawmakers to prefer sound
bites more than substance,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who
chairs the crime subcommittee. McCollum and other Republicans also
excoriated the administration for what they said was a failure to
enforce existing federal firearms regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of nerve,'' McCollum said, ``to bang your fist
and demand tougher juvenile gun laws while doing almost nothing to
enforce the ones that already exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the hearing, which was the first formal debate on gun
control in the House this year, and Gore's news conference showed
that despite emerging bipartisan consensus on many aspects of the
Senate gun-control package, there was still a hearty appetite among
Republicans and Democrats for sniping at each other.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle lines were neither neat nor clean. Just minutes
after Gore vaguely called for a more ambitious legislative push in
the House, Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the minority leader, said he
would be pleased if the House simply passed the same gun-control
measures the Senate had.
</P>
<P>
   That humbler goal suggested that some Democrats remained
cautious about pushing too hard, in large part because of the
belief that advocacy for gun control helped cost them their
majority in Congress in 1994 by drawing the ire and attack
advertisements of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's news conference Thursday was so painstakingly
choreographed that a gaggle of Democratic aides spent about 10
minutes beforehand debating the precise arrangement of the five
American flags that would provide the backdrop for Gore's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore claimed that the refusal of Republican leaders in the House
to satisfy a demand by Democrats for votes on gun control this week
raised concerns that some Republicans were in thrall to the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be under any illusions to what's going on
here,'' Gore said. ``At this very moment there are some on the
other side meeting behind closed doors, plotting to have more
delays in order to preserve loopholes.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they had already expedited the schedule
by promising gun-control votes in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle for those proposals is a juvenile crime bill written
primarily by McCollum. McCollum announced early this week that the
bill would include versions of all the gun-control measures passed
by the Senate, a sign of significant movement by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats at the hearing Thursday appealed for even
more. They variously advocated criminal penalties for parents whose
guns end up causing violence in children's hands; a legal limit of
one handgun purchase a month, and a raise in the legal minimum age
for all handgun purchases to 21 from 18, a measure that the House
speaker, J. Dennis Hastert, has advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, said that the federal response to concerns
about school violence should not focus too exclusively on gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conservative Republicans on the subcommittee,
Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, pointed to a copy of the 10 Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said that if schools were allowed to display these
principles on their walls, ``We would not have had the tragedies
that bring us here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also grilled Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder Jr.
and James Johnson, an official with the Treasury Department, about
statistics that showed minimal enforcement of some existing federal
gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The administration officials conceded that of the thousands of
convicted criminals who tried illegally to buy guns over the last
year and were caught by background checks, only a handful were
federally prosecuted. But they noted increases in prosecutions
under the Clinton administration of other federal firearms
violations.
</P>
<P>
   After a few hours of rival finger-pointing, Rep. Carolyn
McCarthy, D-N.Y., addressed other lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm asking is that when you make your judgments and your
fights, you not be so partisan,'' said Ms. McCarthy, whose husband
was killed by gunfire. ``Remember the victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
