<HEADLINE>
NBA STILL GETTING RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world of TV sports according to me:
</P>
<P>
   WAITING TO EXHALE: NBC has been one lucky peacock when it comes
to its 1999 NBA ratings. The Nielsens to date have been much
stronger than anyone anticipated considering the lockout, short
season and absence of Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   NBC last weekend again showed gains over 1998. Saturday's
doubleheader averaged a 5.9 Nielsen, up 18 percent over the same
weekend in 1998, while Sunday's tripleheader posted a 7.0, up a
tenth (6.9). Sunday's numbers came despite two games closing out
sweeps and another that put a team ahead 3-0. (One ratings point is
worth 944,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   NBC's numbers are actually improving, comparison-wise, from the
overnights, which target only the top 35 markets. This indicates a
wider appeal for the product in mid-sized markets, like
Indianapolis, Portland and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   NBC can only hope this trend stays warm, because the comparisons
will now face their toughest test. NBC has lost its darling, the
Lakers, who were seen more nationally than any other team, but who
also produced NBC's biggest ratings. Maybe fans tuned in the Lakers
hoping they'd lose. Whatever the case, NBC has shown its last
sideline shot of Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nielsens now go head-to-head with '98 games that
featured Michael Jordan and a Utah-Lakers Western Conference final.
If Portland eliminates the Jazz, NBC will be left with one major
market team, the Knicks, and three outsiders. The network's
best-case scenario would be a New York-Utah series featuring one
major market team and another that is familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The viewer's best-case scenario, of course, would feature Ahmad
Rashad being assigned to cricket and Bob Costas being returned to
the pastoral setting of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Costas and Doug Collins, NBC's No. 1 team, have definitely found
a rhythm, a year after the Isiah Thomas experiment flopped and
Costas found rust on his basketball chops. Collins has proven
himself to be a much better sportscaster than coach, and that's not
a knock.
</P>
<P>
   But now Costas is talking too much. The rhythm of baseball that
allows for anecdotes and long story lines doesn't exist in
basketball. Costas is cramming telecasts with too many asides and
witticisms. Basketball is an analysts game. Costas could take a cue
from colleague Tom Hammond, who works a clean game and leaves the
repartee to Bill Walton and Steve Jones.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help Costas at all, either, that he's forced to give
a network plug every 90 seconds. Costas pumped NBC's Noah's Ark
movie so often I swore I saw Shaquille O'Neal and Rebecca Lobo
board the boat in twos.
</P>
<P>
   CALL MISSING PERSONS: You knew Disney chief Michael Eisner was
enamored of ESPN, because he gushed over it when his company
purchased it and ABC from Capital Cities. But you never figured he
would let ABC's sports division go to seed as he has.
</P>
<P>
   When Disney negotiated a new NFL contract, it's priority was
getting the entire Sunday night package for ESPN. Since then, Dan
Dierdorf's Monday Night Football's contract was allowed to lapse
and the powers that be have vacillated on whether it will replace
him. This happens to come in a year, too, that marks MNF's 30th
anniversary and a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   When Disney was faced with negotiations for the NHL, it overpaid
to keep the cable package in ESPN's hands. ABC Sports will air only
four regular season NHL games, or seven less than Fox has been
televising the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ABC just signed a multiyear deal worth $12 million a year for
the Indy 500 and a series of Indy Racing League events, again
ostensibly to keep the IRL events away from Fox Sports Nets. ABC
agreed to air a handful of the IRL events on ABC even though they
have no Nielsen track record.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also apparently has no intention of replacing the retired
Keith Jackson on ABC college football telecasts. It apparently
won't even designate a No. 1 broadcast team. Brent Musburger and
Brad Nessler will split most of the big games.
</P>
<P>
   As of yet, Bob Griese hasn't been reassigned to any particular
partner, and ABC this week lost studio analyst Todd Blackledge to
CBS, where he will replace Terry Donahue as CBS' No. 1 colorman.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, ABC will be pressed to keep the horse racing Triple Crown
away from NBC and Fox; it just bought a vain paid-for-TV golf match
between Tiger Woods and David Duval; and Disney's snit with
baseball over the ESPN/MNF issue could lead to ESPN eventually
being shut out of baseball altogether.
</P>
<P>
   I'd love to know what Howard Cosell would have to say about
this.
</P>
<P>
   CHORTLES: ESPN's effort to rank the 100 greatest athletes of the
century has been sincere, but it's taking a lot of hits from
baseball fans agog that Mickey Mantle ranked 37th and that a horse,
Secretariat, was ranked 35th. Secretariat was a hell of an athlete,
but you leave yourself open to a lot of snorts by putting him on a
list with bipeds. ...
</P>
<P>
   Critics who panned Keith Olbermann's Fox Sports News exclusive
report that Michael Jordan was negotiating to buy into the
Charlotte Hornets should send their apologies in care of the FSN
anchor desk. He was correct, right down to saying the purchase
price for MJ was the potential linchpin to the deal. ...
</P>
<P>
   L.A. radio legend Bud Furillo is back on the air at KXPS (1270
am) in Palm Springs. KXTA officials aren't likely to take my
suggestion, but I'll make it anyway: Furillo would be a superb
addition to the show, considering his long history in Los Angeles
as a newspaper sports editor and talk show host and his ties to the
Dodgers from his KABC days. They may be separated by generations,
but Furillo's natural bite and attitude is much closer to the
spirit of Jim Rome's show than anything or anyone else KXTA airs.
...
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: NBC's Memorial Day schedule (all games 5 p.m.
ET): Saturday, Portland-Utah Game 7 or San Antonio-Portland Game 1;
Sunday, New York-Indiana; Monday, San Antonio-Portland or Utah.
Costas and Collins will work the Western Conference series,
Hammond, Walton and Jones the Knicks-Pacers series ... NBA Nielsens
on TNT and TBS are off seven percent, and it deserves to be noted
that Turner's two networks have been beaten by more than a 2-1
margin by wrestling ... Fox was miffed that it couldn't air a
Colorado-Dallas NHL playoff game last Sunday because of a
scheduling conflict with another event in Denver. Instead, it was
forced to air Buffalo-Toronto, a game destined to producer low
ratings with Toronto across the border ... NBC begins French Open
coverage with three hour shows Saturday and Sunday (11 a.m. each
day) ... Track and field live? No, really. CBS carries the
Prefontaine Classic Sunday at 10 a.m. Sprinters Michael Johnson and
Marion Jones are headliners ... ABC's Indy coverage Sunday begins
at 8 a.m. This will mark the first time in 11 years that Paul Page
won't do the play-by-play. He left ABC to work CART events as a
result of the snit between drivers and Indy 500 chief Tony George.
Bob Jenkins replaces Page ... If you happen to see the new film
``Trippin','' you will find veteran L.A. radio voice Scott St.
James cast in the role of the President. Supply your own intern
joke here ... The latest sign of ESPN's runaway ego: A recent
episode of ESPN's ``Up Close featured ESPN's Chris Berman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
