<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-RENO-HNS &LR;      05-27 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RENO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MEMBERS URGE OUSTER OF BERGER IN WAKE OF CHINESE SPYING
SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With criticism mounting over the Clinton
administration's handling of the Chinese espionage scandal,
Attorney General Janet Reno ruled out resigning Thursday and blamed
subordinates for failing to consult her on a key decision in the
investigation of spying.
</P>
<P>
   As Reno offered an unusually detailed explanation of how the
Justice Department handled allegations of spying at Los Alamos
National Laboratory, more than 80 House members sent a letter to
the president calling for National Security Adviser Sandy Berger to
resign for being slow to react.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Senate adopted the first in what is expected to
be a several measures to counter Chinese espionage and tighten
security for U.S. nuclear secrets. The House, mired in partisan
bickering, postponed consideration of its own bill to better
safeguard the nation's strategic technology and left on a 10-day
Memorial Day recess.
</P>
<P>
   The action, or lack of it on the part of the House, came days
after a congressional report outlining lax controls over defense
secrets and accusing China of systematically stealing nuclear
weapons information from the United States over the past 20 years.
The Chinese government denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Urged by aides to mount a defense against calls for her
resignation from Sens. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., and Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., Reno faulted subordinates at the Justice
Department and FBI for not consulting her two years ago when they
disagreed over whether to wiretap a Taiwanese-born scientist
suspected of spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   During her weekly press conference, Reno explained that when the
FBI first asked Justice Department attorneys to ask a federal court
for permission to put the Los Alamos scientist, Wen Ho Lee, under
surveillance, the warrant application was turned down by her Office
of Intelligence Policy and Review. The FBI, working with Justice
officials, redrafted the application twice, adding information to
each draft.
</P>
<P>
   It was still rejected, each time for failing to satisfy
requirements in the Constitution and in the Foreign Intelligence
Surveillance Act of 1978. ``Based on the facts reported to us in
1997, the department determined that the evidence was insufficient
to support a finding of probable cause'' to believe Lee engaged in
clandestine intelligence-gathering on behalf of a foreign power,
Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, through his attorney, has denied engaging in espionage.
Fired from his Los Alamos post in New Mexico earlier this spring,
Lee has not been charged in any crimes but remains under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said then-Assistant FBI Director John Lewis complained in
August 1997 that his agency was having trouble getting the Office
of Intelligence Policy and Review at Justice to seek court approval
for putting Lee under surveillance, and she asked the agency's
Executive Office for National Security to review it. ``I was not
briefed on the details,'' Reno told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The application was reviewed by assistant attorney general
Daniel Seikaly, who agreed the application failed to establish
probable cause and informed the FBI no wiretap authorization would
be sought from the court. Reno said Seikaly never took up the issue
with her or with Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI did not come back'' to her, Reno said. ``I assumed
that since I did not hear again from the FBI that it was resolved
to their satisfaction.'' Since she has come under fire from members
of Congress, Reno said she has stressed to aides that ``where there
is something serious, where (FBI) Director (Louis) Freeh disagrees
with the findings (at the Justice Department), I think that it
should be discussed at my level.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Reno said looking back now at the evidence
available in 1997, the decision to reject the wiretap application
was correct.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also said she has not even contemplated
resigning, as insisted by Shelby and Torricelli. Reno said she has
talked to White House Counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and ``he assures me
of the White House's confidence'' in her performance.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, congressional criticism seemed to shift to Berger
as 80 members of Congress sent a letter to Clinton demanding that
he dump Berger, blaming him for failing to keep the president
advised of the security breach at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Berger has failed in his responsibility as this nation's
national security adviser by not properly informing you of the most
serious espionage ever committed against the United States,'' the
lawmakers said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., also expressed
misgivings about Berger's performance but stopped short of calling
for his dismissal. ``There has got to be some concern about what
Mr. Berger knew and how he acted and what did he say to the
president and when and why did they do some of the things they
did,'' Lott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the PBS program ``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer,''
Berger said he has no intention of resigning. ``I believe that
personally and within the White House, we acted appropriately when
this information was brought to our attention,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Although notified in April 1996 of suspicions that Beijing had
conducted massive espionage operations at U.S. nuclear
laboratories, Berger acknowledged that he did not discuss the
matter with Clinton until July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president retained
confidence in Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for the weekend, the Senate adopted on a voice
vote a series of proposals by Lott to improve security
investigations of nuclear laboratory employees and to increase
counter-espionage training at the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced as amendments to a bill outlining $288 billion worth
of defense spending, the measures also would tighten security over
technology used to aid in the overseas launch of U.S. commercial
satellites. One proposal would require increased monitoring by the
Pentagon and beef up the role of U.S. intelligence agencies in
overseeing the launches.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one of Lott's proposals would require the president
to notify Congress whenever an investigation is undertaken of a
possible violation of export control laws in connection with a
commercial satellite launch.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Senate Democrats managed to stall consideration of
Republican-sponsored legislation that would reorganize the Energy
Department. The proposal, which is opposed by the White House,
would create a new assistant energy secretary for defense programs
who would report directly to the president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, debate was postponed on a dozen proposed
amendments to a similar defense authorization bill when the
Republican leadership lost support adopting a rule governing how
the debate was to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans bolted because the rule would have
prohibited amending the legislation to include a funding cutoff for
U.S. involvement in NATO's Kosovo campaign. Democrats were rankled
because the rule would not allowed consideration of amendments
supported by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
