</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discovery rockets to the sky
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL _ Boosted by a ray of light as bright as the sun
rising alongside it, space shuttle Discovery rocketed into the sky
Thursday, headed for its first rendezvous with the infant
International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the bone-rattling roar of the shuttle's revved up
engines as it lifted off, one might have heard NASA officials
breathing sighs of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's 6:49 a.m. launch was the first this year, ending one
the longest droughts in the shuttle program's 18-year history _ the
longest gap between shuttle launches since the deadly Challenger
explosion in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The unmanned program has suffered tough times, too, with a
string of six launch failures worth more than $3 billion since
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy we're launching again,'' launch director
Ralph Roe said. ``It had been a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This trip almost didn't get off the ground, either. The launch
was delayed a week after a hailstorm punched 648 dents into the
foam insulation protecting the external fuel tank. Dotted with
patches, it dropped away, as scheduled, eight minutes after
liftoff. The 10-day mission is the second of 36 shuttle trips
planned to construct and stock the space station. The spacecraft _
with its crew of five Americans, a Russian and the first Canadian
to ride a shuttle _ is kind of an interstellar U-Haul, carrying
nearly 2 tons of supplies, including clothing, blankets, computers,
printers, drinking water and more to be used once the station is
inhabited.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's astronauts also will install two construction cranes
during a six-and-a-half hour spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The station, already bright enough to be seen in the pre-dawn
sky, is the mating of two modules _ a Russian control center and an
American connecting hub. The next piece of the $50 billion puzzle
was supposed to be the first Russian-built living quarters. But a
year of construction delays -- the primary reason for the gap in
shuttle launches -- forced the Americans to head into space anyway
and use a makeshift dock to link up with the station in order to
get things moving.
</P>
<P>
   The target date for the living quarters is now November and
another delay would throw off NASA's scheduling again. The first
crew is expected to move in early next year. ``Many of our flight
manifests are linked to the sequential assembly of the space
station,'' said Don McMonagle, manager of launch integration for
the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's crew will dock on Saturday and stay for six days.
The mission isn't just about building. There's already repair work
to be done on the fledgling station, which celebrated its six-month
anniversary on Thursday. The crew will try to fix a communications
problem and a battery problem.
</P>
<P>
   Also onboard: the STARSHINE project, a messy acronym for a
beach-ball-sized satellite covered with tiny mirrors _ 878 in all.
It looks like a disco ball and will be shot into orbit from
Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The mirrors were hand-polished by students all over the world.
Thousands of students are expected to follow the progress of the
satellite and use it to gauge the changes in the density of Earth's
atmosphere. As sunlight bounces off the mirrors, it will glitter in
the sky and will be visible for six months until it burns up in the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Students from St. Michael's Independent School in Stuart were
among those who donated a little elbow grease.
</P>
<P>
   One of the crew's first jobs Thursday was to get some sleep. In
order to be prepared for the space station work, bedtime was set at
just before noon _ not necessarily too early considering their day
started around 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The next shuttle launch is scheduled for July 22. It will be
commanded by Eileen M. Collins, the first woman to command a
shuttle. Three more launches are planned for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is scheduled to return to Kennedy Space Center at 2:43
a.m. on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   See video and get updates on Discovery's mission at Palm Beach
Interactive: www.GoPBI.com/news
</P>
<P>
   Desmon writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
