<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERMO-ANNUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATSOPOULOS GIVEN WARM SENDOFF BY HOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Thermo Electron Corp. shareholders, who have
seen a dramatic drop in the company's stock price in the past year,
nonetheless gave departing chief executive George N. Hatsopoulos a
standing ovation Thursday and welcomed his replacement, Richard F.
Syron, at its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Hatsopoulos, a Greek immigrant who co-founded the firm 43 years
ago and operated it for most of that time with his brother, John,
has come under attack of late for the company's unwieldy structure.
Thermo Electron, which manufactures industrial and laboratory
instruments, is the majority owner of 23 publicly traded firms it
has spun out over the years, with products ranging from airport
security devices to recycling technology.
</P>
<P>
   As shares of the the company's stock tumbled from a high of
nearly 42 1/2 just 13 1/2 months ago to less than 13 last month,
some stockholders revolted. Franklin Mutual Advisers Inc., which
owns 3.4 million shares, or about 2 percent of the company, has
been openly critical of Hatsopoulos and the company's structure. At
Thursday's shareholder session, Franklin senior vice president
David Marcus praised Thermo for taking steps to streamline the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, Thermo Electron has to be more responsive to
business trends and shareholders and ``not be a rest home for
friends and employees'' _ a statement that drew a hush followed by
some hissing from the packed crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Syron and Theo Melas-Kyriazi, Thermo Electron's chief financial
officer, outlined the company's plan to generate $200 million in
cash from the sale of a dozen smaller businesses by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The streamlining, Melas-Kyriazi said, includes a goal of
achieving a 20 percent return on invested capital from all its
operatons by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Syron stressed that Thermo Electron will stick with its core
values of backing individual ideas that can become commercial
successes and increase shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's strong technology and sound management resources
were the reasons I took the job,'' said Syron, the former chief
executive of the American Stock Exchange who will officially
succeed Hatsopoulos on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hatsopoulos acknowledged that the restructuring was personally
painful for him, saying that selling 12 businesses and executing
the mandate to restructure the company all in a year is ``a
horrendous job.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's recent poor performance, the standing-room
only crowd of generally older stockholders and Wall Street analysts
gave Hatsopoulos, who will remain chairman of the company, a warm
sendoff. At one point, a shareholder proposal that only members of
the Hatsopoulos family hold the top post came up for a vote. The
company opposed it and it was resoundingly voted down, prompting
Hatsopoulos to remark, ``I think some members of my family can't
believe that I opposed that proposal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
