<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TABLOID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIP TABLOID APOLOGY LEAVES ROYALS COLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Sun on Thursday published a full-page apology for
having printed a picture of Prince Edward's fiancee, Sophie
Rhys-Jones, with a breast bared, but Buckingham Palace declined to
withdraw its official complaint against the tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the headline ``Sorry, Sophie,'' the newspaper's editorial
page said, ``We admit it: topless photo was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The editors protested the palace's characterization of The Sun's
action as ``premeditated cruelty'' and asserted that its purpose in
printing the ``saucy, but harmless'' photograph of Ms. Rhys-Jones,
34, a London press agent, had been to portray her as ``a fun-loving
woman who is bringing a breath of fresh air to the Royals.''
</P>
<P>
   If this line of argument was meant to clear the freshening royal
air, it did not work. Buckingham Palace officials took note of The
Sun's response but said they would pursue their protest with the
independent Press Complaints Commission. A hearing is planned for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that The Sun printed on Wednesday was a private
snapshot taken on a business trip to Spain in 1988 when Ms.
Rhys-Jones worked for a London radio station. A colleague, Kara
Noble, took the photograph after another colleague had taken a
playful tug at Ms. Rhys-Jones' bikini top.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Noble sold the photo to The Sun for an estimated $165,000,
less than reported on Wednesday. The Sun promised Thursday night to
donate profits from the photo to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Luke Chauveau, of the Press Complaints Commission, said that
even if it found against The Sun, the stiffest punishment it could
exact would be a written apology by the commission and The Sun's
editors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
