<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-NETANYAHU-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU RESIGNS FROM PARLIAMENT BUT HINTS AT COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a defiant parting speech after his defeat in the
Israeli election, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced his
resignation from Parliament on Thursday but hinted at a political
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course we charted together will triumph in the end, and we
will all witness this victory,'' Netanyahu said to cheering members
of the central committee of his Likud Party in Tel Aviv. ``With
God's help, we shall yet return.''
</P>
<P>
   As supporters shouting ``We love you!'' wept and threw kisses,
Netanyahu announced that he was giving up his Parliament seat. He
stepped down from leadership of the Likud Party last week, when he
conceded defeat to Ehud Barak, the leader of the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Barak resoundingly defeated Netanyahu in the May 17 election, 56
percent to 44 percent. Netanyahu remains in office as Barak forms a
new government, a process that could take several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This evening I'm announcing my decision to resign my
membership in Parliament,'' Netanyahu, 49, said over shouts of
``No!'' and ``Stay!'' from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that I'm leaving Parliament, but I am by no means
leaving the battle for the future of the country,'' he added. ``I
will continue to work in my own way to insure this future, and I'll
continue to serve the national idea as I have over the last 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu gave no indication of his immediate plans, but his
spokesman, David Bar-Illan, said this week that he would most
likely write a book and go on the lecture circuit in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's resignation from Parliament will free him of limits
set by Israeli law on earnings by lawmakers from lectures and
similar fees.
</P>
<P>
   Received on Thursday night by long minutes of ringing applause
by the party faithful _ who sang ``Long live, Bibi, King of
Israel'' _ Netanyahu delivered a stern political testament to his
successors in government, reiterating his tough line on negotiating
peace with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we lower the exaggerated expectations of the other
side and its ability to threaten us, the closer Israel will get to
permanent peace,'' Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell us the Arabs won't agree if they don't get
everything they want,'' he added. ``I say the Jews won't agree to
demands that they give what they can't. And they must not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now after the elections, Arab expectations are again on the
rise,'' Netanyahu warned. ``If Israel complies with their demands,
it will soon find itself dwarfed, shrunken, with its back to the
sea. Such a state will be a constant temptation to threats of
aggression and terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel might find that it enjoys much international
sympathy,'' Netanyahu continued. ``Its leaders will receive many
compliments, maybe even Nobel Prizes. But it will not have
permanent peace and security, because after a series of painful
withdrawals in the north, and after the establishment of an Arab
state in the heart of the country, the Arabs will come to us and
say just one short word: more.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu added, ``Whoever is unprepared to struggle in
negotiations, will find himself struggling on the battlefield.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as Netanyahu bowed out, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon
swiftly took control of Likud, winning a unanimous vote to become
temporary party head until a new leader is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging to rebuild the party, Sharon, 71, suggested that he
might run for the leadership of the party, a position that would
make him the Likud Party's candidate for prime minister in the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough to have a candidate, bright as he may be,''
Sharon said in an allusion to Netanyahu, who tended to ignore Likud
in his campaign. ``A candidate needs to have a strong political
movement with him, and we will rebuild it.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of the election was clear, Sharon said: ``A united
Likud will win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
