<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE EN ROUTE TO RENDEZVOUS WITH SPACE STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The space shuttle Discovery is headed for
a late-night Friday rendezvous with the international space
station, where seven astronauts from the United States, Canada and
Russia plan to spend six days setting up housekeeping for the first
permanent crew.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle lifted off its seaside launching pad at the Kennedy
Space Center at 6:49 a.m. ET Thursday to begin its pursuit of the
space station, which was flying parallel to the Carolinas'
coastline, northwest of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the failure of one of 44 shuttle steering jets,
considered a minor glitch, NASA officials said the shuttle's
nine-minute climb to orbit had been flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pristine vehicle,'' said Donald McMonagle, a launch
manager at the Kennedy center. This mission is the first flight of
a shuttle since December, when astronauts joined the first two
segments of the station that is to become a $60 billion outpost for
scientific experimentation by 16 nations.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's crew will prepare the station for the arrival of
its first living quarters, the much-delayed service module being
built by Russia and scheduled to be launched on a Russian rocket
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The five men and two women on the shuttle crew are delivering
more than two tons of clothing, drinking water, laptop computers,
maintenance tools and other supplies before the first permanent
crew takes up residence early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Discovery is scheduled to dock about 12:21 a.m. ET on
Saturday after a 17,500 mph rendezvous and circling of the station.
</P>
<P>
   Two astronauts, Tamara Jernigan and Daniel Barry, will spend
more than six hours in the vacuum of space installing an
American-built construction crane and the mount for another crane,
made in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the external items, the crew will move more than
3,000 pounds of supplies through a corridor leading from the
shuttle into the space station, which is to be completed in five
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
