<SLUG> BC-INFINITY-OUTDOOR-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: INFINITY IS SET TO ACQUIRE OUTDOOR SYSTEMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cry of ``To infinity and beyond!'' heard in the
film ``Toy Story'' is coming true for Infinity Broadcasting, at
least in the booming realm of advertising seen and heard outside
the home.
</P>
<P>
   Infinity, the radio and billboard giant controlled by CBS Corp.
in New York, agreed Thursday to significantly expand its presence
in out-of-home advertising by agreeing to acquire the No. 1 company
in that field, Outdoor Systems Inc. in Phoenix, for about $6.5
billion in stock. Terms of the deal also call for Infinity, led by
the charismatic deal-maker Mel Karmazin, to assume about $1.8
billion in Outdoor Systems debt.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching beyond the front door is a rapidly growing industry
because the proliferation of choices among in-home media like
television and magazines is making it more difficult for
advertisers to reach consumers, particularly desirable demographic
groups like busy, two-income couples. That is why there are ads on
telephone kiosks, wrapped around buses, on postcards in restaurants
and even on the floors of supermarkets and drug stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe, and we've said this a lot, that reaching
the consumer when he or she is closest to the purchase is very
desirable,'' Karmazin, chief executive of Infinity and CBS, said in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Infinity had already been the nation's fourth largest outdoor
advertising company through its ownership of TDI, which specializes
in selling ad posters displayed by subway, bus and commuter rail
systems. Now Infinity will add the 237,000 billboards, New York
City subway displays, posters, mall kiosks and other properties
owned by Outdoor Systems to form a powerful company concentrated in
the major metropolitan areas of North America that are the focus of
most advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Infinity will own radio stations and ad signs in 20 of the 30
largest American markets and 33 of the 50 largest; Outdoor Systems
also operates in 47 big Canadian and Mexican cities and TDI also
sells signs in Britain and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with other Infinity and CBS media properties _ the CBS
television network, the CBS-owned television stations, cable
networks like Country Music Television, TV shows like ``Jeopardy''
syndicated by King World Productions and Web sites like CBS
Sportsline _ the cross-media advertising and promotional
opportunities seem, well, infinite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is a plus, a big plus,'' said Alan Gottesman, who
follows the advertising and media industries as managing director
of West End Communications/Consulting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more points of contact you have with a client,'' he added,
referring to the advertisers that buy commercial time and ad space
from media companies, ``the more you understand where a client's
business is going.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was signed Thursday morning after what Karmazin
called ``five intense days of negotiations'' that ended a year and
a half of on-and-off talks between Infinity and Outdoor Systems.
The deal, endorsed by the boards of both companies, requires
approval from shareholders and federal regulators; it is expected
to close in the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is emblematic of the galloping consolidation
that has been remaking out-of-home advertising in this decade,
particularly in radio and outdoor media.
</P>
<P>
   Infinity, America's largest owner of radio stations with more
than 160, acquired TDI in 1996, the year Infinity was acquired by
CBS. Outdoor Systems has expanded by purchasing the outdoor
operations of, among others, the Gannett Co. and the Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top nine companies in outdoor advertising have 62 percent
of the industry revenue,'' said Nancy Fletcher, president and chief
executive at the Outdoor Advertising Association of America in
Washington. Outdoor ad revenue reached $2.3 billion last year, up
9.1 percent from 1997, the largest increase in 14 years, while
total out-of-home ad revenue climbed 9 percent to $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of the fragmentation of other media; demand
from advertisers in categories like entertainment, hotels and
resorts and retail; increases in new categories for us like
Internet and pharmaceutical advertisers, and technological
improvements,'' Ms. Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the improved graphic quality of many
signs because of the rise of computer painting, which now accounts
for more than 90 percent of signs, she estimated, compared with 5
percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to be at the mercy of the man with glasses painting
the sign,'' he said. ``The creative now has helped a great deal in
attracting fashion and show-business advertisers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco was once the largest spender in outdoor advertising, but
those ads disappeared for good last month under terms of an
agreement between the cigarette makers and state attorneys general.
That negative is being turned into a positive, Gottesman said, as
outdoor companies cultivate other revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies were long-term clients probably paying
unbelievably low rates'' for their ad space, he added. ``Now other
advertisers can come in and pay market rates. It's like when a
rent-controlled apartment turns over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Outdoor Systems holdings will be added to the cross-media ad
packages that CBS offers under the name CBS Plus, which have been
bought so far by advertisers like Pennzoil and Taylor Made Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are able to go to advertisers and their agencies and make
it one-stop shopping if they want it that way,'' Karmazin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am willing to take all of their money,'' he added, laughing,
``if they are willing to give it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And as the agencies have consolidated,'' Karmazin said, ``it's
better for the media to deal with them if we have a consolidated
position as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will mean that Infinity will derive about a third of
revenue from out-of-home advertising and two-thirds from radio, he
added, compared with the present proportions of 12 percent and 88
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   As for organizational matters, Karmazin said, ``our feeling
right now is to let both'' Outdoor Systems and TDI ``operate
separately'' under present management, likening that to having each
of the many radio stations that Infinity owns in New York City,
with programming ranging from Howard Stern to ``golden oldie''
music to Don Imus, run by its own general manager.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal closes, Arte Moreno, 52, president and chief
executive at Outdoor Systems, is to become chief executive of the
Outdoor Systems subsidiary and join the board of Infinity.
</P>
<P>
   William Levine, 68, chairman of Outdoor Systems, will be
chairman of the subsidiary and also join the Infinity board. Both
have agreed to vote their shares, representing about 26 percent of
the outstanding stock of Outdoor Systems, in support of the
acquisition. William Apfelbaum is to continue as president and
chief executive of TDI.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal call for each share of Outdoor Systems to be
swapped for 1.25 shares of Class A common stock of Infinity, which
is 82 percent owned by CBS after a spinoff in December that made
Infinity a public company. CBS will vote its 96 percent interest in
Infinity in favor of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The share exchange valued Outdoor Systems at $32.50 a share, a
13 percent premium to the $26 closing price on Wednesday, the day
before the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, as the Dow
Jones industrial average plunged, shares of Outdoor Systems rose
68.75 cents, to $29.50, shares of Infinity fell 93.75 cents, to
$25.0625, and shares of CBS dropped 93.75 cents, to $40.0625.
</P>
<P>
   The Infinity deal contrasts with an announcement Friday by
Chancellor Media Corp. that it was considering the sale of its
outdoor operations, which were greatly expanded last year when
Chancellor bought Whiteco Outdoor Advertising and Martin Media.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Karmazin said that he remains a buyer rather than a
seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a believer in the power of advertising,'' he
said. ``Now more than ever, branding is the word and how do you
brand? You advertise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And who is the biggest pure-play advertising company?'' he
asked rhetorically, leaving the answer unspoken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
