<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOTHES-BABIES28     05-27 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOTHES-BABIES28 </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents pamper tots as kids' market gets hip to designer duds,
silver rattles and high-end items
</P>
<P>
   By Alma Hill
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a baby boom rattling the fashion industry.
</P>
<P>
   Infants and toddlers have become the muse of the moment,
inspiring designers to produce pricey clothes and accessories that
give new meaning to the word ``pampered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, the upscale baby market has witnessed
the advent of handmade, sterling silver rattles and jewelry by Bali
designer John Hardy that sell for as much as $300.
</P>
<P>
   In November, BabyGap stores welcomed a new sibling called
BabyGap Luxe, for the newborn who needs everything from a $245
cashmere layette to a pair of $98 leather pants. Donna Karan's new
DKNY Infant and Toddler line arrived in stores this spring, and
DKNY Baby is scheduled for a June delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Karan entered the children's wear business in 1997 with DKNY
Kids. But she expanded the line to infants out of frustration.
Karan couldn't find items she liked when shopping for baby gifts
for close friends such as Jane Chung, her ``creative soul mate''
and DKNY design director.
</P>
<P>
   A baby was also behind celebrity makeup artist Bobbi Brown's new
skin care products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babies are happening right now,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   When her third child, Duke, was born 10 months ago, Brown wanted
something special to rub on his skin and wasn't satisfied with
products already on the market. So she created Baby Essentials, a
quintuplet of skin care products that retails for $89 a set. The
line came out in late April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still like Johnson &AMP; Johnson, because they remind me of my
childhood,'' Brown says, ``but I was ready for something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity customers of Brown's, such as Cindy Crawford and
Marlee Matlin, apparently agree.
</P>
<P>
   Origins, a cosmetics and skin care company owned by Estee
Lauder, has also entered the fashionable baby fray by launching
eight all-natural products that range in price from $7.50 to
$13.50. Another entrant: handbag designer Kate Spade, who's
marketing a black nylon diaper bag that retails for $200.
</P>
<P>
   With celebrities such as Madonna, Jada Pinkett Smith, Holly
Robinson Peete, Christie Brinkley and Patricia Heaton cooing with
children, the costly merchandise has a natural audience. But models
and celebrities aren't the only people spending big bucks on their
young.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers and industry analysts say America's booming economy,
and a growing appreciation of the difficulties attached to
later-in-life pregnancies, are what help fuel the sale of items
such as $25 cashmere booties and $100 cotton knit onesies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents see this segment of the market as an extension of
themselves,'' said Vanessa Groce, editor of Earnshaws, a New York
trade magazine for the children's wear industry. ``They buy better
products for themselves, so they want to buy it for their own kids.
It's better-educated, affluent people in urban areas. It's only a
small segment. It's not mainstream at all.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why BabyGap carries its luxury items only in selected
markets. While there is an entire store devoted to BabyGap Luxe
products on Manhattan's Fifth Avenue, the BabyGap at Lenox Square
in Atlanta has Luxe only in newborn sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't discuss strategies in terms of store locations, but it
is based on where we have the greatest response,'' said Amy
Maniatis, director of Gap public relations. ``It's really driven by
our customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers at Neiman Marcus at Lenox like the high-end
merchandise so much that the store carries Hardy's sterling silver
baby collection, Karan's infant and toddler line and a French
couture collection called Babymini par Calimini. ``We're getting
more and more in because it is selling so well,'' said Amy
Doelling, Neiman's public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Greer, news anchor for Atlanta TV station WGNX, is one of
Neiman's regular customers. She also goes to baby boutiques to shop
for her sons, Kyle, 4, and Tyler, 7 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a boy, it's hard to find cute baby clothes,'' Greer said,
referring to the typical department store selection. ``So I usually
buy the Ralph Lauren and the Tommy (Hilfiger) and the Donna Karan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to spend a lot of money on my stuff, so I don't feel
bad when I spend money on the boys' clothes,'' she added. ``My
mother fusses, but they're only my kids once. I won't be able to
dress them in a couple of years, so I'm having fun now.''
</P>
<P>
   For many parents, though, tot-size designer items are for
special occasions only. Dr. Giselle Corbie-Smith, an internist for
Emory University at Grady Memorial Hospital, sticks to basic, more
affordable clothes for her children. The only upscale items her two
boys have are a Tiffany baby spoon she received as a gift when
4-year-old Noble was born and an engraved silver cup given to
17-month-old Aydan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a newborn, those kinds of keepsakes can be real special,''
Corbie-Smith said. ``But not for everyday use. I'm not going to let
him go to Woodruff Park with his silver cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Photos by PHIL SKINNER / Staff
</P>
<P>
   This Mercedes driver takes a spin in a beige shirt ($26),
cashmere V-neck sweater ($88, $24.99 on sale) and leather pants
($98), from BabyGap Luxe. The young girl sports a floral print
jumper ($40) and T-shirt ($18), by DKNY Infant and Toddler at
Dillard's. And the youngest hugs the floor in blue leggings, a
yellow duck top ($38) and orange knit sweater ($62), by Babymini
par Calimini at Neiman Marcus. The tot-sized Mercedes-Benz sells
for $399.50 at FAO Schwarz; the pink cotton knit dress in the top
photo is $98, by i Golfini Della Nonna at Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Cutlines:
</P>
