</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CONVENTION30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta hosting national convention of business, political
supporters
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Americans for the Arts, the national assembly of
business and political leaders in support of the arts, opens its
convention in Atlanta this week, it will be a kind of homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   That is, a visit to the city that five of AFTA's leading figures
_ Fulton County Commissioner Michael Hightower, Fulton County Arts
Council director Harriet Sanford, Woodruff Arts Center director
Shelton g. Stanfill and Donald Greene and Adrian King of the
Coca-Cola Foundation _ call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a celebration of Atlanta's leadership,'' said
Robert Lynch, president of Americans for the Arts, from his
Washington office. ``Those five members of our policy board are the
most from any city, so it's quite a concentration of power down
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is, in a sense, the birthplace of what Stanfill calls
``the nation's most prestigious arts support group.'' In 1995, when
Sanford was director of the National Association of Local Arts
Agencies, and Greene headed the American Council for the Arts
(private and corporate arts supporters), they were brought to-
</P>
<P>
   gether by mutual acquaintance and arts stalwart Jack Schultz of
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the wisdom of working together,'' Greene says, and the
two organizations were folded into the new AFTA.
</P>
<P>
   The combined clout is getting results. Advocating (Lynch prefers
that word to ``lobbying'') for the National Endowment for the Arts
by meeting with congressional leaders, AFTA clearly played a role
in the NEA's survival and growing support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drew up a resolution that said `art matters,' and over 300
mayors signed it,'' Sanford says. ``That gets attention in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention, which will be centered Saturday through June 8
at the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers, is a who's who. Co-chairmen
Hightower and Mayor Bill Campbell will welcome delegates. Featured
speakers include Johnnetta Cole, professor at Emory University;
U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.); and NEA Chairman William Ivey.
Representatives from the White House, the Conference of Mayors and
eight other arts-friendly organizations will sign an accord
authored by King, a statement of principles giving these groups a
unified voice in arts support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tenor of this meeting will shift away from the culture
wars and defensiveness of the past,'' Stanfill says. ``The message
is going to be a more positive one about growth.'' The morning
session of June 7 is dubbed National Youth Arts Forum.
Representatives of the NEA, AFTA and the Justice Department will
demonstrate their collaborative project, the Youth Arts Tool Kit:
books and videos that show community leaders how to use the arts to
enhance academic performance and help at-risk youth.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta theater was selected as the convention's showcased art
form. Theater artists Dwight Andrews and Elizabeth Omilami will
speak on the panel ``Spirituality and the Arts''; both are
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Performances by Jomandi Productions, actor Tom Key and
Neighborhood Playhouse director Sondra Nelson will introduce
convention events. Next Sunday evening, conventioneers will have
the option of attending improv comedy at Dad's Garage Theatre, a
puppet show at the Center for Puppetry Arts or a musical drama by
the Freddie Hendricks Youth Ensemble (``a shining example,''
Sanford said, of the arts as a positive force for urban young
people).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's ``Night on the Town'' will be followed by a dessert and
gospel concert at Ebenezer Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where better,'' Sanford says, ``to get a sense of place and be
filled with the Atlanta spirit?''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
