<HEADER>
A4017 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONDUCT-SEARCH2NDTAKE     05-27 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDUCT-SEARCH2NDTAKE30-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: this point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some qualities he earmarks:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ability to take the ASO into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Good communication skills. What this really means is the
ability to talk from the podium _ something Levi doesn't especially
like to do. But ``Your Atlanta Symphony Orchestra'' (as it bills
itself) wants to appear more user-friendly. So several candidates
this season _ Alsop, David Robertson, William Eddins _ seized a
microphone and worked the crowd at Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An up-and-coming reputation. Bankoff's term is ``rising
star.'' After four years of conflict, first over labor disputes and
then over Levi's dismissal, the ASO's corroded image needs the kind
of replating that a charismatic young conductor could provide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And, ``of course, musical competence,'' Bankoff says.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the ASO board isn't offering much, save exposure. In
addition to podium time, the ASO has a recording contract with
Telarc, though its continuance, without Levi and Shaw, is an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   Not many candidates would be coming here just for the salary.
The ASO board has grumbled that Levi's compensation is excessive,
and the betting among ASO insiders, including several longtime
board members, is that the next director will be paid half, or less
than half, of Levi's $550,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of compensation hasn't come up,'' says Bankoff.
But ``if someone just wanted to make money, he could do better in
New York.'' What the ASO has to offer, he says, is ``an attractive
package (in which) quality of life and an open environment'' play a
part.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million-plus salaries of Masur in New York and Sawallisch
in Philadelphia may make the ASO board quail, but it's the market
rate for a top-notch conductor today.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison's sake, note that Levi, perhaps the city's most
visible artistic figure, makes the same salary as Eddie Perez, the
Atlanta Braves' second-string catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will the ASO's conductor candidates hear much about plans
for organizational growth; in the foreseeable future, the ASO has
none to speak of. The operating budget has remained frozen around
$20 million since 1995. The orchestra roster is fixed at 96
players, and this was reached only after the contentious 1997
episode of six players who sought tenure and fought for months to
get it. The standard size for a major orchestra is 106 players.
</P>
<P>
   The stagnation is largely caused by the ASO's accumulated
deficit, which topped $4 million six years ago, was retired in 1997
and crept up past $1 million this year. Much of the organizational
energy has gone toward coping with it, and few increases on the
expense side of the ledger have been allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The only real carrot the ASO can offer its next music director
is a new performance space in the renovated First Baptist Church, a
project that even its most enthusiastic supporter, ASO board
chairman A.D. Frazier Jr., estimates has a two-in-five chance of
approval by the Woodruff Arts Center board, which will be asked
next month to finance it.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, the conductor who fits the ASO board's
requirements is someone young, glamorous, not too tendentious and
more interested in a career bounce than in the sweaty and thankless
process of orchestra building.
</P>
<P>
   And someone who will remain neutral about plans to reshape _
which probably means downsizing _ the ASO into ``the orchestra
Atlanta can pay for,'' in the reiterated words of former board
chairman L. Neil Williams, current president of the American
Symphony Orchestra League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra that Atlanta can pay for'' is probably not going
to attract the next Tilson Thomas. Or Masur. Or Levi. Conductors at
that level require much more, in salary and perks and recording
contracts. But orchestras such as Atlanta, Houston and Cincinnati,
on the brink of national name recognition but not quite willing to
pay for it, are looking to cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   With orchestras' schedules planned two or more years out,
settling on a conductor is no assurance that the baton will be
passed in time for the 2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably have to be a buffer period,'' says
Bankoff, ``probably two years.'' There may have to be one or more
interim music directors to take the ASO through the transition.
Frazier describes the next music director in terms of a ``successor
or successors'' to Levi.
</P>
<P>
   For an organization whose financial fortunes are dependent on a
charismatic figurehead, such a delay couldn't come as worse news.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this prospect hasn't sped up the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will emerge with a different set of expectations for the
music director than were expected of either Robert or Yoel,'' says
Bankoff. ``The role is in transition in lots of orchestras. ... And
I'd like to see Atlanta play a role in what it means to have a
meaningful orchestral experience in America. A handful of
orchestras will define what it means, and Atlanta should be one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CONTENDERS
</P>
<P>
   Alan Gilbert, 32, Royal Stockholm Philharmonic. Son of New York
Philharmonic musicians Michael Gilbert and Yoko Takebe.
</P>
<P>
