<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard-bitten garden teaches lessons in bouncing back
 &HT;    EDs: Embaroged for Saturday, May 29.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Gardening double can wear you out, but it has
its advantages; enjoying two springs is one of them. Weeks after
that soft, bright season danced through Atlanta, it waltzed around
the North Georgia mountains _ my second second spring. Reassuring
in its constancy, lovely as always, it showed me something special
this year about resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the tiny, tender plants I put into the rocky ground on
this ridge seemed lost during winter's frigid days and nights. And
what didn't suffer from the weather _ a hot, dry summer took its
toll, too _ was bitten to the dust by deer and rabbits and who
knows what.
</P>
<P>
   Resigned to the prospect of having to repeat much of the
planting I had done over the past year, I am amazed at what
survived, thrived even.
</P>
<P>
   In Big Momma's garden, where the rose and the Rose of Sharon
grow, along with many other old-timey plants my grandmother loved,
there were several gratifying comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   Two seedlings from my Atlanta Rose of Sharon, which some call
``trash'' (as a friend says about her men, I like my garden ``a
little on the trashy side''), are recovering from animal pruning
and pushing hard to catch the third, which has reached 2 feet.
Another ``trashy'' plant, the prickly pear, was the most surprising
victim of feasting animals; they apparently felt no pain from
pincushion pads. Well, prickly pear now grows new pads with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny burning bush that was nibbled down to nothing but nub
already has exceeded its original height of 6 inches, putting out
chartreuse-colored leaves much larger than its original foliage,
rushing to grow tall and tough enough to evade the grazers.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the other side of Big Momma's garden stand two mulleins
descended from a Celestine Sibley gift; their big gray-green leaves
had lain plastered to the ground in rain and cold but now have
risen to become the mothers of all mulleins, their stalks already 4
feet high, topped with big buds that will open purplish. Snuggled
next to the mulleins is the badly damaged rose campion, which had
been eaten to the ground. Inspired by the comeback mulleins, the
rose campion puts out gray-green leaves with steady determination.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a comeback creates novelties. All the horsetail reeds
were cut to the ground by animals, and all have put out new reeds
that rise from the ground like vertical caterpillars. One, clump,
however, has grown a single reed like none I've ever seen before:
half an inch in diameter, twice as fat as the others _ and twisted
so that its black rings resemble the spiral of a peppermint stick.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the cabin, in the Japanesque garden, the
hard-bit dwarf mondo struggles back with tentative green growth, as
does cast iron plant and Lenten rose (it produced one lonely
bloom).
</P>
<P>
   A baby azalea, one of the early chomping victims I noticed, has
new leaves right on top of the ground, as it was eaten down to 2
inches. Next to it, a yew has put out bright-green growth after
being nibbled within an inch of its young life.
</P>
<P>
   The poor corkscrew willow, grown from an Atlanta cutting, was
snack food sometime in the winter. Now, its new growth shoots in
myriad directions, desperately seeking escape from the next wave of
hungry animals. A few feet away, a clump of bloodgrass recovers
from its mauling, bloodied but unbowed.
</P>
<P>
   Across the road, where native plants grow a transition to the
woods, a butterfly weed (some name for such a majestic plant)
contributed by Lynn Greer bravely returned after a losing encounter
with some ravenous creature. Similarly, the beautiful beautyberry
survived its grazing and grows strong and promising again. And the
Japanese paper plant branches out after falling prey to a fungus
that wiped out its fragrant blossoms at midlife.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, life. Early, middle or late, it is for learning. This second
second spring has taught me much.
</P>
<P>
   I've always been skeptical about ``animal-resistant plants,''
but those grown from bulbs, rhizomes, corms and tubers may be just
that. Nothing ate iris, lily, anemone, shamrock, garlic. But maybe
they're just on the dessert list. In any case, I would not want a
garden made solely of such plants. Nor am I endorsing the notion of
having my plants chomped to inspire energetic growth; I can prune
them myself.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the garden's response to critters' hard
pruning is heartening; resilience is a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
