A4020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-CHEFWEAR30-COX     05-27 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-CHEFWEAR30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe for comfort: Haute cuisine couture
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So you think you're a gourmet cook. Your kitchen is
equipped with stainless steel restaurant-style appliances; your
pantry is stocked with the finest ingredients and your favorite
recipes are ultra-organized. Guests and family alike practically
applaud when you bring a dish to the table.
</P>
<P>
   But do you have ``the look?'' Have you added a pair of baggy
cotton pants with a whimsical food-themed print and a white chef's
jacket to your apron hook? Do you keep a pair of black leather chef
clogs near the stove? Do you even have coordinated oven mits and
chef hats?
</P>
<P>
   In an age when chefs are celebrities and cooking is more a form
of entertainment than a daily chore for many, fashion has become
the final touch for a perfect gourmet experience.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Chefwear, a company that was founded in 1990 as
an outfitter to food professionals, saw 20 percent of their sales
last year go to home cooks who aspire to have ``the look'' of the
chefs they see on television or in the open kitchens of their
favorite restaurants, according to Gary Fleck, chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to tap into the home market even more, Chefwear staged a
mini-fashion show this month in New York City to introduce a new
line of prints designed by Nicole Miller. It's the first time a
major fashion designer has been involved in creating garments for
chefs. Miller's prints -- Italiano, Vineyard, Habanero and Roundup
-- join Chefwear's other popular prints like Utensils and the
classic Black/White Houndstooth.
</P>
<P>
   Fleck's wife, Rochelle Huppin, first created the all-cotton
pants and jackets when she found the standard-issue polyester
uniforms used in so many professional kitchens uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   If the attire of Atlanta's top chefs at the Share Our Strength
charity event earlier this month is any indication, chefs love the
line. Virtually every chef there was sporting Chefwear pants,
including Nava chef Kevin Rathbun, who said he wouldn't wear
anything else in the kitchen. David Berry, chef of Horseradish
Grill, also is a loyal customer -- he was one of a handful of
national chefs to model at the Chefwear event in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Moore, owner of Cook's Warehouse in Atlanta, said while
most of her Chefwear sales goes to restaurants, more and more home
cooks are picking up the items. ``I had one man say he likes to
cook for his dates and greet them at the door with his chef outfit
on,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cook's Warehouse, Chefwear is sold at Chef Duds
in Alpharetta (Ga.) and Uniforms By Mindy in Norcross (Ga.).
Consumers also can order a Chefwear catalog by calling
1-800-568-2433 or visit www.chefwear.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
