<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SPIRITUALITY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Journeys of the soul
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Saturday.
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poets say summer is the season for love.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists claim it's a time for travel.
</P>
<P>
   But many others think the summer is the perfect time to deepen
your spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of years, people have used travel for renewal.
Ancient Greeks traveled to the oracle of Apollo at Delphi for
counsel. Eastern mystics sought solitude atop mountains.
Christians, Muslims and Jews have been making pilgrimages to holy
sites in the Middle East for many centuries. Such ``sacred travel''
continues to be a part of spiritual life and is the theme of a new
book, ``Sacred Roads'' (HarperSanFrancisco, $22, 268 pages), by
Nicholas Shrady that details his travels to the world's holiest
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a tourist returns from a holiday, they've added a couple
of pounds around their waist and they're rested, but there's
nothing that's changed their perspective,'' Shrady said during a
recent telephone interview from his home in Barcelona, Spain.
``When the pilgrim returns from a journey, the pilgrim is never the
same person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacred travel is one road people are taking these days. But
there are many other spiritual paths, and the summer is a good time
to begin such a trip.
</P>
<P>
   All journeys should begin with a map. Below is a guidebook for
the summer with listings of music, books, films and retreat centers
that offer spiritual renewal for people who are open to change.
</P>
<P>
   RETREAT CENTERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Itawa Retreat Center: This facility, open to people of all
faiths, is located on 72 wooded acres near Dawsonville. It is often
used for mind-body workshops by psychologists, counselors and
support groups. Fees are negotiable. 706-216-2768.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Simpsonwood Conference and Retreat Center: The center, 25
miles north of Atlanta near Ga. 141, offers lodges and campgrounds,
picnic areas and recreational activities. It is affiliated with the
United Methodist Church, but people of all faiths are welcome. In
general, cost is $75 per person per day, but can vary depending on
size of group. 770-441-1111.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monastery of the Holy Spirit: Catholic monastery, at 2625 Ga.
212 near Conyers, offers a retreat center on tranquil farm grounds.
Retreats can be shaped to the needs of the individual or group.
Regular services, featuring Gregorian chants, are open to the
public. All faiths are welcome. Although there is no set fee, $40
per person per day covers lodging and meals. 770-760-0959.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ignatius House: Jesuit retreat center, located on 20 acres at
6700 Riverside Drive, Atlanta. The center offers a place for silent
prayer and reflection, with a focus on the spiritual exercises of
St. Ignatius. Best suited for those with Judeo-Christian beliefs.
Cost is $150 per day and includes private room and bath.
404-255-0503.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Richard Smallwood with Vision
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Healing _ Live in Detroit''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Smallwood sticks with winning formula. His previous
album, a big hit, was recorded live in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Dottie Peoples
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``God Can &AMP; God Will''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Atlanta resident's mix of traditional gospel with
contemporary flavor pulls in both old and young listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Yolanda Adams
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Songs From the Heart''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Gospel veteran departs from usual contemporary music
settings to sing traditional hymns.
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Joanna Hogg
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Looking Into Light''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Hogg, an Irish singer with a stunning voice, sings
traditional hymns set to grand piano and Celtic-tinged
instrumentation.
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Steven Curtis Chapman
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Speechless''
</P>
<P>
   Release: Late June
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Chapman, a Christian music titan, is known for his
well-crafted lyrics and impassioned singing. Expect more of the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Artist:
</P>
<P>
   John Tesh
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``One World''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: Love him or hate him, Tesh's persistent touring and
concert videos are winning more fans _ even with his new goatee.
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Michael Whalen
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``The Softest Touch''
</P>
<P>
   Release: May
</P>
<P>
   The buzz: A fast-rising New Age composer who has made a name
composing rich, moody instrumental music. Whalen now tackles his
first love _ acoustic piano.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Veggie Tales'' series
</P>
<P>
   Author: Phil Vischer
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Tommy Nelson
</P>
<P>
   At a glance: Bob the Tomato and Larry the Cucumber tell cute
parables with a Christian message.
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``The Visitation''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Frank Peretti
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Thomas Nelson
</P>
<P>
   At a glance: Before Armageddon was hot and Y2K was unheard of,
Peretti's novels, featuring wars between angels and demons in
contemporary America, sold millions.
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Sacred Roads''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Nicholas Shrady
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: HarperSanFrancisco
</P>
<P>
   At a glance: Shrady travels to sacred sites around the world. In
India he bathes in the Ganges; in Turkey, he visits the tomb of the
Sufi poet Rumi; in Jerusalem, he worships at the Church of the Holy
Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Every Dead Thing''
</P>
<P>
   Author: John Connolly
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Simon &AMP; Schuster
</P>
<P>
   At a glance: New Age magazine characterizes this thriller as the
``Silence of the Lambs'' gone clairvoyant.
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Yesterday, I Cried''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Iyanla Vanzant
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: Simon &AMP; Schuster
</P>
<P>
   At a glance: Yesterday she may have been crying, but now Vanzant
is sporting a smile _ all the way to the bank. Vanzant, a former
welfare mother and battered spouse, is one of the New Age
movement's top authors.
</P>
