<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS HASN'T EARNED THE JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Jerry Buss turned down Jerry West's attempt to trade
for Mitch Richmond in the middle of the 1997-98 season, there has
been a growing perception that the Los Angeles Laker owner no
longer is the free-wheeling, do-whatever-it-takes spender he was
during the team's Primetime era. And, if Buss retains Kurt Rambis
as his head coach, he will have proven without a doubt that this is
the case.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Rambis was a hard-nosed scrapper who dredged the
most out of limited skills.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, well, there is nothing he did during his brief
incumbency to indicate he was an improvement over Del Harris, or,
even worse, two other predecessors, Magic Johnson and Randy Pfund.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kurt Rambis has about as much business being head coach
of the Lakers as Kurt Russell, considering the numerous tactical
blunders he committed and his inability to motivate the Laker
players.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't Jerry Buss getting tired of firing his coaches at
mid-season, as he did to Pfund and Harris and as he will have to do
again next season if he brings back Rambis, whose modest coaching
credentials are exceeded only by modest leadership qualities. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Forget Phil Jackson winding up with the Lakers. Pat Riley has
a greater chance.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   It's known Riley and wife Chris are thirsting to return to Los
Angeles and that Riley would be amenable to coaching the Lakers
again. Riley would be the perfect fit for a team that is in
desperate need of such a firebrand disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for it to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss has told intimates he never would rehire Riley, who's
making more than $8 million a year for the Miami Heat. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ If the hopelessly spoiled Shaquille O'Neal has even a morsel
of pride and one starts wondering if he does in light of his early
playoff exits each spring he should forget about all his
entertainment gigs in the off-season and concentrate solely on
practicing his free throws and going on a serious diet.
</P>
<P>
   The lumbering Shaq, who tires badly at the end of games, is 50
to 60 pounds overweight. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ In the span of one year, the Dodgers hold the distinction of
firing the hardest working coach in major league baseball, Mark
Cresse, and perhaps the nicest, Charlie Hough. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Oh sure, Hough, the defrocked Dodger pitching coach, has been
responsible for the staff's disappointing work this season. The
fact the team's pitchers just might be throwing to the worst
defensive catcher in baseball, Todd Hundley, is quite irrelevant,
of course. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ If Bill Russell still were around managing this underachieving
Dodger team, you can be sure the team's management would have been
taking terrible potshots at him and preparing for his ouster. But
Davey Johnson has a big reputation and multi-year contract, so no
one dares utter anything unflattering about him. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ When you spend as much money as the Dodgers have their payroll
exceeds $84 million and the team performs far below expectations,
those at the lower rung of the organization are sacrificed to
divert attention from those up high who made all the major
decisions responsible for such distress.
</P>
<P>
   Thus that pencil-pushing , CPA-turned Dodger president geek, Bob
(Don' Call Me Rocky) Graziano, and his top emissary, Kevin Malone,
remain unscathed as the Dodgers stumble and Charlie Hough is
cruelly detached. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ As I said before, the best break of the season for the Dodgers
came in the left elbow of Barry Bonds. If Bonds had been able to
remain healthy, the San Francisco Giants just might have run away
and hidden from the Dodgers by now in the N.L. West Division. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The respect that the Long Beach State president, Dr. Robert
(Fightin' Bob) Maxson, engenders on the national athletic scene was
reflected recently when he was among 44 leaders selected from a
variety of sectors John Wooden, Tom Selleck, John Naber, Dan Gable,
Richard Brown were some of the others to participate in a three-day
Summit Conference in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it was a discussion of ethics, character and honor
in athletics,'' relates Maxson, who was a signatory to the Arizona
Accord that was revealed Tuesday at a press conference at the L.A.
Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Maxson was present and didn't even miss any of his
school's graduation ceremonies. He was joined by Wooden, Naber, Tom
Crawford, director of coaching for the U.S. Olympic Committee and
Michael Josephson, founder and president of the Character Counts
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   For some strange reason, Fightin' Bob's one-time sparring
partner, Jerry Tarkanian, was not invited to participate in the
confab. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ As time goes on, I'm growing more impressed with Oscar De La
Hoya's toughness than I am with his ample skills, which are the
same exact feelings I once had for Muhammad Ali and Sugar Ray
Leonard. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ The rampaging Cleveland Indians have been rolling over the
opposition in the same consistent manner that the New York Yankees
did last season. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Who would have thought that Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine would
turn out to be better in a TV commercial this season than they have
been on the mound for the Atlanta Braves?. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Honestly, it's a draw who I find more nauseating to listen to,
NATO's Jamie Shea, or the NFL's Paul Tagliabue. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ How loony is major league baseball when it attempts to cancel
the final two years of its contract with ESPN? Talk about the old
cut-off-your-nose-to-spite-your-face syndrome over a silly snit.
</P>
<P>
   Does major league baseball have any idea how much publicity ESPN
gives it on a daily basis? Who cares if ESPN shifted three
September Sunday night baseball games to its smaller ESPN2 outlet
in order to make room for its NFL telecasts?. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Baffert decided to run Silverbulletday in the Belmont
Stakes for one reason to prevent his dreaded rival, D. Wayne Lukas,
from winning the Triple Crown with Charismatic. I have a hunch
he'll fail. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Those loudly sticking up for the New York Knicks' beleaguered
coach, Jeff Van Gundy, conveniently forget that he badly mismanaged
throughout the regular season the two men, Lattrell Sprewell and
Marcus Camby, who have played such vital roles in the Knicks'
surprising playoff success. . .
</P>
<P>
   _ One of my favorite human beings, Mr. Lou Trani, sports
historian extraordinaire, is recovering nicely from minor surgery.
. .
</P>
<P>
   _ Big John Papadakis, the famed San Pedro restaurateur and
former USC linebacker star who now weighs a compact 288 pounds,
tells me his son, Taso Papadakis, is in Honolulu filming a bit for
the ``Pacific Blue'' TV series. . .
</P>
</TEXT>
