<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-DEMS-NYT &LR;      05-27 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FORCING REPUBLICANS INTO DEFENSIVE POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the Capitol lawn Thursday, gleefully defiant
Democrats announced a petition drive to force the House to consider
a bill to regulate health maintenance organizations. In another
corner of Capitol Hill, Vice President Al Gore demanded that House
Republicans enact even more restrictions on guns than the Senate
reluctantly did.
</P>
<P>
   And at midday, the House left early for the Memorial Day recess
when Republicans could not gather the votes needed to start debate
on a $289 billion military bill they had planned as a showcase of
their support for strong national defense.
</P>
<P>
   It was all a grand partisan paroxysm on the eve of a Memorial
Day vacation. But the confluence of events did illustrate the
developing dynamic of a Republican-controlled Congress largely
shaped by a Democratic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On issue after issue, Republicans are taking a defensive stance.
They are trying to slow down Democratic initiatives, defuse other
popular issues long associated with the Democrats, or draft their
own, milder versions of Democratic bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear to me as though they have anything to put on
the agenda themselves,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The result _ intentional or not _ is that this Congress so far
is looking more moderate than the Republican Congresses that came
before it. Republicans are taking some surprising stands, if only
because they are constantly being caught in an inactive or reactive
posture.
</P>
<P>
   So if gun control once was anathema to the Republicans, today
the party's senior leadership has endorsed some limited measures.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans once fought hard against increases in the minimum
wage, today some House Republicans are working to draft their own
plan for an increase in the minimum wage, coupled with a business
tax-cut package. Their goal is to keep the Democrats from gaining a
popular campaign issue with their call for a $1 increase in the
minimum wage over two years.
</P>
<P>
   And where the Republicans once wanted to abolish the Department
of Education, now they are rallying around some education spending
measures to call their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the most adamant conservative Republican understands _
just like the most liberal Democrat _ that the country likes
moderate evolutionary changes,'' said Rep. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for this shift, ranging from the public
mood to the Republicans' small majority in the House and the
tactical skill of the Democratic minority. In part the times have
left the Republicans without their traditional issues: the economy
and the battles against communism, welfare and crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the extraordinary economy has dimmed the public's enthusiasm
for tax cuts. President Clinton took steps that cured his party's
vulnerability on welfare and crime. And until the air war against
Yugoslavia, the end of the Cold War had diminished public attention
to foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the issues that have risen to the top of the public
agenda, like education, Social Security, Medicare and health care,
are ones that are historically more associated with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for the Republicans is that nearly all the issues
that hit home with the voters are issues the Democrats have
cultivated and built real credibility on,'' said Geoffrey Garin, a
Democratic pollster. ``The one possible exception is the
reemergence of foreign policy as an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Republicans have worked hard to try to neutralize these
issues. On Social Security, for example, they have backed away from
Republican legislation to remake the Social Security program into a
system of private investment accounts. Instead, they are intent on
trying to look more committed than the Democrats to protecting
Social Security tax receipts from being used for other programs or
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for the Republicans is that even if they wanted
to go on the offensive, their House majority is so small that it is
unlikely they can do so. The difficulty of doing anything in the
House when a five-vote shift can doom any legislation was on
display this week when Republicans lost control of the floor and
could not pass either an agriculture bill or a military measure.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Democrats have become skilled at pressing tactical
advantages. They outmaneuvered the Senate Republicans on gun
control, leaving some Republicans complaining that their leaders
need to do more than stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to get out on front of a number of these issues,''
said Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J. ``We know they are going to come
down the line, and we might as well do it in an orderly manner
instead of looking as though we're only reacting to negative
Democratic tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still far from clear whether Republican moderation means
that anything more will get done this year than in more ideological
years.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, even small differences on an issue can be
difficult to surmount. Take the minimum wage. If Republicans come
up with a package that provides only small increases and couples
them with large tax breaks, the Democrats could very well vote
against such a bill. On the other hand, conservative Republicans
would probably remain opposed to any increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats relish pointing to congressional inactivity. And
particularly in the House, there is a tension between those
Democrats who want to pass legislation and those who think they
would be better off running against a ``do-nothing Congress'' next
year.
</P>
<P>
   So on Thursday, even as they demanded action on legislation to
regulate health maintenance organizations, Democrats could not
resist ribbing the Republicans for their inactivity. Joked Rep.
Robert Andrews, D-N.J.: ``It's hard to tell whether we are in
recess or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
