<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-ADVISORY-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for this week's New America News
Service:
</P>
<P>
   THE SPIRIT OF YITZHAK RABIN. The assassination of Yitzhak Rabin
forced much of Israel to re-examine its humanity, to return to its
capacity to feel and speak from the heart, writes Bill Maxwell, New
America's African American columnist currently on assignment in
Israel. This re-found sentimentality, he noticed, was palpable at
Rabin Square last week, where, significantly, Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak spoke to cheering crowds. Unquestionably, Barak felt the
presence of Rabin's spirit. ``We are meeting here at this place of
memory,'' he said, ``and with hope, in order to embark on our
journey toward unity, peace, security and prosperity. I see myself
as continuing his path.''
</P>
<P>
   PROFILING: THE CRIME OF DRIVING WHILE HISPANIC (OR BLACK).
Profiling is an illegal practice, used by most police in America
for stopping motorists that appear to be criminals by the color of
their skin or their gender, notes columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras.
To legally pull people over, an officer must have ``probable
cause.'' That didn't stop the highway patrol nabbing Contreras on a
California interstate one night recently. For what? As it turned
out, for nothing _ other than Driving While Hispanic. ``Will it
ever stop?'' he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   `INDIANS, HERE FOR THOUSANDS OF YEARS, ARE NOT GOING AWAY.' A
letter published recently in a South Dakota newspaper accuses:
``Even after countless payments for the Black Hills and other Sioux
benefit checks, we are tired of the `poor me' syndrome portrayed by
the Indians. No one else gets a free ride anymore.'' ``What this
writer, and others like him, do not understand,'' columnist Tim
Giago is quick to respond, ``is that our claims are based on
treaties the U.S. government signed with the Indian nations. And,
the U.S. Supreme Court decided in 1980 that the Black Hills were
taken (from the Sioux tribes) illegally.'' The Sioux tribes, he
points out, have never been paid a single penny for them.
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING TRACK OF ANTI-GAY HATE. Hate crimes against gays _
violent attacks and other anti-gay incidents _ showed a ``modest
decline'' of 4 percent in 1998, according to a recent nationwide
study, reports columnist Chuck Colbert. But the bad news is that
the number of `serious' and `violent' anti-gay incidents rose
dramatically. ``This year's report indicates that the severity and
intensity of the violence toward lesbians, gay men, and people of
transgender experience has increased significantly since last
year,'' noted Clarence Patton Jr. of the New York City Gay and
Lesbian Anti-Violence Project.
</P>
<P>
   CASTANEDA CHARTS AN AMBITIOUS COURSE IN MIAMI. After nearly 25
years as editor-in-chief of Puerto Rico's El Nuevo Dia, Carlos
Castaneda has assumed the titles of publisher and editor of El
Nuevo Herald in Miami. His immediate goal for the newspaper? ``To
create a publication that's easy to read and visually oriented for
the TV generation,'' he told Tim Dougherty of Hispanic Business.
But, he added, ``the focus of our paper is not just Miami. To make
a great paper _ that is my great interest and my great challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
