<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILING:CONTRERAS-N     05-27 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILING:CONTRERAS-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILING: THE CRIME OF DRIVING WHILE HISPANIC (OR BLACK)
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I was standing like a gawking tourist, looking up at the
skyscrapers of Downtown Dallas. I was dressed in a suit, carrying a
brief case, wearing dark glasses, as Californians are wont to do
and looking forward to the air conditioning inside the office I was
expected in shortly.
 &HT;    The policeman ordered me to lean forward and place my hands on a
building wall. He kicked my legs apart, then promptly and rudely
frisked me. His partner took my wallet, looked in it and counted
two hundred dollars. I was arrested and booked into jail. My crime,
violation of Texas law: Possession of money by a Mexican.
 &HT;    I woke up startled. My dream _ really a nightmare _ was just
that, a dream.
 &HT;    What wasn't a dream, however, was my getting on the I-15 in
suburban Escondido heading south to San Diego shortly after 10:00
p.m. one night recently. Turning onto the on-ramp right behind me
was a California Highway Patrol car. About two miles down the road,
his lights started flashing and I pulled over and stopped. I kept
both hands on the steering wheel, as taught by police officer
friends wary of trigger-happy cops.
 &HT;    The highway patrolman came to the passenger side, asked me if
there was something wrong with my car, for it seemed, he said, to
be weaving from side to side. He shined his flashlight on my hands
_ still on the steering wheel _ and throughout the car while asking
me the question.
 &HT;    No, I replied, nothing was wrong. I hadn't noticed my car
weaving on the freeway. He shined the light in my face and told me
to have the car checked. He walked back to his car. I drove off. I
hadn't noticed my car weaving, because it wasn't.
 &HT;    I had just been ``profiled.''
 &HT;    Profiling is a method used by police everywhere in the country
to pull people over on no other basis than gender, race or
ethnicity. To legally pull people over, an officer must witness a
traffic violation, or crime, or have a specific description and
notice that the suspect car has been stolen or involved in a crime.
In other words, an officer must have ``probable cause'' to stop
someone. Profiling is illegal.
 &HT;    As to whether or not profiling actually does go on everywhere,
the state of New Jersey is a case in point. Complaints by black and
Hispanic drivers in New Jersey drew heated denials by the state
police chief. However, a court ordered study conclusively proved
that blacks and Hispanics were stopped in far higher proportions
than their percentage of total drives along interstate highways.
Racial profiling was rampant along the interstates of New Jersey.
The culprits? Troopers under the command of the man denying it
happened at all. New Jersey Governor Christy Todd Whitman, fired
the chief.
 &HT;    In Los Angeles, the chief of police states that most profiling
stops are actually done by minority officers on their own people.
The chief, himself, is black. The chief is in denial.
 &HT;    Police officers ignore probable cause and use profiling to stop
people, particularly single males at night _ because they may be
driving under the influence, and black men _ because they may be
drug runners, drug sellers, drug addicts, criminals and/or, simply
because they are black. This has come to be known as ``DWB'' _
Driving While Black. The same is true of ``Hispanic-looking''
males, who have the added burden of being stopped by Border Patrol
officers for the crime of looking Hispanic.
 &HT;    In Arizona, two separate class action lawsuits are working their
way through the courts. One suit alleges that Border Patrol agents
arbitrarily stop cars with Hispanic looking drivers or passengers.
The other suit alleges that Border Patrol officers stop all cars at
night on certain roads but only detain Hispanic looking drivers or
passengers for questioning.
 &HT;    The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals has repeatedly ordered the
Border Patrol to cease stopping people on the basis of skin color
and ethnicity alone. The Court recently ruled that ethnicity could
be one of several factors, but not the only factor.
 &HT;    Let's see: I was a single male driving an expensive car at
night. Did the patrolman know I was of a `minority' persuasion? No,
he couldn't have, for he wasn't close enough to see me, nor was
there any light. Did he know that I might have just left a bar? No,
but he was curious enough to illegally stop me. Was the car
reported stolen, or used in a crime? No, and he knew that because
he would have radioed in for an instantaneous computer check of my
license plate. Given that the car wasn't stolen, why did he stop
me?
 &HT;    He profiled me. How many times does this happen every day in the
United States? How many state troopers, highway patrolmen, county
sheriff's deputies and city police in Everytown, USA, rise from
their boring routines, to pull over a black lawyer, or teacher, or
police officer for the crime of DWB? Near our southern border, how
many men get pulled over because they are Hispanic looking? As for
the Border Patrol, forget them, that's all they do.
 &HT;    Will it ever stop?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
