<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-LAND-RIGHTS:GI     05-27 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-LAND-RIGHTS:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 `INDIANS, HERE FOR THOUSANDS OF YEARS, ARE NOT GOING AWAY.'
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service  &HT;    A letter published recently in the Sioux Falls (S. D.) Argus
Leader demands an answer and an explanation.
 &HT;    The letter stated: ``Even after countless payments for the Black
Hills and other Sioux benefit checks, we are tired of the `poor me'
syndrome portrayed by the Indians. My suggestion is to do away with
the reservations as an out-dated concept and incorporate the
Indians into the 21st century. No one else gets a free ride
anymore.''
 &HT;    The writer added, ``Other minorities have been dumped on just as
bad as the Indians. Blacks as slaves, Chinese with the building of
the railroads and the Mexicans losing land in the southwest states.
But you don't see them always looking for a handout. They ask for
equality instead.''
 &HT;    Let me respond by declaring that the Sioux tribes have never
been paid a single penny for the theft of the Black Hills. The
Black Hills were taken illegally according to a ruling by the U.S.
Supreme Court in a 1980 decision. Aside from the Black Hills, more
than 50 million acres were taken either through treaty or by theft
from the Sioux Nation since the signing of the Fort Laramie Treaty
of 1868.
 &HT;    The treaty clearly spelled out that the Sioux Tribes would be
paid for the land by the government by providing health care and
educational benefits. That treaty is still in effect. The Indian
health services and other benefits are not free. They were paid for
by millions of acres of prime real estate taken by the American
government. Other lands were simply stolen. The meager funds the
tribes receive for health and education are not charity. They are
paltry payments for lands surrendered or stolen.
 &HT;    The Sioux Nation, as all other Indian nations, has one thing
that the Chinese, African-Americans and the Mexicans did not have.
The Indian nations had legal treaties signed between themselves as
sovereign nations with the government of the United States. They
also live on lands with clearly defined borders and boundaries over
which most state governments have no jurisdiction.
 &HT;    The writer of this letter would have us believe that Indians are
funded from cradle to grave. If that is so why were three counties
in South Dakota, all upon Indian lands, declared the three poorest
counties in the United States in the 1990 census? They sure aren't
benefiting from this ``free ride.''
 &HT;    The United States government has been trying to ``do away'' with
the Indian reservations for 200 years. Who does the writer believe
suffers most from these efforts? Certainly not the non-Indian.
 &HT;    Let me bury another myth here. Indians pay federal income taxes.
They pay a sales tax every time they purchase a car, appliance,
clothing or food off the reservation. They pay this sales tax even
though not a single penny of it is used for their benefit. It all
goes into the state coffers. When they register their cars or put
license plates on them, they pay a state imposed tax. They pay all
of the taxes other citizens of the United States pay except taxes
on their land on their respective reservations. The tribal
governments have the right to impose taxes on reservation lands
should they choose to do so. They also have the right to
manufacture their own vehicle license plates should they choose to
do so.
 &HT;    The Indian nations of America have been upon this land for
thousands of years. We are not going away. The best thing that can
happen is that we learn to live with the non-Indians and have
respect for each other.
 &HT;    Letters such as this one only aggravate the situation.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
