<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES:COLBERT-N     05-27 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES:COLBERT-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING TRACK OF ANTI-GAY HATE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hate crimes against gays _ violent attacks and other anti-gay
incidents _ showed a ``modest decline'' of 4 percent in 1998,
according to a nationwide study released earlier this month by the
National Coalition of Anti-Violence Programs (NCAVP), a voluntary
network of 26 community-based organizations and programs that
monitor and respond to anti-gay violence.
 &HT;    Among the study's sixteen local summaries, the total number of
incidents dropped from 2,665 in 1997 to 2,252 in 1998. Those
summaries included 12 cities _ Cleveland, Columbus, Detroit, El
Paso, Houston, Los Angeles, New York City, Orlando, Providence, St.
Louis, San Diego, and San Francisco _ three states _ Colorado,
Massachusetts, and Minnesota _ and the Central Coast region of
California.
 &HT;    That's the good news from the NCAVP's fifth annual report.
 &HT;    The bad news is that the number of serious and violent anti-gay
incidents rose dramatically. ``This year's report indicates that
the severity and intensity of the violence toward lesbians, gay
men, and people of transgender experience has increased
significantly since last year,'' said Clarence Patton Jr. of the
New York City Gay and Lesbian Anti-Violence Project in an
Associated Press story.
 &HT;    For example, the number of anti-gay murders more than doubled,
from 14 in 1997 to 33 in 1998. By contrast the nation's overall
murder rate has dropped to the lowest level in decades.
 &HT;    Serious assaults on gays in which victims sustained broken bones
and other major injuries rose by 12 percent, while the number of
assaults generally dropped by 11 percent. Moreover, reported victim
inpatient hospitalization rose by a whopping 108 percent.
 &HT;    The study also shows assaults and attempted assaults with guns
used against gays and lesbians rose 71 percent from 1997 to 1998;
the use of bats, clubs, and blunt objects by 47 percent; vehicles
by 150 percent; ropes and restraints by 133 percent; and knives and
sharp objects by 13 percent.
 &HT;    ``What this (trend) may be indicating is that perpetrators are
getting bolder; ... their actions are becoming more premeditated
since ... you have to make a decision to leave your house with a
baseball bat,'' Richard Haymes, executive director of the New York
anti-violence project, told the Associated Press.
 &HT;    Still, the speculation and statistics tell only part of the
story. ``As horrible as these statistics are, they don't tell us
about the bloodied and bruised faces behind the numbers,'' said
Dave Shannon, senior advocate for the Violence Recovery Program, at
the Boston-based Fenway Community Health Center.
 &HT;    But the numerous incident narratives of the victims'
experiences, also contained in the anti-violence study, do tell
that story. For example:
 &HT;    _In Massachusetts, an assailant attacked a 46-year-old gay man
he had met on America Online. The attacker punched the victim in
the face, kicked him to the ground, and beat him. During the
beating the assailant and a cohort called the gay man ``fag'' and
``queer.'' They also taunted, ``I bet this wasn't what you were
planning on, fag.'' The victim suffered cuts on his face and
bruises across his entire body; he also required stitches in his
lip.
 &HT;    _Two young, twenty-something men assaulted a gay man in his late
30s while he was roller-blading in a residential section of
Houston. The assailants called him ``fag'' and ``queer.'' The
victim lost an eye as a result of the attack. He said later, ``My
injury was so bad, sometimes I wished they had just killed me. But
I feel they didn't want me to die ... like living with only one eye
would be a constant reminder of the attack and control they had
over me.''
 &HT;    The release of the fifth annual anti-gay and lesbian violence
study came on the day after a man pleaded guilty to the slaying
last fall of Matthew Shepard, a gay college student in Wyoming.
Ironically, the study did not include the high-profile murder of
Shepard because no agency or system tracks such crimes in that
state.
 &HT;    For that matter, of the 40 states that have hate crime laws,
only 21 cover sexual orientation. While there is federal hate
crimes legislation, it only covers race, color, religion, and
national origin. Last year the Hate Crimes Prevention Act _ a bill
that would expand existing federal legislation to include gender,
sexual orientation, and disability _ died in committee in the House
and Senate. A bipartisan group of lawmakers has reintroduced the
bill, and the president endorsed their efforts the same day as the
release of the anti-violence study.
 &HT;    ``We're talking about whether people have a right ... to pursue
their lives and dignity ... free of fear, without fear of being
abused,'' Clinton said.
 &HT;    Let us hope that the anti-violence study and the brutal murders
of Matthew Shepard and Billy Jack Gaither encourage Congress to do
something _ pass this much needed federal legislation.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Chuck Colbert 
