<SLUG> BC-NUEVO-HERALD'S-CASTANEDA-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTANEDA CHARTS AN AMBITIOUS COURSE IN MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM DOUGHERTY 
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    After nearly 25 years as editor-in-chief of Puerto Rico's El
Nuevo Dia, Carlos Castaneda has assumed the titles of publisher and
editor of El Nuevo Herald in Miami.
 &HT;    First published in 1988, El Nuevo Herald served as the
Spanish-language insert of the Miami Herald until last year. The
two publications are now distributed separately.
 &HT;    A Cuba native, Castaneda has distinguished himself as a
journalist and consultant in the United States and throughout Latin
America over the past four decades. Recently, he discussed his
plans for El Nuevo Herald with HISPANIC BUSINESS.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q. What are your goals for El Nuevo Herald?
 &HT;    A. To create a publication that's easy to read and visually
oriented for the TV generation. We've already redesigned the
newspaper, both cosmetically and in terms of content to provide
more news and better local coverage. We've added sports pages
because we believe society's heroes are most often athletes and
television personalities, at least when we're fortunate enough not
to be at war. And we've begun a Sunday section devoted to cultural
developments, complete with book reviews and art criticism. I'm
also determined to minimize jumps, given that 70 percent of them
are never read. Therefore, we have just one jump, from page 1 to 2.
Everything else starts and ends on the first page.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q. What are the main challenges confronting your newspaper?
 &HT;    A. We are becoming increasingly independent from the Miami
Herald, a process begun last year. In the past, the two papers were
packaged together, but now they're sold separately. This year, for
the first time, we are going to have a circulation manager
reporting directly to El Nuevo Herald, and we expect to see a
corresponding increase in circulation. In addition, we are looking
for an advertising manager who is responsive to the tremendous
possibilities of the Hispanic market in Miami. We are home to the
third-largest Hispanic market in the country, and it's an educated,
affluent community. More than 40 percent of Hispanics in the Miami
area have attended college or earned a degree, and 56 percent are
homeowners.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q. You're credited with dramatically increasing the circulation
of El Nuevo Dia. Do you see similar growth opportunities at El
Nuevo Herald?
 &HT;    A. Miami is a smaller market but I think El Nuevo Herald has
great potential. Without having made a market study, my feeling is
that we should be selling 130,000 copies daily in a few years. We
now sell about 88,000 on Sundays and 83,000 daily. I'm now
concentrating on improving the editorial product, which should help
the circulation cause. Sometime soon we'll have audit figures. With
the new product in hand we expect to boost circulation
significantly.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q. Is the future bright for publications that serve Hispanics?
 &HT;    A. It's a broad question because there is no single Hispanic
market. The one in South Florida is distinct from the one on the
West Coast, for example. But I think Miami has great potential in
this respect. Miami is and will continue to be a link to Latin
America, including Cuba. In fact, the Cubans call Miami Havana
North, meaning many of them will remain here and others will come
regardless of what happens in their native country. Miami has the
potential to be a great center for commerce and business in
relation to Cuba of the future.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q. You've been quoted as saying that you'd like to make El Nuevo
Herald the hemisphere's most important newspaper within two years.
What did you mean?
 &HT;    A. Miami is a focal point for Latin America. The number of Latin
Americans who come here is impressive, and they come because they
feel at home.
 &HT;    But many South Americans also feel that we should provide a type
of International Herald Tribune, something published here but also
sold throughout the region, featuring a general view of what is
happening in the world.
 &HT;    For that we have to make enormous changes. First, we're going to
develop a network of stringers (freelance reporters) to provide
better coverage of Latin America.
 &HT;    We already have a daily section that provides several pages of
such news. And we've begun sending people to where the main news is
being developed. We had somebody in Colombia for the meeting of the
president and the guerrillas, and we just came back from Cuba for
the anniversary of the Pope's visit.
 &HT;    This is the type of material that I would like future readers to
expect to find in El Nuevo Herald, stories that South Americans
would like to read as well.
 &HT;    The focus of our paper is not just Miami. To make a great paper
_ that is my great interest and my great challenge.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
<TEXT>
