<HEADER>
A4073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-W     05-27 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTMENT OF MILOSEVIC MAKES DIPLOMATIC SOLUTION TO WAR LESS
LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs second graph to change ``derails'' to ``cripple''; subs
5th graph to clarify; subs 8 through 10 to clarify administration's
position; subs 13th and 14th graphs to drop comparisons with
Hitler. 2nd take is all new)  
(rm) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Publicly, the Clinton administration has applauded
the indictment of Slobodan Milosevic, a move that would appear to
change the Yugoslav president's status from potential deal maker to
an off-bounds pariah.
</P>
<P>
   But in private, administration officials say that the indictment
by the International Criminal Tribunal is likely to cripple their
efforts to find a diplomatic solution through the Russian envoy,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, and the Finnish president, Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment on charges of crimes against humanity has
significantly diminished the hopes of using Ahtisaari as a
go-between who could win Milosevic's acquiescence in a settlement.
Viewed in recent weeks as the most likely candidate to succeed in
negotiations, Ahtisaari would now be extremely reluctant to go to
Belgrade to deal with an indicted war criminal, one colleague said.
</P>
<P>
   And one official described the track with Chernomyrdin as
``pretty shaky,'' a sentiment that seemed to be reflected by others
in the administration who believe the Russian efforts may have
mostly run their course.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more troubling for a White House that has been trying to
avoid the use of troops, the indictment, by complicating the
diplomatic prospects, will enhance the arguments of those in favor
of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   British officials were quick to point out Thursday that the
indictment forestalled the likelihood of cutting what they called a
shabby deal with Milosevic. ``We think it might be helpful in
stiffening their spine,'' a British official said of the
indictment's effect on the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said that with news of the
indictment, he called President Clinton in Florida and urged him
that this was the time to send extra U.S. troops that have been
pledged for the international security force.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with the choice of sending ground troops into a
``non-permissive'' environment in Kosovo or of dealing with
Milosevic on the fine points of a settlement, the administration
was likely to go for the latter unsavory but practical choice.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's initial reaction on Wednesday to word of
the indictment was that it would not preclude direct negotiations
with the Yugoslav leader, but officials acknowledged the
awkwardness of negotiating with a man who has been indicted on war
crimes charges.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Thursday that the White House was
not ruling out the possibility that a diplomatic solution could be
reached with an intermediary at a point much farther down the line.
</P>
<P>
   The administration was notified on Tuesday of the indictment by
Louise Arbour, the war crimes prosecutor at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lead time the administration was handed by Ms. Arbour,
there was time for officials to figure out the landscape ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But except for the consensus that the indictment made diplomacy
more complicated, there was no cohesive judgment on what lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official, said it was conceivable that
Milosevic would take his country down with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 question is Milosevic's reaction and whether this
drives him into a fatalistic mode,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another senior administration official, with less experience in
the Balkans, said he believed that the indictment would weaken
Milosevic among his people.
</P>
<P>
   This could make Milosevic more susceptible to diplomatic
pressure, as well as military pressure, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision ``deepens his isolation, weakens him, makes
him very uncertain about his situation,'' this official said. ``He
has to shore up his strength, and he can't by taking an
intransigent position. If he takes a crazed extremist view, he'll
be all alone pretty soon,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   With Milosevic increasingly isolated among his people, NATO's
air campaign, plus the decision to begin to deploy troops for the
international security force, would have far greater potential for
forcing the Yugoslav leader to cave to NATO's demands, according to
this reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Biden, who met with the national security adviser, Sandy Berger,
on Thursday, also said it was possible that the indictment had the
``potential of further isolating Milosevic within Serbia'' and
causing further discontent there.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator, who met with Milosevic in Belgrade in 1993 and
called him a ``war criminal'' to his face, said that he ``wouldn't
bet the farm'' on his being so isolated among the Serbs that he
would be forced to seek an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Although the timing of the indictment was awkward, Biden said it
carried the ``good news of verifying what NATO is doing.'
</P>
<P>
   The British government, which since the beginning of the air
campaign has been much stronger in painting Milosevic as a man not
to be dealt with, seemed to take great pleasure in Ms. Arbour's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic track with Chernomyrdin was an uncertain bet, a
senior British official said, because Chernomyrdin seemed uncertain
in his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Chernomyrdin was trying to do a deal with a man incapable
of delivering,'' he said in reference to Milosevic. ``This pushes
the equation forward on troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration was taken somewhat by surprise that
Milosevic's right-hand man, Milan Milutinovic, the president of
Serbia, was also indicted. From a negotiating point of view, this
vastly complicated the picture, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of Milutinovic meant that the administration and
NATO had no real replacement with authority with whom to make a
final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility being considered by some senior administration
officials was the effect the indictment would have on Milosevic's
wealthy inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have criticized Milosevic publicly is Bogoljub
Karic, who runs television stations and owns a bank.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some ways to persuade pals of Milosevic, like
Karic, that it would not be helpful to their future to stick with
the regime, one official said. ``Mr. Karic could be reminded of the
Nuremberg example _ where industrialists were considered class A
war criminals,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing appeared fairly clear. The indictment made it
immensely difficult to do a diplomatic deal with Milosevic, for the
simple reason that to do so would undermine the authority of the
war crimes tribunal, the very body to which the Clinton
administration and the British government provided intelligence
information for use in formulating the indictments.
</P>
<P>
   And from Milosevic's point of view, the most obvious maneuver
would be to request immunity from prosecution before making any
settlement arrangements, an impossible scenario for the West to
consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
