Notra Trulock, foreground, former director of intelligence for the
Energy Department, discusses alleged Chinese espionage at U.S.
nuclear labs during a hearing before the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee last week. Trulock, the Energy Department's
intelligence official who first raised the alarm about China's
theft of American nuclear secrets, will receive a special award
Friday from Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. With Trulock is Ed
Curran, director of the Department of Energy's office of
counterintelligence. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
(NYT16) HILLBROW, South Africa -- May 27, 1999 --
SAFRICA-CRIME-COX, 5-27 -- A clerk in the records office of the
local police department files arrest records. There is an enemy
that President Nelson Mandela and his ruling ANC has not been able
to defeat. Crime is to be the only foe that seems to pose any
threat at all to the party's drive to win re-election Wednesday and
install Thabo Mbeki, Mandela's personally selected successor, as
president. (W.A. Bridges/Cox News Service)
</P>
