Matt Bogner and Ross King, remove fences Thursday on a beach which
will be officially opening to the public on Memorial Day. The
fences are used to deter erosion during winter storms. (Dith
Pran/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 27, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 5-27 -- Brian
O'Byrne, nominated for a Tony Award as a leading actor for his work
in ``Lonesome West,'' by Martin McDonagh. An Irish native who took
up acting in college, O'Byrne came to the United States in 1988
after inadvertently winning a green card in an immigration lottery;
his uncle had entered his name without telling him. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 27, 1999 -- MUSICALS, 5-27 --''I Wanna Be
a Dancin' Man,'' Bob Fosse's homage to Fred Astaire in ``Fosse.''
Hollywood's most important artists in the musical form, notably
Fred Astaire, Gene Kelly and Bob Fosse, began on Broadway and kept
up with its fashions after they left; Fosse alternated between
plays and movies throughout his career. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- May 27, 1999 -- BKN-RUSSELL TRIBUTE, 5-27 --
Bill Russell reacts to a standing ovation after being introduced to
the crowd. Thirty years and three weeks to the day after Bill
Russell played his last game for the Celtics, a game that fittingly
ended in a world championship, the town, the team, the fans, and a
glittering list of celebrities and players paid homage to the man
and his career. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WELLESLEY, Mass. -- May 27, 1999 -- HOME-SHEETS-BOS, 5-27
-- French bed linens from Bon Soir. High thread count equals
comfort. Once the concern of European royalty, the obsession with
thread count filtered down a few years ago to the very, very rich.
Now, it has entered the realm of the masses or at least of those
middle-class Americans who have a little extra spending money and
want kingly comfort. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON, Mass-- May 27, 1999 -- FASHION-YURMAN-BOS, 5-27
-- Jewelry designer David Yurman at Saks Fifth Avenue. A former
dishwasher, truck driver, and dry-cleaning delivery man, Yurman
found success in the jewelry design business with a simple
bracelet. Fourteen years ago, he twisted silver strands into a
cable-coil design that quickly became a classic and earned him
millions of dollars. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 27, 1999 -- TAXI-FLOATER, 5-27 -- A cab
driver gives new meaning to the notion of a taxi stand while parked
at one in Manhattan's West side on Thursday. After a couple of days
of thunderstroms and heavy rains, which usually prompts an
increased number of New Yorkers hailing taxis, balmy spring weather
along with bright sunshine returned to the Big Apple. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MEXICO CITY -- May 27, 1999 -- MEXICO-BEER-2, 5-27 -- A
worker puts a destination label on a pallet of Corona beers at the
Modelo brewery warehouse on Wednesday. In 10 years, Grupo Modelo
has transformed Corona from a once-obscure Mexican beer into a
global brand whose recognition approaches that of Coca-Cola or
Marlboro cigarettes. (Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
