</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV ARMY AGAIN SHELLS VILLAGES IN NORTHEAST ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRUME, Albania _ For the second day, Yugoslav forces shelled
villages in northeast Albania Thursday, heightening tensions along
the main crossing point for refugees fleeing from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rasim Sheta, 52, a relative of the two people killed in the
attacks in Cahani on Wednesday, stood beside two fresh graves in a
small cemetery here and said that Albanians would be forced to
fight back if the shelling continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all ready to fight,'' he said. ``We won't allow the
Serbs to attack our villages or get inside our land. We know that
we must keep cool, but we have to defend our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he spoke, gunfire rattled around the hills, and Sheta
looked up to see a huge black explosion rise from an Albanian
village on a nearby hilltop.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, two shells landed at the house of his cousin, Musa
Cahani, 59, killing him and his daughter, Merita, 20. The family
could find only the daughter's leg and hand but buried them all the
same in a grave next to her father.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the morning Thursday, the sound of gunfire and
shelling echoed around the border post of Morini, where 606
Albanian refugees from Kosovo nonetheless had crossed by late
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   During one attack around 10 a.m., a sound engineer from Chile _
one in the pack of journalists who wait by the border for refugees
to cross _ was shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials said the 30-year-old engineer, whose name was
not released, was in a coma and being transported to Italy for
medical treatment. Other reporters said he had arrived only the day
before and was working on a documentary about war correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden there was this whistling and this guy hit the
ground,'' said David Guttenfelder, a photographer with The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He had been standing on a rise in line with a Yugoslav army
bunker several hundred yards away, and it was unclear if he had
been hit by stray gunfire or was shot intentionally by snipers from
the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   The border area buzzed with military activity as Albanian tanks
and trucks, some manned by soldiers in camouflage, moved between
Morini and Kukes, the main town where the refugees are staying,
some 10 miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   The activity was in preparation for Albanian military exercises
planned for Friday, in which tanks and artillery will fire live
ammunition into the hills along the border.
</P>
<P>
   First Capt. Albert Mullai, spokesman for the Albanian military,
said the exercises had been planned before this recent spike in
tension along the border. But he said the maneuvers would
nonetheless demonstrate to the Yugoslav army across the border the
capacity of Albanian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of show of force,'' Mullai said.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it would only complicate the job of NATO, Albanian
officials say they do not intend to get involved militarily in the
conflict in Kosovo despite almost daily incursions of Yugoslav
forces into Albanian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attacks have come in areas with a heavy presence of
ethnic Albanian fighters from the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two days, the rebels and Yugoslav soldiers have
been fighting just across from the Morini border post, in what
rebel leaders say is a major offensive on their part to open a
route from Albania into the heart of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But some of that fighting has spilled over the border. Thursday,
Yugoslav forces shelled Cahani and Kishaj, said Andrea Angeli, a
spokesman for the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe. The two villages were among four shelled on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse at the hospital here, Hate Kadriaj, 35, said the attacks
in this area had increased since NATO began bombing Serbia and
Serbian positions in Kosovo on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of the people who treated Cahani, who had been hit
while drinking coffee on his front porch and while his daughter
tended to the family's cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has now started in this region,'' she said. ``It is a
very tense situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
