<HEADER>
A4098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      05-27 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS FINISH CASE AGAINST REMAINING OFFICERS IN TORTURE
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prosecution wrapped up its case Thursday against
the four police officers still on trial in the Abner Louima
brutality case, but without presenting the kind of directly
incriminating evidence that it did against Officer Justin Volpe,
who pleaded guilty in mid-trial this week and threw himself on the
mercy of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The case appears to be speeding toward a quick conclusion. After
the prosecution rested, just two days after Volpe pleaded guilty to
all the charges against him, the defense case began _ and quickly
ended for two of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Officer Thomas Bruder called no witnesses and
Officer Charles Schwarz's lawyer called only one. Officer Thomas
Wiese's lawyers said they would call a couple of character
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sgt. Michael Bellomo's lawyer has said he will present a
major witness during the defense case _ the sergeant himself. Judge
Eugene Nickerson told the jurors Thursday that closing arguments
could begin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's case against the other defendants is based in
part from Louima's own account of how he was beaten and brutalized,
though he did not identify any of the other officers directly.
Prosecutors also used testimony from fellow officers and police
records to try to tie the other defendants to the abuse of Louima
and subsequent efforts to cover up what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evidence presented against the four remaining
defendants, in three weeks of testimony in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, focused on Officer Charles Schwarz. He is charged with
holding Louima down in a restroom in the 70th Precinct station
house in Brooklyn while Volpe rammed a stick into Louima's rectum,
inflicting severe internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses testified that they saw Schwarz leading Louima
toward the restroom shortly before the attack, and prosecutors
sought to link him with Volpe in the minds of jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Thompson, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, told
the jury at the beginning of the trial, ``Justin Volpe and Charles
Schwarz began to inflict their own special brand of punishment,
their own special brand of torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiese and Bruder are charged with joining Volpe and Schwarz in
beating Louima in a police car before he arrived at the station
house, although Louima could not identify any of the officers he
says beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo is accused of trying to cover up the beating in the
police car as well as a second assault by Volpe on another man,
Patrick Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   The main evidence against Schwarz, 33, came from Louima himself
and two police officers who testified for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Louima did not directly identify Schwarz, but said that the
officer who held him down during Volpe's attack in the restroom was
the same officer who had driven him to the station house. Police
records show that Schwarz was the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers, Eric Turetzky and Mark Schofield, testified
that they saw Schwarz walk Louima, his pants down, toward the the
restroom on the morning of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen Worth, vigorously cross-examined
witnesses. Worth has said that Schwarz was never near the restroom,
that Louima was wrong in saying it was the driver of the police car
who had held him down. He also underscored that Turetzky and
Schofield did not testify that they saw Schwarz taking Louima into
the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyers, Joseph Tacopina and Russell Gioiella, also
largely waged their cases through cross-examination, and when
Thursday's court session ended, they were in the midst of
presenting the several character witnesses who are expected to be
the only witnesses they will call.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against Wiese, 35, includes Louima's testimony that
two of the officers who beat him in the police car were the same
officers who took him to the station house. He did not identify
those officers, but police records show that he was taken by Wiese
and Schwarz. Wiese's lawyers contend that Louima's account of being
beaten in the police car was not to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder's lawyer, Stuart London, had told the jurors in his
statement at the start of the trial that they would not be hearing
much from him: ``There will be many witnesses in this case that I
may not cross-examine or that I may not cross-examine for a lengthy
period of time. That's not because I accept their testimony. It is
because it doesn't affect my client.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima testified that Volpe and a second officer, whom he did
not identify, approached the police car in which he said he was
beaten and joined in the assault. Police records show that Bruder,
33, was Volpe's partner that morning, and records of police
communications also place Bruder at the scene of the reported
beating.
</P>
<P>
   London also said that Louima was not credible in his account of
being beaten in the police car. Among other things, the lawyer
said, and the prosecution agreed, Louima gave the wrong location
for the beating in which Bruder is accused of taking part, and he
argued that the only reason his client was even charged was that
``he was Volpe's partner that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors, from the office of Zachary Carter, the U.S.
attorney in Brookyn, have told the jury that Louima, a 32-year-old
Haitian immigrant, was beaten in the police car and attacked in the
station house restroom because Volpe and three officers still on
trial mistakenly believed he had punched Volpe in the face,
knocking him down, during the street melee. Bellomo is not accused
of taking part in either of the assaults.
</P>
<P>
   That Louima is black and the officers and sergeant are white has
added a bitter racial dimension to the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
