<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY INTERNSHIP PROGRAM TRANSFORMED MANAGER'S THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brandon is one of those mostly forgotten children. A
first-grader and one of 10 children in a fatherless family, he
arrives at a school on Chicago's South Side every day in a state of
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   His nose is perpetually running. His sweater is dirty. His shoes
are always untied.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Peters, a manager with United Parcel Service's Northwest
region, can't get the little boy off his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday, I'd tell him, `Son, you've gotta keep your shoes
tied, because otherwise, you're gonna trip and fall,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters tutored Brandon and other children for four weeks during
a recent internship as part of a senior management training
program. During those four weeks, he learned more about management
than he has in years of wrangling with adult employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bar none, it was the most transforming experience of my
personal life,'' said Peters, a 23-year UPS veteran. ``I was
completely overwhelmed with the people I worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, based in Seattle, is one of about 50 UPS managers who
will go through the company's intensive ``community internship
program'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which started in 1968, is designed to immerse an
elite group of managers in communities with problems that, on the
surface, differ from their own. They leave their jobs and families
to live and work at sites in New York City; Chicago; Chattanooga,
Tenn.; and McAllen, Texas. They don't go to observe. They pitch in,
doing anything that's needed, whether tutoring reading or teaching
interviewing skills, counseling youth or feeding the homeless. In
the process, they build problem-solving and communication skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They learn how to break down barriers,'' said Don Wofford,
national director of the internship program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the program is designed to increase understanding
of difficult social issues ranging from poverty and gang
involvement to unemployment and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them (the managers) to be more sensitive to these
issues, and to become involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the same types of conditions in their own personal
back yards.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS, the national shipping company now based in Atlanta that was
started in Seattle's Pioneer Square, has spent $12 million since
1968 on its community internships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to avoid the quick look,'' Wofford said.
``Volunteers painting houses on weekends is great, but when people
are housed in the environment and see what goes on day and night,
and what individuals who live there face day to day, it makes a
different impression.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience has changed Peters' outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a macro-issues, project person,'' he said. ``I change
processes and make things work better. But in this experience, the
only thing that could change was me. These problems are so huge,
the only thing I can do is make a personal difference in how I
conduct my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And one way he learned to do that is by talking less and
listening more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've advanced to where I am because I've been a good seller of
ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered I have to be a buyer of ideas as well. You've got
to be a good listener. The more I concentrated on listening, the
more solutions appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   It also extended his concept of diversity in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in the workplace today and talk about diversity,
it's about race and gender,'' he said. ``But diversity of ideas is
really important. This experience reinforced that to me. Diversity
infuses a workplace with new and challenging ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience showed him the importance of gathering ideas from
many different people in an organization. ``The best ideas come
from the bottom up,'' he said. ``Very seldom do the best ideas come
from the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who already volunteers in the community, is planning to
increase his involvement, especially in literacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can do is affect an individual or a couple of
individuals,'' he said. ``And you can hope someday that it will
have made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his internship, Peters saw Brandon one last time.
It had been several days since he'd last been with him.
</P>
<P>
   Excited, the little boy ran up to greet Peters. Then he stopped
and knelt down.
</P>
<P>
   And tied his shoe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
