<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-SCANDAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORGAN STANLEY EMPLOYEES SUSPENDED IN WAKE OF SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs 4th graph to clarify that Morgan Stanley and Luethke are
being investigated; subs 13th graph to delete redundancy; last two
graphs are new) 
(rm) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the nation's largest
securities firm, suspended two executives Thursday in connection
with a $10,000 payment that led to the arrest of a former employee.
</P>
<P>
   The firm said in a statement that it had made a ``mistake in
judgment'' last year when it paid a middleman to broker a police
sting operation against the dismissed employee, Christian Curry.
Curry, who is black, was contemplating filing a discrimination suit
at the time. He filed that lawsuit last week, adding false arrest
to his claims and demanding $1.35 billion in compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The development is the latest twist in a case that began more
than a year ago when Curry, the scion of a prominent New York
family, was dismissed from his job as a junior financial analyst at
Morgan Stanley. The firm said it dismissed him for abusing his
expense account abuses, but his termination came days after photos
of him appeared in a gay pornographic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Curry was arrested by undercover police officers
who said they caught him conspiring to plant racist e-mail on
Morgan Stanley's computer system, apparently to bolster his
discrimination lawsuit. Last week, the Manhattan district attorney
dropped all charges against Curry and began investigating Morgan
Stanley and Charles Joseph Luethke, the middleman, for their roles
in arranging Curry's arrest and the $10,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's two leaders, Philip J. Purcell, chairman and
chief executive, and John J. Mack, the president, on Thursday met
with prosecutors in the district attorney's office and pledged to
cooperate with the investigation into the $10,000 payment. The firm
also appointed Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, a
Manhattan law firm, to lead an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of our investigation is to learn the facts as
completely and as quickly as possible. We are sorry for any
distress this entire episode has caused our many clients and
thousands of employees around the world,'' Purcell and Mack said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pending the outcome of that investigation, the firm said it had
suspended with pay two people in its legal department. It did not
reveal the names of the two and did not say why they were
suspended. But people close to the firm said they are Carol
Bernheim, a lawyer trained as a litigator, and Monroe Sonneborn, a
managing director. Both are named as defendants in Curry's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither returned phone calls seeking comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bernheim and Sonneborn were not the main targets of the district
attorney's investigation, and the suspensions were entirely the
prerogative of Morgan Stanley, lawyers involved in the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell and Mack said in the statement that they themselves did
not know about the payment to Luethke beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If either of us had known about Luethke's request for money,
no payment would ever have been made,'' the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   The Curry lawsuit, which asks for $1.35 billion in penalties and
damages, names as defendants Purcell, Mack, Ms. Bernheim and
Sonneborn, along with seven other senior Morgan Stanley employees.
It contends that Purcell had a personal role in planning to entrap
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Charges against Curry were dropped last week, a move that the
district attorney's office described as unavoidable after it
discovered that Morgan Stanley paid $10,000 to Luethke.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley said Thursday that notwithstanding its expression
of regret for the $10,000 payment, it considers Curry's lawsuit
``without merit'' and said it will defend itself vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   But Benedict P. Morelli, Curry's lawyer, said that the firm's
armor is growing weaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is act one, scene one,'' Morelli said. ``We will prove
that our case has merit and theirs is totally without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Luethke has also maintained that Purcell had a role in Curry's
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney continues to investigate both Morgan
Stanley and Luethke. Lawyers involved in the investigation said
they did not expect to reach a conclusion about whether a crime was
committed for at least several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with Mr. Purcell and Mr. Mack,'' said Daniel J.
Castleman, chief of the Investigation Division in the district
attorney's office. ``We regard our talks as a positive step in the
right direction. We will have to wait and see how the investigation
turns out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Curry affair began a year ago April, when Curry, in his
first year as a junior analyst in the firm's real estate finance
division, was fired. Morgan Stanley said that he was terminated
because he abused his expense account. But the firing took place
shortly after the explicit nude photos of Curry appeared in
Playguy, a magazine that specializes in gay pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said he is not gay, but said that people at Morgan Stanley
thought he was when they fired him. Discrimination on the basis of
perceived sexual orientation is illegal in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Curry also claims that he was subjected to discrimination
because he was black. His lawsuit argues that he was excluded from
working on business deals that involved white southern clients, for
example, and that at a Christmas party he was asked to dress up in
an Afro-style hairdo and costume lips as a spoof to tease a senior
black banker who works there.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley now has to juggle an internal investigation, the
district attorney's criminal investigation, and Curry's civil
lawsuit. Lawyers close to the investigation say that the firm will
be under pressure to reveal how the decision to pay $10,000 to
Luethke was made, and who made it.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the criminal investigation depends in part on how
the district attorney resolves a tangle of relationships at the
heart of the case. Among these are the ties between Luethke and
Curry. The two met when they were attending Columbia University,
and they remain in contact to this day. But Luethke also worked
with Morgan Stanley to catch Curry in the act of infiltrating the
firm's computers, authorities say. Morgan Stanley paid the $10,000
to Luethke days after the arrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
