<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW, SEEING OBSTACLE, SENDS ENVOY TO BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After an intense round of talks with his American and
European counterparts, Russia's special Balkans envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, heads on Friday to Belgrade to meet President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's indictment Thursday by a U.N. tribunal was denounced
by the Russian Foreign Ministry as ``politically motivated'' and an
``additional obstacle'' to peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the ministry said the indictment raised
``serious concerns'' here but would not stop Russian efforts to
seek a ``possibly rapid political solution to the conflict around
Yugoslavia, including with the participation of President Slobodan
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's fourth trip to Belgrade was to have begun
Thursday. But it was postponed after he and Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov continued negotiations with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott and President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland throughout the
day in an attempt to align Russia and the West on an eventual
settlement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, whose ties to its traditional Serbian allies are central
to the three-way talks, has insisted that NATO should have only a
limited role in any international peacekeeping mission in the
Serbian province. Russia has also balked at NATO insistence that
Belgrade withdraw all its security forces from Kosovo, and it has
called for a preliminary halt to the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   No agreement was announced Thursday evening, as Talbott and
Ahtisaari, the European Union Balkans negotiator, left for Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ahtisaari told a Finnish news agency that the last
round of meetings had brought progress. ``Our views are approaching
each other, and the facts that bind everyone have been
recognized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Chernomyrdin said Chernomyrdin and Ivanov, in a
joint report to President Boris Yeltsin and Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin Thursday evening, had analyzed ``points of contentions''
and discussed the next round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion-page column Thursday in The Washington Post,
Chernomyrdin underscored Russian investment in a negotiated
settlement, but said that he would advise Yeltsin to pull out of
the process if the bombing did not stop soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2225EDT &QL; 
