<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL OFFICIALS SUSPECT FORMER OFFICE MANAGER OF KILLING
PROMINENT ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One day after federal officials released an
affidavit that accused him of participating in the abduction and
slaying of the missing atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair, her former
office manager pleaded guilty in federal court to two weapons
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The former employee, David R. Waters, 52, has not been charged
with any crime in the September 1995 disappearances of Mrs. O'Hair,
76, her son, Jon Garth Murray, 40, and her granddaughter, Robin
Murray-O'Hair, 30.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is the first time the federal government has
revealed that they suspect him of killing the missing family.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit of Edmund I. Martin, a special agent with the
Internal Revenue Service, says that Waters and three other men
``executed the scheme to abduct, kidnap and murder Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, Jon Garth Murray and Robin Murray-O'Hair for the purpose of
stealing at least $600,000 from the United Secularists of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit, which was used to obtain a search warrant for
Waters' apartment during an IRS investigation of fraud and
money-laundering triggered by the O'Hairs' disappearance with more
than $500,000 in gold coins, quotes a confidential source who said
that Waters hated Mrs. O'Hair: ``He spoke about seeing Madalyn
suffer and snipping off her toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters' attorney, Patrick R. Ganne, derided the affidavit,
saying it ``looks like a script for Oliver Stone's next movie. It's
full of speculation and guesses and nothing more. They don't have
any direct evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Carruth, the assistant U.S. attorney for the Western
District of Texas, expressed satisfaction with Waters' guilty plea
on the weapons charges but refused to comment on the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal investigators believe the O'Hairs are dead,
they have not been able to find their bodies. According to the
affidavit, Waters; Gary P. Karr, who was arrested on March 25 on
charges of possessing stolen property; Danny Raymond Fry, who was
killed in 1995, and Gerald Lee Osborne of Fort Worth, were all
involved in the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Waters was employed in 1993 and 1994 at the American Atheists
General Headquarters in Austin. He was arrested on March 24 after
federal agents found 119 rounds of ammunition in his apartment. He
is prohibited from possessing firearms or ammunition because he is
a convicted felon. In 1965 he was convicted of murder in Peoria,
Ill. He has also been convicted of assault, forgery, theft and
weapons violations.
</P>
<P>
   Waters faces up to 20 years in prison and a fine of $500,000.
Sentencing is scheduled for July 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
