<HEADLINE>
OHIO JUSTICES STRIKE DOWN VOUCHER PLAN IN CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Maine, Wis.)  (jt) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ohio Supreme Court has ruled that Cleveland can no longer
offer vouchers that enable low-income children to attend private
and parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   But in ending the nation's second-largest program of its kind
after two years, the court ruled only on a technical issue, that
the program was paid for improperly, through the state budget
rather than a separate authorization.
</P>
<P>
   The court, which announced its decision on Wednesday, said the
Cleveland program did not breach the separation of church and state
in either Ohio or federal law. As a result, voucher proponents said
Thursday, new legislation is being prepared that would allow the
program to be restored in the fall for the next academic year.
</P>
<P>
   This year the $5.25 million program provided scholarships to
about 4,000 children from low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Bolick, litigation director for the Institute for Justice,
a nonprofit public-interest law firm in Washington that argued in
defense of the voucher program, along with lawyers for the state,
said he was pleased that the court had left the door open to
reauthorizing the program and had not objected to financing
religious education.
</P>
<P>
   The case was brought by the Ohio Federation of Teachers and the
Ohio Education Association, assisted by the American Civil
Liberties Union, People for the American Way and Americans for the
Separation of Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Lynn, executive director of Americans for the
Separation of Church and State, praised the court for striking down
the program. But he said the court ``completely missed the point on
the church-state issue,'' adding, ``The justices struck a blow at
the heart of the First Amendment and ignored clear and unambiguous
language in the state Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the nation's only other broad voucher system is in
Milwaukee. Wisconsin courts have no objections on church-state
grounds. But in Maine, courts ruled against vouchers for those
reasons. In Minnesota, parents can get a tax credit for vouchers.
In Arizona, people who donate money to programs that provide
vouchers can take a tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Florida recently passed a statewide voucher system for private
and religious schools. It is to go into effect later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph P. Viteritti, research director of the Wagner School at
New York University who has written a book on school choice issues,
predicted that the Ohio law would be challenged again, which could
provide enough conflicting litigation for the United States Supreme
Court to consider a voucher case.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, opponents of the Milwaukee program took the case to
the Supreme Court, but the justices declined to hear it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0427 </DOCNO>
