r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     05-27 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL'S GEORGE ON THE EDGE WITH MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Goodrich, the ABC producer of Sunday's
Indianapolis 500, as he has been for the last 14 Memorial Day
weekends, doesn't sweat the thought of having his press credentials
suddenly jerked out from under his headset.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's one of the comforts of having your network pay the
racetrack about $10 million a year for the immunity/privilege of
televising the event. But Goodrich's track record is by far a
greater gauge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, every other media outlet seems to be subject to the
whims of Tony George, the Indy Racing League's grand pooh-bah and
Indianapolis Motor Speedway president who last week tried to block
the entrance of Sports Illustrated. George was mighty upset that SI
motor sports writer Ed Hinton, whom he called ``a danger to himself
and to the sport he covers,'' wrote an eight-paragraph story in the
May 10 issue about an IRL crash in North Carolina that killed three
spectators nearly a month ago. Even more disrespectful, in George's
mind, was an Associated Press photo showing one of the victims in
the grandstands, under a blanket and in a pool of blood.
</P>
<P>
   George's censorship edict lasted two days. A threatened boycott
of the race by several major newspapers caused even more bad
publicity for the irrational IRL ring leader, who admitted he was
trying to make a statement and picked this way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In light of King George's attempt to teach the media beast a
lesson, will there be second thoughts about how Goodrich and ABC
approach Sunday's race? Will Goodrich err on the side of even more
conservatism and tether his replays? Will he be on the phone with
Boss-Hog Tony to get his OK on information released about injuries
and/or deaths?
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich claims that won't happen as ABC does Indy for the 35th
straight year and 12th time live. And we're going to have to
believe him on this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never come to us and criticized us, and we have
criticized things about the IRL,'' Goodrich said from Indianapolis
this week. ``Some owners have said, `Gosh, why did you say this
about that?' But the IRL, never, and no one from Indy has said
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about any repercussions after George's actions last week,
Goodrich said: ``I don't think so. We think it's an isolated case
that doesn't involve us as long we do responsible journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   And will Goodrich address the SI-George controversy in the
telecast?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How it's done: Goodrich says there's a simple philosophy he's
had for years about the way TV should handle a race accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``You journalistically cover what has to be covered and do it in
good taste,'' he said. ``You don't over-replay things. I've tried
to do what I thought was best. And that's really the only guideline
I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaels, who will be included in this year's Indy race
coverage for the first time as a host, has similar thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to document it, but I don't think you can go in with
a hard-and-fast rule because each situation is unique,'' Michaels
said. ``You use your instincts and see how much is too much and how
little is too little.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels remembers all too vividly when he, Jackie Stewart and
Chris Economaki covered the Indy time trials for ABC in 1982, as
Gordon Smiley was killed in an horrific collision that left so much
debris Indy's Accident Prevention Committee could only make a guess
as to what caused it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie described it as an `aircraft accident,''' Michaels
said. ``Total disintegration of the car and Smiley was almost in a
rag-doll mode in the middle of the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did, as I recall the scene becoming so graphic, is
take one replay to see how he lost control, and that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be judicious. It's a tough choice for a
producer because you have to show how something happened and in
effect, you've just begun the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Your opinion counts: Hinton's story on the May 1 North Carolina
tragedy under the headline ``Fatal Attractions'' pointed out how it
was the second time in nine months that spectators were killed as a
result of crashed open-wheel cars. He suggested ``they should
ignite a public outcry that doesn't dissipate until track officials
devise a plan to prevent further episodes of this nature.'' Hinton
also wrote that the best solution to curbing these tragic accidents
is simple but unlikely to happen: The IRL and CART should stop
competing on high-speed oval tracks _ but that would cause the IRL
to ``rethink how it does business.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hinton is considered by many to be a fair and unbiased
reporter, IRL driver Eddie Cheever, last year's Indy 500 winner,
has sided with George on this controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times in my career I've been troubled by a magazine or a
journalist taking an opinion that's not in good taste or
responsible,'' Cheever said this week. ``I've often felt a
one-sided story is for people with a different agenda. From the
view of a racing driver, I think most coverage of that tragedy was
done tactfully and factually, but what Sports Illustrated did was
in extremely bad taste and I believe the journalist was borderline
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've offered to discuss things in the past with him, but he
hasn't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Business matters: While the Hinton-George debate was going on,
the IRL was doing business with ABC and its new sports chief,
Howard Katz. ABC announced a five-year extension in the
neighborhood of $65 million of its contract with the Indy 500. The
previous contract would have ended after this race.
</P>
<P>
   Although ratings for the Indy 500, as well as other IRL and CART
events, have not increased despite the popularity of racing, the
thinking is the sport will be more valuable if rumors of the IRL's
union with CART come to fruition. It would be in ABC's best
interest if they did.
</P>
<P>
   The last Indy 500 involving CART drivers had an 8.4 rating. Last
year's race, the fourth straight with the IRL-only, no-name
drivers, was a 5.5.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will also do the CART race this weekend, the Motorola 300 in
St. Louis, at noon Saturday. Paul Page, who has been at the last 25
Indy 500s and broadcast the last 10 for ABC, will be at this race
instead. Bob Jenkins, who's doing all the IRL races this year,
calls his first Indy 500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Tom Hoffarth's media column appears Fridays in the
Daily News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3661 or sptmediaaol.com.
</P>
<P>
