<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-W.VA-PRATT-MAYORAL-AR     05-27 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-W.VA-PRATT-MAYORAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG VOICE OF ALARM SHAKES UP AN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRATT, W.Va. _ Excitement seems to reach this little town
southeast of Charleston about every 90 years or so, not counting
the fire truck that rolled into the Kanawha River a few summers ago
because someone forgot to set the emergency brake.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912, a 75-year-old union organizer named Mary Harris Jones,
known as Mother Jones, was imprisoned here on charges of inciting
riots after protesting unfair labor practices by coal mine owners.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Wesley B. Nugent, a freshly minted graduate of
West Virginia University who wants to be mayor of Pratt, a sleepy
little town where two-thirds of the 680 residents, the incumbent
mayor among them, are senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks around town, including the mayor, Paul D. Slack, 69,
who is seeking a third two-year term in the June 8 election, say
Nugent's candidacy is a noble but fanciful idea. Nothing wrong
here, they say, other than the need for a few new sidewalks and
maybe an after-school program for children.
</P>
<P>
   But Nugent, 22, who majored in international relations, looks
around and sees a town flirting with extinction _ not this year,
perhaps, but eventually.
</P>
<P>
   As the elderly die, he wonders whether Pratt, with its tidy
little homes and streets, will stay viable or fade away as so many
other places in rural America have when there are no jobs to keep
people from moving away. The pattern is especially acute in West
Virginia, where state officials have been adjusting to a once
mighty coal industry that now relies less on men than machines.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Pratt, which has no traffic lights or parking meters,
shells of old businesses line Route 61, leaving Fowler's Market,
Sherry's Beauty Shop and a gas station as the town's only
commercial enterprises. Most of the working residents drive to jobs
in nearby Montgomery or even to Charleston, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Nugent says, he sees himself as a symbol of
small-town renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to portray myself as that way,'' he said, sitting on a
bench not far from where Mother Jones was imprisoned. ``I've
traveled extensively and was always drawn back here, to the
beautiful scenery and the close-knit community. So many West
Virginia students don't come back to be a community leader. They
don't find it challenging enough or competitive enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As a reflection of his desire to change that cycle, Nugent said
he turned down job offers in North Carolina, Pennsylvania and
elsewhere to run as the Republican candidate for mayor, opposing
two Democrats, Slack and Gary Fields, 51, a former mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the younger residents welcome Nugent's enthusiasm.
``He's a pretty smart guy,'' said Jason Veazy, 23, a
great-great-grandson of the town's first mayor, Oscar Veazy. ``He
could be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Slack, a retired power company salesman, bristles at the idea
that he has lost what it takes. Gearing up for a door-to-door
campaign, he has a letter for distribution, detailing the $1.5
million in state and Federal money he has helped secure for various
public works programs in town.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was especially proud of the part he played in helping
neighboring towns without a sewer system hook into Pratt's. The
connections are scheduled to open next year, and that means four
additional jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, a gas company manager, said he planned to emphasize his
skills as a communicator, which he might need. In his two terms in
office, from 1988 to 1992, voters tried to remove him after he and
his wife were charged with spraying Mace on a neighbor's child and
trying to run over people with a truck. Those charges were dropped
but they pleaded no contest to drunken driving charges and were
sentenced to a day in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Trying a political comeback two years ago, Fields lost to Slack,
166 votes to 95.
</P>
<P>
   To Nugent, the visions of his opponents are too narrow to suit
the future needs of the town. He talks about Federal money that
could be secured to buy a fourth police cruiser, repave streets and
clean up the eyesores on Route 61 ``as a way to draw business in.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else, he fears, the town might go the way of Mrs. Carney's
Boarding House, where Mother Jones was locked up. Several years
ago, town officials got it listed as a National Historic Landmark.
But efforts to raise money to restore it failed, and the house was
razed.
</P>
<P>
   In its place are garden apartments where many older residents
live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
