<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-PINAULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESIEGED GUCCI WINS ONE IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Gucci Group NV triumphed Thursday in the latest round of
a struggle to thwart a hostile bid by its bigger rival, LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton, when a Dutch court upheld Gucci's sale of
shares to the French department store group
Pinault-Printemps-Redoute SA.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in the Netherlands, where Gucci is incorporated,
removed the last obstacle to Gucci's plans to transform itself into
a major multibrand luxury manufacturer. But the court invalidated
another weapon Gucci had used to help repel LVMH, a plan to sell
shares to employees, and ordered Gucci to compensate its workers.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH refused to acknowledge defeat. ``All options are open to
us,'' said James Lieber, an American lawyer who is a senior LVMH
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   He said LVMH was considering whether to ask another Dutch court
to declare the Gucci deal with Pinault-Printemps illegal, as well
as long-term maneuvers that would utilize LVMH's 20 percent stake
in Gucci to subvert the company's efforts to become LVMH's main
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci shares fell 6.5 percent to 64.50 euros ($68.37) after the
announcement. Pinault-Printemps shares rose almost 6 percent to
169.80 euros ($179.29). LVMH shares fell almost 8 percent to 257.10
euros ($271.47).
</P>
<P>
   The hearing in the Netherlands became necessary after Gucci
announced the deal to sell a 40 percent stake to Francois Pinault,
owner of Pinault-Printemps. Bernard Arnault, the LVMH chairman,
asked the court to invalidate the Pinault-Printemps deal. At the
same time, LVMH offered $81 a share, which compared with $75
offered by Pinault-Printemps, for the Gucci shares it did not own.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover struggle began last January after LVMH amassed a
sizable stake in Gucci, then unsuccessfully sought representation
on Gucci's board.
</P>
<P>
   The Gucci fight reflects deep changes overtaking European
business, pitting two French billionaires against each other for
control of an Italian fashion house with a corporate base in
Amsterdam, the Netherlands, and a chief executive, Domenico De
Sole, who is a Harvard-educated lawyer advised by Wall Street
investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Pinault has pledged to help transform Gucci into a major
competitor to LVMH. In response, Arnault has launched bitter
personal attacks on Pinault and Gucci management. The two
executives are now suing each other in French courts over
accusations by Pinault that Arnault slandered him.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole, the architect of the Gucci defense, said he was
delighted by the court's decision. ``We will move ahead with
Pinault,'' he said. Michael Zaoui, a Morgan Stanley banker who
helped Gucci's defense, said ``we look forward to advising them on
their expansion plans.''
</P>
<P>
   De Sole said Gucci will use the $3 billion Pinault-Printemps is
paying for its Gucci stake to shop for luxury brands, most notably
in Italy and France. In March, Pinault paid $1 billion for Yves
Saint Laurent and a stable of French perfume brands that are
expected to be sold to Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   But LVMH's Lieber promised that LVMH would exploit its unusual
position as Gucci's largest minority shareholder and biggest
competitor to make life difficult. The drop in Gucci's share price,
he said, reflected a ``transfer of value'' from Gucci to
Pinault-Printemps. He said the deal gave Gucci no advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see whether they can deliver our primary goal, which
is to create shareholder value,'' he said. ``We will be there if
the strategy fails, if they don't have the staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence Hernandez, a luxury goods analyst at ING Barings in
Paris, said Gucci faces big challenges in integrating Yves Saint
Laurent and expanding. She called it ``a big change in the mix of
activities for Gucci.''
</P>
<P>
   LVMH officials said they had not decided whether to seek a seat
on Gucci's board. But De Sole ruled that out, saying: ``There was a
war over that, and they lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ford, Gucci's chief designer and De Sole's main helper in
restoring Gucci's name in the fashion industry, said the struggle
had been ``extremely time-consuming in the last five months.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about LVMH's potential for disruption, he replied,
`'Clearly, they might not be your shareholder of choice, to be
honest. But we're going to be running the company in a completely
autonomous manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
