<SLUG> BC-ITALY-FERTILITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIL TO REGULATE FERTILITY PROCEDURES GAINS IN ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to remove contradiction from 1st sentence of 8th graf.)  
(gm) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Italian parliament has approved a draft law on
assisted fertility that sets prison terms for doctors who use
donated sperm to perform artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which was passed by the lower house on Wednesday,
requires Senate approval before becoming law. If approved, it would
be Italy's first law regulating artificial fertility procedures. It
has already reawakened a passionate debate over medical ethics,
family values and individual liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also signals the growing political influence of
the Roman Catholic Church on social and moral issues. The bill
includes nonbinding language, sponsored by a conservative Catholic
member of parliament, committing lawmakers to re-examine abortion,
which was legalized in Italy in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives hailed the bill as a victory for law and order.
``The Chamber of Deputies took a big, decisive step forward to help
Italy emerge from the Wild West of assisted procreation,'' former
Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, who leads the center-right
opposition in parliament, said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Italy now has no laws governing artificial fertility practices,
and many critics complain that some private clinics operate without
supervision or ethical restraints. Italy has 298 fertility clinics,
of which 97 are private.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the draft legislation was sponsored by members of
the governing center-left coalition, who hoped to impose some
control over doctors and also broaden the choices for couples in
need of fertility treatments. But conservatives in parliament, as
well as some Catholic lawmakers who broke with the majority over
this issue, reworked the draft, imposing harsh restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Veltroni, who leads Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema's
party, Democrats of the Left, called the law ``fundamentalist'' and
vowed that it would not pass in the Senate. It is not clear whether
he will gather enough votes to block it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill bans couples from using donor sperm or eggs, bans the
long-term freezing of embryos and sets the maximum age at which
women can seek hormone treatments at 45. Italy is one of the
leading countries in post-menopausal pregnancies, most notably
because of the work of Dr. Severino Antinori, who in 1993 helped a
61-year-old woman become pregnant through artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Antinori said that if the law passed, he would
leave the country. ``This is most illiberal law in the world,'' he
said. ``It is an ethnic cleansing against procreation. I can work
anywhere in the world, but what will happen to all those infertile
women? Where are they supposed to go?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is a strong anti-abortion movement in Italy, but in a
country where 90 percent of the population consider themselves
Catholic, it is a movement dominated by the Catholic Church. The
church, which has not given up the fight to ban abortion, has also
lobbied heavily to prohibit in-vitro fertilization, because
embryos, which the pope views as human beings, are sometimes
destroyed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The new law does not ban in-vitro fertilization, but it limits
its use. No donor eggs or sperm are allowed. Doctors can create
only three embryos in the effort _ usually, doctors make more than
six _ and they must be implanted within three months and cannot be
frozen for later use. If the father dies after a woman has banked a
frozen embryo, she cannot seek to become pregnant as a single
mother.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows unmarried couples, as well as husbands and wives,
to seek fertility treatment, but only after they can prove they are
sterile. Single women, however, are almost entirely left out.
Italian law already prohibits adoption by single women. The draft
law would ban single women from almost any fertility procedure,
from artificial insemination to in-vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed the lower house because it was supported
by the center-right opposition, and also by small Catholic parties
that usually vote with D'Alema's center-left party but defected
over this issue. The number of parties with ties to the Catholic
Church has grown since the old Christian Democratic Party collapsed
and splintered in the wake of corruption scandals in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats were pro-Catholic, but often failed to
block legislation that the church opposed, most notably in the case
of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in power, and they did for nearly half a century, the
Christian Democrats had to form alliances and coalitions, seeking
compromises right and also left. Now, no single party can claim to
represent Catholic interests fully, and each must compete to
attract Catholic voters and the favor of bishops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
