<HEADLINE>
INDIANA, LIKE KNICKS, HAS HURTING CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Rik Smits trudged off the Market Square Arena
floor, grimacing enough for his teammates to notice. He is not in
constant pain, but the 7-foot-4-inch center does have something in
common with Patrick Ewing: he's hurting.
</P>
<P>
   The big toe on his left foot, which was fractured in Indiana's
first-round sweep of Milwaukee, has limited his mobility and raises
concerns about how effective he can be in a four-of-seven-game
conference finals with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My broken toe is giving me a lot of trouble,'' Smits said
Thursday after practice. ``I was hoping the days off would help it,
but I don't really feel that it has. I feel my weakness now is back
to the basket, pivoting. Recovery time is not as good as it used to
be. Jumping ability is pretty much gone, not that I had much to
begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It will probably be the summer before the feet start
feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers will have had a week off before Game 1 on Sunday. To
break the monotony, they are planning a scrimmage on Friday for
their fans. Smits has used the time off to rehabilitate the injury,
but the concern over his health is building as the series
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in the Eastern Conference semifinals, Smits had his
way with Ewing. Falling for the simplest of shot fakes, Ewing was
unable to guard Smits effectively. The Knicks went out in five
games mainly because Indiana exploited the mismatch in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Smits averaged nearly 15 points in the three games
the teams played, but he is averaging only 11.1 points in the
playoffs. His highlight came in Game 2 against the 76ers, in which
he scored 25 points and played 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have often made other Pacers beat them offensively,
allowing Smits to get into a flow rather than allowing Reggie
Miller to catch fire from the perimeter. ``It is usually because
they had single coverage on me and I got a chance to do some stuff
in the low post,'' Smits said. ``This season they would keep a
forward on me and keep Ewing down low. Sometimes they had Larry
Johnson on me, and that gave me a big height advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bad toe, Smits may see a new defensive look thrown at him
on Sunday. Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy has entertained the idea of
using the reserve Chris Dudley to defend Smits, whose offensive
repertoire always gives Ewing problems. Dudley would most likely
take Kurt Thomas' spot in the rotation, thus freeing up Ewing from
having to guard Smits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'd relish to be given that challenge down the
stretch to stop him,'' Dudley said. ``But I have confidence in him
as well,'' he added, referring to Ewing. ``I do hope I get put in
that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's pivotal Game 4 at Madison Square Garden, Smits
erupted for 14 points in the final quarter as Ewing struggled to
gain any rhythm on both sides of the floor in only his third game
back from the wrist surgery. Van Gundy wants to avoid a repetition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smits really hurt us in the fourth quarter of Game 4, and
that's why we started Dudley against him when we played him this
season,'' Van Gundy said. ``Smits made a great adjustment against
Chris and scored pretty easily the second time we played him at
Indiana, so now it's up to Chris to adjust to what Smits did to
him.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
