A4119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-CONSOLIDATE-NYT     05-27 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CONSOLIDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTELSMANN IS REORGANIZING RANDOM HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (Eds: Please note that this story is on the financial front page,
not the DISNEY-BOOK story, which moved earlier).  
 (af)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a year after Bertelsmann AG bought Random House and
blended it with existing holdings into the nation's largest
publishing house, top executives moved Thursday to consolidate
several long-established publishing units. Critics called the move
a triumph of corporate organization over literary values.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, including the abrupt departure of a top Random
House publisher and editor, came despite earlier assurances that
the union of Random House with Bertelsmann's Bantam Doubleday Dell
would not erode the independence of the units.
</P>
<P>
   When Bertelsmann announced its plan to buy Random House last
year, Peter Olson, who later became chief executive of Random
House, said: ``The various imprints and divisions are not going to
be affected by this. If anything, our hope is to enhance their
effectiveness and independence.''
</P>
<P>
   With its announcement Thursday, Random House said it intended to
merge eight of its publishing units into four groups or divisions,
including a combination of Bantam Books, the mass-market paperback
publisher with roots dating back to 1945, and Dell Publishing, the
half-century-old publisher of popular authors like Danielle Steel
and Thomas Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Olson said that reorganization was taking place partly to
reflect current trends in the book market such as rising sales of
religious books and the waning popularity of the mass-market
paperback, ``which is not a growth format.'' By merging units like
Bantam and Dell in one group and Doubleday and Broadway Books in
another unit, Olson said that Random House was reorganizing to
create ``two mass-market powerhouses.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the reorganization was ``complete for the
foreseeable future'' and that any layoffs would be decided by the
heads of the individual units.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a cost-driven exercise,'' Olson said. ``It's more
about marketing effectiveness. We have a lot of publishers
competing for limited shelf space and the attention of our buying
and reading public. And the question is how can they be most
effective. That's what drives it. What we want to do is grow
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics reacted with apprehension, saying that the
consolidation of publishing units could reduce competition for
books because there could be fewer bidders for the manuscripts of
authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply distressed,'' said Jean V. Naggar, a literary
agent in New York who is the president of the Association of
Authors' Representatives. ``I think that once again the market for
authors has shrunk. I think diversity has been diminished. And I
think that all of the fears that we had when this merger was
announced have come home to roost.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the reorganization, one prominent executive, Carole Baron,
Dell's longtime publisher and editor, lost her job. William
Shinker, the publisher of Broadway Books, announced his resignation
earlier this month and has declined to comment on the reasons for
his departure.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization could affect the often delicate relationship
between authors and publishers. Critics said they thought it unfair
that Ms. Baron had to leave the company at a time when she appeared
to be on the brink of a major success. Dell is days away from
publishing a book that is expected to sell more than a million
copies _ ``Hannibal,'' Thomas Harris' third book in the Hannibal
Lecter series.
</P>
<P>
   Mort Janklow, the literary agent for Harris and for Danielle
Steel, said Ms. Steel might object to the change because Ms. Baron
had edited the author's books for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be a problem for them I think,'' he said,
adding, ``This has created great consternation among many authors
because they have great affection for Carole.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who is ordinarily reluctant to be interviewed, issued a
short statement criticizing the reorganization. ``Relieving Carole
Baron as president and publisher of Dell in order to follow some
mechanical blueprint of corporate structure is a mindless waste of
the company's best resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Random House said it had tried to find Ms. Baron a new position
within the company, but Ms. Baron said she was leaving the company
after 18 years simply because ``my job doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Random House is home to more than 50 imprints that publish
popular books for adults. Those imprints are then organized in
groups such as the Random House trade group or Knopf Publishing.
Within these various fiefs, editors have the power to bid on and
acquire manuscripts, sometimes in competition with other publishers
that are part of the same corporation.
</P>
<P>
   That system has provided authors more opportunity to find
markets for their work and, often, higher advances _ which is why
literary agents are wary of the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, Random House said it would also combine two
religious imprints, Water Brook Press and the Doubleday religious
unit, as well as two trade book publishers, Anchor Books _ which
was founded in 1953 _ and Vintage Books. The Vintage Anchor
publishing division, as it will be called by Random House, will
become part of Knopf Publishing Group.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, views at Random House were mixed on how these various
publishers would blend. Stephen Rubin, who was appointed president
of the new union of Doubleday and Broadway, said both units would
maintain separate editorial staffs while sharing functions such as
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   However, Irwyn Applebaum, the publisher of Bantam Dell
Publishing Group, the new hybrid of Bantam Books and Dell
Publishing, said he was not prepared to address the issue of
editorial identities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not choosing to talk about the editorial role of how we're
going forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a natural concern about shrinkage and loss of
freedom,'' he said. ``But here at Bantam we're going to define
freedom in a manageable form. And to me that means nurturing the
most interesting books that we can publish. The consumer doesn't
care whatever imprint is on a book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
