<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS FALLS AGAIN AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For the 10th straight year, Pete Sampras concluded his
annual business trip to the French Open, the only Grand Slam where
his greatness has yet to leave its imprint, in Sisyphean fashion.
He fell from contention early, and he fell hard.
</P>
<P>
   After scratching and clawing his way through the opening round
in a four-hour 18-minute marathon against the unrelenting if
unremarkable Juan Antonio Marin of Costa Rica, the second-seeded
Sampras imploded in the second round Thursday afternoon, ground
into submission, 7-5, 1-6, 6-4, 6-3, by Andrei Medvedev of Ukraine,
the former top 10 player now ranked 100th.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was not only an out-and-out failure in his attempt to
win his first French Open, a milestone that would prove him a
champion for all surfaces at long last, he also failed to land the
Slam title that would tie him with Roy Emerson's record of 12 major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   For an athlete who measures his years in Grand Slam victories,
Sampras' 1999 season is now half over, and he has come up empty
after skipping the Australian Open and skidding to a premature stop
here in the second round, the same juncture he exited from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Roland Garros, the name Sampras is still synonymous with
futility. And the player, now 28, is still trying after a decade
after his initial visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He returned quite well, made me hit a lot of low volleys,''
Sampras said of his opponent. ``I just couldn't get it going. I
just need to go out and play my tennis, slip and slide a little
bit, but just keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   He waved off the suggestion that he could use a clay court guru
like Jose Higueras, the coach who girded Michael Chang for this
title in 1989. ``I know what I need to do,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Medvedev did what he needed to do Thursday.
Unlike Sampras, the Ukrainian calls clay his favorite surface and
reveres Roland Garros, where he went to the round of 16 as a
qualifier in his 1992 debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is the greatest player on earth that's ever picked
up a tennis racquet, but I don't think he played his best tennis
today,'' said a gracious Medvedev, whose sole victory against
Sampras in six prior meetings was in their only encounter on clay.
``So I really cannot be unbelievably proud for what I've done. I
mean, it's not his favorite surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay is not the surface of choice for Lindsay Davenport either,
and Davenport, the second-seeded woman here, was nearly ousted
Thursday by a clay court natural, 16-year-old Justine Henin, a
Belgian who won the first WTA Tour event she entered two weeks ago
in Antwerp and won the junior French Open crown as a wild-card
entrant in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Now ranked 121st, and in her first-ever main draw slam event,
Henin used her racquet like a blowtorch, sending a blaze of
one-handed backhand winners past the frustrated Davenport. Henin
didn't fizzle until she served for the match at 5-4 of the third
set. There her adrenaline ran out, and Davenport managed to squeak
through to the third round, 6-3, 2-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like I'm glad to be still in the tournament,''
Davenport said. ``It was a struggle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   She handled her struggle better than eighth-seeded Mary Pierce,
who fell to Conchita Martinez, 4-6, 6-3, 6-3, and ninth-seeded
Nathalie Tauziat, beaten 6-2, 6-4 by Gala Leon Garcia of Spain. But
Sampras' struggle was the most monolithic.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was close to tearing the head off his racquet by the
time he'd elbowed a final forehand return into the net, a flummoxed
Sampras vowed to bear no hard feelings toward the Slam event that
perennially trips him up despite his record six-year reign at No. 1
from 1993-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some ways I might put too much pressure on myself
here,'' Sampras said, ``but I'm never going to give up on it: I've
won all the other majors; this is the one that's my biggest
challenge, and challenge is something that there's no question that
I need right now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sampras' game does not fit well with the challenge posed by
Roland Garros, where the deadening effect of the red clay on his
high-impact style has been further exacerbated by the use of
softer, fluffier balls for this year's event. Sampras also admitted
that he came into this tournament with less than ideal preparation:
a 10-5 match record, 3-2 on clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a little bit of everything, not having won many
matches this year, playing on clay, you know, it's a struggle for
me,'' Sampras said, ``and I guess I'm thinking about that when I'm
playing, that I'm struggling, just struggling really to find my
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It eluded him Thursday just as it has since his first visit in
1989, with the exception of his stellar run to the semifinals in
1996, a campaign he launched just three weeks after the death of
his former coach, Tim Gullikson. That year, Sampras tackled and won
three five-set matches.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, hobbled by a perverse refusal, or inability, to slide
and glide on the grit underfoot, and so unsure of his tactics that
he second-guessed himself into 10 double-faults and 61 unprovoked
errors, Sampras moped through the final set like a man who wanted
to be anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a numb feeling,'' Sampras said. ``I really feel
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the five-setter against Marin on Tuesday was to
blame for Thursday's lethargy. Instead, he pointed an accusatory
finger at his game in general: it's come undone at just the wrong
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes on clay my instinct is not the right call,'' he
said. ``On clay I get into a hole where I kind of want to serve my
way out of holes.'' His five aces provided insufficient artillery
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
