<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS' JACKSON HAS KNICKS HUDDLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ There was chaos on the court for the New York
Knicks about this time last year as a tipped ball was swung calmly
from the Pacers' Chris Mullin to Mark Jackson to Reggie Miller in
three swift motions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the scattered and harried Knicks, Chris Childs found
himself lost in this Bermuda triangle of Indiana talent, failed to
rotate on defense and left Miller alone on the wing, right in front
of Spike Lee, to deliver a 3-pointer with 19.3 seconds left in Game
4 of the Knicks' second-round series against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shot that tied the score and led to an overtime victory
by the Pacers at an eerily quiet Madison Square Garden. It was a
deflating moment the Knicks could not overcome as they went on to
lose the series in Game 5. And it was one more illustration of how
Jackson _ who was marginally open, but smartly deferred to Miller
for the wounding shot _ has continually displayed the right snap
decisions against the Knicks over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as the Knicks prepare for the Pacers in Game 1 of
the four-of-seven-game Eastern Conference finals on Sunday, they
are searching for a way to dilute Jackson's impact as a 3-point
shooter, post-up threat and precision passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think definitely the Jackson matchup has been critical,''
Coach Jeff Van Gundy said Thursday after a three-hour film and
practice session at the Knicks' facility at SUNY-Purchase. ``It's
up to us as a staff to have a better plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to develop a strategy for a boxy point guard who can
bang and post up either Charlie Ward or Childs like he is bumping a
car door shut. At 6 feet 3 inches and 185 pounds, Jackson is an
earth mover as a point guard. Van Gundy could put the 6-7,
235-pound Larry Johnson on Jackson, but that experiment resulted in
a 3-point binge by Mullin _ who was shadowed by Ward _ during the
Knicks' loss to the Pacers on May 2. More likely, Ward and Childs
will be left to guard Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real good and real strong,'' Ward said. ``I guess we're
going to have to lift more weights this week and get stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   From his planted post position, Jackson can whirl inside for a
shot; or, if he is double-teamed, he can find an open man without
so much as craning his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to double him,'' Childs said. ``I'll guard him by
myself, and if he's going to beat us in the post then let him beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs is feeling a little invincible these days as the guide to
the Knicks' up-tempo bench and as half of the defensive clamp on
opposing point guards. Childs and Ward shut down Tim Hardaway in
Round 1 and Mookie Blaylock in the second round. But Jackson has
done more damage to the Knicks in recent years than either Blaylock
or Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two seasons, including the playoffs, the Pacers are
8-3 against the Knicks. In that span, Jackson has averaged 8.7
assists and 12.3 points a game and has made 16 of 28 shots from
3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shoots extremely well against us,'' said Ward, who has been
slow at times to close out on Jackson. ``It's not so much something
we do or don't do. He just plays well against us. I've seen him
play against other teams, and he misses shots.''
</P>
<P>
   There is something about the Knicks that seems to put an extra
edge on Jackson's mentality. He was a Knick until he was traded by
Pat Riley on the ground that his defense was not tough enough. But
what Jackson lacks in speed and quickness _ which are on display in
his backup, Travis Best _ he makes up for in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's instincts on both sides of the ball have been critical
to the Pacers' success in this year's playoff push. Jackson has
done to Milwaukee and Philadelphia what he has done to the Knicks
time after time. In the Pacers' seven playoff games, Jackson has
averaged 10.6 points and 10.3 assists a game and has done a lot
with limited shot taking by making &QC; 9 of 18 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is similar to us,'' Ward said. ``Chris and I aren't
looking to score much. We're looking to penetrate, and we don't
shoot that much. He's similar to what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson has done it much better. In the playoffs, Jackson
has 72 assists to 19 turnovers. Ward and Childs have combined for
68 assists to 23 turnovers. But Ward and Childs seem undaunted by
their task. This series is a chance to further change the
perception that the Knicks' big weakness is at point guard. Last
year, particularly in Game 4 against the Pacers, that was evident.
</P>
<P>
   With clarity of thinking, Jackson made the right decision under
pressure, and Childs, assigned to Miller at the time, did not.
Childs does not need a game film to remind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see it,'' Childs said. ``I know what I did
wrong. I rotated to Mark and gave Miller an open 3. I know that
can't happen again.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
