</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-KINGSTON-TECHNOLOGIES-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A COMPUTER-AGE WINDFALL, WORKERS REINVENT THEIR LIVES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOUNTAIN VALLEY, Calif. _ Within the modest headquarters and
computer memory factory of the Kingston Technology Co. is a living
laboratory in how people react when blessed with windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, nine years after Kingston's start, its Taiwanese
immigrant founders, David Sun and John Tu, sold 80 percent of the
company to the Softbank Corp. of Japan for $1.5 billion. The
founders _ now fabulously wealthy _ generously set aside $100
million from the sale's proceeds for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in January 1997, they lavished $38 million upon 530
employees, giving them bonuses that ranged from $2,000 to six
figures, depending on seniority, pay and performance.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, an additional $20 million was divided among 700
workers, and a like amount is expected to be distributed to more
than 1,000 employees in July.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the bonuses, the founders gave workers memos advising
them to pay off debts and become homeowners. While most employees
paid some heed, many also went on spending sprees.
</P>
<P>
   Most have remained on the payroll and are intensely loyal to the
founders. But some have seen the bonuses as a once-in-a-lifetime
way out of a humdrum existence _ not that work at Kingston is all
that humdrum. Thanks to the founders' management style, the company
still has free Friday lunches, 100 percent health coverage and
unstinting retirement benefits _ Kingston puts $3,000 a year in
each employee's 401(k) and then matches employee contributions of
up to $2,000, dollar for dollar.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that cries for independent financial advice.
Asked what his counsel would be for the employees, Mark D. Wilson,
a certified financial planner in Newport Beach, Calif., said, ``I'd
like them to realize what a wonderful gift they've been given.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed with the founders that home-buying and eliminating
short-term debt would be prudent uses for the money, but he pointed
out that several of the employees had invested some of the money
for their children but had not put any of it away for their own
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he would advise workers to invest half the bonus,
after taxes, for their own retirements _ a far better use than
whittling down mortgages, he said, because mortgage interest is
tax-deductible. For a young employee, he added, a long-term
investment could grow enough to allow an early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He was not surprised, however, that some recipients did not see
things that way. ``Since they are young, I'd expect them to take
the money and run,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bonus was a turning point for Darin Farriola, a four-year
product manager at Kingston who had written a screenplay after
hours. ``There's no more excuses,'' said Farriola, who quit
Kingston in 1997, shortly after receiving a bonus equal to a
half-year's pay.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring that he could cover his bills for awhile, Farriola
began looking for investors to bankroll his film. ``The only thing
I ever directed before was traffic,'' said Farriola, who is 32.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he succeeded in attracting backers for the film,
``Ivory Tower,'' a drama about corporate America. A private showing
for Kingston employees at a local theater received raves. Recently,
broadcast rights were sold to the Showtime cable network, which has
scheduled the film to run sometime in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kingston was the best opportunity I ever had in my life,''
Farriola said. ``But it's not a world I'd go back to.'' The film
work, he said as he worked in his office on stories for movies yet
to come, ``is something I want to do the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the financial planner, applauded his choice. ``Following
your dream is wonderful,'' he said. ``Whether he's successful or
not, it's not blowing the money.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Jaime Chavez, whose family in Mexico City owned a moving
company, America initially was a mean place. For four years, he
endured $4-an-hour landscaping jobs. Digging ditches made his hands
sore, and he got so tired that he fell asleep during lunch breaks.
After asking a boss about unpaid overtime wages, Chavez said, he
got the pay but lost the job.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His fortunes improved after a cousin working at Kingston told
him of a one-day job that soon became full-time, paying $9.50 an
hour. Now, Chavez is the company's maintenance and warehouse
supervisor, managing 12 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give you opportunities even if you are inexperienced,''
said Chavez, 34, who sends his parents in Mexico up to $1,000 a
month from his paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   His bonus, which moved him and his family solidly into the ranks
of the middle class, became the down payment on a 2,200-square-foot
home in Costa Mesa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly a good move, Wilson said. It also meant that his wife,
Marisol Chavez, who is now pregnant with the couple's third child,
did not have to return to work as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself lucky,'' Chavez said. ``What I have right
now is thanks to Kingston.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year before Kingston awarded its first bonus, the mother of
Roseanne Carrillo, a sales manager, died unexpectedly from liver
disease. Ms. Carrillo, 40, borrowed $9,000 for a modest funeral and
buried her mother in an unmarked grave. ``That weighed very heavy
on my mind,'' Ms. Carrillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus paid for an elaborately engraved, $5,000 green
limestone grave marker. ``It was my tribute to her,'' said Ms.
Carrillo, whose father, 69, is Kingston's oldest employee.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the workers are referrals from others, and many
family members work alongside one another. She intends to use her
next bonus to buy the plot next to her mother's.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary payouts instill security, said Ms. Carrillo,
who also erased her credit-card debt. ``Money is such a big worry
for a lot of people,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Tim R. Westland, 35, Kingston's Webmaster, said the
bonus made him a cash-and-carry consumer, free of car payments and
monthly credit card bills for the first time in a decade. And he
intends to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   From a bonus worth more than a year's salary, Westland put 40
percent aside for the education of his 10-year-old daughter. He
also indulged a little, replacing two older-model cars with new
ones and taking a return trip to Maui with his wife, Marci, and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortune smiled on me,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brandi LaPlante, 29, does not expect in her lifetime to see
another paycheck as big as her sole Kingston bonus, which totaled
three times her annual salary. Even so, Ms. LaPlante, who joined
the company at age 20 and in her six years there worked up to a
senior network sales job, left Kingston in 1997 for a start-up
concern where she expected better opportunities for advancement.
She cried on her last day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   A few months before she received the bonus, she and her husband
had moved into a new home. Much of the bonus went toward
improvements like carpeting, wood floors, custom landscaping and a
patio cover. The couple also opened savings accounts for each of
their three children.
</P>
<P>
   Other money went toward new cars _ and a $1,500, 32-inch
television, a gift for Ms. LaPlante's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I've seen my dad cry,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
