</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TECH-HOTELS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT DESK? SEND UP A COMPUTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We may know how much to slip the bellhop for
dragging the bags upstairs, but the modern hotel evokes a new
question: How much do you tip him for tech support?
</P>
<P>
   Consider Alex Peshev. He showed up at my room about 9 p.m.
toting his wireless headset (used for communicating with the front
desk) and found me muttering expletives as I struggled to work the
television-based e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can trouble-shoot almost anything,'' Peshev said patiently.
No surprise. He has a bachelor's degree in computer science and
spends his days as a network administrator, which apparently will
be a job requirement for the hotel worker of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to a night's stay at the W Hotel, a stylish new 31-story
hotel in downtown San Francisco that is your home office away from
home. Like dozens of hotels trumpeting themselves as high tech, it
offers Internet access, in-room computers and a wireless keyboard
to send e-mail via TV, and thus reinforces the tension that
computer and Internet users feel everyday: Sometimes technology is
a panacea, and sometimes a real pain.
</P>
<P>
   The science-fiction-like amenities at the W were fine on the
surface, but they required elbow grease, too. The radio crackled
with static at first, Web access through the television was fuzzy,
and the wireless telephone signals crossed when I tried to call the
front desk. I wound up having an interesting conversation with a
Norwegian fellow named Andre in room 1415.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is this?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, who is this?'' I responded cleverly. It turns out that
Andre Backen is a computer game maker from Oslo and an Internet
aficionado. It took him a half-hour to figure out the Internet
access in his room. I should have sent Peshev, but he was probably
busy upgrading the Unix computer in baggage storage.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the W had just opened, and at least it's trying,
although in that regard it is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, hotels are slowly adding technological
amenities _ making data ports a default setting, offering a fax
machine in every room, making high-speed Internet access as
pertinent as a pillow mint. After all, what good is fresh breath if
you can't e-mail home about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way from when there was a telephone by the
side of the bed and maybe `Magic Fingers' where you put 25 cents in
and get a little shake,'' said John A. Marks, president and chief
executive of the San Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation waxed philosophical. I mourned the fact that
hotels no longer seemed a haven for business travelers but rather
an enabler for the workaholic. Should a night's stay at a hotel
really have to involve user manuals?
</P>
<P>
   Marks countered that hotels are justifiably responding to market
demand. He argued that travelers _ particularly executives _ cannot
afford to fall behind.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but they will in most places. Big chains like Hyatt,
Marriott, Wyndham and Hilton are just dipping their toes into
technology with pilot projects: computers in some rooms or
high-speed Internet access at one or two hotels like the Hyatt San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block is cost. Jonathan M. Tisch, president and
chief executive of Loews Hotels, said it could cost several hundred
thousand dollars just to add high-speed access lines to a single
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   As for the W, owned by Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide,
the gadgets offered a marked upgrade over a traditional business
night's stay _ once they were up and running. The $199 room
included a CD player (with remote control and a selection of CDs
delivered from the front desk), a VCR (movies cost $10), Compaq
computer (I had to order it specially) and a Hewlett-Packard color
printer/fax/copier (in 15 percent of the rooms).
</P>
<P>
   Had I been so inclined, I could have started an e-commerce
business, filed for an initial public offering, then retired rich
in time for cocktail hour.
</P>
<P>
   Among other features of the W was a sensor that detected if I
was in the room. Hotel employees carry a device that looks like a
garage-door opener. When pointed at a door, it indicates whether
the room is occupied, so an employee knows whether to enter.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, I was immersed in a moment of pure gadget bliss: I
was listening to a Dave Matthews CD on the stereo, using the TV to
switch back and forth between the New York Knicks game and surfing
the Net, and sipping a Heineken from the minibar. Like I'm not
executive material.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest asset of the place was its employees (and that
isn't the beer talking), about a half-dozen of whom stopped by
during the evening to make sure everything worked smoothly. I
promise you, if Mother Teresa had a degree in engineering she
couldn't have been as helpful. At one point, two employees came by
just to refresh my towel supply and offer me a fortune cookie _
which required no tech support to open.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the high-tech hotel was a net plus, even if it does
have some electronic bugs to work out. That was something that even
Peshev, the bellhop/computer scientist, conceded. For example, he
hates to wear his wireless headset to communicate with the front
desk, because the ear piece is too small.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night my ear hurt so much, I couldn't even sleep,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he added, ``technology can be more of a headache
than a help.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounded tense. I tipped him $5. But maybe what he really
needed was a quarter for the Magic Fingers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
