<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-TRUCKS-ART-2TAK     05-27 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-TRUCKS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRAND NEW BOOK WITH A FAMILIAR COVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kan.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLTON, Kan. _ How important are General Motors' full-size
pickups? Check out Wall Street's numbers or Main Street's traffic.
These are the company's most popular products, with some 700,000
sold annually.
</P>
<P>
   They are lucrative, returning several thousand dollars in profit
for each one sold. They also serve as the basis for a fleet of big
sport utilities that account for another 400,000 even more
profitable sales.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, with demand exceeding supply, GM hopes to ramp up
production this year to build an additional 300,000 trucks and
sport utilities. If it succeeds, it could end up with $30 billion
in annual sales off this platform _ enough to rank 34th on the
Fortune 500 list, exceeding the value of all the microchips from
Intel, all the drugs from Merck, all the sodas and snack foods from
Pepsico.
</P>
<P>
   GM can use a runaway hit, particularly as it loses its longtime
ranking as the world's largest industrial company. Ford will claim
that title this week as GM spins off its huge Delphi parts
operation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer anecdotal evidence to raw numbers, look at the
streets of Middle America. In this town of 4,000 a half-hour from
Topeka, where the economic focus long ago shifted from farming to
commuting, one thing has not changed. A lot of the folks here,
where I grew up, like Chevy pickups.
</P>
<P>
   You see them in many of the parking spaces around the monumental
county courthouse, and they are lined up at the Dairy Queen
drive-through. Along some streets there seems to be a pickup
wearing a Chevy bow tie in almost every driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks account for 6 of every 10 sales at Clark Chevrolet
Oldsmobile Pontiac Buick, said Bernie Clark, who co-owns the
dealership with his two brothers, and 90 percent of those trucks
are full-sized Silverados. Once relegated to the farm or job site,
they now routinely provide family transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Like most truck owners, Clark's customers are stubbornly loyal;
about 80 percent are repeat buyers. Over the years _ the family's
ties to the dealership date to 1947 _ some customers have driven
away in as many as 15 pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Such loyalty helps to explain why GM has changed everything
about its full-size trucks except the essential way they look. The
styling is new, sure, but even a trained eye must look twice to
tell a '99 from a '98. GM says this is by design, and it marshalls
surveys indicating that many consumers find the Ford F-Series too
cute and the Dodge Ram too brutal. But one has to believe that
others, after plunking down as much as $33,000, want the neighbors
to know they've sprung for something new. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And under the skin, the Silverado certainly is new. After a
10-year run for the C/K series, GM put its might into making its
replacement a success. It came up with new engines, a new frame,
new brakes. The crowning touch is a classy cabin that makes the
competition's look, well, truck-like.
</P>
<P>
   The Silverado isn't perfect but it is genuinely pleasant, and it
sets new standards for pickups. Not that the C/K is bad _ it
remains, despite its dated design, one of the more pleasant pickups
to drive _ but the Silverado handles more securely, accelerates
more briskly, consumes less fuel and provides far more comfort and
convenience. (The C/K is still being built in two plants, alongside
Silverados, to fill fleet orders.)
</P>
<P>
   There are five engine choices: The 4.3-liter V6 is carried over,
but the 4.8- and 5.3-liter V8's are new, though based on the
aluminum Corvette engine. There is also a new 6-liter V8 for
three-quarter-ton trucks. And, for those who want to move
mountains, there is a 6.5-liter turbo-diesel V8 producing 440
foot-pounds of peak torque. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices start around $16,000 for a plain two-wheel-drive model.
The truck I drove in Kansas, a two-wheel-drive LS 1500 extended
cab, had a list price of $26,692; in New York, I had a
four-wheel-drive LS priced at $32,203. I also tested an
extended-cab GMC Sierra SLT _ except for its nose, the Sierra is
much the same _ with a rounded Sportside bed; its sticker was just
over $33,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All three test vehicles were equipped the way most of these
trucks will be, with the 5.3-liter V8. It is a honey, another
example of how GM has put new life in old pushrod designs. Ford,
meanwhile, has switched to more modern overhead-cam V8s that will
allow it to cut truck emissions next year to the stricter level
required of cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevy engine is smooth and gutsy, producing 270 horsepower
and peak torque of 315 foot-pounds, and it ought to please most
everyone from hockey mom to cattle hauler. The torque curve has
been flattened for more pulling power at a wider range of engine
speeds. And in the event of coolant loss, the truck can be driven
to a garage. The four-speed automatic transmission (a five-speed
manual is standard) felt rugged and workmanlike; it offers a
``tow/haul mode'' that shifts at higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel-drive pickups are available with a transfer case that
engages all four wheels automatically when it senses a loss of
traction, along with a standard four-wheel setting and a low range
for serious muck.
</P>
<P>
   Silverados now come with either of two types of steering.
Lightweight two-wheel-drive models get a nimble rack-and-pinion
system, while four-wheel-drive trucks have a conventional
recirculating ball that can stand up to heavy use. The latter
system can seem numb at times, but I still prefer it to the
detached feel of the Ford or the Dodge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Silverado still handles like a pickup, but its behavior is
honest and balanced. The chassis keeps you aware of its limits,
giving you confidence in how the Silverado will behave in any
maneuver. A dignified highway cruiser, the truck is quite
maneuverable in town and unruffled on winding back roads. Some cars
should do so well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with the brakes, never before anything to brag
about. There are disks front and back with 40 percent larger pads.
A four-wheel anti-lock function is standard. Stops are sure and
straight and the pedal is firm now, not spongy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ride, too, is car-like, refined and quiet on all but the
worst roads. The optional firm-ride suspension indeed stiffens the
ride, but it adds little to the handling.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the improvements, the cabin stands out; a lot of thought
went into the needs of pickup owners. The outside mirrors are large
and handsome and the inside door handles are big and easy to grip.
The glove box is split into compartments (even the cargo box can be
divided by thirds).
</P>
<P>
   The gauges are large and legible, and there is an information
center that relays up to 18 messages, from ``cargo lamp on'' to
``transmission fluid hot.'' The knobs are durable and the buttons
are big and chunky. Window and lock controls are lighted at night,
just like those in a nice sedan. Power is retained after the key is
switched off, letting you roll up the windows or catch the end of a
song. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are some sour notes, but they are fairly minor. There are
so many pieces to the dash and console that there seems to be seams
everywhere; imagine trying to clean up a spilled Coke. The optional
CD player is down near the center console, far from the radio. The
ashtray, lighter and two auxiliary outlets reside under a
top-hinged lid that hides them even when open.
</P>
<P>
   The usual GM cruise control switches on the turn signal stalk
are awkward to use and, typically, the cruise had trouble holding a
set speed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One design oddity: The most prominent place on the overhead
console is a blank panel. Buttons for GM's Onstar driver service
may eventually go there; meanwhile, it is a waste of prime real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   And, shucks, I have more gripes: The door locks engage as the
truck moves, but when you stop you have to unlock them manually;
once parked, a handle pull should suffice. The console box is huge
and deep, but the lid won't stay open. And, as usual with GM
vehicles, the combination of daytime running lights _ I'm not a fan
_ and automatic light control can be baffling: Are the headlights
on, or the driving lights? Do I need to switch the lights off, or
will they go out on their own? Why do the lights have to be on if I
want to idle inconspicuously?
</P>
<P>
   My favorite thing about the Silverado may be the optional
six-way power seats, which just could be the best ones GM has ever
put in an American vehicle. Accommodating for anyone up to World
Wrestling Federation size, they are highly adjustable and good
looking. The headrests are good and the lumbar adjustments are
great, taking the lower backrest from pillow-soft to rock-hard.
Safety belts are mounted to the seats, simplifying access to the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the back seats in extended cabs have ranged from
unpleasant to ridiculous. But here finally is a rear seat where
adults can sit in reasonable comfort. The bottom cushion is 2.4
inches longer, and there are four more inches of leg room.
</P>
<P>
   The backrest is slanted, not bolt-upright, and there are even
two headrests, a cup holder and ventilation ducts. There is a price
to pay for this spaciousness, though; the cab's longer roofline
looks a bit ungainly.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from these nits, does the Silverado have an Achilles heel?
Aside from the conservative styling, there's just one thing: Until
fall, you cannot buy a Silverado with a fourth door. This is no
small oversight: Buyers of extended-cab pickups have expressed a
clear preference for two small rear-hinged doors. The Silverado's
third door, on the passenger side, always seemed to be where the
cargo and passengers were not.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that it wanted to be sure it had a safe, solid
design before it brought out a four-door Silverado. That is
commendable. But after Dodge brought out its Ram Quad Cab, Ford
quickly matched it, then offered four doors for all its trucks.
GM's tardiness points up, once again, how slow reaction times force
the company to keep playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, GM has done a remarkable job of fundamentally remaking
the modern full-size truck. But it will rest at its peril; already
Toyota is showing off its new, full-size Tundra. Toyota's last
effort, the T-100, was, uncharacteristically, a disappointment, but
this is a company that doesn't make the same mistakes twice.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time Ford and Dodge remake their big trucks in a few
years, you can bet they'll have dissected the Silverado down to the
tiniest screw. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: One door short of star status. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
