<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-OPERA-HOUSES-2T     05-27 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-OPERA-HOUSES-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RAGE FOR OPERA HOUSES (OH, AND OPERA, TOO)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Sheila Melvin is director of Shanghai operations for the United
States-China Business Council and a freelance writer.  
 By SHEILA MELVIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Regionalism has been a powerful force in China
from time immemorial. In the best of times, cities and provinces
sniff disdainfully at one another and implement policies to guard
their resources from their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst of times, regions battle for land and power. Under
the People's Republic, regionalism has been contained but not
conquered.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial governments still set up checkpoints to keep locally
grown grain from being transported to other provinces. Cities
require taxicab fleets to buy locally produced cars and foreign
companies to purchase locally made parts. Every coastal city has to
have its own deep water port and every province its own airline.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of the strangest regional competitions yet, every
city that can afford one suddenly wants its own world-class opera
house. Now leading the competition is Shanghai, whose gleaming
Grand Theater opened last September. The $150 million building in
glass and steel is up to the minute technologically, with French
design, German construction, a Japanese stage and American
acoustics. A separate concert hall is to open by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, in Shenzhen, a city of four million people that
just 15 years ago was a fishing village, an opera house is also to
be completed by Jan. 1. In Nanjing, bidding is under way for a
grand theater to serve the province of Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed at being left behind, the central government in
Beijing has resuscitated plans for a National Grand Theater, with a
2,500-seat opera house as well as a concert hall, a theater and a
chamber auditorium. Expected to cost $400 million, it will be twice
the size of the Shanghai Grand Theater.
</P>
<P>
   But although the project has been planned since 1958 and was
most recently scheduled to be completed in 2002, two rounds of
bidding have so far failed to produce a design on which China's top
leaders can agree. Beijing's inability even to settle on a
blueprint, while Shanghai presents operas, orchestras and ballets
from around the world in its new theater, has further fueled the
barely civil rivalry between China's two major cities.
</P>
<P>
   When the failure of the second round of bidding was announced,
Internet chat rooms in which young residents of Shanghai and
Beijing usually insult each other's soccer teams suddenly turned to
a discussion of opera houses. While many from Beijing attacked
Shanghai for selling out to foreigners with its French design,
those from Shanghai crowed that Beijing shouldn't even try to
construct an opera house because anything it builds would
inevitably collapse.
</P>
<P>
   (Beijing's new train station, touted as the best in Asia when it
opened in 1996, has been crumbling at an alarming rate, and six
people involved in its construction have been arrested for
corruption.)
</P>
<P>
   This sudden urge to build ``grand theaters'' with opera houses
as their centerpiece has little to do with opera, and few pretend
otherwise. Rather, an opera house is seen as a means for a city
``to distinguish itself not only for its industry, commerce and
finance but also for its culture,'' in the words of Chen Zhili,
when she was deputy secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Party
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Every city in China wants to be seen as modern and cultured, and
an opera house is considered the best way to project that image.
Yet once an opera house is built, the spotlight necessarily turns
from the structure itself to the opera that is supposed to fill it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been waiting for an opera house since the beginning of
New China,'' said Zhou Xiaoyan, the director of the Zhou Xiaoyan
Opera Center at the Shanghai Conservatory of Music. ``And now
there's an opera house, it's a great thing, and we are happy. But
an opera house is not a piece of jewelry to look at. It must have
things inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhou is one of a small group of Chinese artists who have
devoted their lives to Western opera. Educated by Italian Catholic
missionaries, she developed a love for opera early in life. She
went to Paris to study voice in 1938 only to find herself trapped
there during the German occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to China in 1947, she became famous as a teacher and
singer, performing a repertory of Chinese and Western songs. But
when the Cultural Revolution began in 1966, her love of opera and
her overseas education caused her to be labeled a ``cow ghost and
snake spirit'' and sent to the countryside to live in a ``cowshed''
for intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   She never sang again after the Cultural Revolution, but she was
rehabilitated in 1976 and resumed teaching, and in 1988 she founded
her opera school. Though well past retirement age, she is at her
piano, teaching, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The tortuous path of Ms. Zhou's career reflects the brief
history of Western opera in China. It was introduced in the early
part of this century by Chinese students who had studied in Japan,
Wang Shiguang, the president of the National Opera and Ballet in
Beijing, explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really there are two roots to China's modern opera, the
800-year history of Chinese opera and the introduction of European
opera by Chinese students,'' Wang said. ``Then with World War II
and other special circumstances, modern opera developed. European
opera is easier to move people's hearts, and Verdi is good for
encouraging struggle, too. So many more modern operas were
created.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, China's first opera company was established in Beijing.
It consisted mainly of amateur artists who had worked in
anti-Japanese propaganda troupes. Many musicians had left for
Taiwan with Chiang Kai-shek, so orchestras had to be rebuilt and
Western instruments acquired. Opera professionals from the
Tchaikovsky Institute in Moscow came to help, and soon China's
conservatories began to produce instrumentalists and singers.
</P>
<P>
   Several operas by Chinese composers were presented in the early
1950s, followed in 1958 by ``La Traviata,'' the first full foreign
opera staged in Communist China. (``La Traviata'' was also the
first opera staged in old China, performed by Russians at the Lu
Xun Theater in 1920. Its popularity undoubtedly stems as much from
that of its source, Dumas's ``Dame aux Camelias,'' which in 1893
became one of the first foreign novels translated into Chinese, as
from Verdi's struggle-inspiring music.) Opera continued to develop
in the early 1960s, with an emphasis on Chinese-created works,
until the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cultural Revolution was a catastrophe for us,'' Wang said.
``Everything we had done was ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   The catastrophe was nationwide. Shanghai's company did not
perform at all between June 1966 and May 1976. Recovery took
several years, and a generation of performers was essentially lost.
Since there were few opportunities in China even after the Cultural
Revolution, talented singers sought scholarships to study overseas
and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opera in China was like a desert until 10 years ago,'' said
Chen Xiaoqun, a young soprano who studied in Salzburg for six years
and recently returned to Shanghai. ``Now things are more open. We
perform more foreign operas. Before it was all Chinese. We have
more exchanges with the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chen, like Ms. Zhou and Wang, supports the construction of
new opera houses in China as essential for furthering international
exchanges and allowing Chinese audiences to see how opera should be
performed. But she also believes that much more needs to be
invested in maintaining companies and mounting productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it a waste if we invest so much in hardware but nothing
in software?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her complaints are echoed by virtually everyone in opera, from
performers to administrators. Financing for the arts is an
emotional issue in every country, but Chinese operatic artists have
sounder reasons than most to complain. The base monthly wage of an
opera singer in Shanghai is less than $50, the price of the
cheapest ticket to hear Jose Carreras when he sang at the Grand
Theater last September. (The best seats cost nearly $200.)
</P>
<P>
   Even with supplemental bonuses factored in, opera singers in
Shanghai do not earn enough to live on, and the situation in
Beijing is no better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Shanghai Opera has an audition, nobody tries out,''
Ms. Zhou said. ``They make no money, so they are all singing in the
Hilton. If you have no money, you can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, of the National Opera and Ballet, says that the government
has reduced his financing every year since 1988. What he did not
say, but many opera professionals do, is that the government has
not reduced its control in proportion to its financing. China's
opera companies, like all its performing arts troupes, are relics
of the Maoist system in which art was completely subservient to
politics but artists were completely supported by governments.
</P>
<P>
   In the current era of ``reform and opening,'' this system has
been recognized to be unsustainable. ``Reforms'' have included
merging arts groups, significantly reducing their subsidies and
requiring them to give annual tests to performers. Arts troupes
continue to labor under burdensome production quotas, and are not
allowed to release employees they do not need.
</P>
<P>
   Government approval, usually from the culture and propaganda
bureaucracies but sometimes from the Communist Party itself, is
still needed for new productions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most performing arts companies devote all their
energies to finding ways to meet salary and pension requirements
for current and retired employees. They open schools, run
restaurants and travel agencies or go into real-estate development.
Trying to do something new or creative that might sell tickets is
almost certain to invite opposition from one leader or another, so
few bother.
</P>
<P>
   Performing arts companies with their own theaters can mount
small productions cheaply, but neither the National Opera nor the
Shanghai Opera has its own theater. Theaters in both cities belong
to different bureaucracies and must be rented; staging an opera or
even presenting one in concert costs much more than it earns.
</P>
<P>
   Performing in public is thus the last thing many performing arts
groups choose to do. (The production quotas required to retain
subsidies can be met by staging small shows in schools and
factories.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem is so serious that before the Grand Theater was
built, the Shanghai Opera staged one major production a year; last
year it presented two, both co-productions with overseas companies.
As it stands now, nearly all opera in Shanghai is produced and
sponsored by an opera lover named Bonko Chan, who manages a
state-owned freight-forwarding company. Chan is also supporting one
of the two productions so far scheduled for this year, ``The Flying
Dutchman,'' with the Dusseldorf Opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bonko stops, opera stops,'' Ms. Zhou, of the Shanghai
Conservatory, said.
</P>
<P>
   Although corporate sponsorship of the arts is certainly
desirable, it should ideally not depend on one well-connected
person at one company. Opera artists, knowing the role tax
incentives and foundations play in supporting opera in the United
States, dream aloud of such a system here. Some also hope that
professional producers will enter the market, but they probably
will not so long as any mid-level bureaucrat can order a production
to be rewritten, recomposed, recast, redirected or canceled for any
reason, as is now the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, government-arranged co-productions, which draw
financial support from foreign governments and corporations, seem
sure to remain the primary vehicle for staging opera in both
Shanghai and Beijing. This arrangement appears at first glance to
be a good thing, and many support it. Co-productions bring
international directing, conducting and singing talent to China:
perhaps the best example is the ``Turandot'' staged last September
in the Forbidden City in Beijing by the Maggio Musicale Fiorentino
under the baton of Zubin Mehta and the direction of Zhang Yimou.
(The production, taped for video, will be telecast by PBS on June
9.)
</P>
<P>
   But some artists argue that co-productions deny Chinese singers
any opportunity to sing principal roles; principals are almost
always brought from overseas, and local principals are forced to
sing in the chorus. Audience expectations are raised by
co-productions, a good thing in itself, but in the current
situation, those expectations can never be met by a domestic
production.
</P>
<P>
   So nobody wants to see domestic productions, nobody wants to
stage them, and they will never improve. The situation is even
worse for Chinese-composed operas, which have little chance of
being staged in a co-production format.
</P>
<P>
   Few artists actually oppose co-productions; on the contrary,
most value the opportunity to work with outside professionals. But
many object to the government-controlled system that makes a
co-production the only viable way to stage an opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has the talent,'' said a Beijing-based director. ``We
could do it. But because of these cadres, these leaders, it's a
problem of the entire system. The officials' power is too great and
there is nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Western opera in China has come a long way in a short time. But
if the nation's costly new opera houses are to be anything more
than pieces of jewelry, in Ms. Zhou's term, the system that governs
opera must be changed, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese city that truly wants to distinguish itself for its
culture and win the battle of the opera houses might do so with a
little more support for human talent and a little less interference
in artistic affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
