<HEADER>
A4143 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIXENBERG-PHOTOGS-2TA     05-27 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIXENBERG-PHOTOGS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING OUT THE GRAVITAS IN A TOUGH HOUSING PROJECT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 David Hay is a playwright and journalist who writes about the arts
from Los Angeles.  
 By DAVID HAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a cool spring Sunday in the Watts section of
Los Angeles, the photographer Dana Lixenberg watched as Monique
King Cade, a longtime resident of the Imperial Courts housing
project, looked through a box of 50 postcard-size portraits. They
were taken six years ago by Ms. Lixenberg during the second Rodney
King trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. King Cade, known as China, barely looked at the photograph
of herself, in which, her hair in rollers and sporting large gold
earrings, she appears lost in thought. She chose instead to look at
others Ms. Lixenberg had photographed and talk about their fates.
Some were dead; some, she said, were ``in the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Amsterdam and now a commercial photographer in New York,
Ms. Lixenberg, 34, had returned to these two-storied, faded-aqua
apartments to pass out invitations to her first American
exhibition, which opened at the Los Angeles Center for Photographic
Studies in Hollywood on May 15 and remains on view through June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Her 40-by-30-inch Imperial Courts portraits, hanging alongside
another series taken in 1998 of women living in a homeless shelter
in Jeffersonville, Ind., look disconcertingly formal. They are
indicative of a new documentary photography that is turning its
back on the often graphic, verite styles of the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Lixenberg's photographs are reminiscent of the more
studied approach used by photographers earlier in this century.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strong tradition, practiced by, among others, a
photographer Ms. Lixenberg admires, August Sander, who set out to
catalogue all of German society. The tradition has strong roots in
this country, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-American photographers, such as Prentice Herman Polk
working in Tuskegee, have a long history of photographing ordinary
people in formal circumstances,'' said Carla Williams, the
co-author with Deborah Willis of ``The Black Female Body in
Photography.''
</P>
<P>
   But George Pitts, the director of photography at Vibe magazine,
pointed out that Ms. Lixenberg exhibits more than formalism in her
work. ``She brings a degree of compassion while at the same time
maintaining a detachment,'' he said. ``This allows a viewer to come
into the picture and understand the emotions of those she's
photographing.''
</P>
<P>
   These qualities appealed to Aleim Johnson, a member of
Knowtribe, the arts organization sponsoring Ms. Lixenberg's
exhibition. ``Her photographs allow for a complex understanding of
lives which are dehumanized on an almost daily basis,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for these portraits came in late 1992, when Ms.
Lixenberg went to Los Angeles for the Dutch weekly Vrij Nederland
to photograph a story on the aftermath of the riots. When she
departed, she said, she felt she ``had only documented the
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, when asked to submit some photographs to an
exhibition organized by Foto Festival Naarden in her homeland, she
decided her subject would be portraits of gang members in Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Los Angeles, Ms. Lixenberg enlisted the help of
Tony Bogard, a community activist who was involved in negotiating a
truce between the Crips and the Bloods gangs. (He was murdered in
January 1994 by a member of the P.J. Watts Crips.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony asked me if this was some kind of sociological project,
and he wanted to know what they were going to get out of it,'' Ms.
Lixenberg recalled. She had no idea how the project would evolve,
but she assured her interrogators that she was determined to
produce photographs that would challenge the prevailing view of a
daily life made up solely of one violent act after another.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing weeks, Ms. Lixenberg drove to the Imperial Courts
every afternoon, parked her car in the same small lot across 115th
street, set up her camera and took portraits.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I felt like `the other,''' she recalled. ``I was
this white girl, and I represented a group of people that they
didn't view in such a positive light, but I didn't feel any
negative attitude toward me.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``not being a white American certainly made a
difference.'' This not only helped her gain acceptance but
influenced her own perceptions. ``I was not weighed down by certain
preconceptions that a photographer from some other part of Los
Angeles might have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning in Watts, Ms. Lixenberg decided to abandon what
was then the staple of the documentary photographer, the 35-mmr
single-lens reflex camera. She wanted to work with the larger
format 4-by-5-inch field camera, which meant using a tripod. The
time involved in composing each picture insured that everyone would
be a full participant in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a 35-millimeter camera, people never know when they are
being photographed,'' Ms. Lixenberg said. ``This can make a great
picture, but it might not have anything much to do with the
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lixenberg avoided placing her subjects against backdrops
laden with meaning _ a graffiti-covered wall, for example. ``I
didn't want to use the environment to illustrate a point,'' she
said. ``I wanted to cut everything away and focus on the person.
And I hoped that viewers, even if they didn't know anything about
Watts, would see these photographs simply as portraits and then
take the time to really look at the people in them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since she undertook this project, Ms. Lixenberg has
acquired a considerable reputation as a commercial photographer.
Her celebrity assignments for magazines have ranged from Sean
(Puffy) Combs to Barbara Walters to Paul Bowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard to reconcile,'' Ms. Lixenberg said. ``It's not
that I've made money on the Imperial Courts pictures, but they have
done a lot for me. They helped deepen my work. Yet when I go back
there, I can see that life hasn't moved forward much in six
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that time has stood still in Watts. When, on her return
visit, Ms. Lixenberg showed Wyking West his portrait, he was
startled. Taken during a period of high gang tension, the
photograph shows West, known by his neighbors as Lee-Capone,
wearing an unbuttoned black shirt that exposed a silver chain and
ring of large beads.
</P>
<P>
   West projects a range of seemingly contradictory emotions:
defiance, anxiety, as well as a sense of fleeting peace.
</P>
<P>
   But on this Sunday afternoon, West, who now works the night
shift at a bookbinder, was more casually dressed in a short-sleeved
checked shirt, a golf hat pulled low and baggy blue jeans. As he
examined his own portrait, he remarked, ``I look better now than
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ms. Lixenberg approached a group of young men washing a
car. Looking through the portraits, they reacted, often humorously,
to the superficial changes, especially weight gain or loss and the
passing of gang fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But like everyone else encountered this day, they asked Ms.
Lixenberg for one particular photograph, that of Spider, fatally
wounded some years before. This image of an almost smiling young
man, wearing a shower cap and taking a drag from a cigarette, is
how they wanted to remember their friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
