<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4145 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-RICE-NCAA-REGIONA     05-27 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-RICE-NCAA-REGIONAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COACH WAYNE GRAHAM USHERS IN A NEW RICE AGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Wayne Graham was growing up on Houston's North Side, his
father had the most marvelous job he could imagine. He was an usher
at Rice Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' said Graham, now 63. ``For a kid then, it was
just fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the heyday of the Jess Neely football teams, and I got
to go to all the games free. They were a national power and they
had huge crowds, and I got to see all those guys ... George
Walmsley, Tobin Rote, Froggie Williams, Dicky Maegle ...
</P>
<P>
   ``And I always thought, `Gee, what a wonderful place, what a
great school. How could it ever get any better than this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Owls' athletic programs have hit a bump or two in
the intervening years. But ever since Graham returned in 1992 as
the baseball coach, one vestige of the old days has been rapidly
gathering steam:
</P>
<P>
   In college baseball today, Rice is about as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   When the Owls (52-11) open play as the top-seeded team in
Lubbock today, they will be appearing in their fifth consecutive
NCAA regional baseball tournament. They finished the regular season
ranked first, first, second and third nationally in the four major
polls and swept through the Western Athletic Conference tournament,
running their three-year record in that venue to 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, they have won 230 games and produced
four first-round draft picks. The 1997 team won the regional in
Lubbock to earn the school's first berth in the College World
Series in Omaha, Neb. This year's team has set a school record for
victories and is regarded as having a strong chance to produce
Rice's second CWS team. In addition, construction has begun on a
new $6.5 million stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Bubba Crosby, who last year followed Jose Cruz
Jr., Matt Anderson and Lance Berkman as first-round picks in the
amateur draft, ``They owe all of this to Wayne Graham; what he has
done at that school is amazing.''  &LR; subheds:Building a reputation
When he enrolled at San Jacinto College, a two-year college, four
years ago, Damon Thames wasn't thinking much about Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in this \RHouston\S area, I had heard of him,''
said Thames, the Owls' senior shortstop. ``I knew he had built up
the program at Rice, but that's all. But I sure learned a lot about
him when I got to San Jac. His name is all over that campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Transferring to Rice last year, Thames hit .424 with 36 doubles,
26 home runs and 115 runs batted in. He was named the national
player of the year by the American Baseball Coaches Association and
was drafted by the New York Yankees. He chose to return to Rice for
his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, everybody knows it's a great school,'' he said. ``But
the thing about this program is that you come here, and you get
better. Coach Graham has pretty much done it all _ he played
professional baseball, he was in the major leagues, he won all
those national championships \Rfive\S at San Jac, and you learn a
lot from him and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they're doing, and you just keep getting
better. Besides, I wanted to win a national championship, and I
think we can.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same thing Graham said seven years ago. It seemed a
quaint notion at the time, since the Owls had never won a Southwest
Conference title, let alone anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham had played college baseball for Bibb Falk at Texas
and later sat on the New York Mets bench next to Casey Stengel. He
had turned the San Jac Gators into the most feared junior college
baseball team in America, launching his run with a promising young
pitcher named Roger Clemens. Graham was not joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought we could win here \Rat Rice\S,'' he said. ``I
knew we would always have to pay more \Rin tuition\S for fewer
players; that we would probably not have any depth, and there would
be no margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough school academically, and I knew we would not have
access to some of the most promising recruits because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But \Rassistant coach\S Jon Prather has done a superhuman job
in recruiting, and with Chris Feris, we have a very close-knit
staff. We work well together.''  &LR; subheds:Learning from top teachers
After his career at UT, Graham spent a decade in the minor leagues
_ seeing the world by bus, along with three years of winter ball in
South America. He made two brief trips to the majors with the
Phillies and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on his wall is a cherished memento _ a picture of him
receiving the ``most popular player'' award when he hit .316 with
the Dallas-Fort Worth Rangers in 1962 in the American Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I got it was because the guy who was really
the most popular player got called up to the majors,'' Graham said.
``But I learned a lot in those days. I played alongside guys like
Luis Aparicio and Jim Fregosi, and when I went to the Mets I spent
a lot of time sitting next to Stengel on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was amazing. Throughout the entire game he would be
pointing out little things that nobody else saw. After the game,
when the writers showed up, he would go into that mumbo-jumbo
routine that made him so famous _ but during the game he was all
business. And he knew a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you could say that anyone molded my coaching style, I
guess it was Falk. People now characterize me as being very blunt,
and that's the way he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the style, it works. Almost from the beginning _ with
the recruitment of Cruz and those who followed, the program got
better.
</P>
<P>
   For Graham, the pivotal moment came at the end of the '95 season
when the Owls _ making their first appearance in a regional _
rolled into Baton Rouge, La., and defeated host LSU twice, ending
the Tigers' season. Rice went on to lose in the regional finals to
California State-Fullerton, the eventual national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the defining moment for this program,'' he
said. ``After that, we knew we were headed in the right
direction.''  &LR; subheds:Visit to Omaha In '97, led by Berkman, who
hit .431 with 41 homers and 134 RBI, and Anderson, whose fastball
was clocked at 97 mph, that direction took them all the way to
Omaha and the CWS. The team's chances died in the opening game,
when LSU _ en route to a national title _ beat Anderson with a
ninth-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team was actually a little thin on pitching,'' Graham
said. ``Also, it was our first time up there. If we can get there
again, we may do better.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new regional-super regional format designed to favor
teams with strong pitching, the Owls _ with a starting rotation of
Mario Ramos (12-1), Jeff Nichols (13-2) and Kenny Baugh (10-2) _
could be in good shape. The fourth starter, Marc Gwyn (7-1), has
recently defeated seventh-ranked Baylor and won the final game in
the WAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham, who has worn uniform No. 37 throughout his career
because he saw Doak Walker play against the Owls a half-century
ago, retains the ability to think a little like that awe-struck
kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago,'' he says, ``a guy came up and shook my hand and
told me how proud everyone was of the job we were doing. It was
Froggie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. ``Froggie Williams''!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
