<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-DURHAM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINTON JUSTICE WITHDRAWS NOMINATION TO 9TH CIRCUIT COURT OF
APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washinton State Supreme Court Justice Barbara Durham is set to
withdraw her nomination to the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals,
telling Sen. Slade Gorton Thursday night that her husband is
suffering from a terminal heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Durham was recovering from eye surgery Thursday and was not
available for comment. It was not certain whether her husband's
illness would cause her to step down from the state Supreme Court
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Durham was nominated to the federal appellate court by President
Clinton earlier this year. It was part of an agreement between the
state's two senators and the White House aimed at ending a long
logjam in judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Under provisions of the deal, worked out by Gorton and White
House Counsel Charles Ruff, the GOP senator agreed not to block
judicial candidates backed by the Clinton administration. In
return, the White House agreed to nominate Durham, a conservative,
to the 9th Circuit and to give Gorton a role in choosing district
court judges.
</P>
<P>
   Top aides for both Gorton and Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said
that the agreement will remain in force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to Senator Murray's office and the White House,
and both express concern and sadness about the situation,'' said
Tony Williams, Gorton's chief of staff. ``What we suggested is that
Slade would like to provide a handful of prominent people to
consider as a replacement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Desimone, Murray's top aide, voiced general approval but
added that ``the eventual (9th Circuit) nominee would have to be
acceptable to both senators.''
</P>
<P>
   This marks the second time Gorton has been frustrated in an
effort to pick a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer he backed the U.S. District Court nomination of
Seattle lawyer Monty Gray. Gray was forced to withdraw, however,
after it was disclosed that as a student at Princeton in the 1960s,
he headed a student group that defended segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Durham, a self-described ``conservative Republican,'' faced a
confirmation battle, which she was favored to win. A legal advocacy
group, the Alliance for Justice, announced it would fight the
nomination on grounds of her ``inappropriately zealous advocacy''
of capital punishment and conservative rulings on workplace safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Justice criticized appearances that Durham made
on a Seattle radio talk show during her 1996 re-election campaign.
On one program, she discussed a ``notorious example'' of a
California death penalty case in which ``the liberal justices on
the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals'' granted a stay of execution to a
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Durham has been a state Supreme Court justice since 1985 and
recently completed a term as chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Senate has been slow to confirm
judicial nominees. Counting six nominations made Thursday by
Clinton, a total of 44 judicial nominees currently await a hearing
and vote by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Two local judicial nominations are currently before the
committee. Seattle attorney Ron Gould awaits confirmation to the
9th Circuit, and King County Superior Court Judge Marsha Pechman is
waiting for confirmation to the U.S. District Court bench. Pechman
was picked by Murray and Gorton to replace retiring U.S. District
Court judge William Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
has held up confirmations this year in an effort to force Clinton
to pick his nominee to a U.S. District Court vacancy in the
senator's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has pushed the nomination of Ted Stewart, chief of staff
to Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt. He is, however, strongly opposed by
environmental groups because of policies he pursued as Utah's
natural resources director.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said recently that he spoke with Clinton by phone to argue
for Stewart's nomination. Hatch has said in interviews that the
president assumed that his nominations were being held hostage to
Stewart's nomination ``and I did not disabuse him of that notion.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28 judges of the 9th Circuit _ five of whom sit in Seattle _
have become major shapers of environmental and social policy across
the American West.
</P>
<P>
   It was the appellate court that upheld Washington's law against
assisted suicides. The 9th Circuit recently ruled that the U.S.
Forest Service failed to conduct adequate environmental studies on
a sweeping land exchange with Weyerhaeuser. A three-judge panel is
currently considering whether to overturn a $5 billion damage
judgment against the Exxon Corp. stemming from the 1989 Exxon
Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   But the court has seven vacancies. And the Senate has moved at a
particularly glacial pace to fill vacancies on the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle trial lawyer M. Margaret McKeown had to wait more than
two years to be confirmed to the 9th Circuit. University of
California law Professor William Fletcher was confirmed after a
three-year wait.
</P>
<P>
   One 9th Circuit nominee from California, Judge Richard Paez, has
waited more than three years and has yet to get a confirmation
hearing. Gould was nominated to the appellate court in September
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
