<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATRICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TLC BEATRICE TO SELL REMAINING DIVISIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a quiet finale to what has been a sometimes stormy saga, the
remaining businesses of TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc. _
potato chips and ice cream _ will be sold by the end of the summer
and what was once one of the nation's largest black-owned companies
will close its doors.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Thursday that a Spanish company, La
Industrial Carbonica SA, a unit of Iberian Beverages Group, had
agreed to pay about $191 million for the ice cream business, which
is centered in Spain and the Canary Islands. TLC Beatrice's partner
in the business, Don Delfin Suarez, has an option to buy it at the
same price.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, TLC Beatrice is also seeking buyers for its
Tayto potato-chip business, based in Ireland. When both divisions
are sold, the proceeds will be divided among the shareholders in
TLC Beatrice. The company, formed by Reginald F. Lewis, who died in
1993, will cease to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Loida Nicolas Lewis, who has been chief executive of TLC
Beatrice since 1994, said she had mixed feelings about the final
days of the company her husband put together after a $1 billion
leveraged buyout in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis _ who wrote an autobiography called ``Why Should White
Guys Have All the Fun?'' _ became a symbol of African-American
business success, to the point that Michael R. Milken named him as
an example of junk bonds benefiting minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, it is closing a chapter on Lewis' life and
saying goodbye to a lot of business associates who were with the
company from the start,'' she said. ``At the same time, I am
relieved because I believe I have achieved the goals Lewis had when
he did the LBO, which was to maximize returns for the shareholders
while at the same time keeping the businesses he bought healthy and
ready for the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lewis, 56, took over the company a year after her husband
died of a brain tumor when he was 50. He had built TLC Beatrice
(the initials stand for ``The Lewis Company'') into a $2 billion
enterprise that did all of its business overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The company's holdings included Franprix and Leader Price, two
supermarket chains in France, and a wholesale food business there.
There were also beverage companies in Holland, Belgium, Thailand
and France, in addition to the ice cream and potato-chip
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lewis, an immigration lawyer by training, quickly moved to
trim down the TLC Beatrice operation. She laid off employees, sold
the company jet, moved the New York headquarters into a lower floor
in the building at 9 West 57th St., where her husband had a
spacious office with views of Central Park, and by 1997 decided to
sell the supermarkets and the wholesale division.
</P>
<P>
   The leveraged buyout had left the company with a mountain of
debt, and proceeds from the sale were used to pay down that debt,
she said. Last year, the company had sales of $322 million.
</P>
<P>
   After Lewis died, the company was sued by one of its biggest
investors, Carlton Investments, which was a partnership formed by a
group of former Drexel Burnham Lambert executives. The partnership
had feuded with Lewis over what it termed his excessive
compensation, and the lawsuit challenged a $22.1 million payment he
received in 1992. Mrs. Lewis agreed to settle the suit and returned
about $15 million to the company because it was ``in the best
interest of the shareholders,'' she said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said that suit was totally without merit because he
earned his compensation,'' she said. ``What he took, he earned. As
far as I am concerned, he paid for it with his life. I was totally
indignant that they would not acknowledge that.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern for the shareholders led her to liquidate the company's
remaining assets, she said. About 51 percent of the company is held
by Mrs. Lewis and her two daughters, ages 19 and 26. ``It's now 12
years since 1987,'' she said. ``Lewis and his investors came
together in 1987, and now in 1999, it's time to get out together.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how well the various investors had done, she recalled
something her daughter said recently, regarding the sale. ``My
daughter said Dad would say, `Mom, go on with your bad self,''' she
said. ``It means I hit a home run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
