<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIR SUGGESTS YOUTH SHOT BY POLICE WAS OUT TOO LATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Thursday that
the shooting of an unarmed 16-year-old boy by a member of the
Police Department's Street Crime Unit appeared to have been an
accident, and he questioned what the youth had been doing out on
the streets of the Bronx after midnight in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the youth, Dante Johnson, and a friend ran from
three uniformed officers who had approached them early Wednesday
morning because the officers had thought the youths might have been
be armed, Safir said, ``You have to wonder why they're running, why
they're out at 12:30 at night hanging out with a group of people
with criminal records.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks drew an angry response from Johnson's family, who
said the commissioner appeared to be blaming the victim. He
remained in critical but stable condition Thursday at a hospital in
the Bronx with a gunshot wound to the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people are out late at night in the Hamptons and no one
questions what they're doing at 12:30 at night,'' said the Rev. Al
Sharpton, who held a news conference with members of Johnson's
family outside the hospital. ``The issue is not whether or not
Dante should have been home. He had a right to be on that street,
he had a right not to be shot, he had a right not to be presumed to
be a criminal. And that is the issue: not what he was doing, but
what was the policeman doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Safir did offer an apology of sorts for the shooting, which will
be reviewed by a grand jury. ``If it in fact turns out to be an
accidental shooting, I'm certainly sorry; it was an accident,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the incident began when three officers from the
Street Crime Unit, who were patrolling the Morris Heights section
of the Bronx, saw Johnson and a friend, Kyle Thompson, 16, standing
near a large crowd. The officers thought they saw one of the young
men adjusting his waistband, leading them to suspect that he was
armed, police said.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers approached the youths in an unmarked car,
police said, they ran away. Officer Michael Fraterrigo, 27, and
Sgt. Terrence O'Toole, 41, jumped out of the car and caught
Thompson on a highway overpass. The third officer, Mark Conway, 32,
chased Johnson in the car.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is not exactly clear, because investigators
have not yet questioned Conway, police said. What is clear is that
he caught up with Johnson near the intersection of Undercliff and
Sedgwick Avenues, grabbed him through the car window and fired a
single shot that struck him, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A bus driver who witnessed the shooting told detectives that he
had seen Conway reach out of his car window and grab Johnson while
the car was still moving, a police official said. The driver said
he had seen Johnson trying to break free by wriggling out of his
jacket, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Conway is quoted in another police report as telling the first
officer to arrive at the scene, Fraterrigo, ``Mike, we were
struggling with the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing a fleeing suspect from a moving car does not appear to
violate department policy, Safir said. But he added, ``I question
some of the tactics.'' He refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of an unarmed teenager has drawn more criticism of
the Street Crime Unit, which became the subject of a federal civil
rights investigation after four of its members fatally shot Amadou
Diallo, an unarmed man, on Feb. 4 in the Bronx, firing 41 bullets
at him. The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, said Thursday
in a statement, ``This incident raises serious questions once again
about the Street Crime Unit and its adherence to NYPD
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani defended the unit. ``I think the Street
Crime Unit has to do its job,'' he said. ``The shooting is one that
is being looked at, but before people cast any judgments or start
to point fingers at people or see this as the usual knee-jerk,
antipolice reaction, they should wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Johnson had been on probation for a grand larceny
arrest stemming from an April incident involving a stolen wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Safir questioned Johnson's behavior. ``You have to wonder why
somebody runs from a uniformed officer,'' he said. ``You have to
wonder why somebody struggles with a uniformed officer. I believe
families should wonder about kids hanging out at 12:30 in large
groups and wonder where their children are, especially if they're
on probation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton replied, ``For him to question why Dante was out at
12:30 at night rather than question how a policeman can drive a
car, grab a young man and hold a gun all at the same time shows
that he's far more inclined to try and desecrate a victim's family
than try and set policy in policing in this city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
