<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE STREAK WITHOUT A RECORD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Yankee Stadium Thursday night, the primary plot
was not merely Roger Clemens' first start as a Yankee against the
Red Sox but also his success in extending his streak of consecutive
victories to 19 over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But a strange streak also was extended. With two singles
Thursday night, Derek Jeter has now been on base in each of the
Yankees' 45 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens knows the major league record he was approaching: Carl
Hubbell's 24 consecutive victories for the New York Giants from
July 17, 1936 to May 27, 1937.
</P>
<P>
   But for Jeter's streak, no record exists. Of the thousands of
records in ``The Book of Baseball Records,'' the blue-covered bible
published annually by the Elias Sports Bureau, there is no record
for ``consecutive games, on base safely.'' And there may never be
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to have a play-by-play of every major league game
going all the way back more than 100 years,'' said Seymour Siwoff,
the Elias emperor and the keeper of the keys to baseball records.
``And nobody has that.''
</P>
<P>
   During an inquiring conversation with Siwoff Thursday, it was
established that Joe DiMaggio was on base safely in 74 consecutive
games in 1941, a streak created primarily by his most memorable
record: hitting safely in 56 consecutive games that season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter obviously has a long way to go to even approach that
74-game streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``But DiMaggio's 74 games may not be the major league record,''
Siwoff said. ``It might not even be the Yankee record. Because
nobody knows what the record is.''
</P>
<P>
   By clicking their computers, the Elias figger filberts were able
to certify that Jeter's streak was the longest for a Yankee going
back to the 1961 season.
</P>
<P>
   But in that era before computers, somewhere sometime another
Yankee or another major leaguer might have put together more than
the 74 games in DiMaggio's on-base streak.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are obvious: Babe Ruth, Ty Cobb, Lou Gehrig, Ted
Williams, Mickey Mantle, Willie Mays, Hank Aaron, Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it could be a nondescript player,'' Siwoff said.
``Somebody who was a decent hitter and who got a lot of bases on
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   It might even be DiMaggio, who perhaps had a longer on-base
streak in, say, 1939 when he was hitting over .400 in September
before skidding to .381 for the American League batting title. But
any search for the on-base record would start with DiMaggio's
56-game streak in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees center fielder was stopped on July 16 in
Cleveland, he went 0 for 3, grounding out twice to third baseman
Ken Keltner and bouncing to shortstop Lou Boudreau for a double
play. But in the fourth inning, the Indians' starter, left-hander
Al Smith, walked him.
</P>
<P>
   After that hitless game, DiMaggio put together a 16-game hitting
streak before failing to get on base in eight at-bats in an Aug. 3
doubleheader sweep by Johnny Niggeling and Bob Harris of the St.
Louis Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let's look at what DiMaggio did in the games before the
56-game streak began on May 15 with a single off Edgar Smith of the
White Sox at the Stadium,'' said Siwoff, opening a scrapbook of
newspaper accounts and box scores. ``The day before, he got a walk
off Mel Harder of the Indians, but the day before that, against Bob
Feller, he went 0 for 4 with no walks.''
</P>
<P>
   That adds up to 74 consecutive on-base games: the walk in the
game against Harder, the 56-game hitting streak, the walk by Smith
in the game that stopped the streak, then the 16-game hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' Siwoff said, ``that an on-base safely streak would
not include getting on first on a forceout at another base. And if
you could establish an on-base safely record, you might have to
include getting hit by a pitch or being awarded first base on
interference. But it wouldn't be a record unless we could
authenticate it as a record.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Pedro Martinez, the ace Red Sox right-hander, had a
streak of seven consecutive games with at least 10 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard some people call that a `presumed record,''' Siwoff
said. ``But there's no such thing as a `presumed' record. It's
either a record or it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   As Roger Clemens knows, Carl Hubbell has the record of 24
consecutive victories. But for Derek Jeter, there is no on-base
safely consecutive-game record.
</P>
<P>
   And there may never be one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
