<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT NOMINEE WITHDRAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Barbara Durham, a prominent conservative Republican
who was nominated by President Clinton to an important federal
appeals court as part of an extraordinary political deal, is
withdrawing her name, congressional officials said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durham, a supreme court justice from the state of
Washington, was nominated last year to a vacancy on the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals by the president in exchange for
Republican agreement to stop blocking some of his judicial
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Durham has told congressional officials that she cannot
serve because her husband has serious heart problems. The
congressional officials said they did not know if she would
continue to serve as a state Supreme Court justice, although she
suggested in her withdrawal letter that she would do so.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said last year that they would not have
considered putting Ms. Durham on the federal bench if they did not
need help in getting some of their own judicial choices confirmed
in the Republican-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durham was the choice of Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who
told the White House that unless she was nominated he would
continue to block the confirmation of professor William Fletcher,
an old Clinton friend, to the same court.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Fletcher, who taught at the University of
California Law School at Berkeley, was blocked for three years.
After the president agreed to make the bargain, Fletcher was
quickly confirmed as a judge on the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Though the process of nominating and confirming judges is rife
with politics and trade-offs, the Clinton-Gorton arrangement was
highly unusual in that the president ceded to a senator of the
opposition party what is traditionally a closely held presidential
perquisite: the right to choose federal appeals court judges.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Fletcher's confirmation, Republicans agreed to
confirm two other nominees, only one of which has occurred so far.
But with Ms. Durham's withdrawal, the most pressing question is
whether Gorton still retains the right to fill that seat on the
federal appeals court. His aides said Thursday night that he
believes he does, but White House officials would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durham did not return calls placed to her office.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gorton and Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., Ms. Durham
said, ``In the past few days I have received the upsetting news
that my husband has a serious heart condition. After much
soul-searching, I realize that I would not be comfortable with a
travel schedule that would take me away from Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the state court, Ms. Durham need not travel far
from home, but federal appeals judges are obliged to travel
throughout the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit, the largest of the nation's 12 regional circuit
courts, just below the Supreme Court, covers California,
Washington, Hawaii and six other Western states, plus two Pacific
territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
