<HEADER>
A4281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT &LR;      05-27 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLARING CLEMENS TAMES RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those New York Yankees bearing baseball-sized lumps
from Roger Clemens made peace with the Rocket in spring training,
forgiving the beanballs he had thrown in the past, assuming he
would throw many more on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens didn't pitch inside or intimidate in his first six
starts of the season, surprising a few of his teammates. Was it
coincidence that when Clemens did throw a couple of knockdowns
Thursday night, he was pitching against the Boston Red Sox?
</P>
<P>
   Pumping his fist and glaring and zipping some head-high
fastballs, Clemens held Boston to two hits over seven innings in a
4-1 victory at Yankee Stadium Thursday night, maintaining his
perfect record against his former team.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has won 19 consecutive decisions, an American League
record that is five short of Carl Hubbell's major league record,
set in 1936-37. Clemens, who will face the Cleveland Indians next
week, is assured of going more than a calendar year without
recording a defeat; his last loss occurred on May 29, 1998, versus
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Tarasco, who made his first start for the Yankees since
being summoned from the minors on Tuesday, drove in a run; and
Jorge Posada hit a seventh-inning home run. The Yankees (26-19)
have won five of their last seven games and appear to be in the
process of regaining their former dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who had seven strikeouts and walked three, has two
victories since being activated off the disabled list last week.
And for the first time, he threw like the nasty, intimidating
pitcher the Yankees had faced for years.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Clemens' strikeouts came in the first two innings, and
in the bottom of the third, Boston's Pat Rapp hit Chuck Knoblauch
in the ribs. In the top of the fourth, Clemens threw two quick
strikes to Reggie Jefferson _ and then fired a fastball molar-high,
Jefferson ducking out of the way and many of the 27,631 fans
ooohing. Jefferson struck out, Nomar Garciaparra struck out, and
through four innings, the Red Sox had just one infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco was born in New York, and before moving to California at
an early age, he lived in Washington Heights. Tarasco was a Yankees
fan _ his favorite player was Willie Randolph _ and shortly after
Tarasco broke into pro ball with the Atlanta organization, he found
himself during one spring training sitting between Willie Stargell
and Chris Chambliss, the latter a hitting instructor with the
Braves at the time. Except Tarasco didn't recognize Chambliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you name the Yankees' starting lineup from when you were a
kid?'' Stargell asked him, and Tarasco rattled off all but one name
among the regulars. ``I could never pronounce the name of the first
baseman,'' Tarasco said, in earnest, and Stargell keeled over with
laughter, at Chambliss' expense.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco is 28 now and with his sixth organization and knows his
situation: he is a role player who sits most of the time, and if he
wants more, he must seize the day when he does start. He played an
inning of defense Wednesday and afterward, Torre told him he would
start in left field in Thursday night's game. ``I want to get him
involved,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco, inserted in left field, would be in the midst of action
all night, when the game could have turned with just about any
at-bat, any decision, any mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and Rapp dominated the early innings and the Yankees and
Red Sox were scoreless into the bottom of the fifth inning, when
Chili Davis led off with a single. Rapp stared in for the sign on
the next hitter, never bothering to glance at the 39-year-old Davis
leading off first.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing this, Davis began to break for second base, and when
Rapp continued to hold the ball, he stopped, about 25 feet off
first base. Unaware of Davis' activity, Rapp began his delivery and
Davis resumed his course toward second, and even with the big jump,
the throw from catcher Creighton Gubanich beat Davis to the bag.
But with his slide, Davis kicked the ball out of the glove of
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. Safe.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Tarasco grounded the ball through the middle and
Davis chugged home with the first run. One run for the Rocket, who
allowed one hit and struck out five in the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But wildness had infected Clemens in the fifth _ he had gone to
a full count on all three hitters he faced. He walked Trot Nixon to
open the sixth, and one out later, Jeff Frye walked.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens fell behind John Valentin, 2-0, had to throw a fastball
and Valentin whacked it to left, where Tarasco hesitated in
charging the ball before throwing homeward. Posada caught the ball
and swung his gloved hand at Nixon passing by. Too late. Tie game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees responded immediately, running aggressively once
more. Derek Jeter started the bottom of the seventh by ripping a
single to left, and stole second. When Gubanich's throw bounded
into the outfield, Jeter jumped to his feet and scrambled to third
base.
</P>
<P>
   With a runner at third and nobody out and Paul O'Neill, Bernie
Williams and Tino Martinez coming to bat, Boston manager Jimy
Williams had a puzzle to solve.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered the Red Sox infield to come in with O'Neill batting.
O'Neill, who came into the game with 2 hits in his last 27 at-bats
with runners in scoring position, lined out, Jeter holding at
third.
</P>
<P>
   Williams could have had Rapp intentionally walk Williams and
then called on left-hander Mark Guthrie to pitch to Martinez. But
he stuck with Rapp and kept the infield in. Williams grounded to
first, and Jeter again had to hold at third. Two out.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's infield moved back. Williams had the option of going to
Guthrie, but he had come this far with Rapp and stayed with him.
Martinez smashed a bullet off the right-field wall, Jeter trotted
home, the manager watching from the dugout with his arms tightly
wrapped against his chest. Yankees 2, Boston 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens now had separation, and he recovered his control in the
seventh, retiring the Red Sox in order, racking up his seventh
strikeout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
