<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-CENTURY-$ADV3     05-27 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-CENTURY-$ADV30-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20TH CENTURY AMERICAN DRAMA HAS PUSHED THE BOUNDARIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much of the attention at next Sunday's Tony Awards ceremony in
New York, the last of the century, will be trained on a pair of
American dramas that opened 50 and 60 years ago. Arthur Miller's
``Death of a Salesman'' (1949) and Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman
Cometh'' (1939) are rivals for best play revival and occasions for
lauded star performances by Brian Dennehy and Kevin Spacey,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales,'' a 1938 work
receiving its premiere in a spectacular staging, is a contender for
the best new play Tony. Some Broadway handicappers give it decent
odds against a pair of imports from across the Atlantic, ``Closer''
and ``The Lonesome West,'' and American Warren Leight's ``Side
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miller-O'Neill faceoff, alongside a ``new'' Tennessee
Williams play, inspires some layered millennial musing on American
playwriting itself. Exciting as it is to encounter classics in
vigorous new productions as the century ends, revivals renew an
anxiety about what the American theater has achieved and where it's
heading.
</P>
<P>
   Do ``Salesman,'' ``Iceman,'' Williams' leading works and the
other titles on the accompanying list of 50 American plays
represent a measure of enduring greatness? How will the writers of
our own time _ David Mamet, Tony Kushner, August Wilson, Edward
Albee _ stack up in another 50 years, or 500?
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that we just don't know yet. American drama and
comedy in the 20th century tell a continuing story of discovery, a
series of thematic and theatrical thresholds met with an energetic
rush toward the unknown and unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   From the dark, psychological interiors of O'Neill's brooding
marathons to the scintillating works of sexual and racial identity
by Kushner and David Henry Hwang, American playwrights have
continually stretched the borders.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Williams' shimmering, self-destructive heroines _ no
one had ever written female characters in quite that way before.
Arthur Miller, like Clifford Odets before him, used common-man
realism to pry open new questions about the social order. Anna
Deavere Smith inherited the mantle and wore it, all by herself
onstage, in a startling new fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton Wilder and William Inge discovered the rapture and
heartache of the small town. Lillian Hellman pulled the lid off
lesbianism and Southern venality.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Hansberry showed the tenderness and LeRoi Jones the
rage of the black experience. Wilson's multiplay chronicle couldn't
have happened without them.
</P>
<P>
   David Rabe gave the Vietnam era its agitated voice. Mamet made
sentence fragments and obscenities a precise and expressive
language.
</P>
<P>
   In assembling my list of 50 great American plays (I'm gun-shy
about the ``best'' epithet), I favored works that broke new ground
in some way. That, more than anything, seems a uniquely American
characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   There's a vigor in these plays _ from the sun-baked violence of
``The Great Divide'' (1906) and expressionist clamor of ``The
Adding Machine'' (1923) to Kushner's sprawling ``Angels'' (1992)
and Mabou Mines' nervous collage on nuclear power, ``Dead End
Kids'' (1980) _ that reflects the American spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Form isn't a matter of formalism steeped in centuries of
dramatic precedent. American playwrights innovate and break the
rules because that's the way, the only way, to get something said
that hasn't been said before. ``Our Town'' soars from provincial
slice-of-life to transcendent meditation on the strength of the
Stage Manager's lean, Yankee detachment. Sam Shepard blends deadpan
bleakness with a surrealistic glow that lights up the forlorn
beauty of the American West as if for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   America is still a young culture as it enters the new
millennium. We're still finding out who we are and where we belong.
Royall Tyler's ``The Contrast,'' widely regarded as the first fully
formed American play, opened in 1787. Years of melodramas and
mindless entertainments followed.
</P>
<P>
   England had already had its Elizabethan and Jacobean flowering,
its Restoration comedies and post-Restoration reaction. The
Comedie-Francaise was 200 years old when ``The Contrast'' opened.
Spain's Golden Age was long over. American playwrights were just
getting started and produced little of significance before World
War I.
</P>
<P>
   For some critics, the century or so of serious American
playwriting hasn't borne much fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not come anywhere near a Golden Age of the American
stage,'' Emory Lewis wrote in his 1969 book ``Stages: The
Fifty-Year Childhood of the American Theatre.'' Thirty years later,
in a recent New York Times broadside, Matthew Gurewitsch hadn't
found much improvement. Fixated on losers and failure, he wrote,
the great American dramatists lack the stature of Shakespeare,
Ibsen and Chekhov.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But then it's useful to remember that Shakespeare
wasn't an icon when he was alive. He was a playwright writing for a
company of actors and an audience eager for something new.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Plays acquire their true weight and value over time. A quick
scan of the Pulitzer Prize record offers ample proof that judgments
made at the moment are often faulty. ``The Glass Menagerie'' lost
out to ``Harvey'' in 1945. ``Mourning Becomes Electra'' and ``Who's
Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' are among the many prominent Pulitzer
also-rans. Giving awards and making lists is an inherently risky
business.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years isn't much time, but it's proved how thrilling
certain landmark plays are for an audience. Watching ``Death of a
Salesman'' on Broadway or the American Conservatory Theater's ``A
Streetcar Named Desire'' a few seasons back, I felt an almost
physical pull of inevitability and dread.
</P>
<P>
   Great plays do that when they're performed and staged as well as
these productions were. Familiarity gives the plays a suspenseful
sense of urgency. ``Salesman'' and ``Streetcar'' feel freshly
written, raw and exposed, flaws and all. They're unmistakably
American.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, whose unrivaled ambition and scope seems inextricably
bound with his difficulty, is harder to reawaken onstage. Neither
the Broadway ``Iceman'' nor ACT's recent ``Long Day's Journey Into
Night'' conquered the length and fixated redundancies of the
scripts. Some of O'Neill's plays, including his undeniably great
ones, seem dauntingly resistant to production.
</P>
<P>
   So, no doubt, are others on this top 50 list. I'm not sure I'd
much care to see ``The Petrified Forest'' or ``The New York Idea.''
But they belong here, taking their place in a legacy of American
writers pressing into new territory. There are other titles,
including ``The Show-Off'' and ``Aunt Dan and Lemon,'' that could
take the stage tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   People look back when the calendar turns, especially to a big
even number. In the spirit of American playwrights, we ought to
look forward as well. A century's worth of plays is just the start
of a great theatrical culture. Let a new one begin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-99 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
