<DOCNO> NYT19990527.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-LIST-$ADV30-S     05-27 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-LIST-$ADV30-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTY FOR THE CENTURY: A CRITIC'S LIST OF GREAT AMERICAN PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With THEATRE-CENTURY)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here, in chronological order, are my 50 great American plays of
the century. The absence of musical librettos (``The Cradle Will
Rock,'' ``Sunday in the Park With George'') and adaptations from
other works (``Of Mice and Men,'' ``The Green Pastures'') helped
narrow the field. But not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The omissions may be glaring. So, perhaps, are some of the
inclusions. Any ``best'' list, whether made at the end of a year or
a century, is a snapshot of a critic's judgment and era. One can
only hope that it won't fade too badly over time.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The New York Idea'' &LR;  by Langdon Mitchell (1906). A
prescient satire peels away the deceptions of marriage and divorce
in upper-crust Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Great Divide'' &LR;  by William Vaughan Moody (1906). Moody,
who also wrote ``The Faith Healer,'' finds ``whiskey, the sun and
the devil'' at the bottom of his raw tale of a Wild West rape.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Adding Machine'' &LR;  by Elmer Rice (1923). Mr. Zero is the
technology-tormented hero of an Expressionist landmark.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Show-Off'' &LR;  by George Kelly (1924). A Philadelphia
mother and son-in-law face off in a still stage-worthy comedy of
the American family.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``What Price Glory'' &LR;  by Maxwell Anderson and Lawrence
Stallings &LR;   &LR; (1924). It's not exactly an anti-war play, but this
trip into the World War I trenches was an unsentimental
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Strange Interlude'' &LR;  by Eugene O'Neill (1928). In an
astonishing psychodramatic feat, the characters voyage to the
subconscious in a nine-act marathon of adultery and interior
monologues.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Mourning Becomes Electra'' &LR;  by Eugene O'Neill (1931). This
heroic Americanization of the Oresteia got a rare and memorable
production by San Francisco's American Conservatory Theater in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Children's Hour'' &LR;  by Lillian Hellman (1934). Behind
the hush-hush sensationalism of lesbian teachers at a girls'
school, Hellman taps the primal themes of innocence and betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Petrified Forest'' &LR;  by Robert Sherwood (1935). Marxism
comes to Arizona in a heated stew of '30s political passion.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Winterset'' &LR;  by Maxwell Anderson (1935). This lyrically
anguished piece, in blank verse, was written in response to the
Sacco and Vanzetti trial.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Awake and Sing!'' &LR;  by Clifford Odets (1935). The
playwright's spryest and most likable play unfolds around the
kitchen table of a Bronx apartment during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Waiting for Lefty'' &LR;  by Clifford Odets (1935). This anatomy
of a taxi strike has become a museum piece, but its sense of
socially committed urgency inspired plenty of successors.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``You Can't Take It With You'' &LR;  by George S. Kaufman and Moss
Hart (1936). The play celebrates the eccentric American striver;
for today's audiences it's a rich indulgence in ensemble acting.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Women'' &LR;  by Clare Boothe Luce (1936). The playwright
laced her feminism with pitiless satire on the foibles of her
heroines.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Philadelphia Story'' &LR;  by Philip Barry (1939). This poor
little rich girl romance has never lost its insouciant charm and
comic composure.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Little Foxes'' &LR;  by Lillian Hellman (1939). Heartless
greed drives the Hubbard clan in a brazen affront to Southern
gentility.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Our Town'' &LR;  by Thornton Wilder (1939). Wilder gives a New
England small town a timeless transcendence in his sweet, formally
rigorous masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Iceman Cometh'' &LR;  by Eugene O'Neill (1939). Flophouse
denizens play out their haunted pipe-dream melodies in O'Neill's
prolix chorus of the down-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' &LR;  by Thornton Wilder (1942).
Dinosaurs roam the Antrobus house in an allegory ripe for a major
reassessment and revival.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Glass Menagerie'' &LR;  by Tennessee Williams (1945). In a
single, autobiographical stroke, Williams invented the American
memory play and cast his spell of theatrical poetry.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``All My Sons'' &LR;  by Arthur Miller (1947). Clunky as it is,
Miller's back-fence drama called out urgently for personal
responsibility and social justice.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' &LR;  by Tennessee Williams (1947).
Blanche DuBois and Stanley Kowalski aren't just characters; they're
sexually magnetized force fields in Williams' most gripping work.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Death of a Salesman'' &LR;  by Arthur Miller (1949). Willy
Loman's long march to the end swells into a great, bruising tragedy
of the common man.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Picnic'' &LR;  by William Inge (1953). The playwright has
drifted out of fashion, but his hothouse plays catch a uniquely
Midwestern kind of suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' &LR;  by Tennessee Williams (1955).
Forget the deplorable film; the play is Williams' funniest and most
probing dissection of a family.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Bus Stop'' &LR;  by William Inge (1955). Like O'Neill before him
and Lanford Wilson after, Inge felt the gravitational pull of
misfits filling the air with stories and lies.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Long Day's Journey Into Night'' &LR;  by Eugene O'Neill (1956).
O'Neill wrote his most personal play in 1939-41 and wouldn't let it
be produced in his lifetime. It remains a difficult, obsessive,
feverish look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``A Raisin in the Sun'' &LR;  by Lorraine Hansberry (1959). It
shows its 40 years, but the inside-out view of black poverty opened
eyes and hearts on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Night of the Iguana'' &LR;  by Tennessee Williams (1961).
This is a cut below Williams' best work, but there's still a
furious energy and grace.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' &LR;  by Edward Albee (1962).
The academic world never looked the same after Albee's dissection;
neither did marriage.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Dutchman'' &LR;  by LeRoi Jones (Amiri Baraka) (1964). A blond
woman taunts and murders a black intellectual on a subway train in
an explosive short work that opened the floodgates for black
writers.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The Odd Couple'' &LR;  by Neil Simon (1965). The kudos Simon got
for his later ``Brighton/Biloxi/Broadway'' autobiographical trilogy
felt like a lifetime achievement award; this oil-and-water duet
remains a comic archetype.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Hogan's Goat'' &LR;  by William Alfred (1965). This surging
verse drama is set in the brackish world of Boston Irish Catholic
politics.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``A Delicate Balance'' &LR;  by Edward Albee (1966). There's a
deep, tender melancholy in Albee's bemused family and neighbors,
beautifully renewed in a Broadway revival a few seasons back.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``The House of Blue Leaves'' &LR;  by John Guare (1971). Guare
mounts a jolly assault on the Catholic church and the American cult
of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``American Buffalo'' &LR;  by David Mamet (1975). In their blunt,
strangled language, Mamet's small-time crooks articulate the ruse
of the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Streamers'' &LR;  by David Rabe (1976). The third panel of a
trilogy completes a deeply disillusioned picture of the Vietnam
era.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Curse of the Starving Class'' &LR;  by Sam Shepard (1978). From
here to ``True West'' and beyond, the playwright found the psychic
emptiness in the great open spaces of the American West.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Buried Child'' &LR;  by Sam Shepard (1978). In his best play,
Shepard gives his young protagonist a chance to crack the family's
daunting secrets.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Dead End Kids'' &LR;  by Mabou Mines (1980). An early work by
the enduring collaborative ensemble takes an arresting, prismatic
view of the nuclear threat.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``A Soldier's Play'' &LR;  by Charles Fuller (1981). A crackling
courtroom drama, in a military setting, cuts through the fog of
racism and received wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' &LR;  by David Mamet (1983). Real estate
is an American way of life in Mamet's taut, exhilarating reduction.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Aunt Dan and Lemon'' &LR;  by Wallace Shawn (1985). In this sly,
disturbing work, the century's unfinished business with the Nazis
seeps in like a poison.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' &LR;  by August Wilson (1986). The
playwright's musical language finds its most satisfying medium in
this haunted evocation of a Pittsburgh boarding house in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``M. Butterfly'' &LR;  by David Henry Hwang (1988). The true story
of a French diplomat duped by a Chinese drag queen becomes a hall
of brilliant theatrical mirrors on race and gender, art and
illusion.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Prelude to a Kiss'' &LR;  by Craig Lucas (1988). Shaped like a
fairy tale, this delicate work about an old man and a young bride
trading places achieves a rare spiritual transformation.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Six Degrees of Separation'' &LR;  by John Guare (1990). A smart
black kid cons a rich liberal white couple in this telling comedy
of contemporary manners.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Angels in America'' &LR;  by Tony Kushner &LR;   &LR; (1992). The sweeping
two-part saga about AIDS, fear and courage made the American
theater feel vital and essential in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Fires in the Mirror: Crown Heights, Brooklyn and Other &LR; 
 &UR; Identities'' &LR;  by Anna Deavere Smith (1992). In a bravura,
pseudojournalistic solo, a race riot becomes the multifaceted lens
of a modern American kaleidoscope.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; ``Three Tall Women'' &LR;  by Edward Albee &LR;   &LR; (1994). There's a
cubist logic to this play about a woman seen, simultaneously, at
three different times in her life; Albee makes the picture hum with
irony and affection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
