<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ PLANNING TO TRADE 100 BIG STOCKS IN EVENING
</P>
<P>
   The board that governs the NASDAQ market approved a plan to add
an evening session for trading of the 100 largest NASDAQ stocks,
beginning perhaps as soon as September. In response, the New York
Stock Exchange has said that it, too, might add an evening session.
</P>
<P>
   By extending their hours, the exchanges would cause untold
changes in the lives of thousands of traders, clerks and others who
work in and around Wall Street. But the change would also touch, in
ways yet to be seen, millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to add an evening trading session puts new pressure
on newspapers, wire services and television networks already
competing to get the latest market information to their readers and
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY SUSPENDS WORKERS
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley suspended two executives in connection with a
$10,000 payment that led to the arrest of a former employee.
</P>
<P>
   TLC BEATRICE PLANS TO SELL UNITS
</P>
<P>
   The remaining businesses of TLC Beatrice International Holdings
_ potato chips and ice cream _ will be sold by the end of the
summer, and what was once one of the nation's largest black-owned
companies will close its doors. Loida Nicolas Lewis, who has been
chief executive of TLC Beatrice since 1994, said she had mixed
feelings about the final days of the company her husband put
together after a $1 billion leveraged buyout in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYER PLEADS GUILTY IN FRAUD CASE
</P>
<P>
   Hartley Bernstein, a well-known securities lawyer in New York,
pleaded guilty to securities fraud conspiracy and perjury and
agreed to forfeit $850,000 in illegal proceeds made as an insider
in five fraudulent public stock offerings, federal prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DROP FOR 5TH TIME IN SIX DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell for the fifth time in six sessions. The Dow
Jones industrial average tumbled 235.23 points, or 2.2 percent, to
10,466.93, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 23.35
points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,281.41. Losses were more modest on the
NASDAQ composite index, which edged down 8.03 points, or
three-tenths of a percent, to 2,419.15.
</P>
<P>
   IBM OFFICIAL BOLSTERS U.S. CASE
</P>
<P>
   A senior IBM executive testified that Microsoft repeatedly
raised the prices it charged IBM for its Windows operating system
and enforced other onerous licensing terms in retaliation for IBM's
refusal to stop competing with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   GDP GREW 4.1 PERCENT IN FIRST QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of weak growth, corporate profits
rebounded in the first quarter, the Commerce Department reported.
The profit report, the first for the January-through-March period,
appeared in the department's latest estimate of first-quarter
economic growth. The gross domestic product grew at an annual rate
of 4.1 percent, the report SAID, down somewhat from the 4.5 percent
rate reported last month and well below the 6 percent annual rate
in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANY CLOSES RIVAL TV RATING
</P>
<P>
   Statistical Research, which created a television rating system
that network executives identified as the best potential
alternative ever to Nielsen Media Research, announced that it was
shutting down after it failed to receive sufficient financial
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK ON DISNEY CHIEF IS CANCELED
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books, a publishing division of Random House, has
canceled its contract with Kim Masters, a contributing editor of
both Time and Vanity Fair magazines, to publish her book about
Michael Eisner, the chairman of Walt Disney, and his ascension to
Hollywood power.
</P>
</TEXT>
