<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM TAPS INTO THE MUSIC, ART TALENTS OF DISADVANTAGED,
STRUGGLING KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a rehearsal studio near Seattle's Fremont Bridge,
14-year-old Tyler Musgrave and Shorecrest freshman Tom Miller are
no longer just kids.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler is a drummer, a human metronome whose left foot can be as
relentless as a dripping faucet.
</P>
<P>
   Tom is a piano player whose fingers sing of Bill Evans and
Thelonious Monk, with a little Herbie Hancock on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Give them a beat to follow and stand back.
</P>
<P>
   The boys and their surroundings are part of a music and art
program developed in Seattle by jazz pianist Bill Rossi.
Participants learn not only how to play, they learn why teamwork is
important when all there is to share is a downbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi's organization, Youth Advancement Through Music and Art,
or YATMA, recently was awarded a $25,000 grant from the William H.
Gates Foundation. The money will help to underwrite lessons for
kids who can't afford them at a time when many schools can't
either. While the state has designated ``the arts'' as core
academic subjects to be taught right along with reading, writing
and arithmetic, they remain on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arts are always the first to go,'' said retired Seattle
School District music teacher Don Castagna. ``You're supposed to
teach it anywhere at any time. You don't need a desk or tools like
math, or if a kid wants to play an instrument, play it in a closet
or in the bathroom or the hallway.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Cluett, associate director of the Gates foundation, said
YATMA was awarded the grant ``because it offers opportunities in
music and art to kids who haven't had them. And we were very
enthused by the young people we observed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi is, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in creating the next great recording
artist,'' Rossi said. ``We do want to help kids deal a little
better with life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossi's 4-year-old organization operates from a small house on
Seattle's Nickerson Street, but its programs have spread to include
the Seattle Children's Home, the Seattle Art Museum, the Langston
Hughes Cultural Arts Center, and the Delridge Youth Group, a
program of Southwest Youth &AMP; Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   YATMA's lessons are available on a sliding scale depending on a
family's ability to pay. They can continue for years _ or as long
as it takes to turn a child around. Some lessons are private.
Others take place at a classroom level or in groups of three to
four children. The school's present enrollment across the city is
about 300.
</P>
<P>
   At an address on Delridge Way Southwest, single mother Donna
Johnson and two of her three daughters, Tina, 11, and Trish, 12,
arrive weekly to take half-hour turns with YATMA instructor Gregg
Robinson, a jazz pianist with a master's degree in social work.
</P>
<P>
   In a basement, Robinson coaxes his students to play by ear on an
upright piano, copying tunes and tempos they may have heard as
toddlers to the fingering he sometimes provides, but not always. He
lets them plunk around. ``I often start with Happy Birthday. We all
know how it goes,'' he said. ``They get it because their ears know
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The method is a YATMA trademark, a plank in Rossi's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting her turn at the piano, Tina and her mother begin
dealing from two-deck stack of playing cards, and identify their
game as Pennsylvania Rummy. ``It's great for their math,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   So is music _ whole notes divided into half notes, half notes
divided into quarters, eighths and sixteenths.
</P>
<P>
   Studies at the University of California-Irvine showed that
preschoolers with just eight months of piano training demonstrated
a 46 percent boost in the kind of reasoning required to succeed in
math. Irvin studies also showed that piano keyboards were superior
to computer keyboards in generating math skills.
</P>
<P>
   Similar results were demonstrated recently in keyboard studies
at McGill University in Montreal, and in studies of kindergarten
kids in Kettle Moraine, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   In an Auburn University study, music and art heightened a
participant's self image, while similar results were obtained in a
Minnesota program. At the conclusion of a program that included
music, movement, drama and art for at-risk kids, they all liked
themselves better.
</P>
<P>
   YATMA's founder is a 1970s graduate of Boston's Berklee School
of Music, who believes music and art to be ``as natural to a child
as walking and talking, and should be a fundamental building block
in the schools, but rarely is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to help change that, but it's been an uphill
battle,'' Rossi said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the arts are listed as a core subject in Washington
state's latest set of academic standards, they remain largely on
the periphery in many school districts, including Seattle's, where
budgets are tight.
</P>
<P>
   The record is indelible: Lose a tax levy and cut the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Until a series of levy failures began jolting the Seattle School
District in 1975, however, exemplary music programs were the rule
districtwide and drew observers from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Today they are the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Acox heads one of them. Chairman of the Garfield High
School music department, Acox oversees a program that ranges from
choir to the renowned Garfield Jazz Ensemble, and considers himself
``one of the lucky ones.'' He added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had principals who support music all the way All
our schools should. Tragically, they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Acox, recruited from Southern University in 1971, isn't
reaching everyone at Garfield. Hip-hop fans, in particular, don't
conn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
