<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE, USC OPEN PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A college coach rarely memorizes a national
ranking, and they almost never admit to it.
</P>
<P>
   But Pepperdine head baseball coach Frank Sanchez remembers where
the Waves were placed among the nation's top 100 teams by one
prominent magazine in the preseason _ number 67, one spot ahead of
San Diego State and one behind Old Dominion.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Waves got out to an amazing start, winning 30 of their
first 33 games, and suddenly they were ranked No. 3 _ by that same
publication.
</P>
<P>
   As his team prepares for this weekend's NCAA first-round
regional at USC, Sanchez downplays both rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to prove anybody right or wrong until the
season is over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (43-14) hopes the end doesn't come this weekend. The
Waves, who play Harvard (28-18) tonight at 7, are the top seed in
the regional. The host and defending national champion Trojans
(33-23) are the No. 2 seed and play Virginia Commonwealth (40-18)
in the regional's opening game at 3 p.m. The round-robin format
continues Saturday with three games and ends Sunday at noon with
the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the West Coast Conference championship last
weekend at Loyola Marymount, Pepperdine is having its best season
since 1992, when the Waves won their only national title.
</P>
<P>
   Senior third baseman G.J. Raymundo, who leads the team with a
.391 batting average and 15 home runs, isn't worried about
overconfidence; this is Pepperdine's first playoff appearance in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a little more is at stake now,'' he said. ``We all
know what we have to do ... They gave us the No. 1 seed and we have
to finish there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine won 33 games last year but didn't get an NCAA bid.
Sophomore right-hander Jay Adams, who starts against Harvard, said
he noticed a change in the returning players in the fall workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys' attitudes were different,'' Adams said. ``We were
working harder. Guys were staying after practice.''
</P>
<P>
   That ethic didn't change during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about the same amount of enthusiasm today as we had
opening day,'' Sanchez said. ``Very few teams, 20 weeks into the
season, are still chomping at the bit, are still excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-ranked Waves may have been a surprising No. 1 seed, but
they aren't a fluke. Pepperdine's record against teams that made
the playoffs is 12-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to pass a lot of teams (in the Baseball America
poll) to be where we needed,'' Raymundo said. ``We beat a lot of
good teams to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   USC hosts a regional for the first since 1991, and the Trojans
didn't win it that year; they were eliminated by Hawaii. Head coach
Mike Gillespie said he is worried the Trojans are looking past
Virginia Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a crystal ball to know what they really think,''
Gillespie said, ``but my concern is they think they have to beat
Pepperdine to win this thing. Maybe I'm overly concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   His worries are valid. The Rams pounded USC pitching for 20 hits
in a 14-4 upset win in last year's regional at Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we'll get a little payback,'' USC catcher Eric
Munson said. ``That would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The USC coaching staff decided to start right-hander Justin Lehr
(6-2, 4.48 ERA) today instead of All-American left-hander Barry
Zito (11-2, 3.46). It wasn't a snap decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agonized over that,'' Gillespie said. ``We simply felt that
Lehr, even though his wins and losses aren't like Zito's, has
pitched really outstanding for us. We felt if we were going to win
this this thing, this was the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Keyes, VCU's head coach, doesn't think last year's win over
USC has anything to do with today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams are different,'' Keyes said. ``They've lost quite a
few players and we have lost quite a few players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
