<HEADLINE>
VAN BOXMEER'S INTERVIEW WENT WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime in the coming weeks, the Kings will hire the 19th coach
in their history to lead them into their 33rd NHL season, their
first at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that Ice Dogs coach John Van Boxmeer did nothing
to hurt his chances of getting the job when he interviewed Tuesday
with Kings general manager Dave Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good interview,'' Van Boxmeer said
Thursday. ``I was comfortable with it. I have a lot of respect for
Dave Taylor. Dave is a very straight shooter. It's very important
in the coach-general manager relationship to have trust. I have a
lot of trust and confidence in Dave Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two seasons, Van Boxmeer has had frequent dealings with
Taylor because the Ice Dogs have had a limited affiliation with the
Kings, an affiliation expected to continue next season.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players under contract to the Kings who have played
for Van Boxmeer in Long Beach are Pavel Rosa, Jamie Storr, Jan
Nemecek, Jaroslav Modry, Jason Podollan, Dan Bylsma, Nathan
LaFayette and Manny Legace. Additionally, when he was in the
Buffalo Sabres' organization, Van Boxmeer worked with current Kings
Philippe Boucher and Donald Audette.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor acknowledged Wednesday that Van Boxmeer's familiarity
with the Kings was a definite asset in the Ice Dogs' coach and
general manager's bid for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave was feeling me out on a lot of different subjects, what
kind of game I like to play, how I handle certain situations,'' Van
Boxmeer said of Tuesday's interview. ``We've worked together for a
couple of years. It's not like he doesn't know how I handle things
and handle people.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he and Taylor are in accord on the sort of game they'd
like to see the Kings play, Van Boxmeer said, ``I think so. I think
we both like skilled guys who compete hard. I like to get it deep
and forecheck. I like to be aggressive on the forecheck and cycle
the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer said one topic touched on during the interview was
whether he'd want to bring an assistant coach with him if he is
hired. Former Kings defenseman Mark Hardy, a long-time Taylor
teammate, has been Van Boxmeer's assistant in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Taylor) asked me if I had anybody in mind,'' Van Boxmeer
said. ``Mark's name came up. But in Mark's best interest, it may be
better for him to stay in Long Beach and be a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer was the second person to interview for the Kings'
job, which became vacant April 19 when Taylor decided not to bring
back Larry Robinson for a fifth season.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor interviewed former Sabres coach Ted Nolan last week. He
may interview Detroit assistant Dave Lewis, along with a couple of
other candidates, in the next week. After that, Taylor is expected
to conduct follow-up interviews and make a decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
